CLAIBORNE'S JOB: CATCH McNOWN 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After the way he knocked Arizona State quarterback
Ryan Kealy out of the game with a concussion, it's only natural USC
linebacker Chris Claiborne has been asked around campus this week
if he can perform a similar feat against UCLA quarterback Cade
McNown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, definitely,'' Claiborne said. ``But you just play
the course of the game. Any shots I can get on him, you have to
take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Claiborne has faced the Bruins twice, he knows McNown is
one of the more elusive quarterbacks in the country, and more
difficult to hit cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the positions you get caught in that are a problem,''
Claiborne said. ``He knows where he's going but you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   As appealing as it sounds to have a McNown-Claiborne duel
determine the game's outcome, Claiborne said the contest will
really be decided on the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is definitely going to be between our defensive
linemen and their offensive linemen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soward tests ankle: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward tried running on
his badly sprained ankle Wednesday for the first time since getting
injured against Stanford nearly two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the light running were inconclusive, other than
proving Soward will not be 100 percent by Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He struggled to run. As it loosened up, I thought he moved
much better,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``I felt he'll play. I
was encouraged. (But) it's not where he could start and be 100
miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be in a limited role. I just know when it comes
to game time, he's going to want to play. There's nothing we can do
about him. He's frustrated. When you're injured, you're injured.
We're not going to put him in a position to jeopardize the
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   There's still a strong possibility Soward will be given another
anti-inflammatory injection before the game Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he has seen a chiropractor, according to a
source.
</P>
<P>
   Soward declined comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates are becoming resigned to the fact they may face
the Bruins without their star playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sit here and worry about R. Jay right now,'' wide
receiver Billy Miller said. ``That's up to R. Jay and other doctors
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost amid the Soward hype, tight end Lonnie Ford has
recovered faster from his ankle sprain against Stanford, and
returned to practice this week. He is expected to be available for
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tricky team? Hackett expects UCLA coach Bob Toledo to toss in a
few trick plays for Saturday's game, possibly even the first play
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be conscious that you're probably going to get one
on the opening play of the game and you're probably going to get
three or four,'' Hackett said. ``The reason trick plays are so
effective is that they make the defense lay back. We've got six
(trick plays), so maybe we'll use them the first six plays of the
game. Who's going to call the first one?''
</P>
<P>
   The key for the Trojans defense is not to become obsessed with
trick plays, although the players expect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're going to face trick plays, but you have to be
ready and disciplined,'' Claiborne said.
</P>
<P>
   Matock update: Defensive tackle Marc Matock practiced Wednesday
but said he would not play until the Notre Dame game.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Williams, who had a neck stinger that prevented him from
starting against Stanford, will start Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
