<SLUG> BC-FBC-PLAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEVEN PLAYS THAT LIFTED UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One player tells of being in almost a trancelike
state as he made the play. He moved as if in slow motion, and he
insists the stadium, despite 80,568 fans roaring all around him,
was deathly still.
</P>
<P>
   Another player is urged to recount a play he made, but as soon
as an interviewer cites the down and distance, the player
interrupts to say, ``You're sending chills down my spine already.''
</P>
<P>
   An assistant coach describes play after key play, in meticulous
detail, as if there is a reel of tape running in his head. Of a
quarterback sack that occurred seven years ago, he even describes
the move the linebacker used to shed a block, and says, ``I
remember the play like it was yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the essence of the USC-UCLA series, a college football
rivalry so unique it fosters out-of-body experiences and indelible
memories.
</P>
<P>
   Because the proximity of the schools is so close, the ties of
the participants so tight, emotions soar in this game. Commanding
leads are readily overcome, and in recent years, the outcome has
hung in the balance as late as the third quarter, the fourth _ or
the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   Until a single play occurred. A linchpin. The pivot on which the
game turned.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has produced seven of them in a row, resulting in an
unprecedented win streak in the 69-year series. An interception, a
sack, a mad scramble by the quarterback, a recovered fumble. After
each, USC was never the same again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had them down and we let it slip away,'' said USC
defensive backfield coach Dennis Thurman, a noted Bruins-killer
during his playing days with the Trojans in the late 1970s. ``If
you talk to UCLA, they'll say they went out there and took it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made the plays when they've had to. We've had great
comebacks, gotten close, and then, all of a sudden, we don't make
that play to get us over the hump. And they've made those plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering three of the seven games, USC was ranked and UCLA was
not. In another, the Trojans had a superior record. And yet UCLA
has prevailed, narrowly _ the seven straight victories have been
accomplished by an average margin of 5.6 points, less than a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Players on both sides cite a single factor for this: emotion.
Extreme emotion. The rivalry commands it.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Ale, a hero of the '91 game, said a cousin and three of
his high school teammates played for USC that year. Current UCLA
tackle Kris Farris revealed his girlfriend is a USC student, and he
catches heat whenever he walks into her sorority house. Thurman
recalled the time (1972-73) when Rod McNeill was a tailback for the
Trojans and brother Fred a linebacker for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``People probably exert more energy than they realize they're
exerting just because the game is so hyped up,'' said Danjuan
Magee, who produced the decisive play for UCLA in '96. ``It's like
a Super Bowl. People go to the wall, reckless disregard, don't care
what happens to their limbs.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting scenes can border on the surreal.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA linebacker Nkosi Littleton, who knocked down a pass on
USC's two-point conversion attempt in the final seconds of the '92
game at the Rose Bowl, said, ``It was like a movie. It was like
slow motion to me. Even though there were 100,000 people there,
while the play was in motion, you can't hear one word. Not one
thing. It is a dreamlike thing.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, it leaves USC wanting to be pinched. Safety Grant
Pearsall has yet to experience victory in this game despite being a
fifth-year senior for the Trojans. ``I think we're due,'' he said,
``for one of those lucky big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   It's undeniable that at critical junctures lately, the ball has
been bouncing only in UCLA's direction. &QL; 
1991: Blind-sided
</P>
<P>
   USC was down 17-0 just before the half, but quarterback Reggie
Perry brought the Trojans back. They trailed by three and were at
the UCLA 37, facing fourth-and-5, when they called time out with 1
minute, 19 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA opted to blitz Ale from the right, Perry's blind side. Ale
arrived practically with the shotgun snap, sacking Perry and
jolting the ball loose. Teammate Mike Chalenski recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember reading in the paper, their coach said I came
through clean,'' Ale said. ``But there was somebody in front of me.
All I remember is giving a head fake inside, the tackle bit, and I
swam outside. I was home free. I had a kill shot on the
quarterback, but I guess instinct told me to go for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fourth down. I didn't even bother going after the
fumble. I remember thinking the game was over. I just put my arms
in the air. What a great feeling.'' &QL; 
1992: Into coverage
</P>
<P>
   An excruciating defeat for USC. The Trojans had been up 31-17
early in the fourth quarter, but the Bruins swarmed them and took a
38-31 lead with just over three minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   USC quarterback Rob Johnson led a 69-yard touchdown drive and
sneaked in from 1 to pull his team within one point with 41 seconds
left. But on the two-point conversion try, Littleton broke up a
pass to the end zone for tight end Yonnie Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outside linebacker didn't get on (Jackson) right away, so
I just ran over there,'' Littleton said. ``I didn't think (Johnson)
was going to throw it, because I was over there. But he had a
history of throwing into coverage. (Laughs.) And he threw it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Repeated attempts to reach Johnson through the Buffalo Bills
were unsuccessful.)
</P>
<P>
   Littleton: ``They had called a time out. We were on the
sideline, and T.D. (then-coach Terry Donahue) said, `Who's going to
be the one to make this play?' I thought it would be me.'' &QL; 
1993: Picked off
</P>
<P>
   USC was down by six points when Johnson again directed a late
rally. He had the Trojans at first-and-goal from the UCLA 3 with
just over a minute left, but the Bruins stuffed running plays on
first and second down.
</P>
<P>
   On third down from the 2, Johnson's pass for Tyler Cashman was
intercepted by safety Marvin Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the same defense for second and third down, because I
thought they might throw it on second down,'' said UCLA assistant
head coach Bob Field, then the Bruins' defensive coordinator. (USC
rushed for only 7 yards in the game.) ``They came with play action
on third down. We were anticipating pass.'' &QL; 
1994: Maximum coverage
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was the culprit yet again, this time as USC held a
two-point lead in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After UCLA's Darren Schager punted 49 yards to the USC 12,
Phillip Ward sacked Johnson back to the 1 on first down. Then, on
third-and-21, disaster: A pass over the middle was tipped by Paul
Guidry and intercepted by Abdul McCullough.
</P>
<P>
   That set up the go-ahead touchdown for the Bruins and sparked
them to a 12-point victory.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA rushed only three men on the play and blanketed the
secondary with the rest. ``You've got to know it's a pass,'' said
Guidry. ``I was kind of anxious. I wanted to make some kind of
play, leave some kind of mark on the game. I deflected it and Abdul
just happened to be in the right place at the right time... He
still thanks me for it.'' &QL; 
1995: `Keep it'
</P>
<P>
   Cade McNown was a true freshman, all of 18 years old, playing
quarterback in a potentially terrifying situation at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Toledo, then the offensive coordinator, made a daring call
to heighten the tension even more.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA led 21-0 in the second quarter, but USC charged back,
pulling to within 24-20 with 3:30 to play. On the ensuing UCLA
possession, a false-start penalty and two 1-yard runs put the
Bruins in third-and-13 from their own 29. USC hungrily sought to
force a punt and mount a game-winning drive.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo put McNown in the shotgun, called a handoff to the
running back for a sweep left... and then told McNown _ and no one
else _ ``Keep it.'' McNown faked the handoff, fooled USC in
addition to his teammates, and dashed around right end for 21 yards
and a first down.
</P>
<P>
   USC never got the ball back. &QL; 
1996: Jarring it loose
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that mirrored '92 in terms of the miraculousness
of UCLA's comeback and the shock of defeat for USC.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans were up 31-14 early in the third quarter before UCLA
rallied to within a touchdown (38-31) inside the final three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins' subsequent onside kick went out of bounds, and
USC took over in the middle of the field, needing to run only 2:49
off the clock.
</P>
<P>
   On second-and-10 at the UCLA 41, USC's LaVale Woods gained 7
yards, only to lose the ball in a collision with Magee. Kusanti
Abdul-Salaam recovered for UCLA and returned the ball 11 yards. It
set up a game-tying touchdown for the Bruins, who went on to win in
two overtimes.
</P>
<P>
   Said Magee: ``If you watch it on TV, (then-USC coach John)
Robinson is going out there before the play telling Woods to hold
the ball, hold the ball, going like this (clamping hands
together)... I kind of jumped on him (Woods), threw myself toward
the ball and hung on it, almost parallel to the ground.'' &QL; 
1997: At the improv
</P>
<P>
   It was 21-21 in the third quarter, anyone's game, when McNown
came up to the line under daunting conditions: third-and-17 from
his own 18. He was nearly sacked, ducked out of trouble, scrambled,
and hit Danny Farmer for a 36-yard completion.
</P>
<P>
   It kept alive a drive that led to a 38-yard touchdown pass to
Mike Grieb, which put UCLA ahead for good.
</P>
<P>
   The play was pure improvisation. ``It exemplifies the way Cade
and I really know what each other is thinking,'' said Farmer.
``We've experienced so much together, our minds kind of work the
same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Said offensive coordinator Alan Borges: ``I think that's what
great players do _ they bail you out of some jams. Look, over the
years, at every great quarterback, whether it's Joe Montana or
Roger Staubach: They always had that escape dimension or ability to
buy a couple of extra seconds to get somebody open.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown has spent the week going into contortions to play down
his miracle-working against USC. ``It's the biggest game of the
year, but I'm not worried about what has happened or what may
happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McNown is probably kidding himself. Every player who takes the
field Saturday at the Rose Bowl will be mindful of making the play
on which the game will swing.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost count on a play or plays ``in the critical part
of the game,'' said UCLA's Field, ``that will go down in history.
And a few years from now, somebody will be wanting to recall
those.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows,'' said USC's Thurman, ``when that one play is
coming?''!end!
</P>
<P>
   BACK-BREAKERS &QL; 
Pivotal plays during UCLA's seven-game win streak against USC. &QL; 
Year: 1991. &QL; 
Play: Trailing by three points, USC is at the UCLA 37 with 1:19 to
play, and faces fourth-and-five. After quarterback Reggie Perry
takes the snap in the shotgun, linebacker Arnold Ale tracks him
down from the blind side, producing a sack that results in a
fumble. &QL; 
Final score: UCLA 24, USC 21. &QL; 
Year: 1992. &QL; 
Play: USC is down by seven when quarterback Rob Johnson burrows in
from the 1-yard line with 41 seconds left to cut the lead to one.
On the two-point conversion try, Johnson's pass is knocked down in
the end zone by linebacker Nkosi Littleton. &QL; 
Final score: UCLA 38, USC 37. &QL; 
Year: 1993. &QL; 
Play: With 50 seconds left, as USC is attempting to tie the game
with a touchdown, Johnson's third-down pass from the 2 is
intercepted in the end zone by Marvin Goodwin. &QL; 
Final score: UCLA 27, USC 21. &QL; 
Year: 1994. &QL; 
Play: UCLA trails by two in the third quarter as Johnson delivers a
pass from his own 1-yard line. Paul Guidry deflects the ball and
Abdul McCullough intercepts for UCLA to set up the go-ahead
touchdown. &QL; 
Final score: UCLA 31, USC 19. &QL; 
Year: 1995. &QL; 
Play: USC has rallied to within four points, and UCLA faces
third-and-13 from its own 29 with less than three minutes left.
Freshman quarterback Cade McNown scrambles for a 21-yard gain and
the Trojans never get the ball back. &QL; 
Final score: UCLA 24, USC 20. &QL; 
Year: 1996. &QL; 
Play: USC has a seven-point lead and the ball with 1:37 to play.
But UCLA linebacker Danjuan Magee strips LaVale Woods of the ball
and Kusanti Abdul-Salaam recovers. It sets up the tying touchdown
in the final minute, and UCLA goes on to win in two overtimes. &QL; 
Final score: UCLA 48, USC 41. &QL; 
Year: 1997. &QL; 
Play: With the game tied 21-21 in the third quarter, UCLA faces
third-and-17 from its own 18. McNown scurries out of danger to
complete a 36-yard pass to Danny Farmer, which sets up the
game-deciding touchdown. &QL; 
Final score: UCLA 31, USC 24. &QL; 
_Eric Noland
</P>
