A8333 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-VOLUNTEER-KAN &LR;      11-19 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-VOLUNTEER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL VOLUNTEER PART OF AIDS VACCINE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   (Kansas City, Mo.) _ There was nothing
he could do when his best friend died of AIDS. He felt helpless as
the disease felled dozens of other friends and acquaintances.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now this 45-year-old Kansas City man, who wants to remain
anonymous, is taking bold steps against AIDS. Last week, he became
the first local person to participate in testing of an experimental
AIDS vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he met with reporters to urge others to volunteer
for the vaccine trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole concept of this is hope,'' he said at a press
conference at the Kansas City AIDS Research Consortium.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all we have. We watched our friends, our families, our
lovers die of AIDS and we were helpless. Now with the vaccines and
new drugs, and with hope, we'll be here for the cure.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City is among the first 10 cities to take part in a
three-to-four-year study of AIDSVAX, the only AIDS vaccine so far
to reach the final stage of testing.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers hope to eventually enroll about 5,000 men and women
in several dozen U.S. cities to see if AIDSVAX can protect people
from infection with HIV, the AIDS virus. Each subject will receive
a series of seven injections of either the vaccine or a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, the AIDS Research Consortium expects to enroll
150 subjects in the study.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium's first volunteer describes himself as a longtime
political and gay rights activist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, he became an AIDS activist as well after his lifelong
best friend developed AIDS-related pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call in the middle of the night that he was dead. It
was a shock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That shock has been followed by many others over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of weeks ago I was reading the obituaries and I
realized, if I were to put the name of every person who was a
friend or that I knew who had died of AIDS it would cover the whole
obituary page of BEGIN ITAL The Kansas City Star END ITAL.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he is open about his bisexuality, the consortium's
first volunteer wants to remain anonymous to protect himself from
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   This safeguard is necessary because the vaccine study uses
volunteers who are free of HIV, but who engage in sex that puts
them at high risk of infection, said Jan Meier, the consortium's
clinical director.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tell people you're in the study, you've admitted you
engage in some unsafe sexual behavior,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In other cities where the vaccine has been used for some time,
people who have gone public about their participation in the study
have been met with hostility by friends, family and co-workers,
Meier said.
</P>
<P>
   All study participants receive periodic counseling sessions on
safe sex to avoid infection. They also are warned that they might
have received a placebo rather than the vaccine. One-third of the
participants get a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Although AIDSVAX is considered safe, there is no proof yet that
it offers protection against infection. In fact, some researchers
doubt this vaccine is strong enough to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some other AIDS vaccines being developed, AIDSVAX does
not use HIV itself. Instead, it contains a protein the virus uses
as a biological ``key'' to enter and destroy human cells.
</P>
<P>
   By priming the body's immune system to recognize this protein,
scientists hope people exposed to HIV will be able to mount a
successful fight against the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Warnings to avoid unsafe sex and the possibility of HIV
infection may not be needed by the consortium's first volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always tried to practice safer sex,'' he said. ``That's
why I'm HIV-negative today.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I will also continue to try and protect myself.
This (vaccine) does not give me permission to go out and practice
unsafe sex. I consider everyone at risk. There's no such thing as
(completely) safe sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen more local volunteers will receive their first shots
this week, and the consortium is on target to have 40 or 50
subjects enrolled by the end of the year, Meier said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
