A8334 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      11-19 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILES PRENTICE RAISES HOPES ON LOCAL FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   When Miles Prentice put his effort to
buy the Royals over the top, it culminated an individual leadership
initiative the likes of which Kansas Citians rarely see anymore.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thus, keeping major league baseball in Kansas City also seems to
bring with it the bonus of a powerful new dynamic in the higher
echelons of local civic life.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice no doubt will have his hands full creating contenders
on the field and achieving profitability off it. Nevertheless, by
establishing his credentials as a can-do guy, he's raised a lot of
hopes in a community where can-do types are at a premium.
</P>
<P>
   If Prentice is to fulfill the community expectations he's
created, he'd be well advised to counsel early and often with R.
Crosby Kemper Jr., who's another can-do guy.
</P>
<P>
   No offense to all others who partnered up with Prentice to save
the Royals for Kansas City, but Kemper is arguably the first among
ownership equals when it comes to exerting influence on local civic
and business life. The willingness of Kemper to get on Prentice's
bandwagon early gave the New Yorker's quest much-needed credibility
when most other heavy hitters were conspicuous by their absence.
</P>
<P>
   If Prentice is amenable to some mentoring by Kemper, the most
important thing he's likely to learn is the importance of
individual action in Kansas City. Kemper has been critical of the
local ``committee mentality,'' and was quoted earlier this year as
saying, ``We like to do things in groups so we're not overly
criticized.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a keen insight, because it recognizes that when everyone is
in charge, nobody is in charge. This has often created a leadership
vacuum in local circles.
</P>
<P>
   What has distinguished Kemper over the years is his willingness
to act decisively as an individual and stand any gaff that may come
his way as a result. Ewing M. Kauffman, who willed his Kansas City
Royals to his hometown, was another shining example of a business
leader and civic benefactor who did great things for his community
while marching to his own drummer.
</P>
<P>
   As a new kid on the block, Prentice will be subject to criticism
and vulnerable to the yearning it often creates to become one of
the crowd. Kemper may not know much about baseball, but his most
important contribution to the Royals' success will be as Prentice's
rock when the going gets tough. If Prentice is as keen a student of
people as he seems, he knows by now Kemper is the sort you want in
a foxhole with you. The other co-owners should also understand
this.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive aspect of Prentice's job of assembling his
diverse group of co-owners is where he went to find them. While
most everyone recognizes the marquee value of co-owners such as
Kemper and golf legend Tom Watson, most others who stepped up for
Kansas City in this instance aren't part of the usually
acknowledged cadre of civic and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame some leading lights didn't accept the challenge of
trying to keep big league baseball in Kansas City, but it isn't
surprising. While many pursue good works for the community as they
perceive them individually, their collective influence for the most
part has been hollowed out by a reluctance to provide a more
visible rallying point.
</P>
<P>
   If Prentice helps fill this void, it's a win-win situation for
Kansas City.  &LR; tag1:Jerry Heaster's column appears Wednesdays,
Fridays, Saturdays and Sundays. To reach him, write the business
desk at 1729 Grand Blvd., Kansas City MO 64108. To share a comment
on StarTouch, call {(816) 889-7827} and enter {2301}. Send e-mail
to {jheaster &LR; kcstar.com}
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 0030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
