<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REFILING TO FIX SLUG IN NOTES FIELD) 
STARR CHOSE NOT TO SEND REPORT ON WHITEWATER TO CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Late last year, Kenneth Starr wrote a draft
impeachment report centering on President Clinton's purported
involvement in the complicated Whitewater land deal, but decided
not to send it to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel shelved the report after concluding that
the key witnesses accusing Clinton of wrongdoing were felons whose
credibility was suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The description of what brought Starr and his prosecutors to the
brink of a confrontation with Clinton is outlined in the 58-page
presentation that the independent counsel will deliver on Thursday
in his high-stakes appearance before the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Starr exonerates Clinton of personal
culpability in several other inquiries, including the dismissal of
the White House travel office staff and the administration's
improper gathering of hundreds of FBI files on former Republican
officials.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr makes clear that the travel office investigation ``is
not terminated,'' with an announcement of ``decisions and actions
soon.'' Starr also notes there are still ``outstanding issues''
involving one person in the FBI files matter.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony represents Starr's most detailed accounting of his
investigations outside the Monica Lewinsky matter since his
appointment in August 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In summing up the four-year, $40 million inquiry, Starr says,
``The pattern of obstruction of justice, false statements and
misuse of executive authority in the Lewinsky investigation did not
occur in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   As Starr sought to show a pattern of obstruction and
stonewalling by the Clinton administration, he emphasized, and
reserved his strongest language, for the Arkansas land deal.
</P>
<P>
   The basic outlines are well known. Madison Guaranty Savings and
Loan, a Little Rock entity run by the Clintons' business partners,
James B. McDougal and his then-wife, Susan, collapsed. Mrs. Clinton
performed legal work in the 1980s for Madison, which Starr called a
``metaphor'' for the savings and loan crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madison Guaranty was a disaster,'' he said. ``It gambled with
investments, cooked the books and ultimately bilked the taxpayers
of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's inquiry focused on whether Madison money had been used
illegally to help business and political figures in Arkansas.
Indeed, one loan of $300,000 went to what Starr called Susan
McDougal's ``make-believe'' company, Master Marketing, and $50,000
of that benefited Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   Subpoenaed as a defense witness, Clinton testified at the trial
of McDougal and Jim Guy Tucker, a former Arkansas governor, that he
did not know about the loan to Susan McDougal and had never
discussed it with McDougal or an Arkansas businessman, David Hale.
But Hale contradicted the president's statement.
</P>
<P>
   And, Starr said, so did McDougal, after he was convicted and
agreed to cooperate with the indpendent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim McDougal said on one of his first sessions with our office
that the president's trial testimony was, in his words, `at
variance with the truth.'''
</P>
<P>
   Starr acknowledges for the first time that Tucker was not as
useful as prosecutors believed he would be, though he did ``shed
light'' on some Whitewater related deals.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also says that Clinton encouraged Susan McDougal to
stonewall. Starr refers to a September 1996 interview Clinton gave
to PBS, in which he said, ``there's a lot of evidence to support''
various charges that Ms. McDougal made against Starr's office. But
Clinton cited no evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's language is searing: ``Essentially, the president of the
United States, the chief executive, sided with a convicted felon
against the United States, as represented by United States District
Judge Susan Webber Wright, the United States Court of Appeals for
the Eighth Circuit, and the Office of the Independent Counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   An offshoot of the original inquiry centered on the work done
for Madison in 1985 and 1986 by the Rose Law Firm, where Hillary
Rodham Clinton was a partner. Billing records related to Mrs.
Clinton's work at the firm were subpoenaed, but for two years could
not be found. They had apparently disappeared in the White House
residence. Two years later the records mysteriously turned up.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a thorough investigation, we have found no explanation
how the billing records got where they were or why they were not
discovered and produced earlier,'' Starr says in his testimony.
``It remains a mystery to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate Whitewater committee concluded that there was no
other credible explanation than that Mrs. Clinton concealed the
records.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Starr says that he believed Webster L.
Hubbell, a partner at the Rose Law Firm with Mrs. Clinton, and
later a top Justice Department official, might have additional
information.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Hubbell became the focus of Starr's inquiry, after he
had resigned his Justice position, he received payments totaling
$550,000 from several companies and individuals. Many were campaign
donors.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Starr gives his strongest assertion so far
that Clinton supporters bought Hubbell's silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of this $550,000 was given to Mr. Hubbell for little or
no work,'' Starr states. ``This rush of generosity obviously gives
rise to an inference that the money was essentially a gift. And if
it was a gift, why was it a gift? This money was given despite the
fact that Mr. Hubbell was under criminal investigation for
fraudulent billing and was a key witness in the Madison Guaranty
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Starr indicted Hubbell on 15 counts of false
statements and other charges, and said in his statement it would be
inappropriate to discuss the case further.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Starr gives a dispassionate account of the
facts _ as he and his prosecutors see them. But at the end, he
adopts a much more personal tone as he defends his office, his
employees, his methods and his mandate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the hurricane-force political winds swirling about us,
we were well aware that, no matter what decision we made, criticism
would come from somewhere,'' Starr says.
</P>
</TEXT>
