<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-LAWSUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE GIVES EX-LOCKHEED WORKERS ULTIMATUM OVER LAWSUIT DAMAGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Former Lockheed workers who were awarded $760
million in punitive damages have been given a choice by the judge
who presided over their case: Accept a new verdict that slashes the
amount in half or face a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Richard Hubbell stated in a
one-page ruling this week that the 38 plaintiffs who worked on
stealth fighters at the company's suburban Burbank facility have
until Friday to make their decision.
</P>
<P>
   All of the damages were levied against Exxon, Shell Oil, Ashland
Inc., Unocal Corp. and DuPont Co. Lockheed settled out of the
lawsuit for $33 million in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court in its independent judgment determines from the
evidence that (the) amount of the reduced judgment is fair and
reasonable,'' Hubbell wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The jury reached its verdict on the punitive damages Aug. 6,
awarding $760 million -- believed to be the largest payout of its
kind in California history. Hubbell's ruling would cut the award to
$380 million.
</P>
<P>
   The workers claimed they contracted cancer, skin ailments,
breathing problems, psychological damage and other conditions
because of inadequate warning labels on dozens of chemicals and
solvents near the Lockheed assembly lines.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless what choice is made, defendants' attorney Kevin Mayer
said the five companies will appeal the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our position that no amount of punitive damages should
have been awarded in these cases,'' Mayer said.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' lawyer Thomas Girardi could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell's ruling, which was signed Monday, states that the
punitive damages awarded were excessive.
</P>
<P>
   He said a new trial would be granted if the plaintiffs do not
accept the reduction in damages. The ruling does not change the
$25.4 million verdict for compensatory damages, determined by the
same jury a week before the punitive damages verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants' lawyers were critical of the judge's conduct during
the trial, claiming he erred when he told jurors to ``send a
message'' with the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed's Skunk Works plant produced several top-secret
aircraft, including the U-2 spy plane. The plaintiffs, one of
several groups to sue the chemical manufacturers over alleged
problems at Lockheed, claim they were exposed to toxins while
working on stealth fighters.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
