A8340 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREE-SPEECH-SUIT19-CO     11-19 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREE-SPEECH-SUIT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT to defend pamphlet policy against U.S. court challenge
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Think Erwin Center at the University of Texas
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Hear the rock music blaring from an Aerosmith concert _ or the
sweet, sugary sounds of an Ice Capades show.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the place you'd expect to be a battleground in a
fight for free expression. But in 1996, four environmental
activists say they were threatened with arrest outside the Erwin
Center after attempting to pass out pamphlets _ a violation, they
later learned, of a university policy that prohibits any
nonstudents, nonfaculty or nonstaff from distributing leaflets on
UT property.
</P>
<P>
   Today in federal court the four activists will challenge the
policy, which they say is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university is supposed to be a place of free inquiry and
speech and intellectual dialogue, so to prevent people from
peaceably passing out information is terribly wrong,'' said
environmentalist Robert Brister, 43, a plaintiff in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   James Todd, an attorney representing UT, said that like many
universities, UT restricts the distribution of leaflets for fear of
having such activities overrun the campus and interfere with
students attempting to get to class.
</P>
<P>
   ``University space is not unlimited,'' he said. ``It's still
primarily an educational institution, and the first priority is the
teaching of students in classes and laboratories.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 19, 1996, Brister and three other members of Austin
Greens and Austin Earth First _ Roger Baker, Eric Samson and
William Medaille _ attempted to pass out fliers outside the Erwin
Center. The fliers, titled ``World Scientists' Warning to
Humanity,'' documented the toll of pollution and exploding human
populations on the environment. The group targeted the delegates of
the National Issues Convention, which brought together
representatives from all 50 states to discuss issues ranging from
the environment to campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt the people taking part would not be exposed to any
views outside the mainstream Democratic or Republican points of
view,'' said Brister, a founding member of Austin Greens, the local
chapter of the national Green Party USA, a group that supports
issues ranging from protecting the environment to promoting femi-
nism. Since filing
</P>
<P>
   his lawsuit, Bristol has moved to California.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the sidewalk outside the Erwin Center is considered
university property, according to UT officials, and therefore only
officially sanctioned student, staff or faculty groups can
distribute fliers.
</P>
<P>
   Todd said such policies are common on college campuses. ``Any
state university is entitled, if it wants to, to reserve its
properties for the activities of students, faculty and staff,'' he
said. ``Courts all the way up to the Supreme Court have upheld a
university's right not to open its facilities to free speech by
people who are not students, faculty or staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Owen, an attorney representing Brister and the other
plaintiffs, argues that the Erwin Center, which has come to play
host to a wide range of nonuniversity public events from concerts
to dance shows, is in the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they open it up for access, they can't pick and choose
who can come or what they do once they get there,'' Owen said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, environmental groups such as Save Our Springs have
gotten around the regulation against passing out fliers on campuses
by recruiting students to form their own chapters, in order to
distribute the group's literature, Todd said. Such affiliate
student groups must be approved by the dean of students. They can
then distribute any information, so long as it doesn't constitute
solicitation.
</P>
<P>
   UT police said the policy has not been an issue in the past
because outside groups rarely come to campus intending to pass out
leaflets, and if they do, they go about their business so subtly,
they don't attract the attention of campus police or
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that happens often,'' said Sgt. Dennis
Chartier. ``Occasionally, someone will put up posters or fliers
inside buildings. In those cases, people usually will report it to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks will hear testimony from both
sides today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-11-18-98 2126E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
