u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIAMI-U-RALLY19-COX     11-19 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-U-RALLY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students call for swift, strong action on racial hate incidents
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Ohio _ Miami University students Wednesday night called
on University President James Garland to expand diversity efforts
and react more swiftly and strongly to racial hate incidents on
campus.
</P>
<P>
   While some students painted a dismal picture of race relations
on Miami's campus, others defended the university's record and
called on students to initiate needed changes.
</P>
<P>
   The event was billed as a discussion between Garland and a group
of 50 students about the climate on campus for minority students. A
crowd of nearly 500 attended the discussion, but participation was
limited to the 50 selected by Miami's Black Student Action
Association and Student Government Association.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting followed an Oct. 30 incident in the University's
Black Cultural Center in which someone installed racist messages on
computer screens and posted racist leaflets. Last week, a group of
students protested what they viewed as a lack of action by Miami
officials, blocking a street near campus. Seven students were
arrested during the second demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   Garland announced Wednesday the creation of a reward fund of at
least $1,000 for information that assists in apprehension of
suspects involved in the racist messages.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion Wednesday included some spirited exchanges, often
interrupted by applause or grumblings from the audience, but was
overall calm and well-mannered.
</P>
<P>
   Black students described insensitive and insulting remarks by
professors in class and said Miami's diversity efforts are
insufficient. And they pressured Garland to block any university
punishment of the seven arrested students. Garland declined, saying
it would be unfair to treat some students who break the law
differently from others.
</P>
<P>
   One student noted the small proportion of black students and the
hostile climate on campus. ``This campus trains people to be
racist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nathan Estep, Miami's Student Government President and a
black student, suggested that he and other Miami students are
``spoiled.''
</P>
<P>
   Students ``come here expecting it be a utopia'' _ with no
racism, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Estep called on students to improve the climate on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Garland can't make it happen from his office,'' Estep
said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Estep issued a statement expressing ``disdain'' for his
fellow students' protest tactics last week. He said the student
protesters ``insist instead of understand, attack rather than
heal.''
</P>
<P>
   After the forum, Garland led a unity rally outside the Student
Union that featured remarks from Oxford's mayor, local residents,
faculty and others.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
