<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-SHIRTS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 Falcons feather nests with `Bird' shirts
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To the victors go the spoils.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what two Falcons players are hoping.
</P>
<P>
   Starting right guard Gene Williams and deep snapper Adam
Schreiber have started a corporation named Dirty Birds Football, in
honor of the team's new touchdown celebration dance, and have
started selling T-shirts and hats.
</P>
<P>
   The players are trying to capitalize on the Falcons' NFC
West-leading 8-2 start.
</P>
<P>
   By next week, fans will be able to place orders on the Internet.
A Web site _ dirtybirdsinc.com _ is under construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam and myself thought this was a pretty good thing, so we
paid $250 to apply for a trademark for the term `Dirty Birds
Football,' and we hired an attorney to help form a corporation,''
Williams said. ``Basically, our mission is to get the Dirty Birds
out there in the public.''
</P>
<P>
   The first black T-shirts say ``Dirty Birds Football'' on the
front and ``You can do eet'' on the back and were worn by players
Friday after practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Dirty Birds name was bestowed on the team by tight end O.J.
Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Philadelphia game (Sept. 13), an old guy in the
stands pointed at me and said, `Dirty Birds, baby,' and from then
on I was saying it everywhere,'' Santiago explained. ``I took it
into the locker room, and before long everybody was saying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a few days before the New England game Nov. 8, many of the
players saw the movie ``The Water Boy'' and borrowed the ``You can
do eet'' line.
</P>
<P>
   The players repeated the line often in the locker room before
the game against the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   When Santiago scored two touchdowns and unveiled his end-zone
dance, the Dirty Bird theme took flight.
</P>
<P>
   So Williams, an 8-year veteran from Omaha, Neb., and Schreiber,
a 15-year veteran from Galveston, Texas, got busy.
</P>
<P>
   They hired former Falcons public-relations assistant Bill Rosen,
who was with the team from 1994-97. Thursday, Rosen went to
Hartsfield International Airport to see if vendors were interested
in the merchandise and has talked with numerous retail outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some business cards printed up, and I was handing them
out at last Sunday's (game) in the Georgia Dome,'' Rosen said.
``We've taken orders for a few dozen T-shirts, but I've placed an
order for 25 dozen more. They'll be available in black and white.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes the Department of Trademarks and Patents between three
and six months to process an application. But Williams and
Schreiber said they already have secured exclusive rights to the
phrase. Williams said other slogans will appear on shirts soon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
