A8351 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEARDOWN-SNAFU-LADN     11-19 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEARDOWN-SNAFU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY RENOVATING CIVIC BUILDING SCHEDULED FOR DEMOLITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICK McGREEVY and DEBORAH SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The city is spending $470,000 to renovate the
one-stop building permit facility at the Van Nuys Civic Center,
even though the building is scheduled to be torn down in two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles City Council approved the project based on a
report that failed to say the building will be razed to make way
for the new, $35 million center for government services in the
suburban San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Some city officials said the Valley deserves an improved
building permit office, even if it will be demolished in just two
years. But some council members said that if they had known the
Civic Center was to be torn down, they might have opposed spending
money on remodeling the one-stop permit center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not have been in favor of that,'' said Councilman Nate
Holden. ``The money should be used to remodel only if it was not
going to be demolished.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mike Feuer also now questions the need for such a
project, said spokesman Daniel Hinerfeld. ``He does not think it
makes sense to pour that kind of capital into a building that is
not going to be around in two years,'' Hinerfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   But Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski, who championed the
renovation project, said the work is justified. She said the fact
that the demolition wasn't noted in the report is unimportant
because the center is needed, even if just for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that there is a building boom and Van Nuys is
encountering a large number of new applications for permits, I
think it's money well spent,'' Miscikowski said.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the money is coming from a surcharge imposed on
each building permit issued, so the city is not spending money from
its general fund.
</P>
<P>
   The $470,000 project was approved by the City Council last month
to relieve crowded conditions at the Van Nuys Construction Service
Center. The office allows residents and developers to obtain
necessary permits from city agencies at a single location.
</P>
<P>
   About $233,000 will be spent to enlarge the public area,
lengthen the public counter and redesign the layout of the office,
said Claire Bartels, the city's project manager for the Van Nuys
Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   Other money will be spent to relocate workers to temporary
offices during the renovation. About $100,000 will be spent on
computers and other equipment that can be transferred to the new
Civic Center, Bartels said.
</P>
<P>
   But roughly 80 percent of the cost, or about $376,000, will not
be transferable, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   This week, workers were replacing stand-up counters with
desk-height ones, and they moved them back from the walls to create
a larger waiting area.
</P>
<P>
   When completed, the remodeled center will have a computerized
check-in system and a waiting area with a free fax machine, copier,
computer and phones, said Steve MacDonald, director of development
services for building and safety.
</P>
<P>
   The renovations have been needed but deferred since the
mid-1980s, when the building was last remodeled, MacDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a choice to make: Do we provide improved conditions for
Valley residents now, or make them wait?'' he said. ``And it was
the opinion of our department, the One-Stop Committee, the City
Council and the mayor that we provide the type of customer service
the Valley deserves now.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers waiting for service seemed unaware of the improvements
under way for their benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really familiar with it, but I just stepped in a big
puddle of cement over there,'' said Roger Camras of Van Nuys,
cleaning gray muck off his shoe as he waited to submit plans for a
new garage. ``I don't know what they're doing. Looks like they're
improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Bergerson said the office, whether before or after, was
fine with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked pretty well before,'' said Bergerson, an architect
in nearby Woodland Hills. ``And anything that they can improve on
will be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Valley civic activists who routinely push to improve Valley
services said the expenditure is wasteful and a sign of poor
planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to spend that kind of money now. It does not
make sense,'' said Gordon Murley, president of the San Fernando
Valley Federation, a coalition of area homeowner groups. ``They can
wait until the new building is finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Silver, president of Homeowners of Encino, also said the
money could be better spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears shortsighted,'' Silver said, noting that the city
needs more money to buy up property around the expanding Civic
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said he is concerned that wasting money will only add
momentum to a create a Valley city that would be separate from Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Don Schultz, president of the Van Nuys Homeowners Association,
said he believes work on a new Civic Center will take more than two
years, which will extend the usefulness of the one-stop permit
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we see this in five years, we'll be lucky,'' Schultz said.
</P>
<P>
   Final plans for the new Civic Center, including a lease
arrangement with the developer, are scheduled to go to the City
Council in two months for approval, with construction expected to
take two years. The existing Building and Safety Department
structure will not be demolished until the new Civic Center is
completed, Bartels said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Civic Center is rebuilt, the one-stop permit center
will be relocated there. The 50-year-old building that houses the
office now will be torn down to provide a pedestrian mall, Bartels
said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Close, chairman of Valley Voters Organized Toward
Empowerment, said he wonders whether spending money on a building
permit office is a sign that the city might back away from the
Civic Center project.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always get suspicious when you put more money like this
into a temporary building,'' Close said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
