<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TO DEPORT FOREIGN REPORTER, SECOND IN A MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 6th graf, Kremb, 41 ..., to CORRECT number of years he
has reported FROM China to EIGHT, sted seven.) 
 (JT) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China Wednesday expelled a reporter for the German
news magazine Der Spiegel, one day after eight officials burst into
his office and accused him of possessing secret documents. The
reporter, Juergen Kremb, said he was told he must leave China
within 48 hours and could not return for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Last month another foreign reporter, from the Japanese newspaper
Yomiuri Shimbun, was also charged with possessing state secrets and
was deported.
</P>
<P>
   Both reporters denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   In China almost any political or economic information that has
not been published in the state media or announced by a senior
official can be defined as a state secret, giving the authorities a
ready tool for attacking people seen as opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Both recent cases involved reporters who have angered security
agencies with their reporting on human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
   Kremb, 41, has reported from China for eight years. He is the
author of a recent biography of Wei Jingsheng, the prominent
democracy advocate who was sent from prison into exile in the
United States last fall.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Kremb was detained for two days when he visited Wei's
family in Anhui Province. In a spottily enforced rule, journalists
are supposed to obtain the permission of provincial authorities
before conducting interviews anywhere in China.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer Kremb began working in Singapore, but he was in
Beijing this week in the latest of several reporting trips before
his official accreditation and visa to work here as a journalist
expire at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Kremb said the agents who raided his office pushed him roughly
against a wall and read loudly from a document accusing him of
violating the law. They searched the office for three hours, then
confronted him with what they said were secret papers he held, and
demanded that he sign a confession.
</P>
<P>
   Kremb said he had refused to sign, and suggested that the
officers might have planted evidence. ``I was shown documents but
refused to touch or even read them,'' he told the Reuters news
agency. ``I haven't been in my office for a long time and I don't
even know if they were mine.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday, the Chinese foreign ministry said,
``Mr. Kremb illegally possessed secret Chinese documents in
violation of the law.'' The security agents lawfully searched
Kremb's office, the statement said, ``found a large amount of
evidence and ordered him to leave China.''
</P>
<P>
   The German foreign ministry said it had complained about the
treatment of Kremb to the Chinese ambassador in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
