<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' FISET NERVOUS ABOUT RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ For Stephane Fiset, the past month on the sidelines
has been a taxing time, both physically and mentally, as he's
worked to recover from the effects of the two groin strains that
have deprived the Kings of their No.1 goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't feel like you're part of the team,'' Fiset said
after a full practice Wednesday morning before the Kings' game
against the San Jose Sharks. ``You feel sad and frustrated every
day. You want to go out and help the team win some games.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as soon as tonight, when the Kings play host to the New
York Rangers, Fiset will get the chance to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he says he's ready to go (today),'' Kings coach Larry
Robinson said Wednesday, ``he's in.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he returns tonight _ or Saturday at home against
Chicago, or later than that _ Fiset said he will be a tad wary.
After all, he's working on a two-game groin-straining streak, and
he doesn't want it to reach three.
</P>
<P>
   Originally injured in a 5-5 tie with Colorado on Oct.18, Fiset
returned 10 days later against New Jersey, only to suffer another
groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure, I'm going to be thinking about it, and I'm going to
be scared about it,'' Fiset said. ``But if I think about it, I'm
going to go out there and get hurt again. I have to think about
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Storr almost ready: Trainer Peter Demers said goalie Jamie
Storr, who also suffered a groin strain on Oct.18, also is close to
returning. Once he is deemed healthy, Storr may play a couple of
games for the Long Beach Ice Dogs before rejoining the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week from now, hopefully we'll have them both back,'' Demers
said of Fiset and Storr.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, this most likely will mean a return to Long Beach
for goalie Manny Legace. Because he's been with the Kings on
emergency recall, Legace will not need to clear waivers to return
to the minors. Legace did have to clear waivers when the Kings
assigned him to Long Beach before the season.
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Demers said the return of No.1 center Jozef Stumpel
_ who on Monday sprained his right ankle for the second time in two
months _ is uncertain. ``The next day or two will tell us quite a
bit,'' Demers said. ``Once we get past the acute stage of the
injury, we'll take a look at it.'' Stumpel, the Kings' leading
scorer last season, has played in just eight of the Kings' first 19
games.... The healthy scratches against San Jose were center Ray
Ferraro and winger Josh Green.... Defenseman Doug Bodger (broken
hand) may return to the lineup within two weeks.... Eric Lacroix is
the latest King to sport a closely shaven head of hair, joining
Mattias Norstrom, Vladimir Tsyplakov and Ian Laperriere. In fact,
Laperriere was Lacroix's barber. ``You've got to start somewhere,''
Laperriere said when asked about his fledgling career as a
hairdresser. Describing Lacroix's hairdo, Ferraro said, ``You ever
see `Full Metal Jacket?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
