A8360 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TCU-NEW-ORLEANS-T     11-19 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-NEW-ORLEANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROGS' WIN SPARKED BY FOWLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jennifer Floyd 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU coach Billy Tubbs posed a rhetorical
question about guard Prince Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you think we'd be in trouble if he doesn't play?'' Tubbs
said.
</P>
<P>
   He got his answer in last night's 74-61 victory against New
Orleans (0-1) at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum, and the evidence said yes.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler didn't start, and TCU (3-1) struggled.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler said Tubbs had benched him for an altercation with a
teammate in practice this week. Fowler finally came in with 14:54
remaining before halftime, when TCU had more turnovers (4) than
points (2).
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he didn't start Fowler, Tubbs simply said: ``I
didn't want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler admitted that he and freshman guard Michael Causey had
exchanged a few pushes and a few unkind words. He said both were
fine now, and that he had learned from his experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing serious. I understood what coach Tubbs meant,''
Fowler said about being unable to start. ``I had to wake up after
that. I know this team needs me.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU lost Fowler again late in the second half when he aggravated
a groin strain after slipping on a wet spot on the floor. Fowler
said he had been struggling with the strain for about a week, but
that he'd likely play in Saturday's game at UT-El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hoped he'd sit out the whole game,'' New Orleans coach Joey
Stiebing said. ``I think he was the key to the game. Every time we
got close, he hit big shots.''
</P>
<P>
   When Fowler came in, he immediately assisted on buckets by Lee
Nailon and Ryan Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   He also had a couple of crucial 3-pointers in helping the Horned
Frogs distance themselves from pesky New Orleans. He finished with
15 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's in, everything runs so smooth,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs looked anything but smooth in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   They attempted to bang the ball inside to Nailon despite double
teams that swamped him. Turnovers resulted, 25 in all and 12 that
Tubbs characterized as careless and unforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had Lee Nailon, I'd be trying to get it to him, too,''
Stiebing said.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans anticipated this and sent a swarm of bodies to
surround him. His shots were all contested. His body constantly
banged. His arm constantly bumped.
</P>
<P>
   Nailon finished with 17 points, seven on free throws, and 12
rebounds, and Frogs forward Marquise Gainous had 14 points and 12
rebounds. It was the first time both players had a double-double in
the same game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to shoot when you have 210 pounds draped on your
arm,'' Tubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   Stiebing said that had been his plan. He wanted to force
somebody other than Nailon beat him.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler answered that call when he came in. He said being unable
to start had inspired him, as he had been trying to do in practice.
He said he just got a little too aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get a fire into the team because we've been
slacking,'' Fowler said. ``Nobody has stepped up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler looks like he just did.
</P>
</TEXT>
