<SLUG> BC-FBC-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
McKAY WAS ARCHITECT OF USC POWERHOUSE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was no one, not Bear Bryant, not Woody Hayes, not Bo
Schembechler, not Bob Devaney, not anyone else at the time, bigger
in college football than John McKay was in 1975 when he decided to
leave the sport.
</P>
<P>
   There was no one who had a built a stronger program than the
colossus he created during his 16 seasons at the University of
Southern California when his teams went 127-40-8.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, John McKay willingly gave up his fiefdom and the power and
adulation that went with it to accept a lucrative offer to take
command of an NFL expansion team called the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   He would have moments of success with the Buccaneers during
those three seasons the team qualified for the playoffs, but there
were lengthy bleak periods like a 26-game losing streak that
resulted in his having to endure national mockery and cruel
ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   It always has been the feeling here that John McKay chose the
wrong career path, that he would have become one of the revered
figures of American athletics had he remained at USC.
</P>
<P>
   I've always wondered about his feelings on the subject, and I
finally got a chance to ask him about it the other day when I
reached him at his home in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any regrets about leaving USC when you did?'' I
asked McKay, who wound up 44-88-1 during his nine seasons with the
Bucs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought at the time it was good for me to make a change,''
he said. ``I had gone about as far as I could go at the university.
They weren't making me a wealthy man. I was making $48,000 at the
time I left.''
</P>
<P>
   John McKay would earn a lot more money working for Hugh
Culverhouse in Tampa Bay, but he never again would ascend to the
dizzying heights he did when his Trojans were rolling through the
autumns with a monotonous ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``So no regrets leaving USC?'' I said again.
</P>
<P>
   There was a brief pause, but this time John McKay answered
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, to be honest with you, I wish I never would have
left,'' he said. ``I was happier in L.A. The people treated me so
well there. I've been treated well in Florida, too. But it was
different in L.A. I think the family liked it better there. I wish
I had never left.''
</P>
<P>
   McKay's voice evokes images of USC gridiron grandeur ...
astounding comebacks against Notre Dame, O.J. Simpson's 64-yard,
game-winning, Rose Bowl-clinching run against UCLA, Anthony Davis'
spectacular kickoff returns, historic victories over Alabama,
maulings of Woody Hayes, national championships, etc., etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   His voice still is strong and vibrant, as it was when it barked
orders to a generation of athletes that turned USC into the most
feared football school in the country.
</P>
<P>
   John McKay is 75 years old now and has been out of coaching
since 1984, but has continued to watch both college and pro
football games on television.
</P>
<P>
   He admits one of the most astonishing developments during his
departure has unfolded in L.A., where the Trojans have not beaten
the Bruins since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   When McKay was at USC, he had a 10-5-1 record against UCLA, and
the longest losing streak he had against the Trojans' crosstown
rivals was two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe that USC has lost seven straight games to
UCLA?'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope ... and I don't understand why it has happened,'' he
replied. ``It just doesn't seem right.''
</P>
<P>
   Pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess times change,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, times do change, as USC, once the dominant football
power in this vicinity, has suffered the indignity of being
enveloped in UCLA's shadow in recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think of this year's game?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we (the Trojans) have a good chance,'' he said. ``UCLA
no doubt scores a lot of points, but its defense has had problems.
You always have a chance against a team struggling on defense. I
also think the Trojans have been getting stronger and stronger as
the season has gone on. I like the new quarterback (Carson Palmer).
I think there could be an upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, John McKay has many memories of the UCLA-USC matches,
but two stand out most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the highlight of the series for me was O.J. Simpson's
scoring run in the 1967 game that resulted in a Rose Bowl
appearance and national championship for us,'' said McKay. ``It was
just an incredible run. I'm not sure a normal running back would
have gained more than a couple of yards. It's probably the play
shown most often in re-runs of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there was that game in 1973 when we came down the
tunnel before pre-game introductions, and noticed the UCLA players
holding roses. If they beat us, they were going to go to the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Jimmy Sims (Trojan linebacker) was standing next to me,
and said, `Those guys are holding those roses like they think they
have a chance to win.' We wound up beating the Bruins and knocking
them out of the Rose Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   John McKay will watch Saturday's UCLA-USC game on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the full ESPN cable football package and that allows me
to watch all the important college games,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He and wife Corky live a tranquil life these days in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get up early, do some reading, go down to the country club,
spend a few hours there, and I'm back at home by 1:30,'' said
McKay, who still spends the first three months of each year in Palm
Desert. ``I'm usually in bed by 9 o'clock. When you're my age,
sleep becomes quite important.''
</P>
<P>
   What was John McKay's fondest recollection at USC?
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt, the 1974 game against Notre Dame when we won 55-24
after trailing 24-0 late in the first half,'' he said. ``My line on
that game was that I got tied up in freeway traffic during the
first half, and made an appearance in the second half when we
scored 49 points. Nothing at USC topped that game, but I had a lot
of other great memories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
