<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE SUCCESS EVEN SURPRISES PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ The easy way out was to eliminate football.
Drop it and Cal State Northridge's athletic budgetary worries would
evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four years ago, the administration said no, choosing to
build the football program into a flagship sport that would
eventually draw nationwide recognition.
</P>
<P>
   People laughed at the notion, pointing to the football team's
perennial losing record. There was no way the Matadors could rise
to the top of the Big Sky Conference, arguably the best Division
I-AA football league in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In a short time, CSUN has come a long way. The 23rd-ranked
Matadors are a win away from their first conference title in 37
seasons and a likely first playoff bid. The lone obstacle is a
beaten-down Idaho State, whose program is in such turmoil that
coach Tom Walsh's firing takes effect at the end of Saturday's game
at Holt Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's solution was to drop it and some people in the
administration made some very courageous decisions to stick with it
and to make the jump into a legitimate football conference,'' said
assistant head coach Jeff Kearin, in his fourth year at CSUN. ``The
real courageous part was the administration saying, `Let's make
this a football school.' Ever since that time, the only talk of
dropping football has been by people that don't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in CSUN's past provided an indication this was possible.
Not four years ago and certainly not coming into this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be a rough season,'' CSUN junior
defensive end Brennen Swanson said. ``I knew we had good things to
come with (coach Ron) Ponciano coming in, but I didn't think it was
going to be this year. After spring practice but before the season,
I knew we were going to have a pretty good team. I just didn't know
how good.''
</P>
<P>
   A steady increase in scholarships from 17 to 50, going up to 55
next season, helped CSUN's movement, as did a bevy of Division I-A
transfers who found their way to the school during the summer. CSUN
opened training camp in August with 49 players who weren't with the
4-8 Matadors of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   More administrative support, mostly behind the scenes, enabled
Ponciano to dream during training camp until...
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line was devastated by injuries. So the philosophy
of patchwork _ usually implemented to keep the program afloat _ was
refocused toward keeping the offense from falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   Taffe Aina was an academic casualty. Beau Cherry, Mike Barnes
and Joe Bergman went down with injuries. All of a sudden, freshmen
Tim Shoffeitt and Keith Kincaid were starting on the right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a very nice transition from a really bad I-AA team
to the 15th-ranked team in the power ratings,'' Ponciano said.
``Early, I thought we could make a run. There wasn't a coach in the
Big Sky that didn't think they could make a run. Then the stuff
happened with the offensive line, and you think, `Oh, boy, how can
we keep this going?' But right now we have a good chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely season has the Matadors (7-3, 5-2 Big Sky) a win
from the league title. If they defeat Idaho State (2-8, 1-6), they
would claim a share of the conference title. If that happens and
Montana beats Montana State, the Matadors would gain the league's
automatic bid to the playoffs. If Montana State and CSUN win, the
Matadors would have to wait for a 10 a.m. call Sunday to get an
at-large bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought we'd be in this position,'' senior wide
receiver Mike Ogas said. ``I saw Aaron Flowers graduate, Marc
Goodson graduate, a couple other key seniors graduate. We were
losing leadership.... I never thought we'd win the Big Sky this
year. It's still amazing to me that we're in this spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Ponciano said defensive linemen Sean Beard (leg) and
Jacob Mageo (knee) most likely won't make the trip. He also said he
is leaning toward leaving defensive lineman Quinton Reed (shoulder)
home.... It's unlikely kicker Manny Marquez will go to Idaho,
leaving punter Ethan Beck as the place-kicker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
