<SLUG> BC-CT-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: MASS., R.I.) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: UPDATES throughout with Rowland spokesman saying the team has
agreed to move to Connecticut; NO pickup.) 
PATRIOTS SET TO ANNOUNCE MOVE TO DOWNTOWN HARTFORD  
(rl-nk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. &UR;  &LR; _ Gov. John G. Rowland and the owner of the New
England Patriots scheduled a news conference at the Capitol
Thursday to announce an agreement to move the National Football
League team from Massachusetts to downtown Hartford, a spokesman
for the governor said early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut officials have agreed to build a stadium for the
owner, Robert K. Kraft, in return for 10 percent of its revenues
over the 30 years of the agreement. The stadium is expected to take
three years to build, meaning that the first games would be played
in the stadium in 2001. The league would have to approve any move
by the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   A tentative agreement, which was reached in a matter of days
after years of on-and-off talks, came in a late-night phone call
between Rowland and Kraft, according to Dean C. Pagani, the
governor's spokesman. Stacey T. James, the Patriots' director of
media relations, confirmed that he expected an announcement
Thursday about the team's relocation.
</P>
<P>
   Hartford Mayor Michael P. Peters said the team would lure
businesses and visitors, helping to rescue a city that has tried in
frustrating fits and starts to emerge from decades of decay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ripple effect is beyond belief,'' he said. ``We won't just
be known for finance or insurance. Now, we've got all the pieces of
the pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, working on the final details of the deal at the Capitol
on Wednesday, said the Patriots would do more in one stroke to help
downtown Hartford than countless smaller projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge deal for everybody,'' he said, coatless and in
shirtsleeves as he shuttled between his office and a stadium war
room that he set up. ``In the scheme of the things we could do,
this is an 800-pound gorilla.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, Rowland summoned two dozen legislative and
business leaders to show off drawings of the proposed stadium and
explain how it would be paid for. The stadium would be part of a
$350 million redevelopment project on the Connecticut River that
would include a convention center and a hotel, state officials
said. The state had already committed $300 million to build a
redevelopment project on the site, known as Adriaen's Landing.
Kraft would pay no money for the stadium, but would be expected to
help pay for another part of the project, possibly the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The deal seems to carry risk for all the parties involved.
Hartford lost its National Hockey League team, the Whalers, in
1996, raising questions about its ability to support a major league
franchise. And the National Football League, which lacks teams in
Houston and Los Angeles, would be adding Boston to its list of
lucrative markets without a team.
</P>
<P>
   But Kraft has said through years of bitter negotiations with
Massachusetts officials that he was determined to keep the team in
New England.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut lawmakers said that in recent conversations Kraft
has said he was livid that the Massachusetts Legislature had not
come up with an acceptable plan to replace the team's Foxboro
Stadium, which is 27 years old. He said that if Connecticut's final
offer met his needs, he would take it and not seek to match it in
Massachusetts, according to legislators who spoke to him.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft proposed to spend $200 million for a new stadium near the
current one, 30 miles of south Boston, and in return he wanted the
state to pay $72 million to buy land, build roads, and install
lighting and other utility lines. The Massachusetts Senate passed
the package. But Thomas Finneran, speaker of the Massachusetts
House, and his colleagues in the House refused to approve more than
$57 million, which killed the deal for Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that aides to Roland and Kraft were working on
the deal, Finneran was once again refusing to come to the aid of
the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes them special?'' Finneran said outside his office.
``What makes them different? What makes them entitled to a deal
that goes beyond the bounds of anything that's reasonable and quite
frankly bullies and pillages the taxpayers?''
</P>
<P>
   Acting Gov. Argeo Paul Cellucci, who supported the Senate plan,
said Wednesday in a statement, ``I urge the citizens of the
Commonwealth to call their state representatives and let them know
they want to keep the Pats here.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Aiello, the National Football League's vice president of
public relations, said a move would require the approval of 24 of
the league's 31 clubs. ``The fact that the Patriots would be
staying in New England would be viewed as a positive by the rest of
the league,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, when Connecticut officials last made a pass for
the team, legislators became boosters, parading around the Capitol
in Patriots caps and jerseys. This time, to avoid being used as a
bargaining chip by Kraft in his negotiations with the Massachusetts
Legislature, Rowland conducted the talks quietly and played down
the possibility in public.
</P>
<P>
   So legislative leaders were taken by surprise on Monday morning,
when Rowland told them that he had made an offer to Kraft during a
two-hour meeting on Friday, and that he seemed ready to move.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kraft has not commented publicly on his plans, he flew
into Hartford on Monday afternoon and signaled his approval of the
proposal by visiting legislators to answer their questions.
</P>
<P>
   A special session of the Connecticut Legislature would be called
next month to approve the project. ``We don't want to give
Massachusetts time to react,'' said a senior official involved in
the talks.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Moira K. Lyons, a Democrat from Stamford who is the
incoming Speaker of the Connecticut House, said she wanted to see
more financial details before she would commit to supporting the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a lot of enthusiasm, and that's
understandable,'' she said. ``But we have an obligation to look at
it and analyze it to be sure it will be beneficial to the region
and to the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Some local officials expressed caution, however, saying that the
Patriots alone were not a solution to a downtown that seems
deserted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be an Atlantic City, where we have one
shining strip and two blocks away there's dire need,'' said state
Rep. Marie M. Kirkley-Bey, a Democrat from Hartford. ``Those of us
who have districts where there is a lot of blight would hope
there's a way to use the project to help refurbish our
neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   As sketched by legislative and administration officials, the
deal calls for a 65,000-seat open-air stadium with a grass surface.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would last for 30 years, and the stadium would be
paid for with the sale of bonds. State officials said that to pay
off the bonds, Kraft would pay the state a 10 percent cut of
tickets, concessions and parking.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the stadium would not impose any new costs
on taxpayers. But skeptics in the Legislature who have reviewed the
plan said it relied on quite optimistic projections of attendance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
