 ALICE McDERMOTT WINS NATIONAL BOOK AWARD FOR FICTION 
 (nk) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alice McDermott, author of ``Charming Billy,'' a
quiet novel about Irish-Americans and the way a lost love can
continue to haunt a life, was the surprise winner of the National
Book Award for fiction Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The expected winner had been Tom Wolfe's `` A Man in Full''
(Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux), a big, muscular book about race and real
estate in the New South. It also beat another strong contender,
``Damascus Gate'' (Houghton Mifflin) by Robert Stone, the story of
a conspiracy to blow up the Temple Mount in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the judging panel for fiction, Thomas Mallon,
said ``Charming Billy'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux) had ``a voice
like nothing we could recall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It found us,'' he said. ``It was what we kept hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel is told from the point of view of a young narrator
about two men: her father and his cousin Billy, a romantic charmer
who falls in love with an Irish housemaid. Billy thinks he has lost
her when he is told she has died. But years later, he discovers
that she is living. Now married to a plain and devoted wife, Maeve,
Billy sees his decision to marry as a betrayal of ``the faith he
had sworn to an unrealized future.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDermott, who lives in Washington and was a National Book
Award finalist in 1987 for her novel ``That Night'' was taken aback
by the award. She hadn't even bothered to compose an acceptance
speech, she told the crowd of over 800 people at the ceremony at
the Marriott Marquis Hotel in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be true to my Irish heritage if I thought this were
entirely a good thing,'' Ms. McDermott said. ``I will clutch onto
my Irish humility with great vigor.''
</P>
<P>
   The nonfiction award went to Edward Ball for his first book,
``Slaves in the Family,'' about his search for the descendants of
the slaves owned by his ancestors in South Carolina, and his
attempt to confront the moral burden of slavery. Ball, who was a
columnist for The Village Voice, said he planned to use a fourth of
his book's earnings to set up a foundation with both black and
white members ``to create restitution programs we design
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the poetry award was Gerald Stern for ``This Time:
New and Selected Poems'' (W.W. Norton). Stern, whose book is a
summary of a lifetime's work of poems about the city, memory and
faith, was the expected winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I, like a hare, like a hare, like a hare, I watch the
turtle lift a leg,'' Stern said, reciting from one of his poems,
``then head for home roaring with vigor.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Sachar won the award for young people's literature for
``Holes'' (Francis Foster Books/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux), his
darkly humorous story of a teen-ager who is wrongly sent to a
juvenile detention center.
</P>
<P>
   Each winner received $10,000, with $1,000 each for the
runners-up.
</P>
<P>
   The National Book Foundation, which administers the awards, gave
John Updike, author of 49 books, the 1998 National Book Foundation
Medal for Distinguished Contribution to American Letters and
$10,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his acceptance speech, Updike remembered his childhood and
falling in love with books. He recalled going to the library with
his mother, who wrote fiction but suffered many rejections.
Nonetheless it was she, Updike said, who imbued him with his love
of books.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something glamorous about the Reading, Pennsylvania,
Library,'' Updike said, ``a romantic savor to the much thumbed
books.''
</P>
<P>
   Updike noted that he had won the National Book Award twice
before. First for ``The Centaur,'' his first novel, in 1963 _ ``a
moment I am still dizzy from,'' he said _ and then for ``Rabbit Is
Rich'' in 1981. ``Like some graying comet I return every 17 years
or so from the realm of the unnominated,'' Updike said.
</P>
<P>
   As they are nearly every year, this year's nominations, chosen
from 916 titles submitted by publishers, were the subject of some
second-guessing by publishers and editors, especially because
several major novels, including Philip Roth's ``I Married a
Communist,'' Updike's ``Bech at Bay,'' Russell Banks's
``Cloudsplitter'' and Ron Chernow's biography of John D.
Rockefeller Sr., failed to receive nominations.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright Wendy Wasserstein, who was host at the awards,
said that the ceremony was a celebration of ``the author's craft,
integrity, loneliness and insanity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What this evening is about,'' Ms. Wasserstein said, ``is the
continuity of the American voice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
