u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-AUCTION-1STLD-WRI     11-19 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-AUCTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL SALE AT CHRISTIE'S YIELDS PRICES TO MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `It was ..., to CORRECT quote. )  
 (js) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The dealers and collectors who jammed Christie's Park
Avenue salesroom Wednesday night kept a watchful eye on prices as
Impressionist and 19th-century artworks by masters like Monet and
Signac, Cezanne and Bonnard, spun around on the turntable. Only
when a top-quality work was offered did the room come alive with
bidders. Even then, heads remained cool, and only 14 works out of
the 43 offered exceeded the expected price.
</P>
<P>
   The sale totaled $44.9 million, less than its low estimate of
$47.6 million. Only 35 of the works found buyers.
</P>
<P>
   One of Wednesday night's most popular paintings, and the most
expensive work of the evening, was Monet's ``Boatmen at
Argenteuil'' (1874), being sold by the heirs of the Paris dealer
Paul Durand-Ruel. The sun-dappled scene of sailors and rowers,
which had not been on the market since 1895, was estimated at $6
million to $8 million. Three people seriously wanted the painting,
and after bids flew around the room, it went to David Nahmad, a
Manhattan dealer, for $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite surprising, the number of people who really
fought to buy the Monet,'' said Franck Giraud, head of
Impressionist and 19th-century art at Christie's. ``It is
Impressionism at its best.''
</P>
<P>
   Vuillard's ``Conversation (Terra Cotta Pot),'' a tapestry-like
1895 domestic interior from the artist's Nabi period, had four
people who wanted to take it home. It sold to an unidentified
bidder for $4.7 million, the second highest price ever paid for a
painting by the artist.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include the auction house's commission, 15 percent
of the first $50,000 and 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not
reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   Christie's had an advantage over Sotheby's, which had its sales
of Impressionist, modern and contemporary art on Monday and Tuesday
evenings. After those sales produced mixed results, Christie's
warned sellers of the tepid market (as both auction houses
generally do, given the chance), and in some cases, reserves _
secret minimum prices agreed upon by the sellers and the auction
house _ were obviously lowered.
</P>
<P>
   Which, in some cases, made the difference between selling a
painting and not selling. Often, works sold for far below their low
estimates. Courbet's ``View of Ornans and Its Steeple'' (1858),
which had been owned by the British Rail Pension Fund Collection
until it was sold at Sotheby's in London in 1990, was again on
offer Wednesday night. It went to an unidentified telephone buyer
for $607,500, far below its $800,000 low estimate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Monet was well represented, but the results were mixed. His
``View of the Water Lily Pond'' (1917-19) was estimated at $6
million to $8 million but sold to an unidentified telephone bidder
for $5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another Monet, ``The Ducal Palace,'' a 1908 scene of the Grand
Canal in Venice with the palace reflected on the water, was
estimated at $3.5 million to $4.5 million. Nobody was willing to
pay more than $2.7 million, and it went unsold.
</P>
<P>
   Other water scenes performed well. Signac's ``Concarneau.
Morning Calm. Opus 219 (Larghetto),'' from 1891, was painted at a
time when the artist was inspired by his love of music, combining
colors that were divided and then harmonized in much the same way a
composer produces a melody. The scene of boats on the water was
expected to bring $2.5 million to $3.5 million. Three bidders tried
to buy it, and the painting eventually sold for $4.4 million to
David Nash, the former director of Impressionist and modern art at
Sotheby's, who now runs Mitchell-Innes &AMP; Nash, a Madison Avenue
gallery with his wife, Lucy Mitchell-Innes.
</P>
<P>
   Another strong price was paid for Bonnard's ``Tea in the
Garden'' (1891). Estimated at $800,000 to $1.2 million, it finally
sold to an unidentified telephone bidder for $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   An 1877 Cezanne landscape, ``The Winding Road,'' had three
people wanting it, but at the right price. It sold to an
unidentified bidder for $2.8 million, its low estimate.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, pastel dancers by Degas brought big prices, but
not on Wednesday night. ``Le Pas Battu'' (1879), estimated at $2
million to $3 million, remained unsold when nobody wanted to pay
more than $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   As generally happens when bidding is controlled, bottom-fishers,
especially dealers, came out in full force. ``Prices have been so
strong until now that dealers couldn't afford to buy,'' said
Abigail Asher, a Manhattan dealer. ``It was clear tonight that the
Impressionist market is still trying to find its price point.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some happy buyers were seen leaving the sale. Scott
Black, president of Delphi Management in Boston, took home a
Bernard and a Toulouse-Lautrec. ``Good paintings found buyers,'' he
said. ``But overall the evening was pretty lackluster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
