<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MVP-GONZALEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' GONZALEZ IS NAMED MVP FOR AMERICAN LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RAY CORIO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pattern seems apparent: the New York Yankees win the pennant
and Juan Gonzalez captures the most valuable player award.
</P>
<P>
   It unfolded again Wednesday when Gonzalez, the slugging
outfielder for the Texas Rangers, was named American League MVP for
the second time in three seasons in the kind of landslide vote the
1998 Yankees could identify with.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when the Yankees eliminated Gonzalez's Rangers in
the first round of the playoffs on the way to a pennant and World
Series title, Gonzalez beat Seattle shortstop Alex Rodriguez,
290-287, to win the MVP ``The first time was too tight,'' he said
Wednesday, speaking from San Juan, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   This season, when the Yankees became one of the best teams of
the century with a league-record 114 victories, they knocked the
Rangers out in Round 1 again en route to another Series title. And
Gonzalez, in a romp of his own, beat another shortstop, Nomar
Garciaparra of the Boston Red Sox, 357-232.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for this year was staying healthy, playing 154
games,'' Gonzalez said. ``When I'm healthy, I'm putting up the best
numbers I can.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 numbers helped make him the first Latin American native
to win two MVP awards. Gonzalez batted .318 with 45 home runs and
157 RBIs, the most RBI in the American League since Ted Williams
and Vern Stephens each had 159 for Boston in 1949. Gonzalez had 101
RBIs by the All-Star Game break.
</P>
<P>
   In voting by two baseball writers from each of the league's 14
cities, Gonzalez received 21 of the 28 first-place votes and seven
seconds. Garciaparra, last season's rookie of the year, had five
firsts, seven seconds and seven thirds.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who were saluted all season for their emphasis on
team play rather than individual accomplishments, underscored that
in the MVP voting with four players among the first 16. Shortstop
Derek Jeter received two firsts, six seconds and three thirds and
finished third.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Bernie Williams was seventh with 96 points, right
fielder Paul O'Neill 12th and David Wells, who pitched a perfect
game and had an 18-4 record, was 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Not often does a team as proficient as the 1998 Yankees, who won
the division by 22 games and the World Series in a sweep, fail to
produce a serious contender for MVP.
</P>
<P>
   On the 1961 Yankees, for example, Roger Maris and Mickey Mantle
finished 1-2, and three teammates were in the top 14.
</P>
<P>
   On Cincinnati's Big Red Machine teams of 1975 and 1976, Joe
Morgan was a two-time winner, with Pete Rose, Johnny Bench and
George Foster in the hunt. And on the powerful 1970 Baltimore
Orioles, Boog Powell led the voting, with Brooks Robinson and Frank
Robinson also in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the Yankees' showing in this year's MVP voting most
closely resembles that of their crosstown rivals, the Mets, among
highly successful teams of recent decades. When the Mets won 108
games and a World Series in 1986, their best MVP showing _ like the
1998 Yankees _ was third (Gary Carter). They also had a fourth
(Keith Hernandez), a 14th (Ray Knight) and a 17th (Roger McDowell).
The Phillies' Mike Schmidt topped the voting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 0140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
