<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-KIDS-BOAT-ART-2TAK     11-19 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KIDS-BOAT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH BRONX TEENS BUILD THEIR DREAMS ON A BOAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds: Collin Powell's first name is CQ.) 
(mk) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Craig Salazar walked into the basement, his face
betrayed his pain. He was worried about his grandmother, who was
gravely ill in the hospital, and annoyed that he had got himself
suspended from school for fighting.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike so many of his friends, Craig, 14, had a way to
channel his stress. Picking up a carpenter's plane, he began to
drag it briskly and repeatedly along a quarter-inch-thick piece of
mahogany plywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I do this, it just clears my mind,'' he told a visitor
between strokes, as the layers of wood peeled away and the
tightness in his forehead receded. ``I think about what I am
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   What he was doing was building a boat _ a 14-foot replica of a
19th-century Hudson River rowboat known as a Whitehall _ in the
basement of an apartment building in the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   If it seems a bit of a non sequitur to be sanding, hammering and
gluing together a wooden rowboat in such a space _ one that, just
weeks earlier, had stored rusty appliances _ then that's sort of
the point, Adam Green says.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Green, a 25-year-old graduate of Vassar, opened an
after-school boat-building workshop for neighborhood children in
the basement of the New Settlement Apartments, a mixed-income
development that rose from the rubble of Morris Heights eight years
ago and now includes 300 formerly homeless families among the 900
families that reside there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of the last thing you'd think of as happening where
it's happening,'' said Green, whose wiry red beard gives him the
look of a mariner, albeit not an ancient one. ``I want the kids to
do something that stands out completely from anything they've ever
done before and from anything that anyone around them has seen
happen in their community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't,'' he added, ``have to go to Maine to build a
boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after he plastered the neighborhood last month with posters
bearing an Uncle-Sam-wants-you come-on _ ``Build a 14-foot wooden
boat from scratch and then sail it in the rivers around the Bronx''
_ 10 teen-agers signed up to join Green on his 12-week construction
project. (Two additional boats are to be built in the shop by
different groups of children beginning early next year.)
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have become regular fixtures in the shop are
Jeffrey Bernardez, 13, an eighth-grader who dreams of becoming a
professional wrestler but who is as comfortable with a screwdriver
as a pile driver; Erika Torres, 13, the shop's only female worker,
who quickly impressed the boys with woodworking skills mostly
superior to theirs, and Collin Powell, 14, who is not named after
the general _ ``I have the same middle initial, but mine's for
Lashawn and his is Luther'' _ but who does share his charisma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait till I get here,'' said Collin, surveying the
shop in his work wear, a blue-and-gray-striped rugby jersey
untucked at the waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little crazy,'' he said of the project's mission. ``But
you're like the first to do it. I feel special.''
</P>
<P>
   To Green, whose carpentry experience was largely limited to a
summer spent building houses upstate and whose major in college was
Hudson Valley storytelling and folk tales, the fashioning of a boat
out of a pile of white oak planks and plywood is a vehicle to many
educational outposts. But the setting in which the teen-agers are
learning is intended to be as unlike school as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Collin, for one, has noticed. ``We don't have to write down
stuff,'' he said. ``We don't have to bring textbooks. You get
treated like an adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Green has already used the design phase to teach his crew about
geometry, fractions and trigonometry. He's also plied his charges
with history lessons describing the Whitehall's role in the 1800s
as a ship-to-shore transporter of food and supplies, as well as a
small ferry from the Battery to points north.
</P>
<P>
   Two weekends ago, he took his young workers rowing on the Harlem
River on a boat just a foot longer than the one they are building,
giving them a sneak peak at the finished product and a glimpse of
the aquatic life just one and a quarter miles away from their homes
_ 14 brick buildings clustered near 172nd Street and Townsend
Avenue. The boat they rowed was built several years ago by Floating
the Apple, a Manhattan organization seeking to draw attention to
the city's waterways.
</P>
<P>
   The dreamer that frequently seizes hold of Green's speech makes
clear that his and his workers' journey is as much a philosophical
one as one intended to steer them clear of the temptations of the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to learn something from creating,'' he said, ``then
to use it to transport ourselves to places that give us a whole new
realm of experience: That's phenomenally powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of the three afternoons each week that he meets
with the teen-agers, Green demonstrates what he wants his crew to
do, and then gets out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Delegating Collin and Jeffrey, the wrestler, to pare down the
outer keel, Green crouched beside them at the side of a wooden
workbench, the beam held tight in a vise, and showed them how bumpy
it looked. He told them how they could tell if they were planing in
the right direction. ``If you're going with the grain, it's a
smooth sound and it looks kind of shiny,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each boy then grabbed his plane with both hands and, standing
sideways next to the wood, began propelling it in short bursts
across the wood's surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like punching,'' Jeffrey told an observer.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, pausing to survey his work, he confessed he was
having trouble seeing the finished product in his mind, with nine
weeks still to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like the bottom of the boat,'' he said of the
plank, which was narrow at its tips but grew gradually wider on
either side to its midsection. ``To me, it looks like a
surfboard.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Green, the son of a social worker and an editor in the
publications department of the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority, learned to love the water at a young age. Though he grew
up on Central Park West at 95th Street, he was a frequent visitor
aboard the Clearwater, the 106-foot sloop that the folk singer Pete
Seeger helped launch as a floating classroom on the lower Hudson
River 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Clearwater's twofold mission, to teach about the environment
and to promote conservation, influenced Green greatly, and Seeger
is serving as an informal adviser on Green's project.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview from his home overlooking the Hudson at the
Newburgh-Beacon Bridge, Seeger said, ``They are learning that life
is more than just, `Sit there and keep an eye on the screen,' or
standing around doing the same thing over and over, making just
enough money to pay the rent and feed themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Green took time off in his senior year at Vassar to work and
live as a crew member on the Clearwater. He built on that monthlong
experience by volunteering to help students at an East Harlem
junior high school construct a small dinghy, using a diagram from a
magazine as his guide. It was the first boat he had ever built, and
he was as amazed as his students when it survived a test float in
the school pool.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Green came to the conclusion that there was a career
in such work, and last year he brought his idea to Hostos Community
College in the Bronx, where he led an after-school crew in the
construction of his first Whitehall. It took eight months.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he has expanded his operation greatly. During the
summer, he raised $53,000 in grant money, enough to pay his $30,000
salary and buy material for three boats, as well as to pay two
part-time assistants.
</P>
<P>
   He moved the project to New Settlement, which provides him with
work space, electricity and a pool of eager volunteer crew members.
He chose the housing development, he said, in part because he loved
the idea of showing the children that a boat could arise from the
basement of one of the places they live in.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, the boy whose fighting earned him a week's suspension
from school, said he had arrived at Green's shop under duress. His
older sister had all but forced him to join, he said, ``to keep me
out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says, he needs no prodding to go to the shop. Jeffrey
went further, saying that, though it had not altered his plans for
a career in the ring, working in the shop had him thinking about
starting a similar after-school program wherever he chooses to
settle down.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he should wait to see if the boat floats, when it is
launched during a neighborhood festival in the spring, Jeffrey grew
insistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you work with all the people and you picture how it's going
to float _ no cracks, no leaks _ it will float,'' he said. ``You've
got to have confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 0146EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
