<SLUG> BC-NY-ATTORNEY-GENERAL-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPITZER HANGS ON TO LEAD WITH ALMOST ALL VOTES COUNTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the counting of paper ballots nearly done in the
state attorney general's race, state election officials said
Wednesday that Democratic challenger Eliot Spitzer was maintaining
a thin lead, and aides to Spitzer said he was preparing to declare
victory Thursday over Republican incumbent Dennis Vacco.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, aides to Vacco say they are far from conceding
defeat, and lawyers for his campaign went to state Supreme Court in
Manhattan on Wednesday to challenge the vote count in New York
City, saying there were widespread discrepancies in the tallies.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, Spitzer had a 22,334-vote lead over Vacco _
2,064,036 votes to 2,041,702 _ with about 20,000 paper ballots left
to be counted, said Lee Daghlian, a spokesman for the state Board
of Elections.
</P>
<P>
   He said the uncounted ballots were from 10 counties, including
Westchester, Oneida and some in New York City. In the counting so
far, Spitzer has had an advantage in the city greater than 3 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials said they would not declare a winner in the
Nov. 3 race until all the votes were counted. They said they
expected the counting to be completed sometime next week.
</P>
<P>
   Polls taken a week before election day showed Vacco with a
healthy lead, but election night ended with Spitzer ahead by about
18,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, election officials around the state have engaged in
a tedious rechecking of machine tallies and hand counting of paper
ballots, all the while watched by representatives of both camps.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the current count and Spitzer's demonstrated strength in
New York City, aides to the Democratic candidate said that he would
hold a news conference Thursday at which he intended to declare
victory, 16 days after the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put a fork in this election,'' said Steven Goldstein,
Spitzer's campaign press secretary. ``It's done.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Vacco campaign was equally adamant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an election that will be decided not by press
conference but by counting the votes,'' said Kieran Mahoney, a
political consultant for the Vacco campaign. ``I can hold a press
conference tomorrow declaring myself the pope, but that doesn't
mean the College of Cardinals is going to listen to me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a hearing in state Supreme Court on Wednesday, Vacco's
lawyers raised questions about the counting of votes in the days
since the election.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said that the number of votes reported on election
night did not correspond to the number released by the Board of
Elections a week later based on a recount of tallies from voting
machines in New York City and Westchester County. They said that
the count was off by about 34,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are addressing the verification of machine
numbers,'' said Thomas Spargo, a lawyer for Vacco's campaign. ``Our
problem has been the lack of reliability, from our perspective, in
how the final voting machine numbers were tabulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Thomas Keegan told officials of both campaigns to spend
the next few days inspecting the thousands of voting machines in
the city and to report their findings to him in court on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the New York City Board of Elections said they
were confident that their figures were accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board's numbers will definitely hold,'' said Daniel
DeFrancesco, the board's executive director. ``Mr. Vacco is
entitled to his day and Mr. Spitzer is, too. But I honestly believe
that the board's numbers are good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
