<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FIND NEW WAY TO LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ The latest bizarre twist in the decline and fall of
the Kings comes to us courtesy of defenseman Philippe Boucher,
former King Tony Granato and referee Terry Gregson.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday night, with the score tied and the Kings on a
power play, they discovered an interesting way to allow a
shorthanded goal and, in the process, lose their fifth consecutive
game.
</P>
<P>
   Everything appeared under control. Boucher had the puck deep in
the Kings zone and passed it ahead. But it hit Gregson, resulting
in a point-blank shot by Marco Sturm. Goalie Manny Legace made the
save, but Granato fired in the rebound with 7:07 to play, and the
Kings went on to lose 5-4 before a San Jose Arena crowd of 16,703.
Granato had scored the tying goal for the Sharks six minutes
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when rookie defenseman Mark Visheau recorded the
first two points of his career, a night when Legace notched his
first NHL assist, and a night when the Kings (5-11-3) scored three
goals in a period for the first time this season, they still found
a way to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The day began badly when Legace took a shot by coach Larry
Robinson off the mask during the morning practice, which left him
with a mild headache.
</P>
<P>
   And the night did not go so well, either. Before the game was
two minutes old, they'd allowed a 3-on-1 that resulted in the third
goal of the season for Joe Murphy and a 1-0 lead for the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings sank deeper 6:28 into the second period, when Jeff
Friesen made it 2-0, a margin that ordinarily would appear
mountainous for their struggling offense to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   In stunning fashion, though, the Kings responded with their
version of a volcanic eruption, scoring two goals in a 32-second
span midway through the second period to even the score.
</P>
<P>
   First, Glen Murray set up Luc Robitaille on a 2-on-1, and
Robitaille slid the puck between goalie Mike Vernon's pads for his
team-high 10th goal of the season. Then, Murray deflected home a
shot from the right point by Mark Visheau, who recorded his first
NHL point and later in the period would record his second.
</P>
<P>
   A minute after Murray tied the score, however, the Kings went on
a penalty binge that threatened to instantly negate the comeback.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:33, Eric Lacroix was sent off for goaltender interference,
and at 12:31, Nathan LaFayette received a double minor for
high-sticking Friesen, who was left with a gash under his chin.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks could not capitalize on a 62-second two-man
advantage, but finally scored with 31 seconds left in LaFayette's
second penalty, when Friesen scored after Mattias Norstrom had
blocked a shot from the slot by ex-King Bernie Nicholls.
</P>
<P>
   On the same play, Sean O'Donnell flattened Owen Nolan with a
cross check, so the Kings had to play shorthanded for two more
minutes. But Murray picked up Visheau's clearing pass in the
neutral zone, used his speed to create a breakaway, and tied the
score at 16:50 with his eighth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings then killed the remaining 1:10 of O'Donnell's penalty,
meaning that in the 6:27 span during which they were shorthanded,
they broke even. And at the final buzzer of the second period, a
Marcus Ragnarsson high-sticking penalty gave the Kings a power play
to open the third.
</P>
<P>
   For a change, the Kings took advantage of the extra man, with
Olli Jokinen carrying the puck from the right corner to the crease
and snapping a quick shot over Vernon's glove at 1:04, for his
second power-play goal in as many games.
</P>
<P>
   But six minutes later, Bob Rouse did a good job keeping the puck
in the Kings' zone, and it eventually landed on Granato's stick in
the right circle. Granato rifled the puck past Legace, and not much
later, courtesy of Gregson, he added the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   With Legace off for an extra skater in the last minute, Vernon
stopped a point-blank shot by Murray, preventing the Kings from
sending the game into overtime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
