<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-HIKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL HIKING AT ITS BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Supposedly, black bears will run.''
</P>
<P>
   The odd utterance from my hiking partner as we hit Rattlesnake
Trail high in the heart of the San Gabriel Mountains sounded eerily
like famous last words.
</P>
<P>
   I'd already been warned about the track's dangerously steep
overhangs, where one misstep could send a hiker plummeting into a
deep chasm.
</P>
<P>
   The very name of the footpath seemed ominous, as a hiker we met
along its course made apparent. ``First off, it's called
Rattlesnake Trail, so, right off the bat, it's got a certain
something,'' said John Burnett of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Add bears to the mix, even bruins that supposedly run when
confronted, and the intrigue of the day would stand to escalate
dramatically. To our disappointment, however, by day's end there
was no evidence of bears. Nary a snake.
</P>
<P>
   But for fall hiking in the Angeles National Forest, little
compares to Rattlesnake Trail and its companion to the west, Cooper
Canyon Trail. Together they offer rugged territory accentuated by
sheer crags, crystalline streams, quaint waterfalls and a diverse
arrangement of flora and ecological zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about as attractive as any of the walks in the San
Gabriels because it has quite a variety of fauna and trees and
bushes,'' said Los Angeles corporate lawyer Robert Taylor, who
crossed our path near Rattlesnake Spring. ``Plus there is a lovely
stream down there, where we had lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor should know. He says he's hiked most of
Mexico-to-Canada's Pacific Crest Trail, which calls the entirety of
the Rattlesnake and Cooper Canyon trails its own.
</P>
<P>
   The stream he spoke of is Little Rock Creek, a defining element
of the canyon country along the Northern San Gabriels' desert
slopes. It is joined by Cooper Canyon's outlet 3{ miles from
Rattlesnake Trailhead at Eagles Roost picnic area. Hikers who make
it to this serene confluence are rewarded a quarter-mile farther
west with a waterfall that neither gets airborne nor drops a great
distance but allows visitors to get lost in its understated allure
just the same.
</P>
<P>
   The east-to-west hike covers 7{ miles from Eagles Roost to
Cloudburst Summit and is resplendent with Jeffrey, Coulter and
sugar pine, white fir, oak, alder and, most impressively, towering
incense cedar. Recreationists enjoy forest, canyon and riparian
ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
   The path is seemingly far from mankind's reach, though only 1\
miles north of the paralleling Angeles Crest Highway at its most
removed point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the farther you go in, you see the trees getting
bigger and you wonder where the lumberjacks had to stop, where it
wasn't worth their trouble to come and take that tree out,'' said
hiker Burnett, who was breaking in a pack and cold-weather clothing
for winter trekking.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at an elevation of 6,725 feet, the crooked, old
Rattlesnake Trail _ a real compass buster _ winds down in about a
mile to Little Rock Creek (6,275 feet), canvassing a fire road at
first, then a narrow trail.
</P>
<P>
   From here, the route follows the creek downstream for more than
two miles along a high contour. The gorge below is stunning.
</P>
<P>
   At the 3{-mile mark, Rattlesnake Trail is bisected by the
Burkhart Trail, which traverses Pleasant View Ridge and connects
the Antelope Valley to nearby Buckhorn Campground over 8\ miles.
The aforementioned confluence of streams is found here (5,675
feet), and the waterfall is just up what is now the Cooper Canyon
Trail. The cascade is an appetizing lunch spot.
</P>
<P>
   The southern portion of the Burkhart Trail breaks off here,
while the Cooper Canyon Trail continues to the west, climbing a
rocky fire road to a wide, dry streambed until stumbling onto
Cooper Canyon Trail Camp (6,240 feet). Southerly views of
7,283-foot Buckhorn Peak come into play during the 1\ miles between
the falls and the camp. The area was frequented by American Indians
and, in the 1890s, by Pasadena hunting siblings Ike and Tom Cooper,
who targeted deer and bear, according to John W. Robinson's
invaluable guide ``Trails of the Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   New maps indicate Cooper Canyon trail takes a northwest jog as
it meets a fire road employed by maintenance vehicles that service
the trail camp via Cloudburst Summit (7,018 feet). My old map does
not make that subtle distinction, and we hoofed the final 1.6
unflattering miles up the fire road.
</P>
<P>
   The fire road saves the more hurried _ and exhausted _ hikers
time and a mile's distance, but I would have much preferred my
boots stomp a thin track than a wide swath. But don't sweat the
little things, especially on a quality trek like this one, where
it's pretty much all good. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU'RE GOING ....
</P>
<P>
   Hiking the Rattlesnake and Cooper Canyon trails is a shuttle
trip requiring two vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Drive both over Angeles Crest Highway (2) to Cloudburst Summit _
32.3 miles northeast of the highway's outset in La Canada
Flintridge. Drop off one car here at the Cooper Canyon Trailhead _
the termination of this trek.
</P>
<P>
   With all adventurers and their gear in the second auto, drive
another 4.6 miles _ using caution to avoid fallen rocks _ to Eagles
Roost picnic area and park. Rattlesnake Trail commences across the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   To be legally parked in the Angeles National Forest, a car must
have a National Forest Adventure Pass displayed. The daily fee is
$5 and the permit can be purchased en route at the Clear Creek
Visitors Station, at the junction of Angeles Crest and Angeles
Forest highways.
</P>
<P>
   The trails are found on the Waterman Mountain 7.5-minute series
topographic map and Tom Harrison Maps' recently updated ``Angeles
High Country Trail Map.''
</P>
<P>
   Allow at least five hours to complete the 7{-mile track.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (626) 574-5200. &QL; 
_Brett Pauly
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
