<SLUG> BC-OUT-SKIING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY CHANGES IN STORE AT SKI RESORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART BENTLEY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thou art lost and gone forever. Dreadful sorry,
Clementine.
</P>
<P>
   And good riddance. The Clementine of interest to Southland
skiers was not a miner's daughter but Bear Mountain's
excruciatingly slow fixed-grip triple chairlift. By Dec. 17,
Clementine's replacement _ a high-speed four-seater, the resort's
second quad _ should start running.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of several upgrades and changes at area resorts that
skiers and snowboarders can expect this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Those who seek access to the challenging terrain of Bear
Mountain's Bear Peak will no longer face a most exasperating
conveyance that frequently presented long lift lines. Now visitors
to the Big Bear Lake facility will enjoy a brief passage to its
base via the new lift, dubbed Access Express. From, there its up
the Bear Peak Triple to Geronimo, a double-diamond run with an
incline of 35 degrees and 1,100 feet of vertical drop.
</P>
<P>
   When the snow is abundant, Bear Peak delivers exciting off-piste
descents that are steep and thickly wooded. The management has been
longing to cut runs down these slopes and throw lifts up them for
more than a decade, but development plans have been blocked by
advocates of certain flora and fauna who say the species are
endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Access Express is the region's most skier-friendly capital
improvement; modifications at other resorts are more modest.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain High near Wrightwood, under new ownership since 1997,
is using an electronic-ticket system with computer chips that open
turnstiles to lifts. Patrons can buy tickets good at specific times
or for a specific number of rides. The chips are embedded in season
passes, club cards or wristbands sold at the resort. Widespread in
Europe, such high-tech ticketing is catching on in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Snow Valley, outside of Running Springs, is touting a 33 percent
expansion of its learning area, arguably the area's best and most
extensive beginner terrain. The base lodge has also been renovated.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, snowboarders at the little spot that calls itself Big
Air Green Valley will have company this season of a kind not seen
on the slopes for several years. Skiers will once again be
welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Baldy, north of Upland, has made what in the long term may
be one of the most significant strides of all, winning approval
from the U.S. Forest Service of a development plan and an
environmental impact report. These are among the hurdles that must
be cleared if lifts are to be installed on the precipitous slopes
immediately north of the resort's present boundary. If plans are
ever realized, the additional territory could catapult Baldy into
the big time.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, up Highway 395 in the Eastern Sierra, the
metamorphosis continues at Mammoth Mountain, which gets most of its
business from the Southern California faithful. The resort has
replaced its upper gondola and installed two more high-speed quads.
</P>
<P>
   The new gondola cabins hold eight passengers instead of six and
the duration of last season's eight-minute ride from mid-mountain
to the summit has been cut almost in half.
</P>
<P>
   One of Mammoth's new quads loads near the bottom of the popular
Stump Alley intermediate run and drops off passengers at the saddle
between Lincoln Mountain and the top of Chair 5. For the first
time, runs such as Solitude, Spook and Lower Dry Creek will be
reachable via just a single lift ride from the lower mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The other quad replaces perennial favorite Chair 4, a double, in
the Canyon Lodge area _ formerly Warming Hut II. Following the same
line but doubling the uphill capacity, the lift serves runs that
include Roller Coaster, Crosswalk, Avalanche and Sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHLAND SKI AND SNOWBOARD AREAS
</P>
<P>
   Two regional resorts are already up and running and two more are
expected to fill chair lifts this weekend. Where to strap on
boards, with telephones, anticipated opening dates (call to confirm
before leaving home) and prices of all-day adult lift tickets:
</P>
<P>
   Ski Sunrise: (760) 249-6150, Christmas week, $20.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain High: (760) 249-5808, opened Nov. 10, $25/$35.
</P>
<P>
   Big Air Green Valley: (909) 867-2338, Dec. 19, $27.
</P>
<P>
   Snow Valley: (909) 867-5151, Friday or Saturday, $34.
</P>
<P>
   Snow Summit: (909) 866-5766, Saturday, $32.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Mountain: (909) 585-2517, opened Friday, $25/$30.
</P>
<P>
   early-season fee.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Mount Waterman, (626) 440-1041, could not be reached.
Mount Baldy, (909) 982-0800, and Snowcrest at Kratka Ridge, (626)
440-9749, did not return calls to the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, Mammoth Mountain opened Nov. 6. Early-season
rates are $39 through Sunday, $49 afterward. Information: (760)
934-2571. June Mountain plans to open Dec. 12 at $40 a ticket.
Information: (760) 648-7733. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
