r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-STAMP-LADN     11-19 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-STAMP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDFOWLER GETS STAMP OF APPROVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM MATTHEWS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BERNARDINO _ For the first time in the 65-year history of
the Federal Duck Stamp Art Contest, a painting with a hunter in the
design has won.
</P>
<P>
   The hunter and his dog in their boat may be but a small part of
the depiction of two greater scaup winging across a windswept
waterway. But it is symbolic of how hunters have largely been in
the background of the effort to conserve wetlands and waterfowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been surprised to the reaction to the hunter in the
painting,'' said Jim Hautman of Plymouth, Minn., whose artwork won
the competition for the 1999-2000 hunting-season stamp. ``Of
course, the hunters like it, but even a lot of non-hunters like the
hunter in the painting.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of three brothers, Hautman became the fourth artist
to win the contest three times. His brothers each have won the
competition once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunting and painting all go hand in hand to me. It's hard to
explain to people who don't hunt... but no one hunts something they
don't love. You don't go out and hunt something you hate,'' he
said. ``Hunters already get it; they understand. And non-hunters
may never get it. The real irony is that anti-hunters and hunters
want the same thing _ better habitat and more animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Waterfowl shooters are required to purchase the $15 stamp (it's
a hunting document, not a postage stamp) and carry it with their
hunting license; 98 percent of the proceeds goes to the Migratory
Bird Conservation Fund, which purchases wetlands for the National
Wildlife Refuge System. The stamp contest is the nation's only
federally sponsored art competition, according to organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Hautman's winning design and the other top 20 paintings from
this year's judging will be displayed Friday through Sunday during
the Wildlife Art Festival at the San Bernardino County Museum, 2024
Orange Tree Lane in Redlands. It is one of only two spots across
the country where the stamp art will be exhibited. Hautman and 27
other prominent wildlife artists will be on hand to show off their
paintings, sculptures, carvings and limited edition prints.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $6 for adults; $5 for students, seniors 60 and older,
and ages 13 to 17; $4 for ages 5 to 12; and free for children 4 and
under. Hours: 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Friday and Saturday; 9 a.m. to 4
p.m. Sunday. Information: (909) 307-2669 or (888) 247-3344.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
