<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FIND NEW WAY TO LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ The latest bizarre twist in the decline and fall of
the Kings comes courtesy of defenseman Philippe Boucher, former
King Tony Granato and referee Terry Gregson.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday night, with the score tied and the Kings on a
power play, they discovered yet another way to allow a shorthanded
goal and, in the process, lose their fifth consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   Everything appeared under control. Boucher had the puck deep in
the Kings zone and passed it ahead. But it hit Gregson and landed
on the stick of Granato, who set up a point-blank shot by Marco
Sturm.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Manny Legace made the save, but Granato fired in the
rebound with 7:07 to play, and the Kings went on to lose 5-4 before
a San Jose Arena crowd of 16,703. Six minutes earlier, Granato had
scored the tying goal for the Sharks (4-7-4).
</P>
<P>
   ``Same story, different town,'' Kings coach Larry Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher added, ``I looked up ice and saw Yanic (Perreault). I
wanted to give it to him and I hit the ref. You've got to get it
through. You can't blame the ref. He's got to be somewhere on the
ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, on a night when rookie defenseman Mark Visheau recorded
the first two points of his career, a night when Legace notched his
first NHL assist and a night when the Kings (5-11-3) scored three
goals in a period for the first time this season, they still found
a way to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also lost winger Russ Courtnall to a bruised right
ankle late in the game. He is scheduled to undergo X-rays today.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson recently said a black cloud seems to be hanging over
his jinxed team. Almost from the start Wednesday, the monsoon
continued.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with Legace taking a Robinson shot off the mask
during the morning practice, leaving him with a headache that
remained throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   The night did not begin or end well for the Kings, either.
Before the game was two minutes old, they'd allowed a 3-on-1 that
resulted in the third goal of the season for Joe Murphy and a 1-0
lead for the Sharks, and by the time the game was seven minutes
old, the Kings had allowed two more outnumbered rushes by San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second period, Jeff Friesen made it 2-0, when his
centering pass deflected off the stick of defenseman Sean O'Donnell
and past Legace, the sort of bad bounce the Kings have been getting
all season.
</P>
<P>
   In stunning fashion, though, the Kings responded with their
version of a volcanic eruption, getting goals in a 32-second span
midway through the second period from Luc Robitaille and Glen
Murray to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked hard, and we came back,'' Boucher said. ``But it
seems like we find a way to lose all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Penalties almost proved the Kings' undoing in the form of a
second-period span during which they were shorthanded for 6:27, 62
seconds of that at a two-man disadvantage. But the Kings only
allowed a Friesen goal while one man down, and Murray tied the
score, 3-3, with a shorthanded goal during the same sequence.
</P>
<P>
   And at the final buzzer of the second period, a Marcus
Ragnarsson high-sticking penalty gave the Kings a power play to
open the third.
</P>
<P>
   For a change, they took advantage. Olli Jokinen gave the Kings
their only lead 64 seconds into the third with his second
power-play goal in as many games.
</P>
<P>
   But six minutes later Granato tied the score, and with an assist
from Gregson, the brother of Kings color commentator Cammi Granato
added the game-winner another six minutes after that.
</P>
<P>
   With Legace off for an extra skater in the last minute, Sharks
goalie Mike Vernon stopped a point-blank shot by Murray, preventing
the Kings from sending the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating the Kings' current theme of despair, Robinson said
grimly, ``The puck didn't want to go in.'' &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
