<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS DEFEAT RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Wayne Gretzky may be the Great One, but Marty McInnis
is proving to be the great pickup of the year, and Guy Hebert is
just playing great.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis scored the game-winning goal at 6:42 of the third period
and Hebert made 29 saves as the Mighty Ducks defeated the New York
Rangers 3-1 on Wednesday night before 15,245 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' third consecutive win and fourth in five games moved
them over the .500 mark (7-6-4) for the first time since Nov. 14,
1997 when they were 8-7-5.
</P>
<P>
   It also improved Anaheim's record over New York to 6-2-1 overall
and 5-0 at the Pond, which has become the Rangers' own personal
house of blues.
</P>
<P>
   The Broadway Blues were already in a major funk coming in. New
York (4-8-5) is last in the Eastern Conference and has won only
once in its last seven games (1-4-2).
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers outshot the Ducks 30-16, but they failed to convert
any of nine power plays, gave up the game-winning goal after Kevin
Stevens' ill-advised elbowing penalty and allowed the game's first
goal to be scored one second after one of their power plays had
expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight's game was discouraging, especially with all of the
opportunities we had in the first period (13 shots),'' said
Gretzky, who assisted on Niklas Sundstrom's goal at 16:34 of the
second period.
</P>
<P>
   That goal tied the game, 1-1, but McInnis scored his fifth goal
and 11th point in 11 games as a Duck to give Anaheim the lead for
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played against him before, he was more of an agitator,
a good penalty killer,'' said Paul Kariya, who set up the winning
goal when he faked Adam Graves to the ice and got a shot off that
resulted in a rebound that McInnis buried. ``I didn't realize he
had such good offensive skills. He goes to the net well and has a
hard shot.''
</P>
<P>
   And since being acquired from Calgary on Oct. 27 for a fourth
round draft pick, he has a new outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very excited to come here,'' said McInnis. ``I felt like
I was getting a fresh start. The coach (Craig Hartsburg) gave me
some confidence. It makes you feel confident to contribute
offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, nobody is more confident, or effective as Hebert is
right now.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim goalie came into the game with a .934 save
percentage and has lost only two of his last 13 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a goalie it's all confidence,'' said Hebert who has
started 16 of the Ducks' 18 games. ``When you feel good you don't
want to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg doesn't figured to be making any changes soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a goalie playing like this, you just keep
playing him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis' game winner came less than two minutes after Hebert had
turned away yet another New York threat, stopping Sundstrom on a
two-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   After spending much of the first period killing penalties, the
Ducks couldn't generate any offense in the second until the Rangers
got another power play chance late in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim had managed but one shot in 15 minutes, but just after
Pavel Trnka stepped back on the ice, Steve Rucchin intercepted
Alexei Kovalev's pass intended for Brian Leetch and converted the
ensuing breakaway with a backhander that beat Richter.
</P>
<P>
   New York quickly tied the game when Gretzky, shortly after being
leveled by Trnka, set up Sundstrom's goal from behind the Anaheim
net.
</P>
<P>
   The Gretzky-Sundstrom combination nealry clicked again with just
over a minute left in the period. Hebert, however, maanaged to stop
Sundstrom's deflection from point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   Before the period would end, Hebert had to come up big one more
time, flopping on his back to stop Leetch, who appeared to have a
wide-open net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
