<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-SECESSION (Quebec City) _ Secession is back on center
stage with the Quebec provincial election two weeks away. The
separatist premier vows another secession referendum if he is
re-elected. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-RIGHTS (Santiago) _ The archbishop of Santiago is leading
an effort to reopen the Truth Commission to look into abuses during
the Pinochet era. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PHARMACEUTICALS (Beijing) _ Imported Western
pharmaceuticals have taken China by storm, straining pocketbooks as
they hold out promises of cure. Sales have been buoyed by a new and
unlikely symbiosis: Western drug companies have been aggressively
courting China's doctors and hospitals not only with new pills but
also with gifts, money and even kickbacks, practices that are often
banned in the United States. By Elisabeth Rosenthal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SMOKING-PARIAHS (Sycamore, Ill.) _ To be a smoker in America
today is to be an outcast. It means being viewed as weak, offensive
and, perhaps most of all, dimwitted. Most people who have never
smoked cannot fathom why anyone would put a cigarette in his or her
mouth and draw the noxious fumes. It should be simple to stop. But
almost anyone who has smoked heavily knows otherwise, as one
woman's story attests. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CHILD-SUPPORT (New York) _ A group with members Africa,
Europe, Asia and the United Statesmeet monthly across from the
United Nations. They call themselves the United Nations Family
Rights Committee, and what they have in common is that because of
the complex legal netherworld of diplomatic immunity, they find it
almost impossible to claim the kinds of protections and payments
that other divorced people qualify for automatically. By Jim
Yardley. (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-GUGGENHEIM-MUSEUM (New York) _ The Solomon R. Guggenheim
Museum is quietly developing plans for a large new branch to be
designed by the Los Angeles architect Frank Gehry and built at the
Hudson River on Pier 40 off Houston Street, said people who were
consulted on the project. By Ralph Blumenthal and Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
