   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-DEFENDERS (Las Vegas) _ It is in the aisles of the
Microsoft pavilion at the Comdex computer show where William Gates
finds his staunchest supporters. And the support comes not only
from those cottage programmers who make their livings by writing
programs that run on the Windows and Windows NT operating systems.
The defenders of Gates also include many of the software industry's
most successful figures, even those who feel that Microsoft's
tactics have occasionally crossed the line. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   CISCO-DEALMAKER (San Jose, Calif.) _ At 31, Michelangelo Volpi
of Cisco Systems Inc. has become one of the most influential deal
makers in technology, in many ways more powerful than the myriad
investment bankers and venture capitalists plying their trade in
Silicon Valley. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COKE-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ While much of America spent its
summer vacation lying on the beach or relaxing on a mountaintop,
some key shareholders of Coca-Cola Enterprises spent theirs in a
flurry of trading on the stock exchange. Early filings for the
third quarter show that at least one big mutual fund company, a
money manager and a trust company with significant positions in
Coca-Cola Enterprises sold nearly all their shares during that
period. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   MERGER-AD-COLUMN _ A merger that would have created a giant
media services agency, ranking among the world's three largest, has
unexpectedly been called off. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
