<HEADER>
A8459 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTEROID-PARTICLE-SFC     11-19 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTEROID-PARTICLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIP OFF ASTEROID THAT DOOMED THE DINOSAURS  
 BY DAVID PERLMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    Scientists say they have found a tiny piece of a monster
asteroid that probably crashed to Earth some 65 million years ago
and drove the planet's dinosaurs to extinction.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dark brown chunk of fossil rock _ smaller than a pencil's
eraser tip _ which was found deep beneath the Pacific Ocean floor,
contains clear evidence that it originated in far-off space. Frank
Kyte, a geochemist at the University of California at Los Angeles
who discovered the fragment, is convinced that it came from a giant
asteroid that slammed into the Earth and gouged a crater more than
185 miles wide off the Yucatan peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Kyte said Wednesday that he discovered the jagged little rock
recently while studying a core sample of mud lifted from 150 feet
below the ocean floor by a scientific drilling ship in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing its minerals, Kyte found chemicals indicating that the
rock was a typical carbonaceous chondrite _ a class of meteorites
that occasionally fall to Earth from the thousands of asteroids
that orbit the sun in a belt between the orbits of Mars and
Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Kyte also found that the tiny rock contained an unusual quantity
of the rare element iridium, abundant in asteroids. The discovery
of iridium in a thin layer of rocks all around the world led UC
Berkeley geologist Walter Alvarez to propose in 1980 his seminal
theory about the extinction of the dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   More evidence emerged from the 65 million-year-old fossil fish
scales that were found in the mud sample pulled from the seabed,
Kyte said.
</P>
<P>
   In the clay around the tiny rock, Kyte also found bits of
shock-blasted quartz as well as microscopically small droplets of
minerals that must have once been molten from the heat of an
asteroid's crash to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   When Alvarez first discovered the planetwide iridium layer in
ancient rocks, they were age-dated to about 65 million years ago,
when dinosaurs and more than 75 percent of all life forms became
extinct. The time is known to geologists as the Cretaceous-Tertiary
boundary.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez and many other scientists theorized that a giant
asteroid or comet plunged to Earth at that time and created a
life-destroying ``nuclear winter'' marked first by blazing heat and
then by millennia of darkness and cold that disastrously altered
the Earth's environment.
</P>
<P>
   Later, scientists unearthed powerful evidence for the event in a
giant undersea structure called the Chicxulub crater that stretches
from the Yucatan all the way to Cuba and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   No one could tell, however, whether the object from space was a
comet or a chunk of asteroid. But now Kyte's rock offers the first
bit of evidence large enough to analyze indicating that the
meteorite came from a crashing asteroid. The tiny bit of debris was
probably flung by the long-ago impact across nearly 6,000 miles of
the North Pacific _ about halfway between where San Francisco and
Tokyo now stand _ Kyte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the worst days the Earth had in the last
billion years, and it is important to understand what happened,''
said Kyte, a geochemist at UCLA's Institute of Geophysics and
Planetary Physics. ``There is a strong possibility that this is a
bullet from a smoking gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyte's full report, ``A Fossil Meteorite From the
Cretaceous-Tertiary Boundary,'' is being published Thursday in the
scientific journal Nature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
