<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAWAII-ORIGINS-SFCHRO     11-19 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAWAII-ORIGINS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS LOOK DEEP INSIDE EARTH FOR HAWAII'S SOURCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    Tracking earthquakes halfway to the center of the Earth, a team
of California scientists may have found the mysterious source of
the Hawaiian Islands.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The upwelling river of rock known as the ``Hawaiian plume,''
which has been spewing forth into a seething geologic ``hot spot''
below the Pacific floor for some 80 million years, appears to run
all the way through Earth's thick outer mantle to the boundary zone
surrounding the planet's core.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean the volcanic material that developed into the
Hawaiian Islands had to start its amazing journey about 1,800 miles
down. Some previous estimates had placed Hawaii's geologic
birthplace well within the mantle layer, perhaps only 400 miles or
so below the ocean bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it came from a plume. The question was how deep did
the plume go,'' said researcher Sara Russell at the University of
California at Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   A summary of the findings appears Thursday in the journal
Nature, along with a separate report showing that another narrow
plume, also extending down to the so-called ``core-mantle
boundary,'' formed Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   The research teams in both reports mined earthquake data to
tunnel deeper than ever before into the mysteries of the inner
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawaiian study took advantage of 54 relatively minor
earthquakes in the Tonga-Fiji region between 1990 and 1995. Energy
waves from the quakes radiated through the Pacific and were
recorded on monitoring stations along the California and Oregon
coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers looked for changes in the shape and direction of the
seismic waves to decipher changes in the materials through which
the waves passed. The underground mapping process, called ``seismic
tomography,'' works in much the same way as the scanning devices
doctors use for medical purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference is that doctors can control when and where
their patients get scanned _ earth scientists can't start
earthquakes at will and must use information generated by a limited
array of tracking stations.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions all fell into place when Russell, UC Santa Cruz earth
scientist Thorne Lay and UC Berkeley seismologist Edward Garnero
set out in search of the root of the ``Hawaiian hot spot'' _ as the
plume-fed lump of Pacific magma is called when it reaches the
Earth's crust.
</P>
<P>
   Their data suggested that the root is an estimated 900
horizontal miles southeast of the present-day islands, which drift
along with the moving plates that form the Earth's outer surface.
Researchers likened it to ``a hot smoke cloud rising into a windy
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   The geologically ancient events that shaped the Hawaiian plume
caused hot lumps of material to pool at the Earth's crust,
conditions which gave rise to volcanic eruptions that formed the
actual islands. Research shows that though the material they are
made from is very old, the islands themselves are quite young,
about 6 million years old or less.
</P>
<P>
   The plume that formed them are caused by the inherent
instability at the mantle-core boundary zone, where enough rock has
melted and softened to allow movement. The temperature at the
bottom of the mantle is about 3,000 degrees Celsius, owing to the
semi-molten core surrounding the solid material at the very center
of the Earth. This solid inner core is thought to be about 7,000
degrees.
</P>
</TEXT>
