 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 410 - November 18, 1998   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 410 -- Nov. 18, 1998 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. 'REAR WINDOW' OFFERS A NEW LOOK AT CHRISTOPHER REEVE Since
the tragic horseback-riding accident that left him a quadriplegic,
actor Christopher Reeve has reinvented himself as an author, an
Emmy Award-winning director and a spokesperson on spinal-injury
issues. On Nov. 22, however, he will make his long-awaited return
to acting in an ABC remake of the classic Hitchcock film ``Rear
Window.'' Reeve talks about the new film, the challenge of
undertaking a role made famous by James Stewart, why he still
believes that someday he'll walk again and how so physically
commanding an actor managed to reinvent his style using only his
face and voice to act. By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
ANTHONY HOPKINS INTERVIEW: LONE STAR Who's that long-haired,
solitary drifter lighting candles and talking about flowers? It's
60-year-old Oscar winner Sir Anthony Hopkins. By Merle Ginsberg.
From W magazine. 1,500 words + photos. 3. DOUBLE-DECKER DOCUMENTARY
Timothy ``Speed'' Levitch is the most unusual tour guide in America
- and probably the world. Levitch, 28, is a guide on a Manhattan
double-decker tour bus. He's been called a madman, a genius, an
artist, a freak. Young documentary filmmaker Bennett Miller was so
intrigued by Levitch that he made him the subject of his first
feature film, ``The Cruise,'' a revealing cinema-veriti portrait of
Levitch and New York. By J. Mooney. BPI. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
TODD HAYNES MINES GLITTER OF GLAM ROCK'S ENDLESS PARTY It was a
time of flamboyance and hedonism, of bisexual chic and open drug
use. ``Glam rock'' flickered during the early to mid-1970s. Todd
Haynes was fascinated by the sounds and images of David Bowie, T.
Rex, Roxy Music, Slade and The Sweet in England, the New York Dolls
and Lou Reed in New York, Iggy and the Stooges in Detroit. Last
year, Haynes, now 37, began filming ``Velvet Goldmine,'' his homage
to the glam rock era. By Jim Sullivan. From The Boston Globe. 1,400
words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
HOLLYWOOD'S LAST MOGUL : For nearly 60 years, Hollywood mogul Lew
Wasserman was one of the most powerful men in America. Interesting
revelations are made by Dennis McDougal in his bombshell new book,
``The Last Mogul : Lew Wasserman, MCA, and the Hidden History of
Hollywood.'' By Ivor Davis. 1,000 words + photos. (N/A Great
Britain and Australia.) 
____________________________________________________________________
___________ 6. EDITORS : WE ALSO HAVE SPECIAL INTERVIEWS AVAILABLE
</P>
<P>
   FROM BPI ENTERTAINMENT NEWS SERVICE WITH :
</P>
<P>
   (A) ALANIS MORISSETTE ; (B) BRUCE SPRINGSTEEN ; (C) GARTH BROOKS
; (D) WHITNEY HOUSTON.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
CATE BLANCHETT TAKES A FRESH LOOK AT GOOD QUEEN BESS Elizabeth I of
England was one of the most imposing women in history, and the role
is a challenge for any actress. Australian actress Cate Blanchett
carries it off with panache - and with rumours of an Oscar
nomination. In this interview she talks about the new film
``Elizabeth,'' how she tackled the demanding title role, how she
compares her ``Elizabeth'' co-star Joseph Fiennes with her ``Oscar
and Lucinda'' co-star, his brother Ralph, and why she didn't study
the history books to prepare for the part. By Ian Spelling. 1,400
words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
DREW BARRYMORE ON LIFE, LOVE AND A GUY NAMED LUKE The director of
the new movie ``Home Fries'' had a hard time getting co-stars Drew
Barrymore and Luke Wilson to stop their kissing scenes. It's not
surprising, since they are a couple on and off the screen, and this
is their first film together. In this interview Barrymore tells how
she met Wilson, why she thinks that this time it will last and how
they handle the contrast between his stable Texas background and
her tempestuous Hollywood life as the heir to America's most famous
acting family. By Jeanne Wolf. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
CAMERON DIAZ : DEALING WITH 'BAD THINGS' The title of her new movie
``Very Bad Things'' captures Cameron Diaz's mood right now, having
been bruised by tabloid tangles and scarred by a recent breakup
with boyfriend Matt Dillon. In this interview she talks about the
movie, the breakup, what she's learned about dealing with fame and
why she doesn't think of herself as a nice girl any more. By Cindy
Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
FACE VALUE CARTOON : MY WORST ENEMY'S WEDDING An intriguing cartoon
of Cameron Diaz as Death in her new film ``Very Bad Things,''
depicted in an imaginative single-line drawing toppling the
ornament from the top of a wedding cake. By Vince Lehmkuhl.
