<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8771 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-CRIME-LATINTRA     11-19 1812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CRIME-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S WAR ON CRIME
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By BRENDAN M. CASE 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MEXICO CITY _ It was already a sad day for the Guerrero family.
Alfonso, the family patriarch, was in the hospital for a serious
cancer operation, and his children and grandchildren had come
together for a vigil outside his room at Mexico City's Santa
Patricia Hospital.
 &HT;    But things got worse thanks to some thugs. As relatives waited
for news, two men burst into the waiting room. One removed a pistol
from a fake plaster cast on his arm. They took everything from
everyone in the waiting room: money, jewelry, watches, cellular
telephones, even pens.
 &HT;    Hospitals, apparently, have become the final frontier for
Mexico's ever bolder thieves.
 &HT;    ``In the end, we didn't care that much about the robbery because
my grandfather pulled through the operation,'' says Ariadna Alba
Guerrero, 28, a kindergarten teacher. ``But being robbed in the
hospital? These people have no shame.''
 &HT;    No one anywhere seems safe. Crime in Mexico, once a sore on the
fringes of society, has come to infect the entire country.
 &HT;    Many of the horror stories make the Guerrero family seem lucky.
There was the murder last December of Peter John Zarate, a U.S.
real estate executive and father of three. He was killed in a
taxicab robbery gone wrong. Then there was Jan Reid, a writer for
Texas Monthly magazine. She was shot under similar circumstances
and left partially paralyzed, prompting the U.S. State Department
to repeat its warning that U.S. visitors should only take special
``Sitio Taxis'' from taxi stands.
 &HT;    Then there are the countless muggings, cargo robberies,
kidnappings, and murders that occur every day. About half of all
Mexicans say they have been the victim of a crime during the last
year, particularly armed robbery, according to informal surveys
conducted by security experts. Nearly all say they know someone who
has been a victim.
 &HT;    Crime often seems to reach into the least likely venues. This
reporter lost a washload of clothes when gun-toting thieves
sauntered into a Mexico City laundromat and demanded the business's
money. Because the proprietress only had US$25, they took all the
customers' clothes.
 &HT;    Official figures indicate that crime doubled between 1994 and
1996, though security specialists note that public distrust of the
police means many crimes are never reported.
 &HT;    ``Police are part of the problem,'' says Pete Palmer, the
director of Problem Solvers, a private security firm in Mexico
City.
 &HT;    The lack of public safety has gotten so bad that political
analysts are talking about the government's failure to provide for
citizens' basic security needs. And many foreign companies are
wondering if Mexico is such a good place to do business after all.
 &HT;    The worst problem for them might not be muggings and
kidnappings, but cargo theft. According to the National Truck and
Cargo Chamber, 200 trucks were robbed of their loads in the first
half of 1998, though chamber oficials said most of such robberies
are not reported. Several hundred more passenger buses have been
robbed, a third in or near Mexico City.
 &HT;    ``Crime is a huge issue for the companies we work with,'' says
Phillip Hendrix, the director of the Texas state trade office in
Mexico City, adding that Texas companies account for more than 40
percent of U.S. exports to Mexico and provide a large share of
foreign direct investment. ``We recruited 10 Texas companies to
come here for a trade show, and six canceled because of the State
Department advisory on taxis. We have other people who simply won't
come to Mexico, regardless.''
 &HT;    The crime situation in Mexico may seem outrageous, but a little
perspective might be in order. Yes, crime is bad, particularly in
Mexico City. And yes, private-sector experts believe it's getting
worse, despite the claims of the city government. But in one sad
sense, Mexico City has only been catching up to big cities in the
rest of the region, including New York, Bogota and Rio de Janeiro.
 &HT;    ``Yeah, we got a hell of a lot of crime, but it is not as
violent as north and south of here,'' says Palmer. ``The good news
is that criminals are not hopped up on some chemical the way they
often are in other countries, so they're less likely to shoot. And
you can get them to pick on someone else.''
 &HT;    Mexico City was once one of the safest cities in the hemisphere,
and it's still considered safer than New York. The Big Apple had
5,800 crimes per 100,000 persons every year; Mexico City had 3,000
per 100,000 persons (although experts say that number might be
understated because many victims do not report crimes).
 &HT;    Experts trace the current crime wave to a laundry list of
factors. Among them, the incipient family breakdown and the popular
perception of wealthy politicians, such as former president Carlos
Salinas de Gortari and his brother, Raul, as thieves. There's also
the sense of disorder that seems to accompany Mexico's political
and economic transition, and the increased respect for human rights
that goes with Mexico's democratic political development, but also
prevents police from using strong-arm tactics. There are few police
who know how to do proper investigations, and antiquated laws that
make them cumbersome, anyway.
 &HT;    But one statistic jumps out more than any other. For every 1,000
crimes committed (and reported to police), only 36 lead to arrest
and conviction.
 &HT;    ``Criminals evaluate their risks just like everyone else,'' says
Tom Cash, a senior managing director with the U.S. multinational
security firm Kroll-O'Gara. ``But there are so few arrests that the
chances are pretty good that things will work out for them.''
 &HT;    Many police officers actually participate in crimes, and the
honest ones simply don't have the manpower to handle the deluge.
Impunity reigns, say experts.
 &HT;    Responding to growing public outrage, President Ernesto Zedillo
recently unveiled a ``National Crusade against Crime and
Delinquency.'' Experts welcomed the $350 million program as a step
in the right direction in some ways. For example, the program
proposes counting all the police officers in the country _ an
unknown figure _ and keeping files on each one. That should help
prevent dirty officers from escaping their past by moving to
another state.
 &HT;    ``We have faltered, but we will not fail,'' says Zedillo.
 &HT;    The program also proposes to toughen penalties for white collar
crimes, which today are laughably light. For instance, for nearly
four years, the Mexican government assembled such a strong case
against fugitive banker Angel Isidoro Rodriguez, who is accused of
bilking shareholders of Banpais bank of more than $10 million, that
a court in Spain agreed to extradite him. But when he arrived in
Mexico this summer, he was released on bail because his alleged
offenses were not deemed ``serious'' under Mexican law.
 &HT;    But Zedillo's National Crusade could be a costly failure in
other respects, says Rafael Ruiz Harrell, Mexico's leading
criminologist. The plan stresses building more prisons and
toughening sentences, a deterrent whose effects are debatable.
Moreover, the plan does not consider ways to prevent crime before
it happens, an idea that was a cornerstone of the New York Police
Department's successful ``zero tolerance'' program.
 &HT;    ``The words preventive police are not even used in the wording
of the Crusade,'' says Ruiz Harrell. ``Zero tolerance was based on
the idea of promoting problem-solving police instead of reactive
police, but they haven't understood that here. For the government,
crime is a mechanical problem that occurs in a world parallel to
society. Let's just hope that the lack of stress on prevention
doesn't lead to human-rights abuses or repression.''
 &HT;    Perhaps the only good news to come from Mexico's crime wave is
that the average person is not entirely defenseless. While criminal
gangs dominate the kidnapping and auto theft industries _ infamous
kidnapper Daniel Arizmendi, known for cutting the ears off his
victims, worked with several dozen associates before his arrest in
August _ most run-of-the-mill thieves are amateurs. And while
assaults in hospitals or dark alleys or taxis might be hard to
avoid once they start, average people can take some precautions.
 &HT;    First, many thieves thrive on the element of surprise, and
prefer to avoid confrontation. Making eye contact and appearing
alert can scare them off.
 &HT;    ``If you've lived in New York or Los Angeles, you can handle
Mexico City, but don't leave your common sense on the airplane,''
says Palmer. ``It's not your profile that's dangerous, it's your
behavior. If you take certain precautions, the problem goes away.''
 &HT;    A little effort can help avoid other types of crime. Private
security firms offer courses that teach advanced driving techniques
to avoid assaults. Top executives should vary the routes they take
to work, make sure their office buildings are safe and consider
security guards, specialists say.
 &HT;    Cargo theft can be greatly reduced if companies keep careful
track of who's hauling their merchandise. The old system of
informal carriers is giving way to more professional trucking
companies.
 &HT;    The problem is that many of these measures are expensive. Top
security firms charge around $1,500 per day for consulting services
and courses, putting them out of the reach of most companies that
are not big multinationals.
 &HT;    The difficulty of reorganizing police forces and rewriting laws,
plus the recent rise in drug use registered among teenagers,
suggest that the fight against crime has only just begun in Mexico.
One question is whether it can be won. Another question is if it
can be won in time.
 &HT;    ``One big danger to Mexico is if these multinational businesses
leave because of unsafe conditions,'' says Cash, of Kroll-O'Gara.
``Do they move to Monterrey or Hermosillo? Or do they move to
Dallas or Houston or Miami?''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
