<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8780 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-WINTER-$ADV22-     11-19 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-WINTER-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA COPES WITH HARD TIMES AND A HARD WINTER AHEAD
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-AID-$ADV22.
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    EDs: For the purposes of a locator map, Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky
is situated on the Kamchatka peninsula between Japan and Alaska's
Aleutian Islands.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Nov. 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETROPAVLOVSK-KAMCHATSKY, Russia _ At Public School 17, students
and teachers are bundled in winter coats and thick wool sweaters.
Each breath fogs in the frigid air as they recite grammar lessons.
The potted plants on the window sill, intended to add some life to
the drab classroom, are frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Outside a thick blanket of snow already covers the remote
Kamchatka peninsula in Russia's Far East. Temperatures have been
below freezing for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the school on a recent November morning, the mercury
wasn't much higher, because after weeks of numbing cold, the
heating came on for the first time this season only hours ago.
</P>
<P>
   Winter arrives early and hard in this Pacific port city, and
throughout Russia's remote regions in the Arctic, central Siberia
and the Far East. Russia's economic crisis and the annual arrival
of ice and snow are a dangerous combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live like primitive people. No heat. No lights. No money.
Things are awful. The coming 21st century doesn't matter in
Kamchatka. It matters only in other countries. Here it is the 19th
century,'' complained Oxana Ivanova, 17, a student at P.S. 17.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, fuel shortages cut heat and electricity to
homes, businesses and schools and caused several deaths on
Kamchatka, nine times zones and 5,000 miles east of Moscow. Similar
shortages have hit other remote areas and forced evacuations as the
government in Moscow cannot afford to supply food and fuel.
</P>
<P>
   At Public School 17, perched on a ridge in the shadow of a
dramatic range of snow-peaked volcanic mountains that meet the
Pacific Ocean, heat and lights were restored this week, as they
were to most parts of Kamchatka, a peninsula roughly the size of
California and home to 400,000 Russians.
</P>
<P>
   But for weeks, temperatures inside apartments, classrooms and
offices dipped below 45 degrees as winter storms descended. Lacking
fuel to run two main power plants, electricity was rationed to
three hours a day and the central heating network, which supplies
virtually every building on the peninsula with steam heat, was not
turned on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about such conditions from my grandfather and now this
year I found myself in such terrible times,'' said Ludmilla
Nanovskaya, an English teacher at P.S. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Adding financial anxiety to the aching cold, the region's
teachers have not been paid since the school year began on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Electricity and heat began flowing -- at least for now -- after
embarrassed authorities in Moscow acknowledged the emergency and
ordered 10,000 tons of fuel oil from the Pacific navy fleet's
reserves to feed the peninsula's power plants.
</P>
<P>
   They were goaded to the task after the local Kamchatka
legislature drafted and threatened to send a direct appeal for
humanitarian assistance to the United Nations. Other strapped and
suffering regions in Russia have made similar appeals, an ominous
and awkward reminder to the Kremlin of the country's vulnerability
as four months of brutal winter begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until this problem is solved we will continue to work from
crisis to crisis,'' said Yevgeny Klochkov, director of
Kamchatskenergo, the local utility that provides heat and
electricity to the peninsula. ``The problem is not resolved for the
entire winter because we do not have the cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian weather forecasters have predicted the harshest winter
in 30 years. This discouraging news came amid last month's report
that Russia's grain harvest was nearly half the levels of 1997 and
the worst in 45 years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the economic crash of August, which sent the ruble
plummeting, has made more than half of all Russians poor. According
to the Russian Center of the Standard of Living, 79 million
Russians now live in poverty, out of a total population of 147
million.
</P>
<P>
   To help alleviate concerns about food supplies, the United
States and Russia last week reached a deal to ship 3.1 million tons
of American food aid, including grain and meat -- about half of it
in the form of direct aid.
</P>
<P>
   Here by the sea in Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky there are no food
shortages. But as in much of Russia, food is out of reach with the
country's economy in shambles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has this problem. There are things to buy but no one
is buying because no one can afford it. So people grow their own,''
said Olga Kosmynina, editor of the local Rybak Kamchatsky
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Since Russia's economic crisis erupted in mid-August, her paper
has been running a regular ``how to survive'' feature -- such as
tips on how to pickle cabbage for the winter and how to better seal
your windows from the icy winter winds.
</P>
<P>
   The predicament in Kamchatka was caused by a chain reaction that
reflects the paralysis of Russia's economy today, not quite a free
market and not quite the welfare state of Soviet times.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, virtually bankrupt, cannot pay the
military, the largest single consumer of energy in Kamchatka, which
is dotted with naval and air force bases. Thus, the military cannot
pay the local utility, which has amassed $146 million in debts and
was unable to buy fuel to run its plants.
</P>
<P>
   Until mid-November, people read by candlelight and there was no
hot water. They slept in their parkas and wool caps. The school day
and business hours were cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   This in a country that is the world's premier producer of
natural gas and on a peninsula seething with active volcanoes --
geothermal energy just waiting to be tapped. Plans call for a new
gas pipeline and geothermal plants, but construction has been
hampered by Russia's economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   The perplexing irony is that if this region were gauged by its
natural resources, geography and educated populace, it would be
rich. The peninsula and the surrounding waters are bountiful in
seafood and deposits of gold, copper and nickel. Kamchatka is
nearer to Tokyo and Anchorage than to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   In Soviet times, such outposts were supported by the communist
government, who settled the remote regions to fortify the empire
and exploit the natural resources. But post-Soviet Russia, rife
with corruption, struggling to reform its economy and nearly out of
cash, finds it increasingly difficult to subsidize the regions.
</P>
<P>
   Russian lawmakers have called for the evacuation of over 1
million residents of the worst-hit areas. Heating fuel rations and
electricity cuts also have reached the Yakutia region in
northeastern Siberia and Sakhalin Island, Chukotka and Koryak on
Russia's northern Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   In Kamchatka and elsewhere, Russians approach the coming winter
with docile forbearance, relying on food they have grown during the
summer to last them through the winter.
</P>
<P>
   No one predicts catastrophe, yet no one is happy about their
circumstances either as they cope to combat hunger and cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Russia, we like to emphasize that Russia is so great, so
large,'' said Vladimir Yefimov, director of the local television
station in Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky. ``But there is less and less
of that. Russia is being whittled away.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
