<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN22-CO     11-19 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: U.N. tribunal too gentle on war criminals
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, Nov. 22, 1998.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the many who believe the U.S. criminal justice system,
particularly the courts, has gone too soft, meet the United Nations
war crimes tribunal. Last week, a three-member court in The Hague,
Netherlands, found three men guilty of war crimes against Bosnian
Serb prisoners in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But did the punishment fit the crimes?
</P>
<P>
   Well, what do you get for being a prison camp commander who
allowed guards to murder nine Serbs and torture six?
</P>
<P>
   Seven years. That's it, seven years. No wonder Zdravko Mucic
smiled when his sentence was handed down. He's only 42, will be 49
he gets out; plenty of time for more negligent command.
</P>
<P>
   He could have gotten life imprisonment. In the U.S., he likely
would have gotten a ticket to a lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Mucic's deputy, 37-year-old Hazim Delic. He was
convicted of murdering two people, raping two women and torturing
other prisoners. The price for multiple murder, rape and torture,
according to the U.N. tribunal? Twenty years. Not life, but 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   The upside of it, I suppose, was that at last rape is being
treated as a war crime after millennia of it being seen as nothing
but a spoil of war.
</P>
<P>
   It was in sentencing Delic that presiding judge Adolphus
Karibi-Whyte of Nigeria said that rape was ``a despicable act which
strikes at the very core of human dignity.'' But it wasn't
despicable enough, along with a couple of outright murders and some
torture, to get Delic life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In the 483-page ruling, the three judges said Delic appeared
``to take a sadistic pleasure in causing the detainees pain.'' Just
20 years, though.
</P>
<P>
   Esad Landzo, a guard at the Celebici prison camp in central
Bosnia in 1992, was convicted of three murders and of torturing at
least three other inmates. The 24-year-old had been charged with
killing five, but convicted of only three. Prosecutors said Landzo
beat one prisoner to death with a wooden plank and that he and
Delic beat another man to death, then nailed a badge of the Muslim
political party into his head.
</P>
<P>
   For all this, young Landzo, described as a thug, got 15 years.
In the United States, that's a likely sentence for robbing a
7-Eleven with a handgun _ before they start taking off gain time.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier stories about their atrocities, written when the men
went on trial 20 months ago, said their prisoners were beaten with
steel cables, wood and metal bars, burned with heated scissors,
kept in vats of water. They also were forced, according to a wire
service story, to act like animals and perform oral sex on each
other. And the women were raped.
</P>
<P>
   The officer who had overall command of the camp, outranking
Mucic, was aquitted by the court of all charges, for which he told
the tribunal that it was ``a very wise judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the weakness of the U.N. sentencing _ capital punishment
not allowed, by the way _ makes the American system any better; it
just looks that way. We still are tethered to a system where plea
bargaining, prison overcrowding, gain time, sentencing guidelines,
parole boards and wimpy judges put too many thugs, murderers and
rapists back on the streets too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison with the U.N., however, we look tough.
</P>
<P>
   I'm trying to comprehend one thing: I had been led to believe,
in what I read and saw, that the World War II war crimes trials set
the standard. Didn't a bunch of German and Japanese war criminals
get their necks stretched for what they did to humanity? Now, 50
years later, it's only 15 or 20 years?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
