</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: 'Unfinished Business' forum needs a champion
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. Many useful words and even some important
ones were spoken in the three days of the ``Unfinished Business''
forum in Birmingham, Ala., last weekend, as some 400 activists
agonized toward a new agenda for a New South. But I think I know
what was missing.
</P>
<P>
   There was no architecture of national caring to house the
undertaking, no validating political context as a frame of
reference. What was missing, in short, was the New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   The conference echoed the brave Southern Conference for Human
Welfare in the same city 60 years earlier. Then, some 1,500
progressives convened to write and adopt a social wish list for a
region marred by the grossest racism, ignorance and what looked
like permanent economic depression.
</P>
<P>
   The 1938 meeting was brazenly biracial, and although the basic
racial and economic justice it called for is now acknowledged as an
essential precursor to the modern boom that has brought prosperity
to much of the old South, the agenda was widely denounced at the
time as radical and frightening. Even so, it had a certain implied
cache just by being issued under the protective cover of the
reformist New Deal, recently reinforced by President Franklin
Roosevelt's re-election by near-acclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Even to our own conservative times, there is little that is
comparably scary in the recent conference's calls for strengthened
public education (a disavowal of the voucher hustle to fund private
schools), universal health care, full employment, affordable and
safe housing and a justice system scrubbed of its racial
grotesqueries and economic inequities.
</P>
<P>
   But if not such a bugaboo as the original, there is something a
bit forlorn about the new agenda even so. It is easier to get
notice at least, and engagement if not concurrence, in a can-do
atmosphere than in today's stubborn stasis, compounded as it is of
smug satisfaction, indifference to such distortions as the
dangerously widening gap between rich and poor and a political
fatalism that bars any public intervention for the common good.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there aren't worthy and even heroic efforts under way
for something better.
</P>
<P>
   The Workforce Alliance has pulled public and private sectors
together in Mississippi County, Ark., to upgrade worker skills, cut
unemployment and increase incomes. Birmingham's Bethel-Ensley
Action Task, a partnership of churches and neighborhood groups, has
revived a seemingly moribund part of the city. In Greensboro, N.C.,
the Partnership Project managed to get at least a few crucially
placed whites to see that, although overt racial discrimination is
tamped down, its deadly assumptions and purposes remain imbedded in
our basic social fabric, producing such racial deformities as those
of the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   But however admirable in their own right, those and the many
more similar gestures struggling in near anonymity around the
country will remain patchy palliatives until we become willing to
look up from the busy perfecting of our pocketbooks and
additionally begin to work again on the well-being of the nation.
Not all of our unfinished business will take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
