<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-APOLOGY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FINDS LEWINSKY CASE FOLLOWS HIM TO TOKYO 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: New 7th graf with Clinton demeanor.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ As the House began impeachment hearings in Washington
Thursday, President Clinton traveled more than 8,000 miles to Tokyo
only to be confronted by an indignant Japanese housewife who
questioned his apology to his wife and daughter for the Monica
Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you apologize to Mrs. Clinton and Chelsea?'' the
mother of two asked in a nationally televised 43-minute
question-and-answer session with the president. ``I feel I would
never be able to forgive my husband for doing that, but did they
really forgive you, Mr. President?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who had been jocular and animated during the opening
minutes of the broadcast, appeared startled by the question from a
woman in a television audience in Osaka that was linked via
television hookup to Clinton, who was sitting in the studios of the
Tokyo Broadcasting System here in the Japanese capital.
</P>
<P>
   The invited audience of 100 of Japan's future leaders seated
before him reacted with a collective sigh to the question, which
the unidentified housewife posed in Japanese and the president
heard through a translator.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who had already fielded seven questions, replied in a
deliberate, patient tone with a strained smile crossed his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well I did it in a direct and straight forward manner,''
Clinton explained, speaking slowly. ``I believe they did, yes. But
that's really a question you could ask them better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   The president clinched his jaw after completing his response.
Appearing weary from the overnight flight to Tokyo, he spoke slowly
and was less effusive than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mrs. Clinton nor Chelsea accompanied the president to
Tokyo. Mrs. Clinton is touring hurricane-damaged nations in Central
America; Chelsea is a sophomore at Stanford University, in Palo
Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   TV personality Tetsuya Chikushi, host for Clinton's town-meeting
session, quickly injected, ``Let's change the subject now.''
</P>
<P>
   Chikushi shifted the subject to U.S.-Japan relations, observing:
``Now our bilateral relationship is the most important of all.''
</P>
<P>
   Chikushi is Japan's version of former talk show host Phil
Donahue. He and the president sat before the live audience on two
bar stools with a large video screen before them that linked the
studio to Osaka.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton delighted his audience with a series of personal
insights.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question,, Clinton boasted about his close
relationship with his daughter, who he had helped with her homework
``until it became too difficult for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He offered public speaking advice to another questioner, telling
her to pretend ``that you're speaking to a few of your friends''
rather than addressing a large audience via television. ``You don't
have to change; you just have to be yourself,'' Clinton counseled.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told of his efforts during a busy presidency to achieve
``a balanced life'' with work, family time, church and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do the things that remind me that I'm a normal person and I
need a balanced life,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name the favorite ``dishes that your wife cooks,''
Clinton said that he is known in America for liking a variety of
food.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people make fun of me because of that,'' said
Clinton. ``But I suppose my favorite dish is a Mexican dish _
chicken enchiladas,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he and the first lady usually have dinner
together at the White House three or four times a week. ``My wife
and I have dinner together every night when we're both home,''
Clinton explained. ``That is unless she has to go out to an
engagement or I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
