A8800 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLEN-CELEBRITY20-COX     11-19 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLEN-CELEBRITY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REVIEW: Allen's `Celebrity' both bearable, funny
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Celebrity.'' 3 stars. Starring: Kenneth
Branagh, Judy Davis, Leonardo DiCaprio, Winona Ryder, Charlize
Theron, Melanie Griffith. Director: Woody Allen. Screenwriter:
Woody Allen MPAA rating: R for language, sex, some drug use.
</P>
<P>
   The films of Woody Allen in the 1990s have been ragged, hasty
affairs, premised on watery conceits and executed with an alarming
disregard for the medium's capacity for beauty and order. Worse,
they haven't been very funny.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decade, Allen's film-a-year output has spanned the
trifling and haphazard (``Bullets Over Broadway,'' ``Manhattan
Murder Mystery'') to the luridly unbecoming (``Deconstructing
Harry''). In only one instance, ``Husbands and Wives,'' did humor
and thematic heft intersect rewardingly. And that movie, the camera
quivering like Jell-O on horseback, required Dramamine to endure.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sad testament to the artist, but Allen has been at his
best alluding to his most popular phase of filmmaking, that
feverish interlude which began with ``Annie Hall'' (1977) and
petered-out with ``Hannah and Her Sisters'' (1986). Woodyphiles
could have a field day cataloging the recycled jokes littering the
later films.
</P>
<P>
   His new comedy ``Celebrity'' is chock full of knowing allusions
to Allen's unofficial golden age, which helps to make ``Celebrity''
two things most of his recent work has not been: 1) bearable, and
2) pretty funny.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Celebrity,'' a whooshing, heavily populated movie that
takes a weed-whacker to the fields of fame, also shares qualities
of the sloppy late works. It's unfocused, ungainly, swollen with
distracting cameos by a Hollywood Who's Who, and requires the lead,
in this case Kenneth Branagh, to fussily mimic the famous Allen
persona. (Remember when even Mia Farrow was doing the stammering,
gesticulating nebbish routine? That was icky.) Allen's new vulgar
streak _ the X-rated invective, the juvenile fixation on oral sex _
is also disturbingly present.
</P>
<P>
   Branagh, hiding his British accent, plays Lee Simon, a celebrity
journalist in _ where else? _ Manhattan. More sycophant than
scribe, Simon gloms onto the glitterati like a pilot fish to a
shark, feeding off the vestigial glow under the pretext of chasing
stories.
</P>
<P>
   In a careworn Allen plot point, Simon has dumped his wife (a
harried, shrewish Judy Davis, repeating her roles in ``Husbands and
Wives'' and ``Harry'') and is panting after celebrity women often
half his age (Winona Ryder as a fledgling actress, Melanie Griffith
as a starlet, and Charlize Theron as a supermodel).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Simon's life is a sham. He's spent it hydroplaning
the surface and pinballing to anyone he believes can advance his
hollow course. He's a tragic figure, chasing the impossible as a
way to distract himself from the hard work of charting a meaningful
existence. This is beaten terrain for Allen (he played essentially
the same unenlightened sap in ``Manhattan''), but there's a
satisfying kick in walking it again.
</P>
<P>
   As far as its titular promise, ``Celebrity'' is not strenuous
satire. Staged like an Altmanesque cavalcade, the story lopes
through the starry milieus of film, acting (see Leonardo DiCaprio
snort coke and smash furniture!), fashion, art, television, books
and sports, with mocking pit stops at Christianity (celebrity
priests and Jesus action figures) and the weird world of famous
criminals and their victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can learn a lot about a society by who it chooses to
celebrate,'' says a character. I'm not sure what we can learn that
we don't already know, and in ``Celebrity'' it's never clear what
Allen wants to teach. Clearly, he revels in hating the sick,
symbiotic fame game, a distaste he so bitterly displayed in the
recent documentary ``Wild Man Blues'' and the 1980 hate-letter to
his fans, ``Stardust Memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen mocks the swank milieus with gimlet-eyed observation
rather than harsh commentary, yet it still feels nasty. He
satisfies his editorial druthers by staging the scenes with a sheen
of hyperbole, giving the characters enough rope to hang themselves.
</P>
<P>
   What to say about Branagh's tic-specific, Woody wannabe act?
Branagh (a man, it should be noted, with no lips) blows through the
film's teeming vignettes like a dried leaf. He has ``Woody Allen''
nailed: His shoulders cave-in as his arms do their stubby
gesticulations. He whines in that piercing singsong, and the
chronic stammers grind his lines to elliptical sawdust.
</P>
<P>
   (Why Allen encourages this bald aping is beyond me. It's more
than a little embarrassing and is further confirmation of Allen's
vaunted narcissism.)
</P>
<P>
   If the material is untidy, ``Celebrity'' looks fabulous. Allen
has recovered control of mise-en-sce(accent)ne, not to mention
directorial command of his actors. Filmed in his famed superlong
takes, scenes possess an artful order: the depicted chaos flows,
doesn't pile-up. The film was shot in silken black-and-white by
famed cinematographer Sven Nykvist.
</P>
<P>
   Like the bulk of his recent films, there's something palpably
off in ``Celebrity.'' Allen is increasingly becoming film's sour
old man, and although the throwback humor is mildly satisfying, the
movie is never as funny as you'd like it to be. It kind of hangs
there, another oddity in the Allen oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
