u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN20-COX     11-19 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fighting off the fungus, bugs and other evils
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The grass is always greener...
</P>
<P>
   I'm nearly six months into my role as sole Lawn Boy out here in
the semi-country. My massive spread of San Augustine sod survived
the Summer from Hell; as a result I can take sole credit for the
city's budget surplus, due to the ridiculous amount of water it
took to keep 60 pallets of grass alive during the Time it Never
Rained. I had water bills that rivaled car payments for a while.
</P>
<P>
   All that is past, a distant memory now that cool weather has
finally arrived. It's interesting how quickly we forget unpleasant
things, like 35 straight days of 100-plus degree temperatures. I
read somewhere that's why women are often willing to go through
childbirth more than once, because nature blots out the memory of
the pain they went through the first time. I don't know about that,
being of a different gender and averse to all forms
</P>
<P>
   of pain. I'm just proud not to be sweating seconds after walking
out the front door.
</P>
<P>
   But all is not coming up roses here. A yard of San Augustine
grass is like having a sickly child. It's always something. Chinch
bugs. Armyworms. Brown-patch fungus. Fireants. Gophers. Armadillos.
Weird weeds, whose name I don't care to know. My precious grass,
and I mean that in all senses of the adjective, has been under
constant attack from the dark side of Mother Nature since Day One.
</P>
<P>
   I have fertilized, fungicided, weeded, whacked, sprayed and
flayed this lawn. It is an obsession with me. And like most
obsessions, something is always going haywire.
</P>
<P>
   A landscaping fetish is in general a male thing. Women, and I'm
</P>
<P>
   stereotyping here, generally look at the lawn after their spouse
or
</P>
<P>
   significant other has sweated and labored for hours, and say,
``That's nice, dear,'' then head back into the air-conditioning. I
figure they're getting even for childbirth. Men consider their
lawn-taming accomplishments a temporary triumph of the will against
the way of the jungle _ no small feat, a big deal that is
unappreciated by other household members.
</P>
<P>
   This y-chromosome thing is also what's at play in vehicles with
trip meters. Men generally reset the trip meter after filling up or
when about to go on a trip. We do this to keep track of vital
information, such as gas mileage, how far 'til we get there, and to
make sure the gauge hasn't gone haywire. I know I can get about 300
miles to a tank, so it's a backup for the gauge. I always reset the
trip meter after filling up.
</P>
<P>
   Women in general regard the trip meter as a useless device,
right up there with the emergency brake. They don't give a whit
about gas mileage, figure they'll get there when they get there,
and plan on suing someone if the gas gauge doesn't work as
advertised.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm getting off track. Back to the grass. The brown-patch
fungus began wreaking havoc on the lawn once the weather cooled.
Once I figured it out, not being real observant, huge chunks of
grass had turned yellow, wide circles of sick sod. I have put out
several sacks of fungicide at $23 a bag to stop the damage, and the
grass likely won't die. But it looks tacky, a sad result after all
those months of anal-retentive care.
</P>
<P>
   So, against my better judgment, I bought a 50-pound sack of rye
grass and over seeded the lawn last week, to hide the yellow grass.
I did this once before, out in the country, but I used regular
pasture rye grass, which grows at an alarming rate. That grass
would grow before your eyes. You could mow in the morning and have
to hop back on the mower by sundown. Since I planted about two
acres of the stuff, it became a burden in a hurry. Before it was
over, I ended up buying three cows and letting them loose on the
lawn. This is true.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, I'm using regular golf-course/lawn seed, which
grows much slower, I'm told. Despite slow growth, I will be mowing
throughout the winter, through sleet and rain, harsh winds and all.
I figure Christmas Day will consist of opening presents and mowing
the lawn. Ditto with New Year's. Maybe even Valentine's Day, too.
</P>
<P>
   By then, I may be hunting a few cows, which I'm told are cheap
right now. I'll have to check the homeowners' association rules to
see if livestock is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   At least I'm not having to water anymore. The city is on its own
again, financially speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
