<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jet-setting Levi finds a refuge in Mahler
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yoel Levi sounds like a conductor in a candy store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you, I'm excited to come back,'' says the maestro,
calling between rehearsals for this weekend's Atlanta Symphony
Orchestra concerts, his first since Oct. 3. Not only is he
conducting Mahler's Symphony No. 7 _ and recording it for Telarc _
but at Saturday night's glitzy ASO ball, he'll lead the orchestra
in a selection of Broadway show tunes.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, folks. It's Mendelssohn and Mahler one night,
``Girl Crazy'' and ``My Fair Lady'' the next.
</P>
<P>
   But before we go there, Levi wants to tell us about that darned
staircase in Amsterdam's Concertgebouw, where he recently led the
Netherlands Radio Philharmonic in works by Delius, Arensky, Liszt
and Ives. The acoustics are legendary, Levi says, but those steps
are the pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come through the audience going down, and everyone watches
you. It's a big tradition there _ how do you negotiate the stairs?
You can imagine negotiating those stairs every time you finish a
piece. ... I should have worn a cape, since I was born in
Transylvania _ like Dracula.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh ... was it Halloween?
</P>
<P>
   ``When was Halloween?'' he asks blankly, sounding as if a few
cobwebs might've crept in among the music. Momentarily confused by
his jet-setting calendar, he soon remembers that he was in fact in
the Dutch city Oct. 31. And before returning to Atlanta, he stopped
in Stockholm, Sweden, for a festival honoring 77-year-old composer
Ingvar Lidholm.
</P>
<P>
   The music was difficult, but Lidholm ``was absolutely blown off
his feet when he realized I conducted everything from memory,''
says Levi, 48. ``He was totally shocked. He was so sweet and
grateful. He came and hugged me and kissed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Levi's elated to be home, conducting his hands-down favorite
composer, Mahler. After recording Mahler's fourth, fifth and sixth
symphonies for Telarc, the ASO is adding No. 7 to its shelf in
recording sessions Sunday and Monday. Compared to Mahler's bleaker
fin de siecle works, No. 7 contains passages of sheer ecstasy and
even has solos for guitar and mandolin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no composer who was able to express and portray all
the different aspects of life the way Mahler did, the hopes and
dreams and struggles,'' says Levi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cynical part of life and the bad part of life and the
question of death are always there.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does he feel when it's all over?
</P>
<P>
   ``It really takes many hours until you wind down. The music
keeps ringing and playing in your brain, and it takes forever to
fall asleep. You cannot detach yourself from what happened a few
minutes ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Should be an ennobling moment _ for the conductor and the
symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
