</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVERTISING-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTS AND PEOPLE IN THE ADVERTISING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Calif., Conn., Mass., Minn., Nev., N.Y., Ore.,
Texas)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GSD&AMP;M Is Chosen By Mirage Resorts
</P>
<P>
   Mirage Resorts Inc. in Las Vegas, Nev., said Wednesday that it
had named GSD&AMP; M in Austin, Tex., to handle the creative portion of
its account, with billings estimated at $30 million. The account
had been handled for a decade by Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney in San
Francisco, part of Publicis S.A., until Riney and Mirage mutually
parted ways last month.
</P>
<P>
   John Schadler, vice president for advertising at Mirage Resorts,
said that GSD&AMP; M, a unit of Omnicom Group, was awarded the
assignment after a monthlong informal review that also included
Richards Group in Dallas and TBWA/Chiat/Day in Playa del Rey,
Calif., another Omnicom unit. The Los Angeles office of Western
International Media, part of the Interpublic Group of Companies,
continues to handle media services for Mirage Resorts, which
operates properties that include the new Bellagio hotel, the Golden
Nugget, the Mirage and Treasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   New York Studios Names Arnell Group
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York Studios Inc., which plans to build a
high-technology film and television production studio at the
Brooklyn Navy Yard, said Wednesday that it had named Arnell Group
Brand Consulting in New York to handle strategic brand development
and marketing communications. Billings were estimated at $1 million
for the first year. Arnell was awarded the assignment without a
review. The studio, scheduled to open in the first quarter of 2000,
was founded by Delphi Studios and Progressive Internet
Alternatives. In July, Louis Madigan, chief executive at New York
Studios, and Cary Hart, its president, signed a contract for a
70-year lease for the project with the Brooklyn Navy Yard
Development Corp..
</P>
<P>
   Footwear Campaign To Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
</P>
<P>
   Just For Feet Inc., the athletic footwear retailer in
Birmingham, Ala., has named the Rochester office of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi as the first agency to handle advertising for a national
branding campaign, with billings estimated at $25 million to $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi Rochester, part of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC, was
awarded the assignment after an informal review that also included
three agencies in New York: DDB Needham and TBWA/Chiat/Day, both
owned by Omnicom Group, and Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding, part of True
North Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will begin with a 15-second teaser commercial to
run during the National Football Conference championship game, then
continue with a 30-second spot during Super Bowl XXXIII. A $70
million account, for regional advertising for the nearly 300 stores
operated by Just For Feet, remains at Rogers Advertising in
Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Bartle Bogle Hires Team for New York
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The new New York office of the British agency Bartle
Bogle Hegarty &UR;  &LR;  has hired its first creative team: Stephanie
Crippen, a copywriter, and Kilpatrick Anderson, an art director.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Crippen, 33, had held a similar post at the New York office
of Fallon McElligott, and Anderson, 30, had held a similar position
at Cliff Freeman &AMP; Partners in New York, part of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
PLC. Both report to Ty Montague, creative director of Bartle
Bogle's U.S. operations.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonesta International Hotels Corp., Boston, to Irma S. Mann
Strategic Marketing Inc., Boston, to handle advertising for its
Sonesta International Hotels, Resorts and Nile Cruises unit, which
had been handled in-house. Billings were estimated at $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Crystal Farms, Minneapolis, a division of Michael Foods Inc.,
to Clarity Coverdale Fury, Minneapolis, to handle advertising for
the marketer and distributor of products including cheese, butter
and bagels, which had been handled by Carmichael Lynch,
Minneapolis, part of the Interpublic Group of Cos. Billings were
estimated at $1.5 million. Clarity Coverdale was recently named
agency of record for the Michael Foods food-service division.
</P>
<P>
   People
</P>
<P>
   _ Meg Kannin &UR;  &LR; and &UR;  &LR; Jon Wyville were named co-creative directors
at Arian, Lowe &AMP; Travis, Chicago, succeeding Mike Fornwald, who
left to become a commercial director. Ms. Kannin had been senior
copywriter and associate creative director at Arian, Lowe; Wyville
had been associate creative director at Pagano Schenck &AMP; Kay,
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   _ Valerie Muller was named senior vice president and media
director at Pedone &AMP; Partners, New York, succeeding Sheila Band,
who left. Ms. Muller had been an independent media consultant and
before that was executive vice president and director for media
operations at DeWitt Media Inc., New York.
</P>
<P>
   _ Owen Dougherty was named to the new position of senior vice
president and corporate affairs director at Grey Advertising, New
York, assuming some responsibilities from Toni Lee, vice president
for public relations, who left to become president at TL
Communications, Wilton, Conn. Dougherty had been senior vice
president and corporate communications director at BBDO Worldwide,
New York, part of Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan A. Sneed was named to the new position of senior vice
president for corporate communications worldwide at TBWA Worldwide,
New York, part of Omnicom Group. She had been executive vice
president for corporate communications at Wells BDDP, New York,
which closed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul Taaffe, president and chief executive of Hill &AMP; Knowlton
Europe, Middle East and Africa, London, was named to the additional
new position of president at Hill &AMP; Knowlton Inc., part of WPP
Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rick Schreuder, vice president at Wunderman Cato Johnson,
Chicago, part of Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc., was named to the new
position of managing director for the office, which is becoming the
Midwest office of Brand Dialogue, the Y.&AMP; R. Inc. interactive unit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Perlis was named president of Ziff-Davis Publishing,
New York, a unit of Softbank Corp., succeeding Claude Sheer, who
was named to the new position of chief Internet strategist. Perlis
had most recently been president and chief operating officer at
TVSM Publishing Inc., New York, which is now owned by News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leslie Alphen Picard, advertising director at Vanity Fair
magazine, New York, part of the Conde Nast Publications unit of
Advance Publications, was promoted to the new position of corporate
advertising director at Conde Nast.
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter T. Blank was named to the new position of vice president
for creative services at iXL Inc., New York, a unit of iXL Holdings
Inc. He had been senior counselor and creative director for new
media at Osgood, O'Donnell &AMP; Walsh, New York.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mary King &UR;  &LR; was named creative manager at Messner Vetere Berger
McNamee Schmetterer Euro RSCG, New York, part of Havas Advertising,
succeeding Kyle Daley, who left to join Kendall Tarrant Worldwide,
New York, as managing partner. Ms. King had held a similar post at
Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alison Adler Matz was named to the new position of associate
publisher at US magazine, New York, a unit of Wenner Media Inc. She
had been advertising director for Country Home, Country Gardens and
Country Home special interest publications, New York, part of
Meredith Corp. &QL;
</P>
