<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REVIEW: Noisy `Enemy' bleeps, twitches through thin plot
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Enemy of the State.'' 1 star. Starring: Will
Smith, Gene Hackman, Jon Voight. Director: Tony Scott.
Screenwriter: David Marconi. MPAA rating: R for violence, language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enemy of the State'' bleeps and chirps, tweeps and twitches in
a cacophony of high-tech hubbub. It's filled with scenes of techie
dweebs wearing headsets, their gripped faces bathed in the sallow
glow of computer monitors. They talk in clipped, military phrases
as their fingers perform furious tap-dances on the plastic keys,
sounding like so much popcorn popping.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is noisy, noisome and numbing.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by baron of bombast Tony Scott (``Top Gun,'' ``The
Fan''), ``Enemy of the State'' is a puny bore made to look large
under the magnifying glass of high production values, an
over-two-hour running time and dense pileups of techie
gobbledygook. The only thing that's large, however, is the movie's
soaring tedium.
</P>
<P>
   The story, about an innocent everyman blackmailed by a powerful
baddy, is as thin as pantyhose. It probes the scary proposition of
government surveillance technology pervading our lives, down to
tracing our every move behind closed doors. It presents themes that
were cool in, oh, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, screenwriter David Marconi and uber-action producer Jerry
Bruckheimer get all fussy on us, though, and turn the smooth,
groomed concept into a tousled, impenetrable rat's nest of kinetic
. . . stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Things happen fast and blurry, and jargon is tossed like
confetti. Star Will Smith runs a lot. All the while, the soundtrack
swoops with faux patriotic anthems, played presumedly on an antique
Casio keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Arthritic cliche(accent)s abound. Computer lettering flickers
across the screen to announce establishing shots, including neat-o
military time. (``Reynolds' Residence 2236 Hours.'') For the
climax, Scott steals the bullet-showered climax from his own ``True
Romance.'' Shameless.
</P>
<P>
   The finest moment in ``Enemy of the State'' comes when Smith
catches on fire. But he's put out with disappointing haste and our
delight with it.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Gene Hackman is in the movie, too. The cinematography is
kinda pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
