<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. could use history lesson to remind them of oil crisis
 &HT;    By Ana Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In these days when we're drowning in cheap oil, it's startling
to think that 25 years ago we were being told we would be out of
the stuff by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Arab oil embargo?
</P>
<P>
   Those were the times of odd/even days when the numbers on your
license plate determined whether or not you got a fill-up, or
whatever gasoline was available.
</P>
<P>
   People were hesitant to travel for fear they would find no fuel
for a return trip. And no one paid attention to the pleas to not
top off our tanks.
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange and new sight to see service stations with
``closed'' and ``out of gas'' signs posted. Strange and
frightening.
</P>
<P>
   When you did see a station open, you stopped regardless of what
your fuel gauge said because you didn't know when your next chance
would come. You stopped if you could afford it, that is.
</P>
<P>
   David Fuller, an attorney for R Lacy, a family-owned oil
exploration company, said he was a ``poor, struggling law student
living in a $70 a month apartment'' near Baylor University in 1973.
Finances and the oil shortage caused him and his friends to choose
activities within walking distance of campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was worse in other parts of the country,'' he said,
recalling news accounts of violence in the long gas lines,
especially on the East and West coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a couple of slumps and one war later, the United States has
slid into an even greater dependence on foreign oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been lulled into a false sense of security that it will
always be that way,'' he said, referring to plentiful, and cheap,
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   And we are much more vulnerable than we were 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Exploration is almost exclusively off U.S. shores and in foreign
countries. Oil was what the Gulf War was about and the other areas
on which we depend for oil are not exactly bastions of political
stability: Russia, South America, Mexico, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller, who returned to his hometown of Longview, Texas, 10
years ago, said he really hopes that oil-supplied energy will
always be plentiful, but that is by no means a certainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do forget what it was like,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of comical to think about it now. The government
actually thought we were truly running out of oil. Now, 25 years
later, the world is literally awash in oil. ... Go back and look at
what the Department of Energy was saying in 1973. Reports published
by credible people said we would be out of oil by the year 2000,
(others said) we would be using it for only 10 percent of our
energy needs. But no one predicted that we would be as heavily
dependent as we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there are some folks who don't have to learn a lesson more
than once.
</P>
<P>
   My dad, who operated a gas station for some 40 years, supplied
me with a 1959 Buick when I turned 16 in 1972. All my friends and
their friends could fit in that car.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime shortly after 1973, I was driving a Volkswagen Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, P.O. Box 1792, Longview TX 75606.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: awalker(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
