<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY-DEATH (Skellytown, Texas) _ Three years after the death
of a woman in the Texas Panhandle, the sheriff who investigated the
case says he still has no answers about how the woman died. Her
widower _ who admits they had a fight after swapping sexual
partners _ insists it's a case of suicide. But Sheriff Loren Brand
sees scant evidence that she took her own life. By ROY BRAGG. (For
release Sunday, Nov. 22)
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY-DEATH-SIDE (Skellytown, Texas) _ Danny Howell was
distraught at learning of his wife's death as he sat in a sheriff's
office. Later, with family members around, he plunged a knife into
his stomach. He survived, and so do questions about Cynthia
Howell's death. By ROY BRAGG. (For release Sunday, Nov. 22)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DIAZ-PROFILE (Toronto) _ There's something about Cameron
Diaz, the 26-year-old actress who shot to fame with the summer hit
``There's Something About Mary.'' In her new movie, Diaz does some
``Very Bad Things.'' By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-FELICIANO-PROFILE (Houston) _ Three decades, six Grammys
and dozens of platinum albums after he began his music career, Jose
Feliciano, who was born blind, is still going strong. His latest
album, ``Senor Bolero,'' is a smoldering collection of romantic
tunes that harkens back to the singer's humble beginnings recording
boleros in South America. By JOEY GUERRA.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-POLLOCK (New York) _ In 1949, Life magazine published a
story provocatively titled, ``Jackson Pollock: Is he the greatest
living painter in the United States?'' ``Jackson Pollock,'' at the
Museum of Modern Art through Feb. 2, updates that question,
implicitly asking whether Pollock (1912-1956) is the greatest
American painter of the century. By DAVID BONETTI.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMDEX (Las Vegas, Nev.) _ Five hundred and ten football fields
of floor space showcasing thousands of computer products. That's
what confronted visitors this week in Las Vegas at the Fall Comdex
98 trade show. It was the consumer equipment that was making
headlines, especially the flat-panel displays and hand-held
computers that the major vendors believe will produce the next
surge in sales. Here are some of the eye-catchers for the home
computer user. By MATT BEER.
</P>
