<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPP SHOPS FOR AN AGENT  
 SCANDALOUS ENDOWMENT  
 MODEL BEHAVIOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH JOYCE WADLER AND MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Linda Tripp, who surreptitiously punched the record button when
Monica Lewinsky poured out her heart on the phone, is looking for
an agent. No, not Lucianne Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to Ms. Tripp who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said that she and Ms. Goldberg never had a formal
arrangement for Ms. Goldberg, a Manhattan literary agent, to
represent her. This person said that Ms. Tripp and Ms. Goldberg
remained friends but had ``agreed'' that Ms. Goldberg's appearance
before a grand jury in Maryland last week made it impossible for
them to have a ``formal relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury is considering whether Ms. Tripp, who lives in
Howard County, Md., broke the Maryland wiretapping law by taping
about 22 hours of conversations without Ms. Lewinsky's knowledge.
Ms. Goldberg said after she testified last week that she was wrong
when she told Ms. Tripp it would be legal to make the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The person close to Ms. Tripp said that Ms. Tripp had been
dining with media types in Washington, including Larry King, the
CNN talk-show host. ``She certainly would be well within her rights
to write a book,'' the person said. The Pentagon's refusal to let
Ms. Tripp return to her job there and the possibility that she
might be dismissed ``makes it particularly important for her now to
explore her economic options,'' the person said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Goldberg, she, too, said that she had never
represented Ms. Tripp. ``I don't know why,'' she said Wednesday,
``but it's taken me a year to get people to realize I'm not Linda
Tripp's agent and I never was.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bit Too Jumbo
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The U.N. Sculpture Garden now has a full-size bronze
elephant, a gift from Kenya, Namibia and Nepal. And it caused a
stir even before its unveiling Wednesday at a ceremony attended by
Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   It was too well-endowed for some.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Sunday, I received a call from the ambassador from Nepal,
who said: `The penis is enormous. We brought in an expert to look.
There has to be a surgical operation,''' said Hans Janitschek,
chairman of a nonprofit group that had raised money for the
project. ``Where this expert came from I do not know.''
</P>
<P>
   Narendra Bikram Shah, the permanent representative from Nepal,
said Wednesday that he had no problem with the sculpture. But such
was the concern at the United Nations that a meeting was held in
the office of Undersecretary- General Alvaro Desoto. The solution?
To plant some bushes that block the view.
</P>
<P>
   Runway Irregulars
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So they were not really supermodels. But on Tuesday
evening, half a dozen women looked like runway regulars in the
Fifth Avenue showroom of Asprey &AMP; Garrard, jewelers for the English
royals.
</P>
<P>
   The models, women in their 30s who belong to the director's
council of the Museum of the City of New York or the store's
``tastemaking'' advisory board, included Whitney Fairchild, Tara
Rockefeller, Rachel Hovnanian, Alexia Pickett and Olexa Farrell.
They got to dress up in beaded evening wear by Tomasz Starzewski.
They had hair and makeup done by John Barrett at Bergdorf Goodman.
And they got to wear baubles from Asprey &AMP; Garrard _ several
million dollars' worth of diamonds, emeralds and gold.
</P>
<P>
   They had to give back the dresses and the jewelry. But that was
after they had paraded in front of 350 guests, who had packed the
store and spilled out onto the sidewalk on 56th Street at Fifth
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a fantasy,'' said Ms. Hovnanian, who was perhaps a
little too attached to the $57,000 diamond pave dropped earrings
she had been wearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look great on you,'' a woman at the party said to her,
and then suggested that maybe Ms. Hovnanian's husband, Ara, a New
Jersey real-estate executive, might buy them for her.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged. The earrings went back to the vault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
