<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MISSILES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO WARN JAPAN ABOUT NORTH KOREAN MISSILE THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ President Clinton will warn Japanese Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi that fresh intelligence shows that North Korea can
launch a second long-range ballistic missile over Japan at any
time, U.S. officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton is discussing the development
with Obuchi during his two-day visit to Tokyo before flying to
Seoul late Friday to discuss the issue with South Korean President
Kim Dae Jung.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the president hopes the warning will
forge greater cooperation among the United States, Japan and South
Korea to deal with North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   A senior official on the White House National Security Council
said U.S. officials ``anticipate that there will be additional
missile launches'' by North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone is going to be surprised that they're
going to have a test and that there will be political reaction to
that,'' said one U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea rang alarm bells across Asia on Aug. 31 when it
conducted a surprise test launch of a three-stage rocket with an
estimated range of 3,300 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The Taepodong II missile, ostensibly carrying a satellite into
orbit, crossed over Japan and broke up over the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials also are concerned that Pyongyang's construction
of a suspicious underground cavern may be a step in nuclear weapons
development and a violation of an agreement to cease such work.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea agreed in 1994 to freeze _ and eventually dismantle
_ its nuclear weapons program in return for international shipments
of heating oil and construction of two nuclear power reactors by a
U.S.-led international consortium.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not mention North Korea during his public remarks
here. However, during a ``town hall'' meeting, the president
recalled the terrorist nerve gas attack in the Tokyo subway system
in 1995 that killed 12 and injured thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Japan faces a threat from chemical or biological weapons in the
hands of terrorists or ``rogue nations,'' Clinton said. ``This is
not an academic issue to you; this is a real issue to you,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Nations must retain the option of combating such potential
threats, as the United States has done with Iraq, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace is always better than war if you can do it consistent
with the long term security and freedom of the people,'' Clinton
said. ``If you can do something to stop it now, we should do it _
even if it requires military action.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke a day after his special envoy on Korea, Ambassador
Charles Kartman, left Pyongyang after failing to gain access to the
suspicious underground construction site.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. intelligence officials say spy satellites show thousands of
North Koreans burrowing into the side of a mountain in what may be
an effort to construct a nuclear weapons' site.
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, spokesman for the National Security Council (NSC),
said NSC staffer Jack Pritchard, who accompanied Kartman into North
Korea, arrived in Tokyo Thursday to brief Clinton's national
security adviser, Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese public remains acutely concerned about developments
on the Korean peninsula. A recent survey conducted before the
missile test found 75.3 percent of those surveyed identifying the
Korean peninsula situation or weapons of mass destruction as their
top concern.
</P>
<P>
   In response to North Korea's missile firing, Japan has taken a
hard line toward North Korea, halting famine relief and delaying
resumption of negotiations for diplomatic relations. Japanese
authorities have kept the nation's armed forces on alert, as well,
and warned that a second test would be ``totally unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the United States and South Korea have kept open
the door to North Korea, continuing the cross-border dialogue and
urging Japan to continue cooperation with international efforts to
substitute alternative sources of power for North Korea's
weapons-oriented nuclear reactor program.
</P>
<P>
   A cruise ship bearing 780 South Korean tourists docked in the
North Korean port of Changjon on Thursday, bringing the first South
Korean tourists to North Korea since the start of the Korean War in
1950.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
