 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2500 - November 19, 1998   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2500 -- Nov. 19, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. A NEW LOOK AT HITLER : INSANE OR JUST EVIL? In the book
``Hitler : Diagnosis of a Destructive Prophet,'' Dr. Fritz Redlich
examines Hitler's medical condition and links it to his political
goals for what he calls ``a study of the life and character of an
individual, as influenced by disease.'' Among his findings :
Hitler's obsession with syphilis and mental degeneration in his
family fueled his anti-Semitism and his determination to ``save''
the German race. By Erica Goode. New York Times Science Times.
1,700 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
TOO MANY BREAKTHROUGHS Novelist Richard Powers writes on the ethics
of cloning organs from human stem cells. New York Times Op-Ed.
1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
SEX ON HOLIDAY : TARGETING SAFETY Sexual risk behaviour among
international travellers has become an important issue because of
the HIV epidemic. Researchers from seven European countries report
the results of a survey to identify factors associated with risky
sexual behaviour. Men's risk behaviour while abroad reflected their
behaviour at home. Women's risk behaviour was shaped by the
background of their sexual partners. Campaigns to promote safer
sexual behaviour must be designed differently for men and for
women. By Ros Osmond. The Lancet News Service. 1,000 words. 4.
INSTEAD OF GIFTS, PLEASE WALK THE DOG The best presents a new
mother could hope for come in the form of hands-on help. Here are
seven suggestions for making a new mother your friend for life. By
Leslie Bulion. From Child magazine. 600 words. 5. THE MAGIC OF
MAGIC Psychologist Robert Baker recommends that ``anyone interested
in magic ... should buy and read the book 'Abracadabra : Secret
Methods Magicians and Others Use To Deceive Their Audience' written
by Nathaniel Schiffman. Schiffman (who is also a professional
magician,) has provided the public with a definitive look at the
art and science of conjuring, as well as a comprehensive overview
of tricks, secrets and illusions in use for literally thousands of
years. Review by Robert A. Baker. From Skeptical Inquirer magazine.
1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   6. IRAQI CRISIS ISN'T OVER BUT BOMBING WOULDN'T HAVE SETTLED IT
It is demeaning to regret that the bomb attack on Iraq was
cancelled, as some seem to do out of frustration and anger at
having to acknowledge the limits of America's power. The purpose of
military destruction cannot just be a show of strength. By Flora
Lewis. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
ISLAM'S WAR WITH ITSELF The ``long war'' between Islam and the west
is a side-show to the much deeper conflict over modernisation
within Muslim societies. Interests of states, ethnic rivalries and
confessional differences between Sunnis and Shiites all play a
part. By Fred Halliday. From Prospect magazine. 2,000 words. (N/A
U.K.)
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
From MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE:
</P>
<P>
   A. DRUG COMBINATION GIVES HEPATITIS C A KNOCKOUT PUNCH A
combination drug therapy may wipe out hepatitis C virus in some
people. 500 words. B. SMOKING IN TEEN YEARS MAY CAUSE GENETIC
DAMAGE TO SPERM Adding to the list of reasons to kick the smoking
habit, researchers have found that smoking may alter genetic
material in sperm. 500 words. C. STUDY LINKS WELL-DONE MEAT
CONSUMPTION AND BREAST CANCER A new study shows that women who
choose to eat thoroughly cooked beef and bacon may be upping their
risk of breast cancer. 500 words. 9. DUMP ME, PLEASE Why will some
men do almost anything to break off a relationship except talk
things over and tell the truth? By Rosanne Rosen. 600 words +
50-word sidebar of common break-up lines. 10. WHEN HARMLESS HERBS
BECOME DEADLY DRUGS Self-administered herbal treatments can lead to
unexpected complications, especially when used in combination with
prescription drugs. By Nancy Beth Jackson. From New York Times
Science Times. 750 words. Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or
33.1.47.42.18.81
