<HEADLINE>
A POOR FAMILY'S THANKSGIVING, ENRICHED BY MOTHER'S GIFT
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``l''
lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By BILL MAXWELL 
 &HT;    (Bill Maxwell, African American, is an editorial writer and
columnist for the St. Petersburg Times in St. Petersburg, Fla. He
can be reached on the Internet at maxwell(at) sptimes.com) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Even as a child, I was the family cynic. And nothing brought out
the Diogenes in me more than Thanksgiving. What, I used to ask,
were we _ our mother and my five siblings _ to be thankful for?
After all, as black people in the South, we did not count for much
in the eyes of white people and even fellow blacks.
 &HT;    Sometimes, I thought that God had abandoned us. Our father ran
off for good when I, the oldest, was 10 years old. We never had
enough money and lived in a two-bedroom, run-down apartment in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla. Weekdays, my mother cleaned hotel rooms; weekends
she picked vegetables.
 &HT;    We rarely had new school clothes, almost everything coming from
`used' shops. We did not own a car. And we never had enough food _
which caused my mother more shame than anything else.
 &HT;    What did we have to be thankful for?
 &HT;    When I was 14, I finally learned that we had much to be thankful
for. I had been living for three years with grandparents in
Crescent City, Fla., because my mother simply could not support all
of us. In Crescent City, I had everything _ delicious food, new
clothes, my own bedroom, a new bicycle, books and all of the Nehi
grape soda I could drink.
 &HT;    In 1959, my mother asked me to return to Fort Lauderdale to
celebrate Thanksgiving with the rest of the family. Always the
traveler, I caught the Greyhound bus the day before Thanksgiving.
 &HT;    The family lived in the same cramped apartment, and when I saw
the grime and smelled the stench of the trash cans behind the
complex, that old feeling of hopelessness and anger returned. I did
not want to be there for Thanksgiving.
 &HT;    What did my mother and the other children have for which they
should be thankful?
 &HT;    I was in the courtyard when my mother got off the bus hugging
several grocery bags. She had worked all day. I ran to her, took
the two largest bags and carried them inside, asking if we were
having turkey and ham. No, she had bought ``two roasting hens.''
But hens are chicken, I said, knowing full well that these two
small birds would not feed seven hungry people.
 &HT;    Seeing my disappointment, my mother reassured me that we also
would have collard greens, yams, green beans, potato salad, corn
bread and sweet potato pie for our Thanksgiving meal. But for
supper that night, we had rice and flour bread that we used to sop
up the juice from neckbones. I noticed that mother did not eat.
Asked why, she said that her stomach was upset.
 &HT;    On Thanksgiving morning, we had flour bread and cane syrup and
powdered milk for breakfast. Again, my mother did not eat. After I
finished washing dishes, I joined my brothers and sisters in the
courtyard while my mother began to prepare our meal.
 &HT;    Occasionally, I would pretend to use the bathroom so that I
could take a peek at the food. I was thinking of my grandparents in
Crescent City and the turkey and ham feast that they would have. I
wanted to be with them.
 &HT;    Once, as I came out of the bathroom, my mother asked me to baste
the hens while she peeled potatoes. Using a large spoon, I dipped
drippings from the bottom of the roasting pan and poured it evenly
over the birds. Before long, I was enjoying myself. Apparently
noticing the change in me, my mother asked me to wash the collards.
I dumped them into a sink of cold water, where I swished them
around. Then I cut them thinly and put them into a pot of boiling
water and smoked neckbones.
 &HT;    Next, I snapped beans and put them into a pot. Mother told me
that I was a good cook. From that point on, I moved from task to
task without being told. It was giving me real pleasure and I felt,
too, that I was making a difference.
 &HT;    After everything was done, I told my mother not to set the table
until I returned from the grocery store near the apartment. With
part of the money my grandmother had given to me, I bought two cans
of cranberry sauce. Mother was surprised and grateful.
 &HT;    Setting the table, I was proud of the brown, juicy hens. Mother
told me that, since I was the man of the house, I could carve the
meat and serve the plates.
 &HT;    Seeing that my mother had not set a plate for herself, I removed
mine from the table. I was catching on: Mother had not eaten supper
and breakfast so that the children would have enough to eat. She
was waiting until they had finished Thanksgiving dinner before she
ate. After we said grace, my brothers and sisters ate with relish,
each taking several slices of cranberry sauce. Each took a big
helping of collards, which I had cooked, and each seemed to enjoy
my stringed beans.
 &HT;    I was surprised that the children left two pieces of hen _ a
breast and a drumstick. My mother offered me the breast because it
was my favorite. I insisted, though, that she eat it because it was
bigger than the drumstick. She did not argue, and we sat down to
the best Thanksgiving dinner I have ever had.
 &HT;    I knew that I was fortunate to have a mother who worked hard and
sacrificed for us. I have appreciated the essence of our most
American holiday ever since.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Bill Maxwell 
<TEXT>
