</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:PIATOTE-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKSGIVING: INDIANS MUST FIGHT FOR THEIR PLACE AT THE TABLE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``a'' general
news and ``l'' lifestyle files.) 
 By BETH HEGE PIATOTE 
 &HT;    (Beth Hege Piatote, Nez Perce/Colville Indian, is a writer
living in Eugene, Ore., where she teaches at the University of
Oregon School of Journalism and Communication.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Ah, Thanksgiving. Time once again for all good Americans to kick
back with the family, have a little turkey, and give thanks for the
NFL, four-day weekends, and Manifest Destiny.
 &HT;    It is also time once again to open the mythical family album and
cast our collective gaze upon our forebears, those who brought us
the First Thanksgiving nearly 400 years ago, with all the Pilgrims
and Indians peacefully seated around the table, engaged in a joyous
and mutually salutary feast.
 &HT;    This portrait of a benign birth of America is engraved in the
minds of citizens at an early age, with the rather unpalatable
images of native genocide, black slavery, large-scale land theft,
and gender oppression against women conveniently airbrushed out.
 &HT;    I am fascinated with the staying power of the Thanksgiving myth.
Every year, primary school children around the nation re-enact the
pageantry of this seminal moment in American history. A myriad of
greeting cards and kitsch ceramic Pilgrim and Indian figurines are
sold and displayed as reminders of that grand event. While the
narratives of much younger American holidays like Labor Day and
Veteran's Day recede in the collective conscience, the imprint of
the Thanksgiving story remains strong.
 &HT;    Though fascinated, I am not mystified by this. It is clear to me
why this narrative stays in place. Like every creation story, it
puts the world in an orderly manner.
 &HT;    In the story of Thanksgiving, the Pilgrims are placed at the
center of God's grace and privilege. It is the Pilgrims who express
gratitude to their God for the bounty placed before them.
Ironically, the Indians _ the native people of the land _ are
marginalized by this story. They are at best the guests of the
Pilgrims, and at worst a part of the bounty itself.
 &HT;    The myth is critical for inscribing the cultural templates that
continue to dictate social roles today. One is either The Chosen or
The Other. Fortunate Pilgrim or tragic Indian. Meritorious
candidate or affirmative action hire. Citizen or alien. Despite our
multicultural society, there is no room for any other roles; this
was established in the beginning.
 &HT;    Beyond that, the Thanksgiving fable serves as a necessary salve
when confronted with the actual bloodiness of the founding of
America. It is important for Americans to believe that despite all
the gore, there was a moment in history when the Pilgrims
(oppressed in their own right by religious intolerance in Europe)
sat down in peaceful co-existence with the natives (perhaps naive
in their generosity) and gave thanks together.
 &HT;    From a native perspective, it seems that if that sublime moment
ever existed, it has been downhill for us ever since. And I say
that not only for Native Americans who today suffer the highest
rates of poverty and massive underrepresentation in positions of
power, but for all those who have been categorized as ``Other'' in
America's grand scheme.
 &HT;    Still, there are subversive ways to read this story. While for
much of mainstream America, the Thanksgiving myth re-inscribes a
position of power, for others of us it serves as a reminder: we
cannot stop fighting for our place at the table.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Beth Hege Piatote 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
