<SLUG> BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:WU-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERELY TO BE THANKFUL IS NOT ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``a'' general
news and ``l'' lifestyle files.) 
 By FRANK WU 
 &HT;    (Frank Wu, Chinese American, is a columnist for Asian Week and
associate professor of law and supervising attorney at Howard
University.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Like everyone of my generation or older, I celebrated
Thanksgiving in the classrooms of the public school. We made
costumes out of construction paper, using crayons out of a bucket
of broken stubs to decorate, paste out of huge cannisters to hold
the pieces together. We playacted a meeting between the Pilgrims
and the Indians. We called the corn ``maize'' and we carved the
pumpkins into jack-o-lanterns.
 &HT;    Children could feel that most adults, too, shared the
excitement. The seasons changed, the clocks were turned back, and
the leaves started to fall. The Salvation Army Santa Clauses began
to ring their bells outside stores. The Christmas shows commenced
their appearance on television.
 &HT;    Twenty-five years later, I sense that the quaint innocence of
that scene already contained messages about multi-culturalism. But
they weren't quite understood.
 &HT;    I grew up in the Detroit suburbs, shortly after the riots that
propelled ``white flight'' progressively farther into land where
maize and pumpkins had actually been grown.
 &HT;    At my elementary school, there was not a single African American
person: no students, no teachers, and no administrators. Until my
younger brothers turned up, I was about the only person of color.
There were no Native Americans. There were no Hispanics. There were
only a few Catholics and no Jews.
 &HT;    Perhaps my family was typical of immigrants. We tried to copy
what our neighbors did.
 &HT;    We sought to have the same public displays around the holiday
season: if they strung up twinkling lights next door, we'd visit
the hardware store and then stand outside our home struggling to
connect the extension cords together, too. But somehow, the very
public nature of the good cheer made it all the stranger and more
difficult to understand.
 &HT;    Thanksgiving was especially odd, because it is at once less
religious but more American than Christmas. It is invested with
symbolism about what it means to be a citizen.
 &HT;    Like Columbus Day, Thanksgiving has become controversial because
it is a ritual about the New World becoming European and
`civilized.' We re-enact a script that emphasizes two groups coming
into contact as equals, but we know from the subsequent events that
the encounter worked out well for the Pilgrims only.
 &HT;    So I wonder, when I was dressed up for Thanksgiving _ I forget
which role _ whether anyone noticed the lone pair of Oriental eyes
among the white faces. Or if today, as the thousands of
schoolchildren _ whose parents brought them from all over Asia _
become Pilgrims, anyone wonders how they are there.
 &HT;    Now, I make my living as a teacher, lawyer, and writer pointing
out these uncomfortable facts. And though I mean to change the
spirit of Thanksgiving, it is not my intention to ruin it.
 &HT;    It is important for all of us who have the opportunity to enjoy
turkey and cranberry sauce to reflect on the amenities of life that
we take for granted. We have much to be thankful for. That we are
Americans. That we possess civil rights. That we may participate in
shaping our future.
 &HT;    To be thankful requires that we be aware of these advantages and
their implications. That others are not Americans. That others lack
civil rights. That they might not participate in shaping their
future.
 &HT;    So, merely to be thankful is not enough.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Frank Wu 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) &QL;
</P>
