<HEADER>
A8904 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:LEST     11-19 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:LESTER-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW OLD FRIENDS AND A PRAYER THAT ACKNOWLEDGES OUR FULL HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``a'' general
news and ``l'' lifestyle files.) 
 By JOAN STEINAU LESTER 
 &HT;    (Dr. Joan Steinau Lester is a partner in The Equity Consulting
Group in Berkeley, Calif., and author of the book, ``Taking Charge:
Every Woman's Action Guide to Personal, Political and Profession
Success.'') 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    When I was a child in the 1940s and '50s, Thanksgiving signified
Pilgrims and feathers. At school we cut out Pilgrim hats and
re-enacted the First Thanksgiving Dinner. The Pilgrims were paper
heroes; the Indians were copper-toned, featherered, and happy
helpers.
 &HT;    When I grew up, in the 1960s, I began to understand the
impossibility of Europeans ``discovering'' an already inhabited
land. As Dick Gregory famously quipped, ``Hey man, I just
discovered this Cadillac sitting by the curb.''
 &HT;    I began to learn more about just who had owned the Cadillac. I
discovered that helpful Squanto himself was captured by an English
sea captain and sold into slavery in Spain, where he lived for
years before working his way back to his native land, only to
discover that all the members of his tribe, the Patuxet, were wiped
out by epidemics. This, just before the First Thanksgiving.
 &HT;    And I learned that Lord Jeffrey Amherst, after whom the
illustrious college town in Massachusetts is named, deliberately
gave smallpox-infested blankets and handkerchiefs to Shawnee,
Delaware and Mingo people.
 &HT;    I got it.
 &HT;    Which meant I could no longer commemorate a day that marked the
beginning of the end _ literally _ for Native Americans _ who
shrank from about 10 million people, pre-Columbus, to 250,000 by
the late 19th century.
 &HT;    I spent a decade boycotting Thanksgiving. I wasn't going to
participate in this cover-up, this celebration of genocide.
 &HT;    Then, for several years, I deigned to join my family for the day
_ but insisted on reading angry Indian poetry (``Off my land, white
man!'') before the meal to the properly chagrined assemblage.
 &HT;    By the late '70s, I relented. By this time I was a vegetarian;
my ever-accommodating family began to include quiche at our holiday
feasts. We served dinners to homeless people; we gave away baskets
of food.
 &HT;    During the '80s I waffled. Some years I was on, some years off.
Thanksgiving, that is.
 &HT;    Now, I celebrate the day with family and close friends, eating
the traditional turkey meal, with cranberries and pumpkin pies.
 &HT;    I seem to have come full circle. But it's a circle that includes
more perspectives: the Pilgrims aren't heroes, and they were
fleeing their own persecution; Thanksgiving is still commemorated
as a day of mourning by many Native Americans; and it's not
betrayal to use the day, so appropriate at this time of darkening
sky, to nurture each other. And to reflect.
 &HT;    Building on our Thanksgiving tradition of gathering together,
drawing close into the fertile night, and giving thanks, perhaps we
can take a tip from the Million Man March (or, for that matter, Yom
Kippur) and transform the holiday into a national day of atonement
and reconciliation, as well as a day of gratitude.
 &HT;    We might create our own version of South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission: acknowledge the land-grab, grieve for
those who lost the war, and repent. We could stimulate a public
dialogue, with space to tell the story, in all its details, from
all its perspectives: opening and healing these old wounds.
 &HT;    The United States has a dynamic culture; we often absorb new
content into old forms. Other holidays, like Halloween, have
evolved: Halloween started as a day to honor the dead. And some
rituals are newly created: Kwaanza was initiated by Ron Karenga
just a few decades ago.
 &HT;    Thanksgiving itself has not even had a clear path from that
``first'' one in 1621. That feast was a one-time event, resurrected
briefly in 1676 by the Governing Council of Charlestown, Mass., who
proclaimed June 29 as a day of Thanksgiving to God for destroying
``our Enemies ... the Heathen Natives of this land.''
 &HT;    Then Thanksgiving languished until George Washington proposed a
Thanksgiving day to celebrate the establishment of the new nation.
(Thomas Jefferson nixed it as ``the most ridiculous idea I ever
heard.'')
 &HT;    Finally, President Lincoln revived the custom in 1863, and in
1941 Congress decreed the holiday be celebrated on the fourth
Thursday in November.
 &HT;    And so, this year, at my home, we will celebrate our blessings.
We will have some turkey. (Organic, of course. Free-range and
farm-fed with only the purest ingredients; plus weekly massage and
therapy.)
 &HT;    We will sit, on Thanksgiving Day, amongst a few old friends who
have gathered together for most of a decade. Our dishes will
include raw vegetables for the Vegans among us ... as well as
marshmallow toppings for the sugar lovers. And we'll say a prayer
that acknowledges our full history: its generosity to some, its
iniquities to others. We'll conclude with thanks that we, the
living, are here today, surrounded by people we love, enjoying the
bounty of a plentiful harvest. And we'll recommit to doing our part
to create such conditions for all.
 &HT;    That's Thanksgiving in the '90s, at my house.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Joan Steinau Lester 
<TEXT>
