<HEADER>
A8906 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:BASU     11-19 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:BASU-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFYING THANKSGIVING
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``a'' general
news and ``l'' lifestyle files.) 
 By REKHA BASU 
 &HT;    (Rekha Basu, a Moslem from India, is a journalist for the Des
Moines Register in Des Moines, Iowa.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The first Thanksgiving after I was married, I decided to show my
new mother-in-law that the foreigner her son had wed could cook a
Thanksgiving meal as memorable as any she'd had in the Bronx, N.Y.
 &HT;    No ordinary turkey for this meal, I decided. Only lobster would
do.
 &HT;    Of course, only a foreigner could make such a miscalculation. My
mother-in-law, who had already put up with her only child
vacationing in India, marrying a bride who wore a red sari rather
than a white gown and one who regularly mispronounced cavatelli,
responded as graciously as she could to the news. I'm sure it was
not lost on her, however, that her new daughter-in-law thought
nothing of dispensing with centuries-old tradition on the most
original of American holidays.
 &HT;    The meal was a disaster.
 &HT;    I bought the lobsters live the day before, and stored them in
the bathtub, where, by evening, they were dead. Lobsters have to be
alive before you cook them, and they don't survive in water that is
not aerated. I learned that a little too late.
 &HT;    There was a message in this, I am certain: Tradition does not
let you go quite so easily. Try as you might to defy it, it finds
its way back into your life.
 &HT;    In retrospect, I've realized there was also a message in my
trying to bend the rules: I was subconsciously setting myself
apart.
 &HT;    As an Indian child growing up in America, tradition around
holidays was a complicated thing. There were few traditions that
really belonged to us. We'd hardly lived as a family in India, and
my parents had been away from home long enough that they'd long
since given up celebrating Indian holidays. Complicating everything
was the fact that most Indian holidays are religious anyway, and
they didn't share the same religion.
 &HT;    But I loved all holidays _ anything, in fact, that involved good
food and gift-giving. The part of me that wanted to be just like
everyone else longed to celebrate Thanksgiving, Christmas and
Easter as much as my American friends.
 &HT;    We went through the rituals at friends' homes, grateful to be
included, but not really feeling we had the right to celebrate them
on our own. By the time I was in high school, however, Thanksgiving
had become our family's holiday. The people whose homes we used to
go to now came to ours instead. I think they found some special
meaning in celebrating that quintessential of American holidays in
a non-American home. And we took some special pleasure in being
able to host it.
 &HT;    If I had to isolate a single point at which my whole family went
from being outsiders to really feeling like we belonged, it was
around these Thanksgiving dinners. Somewhere along the line, we
stopped just going through the motions and the celebration became
real.
 &HT;    I don't mean we were suddenly identifying with the Pilgrims as
they landed at Plymouth rock. But we felt we had permission to
celebrate, among friends and family, even if it wasn't our history.
 &HT;    We'd all converge at our country home in Woodstock, N.Y. for the
weekend. My father would cook an enormous turkey and a plethora of
gourmet side dishes. There'd be pate, watercress and endive salad,
corn pudding, herring, champagne and, of course, all the usual fare
of Thanksgiving dinner. He would even reach beyond Thanksgiving
tradition to add his own special touches, like notes written to
each member of the party and tucked under our dinner plates saying
why he was thankful for each of us.
 &HT;    In the early years of married life, with an Italian-American
husband and American children, I thumbed my nose at convention and
fixed the dinners my own way. If it wasn't lobster, it would be
goose. But as my children grow, they've become the sticklers for
tradition, bringing me back on track to how it's supposed to be
done _ bringing me back to turkey.
 &HT;    Not that tradition can't be expanded upon. I still throw in an
Indian dish here, an Italian one there. And so, I've made my peace
with Thanksgiving dinner.
 &HT;    But now a new problem has arisen. My 12-year-old son has become
a vegetarian. Ironically I, the Indian, am not one. The Vegetarian
Times magazines are piling up, with helpful suggestions on how to
do Thanksgiving dinner without meat.
 &HT;    So, this year it's my son wanting me to break the rules.
 &HT;    We've come full cycle, it seems.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Rekha Basu 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
