<HEADER>
A8908 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:EVAN     11-19 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:EVANS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY BLACKS CELEBRATE THANKSGIVING WITH AMERICAN INDIAN DAY
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``a'' general
news and ``l'' lifestyle files.) 
 By JOYCE EVANS 
 &HT;    (Joyce Evans-Campbell, African American, is a columnist for the
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    When we speak of slavery, and of the slaves who escaped it, we
often talk about the Underground Railroad.
 &HT;    We forget to mention the runaway slaves taking paths to Native
American villages where black men and women found friendship and
refuge. Yet this often happened in the early days of our country,
and the offspring of black-and-Indian marriages shaped the early
days of fur trade and the alliances formed to fight the military in
frontier fights.
 &HT;    This Thanksgiving and on American Indian Day, Nov. 27,
African-Americans should pay homage to their Native American
heritage.
 &HT;    I will.
 &HT;    From memory, I can still see that giant, black and white
portrait of the woman with the waist-length black hair and the
smooth caramel complexion.
 &HT;    ``That was my grandmama and your great-grandmama. She was
Indian,'' my mother told me.
 &HT;    I later learned that my mother's ancestors were Cherokee from
North Carolina. ``She was the only person who ever loved me,'' Mom
says of her grandmother.
 &HT;    Her grandmother Sarah, who usually kept her hair pulled back in
a bun, mother said, married a freed black man named Dave Lane and
had five daughters. One of them, my mother's mom, died at age 16 _
six months after my mother was born.
 &HT;    Two years ago, when my daughter KJ did a family genealogy report
for school, she discovered sparse information about the early North
Carolina settlers.
 &HT;    Since Alex Haley's ``Roots,'' more and more of us are searching
for who we really are. But that search was mostly for African roots
for black Americans. William Loren Katz's book, ``Black Indians: A
Hidden Heritage'' explains why:
 &HT;    ``When black Americans have pursued their genealogy, they have
focused on their African roots and sought a meaningful black
heritage. Children of the black awareness of the 1960s have rarely
cared to mention an Indian ancestry because this might be seen as a
denial of their African origins and the value of blackness. All
this is part of the racial nightmare we have inherited.''
 &HT;    If the racial nightmare ever ends, it has to start with each of
us. Those of us who're looking into our Native American heritage
are not trying to avoid being called African-Americans.
 &HT;    Discovering who we are is as important to us as it was to the
family who recently got DNA test confirmation that Thomas Jefferson
fathered a child by his longtime slave, Sally Hemings.
 &HT;    But the records of these marriages between blacks and Native
Americans don't always disclose information about the Native
American ethnicity.
 &HT;    Alice Kehoe, the Marquette University professor who specializes
in Native American issues, said, ``They had to keep quiet about
what they were because the government wanted the Native Americans
to go to the reservation.''
 &HT;    Kehoe, who's written a textbook, ``North American Indians'' with
a chapter on black Indians, said the Native Americans mixed with
people of color after the Indians were segregated from whites. The
story isn't all positive, she said. The complications were that the
Cherokees bought black slaves. Some of them were well-to-do
plantation owners, but then there were other Cherokees who provided
refuge for runaways.
 &HT;    Perhaps, someday we will speak of these people who provided
refuge for runaways. Someday, when we learn all of our history.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Joyce Evans 
<TEXT>
