<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAIN TO THANKSGIVINGS PAST
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``a'' general
news and ``l'' lifestyle files.) 
 By KIRSTEN CHAPMAN 
 &HT;    (Kirsten Chapman writes a weekly column for the Columbus
Dispatch in Columbus, Ohio, and is the author of three books, one
just published.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Each Thanksgiving I see myself aboard a train, heading home from
college.
 &HT;    Leaning my forehead against the window, I watch Illinois fields
rush to meet a Wisconsin prairie. Forgotten pumpkins, round as a
rising moon, colorfully dot the gray ground _ while the slate sky
shakes loose a flurry of snowflakes. A freshman, I feel light-years
older than I did when I left for school; surely my parents will
notice the difference. As the train pulls into the depot, I spot
them standing on the platform.
 &HT;    I remember other earlier years and Thanksgivings, riding in the
back seat of the car on the way to our grandparents' house in
another city.
 &HT;    Are we there yet? How much longer? As the car pulls into the
drive, our cousins rush out to meet us.
 &HT;    Or I recall my children's youth: When I pack boots, the weather
turns springlike. When I forget, blizzards stall cars and send
others spinning into ditches. Arriving close to midnight on the eve
of Thanksgiving, we carry sleeping children into the welcoming
house where their grandparents are still up.
 &HT;    We take a journey each Thanksgiving, not only to where a table
waits for us, but to Thanksgivings past. Retracing our steps, we
travel an inner road, discovering who we once were, reaching who we
are.
 &HT;    When Mother was little, she and her family would ride into town
to share Thanksgiving with Aunt Claudine. She wanted to join the
camaraderie at the festive table, but her aunt relegated the
children to a table in another room. I still hear disappointment in
Mother's voice as she retells the story each year. (Years later,
she would give up her dining-room seat to one of her grandchildren
if there was not enough room round the family table.)
 &HT;    My mother-in-law, in her younger days and when she was home from
college, used to help her father pick watercress in a cold stream
for Thanksgiving Day's feast. What was gathered more than six
decades ago is remembered at our table today.
 &HT;    This year, our daughter will miss our family Thanksgiving to
visit her friend and his family in Boston.
 &HT;    My father and father-in-law are now forever absent. And so is my
sister.
 &HT;    As youngsters, she and I would color while sprawled on the
living room floor at our grandparent's house _ where even then,
thanks to radio, football permeated the air almost as much as the
aroma of roasting turkey.
 &HT;    With the quilt of family covering us, we slept on our way home.
Back then, we didn't worry about fitting in; we just did _ always
with a place at the table.
 &HT;    A few years later, when I tried squeezing back into my old youth
chair in the attic, I became aware of how much I had changed.
 &HT;    When I arrived home as a college freshman, I sensed another new
self, yet I easily slipped back into ``a highchair'' of old habits,
allowing clothes to spill over my bedroom chair, disappearing when
dirty dishes piled up in the sink.
 &HT;    Imperfection, however, isn't what we usually recall when past
Thanksgivings roll down the track for an annual review: It's the
perfection of faded memory _ like the image I have of my parents
sending me back to college after Thanksgiving vacation.
 &HT;    Waiting on the platform, the three of us huddled close against
the cold. How I wished the train wouldn't arrive, just as I wished
Sunday afternoon hadn't.
 &HT;    ``If we never said goodbye, we couldn't say hello,'' said
Mother, trying to cheer me.
 &HT;    ``Christmas will be here before you know it,'' Dad said.
 &HT;    The train whistled and thundered near. After I hugged my
parents, Dad pressed a $10 bill into my hand.
 &HT;    ``Here's a little something,'' he said, ``just in case.''
 &HT;    Later, from the window, I watched my parents grow smaller as the
train pulled me faster and faster into my future.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Kirsten Chapman 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
