<HEADER>
A8914 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:GIAG     11-19 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSION SCHOOLS KEPT CHILDREN AWAY FROM FAMILY THANKSGIVING
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``a'' general
news and ``l'' lifestyle files.) 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is publisher and editor-in-chief of
Indian Country Today. His Indian name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I believe Thanksgiving Day is a holiday one grows into as a
child. It is a holiday when children went ``over the river and
through the woods'' to grandmother's house.
 &HT;    Thanksgiving is a day when old family traditions are renewed and
sumptuous meals of turkey, ham and cranberries are served; where
pumpkin pies are topped with whipped cream.
 &HT;    It is a day one learns to appreciate as a child and then its
continuation as an adult becomes a part of family tradition.
 &HT;    Thousands of Indian children never had the opportunity to grow
into this holiday as a family event. Many of us spent our
Thanksgiving Days at Bureau-of-Indian-Affairs or Indian-mission
boarding schools. We did not have our families surrounding us on
this holiday.
 &HT;    In the late 1800s, the federal government and the many churches
in America collaborated to build boarding schools and Indian
missions on, near or far away from the Indian reservations.
Children were placed in these schools from about age 6 and were
there nine months out of the year.
 &HT;    Thanksgiving Day meant something different to these boarders. To
me it meant I got to sleep until 7:00 a.m. instead of being rousted
out of my bunk at 6:00 a.m. It meant that instead of getting our
usual fare of yellow mush, we were served crisp, tasty corn flakes
for breakfast.
 &HT;    On all other days, except Sunday, we were awakened at 6:00 a.m.
by a prefect _ usually a white man studying for the priesthood _
with a large, hand-held bell. He would walk up and down the aisles
of the dormitory clanging the bell. If you turned over and pulled
the pillow over your head, he would stand at your bed and clang the
bell until you jumped out.
 &HT;    Once out of bed, we rushed to the long row of wash basins filled
with ice-cold water. We washed our faces, brushed our teeth _
shivering in the morning cold _ and got dressed for the
early-morning mass we attended every morning of the week.
 &HT;    After church we marched to the dining hall, took our places in
company ranks at the breakfast tables and said grace while keeping
a baleful eye on the stack of bread in the center of the table.
Before the ``Amen'' faded away, we dived at the bread like starving
prisoners and, if we were lucky, came away with a slice or two.
Some of the older boys chose locations around the furnace in the
center of the dining hall, placed their slices of bread on top, and
waited for it to toast. Each boy was allotted one cube of salty
butter. We often used this butter as bargaining chips. ``Give you
my butter for a whole week for some of that chokecherry jam.''
 &HT;    Some of the smaller and weaker kids never tasted butter the
entire school year. Of course, we could always count on our daily
bowl of yellow mush. We mission boys often saw hand-painted signs
outside different gymnasiums when we traveled to other schools to
play basketball. They read, ``Crush the Mush.''
 &HT;    I suppose, thinking back on it, I never really placed a
historical context in my heart for Thanksgiving. I, as all of the
other boys and girls at the boarding schools, sat in the classroom
and heard the story of the first Thanksgiving; about how the
Pilgrims and the Indians celebrated a feast to mark the first year
in this land the visitors called the New World.
 &HT;    Many years ago I heard a Caddo Indian woman speak to an audience
about her daughter coming home in tears the day before
Thanksgiving. She said, ``Mom, these kids dressed up like Indians.
They put cardboard feathers in their hair and then they danced
around and made war whoops. Why are they making fun of us?''
 &HT;    It wasn't until I left the Indian mission and got out into the
real world that I researched the conclusion to the Thanksgiving
story. I read about the mistreatment and the eventual annihilation
of the Indians who brought the first Thanksgiving to the Pilgrims.
I read about the religious intolerance practiced by the Pilgrims
and of a village of more than 300, peaceful, Christian Indians
slaughtered _ to a man _ by white Christians angry over the death
of one of their own at the hands of one lone Indian.
 &HT;    Thinking back to my childhood, I suppose my most cherished
memory of Thanksgiving is that it was one of the few days in the
year at the boarding school when we were served a delicious meal.
Instead of our usual fare of boiled meat and boiled potatoes, we
had turkey with all of the trimmings, cranberries, pumpkin pie. We
also had a chance to take a day off from studies, sleep an extra
hour and see an extra movie that day.
 &HT;    If we had not been forcibly separated from our parents and
grandparents, we might have learned to love Thanksgiving as a day
when the family gathers to give thanks for all of the good things
in life.
 &HT;    It would have been nice to go ``over the river and through the
woods'' to grandmother's house.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Tim Giago 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
