<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:MARX-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY FIRST PARENTLESS THANKSGIVING
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``a'' general
news and ``l'' lifestyle files.) 
 By LINDA MARX 
 &HT;    (Linda Marx is a Florida-based columnist and talk-radio
commentator.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In recent years I have hosted Thanksgiving in my home for my
husband, father, brother and his wife, close friends from
childhood, and a newer friend whose children have become as close
as family. This ritual for the holiday began after my mother died.
 &HT;    But now, again, it has changed _ as Dad has gone, too. And so,
this year, Thanksgiving won't be the same. A former sports
commentator, his colorful quips on the football games, and his
entertaining personality capped with old fashioned values was
always a hoot and a highlight.
 &HT;    But none of the years since Mother's passing have resembled the
wonderful times we had as children when she hosted several dozen in
our home for the late afternoon feast.
 &HT;    She prepared roast turkey with mushroom gravy, wild rice
stuffing, mashed potatoes, candied yams, sauerkraut, green beans
with red bell peppers and almonds, cranberry sauce with dried
cherries and cloves, potato bread, pumpkin muffins, pumpkin
cheesecake, carrot cake, pecan pie, deep-dish caramel apple pie and
blueberry pie with vanilla ice cream.
 &HT;    I intend to keep the family tradition as strong as my mother
instituted, and my father perpetuated. As time consoles my sadness,
the love of family and good friends adds to the warm glow of Mom's
silver candelabra.
 &HT;    Even though my cooking would make Julia Child weep, I am
utilizing lessons learned from both parents: mother encouraged me
to organize; dad understood the merits of great catering. Each
taught me that Thanksgiving is the time to give thanks for the good
in our lives, to nourish both our bodies and souls, and to help
others who are less fortunate.
 &HT;    I was married on Thanksgiving Day in 1984. For the following six
years my parents helped us entertain 150 for the traditional meal.
What started out as a celebration of Thanksgiving and our wedding
anniversary, eventually turned into the party of the season. Living
in south Florida, orphans, widows, bachelors, divorcees, friends
and entire families counted on us to provide their Thanksgiving
spread. It was a great deal of work and probably grew too large.
But we had lots of fun with my parents sharing these
responsibilities.
 &HT;    It continued each Thanksgiving until mother was gone. I couldn't
host such an ambitious project without her talents, nurturing and
organizational skills. And dad was relieved when we returned to a
smaller group, a more manageable event, a meal like the ones we
enjoyed in those early years.
 &HT;    This year's Thanksgiving will combine the traditional with the
modern and involve about two dozen guests. It will be hosted as a
tribute to both of my parents, and include my family and old
friends, plus a baker's dozen of preschool children, new parents,
young grandparents, and one spirited great grandparent. We
represent several religions and nationalities, including a few
native born Hawaiians.
 &HT;    My husband, a gourmet cook, will prepare the turkey, mashed
potatoes, gravy, and rich, one-of-kind stuffing with cognac, dry
Vermouth, sausage, oysters and cream. Female guests, including my
sister-in-law, have offered to make special side dishes: peas with
Parmesan butter, baked acorn squash filled with sauteed spinach and
leek, cracked pepper biscuits and orange marmalade muffins.
 &HT;    With a little bit of luck and several instructional cookbooks
(``If you can read, you can cook,'' Mom always said), I'll attempt
a contemporary array of hors d'oeuvres such as roasted-peppers and
artichoke-heart frittatas, portobello-and-herb-filled phyllos and
orange-marinated olives.
 &HT;    Though it will be my first parentless Thanksgiving, I am
learning that a good way to fight the pain at holidays is to try
and recreate the family table with good food, family and friends.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Linda Marx 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
