 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Renowned writers and columnists representing America's rainbow
society tell their own stories about Thanksgiving: their memories,
histories, traditions, menus and their unique take on this the most
American of holidays.
</P>
<P>
   VOICES OF AMERICA AT THANKSGIVING:
</P>
<P>
   A POOR FAMILY'S THANKSGIVING, ENRICHED BY MOTHER'S GIFT. By Bill
Maxwell. African American, he is an editorial writer and columnist
for the St. Petersburg Times in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   THANKSGIVING: INDIANS MUST FIGHT FOR THEIR PLACE AT THE TABLE.
By Beth Hege Piatote. Nez Perce/Colville Indian, she is a writer
living in Eugene, Ore., where she teaches at the University of
Oregon School of Journalism and Communication.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:PIATOTE-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   THE MOTHER OF ALL TURKEYS: EL GUAJOLOTE. By Raoul Lowery
Contreras. Mexican American, he is a columnist and editorial board
member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own radio talk show on
KOGO-AM.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   TRAIN TO THANKSGIVINGS PAST. By Kirsten Chapman who writes a
weekly column for the Columbus Dispatch in Columbus, Ohio, and is
the author of three books, one just published.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   MERELY TO BE THANKFUL IS NOT ENOUGH. By Frank Wu. Chinese
American, he is a columnist for Asian Week and associate professor
of law and supervising attorney at Howard University.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:WU-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   EL DIA DE GRACIAS _ TEXAS STYLE. By Barbara Renaud Gonzalez.
Mexican American, she is a Dallas-based columnist and writer for
several leading Texas newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:GONZALEZ-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   DEFYING THANKSGIVING. By Rekha Basu. A Moslem from India, she is
a journalist for the Des Moines Register in Des Moines, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:BASU-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   MISSION SCHOOLS KEPT CHILDREN AWAY FROM FAMILY THANKSGIVING. By
Tim Giago. Lakota Indian, he is publisher and editor-in-chief of
Indian Country Today. His Indian name is Nanwica Kciji.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   MANY BLACKS CELEBRATE THANKSGIVING WITH AMERICAN INDIAN DAY. By
Joyce Evans-Campbell. African American (whose great-grandmother was
Cherokee), she is a columnist for the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:EVANS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   A FEW OLD FRIENDS AND A PRAYER THAT ACKNOWLEDGES OUR FULL
HISTORY. By Dr. Joan Steinau Lester, a partner in The Equity
Consulting Group in Berkeley, Calif., and author of the book,
``Taking Charge: Every Woman's Action Guide to Personal, Political
and Profession Success.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-THANKSGIV-VOICES:LESTER-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
