<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8972 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-THANKS-1120-C     11-19 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-THANKS-1120-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ENGLAND'S PLYMOUTH WANTS TO GIVE AMERICANS THAN KS
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ While the turkey will be British and the football
round, the city from which the Mayflower embarked for the New World
wants Americans to come and feel at home for Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The port city of Plymouth is making plans for its first American
Thanksgiving Festival, complete with such exotic-sounding dishes as
succotash and pumpkin pie to complement a dinner of turkey with
cranberry sauce.
</P>
<P>
   By some counts, as many as 250,000 Americans live in the United
Kingdom, and many feel somewhat dislocated during periods of
traditional U.S. holidays such as Independence Day, Halloween and
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a full embrace by many Britons of such American
cultural icons as McDonald's, shopping malls and Homer Simpson,
there is only a vague awareness that there is any significance to
the last Thursday of November.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, part of the job for Plymouth organizers is to
explain to locals what it's all about. ``Plymouth has been slow to
recognize this part of our heritage, but we're learning and want to
be recognized as being a very American-friendly place,'' said Neill
Mitchell, chief executive of the Plymouth Chamber of Commerce.
``Local people are starting to get the hang of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The city of 257,000 has a number of historic, cultural and
business connections to the United States and Thanksgiving seemed
the perfect time to take note of these, Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being the departure point for 102 men, women and
children aboard the Mayflower, the port also has seen ships
embarking with such noted explorers as Francis Drake, Walter
Raleigh, Capt. William Bligh and Charles Darwin. The Mayflower
Stone and Steps, the place from which the Mayflower set sail, has
been preserved as a monument to the Pilgrims who left England to
establish a colony in Massachusetts. Many died over the winter, and
a feast of thanksgiving was held the following autumn.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim begins here.)
</P>
<P>
   The old part of Plymouth city clusters around the Hoe, the
famous patch of turf on which Drake is said to have finished a calm
game of bowls before heading off to defeat the invading Spanish
Armada in 1588. Plymouth also was an embarkation point for U.S.
troops heading for the Normandy invasion in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Commerce was founded in 1813 during one of the
unpleasant spells when Britain and its former colonies were at war.
``That's when the fleet from Plymouth was being molested in
Newfoundland by your fleet,'' Mitchell told an American reporter.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends here.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put that whole jigsaw puzzle together you begin to
see that there's quite a lot of American heritage represented
here,'' he said .
</P>
<P>
   This year's festival will be from Nov. 26-29, with a 1940s-style
big band dinner held the Friday after Thanksgiving and the arrival
at Plymouth docks of a group of NATO ships led by the American
warship the U.S.S. Stark.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the event has been given scarce attention in
Britain, it has been received warmly by Americans -- including
those back in the States -- because of a six-month old posting on
the World Wide Web, Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   The American community in England, a fairly affluent bunch of
corporate executives and such, relies heavily on the Internet to
keep in touch. ``Were it not for the Internet, I'm not sure what we
would have done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   True to its American style, the celebration, much as its
namesake in the United States, will have commercial undertones.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to boosting tourism and providing exposure to
American business people in Britain, the event could help lure a
few Yankee dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``When President (Franklin) Roosevelt fixed it on the calendar,
it was clearly an effort to help extend the Christmas shopping
season,'' Mitchell said. ``Americans could start the season in
Plymouth and then head on to London or Paris for Christmas
shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
