<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8973 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TOWN-1120-COX     11-19 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TOWN-1120-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EVEN IN JAPAN, CLINTON UNABLE TO ESCAPE LONG SHADOW OF 'MONICA'
 &HT;    With CLINTON-JAPAN-1120.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ President Clinton traveled 8,000 miles away from
Thursday's impeachment proceedings on Capitol Hill, but it wasn't
far enough to escape questions about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Venturing back into what was once among his favorite public
settings, Clinton hosted a televised town hall-style forum here on
Thursday, and an Osaka housewife threw him a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ''Regarding Miss Monica Lewinsky -- how did you apologize to
Mrs. Clinton and Chelsea,'' the mother of two wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would never be able to forgive my husband for that,'' she
added. ''Did they really forgive you, Mr. President?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton paused, then delivered an answer that was succinct and
sober.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, I did it (apologized) in a direct and straightforward
manner, and I believe they did (forgive), yes,'' he replied. ''But
that's really a question you could ask them better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mrs. Clinton nor Chelsea accompanied the president to
Tokyo. Mrs. Clinton is touring hurricane-damaged nations in Central
America; Chelsea is a sophomore at Stanford University, in Palo
Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly not wanting to build on the theme, program moderator
Tetsuya Chikushi of the Tokyo Broadcasting System took evasive
action.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's change the subject now,'' he quickly interjected.
''Let's talk about U.S.-Japan relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Chikushi and the president sat before the live audience of 100
of Japan's future leaders on two bar stools with a large video
screen before them that linked the studio to Osaka.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging exchange with Japanese from a variety of walks
of life, Clinton fielded questions about his favorite food --
chicken enchiladas, he said, ''although I like sushi too,'' -- his
advice on public speaking -- ''be yourself'' -- and even his views
on government service -- ''I can't run for a third term under our
laws,'' he said. ''If I could, I would, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   He also explained, in his fullest form yet, the thinking behind
his decision to call off air strikes against Iraq last weekend
after Baghdad agreed to submit to United Nations weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we had conducted a comprehensive attack directed at their
weapons of mass destruction program, the production capacity, the
laboratories, all the support sites and the military infrastructure
that supports it,'' he said, ''unless everyone knew in advance and
left the premises, large numbers of people would be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ''the United States has a special responsibility,
because of the unique position of our military might, at this
moment in history, to be very careful in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made clear, though, that he would not shrink from air
strikes in the future, if he feels they are necessary to counter
Iraq's efforts to build chemical, biological and nuclear arms,
which, Clinton said, could one day make their way into the hands of
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can do something to stop it now,'' he said, ''we should
do it, even if it requires military action.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1229EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8974 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-CLINTON-1120-CO     11-19 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-CLINTON-1120-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: May update at 9:30 p.m. EST.
 &HT;    CLINTON URGES JAPANESE TO SUPPORT GOVERNMENT'S ECONOMIC PLAN
 &HT;    With CLINTON-TOWN-1120.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Taking his message of hope and change far from home,
President Clinton gave Japan an economic pep talk on Thursday,
urging the country to get behind a controversial set of programs
aimed at ending seven years of stagnation here that is dragging
down the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   With Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi struggling to implement $700
billion worth of initiatives meant to shore up the country's
debt-ridden banks and stimulate spending and growth, Clinton
avoided high-pressure rhetoric, publicly at least, and instead
encouraged the Japanese to embrace Obuchi's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do not be discouraged by the present economic difficulties:
they can be overcome,'' Clinton said, taking his powers of
political persuasion abroad. ''Support your government in
aggressively dealing with the financial institutions, aggressively
moving to support greater consumption, aggressively moving for
structural changes that will create more jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who arrived here Thursday afternoon, made the remarks
during a nationally televised town hall meeting designed to help
take the edge off of the U.S. message that Japan must do more than
it has so far to get its economy out of the horse latitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to address the American business community
here and to hold additional meetings with Obuchi on Friday. In
those meetings, officials said Clinton will warn Obuchi that fresh
intelligence shows that North Korea can launch a second long-range
ballistic missile over Japan at any time.
</P>
<P>
   He will also discuss the issue with South Korean President Kim
Dae Jung after traveling to Seoul late Friday for two days of talks
expected to center on security. White House officials said the
president hopes the warning will forge greater cooperation among
the United States, Japan and South Korea to deal with North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton travels to the American possession of Guam on Monday
before returning to Washington that night.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. frustration over Japan's lingering economic malaise has
strained U.S.-Japan relations over the past year, and part of
Clinton's task during a two-day summit here is to try to set the
alliance back on firm footing, largely by accentuating the
positive.
</P>
<P>
   ''The relationship between our two countries has always been
important, but never more important than now,'' Clinton said during
a toast at a state dinner hosted by Obuchi at a downtown hotel.
''Our security alliance is the cornerstone of Asia's stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, administration officials have voiced agitation with
Tokyo for being slow in responding to Japan's worst economic
performance since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Stagnant for seven of the past eight years, Japan's economy is
expected to contract by 2 percent or more this year, and economists
expect little, if any, growth in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The languid economy here is blamed as a key reason behind a
regional recession that has pulled down emerging markets from
Russia to Brazil, causing the United States and its wealthy
partners to pony up more than $170 billion over the past 18 months
in emergency assistance aimed at cushioning the pain of economic
woe and propping up failing currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's sorry economic performance has also put pressure on
American companies and workers. Because Japan's consumers are
buying fewer goods and services from U.S. companies than they would
during healthier times, the U.S. trade deficit with Japan is
mushrooming.
</P>
<P>
   That gap was $48 billion, in Japan's favor, just two years ago.
It soared to $56 billion last year and is on track to top $60
billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our long-term prosperity requires a healthy global economy,''
Clinton said in Washington on Wednesday before departing for Japan.
''If people overseas lose their jobs, therefore, they can't afford
American products and our workers and farmers pay the price.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi took office in August after his predecessor, Ryutaro
Hashimoto, resigned to take blame for the faltering economy.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi announced on Monday a 24 trillion yen (roughly US$200
billion) package of tax cuts and stimulus measures, in hopes of
pulling Japan out of its funk sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   That comes on top of a plan announced earlier this year to make
up to 60 trillion yen, equal to about US$500 billion, to bail out
Japanese banks. The banking industry is saddled with an estimated
$1 trillion in bad debts. The situation has crimped lending,
creating a credit squeeze that is stifling growth.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
