<HEADER>
A8987 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BR     11-19 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BRIEFS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: NONFICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 THE CENTURY 
 By Peter Jennings and Todd Brewster 
 Doubleday, $60  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This ragtag century of ours is getting to seem like a garrulous
uncle who keeps coming back with his same old stories: his great
wars and his great depressions, evils daunted and lessons sorely
learned. Crowds cheering the troops into World War I, the folly of
the Treaty of Versailles, the masses on their feet in Nazi salute
at the 1936 Olympics in Berlin -- and on and on. THE CENTURY is
comprehensive, balanced, eminently readable and fairly onerous,
taken cover to cover. The narrative by Peter Jennings, the
broadcaster, and Todd Brewster, a former editor and writer at Life,
is a good textbook history of the American experience of the 20th
century, told from the perspective of the American 1990's, rather
than what might have been more interesting, the century as seen
from each of its successive eras. Important phases and events are
captured in a series of first-person accounts, most filling a
single page, with a boxed biography of the speaker and several
photographs, often snapshots; together these form an effective, and
in some ways more satisfying narrative, and are the real meat of
this book. The photo selection of Katherine Bourbeau is excellent,
with an eye for the unfamiliar image (John F. Kennedy and Richard
M. Nixon in a handshake that separates rather than brings them
together; students at Harvard mourning Kennedy's murder), while a
familiar image like Dorothea Lange's ``Migrant Mother'' is treated
as subject rather than illustration, and captioned with a quotation
from the photographer, describing the circumstances of the shot.
With so much to browse and relive, there will be something here for
everyone. _ DAVID WALTON
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SCIENCE TIMES BOOK OF INSECTS &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Nicholas Wade &QL; 
 &UR; Lyons, $25 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Insects preceded people on this earth by about 300 million
years, and may well survive mankind by longer than that. Such a
prospect deserves respect, and that is what insects (and a few
other arthropods) receive in THE SCIENCE TIMES BOOK OF INSECTS,
edited by Nicholas Wade (Lyons, $25), a selection of nature
reporting, from The Times's weekly science section, about insects
and the scientists who study them. Intriguing new findings concern,
for example, the recycling tactics of dung beetles, without whom
this planet would be a mess; the invasive habits of the Halloween
ladybug, an innocent aphid eater that can alarm whole suburbs with
its vast October swarms; and, perhaps best of all, research at
Cambridge University that appears to have determined how the
proverbially unairworthy bumblebee manages, in defiance of
conventional aerodynamics, to fly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEATLES &QL; 
 &UR; An Oral History &QL; 
 &UR; By David Pritchard and Alan Lysaght &QL; 
 &UR; Hyperion, $23.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What used to be called a clip job now passes for ``oral
history.'' ``The Beatles,'' by David Pritchard and Alan Lysaght,
two Canadian radio and television producers, is a compilation of
twice-told tales culled from interviews with the Beatles and their
contemporaries and is more seriously in need of editing than the
``White Album.'' Far too much of this material has been told more
vividly elsewhere. However, there are a few gems: George Harrison's
sister, Louise, says their mother listened to Radio India on Sunday
afternoons when she was pregnant with George, so that he may have
been influenced by the sitar before he was born. There is a
wistfulness to those left behind by the Beatles' fame: a Hamburg
nightclub owner named Horst Fascher wishes he had ``collected more
things that they threw away, like drumsticks and guitar strings.''
For die-hard Beatlephiles, there are technical tidbits like the
fact that ``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band,'' one of the
most celebrated stereo rock albums, was largely mixed in mono.
Unfortunately, the book is shapeless and stuffed with filler. An
oral history of the Beatles should have been a lot more fun. _ ERIC
P. NASH
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LONG-WINDED LADY &QL; 
 &UR; Notes From The New Yorker &QL; 
 &UR; By Maeve Brennan &QL; 
 &UR; Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, paper, $13 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some writers hold your attention with grand tales of love or
war. Maeve Brennan had smaller goals. For nearly three decades she
wrote for The New Yorker's Talk of the Town section under the
woefully apt pseudonym the Long-Winded Lady. In her vignettes of
city life she natters about little things like yappy dogs, or
dinner at her favorite steakhouse, where a stranger had the veal,
or the weather, which came in three flavors -- heat wave, downpour
and snowstorm. Brennan is a distant observer of couples in the
park, loners on the roof and cats in the alley; she is always
watching, often conjecturing, rarely engaging her subjects in
conversation. Mixed with these ramblings is a bittersweet chronicle
of New York in transition in the 1950's and 60's as the residential
hotels of her beloved neighborhoods, Greenwich Village and Times
Square, are torn down for high-rises. Unlike that other chronicler
of old New York, Joseph Mitchell, who relished its odd corners and
people, Brennan keeps her neighbors at arm's length. _ LAURA GREEN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BRIEFS-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: LAURA GREEN) &QL; 
 &UR; DIANE &QL; 
 &UR; A Signature Life &QL; 
 &UR; By Diane Von Furstenberg with Linda Bird Francke &QL; 
 &UR; Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is almost too easy to dismiss the designer Diane Von
Furstenberg as a socialite and dilettante whose once ubiquitous
wrap dress succeeded on the merit of her connections and title (her
former husband is a prince). Indeed, several passages in ``Diane,''
the autobiography she has written with Linda Bird Francke, would
support this assumption. Attending a White House dinner celebrating
the 1979 Egypt-Israeli peace accord, she writes that she would have
argued more strenuously with the pessimism of her table mate,
Yitzhak Shamir, if only the damp night hadn't left her so cold.
After a Secret Service agent lends her a raincoat, she laments,
``There was nothing anyone could do, however, about the terminal
damage done to my new Manolo Blahnik shoes by the wet White House
lawn.'' Since the moment the Belgian-born Von Furstenberg arrived
in New York in 1969, she has lived a rarefied existence. In
difficult situations, she consults with Barry (Diller), Ronald
(Lauder) and Bianca (Jagger), and when considering applying for
American citizenship, she remarks on the section requiring her to
list visits abroad: ``Reconstructing the hundreds of trips I had
taken was just too much.'' Such blithe commentary masks what is by
any measure a success story; Von Furstenberg did not inherit
privilege. Her mother survived Auschwitz and her father built his
own business that financed the boarding school education that
introduced Von Furstenberg to the people who introduced her to the
world of Andy Warhol and Studio 54. She persuasively illustrates
how her hugely successful clothing and cosmetics businesses were
nurtured by endless hours of hard work and hundreds of personal
appearances. Despite bouts of superficiality, Von Furstenberg is a
likable and surprisingly earnest figure. This is breezy reading for
anyone who enjoys columns with a plenitude of bold-faced names. _
MICHELE ORECKLIN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HISTORY IN OUR TIME &QL; 
 &UR; By David Cannadine &QL; 
 &UR; Yale, $25 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In these reviews of other historians' books, David Cannadine
works a provocative series of transformations -- taking new angles,
amplifying themes and giving his own acerbic voice the final word.
These pieces examine the last four centuries of British history,
from Henry VIII to Diana, Princess of Wales, lingering over
imperialism, Victorian culture, Florence Nightingale and Winston
Churchill (as well as second-rank figures like the English fascist
Oswald Mosley and John Buchan, the novelist and politician). The
heart of ``History in Our Time'' is 10 essays that focus closely on
the British monarchy. There is a fascinating sketch, based on a
study by Phillip Hall, of how the Windsors made their money (mostly
done since 1910, through the hoarding of public funds and the
careful negotiation of personal tax exemptions). Ironically, when
he turns to the Royal Family, Cannadine's withering glare is very
much a spellbound gaze. He sympathizes with kings who have honored
their duties -- notably George VI, a dull, decent figurehead who
worked hard at sharing his people's wartime hardships yet amused
himself by personally designing ``a new style of trousers to wear
with the Order of the Garter.'' Cannadine wants to overhaul the
monarchy, but only to adapt it to downscaled, postimperial times.
He repeatedly intimates that princes need broader experience and
better education. ``History in Our Time'' displays its author's
range as a historian and his skills as a working critic. _ ALLEN D.
BOYER
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
