<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8992 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DINING-NYTSF     11-19 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DINING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINING OUT
</HEADLINE>
  Secrets From America's Leading Critics, Chefs, and Restaurateurs 
 By Andrew Dornenburg and Karen Page 
 Illustrated. 343 pp. New York: John Wiley &AMP; Sons. Paper, $29.95. 
 ------ 
 KNIFE, FORK AND SKI MASK 
 By MICHAEL RUHLMAN 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I almost couldn't finish reading ``Dining Out: Secrets From
America's Leading Critics, Chefs, and Restaurateurs,'' because
every time I lifted it, my fingers, against my will, began riffling
the pages for all the tasty sidebars and marginal quotations from
prominent critics and chefs. I couldn't stop; it was like eating
salted nuts. Yet it's almost impossible to do otherwise, I soon
realized, because the book is virtually composed of such random
blocks of text, plus artful (but maddeningly captionless)
photographs.
</P>
<P>
   For all its disjointedness and design-over-content feel, though,
``Dining Out'' is a fascinating collage, a study of the profession
of restaurant criticism from the vantage point of scores of critics
and the chefs those critics review, and criticism's effect on the
booming restaurant business -- ultimately, a book-length panel
discussion on cuisine's growing prominence in our culture.
</P>
<P>
   This is Andrew Dornenburg and Karen Page's third book in a
trilogy that includes ``Becoming a Chef'' and ``Culinary
Artistry,'' and its method is to heap on information via quotation
after quotation, broken up by the ubiquitous sidebars. In the very
first chapter, in addition to the brief introductory text we get a
time line, beginning in 1765, of restaurants and influential
guides; references to two First Amendment cases involving critics
sued for libel; an extended quotation from the Chicago Tribune
critic William Rice; the Esquire critic John Mariani picking
America's most influential restaurants; a history of restaurant
critics at The New York Times; movies that prominently feature food
and cooking; a list of celebrity restaurateurs and their
restaurants; and more than a dozen pull-out quotations in gold
print.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for anyone serious about food, all of it is
interesting. I was enthralled to learn the tricks of the restaurant
reviewer's trade -- how critics maintain anonymity, what they do
when they're discovered, how they became critics, how they take
notes (one critic speaks throughout dinner into his tie, where,
presumably, a microphone is housed), whether they call the chef
afterward to check details and confirm guesses.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps surprisingly, few critics have professional cooking
experience or formal culinary education, according to Dornenburg
and Page. One unnamed chef grumbles, ``Sometimes I resent that
after working for decades in this business, I have to wait for
marks like a schoolboy, and from people who know barely one-tenth
as much as I do about cooking.'' Norman Van Aken, chef-owner of
Norman's in Coral Gables, Fla., offers a suggestion: ``Food critics
should, perhaps, be licensed.'' Even some critics agree. David
Rosengarten, who writes for Gourmet magazine and has a Ph.D. in
dramatic literature from Cornell, comments that ``there should
almost be some sort of diploma program before you can actually
start to write about food in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Reichl, once a chef and restaurateur, now the restaurant
critic of The New York Times, is arguably the most powerful food
critic in the country. She entertainingly describes how she works,
how she schedules her days, including managing all her
reservations, given that at any one time she is researching 20
different restaurants. And then there is the anxiety inherent in
her position: she says she didn't sleep for three days after she
decided to remove one of Le Cirque's four stars (she later returned
it). But some concerns of the reviewer's life are not intellectual
or critical. ``In many ways, it's a very wearing, difficult,
invasive job because it's something you devote your whole body
to,'' says Phyllis Richman of The Washington Post. ``And you eat a
lot of bad food -- probably more bad food than anybody who cares
about food would choose to eat!''
</P>
<P>
   Reichl was photographed (in semi-disguise) for the cover of this
book, and her words conclude it: ``The great thing about great food
is that it can bring people real pleasure and enjoyment, every day.
And for all of us who are committed to making food even better in
this country, that is ultimately the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   To dismiss this book as a series of articulate comments
tediously strung together, a hodgepodge of sidebars with no clear
progression or core, would be easy but unfortunate. Offering
insiders' knowledge and illuminating insights from some of the
country's best chefs and food critics, the moderators Dornenburg
and Page have brought a generous curiosity and balance to a subject
of compulsive interest to a growing number of people.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ruhlman's most recent book is ``The Making of a Chef:
Mastering Heat at the Culinary Institute of America.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
