<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ARMADILLO-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMADILLO
</HEADLINE>
  By William Boyd 
 337 pp. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $24 
 ------ 
 AS ILL LUCK WOULD HAVE IT 
 By A. O. SCOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the course of investigating a suspicious insurance claim,
Lorimer Black, the hero of William Boyd's new novel, ``Armadillo,''
encounters an entirely minor character named Francis Home. Noting
Home's olive complexion and ``dark crinkly hair,'' Lorimer wonders
about his background: ``Cypriot? Lebanese? Spanish? Egyptian?
Syrian? Greek? Like himself, Lorimer knew, there were many types of
Englishmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Like himself: Lorimer Black, educated in Scotland and given on
occasion to appearing at dinner parties in a kilt, is not who he
seems to be. ``You're not Angus Black's youngest, are you?'' asks
Sir Simon Sherriffmuir, head of Fortress Sure, the insurance giant
with which Lorimer is affiliated, trying to place this outsider in
his own rarefied social world. Lorimer Black -- senior loss
adjuster, research subject at the Institute of Lucid Dreams, author
of a private memoir called ``The Book of Transfiguration,''
collector of antique military helmets and obsessive pursuer of the
mysterious actress Flavia Malinverno -- is not Angus Black's son.
He's not Lorimer Black at all, but rather Milomre Blocj, the son of
Bogdan Blocj. Milomre (Milo to those few who know his real
identity) comes from a large family of East European Gypsies who
run a prosperous car-and-van service on the outskirts of London.
</P>
<P>
   The multiculturalism of modern Britain -- and of London
especially -- has become a staple of British fiction and has
supplied it with new subjects and new energies. It's impossible,
for instance, to imagine most of Martin Amis's novels (some of
which ``Armadillo'' calls to mind) without the clatter and menace
of colliding versions of the English language. And indeed many of
the most inventive British novelists of recent years -- Salman
Rushdie, Hanif Kureishi, Caryl Phillips, Kazuo Ishiguro, James
Kelman -- have reinvigorated the idioms and widened the scope of
English literature by, in effect, colonizing it.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd's previous books have also contributed to what might be
called the globalization of the English novel. From early satirical
efforts like the comedy of postcolonial diplomatic manners ``A Good
Man in Africa'' and the American road novel ``Stars and Bars'' to
ambitious, unclassifiable mature works like ``Brazzaville Beach''
and ``The Blue Afternoon,'' Boyd has shown himself to be at ease
with a startling diversity of settings and subjects. With
``Armadillo,'' he has come home, after ranging from Africa to the
Philippines to the American South, and found his native ground as
haunting and strange as any of them. But in spite of his taste for
the exotic, all his work, including this book, manifests some
welcome English virtues: understated wit, graceful prose and an
expert sense of pacing and narrative complication.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd's blithe cosmopolitanism may confuse American readers who,
steeped in ``Masterpiece Theater'' and recent film adaptations of
Jane Austen and E. M. Forster, associate England and its literature
above all with class. But the system of rigid social codes and
carefully maintained hierarchies that defined British life (and
animated its literature) for so long has been replaced, at least on
the evidence of this novel, by something we ex-colonials may find
more familiar -- a hectic, polyglot urban world of getting and
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Lorimer Black's London -- a rendering, it seems, of the capital
of Tony Blair's ``Cool Britannia'' -- is a city on the make,
bursting with new construction projects, trendy cafes and other
signs of affluence. At first, it seems a perfect habitat for the
ironical, deracinated Lorimer, who listens to African pop music,
drinks cappuccino and reinvents himself for each social, business
and romantic encounter by subtle alterations in his mode of dress.
He is successful at his job, in spite of the psychotic bullying of
his boss, an old-fashioned Englishman named Hogg, and diverted by a
pleasant, if not exactly passionate, affair with a divorcee named
Stella Bull. He has money for exquisite clothes and his beloved
helmets. He pays regular, if somewhat strained and chaotic, visits
to his family, and looks after his aging downstairs neighbor. His
only real problem is persistent insomnia.
</P>
<P>
   But then, through a sequence of events too complex to recount
here (the connections between which, in any case, are never fully
explained), everything in Lorimer's life begins to go wrong. His
reversal of fortune is attributed to a principle defined in one of
the reflective passages from his diary that punctuate the action of
the novel:
</P>
<P>
   ``Serendipity. From Serendip, a former name of Ceylon, now Sri
Lanka. A word coined by Horace Walpole, who had invented it based
on a folk tale whose heroes were always making discoveries of
things they were not in quest of. Ergo: serendipity, the faculty of
making happy and unexpected discoveries by accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what is the opposite of Serendip, a southern land of spice
and warmth, lush greenery and hummingbirds, seawashed, sunbasted?
Think of another world in the far north, barren, icebound, cold, a
world of flint and stone. Call it Zembla. Ergo: zemblanity, the
opposite of serendipity, the faculty of making unhappy, unlucky and
expected discoveries by design. Serendipity and zemblanity: the
twin poles of the axis around which we revolve.''
</P>
<P>
   Zemblanity in Lorimer's life takes many forms: a paranoid rock
star selects him as a confidant; his car is vandalized, either by
the subject of one of his insurance investigations or by Flavia
Malinverno's jealous husband; he inherits his elderly neighbor's
dog; his father dies. But if zemblanity could be personified, it
would assume the shape of Torquil Helvoir-Jayne, an erstwhile
colleague of Lorimer's who, when taken alongside the thuggish Hogg
and the unprincipled Sir Simon, may convince you that the only
thing wrong with England these days is the English.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-ARMADILLO-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: the English.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helvoir-Jayne (it's pronounced -- oh, never mind) is one of the
great comic creations of recent literature; he belongs in the
gallery of British grotesques alongside the best efforts of Martin
Amis (Keith Talent, say, in ``London Fields'' or John Self in
``Money'') and his dad, Kingsley. The spectacularly boorish
Helvoir-Jayne attaches himself to Lorimer like a leech. He
inveigles Lorimer into helping him cover up one of his tawdry
adulteries, and then moves in with Lorimer when his wife throws him
out. And Torquil seems to be involved in some suspicious doings
involving Fortress Sure and one of its clients, for which Lorimer
ultimately will take the fall.
</P>
<P>
   TORQUIL'S opposite -- Serendip to his Zembla -- is the elusive
Flavia Malinverno, first glimpsed through the window of a passing
taxi and then in a Fortress Sure advertisement. Of course,
Lorimer's pursuit of her precipitates complications of its own,
thanks to her violent-tempered husband and her propensity to shade
and amplify the truth.
</P>
<P>
   But Lorimer confronts it all with philosophical detachment: ``I
do not mind contradictions, paradoxes, puzzles and ambiguities.
What is the point of 'minding' something as inevitable and
entrenched in our nature as our digestive system is in our body?''
Such an attitude will help the reader of this novel as well.
``Armadillo'' is full of loose ends, unsolved mysteries and red
herrings. But it is also charming, unsettling and sneakily,
serendipitously profound.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   A. O. Scott is a senior editor of Lingua Franca.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
