<HEADER>
A8997 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DREAM-NYTSF     11-19 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DREAM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
------ 
 STILL WAITING
</HEADLINE>
 
 A Dream Deferred 
 The Second Betrayal of Black Freedom in America 
 By Shelby Steele 
 185 pp. New York: HarperCollins Publishers. $24  By MICHAEL ANDERSON 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the subject is race, this land of free speech is deathly
afraid of plain talk. A legacy of rebellion and resentment,
complacency and commiseration has us tongue-tied; afraid to speak
our minds, we mystify ourselves with a bedazzling lexicon of code
words, euphemism and soothing gobbledygook.
</P>
<P>
   Consider ``diversity,'' for example. ``No two people define it
the same way,'' Shelby Steele writes in ``A Dream Deferred,'' his
second collection of essays. ``It is a word that is useful for the
very specific thing that it does not mean, which is racial
prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the rest of the current cliches -- ``inclusion,''
``pluralism,'' even the ubiquitous ``multiculturalism.'' For
Steele, each is a word with no meaning except that it disassociates
people ``from the stigma of racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele argues that the never-ending discussion of race relations
is, far too often, a sham battle of empty rhetoric. ``American
racial policy,'' he writes, has ``a decidedly 'post-modern' feel.
Its subtext is more important than its text.'' What is unspeakable,
Steele contended in his first book, ``The Content of Our
Character'' (1990), is white guilt and black fear -- the need of
white people for redemption from a history of oppression, the needs
of blacks to confront ``integration shock . . . the shock of being
suddenly accountable on strictly personal terms.'' And so black and
white Americans have entered into a powerful and unspoken collusion
to elude the sacrifices and risks that true racial harmony demands.
``This fear,'' he added, ``is the measure of our racial chasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, we live in a brave new world in which the cure for
discrimination is more discrimination, in which a quota mentality
is commonplace, in which good intentions form new cobblestones on
the pathway to perdition. Steele's tone has accordingly hardened.
His new essays take polemical relish in their finger-pointing at an
emperor wearing no kinte cloth. ``The president of a public
university could simply say the word 'diversity' and be justified
in excluding people from his university solely because of their
race,'' he writes. (``After all, diversity has no darkness or evil.
Thus people who serve it can do no wrong.'') In one of his sharpest
passages, Steele imagines the fate of a young Charlie Parker
subjected to a contemporary tutoring program taught by a white
college student:
</P>
<P>
   ``The tutor learns that Parker's father drank too much and
abandoned the family, and that his mother has had an affair with a
married man. Young Charlie is often late to his tutorial sessions.
Secretly the tutor comes to feel that probably his real purpose is
therapeutic, since the terrible circumstances of Charlie's life
make it highly unlikely that he will ever be focused enough to
master the complex keying system of the saxophone or learn to read
music competently.'' Charlie, having ``heard from many that the
saxophone -- a European instrument -- really has little to do with
who he is,'' gives up. The tutor is sympathetic. '' 'Can you
imagine,' he says, shaking his head in disbelief at himself,
'teaching saxophone to a poor black kid from Kansas City?' ''
</P>
<P>
   This sassy satire illustrates Steele's central thesis: What
white people really want is not to reform an unjust society but to
restore their own sense of virtue. Expunging that shame has been
the silent agenda of American social policy for a generation.
Indeed, Steele contends, much so-called reform is a continuation of
white supremacy by other means. ``The liberal looks at black
difficulties -- high crime rates, weak academic performance,
illegitimacy rates and so on -- and presumes them to be the result
of victimizing forces beyond the control of blacks.'' By this
``specific act of imagination,'' to ``always imagine blacks outside
the framework of individual responsibility,'' Steele writes, ``is
also to imagine them as inherently inferior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Double standards, preferential treatment, provisions for
'cultural difference' and various kinds of entitlement all
constitute a pattern of exceptionalism that keeps blacks (and other
minorities) down by tolerating weakness at every juncture where
strength is expected of others,'' Steele writes. ``Then, after
black weakness has been massaged, accepted, understood and felt
for, people wonder why the infamous gap between blacks and whites
on tests and other performance measures won't close. The answer, of
course, is that nobody seriously asks that it be closed.'' He is
particularly incisive on how good intentions have become an end in
themselves (``President Clinton gets credit for supporting
affirmative action, not for making it work''). Both races have
allowed themselves to be seduced by the siren song of
victimization: ``Whites agree to stay on this hook for an illusion
of redemption, and blacks agree to keep them there for an illusion
of power.'' But, as Steele wisely concludes, ``Victimhood lasts
only as long as it is accepted, and to exploit it for an empty
sovereignty is to accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For America to survive its struggle with racial shame, it will
have to stop cringing before it,'' Steele writes. ``We are no
longer trying to redeem the United States or resolve our tortuous
racial history; we are dealing with poor reading skills or a lack
of preparedness for employment or too many pregnant teen-age girls
made that way by too many young men.'' His book would benefit from
more attention to such social realities. History, like biology, is
destiny, and more attention to its patterns could only serve to
clarify the present. (For example, perhaps the different styles of
discrimination in the North and South evoked distinct
counterstrategies: a legal challenge to de jure segregation, social
engineering to the de facto version.) And Steele's agonizing over
principles too often takes on the tone of a scolding schoolmarm;
like many conservative critics, he seems all too quick to impute a
deliberate moral delinquency.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Steele assuredly is correct when he declares that
integration is 20th-century America's ``elaboration of democracy.''
Too often confused with assimilation -- that (somehow) all of us
would wind up bleached blond -- integration is a dynamic process;
in little more than a generation, American society has transformed
itself. In our rather stumbling way, we continue this process. As
Steele reminds us, ``the profoundness of our relationship to
democratic principles despite our many failings and duplicities''
is what constitutes our national identity. ``The United States has
to accept its past as proof of its need for principles today.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Michael Anderson is an editor at The New York Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
