<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MADNESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADNESS ON THE COUCH
</HEADLINE>
  Blaming the Victim in the Heyday of Psychoanalysis 
 By Edward Dolnick 
 Illustrated. 368 pp. New York: Simon &AMP; Schuster. $25 
 ------ 
 TALKING CURE? 
 By DEREK BICKERTON 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bleeding. Trepanning. Castration. Electroshock. Powdered unicorn
horns. Horse-blood injections. An ice pick through the eye socket.
Incarceration with snakes. Exposure to extreme temperatures.
Artificially induced epilepsy. Insulin coma.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a catalogue of ancient and modern tortures. All
these methods were used at various times, by supposedly expert and
well-meaning physicians, to treat sufferers from mental illness.
Small wonder, then, that when members of a respected school of
thought claimed they could cure psychoses by simply talking,
clinicians and the public responded with relief and approbation.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Madness on the Couch,'' Edward Dolnick, formerly the chief
science writer for The Boston Globe and now a contributing editor
for Health magazine, describes how, in the 1950s and '60s, Freudian
psychoanalysts sought to adapt their master's theories to treat
schizophrenia, autism and obsessive-compulsive disorder. The title
is potentially ambiguous: was the true madness that of the
patients, or did the doctors themselves, blinded by arrogance and
self-righteousness, embark on what now seems a course of lunatic
folly? Seldom has there been a more pungent illustration of the
adage ``The road to hell is paved with good intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by public acclaim and a virtual absence of critical
scrutiny, truly believing that all mental illness could be healed
if the patient could be made to confront its (purely mental)
causes, many of Freud's followers boldly entered fields where Freud
had carefully refrained from going -- even where he had warned
against going.
</P>
<P>
   Two fields were fraught with special pitfalls. Schizophrenia
affects mainly young adults; autism is diagnosed in young children.
If one rules out biology (and Freudians dismissed it on principle),
parental indiscretion is the only plausible culprit. The
possibility of ``a schizophrenogenic mother,'' casually mentioned
in a paper by a noted psychiatrist, Frieda Fromm-Reichmann, was
seized on and developed into elaborate profiles of
schizophrenia-causing families. Though it was the brainchild of a
clinical amateur, the anthropologist Gregory Bateson, the ``double
bind,'' a Catch-22 message from parent to child, received equally
enthusiastic acceptance. As for autistic children, their apparently
willful self-isolation must reflect the hostility and indifference
of ``refrigerator parents'' -- cold, mechanical creatures who,
according to Bruno Bettelheim, wished that their children ``should
not exist.''
</P>
<P>
   The belief in parental cause soon passed into the popular
culture, resulting in untold agony to countless innocent people.
For Freudian psychotherapy had double binds, but no double blinds:
its devotees did not take the elementary precaution of comparing
parents of schizophrenics or autistic children with other parents,
let alone test whether ``blind'' observers, ignorant of which group
individuals belonged to, could correctly assign them on the basis
of objective data.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Freudians might have survived this lack of empirical
support, even the absence of any nontemporary improvement in their
patients, but for developments outside therapy altogether. Evidence
accumulated that biological factors did indeed predispose
individuals to schizophrenia and other disorders. Simultaneously, a
series of largely serendipitous discoveries by practicing
clinicians revealed that for many conditions, medication could do
far more, far more quickly, than psychoanalysis. Acclaimed
therapists suddenly found themselves facing huge malpractice suits
for failing to prescribe what were already proven treatments.
</P>
<P>
   This bare summary of Dolnick's theme, however, does his book
scant justice. He brings to his task a formidable array of
strengths. Interviews with Freudians, anti-Freudians and their
patients, as well as an exhaustive reading of relevant literature,
provide his persuasive account with vivid anecdotes, from the
bizarre ritual demanded by Howard Hughes (an obsessive-compulsive
in later life) before opening canned food to the naive excursion,
``akin to the idle speculation of nannies at the park,'' that the
renowned ethologist Nikolaas Tinbergen made into autism. A diverse
cast of characters is captured in brilliant thumbnail vignettes:
the birdlike, charismatic R. D. Laing, who at the end delivered a
lecture ``drunk and stoned''; the dogged young doctor Leonard
Heston, who, when refused a Federal grant, did the research (on
children of schizophrenic mothers who were given up for adoption)
on his own time, money and barnstorming ingenuity; and many more.
Dolnick's narrative moves smoothly and effortlessly, never
lingering too long on any topic yet never leaving a topic until its
full significance has been explored. Despite its somber theme, the
book is a delight to read.
</P>
<P>
   But just what is its significance? In his prologue, Dolnick
limits his goal to describing the excesses of Freud's followers; he
explicitly disavows any intention of debunking psychotherapy, which
has helped people to ``cope with a divorce, or a child's death, or
a vague but oppressive feeling of inadequacy.'' But here, in a rare
misstep, he seems to confuse psychotherapy and psychoanalysis.
Freudian psychoanalysis is but one variety of psychotherapy; other
approaches -- behavioral, humanistic, cognitive -- eschew the
deep-analytic, symbol-chasing style of Freudians and Jungians for
more practical, problem-solving techniques. These alternative
therapies, which he never distinguishes, are far likelier than
analysis to be used, and useful, in dealing with grief, marital
problems and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Dolnick's disclaimer seems aimed at avoiding accusations of
Freud-bashing. His earlier chapters, where he lays the groundwork
for his assault on therapeutic hubris, show that all the errors of
Freud's disciples -- overconfidence, dogmatism, indifference to
empirical proofs, roseate evaluations of treatment outcomes,
willingness to interpret a patient's ``No'' as either ``No'' or
``Yes,'' whichever fitted the analysis -- were already latent in
Freud's own theory and practice. The excesses Dolnick recounts
sprang not from personal failings of individual therapists but from
the nature of their approach.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the book leaves one with a disturbing thought.
Practices that now seem reckless and sometimes downright cruel were
hailed in their day as pinnacles of medical achievement. Which of
today's lauded practices, one wonders, will stand condemned a few
decades hence?
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bickerton's most recent books are ``Language and Species''
and ``Language and Human Behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
