<HEADER>
A8999 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SQUARE-NYTSF     11-19 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SQUARE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL SQUARE
</HEADLINE>
  By George Packer 
 348 pp. St. Paul: Graywolf Press. $24.95 
 ------ 
 THE LEFT BANK 
 By RAND RICHARDS COOPER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   American novelists love the city, and they love hating it, too.
From Theodore Dreiser to Jay McInerney, writers have plumbed our
ambivalence toward urban life so often, and so eagerly, that it's
tempting to call the American novel an urban art form. One doubts
cities always appreciate the attention. Cambridge, Mass., at any
rate, will not rush to embrace ``Central Square,'' George Packer's
mordant look at life along the left bank of the Charles.
</P>
<P>
   On display in ``Central Square'' is not upscale, Victorian,
boutique-and-cafe Cambridge but the grittier middle stretch of
Massachusetts Avenue, a no man's land of the benighted. Here the
raucous contrasts that novelists once discovered in urban life --
vice and hope, squalor and splendor -- have given way to
postindustrial anomie. Factories have closed down; rumors circulate
of a casino in the works; shelters and mental health centers
constitute the only growth industry.
</P>
<P>
   Packer follows a trio of characters into this drab panorama.
Paula Voorhees is a clinical social worker sliding into burnout.
The therapy she dispenses to the homeless and the battered strikes
her as farcically inadequate -- a Band-Aid applied to the gushing
wounds of the disenfranchised. In her own life, self-protectiveness
drifts toward cynicism; she fears being single (``a condition --
suppressed panic with a whiff of cat hair'') but sleeps with a man
she's careful not to risk loving. After work, back at her dingy
apartment, she and the super's needy, abused wife exchange blunt
insults, and she goes away refreshed: ``It felt like her first real
human contact of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   A different panic stalks Eric Barnes. A novelist, he has three
money-losing books on his resume and is stuck, dismally, partway
through a fourth. His career is stalled, his wife is pregnant, his
study is being remodeled into a nursery, and when he dares to
renegotiate his tiny advance, his editor humbles him with revenue
printouts. Increasingly, all Eric can see about his friends is how
successful they are -- like the lawyer who is ``deeply sentimental
in a way, Eric thought, made possible by money.''
</P>
<P>
   Packer excels at portraying the mired and anxious:
college-educated 30-somethings whose easy idealism is yielding to
bleak encroachments of failure. There's more humor to this than you
might expect -- like Eric's perception of what having children does
to one's parties (``The grown-ups discussed toilet training while
Zach smeared goat cheese on the leather ottoman'') or Paula's take
on a patient who confides homicidal feelings (``This was progress,
but it felt like training a drugged bear to perform tricks designed
to put her life at risk''). In his study, Eric soothes himself by
contemplating vengeance on a rat scratching behind the wall, even
as he conducts a running argument with a radio-show guest touting a
book called ``Hold On, You Can Have Everything!'' A generous irony
marks the best moments of ``Central Square.'' These are characters
whose last redoubt, in the face of despair, is a weary, rueful
verve.
</P>
<P>
   When Packer tries to figure out what to do with these
characters, however, things get a little dodgy. Through a chance
encounter in the Widener library at Harvard, Paula and Eric meet,
and soon become lovers. Their illicit trysts take up a lot of
terrain in ``Central Square,'' and it isn't very rich soil.
``Falling into an affair would be a . . . revolt, and yet he also
knew that the moment with Paula by the river was the best thing
about him -- cheerful, loving, generous in spirit.'' Packer seems
to lose sight of how steeply we will discount Eric's passion as
mere flight from the responsibilities of fatherhood. At times, the
novel turns you into a bad therapist, impatient with Eric's
self-deceptions; the narrative voice occasionally resembles that of
a colluding enabler.
</P>
<P>
   But the weakest part of ``Central Square'' is the plot Packer
weaves around his third character, an enigmatic African-American
named Joe. Returning from a stay as a volunteer in Africa, Joe
decides, obscurely, to pass himself off as Amouzou, a village
shaman. Soon he wins a reputation in Central Square. (``They say he
gets inside you,'' a man tells Eric, ``changes your shape or
something, fixes your problems.'') He joins a shadowy organization,
known as the Community, that has been papering the streets with
cryptic exhortations on blue fliers. Part encounter group, part
populist uprising, it is led by Paula's sleazy boss, Peter Fine, a
would-be ``therapeutic rock star'' with a talent for stoking the
resentments of the underclass. Packer seems to be making a point
about therapy's potential as a language of demagoguery. But Fine's
rabble-rousing is so banal (``You and I need to have the courage to
heal on the next level'') that you don't believe anyone could be
``mesmerized,'' or that Paula, watching a crowd of listeners, would
feel ``a shiver'' of fear. Such scenes seem contrived.
</P>
<P>
   The same holds for the portrayal of Joe himself. Though Packer
supplies him with distant memories of a childhood with foster
parents killed in a car accident, Joe seems almost entirely
metaphorical, deployed to play ironically against the other two
main characters. Is he the true healer? Or is he the true writer,
who can shape-shift into any new identity? Or perhaps he's a
sacrificial sufferer, bearing the burden of everyone else's
inauthenticity and pain? When Eric, having discovered the truth
about Joe, recognizes ``something of himself'' in the man's
masquerade and exhorts him to ``let them know who you are,'' the
encounter seems stage-managed in order to deliver the realization;
its meaning hasn't been earned on the ground but imposed from
above. The magic of fiction, William Gass once wrote, is that when
we read it, ``thought seems to grow a body.'' But as ``Central
Square'' boils away toward its overheated denouement, the
characters get thinner and thinner.
</P>
<P>
   Packer's novel can be read as a running argument with the
therapeutic culture -- its personalizing of the political, its
rejection of tragic and comic perspectives in favor of
``irony-free'' personal-growth platitudes. And yet as ``Central
Square'' proceeds, its own irony leaks away; the narrative voice
loses its edge. Eric finally comes before the Community to be
cross-examined about his shortcomings. ``He was glad they had made
him name his issues. He felt hopeful, he didn't know why or for
what.'' It's as if Packer has capitulated, lost the argument, been
swallowed by the monster he set out to slay. Fair warning, perhaps,
for irony in the age of therapy: novelist, heal thyself.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Rand Richards Cooper is the author of a novel, ``The Last to
Go,'' and a collection of stories, ``Big as Life.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
