<HEADER>
A9002 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MONROE-1000&AMP;A     11-19 1571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MONROE-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MARILYN MONROE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Barbara Leaming.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 464 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Crown Publishers. $27.50.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; ENGINEERING AN ICON &QL; 
 &UR; By Molly Haskell &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The old Hollywood folk tale of the pretty girl ``discovered'' at
a drugstore and turned into a star conjures up an image deeply
comforting to traditional notions of sexual behavior: a sleeping
beauty plucked from obscurity by a male power broker and catapulted
to fame. The myth buttresses the ideal of feminine passivity and
male agency at the expense of a more subversive truth: the hustle,
the drive, the shrewdness of those women, who among thousands of
wannabes rose to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, no one has slid more smoothly into the myth of
female dependency than Marilyn Monroe. By tying her fate to a
string of male rescuers and by dying young and alone, she left
behind an open-ended scenario of victimization, whose architect
could be supplied according to the onlooker's politics and
proclivities. (Fill in the blanks with your favorite malefactor:
the patriarchy, the studio system, male concupiscence, the
Kennedys.) Yet as we learn from ``Marilyn Monroe,'' Barbara
Leaming's engrossing new biography, no one worked the drugstore
scene (not to mention the prescription counter) more shrewdly than
Monroe, and no one displayed such a furious desire to live and
succeed in the face of greater, more overwhelming odds. The chief
virtue of this retelling of the oft-told tale is that the author
restores Marilyn's humanity, gives flesh and blood, intelligence
and initiative, to the archetypal dumb blonde.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she wasn't used and abused, manipulated and exploited.
But she was an intuitive strategist: she found willing champions,
ingeniously playing an ally like Spyros Skouras, the president of
20th Century Fox, against his enemy and colleague, Darryl Zanuck,
the studio's production chief. She also made brilliant use of
publicity and her own photogeneity -- she was inspired in her
handling of the nude photo episode -- to boost her career with Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Major revelations aren't the point here, and other biographies
have been more comprehensive, but Leaming, whose most recent book
was a biography of Katharine Hepburn, has a sure dramatic instinct
for illuminating overlooked material and re-examining the most
interesting episodes. I was initially skeptical: could there really
be anything new to say about this endlessly reproduced pop icon?
But following Leaming's lead, I soon found myself devouring other
material, particularly the autobiographies of Elia Kazan and Arthur
Miller, to see where Kazan, Miller and Monroe agree and (more
fascinatingly) when and how they differ. It's this three-way
relationship, with its political and artistic, hetero- and
homoerotic components, that Leaming explores in the book's richest
leitmotif.
</P>
<P>
   We begin in 1951, at a perilous moment in the young starlet's
career -- her contract with Fox is up, Zanuck loathes her and
Johnny Hyde, her agent and staunchest ally (as well as her ardent
pursuer), has just died. She is finishing ``As Young as You Feel,''
with Monty Woolley and Constance Bennett, weeping between takes,
when Elia Kazan, with Arthur Miller in tow, arrives on the set to
ask her out. Kazan has recently directed Miller's ``Death of a
Salesman'' on Broadway, and they are in Hollywood peddling a Miller
script.
</P>
<P>
   At first Monroe refuses Kazan's invitation, then, shrewdly
reconsidering (he is ``hot,'' having just finished shooting ``A
Streetcar Named Desire'' and now casting for ``Viva Zapata!''), she
goes after him and they become an item. By day, Kazan, Monroe and
Miller are high-spirited pals; by night, Kazan and Monroe occupy
one of the guest rooms at the agent Charles Feldman's, while Miller
sleeps fitfully down the hall. The playwright, whose marriage is
wobbly but still on its feet, is so taken with Marilyn that he soon
flees Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe, however, has been smitten with this man, who treats her
respectfully and represents everything that Hollywood is not. After
his departure, she continues to sleep with Kaza, but on the shelf
above her bed, watching their every move, are photographs of her
two idols, Arthur Miller and Abraham Lincoln. Miller -- the vital
absentee in a weird triangle -- is the major subject of Kazan and
Monroe's postcoital conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Thus does Monroe find herself partitioned, virgin and whore,
between two men: one, Kazan, an admitted philanderer, who
(according to his own autobiography) sees her as fun, a mistress,
not the type anyone would want to marry, and the other, Miller, the
repressed but honorable puritan, who takes her as seriously as he
takes himself, thus providing her with a reflection more to her
liking. It's a split that finally tore her apart, while both of the
men survived to work and flourish, and to tell their sides of the
story -- not only of the Hollywood days but of their early
association with the Group Theater and Communism, the split between
them over Kazan's friendly testimony before the House Un-American
Activities Committee and their reunion for the Monroe-inspired
play, ``After the Fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Monroe needed Miller to accept the Marilyn who
wasn't just a ``happy girl,'' but the demands of that darker, more
complex personality were more than he could handle. (Joe DiMaggio,
her husband before Miller, found himself enmeshed in a similar
paradox when, after marrying the blond sensation, he wanted her to
give up her career and live like a normal woman.) The line between
sexiness and parody was gossamer thin, and impossible to maintain.
Her most successful films -- ``Gentlemen Prefer Blondes,'' ``How to
Marry a Millionaire,'' ``The Seven Year Itch,'' ``Some Like It
Hot'' -- capture the innocence of her pose and its satirical savvy.
But it was all as fragile as a bubble, and for her, as the pills
and insecurity mounted, there was no second act.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-MONROE-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: second act.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of her career, Monroe, with the help of Ben
Hecht, had advanced the idea that she was an orphan. It was a
cunning bid for the sympathy of women, who might be put off by her
sexual display (and who indeed would later turn against her).
Though the story was exposed as a hoax, the truth was worse: she
had been abandoned by her mother, Gladys, left with foster families
(who also abandoned her) and never knew who her father was. It was
one of her foster parents, ``Aunt Grace,'' who convinced her that
she could be another Harlow, and who encouraged her to use her sex
appeal, but who then turned on her when those charms attracted
Grace's own husband. Thus was enacted in microcosm the social
double bind into which all women are born but whose contradictions
the love goddess acts out on a high wire over the abyss: be
beautiful but not too beautiful; use your sex appeal, but forfeit
the right to be taken seriously; be childlike, but expect a
seriously reduced shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   Leaming underlines the importance of a moment when, while making
``How to Marry a Millionaire'' with Lauren Bacall and Betty Grable,
Monroe sees the handwriting on the wall: Grable, the leggy blond
oomph girl, is about to become a has-been at 36 and is gallantly
handing the torch to the new bombshell on the block. It was
Monroe's desire not to get caught in the same trap that fed her
often misguided ambition to play serious roles, to downgrade her
own enchanting comic temptress.
</P>
<P>
   She needed a grotesque parody of a woman's support group --
female monsters like her coach, Natasha Lytess, and the acting guru
Paula Strasberg -- to be present on the set running interference
for her. Reading the description of Strasberg, clad in black,
standing behind the director and waving hand signals like a catcher
at home plate, one can't help thinking of the tortured relationship
between Monroe and her mother -- who would suddenly surface from
time to time to express outrage over some flouting of propriety
perpetrated by her daughter. In response, Monroe would up the ante,
dressing even more seductively, provoking public outrage and
sabotaging her own success.
</P>
<P>
   If she has now become more famous as a photographic icon, in
black and white, than as a movie performer, there's a good reason.
She was as exhilaratingly at ease before the still camera as she
was paralyzingly insecure before the motion picture camera. Without
minimizing Monroe's hugely irritating and destructive behavior
toward the end, Leaming suggests heartbreaking moments when things
might have taken a different turn: if one of her numerous
pregnancies had come to term; if she and Laurence Olivier hadn't
got off to a bad start while filming ``The Prince and the
Showgirl''; if just one of the moguls in Hollywood had understood
that she was a woman who wanted, more than fame and money, credit
for her part in the creation of ``Marilyn Monroe.'' At least that
battle has been won in this gripping and corrective book.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Molly Haskell's most recent book is ``Holding My Own in No Man's
Land: Men and Women, Films and Feminists.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
