<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9005 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-ESCAPISM-NYTS     11-19 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ESCAPISM-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 ESCAPISM
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Yi-Fu Tuan.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 245 pp. Baltimore:
</P>
<P>
   The Johns Hopkins University Press. $28.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; THE MAN THAT GOT AWAY &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANCIS I. KANE &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yi-Fu Tuan, you've just capped a long and eminent career with
the publication of your latest work, 'Escapism.' Where are you
headed to now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To Disneyland, of course!''
</P>
<P>
   Yi-Fu Tuan is no Joe Montana with three most valuable player
awards in the Super Bowl and as many trips to Disneyland, but the
facetious scenario is not so far off the mark; for it was an
invitation to Disney's fantasy world that prompted Tuan, a
distinguished cultural geographer at the University of Wisconsin,
to write his latest work. Much to his surprise, he was charmed by
the place for the same reason that his academic colleagues loathed
it: it was unadulterated escape. That flight from the bleak
Wisconsin winter to sunny California led him to reflect on the
underestimated role that escapes play in our public and personal
lives.
</P>
<P>
   In his eyes, escape is everywhere -- whether we move from the
jangling chords of civilization back to a serenely pastoral nature,
or from that same nature now experienced as hostile and forbidding
to the covers of our warm beds in our well-constructed homes. In
fact, so pervasive is flight that Tuan proffers a rather startling
definition of culture: ``the totality of means by which I escape
from my animal state of being.''
</P>
<P>
   Why are we continually in flight? Well, we flee our bodies
because of their embarrassing demands -- for food, elimination,
sex. And we flee from our very selves into the social crowd,
because, as the author notes, uniqueness, however cherished, can at
times be quite intolerable. Once we have fled, however, we grow
disenchanted and escape in the other direction -- away from wispy
thought back to the ponderous body; away from the suffocating crowd
back to solitude. So inescapable are these flights that Tuan offers
one more definition of the human species: ``an animal who is
congenitally indisposed to accept reality as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Innovative as such claims seem to be, the reader might be
reminded of that groundbreaking book of a half-century ago, ``Homo
Ludens,'' in which Johan Huizinga argued similarly that play was
the central element in human culture. Both books persuade us to
adopt different angles of vision on culture and let us see such
familiar, mundane realities as play and escape in a more promising
light. For Yi-Fu Tuan, it is a case of getting us to see escapes
not as insubstantial diversions but rather as the very condition of
all that is good, and bad, in human culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Escapism,'' though, is not so much an argument as a tour --
sometimes a tour de force -- of cultural escapes with exotic stops
and unexpected twists and turns. And such a convivial tour guide!
Tuan is chatty, engaging, unpretentious and charming. The
atmosphere he creates is that of your friendly pub, where you are
regaled with captivating stories by a wise old man whose eyes still
betray a childlike wonder. This is decidedly not your old grade
school geography lesson. You indulge his sometimes professorial
locutions and even the occasional but maddening lack of conceptual
clarity (if everything is escape, then what distinctive meaning can
the word have?) because here is a geographer unafraid to bump up
against the ultimate human questions.
</P>
<P>
   His thesis, however, is clear. Escapes, those imaginative
reconstructions of reality, are indispensable. While flights from
our animal selves can be silly, preposterous, even cruel and
dangerous, they can also create new and more expressive ways for
humans to flourish. While romantic love, for example, may have
originated in a flight from our more bestial selves, it has become
over time just as real and decidedly more human than mere animal
couplings.
</P>
<P>
   For Tuan, it is the power of imagination that serves as the
mechanism of escape, and he pursues it down its labyrinthine ways,
noting both its destructive and creative impulses. Because of its
enormous power, imagination must be checked by the moral weight of
the good, and that, finally, is where his study culminates, on
moral grounds that are provided for by his Western (Greek) and
Eastern (Confucian) heritages. He is most at home in the proverbial
``middle way''; in fact, his favorite metaphor for an ethical
escape is ``landscape,'' both as nature and artifice. More
particularly, ``middle landscapes'' -- Chinese gardens and
cultivated fields -- serve as the geographical analogue for our
moral center; for Tuan they open up a world that is both at home
and in tension with nature. In these middle landscapes, we are
neither angels nor beasts, neither Icarus nor Caliban, but mortals
anchored in the earth yet borne aloft on the wings of imagination.
</P>
<P>
   I only wish that Tuan had argued more strenuously for these last
moral considerations, so sound and yet in such disrepute today.
Perhaps he does not because his method is not to argue the point
but to point long and hard enough until you see it. In the last
line of the book, he tells us that it doesn't take talent or status
to go off on flights that are truly good, just a ``willingness to
look in the right direction.'' But how do you know when you are
looking in the right direction? Indeed, what is the right
direction?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I confess that even after all that looking, I was
not persuaded that all culture is escape. The very same moral
considerations the author points to would, I think, require that we
discriminate between mere escape and authentic liberation. Two
older books responded to these questions rather more directly: a
scholarly work, ``Leisure: The Basis of Culture,'' by the
philosopher Josef Pieper, and a more popular book, ``The Decline of
Pleasure,'' by Walter Kerr, theater critic for The New York Herald
Tribune and later for The Times. Both authors admirably distinguish
between escapes that afford authentic leisure and genuine pleasure
-- reading a good book, for example -- and those mere diversions
that simply distract us from our workaday world, like building a
garage on our day off. Both of these books generously employ
another defining human characteristic, not developed nearly enough
in Tuan's otherwise praiseworthy book: the capacity to judge. If we
are going to look in the right direction, we will have to do more
than look. We will have to assess, evaluate and discriminate. There
is no escaping that.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Francis I. Kane teaches philosophy at Salisbury State University
in Maryland. His most recent book is ``Neither Beasts Nor Gods:
Civic Life and the Public Good.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
