<HEADER>
A9082 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS &LR;      11-19 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_STUDIES COULD ADVANCE HEPATITIS C TREATMENT  
 _STUDY SHOWS PROZAC FIGHTS PANIC DISORDER  
 _MAJOR LUNG SURGERY IS SMALL OPERATION  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Studies could advance hepatitis C treatment
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until now, there has been no truly effective treatment for
hepatitis C, a blood-borne virus that is spread in the same ways as
AIDS, and that is believed to infect about 4 million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   A drug called interferon helps in 40 percent of cases, but the
benefits are short-lived. Only 10 to 15 percent of patients remain
in remission, six months after treatment is stopped.
</P>
<P>
   But two studies published in the current New England Journal of
Medicine offer new hope. One, led by researchers at the Scripps
Clinic and Research Foundation in La Jolla, Calif., found that six
months after treatment, a combination of interferon and a drug
called ribavirin was 31 to 38 percent effective among patients
being treated for the first time. That's 3 to 5 times the response
rate for people getting interferon alone.
</P>
<P>
   The other study, led by researchers at the University of Florida
College of Medicine in Gainesville, found that six months after
treatment, the same combination was 49 percent effective in
patients who had relapsed after previous treatment. This is 10
times higher than treatment with interferon alone.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the studies represent an ``important advance,'' says
Dr. T. Jake Liang, chief of the liver diseases section at the
National Institute of Diabetes, Digestive, and Kidney Diseases,
part of the National Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   It is still not clear how long treatment should last. In the
California study, there was little difference in outcome whether
people were treated for six months or 12. But the studies are ``a
big step forward,'' Liang said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Study shows Prozac fights panic disorder
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's official: Prozac, like the antidepressants Zoloft and
Paxil, has now been shown to work against panic disorder, a
debilitating illness that affects 3 million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In a study led by Dr. David Michelson of Eli Lilly, the maker of
Prozac, the popular antidepressant proved safe and effective in
reducing panic attacks and symptoms of phobia, anxiety, and
depression in people with panic disorder, a syndrome in which a
person suffers repeated attacks of panic. The study is in this
month's American Journal of Psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate study published in the current Journal of the
American Medical Association, Brown University researchers showed
that Zoloft, already used for acute depression, is also effective
as an ongoing treatment for chronic depression.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Major lung surgery is small operation
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Minimally invasive surgery _ in which doctors operate through
one or more small incisions, often aided by tiny TV cameras in
fiber optic cables _ is clearly an idea whose time has come.
</P>
<P>
   But is it really possible to remove an entire, intact lung this
way and send the patient home the same day?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, says Dr. Eduardo R. Tovar, a thoracic surgeon at St. Jude
Medical Center in Fullerton, Calif., who describes his technique in
this month's issue of Chest, a journal of the American College of
Chest Physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, surgeons have used one long incision _ from the
shoulder blade, under the arm, around to the front _ to remove a
cancerous lung. In the last five years, they've also used minimally
invasive surgery, which involves four or five small incisions
between the ribs for viewing plus a 4-inch incision under the arm
through which the lung is removed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tovaro says he can remove a lung using only one small _
3-inch _ incision on the patient's side.
</P>
<P>
   In the five patients reported on _ he has also done four others
_ Tovar occasionally uses a miniature TV camera inserted through
the same incision to see ligaments that he needs to cut. He
anesthetizes nerves in the area by freezing.
</P>
<P>
   One patient went home the same day. Four others went home the
next morning. With standard minimally invasive surgery, patients
stay in the hospital five to seven days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an eye-opening article,'' says Dr. Joseph LoCicero,
chief of general thoracic surgery at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center in Boston, though it's unclear how many patients can
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   It ``boggled my mind,'' adds Dr. A. Jay Block, editor in chief
of the journal. But, he said, ``I doubt there are a whole lot of
surgeons who could do this at the moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9086 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TOBACCO-BOS &LR;      11-19 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO FOES CITE US CLAIM IN SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With much of the focus on the $4 billion that
Massachusetts could receive by joining the national tobacco
settlement, some antismoking advocates who oppose the deal
Wednesday raised an issue few have considered: The federal
government has a 50 percent claim on those funds.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement worked out with eight attorneys general,
tobacco companies would reimburse Massachusetts and the other
states for payments it made under the Medicaid program for
smoking-related illnesses. Half the funds for that program come
from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $4 billion figure is a lot but people don't understand
that half of the money belongs to the feds,'' said state Senator
Lois Pines, the Newton Democrat who engineered the change in state
law that opened up the state's suit against the tobacco industry.
``They paid half our bills, but nobody is mentioning that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, earlier this week
indicated that the federal government is under some obligation to
claim some of this money as its share of the state's Medicaid
costs. He told reporters, however, the Clinton administration may
be open to negotiating to make sure the money is used to battle
smoking among teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pines, a longtime Beacon Hill leader in the
antismoking movement, joined with the state's tobacco-control
coalition Wednesday in calling on Attorney General Scott
Harshbarger to reject the settlement because its public health
provisions are too weak.
</P>
<P>
   The antismoking leaders argue that Harshbarger's current case
against the tobacco industry, scheduled for trial in Middlesex
Superior Court in February, is one of the strongest in the nation
and the state should pursue it rather than settle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Massachusetts, we have a special law that gives us an
upper hand in court,'' Pines said. ``If we join this weak
settlement, our hands will be tied and our legal advantage will go
up in smoke. ... Let's not be bribed by cold, hard cash.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed national agreement worked out in New York last week
would provide $206 billion over the next 25 years to all the states
and would create some marketing restrictions on the industry.
Massachusetts would get $4 billion, or $7.6 billion when inflation
is factored in, over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The deal provides less money than the $368 billion national
tobacco settlement worked out last year, but killed by Congress
last June. The current agreement does not need congressional
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger, contending the industry was refusing to agree to
strict public health regulations and marketing restrictions, walked
out of the talks last August, saying he wanted to focus on the
state's court suit.
</P>
<P>
   But Harshbarger and all the 40 other states not at the
bargaining table have until Friday to decide whether to join the
settlement. Nationally and in Massachusetts, antismoking leaders
are calling on Harshbarger to reject it, arguing the Massachusetts
court case is the strongest one of the many that have been filed
against the industry.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources familar with the internal debate at the
attorney general's office, Harshbarger was Wednesday leaning
strongly toward accepting the settlement. He is also getting strong
advice from his top advisers to sign on to the settlement. A public
statement could come as early as today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 90 percent there to accepting it,'' said an individual
familar with the discussions. ``He just wants to make sure the
money is going to go for anti-smoking programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Cafasso, Harshbarger's press secretary, said the issue of
whether the state would lose half of its reimbursement is not
clear. He said President Clinton has indicated he will support any
efforts to protect the states from any seizure of the funds that
are reimbursed by cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that this is a battle that the states have clearly
won and won on their own and both Congress and the federal
government will recognize it is the fruit of state labor and state
labor only and should be allowed to stay with the states,'' Cafasso
said.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's decision on the settlement has far reaching
implications for the state. If he rejects the settlement but loses
in the courts, Massachusetts will lose billions of dollars,
including a $98 million upfront payment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
