<HEADLINE>
KRAFTS PURCHASE SAN JOSE CLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Kraft family believes in investing in professional
soccer. The Krafts Wednesday announced the purchase of the San Jose
Clash, their second Major League Soccer franchise, for more than
$25 million, five times the amount they invested in the Revolution
three years ago. The Miami Fusion expansion team had a $20 million
price last year, and Anschutz Sports Enterprises paid $26 million
for the Los Angeles Galaxy last month.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose operated under the direction of the MLS office in New
York in its first three years. An agreement to purchase the team
had been announced by former US Soccer Federation president Alan I.
Rothenberg and Dentsu Inc. of Japan, but the deal was called off
recently.
</P>
<P>
   The Clash, like the Revolution, has qualified for the MLS
playoffs only once. Its home field, Spartan Stadium, is owned by
San Jose State University and has a listed capacity of 19,166, but
was expanded to 31,683 for the MLS inaugural game April 6, 1996.
and has played host to US national team games. Average attendance
was 13,800 during the regular season, about the crowd expected for
last night's exhibition between the Clash and Toluca of Mexico's
first division. The field at Spartan Stadium, which also was home
to the Earthquakes of the North American Soccer League in the
1970s, had been smaller than accepted standards before being
expanded to 70 by 110 yards this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were under the assumption that Alan Rothenberg would be in
here pretty quickly, but that changed in the last week or so,'' a
Clash spokesman said. ``The Krafts saw a good opportunity and they
grabbed it. We have a solid organization, even though we haven't
done well on the field, and a great little stadium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
