<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEXY COD RENDER NORWAY'S NAVY IMPOTENT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Who says technology is king? In the stinging
cold sea waters that surround Norway, millions of codfish have
rendered some highly sophisticated sonar tracking equipment
essentially impotent.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by the Norwegian Defense Institute, the cod
constitute a bona-fide threat to the safety and security of
Norway's military because they emit ``grunt-like sounds'' every 80
seconds or so. The purpose of the grunts? For the same reason many
people put on a Frank Sinatra record, mix martinis and turn the
lights down low: They're in the mood for love.
</P>
<P>
   February and March in Norway are prime cod mating months. You
get enough horny fish emitting enough grunts, and you wreak havoc
on the Norwegian navy's underwater surveillance and navigation
systems. Nobody can tell the difference between a foreign submarine
and a pack of hormone-seething male codfish.
</P>
<P>
   Until they can figure out a way to distinguish the cod grunts
from the other noise, the scientists can only advise navy subs to
stay out of known spawning areas during peak mating season.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what John McCosker of the California Academy of
Sciences shared with me, the Norwegian navy might as well build
regular February and March furloughs into its long-range plans.
Male codfish don't just grunt at 80-second intervals, they dance,
growl and make ``escape sounds'' with their internal gas bladders.
</P>
<P>
   They may run deep, but they don't run silent.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only person in America who has read ``Cod, A
Biography of the Fish That Changed the World,'' McCosker gleaned
most of his cod-audio info from a 1961 treatise by British
researcher Vivien M. Brawn. Under the tutelage of Dr. H.O. Bull
(honest), Brawn studied cod mating habits at the Dove Marine
Laboratory of King's College at the University of Durham.
</P>
<P>
   The paper comes complete with an illustrated mating cycle that
depicts the male from his first raised median fin, through his
``courtship flaunting display,'' right into the climactic ventral
mount. But it is Brawn's prose that comes closer to explaining how
mating codfish could mess up sonar equipment.
</P>
<P>
   As McCosker noted in his fax, ``This is pretty racy stuff. I
looked through the literature and discovered that Brawn was never
seen or heard from again. She (or he) may have crossed the line
with this one.''
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt: ``Once the male had mounted dorsally, he immediately
slipped down one side of the female, still with his ventral surface
closely pressed against her body and clasping her with the pelvic
fins. The male came to lie in an inverted position below the female
with the ventral surfaces of both fish and their genital apertures
closely pressed together ... The combined movements of the tails
drove the pair round in a horizontal circle at the surface and
doubtless served to mix the eggs and sperm.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubtless.
</P>
<P>
   Brawn also observes that, while the male grunted during his
pre-spawn fin raise, tail wag and snout prod, ``No grunts were made
during the dorsal or ventral mounts or while the fish spawned.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards was a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Post-spawning ``the female swam down to the bottom and joined
the group of fish outside the male's territory. The male sometimes
became extremely aggressive ... and rushed at the group of
individual fish with many grunts.''
</P>
<P>
   Male humans have long been accused of going back to the locker
room to brag of their sexual exploits. Could the post-spawn cod
grunts be a variation on the same macho theme? If so, the Norwegian
navy might as well take the whole winter off.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
