A9094 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-CANNON-BOS &LR;      11-19 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-CANNON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANNON'S EXPANSION COULD MEAN A RETURN TO ITS GLORY DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANCONIA, N.H. _ Fifty years ago, it was the standard by which
real skiing mettle was measured. Some of the most prestigious ski
races in the country took place there, and its very name struck a
rather stately, stoic image.
</P>
<P>
   Today, despite being well back in the high-stakes game of fast
detatchable lifts, snowmaking and grooming, on-slope restaurants
and condos, Cannon Mountain is still a standard for serious skiers.
</P>
<P>
   But the area where the first aerial tram for skiers was built in
1938 hangs in the balance this season. Today at the Franconia Town
Hall, there will be a public hearing on a plan to completely
modernize Cannon and open up nearby Mittersill as another
state-owned area.
</P>
<P>
   The big change would come in capacity _ from 2,500 skiers to
about 6,000. That would mean increased revenues, which Cannon badly
needs if it is to remain viable.
</P>
<P>
   Sno-Engineering of Littleton, N.H., one of the premier
developers of ski areas and ski systems, has been hired to develop
a master plan at a cost of $24 million over 10 years, according to
Sno-Engineering consultant Walter Erlander.
</P>
<P>
   The first two years of the plan would focus on replacing ski
lifts and improving trails at Cannon, which would cost
approximately $6 million. Most of that work could be accomplished
in a single off-season, Erlanger told the Cannon Mountain Advisory
Committee in October.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago the state bought Mittersill, which had been out
of operation for several years. Expanding the lodge already on site
and upgrading the parking lots would cost another $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The final phase _ about $12 million, according to Erlander _
would involve installation of lifts and an expanded trail system at
Mittersill.
</P>
<P>
   The improvements to Cannon and Mittersill would be funded
largely from lease money coming in from Sunapee _ the other
state-owned area _ and from higher lift-ticket prices at Cannon as
the area improves.
</P>
<P>
   Through the last few decades Cannon has slipped from its glory
days when it introduced the aerial tram to US skiing. In the 1930s,
such tramways were used in nonskiing ways, such as during the
construction project on Mt. Rushmore by sculptor Gutzon Borglum.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1938 Alex Bright and Roland Peabody developed the first
skiers' tram, which, at 2,000 vertical feet, was the longest ski
lift in the country. In 1980 the original tram was replaced by the
present one, but not before it had hauled some seven million skiers
to the top of Cannon.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years, as nearby Loon and Waterville Valley
developed, along with several Vermont areas not far away, Cannon
did not keep up and _ except for its unalterably wonderful terrain
_ slipped into the second tier of ski areas.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, snow grooming on this mountain was done by a few
workers with shovels. Snowmaking was nonexistent, and the northwest
wind barreled through the valley, scouring the snow to a crusty
surface or as ice hard as porcelain.
</P>
<P>
   In legend, the trials were narrow, twisty, with natural fall
lines that pitched all over the place. The steeps were so tough
that only the expert skiers could survive the rigors.
</P>
<P>
   But, even before the proposed renovations, that mythology had
been widely exaggerated. A full 95 percent of its 150 skiable acres
is covered with snowmaking that is groomed, pulverized, and
regroomed when it turns icy. Perhaps retrofitting of the terrain
through the years has widened many of the trails, or perhaps they
were never as narrow as legend had them. Whatever, Cannon is as
perfectly accommodating to intermediates as it is to advanced
skiers _ albeit intermedates willing to ski attentively. This is
still no mountain for relaxed, back-seat cruising.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the summit is served by a fixed-grip quad that
is, when the weather is benign, a pleasant and quite beautiful lift
up over the vistas of the national forest, with views of Jefferson
and the other Presidentials. The tram handles 80 riders and takes
about six minutes to arrive at the top.
</P>
<P>
   If the area is not as brutal as some legend has it, there
certainly is plenty of challenging terrain. Upper Cannon is steep
and often firm because of the wind and altitude (4,100 feet). Upper
Hardscrabble has many of the same properties. But even casual auto
travelers coming along Route 3 have seen the famous lineup of
trails known affectionately as the ``front five.''
</P>
<P>
   They all look tough, but Zoomer, Polly's Folly, and Avalanche
are the expert-rated trails, and Zoomer has VW-sized moguls most of
the time. Rocket is rightly named, because it is a straight open
shot top to botom _ usually without bumps, as is its sidekick,
Gary's.
</P>
<P>
   The best cruising on Cannon is on long runs from the top,
including Upper Cannon, Vistaway, and Tramway. The very best is the
Profile Trail, a groomed fast cruiser that always has plenty of
snow.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed master plan would bring more lodging closer to the
mountain; but at this point, visitors to Cannon have about 5 miles
to drive to the nearest lodging. However, there is plenty _ more
than 12,000 beds _ both in the direction of Twin Mountain and
Bretton Woods, and the other way, south of Franconia Notch.
</P>
<P>
   Before the big changes, Cannon has one of the lowest ticket
prices for an area with such terrain _ $39 adult weekend, $28
midweek. Tuesdays and Thursdays are two-fer days _ two tickets for
$28. For information, call 603-823-5563.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
