<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-19 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ON CLINTON: THE REEL THING, PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The public says it is sick of the presidential
sex scandal. They're sick of Monica and Linda. They're sick of
Kenneth Starr. They're sick of Bill Clinton being bashed by the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Let the president get on with the real business of government,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   You know, like sending bombers toward Iraq, but stopping short
of the legal definition of war _ the one about cruise missiles
having inappropriate relations with civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Now wait a minute. If war is one of our other choices, how can
anyone say they're sick of this scandal?
</P>
<P>
   For a while I thought Clinton's reckless sexual acts and lying
would open the way to a right-wing takeover of government. Instead
the Republicans lost the last election big-time, and Newt Gingrich
was the one who had to leave office in shame.
</P>
<P>
   How can you hate a scenario like that?
</P>
<P>
   One or two more reports on Clinton's sex life, and liberal San
Francisco will be the new capital of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is the country that invented both the scarlet
letter and blue movies. It's only natural that Starr's harshly
high-minded testimony before the House Judiciary Committee should
follow the release of tawdry tapes secretly made by his informant,
bad-trip Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   We've heard Monica Lewinsky call her lover, our
commander-in-chief, ``Butthead.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't beat that, either for accuracy or entertainment. We
should revel in this.
</P>
<P>
   So you think this doesn't leave anything to the imagination? It
leaves lots to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The only voices we've heard on tape talking about sex are the
two women, the Wicked Witch of Washington and Buffy of Beverly
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The men, Starr and Clinton, the guys responsible for all this,
haven't been secretly taped. Or at least the tapes haven't been
released.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't fair. They get to talk about sex in rehearsed
presentations, fully aware they are being taped, so they don't talk
with their mouths full or say, ``So, it's like, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Clinton talked about sex, he said he wasn't. He said
he was just talking about inappropriate relations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has used language to mislead. Starr has used language to
lead us to his psyche.
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who censored expletives like ``crap'' from his
report, but left in four-letter words for the male sexual organ. I
don't know what Freud would say about that, but I'm sure the
phrases ``anal-retentive'' and ``fixated'' would come up.
</P>
<P>
   Starr deserves the Tripp tape treatment. What do his phone
conversations with his assistant prosecutors sound like? Just
looking at Starr's Mr. Toad smile, I imagine it isn't typical boy
talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that poopy-head,'' we can imagine Starr saying
after the election. ``We had all the doo-doo on him, and yet he
beats the pucky out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he'd probably sound like a tricky prig.
</P>
<P>
   The big question about Clinton, of course, is what he sounds
like when he's doing the Alexander Graham Bell boogie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet his phone sex is pretty cursory,'' my wife said. ``He
probably doesn't do any of the talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he put Monica on hold when a big contributor called? Did he
put her on speaker phone so he could eat a Big Mac at the same
time? Linda Tripp managed to slurp dinner on her own tape, while
Monica wailed and wept.
</P>
<P>
   Did Bill say ``Thank you'' or ``Goodbye''? Did he say ``Was it
good for you?'' Maybe he said, ``I'll get back to you on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is a complex and verbally adept man. He adjusts his
message to his audience. He can talk like a sensitive guy to women,
and talk locker-room talk with Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   That's another tape I want to hear. What do those guys talk
about when they're out in that golf cart on Martha's Vineyard?
</P>
<P>
   Bill: ``I think I'm beginning to get a crush on Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   Vernon: ``Well, she's very crushable.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   That's girl talk. That's the kind of thing Monica and Linda
said. When guys talk about their affairs with women, they tend to
use shallow physical adjectives rather than deep emotional
adjectives like ``crushable.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, though, I imagine Vernon said, ``Man, we've got to
get you out of this (bleep).''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's wife probably said that at one point, too.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wants to hear tapes of Bill's and Hillary's
conversations. However, if the bug had been put in a lamp, it would
have been broken. Over his head.
</P>
<P>
   All I can think of is what Marine Corps language might sound
like in Wellesley diction. Or the hot and lathered forgiveness that
follows.
</P>
<P>
   David Mamet probably could invent that. But I want to hear it
for real.
</P>
<P>
   The public needs to know. We know too much now not to know it
all. My president, right or wrong, and right out loud.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
