<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9098 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-HILLARY-ART-B     11-19 1629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-HILLARY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIR EDMUND HILLARY'S VIEW FROM THE SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He rep-re-sents the last, if not lost, generation of world-class
explorers, 20th-century adventurers for whom the ends of the earth
were mere departure points for measuring what the human body _ and
human spirit _ is capable of enduring.
</P>
<P>
   With his 80th birthday comfortably in sight, Sir Edmund Hillary,
the first Westerner to reach the summit of Mount Everest, is a
living deity on two continents and a towering presence wherever he
roams _ in the shadow of the approaching millennium, the closest
approximation we have, arguably, to Winston Churchill, Charles
Lindbergh, and Jimmy Stewart all rolled into one.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hillary, who passed through Boston on a fund-raising mission
earlier this week, seems oddly uninterested in resting on his
considerable laurels. The man who conquered Everest in 1953 (along
with legendary Sherpa guide Tenzing Norgay) and was knighted by
Britain's Queen Elizabeth for his efforts, who braved Antarctica in
the late '50s and the remotest reaches of the Ganges two decades
later, continues his lifelong quest to expand the horizons of all
humankind _ while insisting that he never set out to become a hero,
the renewed interest in all things Everest today notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media automatically turned us into heroic figures,''
remarked Hillary, speaking on Tuesday to an audience at Grand
Circle Travel in Boston. ``I think Tenzing may well have been one,
because he came from extremely modest beginnings and had great
courage and determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never, never regarded myself as a hero, though,'' Hillary
said, untainted by a tone of false modesty. ``I was just an
enthusiastic mountaineer who wanted to be the first, if possible,
to reach the summit of great mountains. And perhaps take a few
risks in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Having failed to ``destroy my public persona,'' Hillary added
with a chuckle, ``in the end I came to accept it. Because if I
didn't, I could not move on.''
</P>
<P>
   And move on he has. Hillary _ a small mountain of a man with
bushy eyebrows, ruddy red cheeks, and vestiges of the boyish grin
that once flashed around the world from the very top of the planet
_ maintains a punishing travel schedule, accompanied by his second
wife, June. (Hillary's first wife and daughter died in a plane
crash in Nepal in 1977.)
</P>
<P>
   Based in New Zealand, where Hillary was born in 1919 to an
Auckland beekeeper, the couple spends eight months a year on the
road, with April penciled in for Nepal. From 1985 to 1990, Hillary
served as New Zealand's ambassador to India, Bangladesh, and Nepal.
No diplomat who ever landed in New Delhi was more beloved than
Hillary was during his 4 1/2 years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Hillarys' time these days is spent raising funds and
awareness for his Himalayan Trust foundation. Established more than
30 years ago, the trust has built 26 schools, 13 health centers,
and two hospitals for the Sherpa people of the Himalayas, one of 50
ethnic groups native to Nepal; famous for their adaptation to high
altitudes, the Sherpas are Tibetan by origin and Buddhist by
religious preference. The trust's current focus is a
teacher-training program designed to help staff the Nepalese
schools built by Hillary's indefatigable philanthropy, one facet of
a post-mountaineering career that has also embraced
environmentalism, conservation, and diplomacy. In Washington this
week, the Smithsonian Institution awarded Hillary its James
Smithson Bicentennial Medal for his humanitarian efforts in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the more remote schools, the level of education is nowhere
near what it could be,'' Hillary explained in a private interview
prior to his slide show for employees of Grand Circle, a major
benefactor of the teacher-training program. ``We expected to have
30 to 40 teachers our first year. We had 180 instead, so already it
has been a great success.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he considers his work in Nepal some form of repayment
for a lifelong debt, Hillary nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel not only a great friendship with the Sherpa people,''
he said, ``but also a deep appreciation for what they've done for
all mountaineers and trekkers. If you ask them what they want, they
mention health care and education facilities. So we try to help
them. Rarely do we go into an area and tell them what they should
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the interview turned in the direction of Everest,
which, owing to Jon Krakauer's best-selling book (``Into Thin
Air'') and David Breashears's breathtaking IMAX film is back in the
public consciousness to a degree rivaling any period since
Hillary's ascent. In both cases, book and film, Everest's capacity
to claim lives, not just elevate them, serves as the dramatic
centerpiece. Eight people died on the mountain during the
calamitous May 1996 storm witnessed by both author and filmmaker.
Hillary, never one to downplay the danger involved, has been
critical of what he sees as the overcommerialization of
high-altitude mountaineering. And when an authority like Hillary
speaks, the professional climbing community listens.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the current fascination has to do with the disasters
that have occurred,'' Hillary said, seated alongside his wife.
``The fact that everything coincided _ the film team, Krakauer, the
storm _ brought Everest to the forefront of public interest. To me,
the Everest film was quite exciting, particularly the helicopter
shots. It was not quite like I remember it _ '' he laughed heartily
``because Tenzing and I were at ground level, naturally. Navigating
ice fields offers a different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really the lucky ones,'' Hillary continued. ``We had
to do everything ourselves: establish the route, battle our way up
the ice cliffs and across the crevasses, make our way high up the
mountain. It was up to us to do it all. Nowadays a lot of these
commercial expeditions are really conducted tours. The people who
go up Everest never set foot on snow that doesn't already have a
footprint on it. They climb up fixed ropes and on aluminum ladders.
There are still dangers, of course, but it's not quite like solving
a monumental problem on your own.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Hillary's historic climb, approximately 700 people have
reached the top of Everest. Another 150 have died making the
attempt. To join a modern Everest expedition, a climber who meets
the basic physical requirements needs little high-mountaineering
experience _ but plenty of cash. Paying $65,000 or more to be
escorted up Everest strikes Hillary as a formula for disaster, and
he has been unafraid to say so. Among the targets of his criticism
was his friend Rob Hall, the famed New Zealand climber who led
Krakauer's 1996 expedition and perished in the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had argued with Hall about the overcommercialization issue,
and obviously we disagreed about this,'' said Hillary. ``But when
you take along people with very little mountaineering experience
who have paid all that money, there's a great determination for
them to get their money's worth. So Rob may have pushed things when
he knew all too well not to. I'd been forecasting some sort of
disaster under these circumstances, so it did not altogether
surprise me when it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   For a year or so afterward, Hillary observed, the number of
expeditions permitted on Everest was cut back. That trend has
reversed itself, however, despite Hillary lobbying the Nepalese
government to restrict access. Now instead of two or three climbing
groups per season there are as many as 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nepalese collect $10,000 per climber,'' Hillary noted.
``At seven climbers per expedition, that's a lot of US dollars. I'm
afraid the money is more important to them than the welfare of the
climbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he ever truly afraid for his own life during his many
expeditions into the wild?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I've been scared to death hundreds of times,'' replied
Hillary. ``I've fallen down crevasses and been in avalanches, seen
some filthy weather and exposed places. But I happen to believe
that fear can be quite stimulating too. It helps you take a
disadvantage and turn it into an advantage. When I hear someone
says he's setting off on an adventure with great confidence he'll
be successful, I ask, why on earth is he going at all? Why not try
something he's not so confident about? That's certainly been my own
philosophy over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon his return from Everest, Hillary later told his audience,
British physiologist Dr. Roger Bannister _ the man who broke the
four-minute-mile barrier as a runner _ invited the mountaineer to
his clinic for a series of tests. Hillary had been feasting on
smoked salmon and champagne for a week, he recalled. When Bannister
was finished doing the tests, he looked at Hillary and said,
``Well, I don't know how you did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary still finds Bannister's pronouncement most amusing. The
man who stands and applauds a new chapter in Himalayan
mountaineering history pride _ symbolized by the record-setting
Everest climb this year by Kaji Sherpa, Tenzing Norgay's spiritual
heir _ remains circumspect about his own accomplishments. If John
Glenn can return to space, it was suggested to Hillary, might he
not yet have mountains to climb?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at my stage of life, no,'' he said, shaking his head.
``But if I thought I was fit enough, and the opportunity presented
itself, I would go up into space, no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He winked at Lady Hillary, who smiled back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a rocket,'' she said with a sigh. ``Like a rocket.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
