<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9106 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-PEMEX-ART-BOS &LR;      11-19 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PEMEX-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO GROANS UNDER WEIGHT OF STATE OIL BEHEMOTH PEMEX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A map is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ When President Lazaro Cardenas seized control of
Mexico's oil supply from greedy American and European companies in
1938, he was considered a hero by his proud but downtrodden
countrymen. From that one decree to nationalize the petroleum
industry, oil became Mexico's lifeblood, and a state-controlled
organization called Petroleos Mexicanos, better known as Pemex,
became its sole legal guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years later, Pemex's image is anything but heroic.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the company's political and economic ties to the
government have made it a haven for patronage and inefficiency that
has caused significantly higher prices for consumers. Many citizens
who once supported the idea of a nationally controlled oil industry
now say they are growing weary of subsidizing an increasingly
costly bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, we have been told that our political sovereignty
depends on petroleum, but that's not true anymore,'' said Miguel
Garcia Reyes, a professor at Colegio de Mexico who specializes in
energy and oil studies.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the Mexican government announced last
Friday that it would raise gasoline prices 15 percent to about
$1.60 a gallon to cover budget shortfalls and lower revenues earned
this year by Pemex. Over the last four years, the price of gasoline
in Mexico has increased more than 300 percent _ at a time when
world prices are near their lowest in a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   The gas hike was the last straw for Mario de la Rosa Vega, a
Mexico City taxi driver who must fill up his boxy sedan every other
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are one of the biggest oil countries in the world, but we
pay so much money for gasoline,'' said de la Rosa. ``This is the
price that ordinary Mexicans pay for being prisoners to Pemex.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Pemex has outlasted other monopolies in Mexico.
Telephones, railroads, and electricity, all once considered vital
to the country's survival, have been privatized or opened to the
free market. Even Cardenas's own Institutional Ruling Party, or
PRI, which has won every presidential election since 1920, now
shares power with an opposition-led Congress and with several
governors and mayors who belong to other parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many things have changed in technology, economics, and
society,'' Garcia added. ``I'm not saying we just sell off all of
Pemex, but it's time for a new model.''
</P>
<P>
   The current model allows Pemex to act and look much like a
Fortune 500 corporation. It has a director and board of directors.
The company's headquarters is in a modern, 48-story skyscraper. The
behemoth is carved into four main areas: exploration and
production, natural gas, petrochemicals, and refineries. All of the
nation's gas stations bear the Pemex name and sell its fuel.
</P>
<P>
   But Pemex functions more like a public agency. The director
reports to the federal energy secretary and often answers directly
to the president. Jobs and contracts are often doled out to those
most connected to the ruling party. And much of the company's
yearly revenues are funneled into the central treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The government has benefited most from this arrangement. More
than one-third of its roughly $100 billion in yearly revenues comes
from Pemex oil fields, royalties, taxes, and fuel sales. With so
much dependence on Pemex funds, experts say, the government has
done little to diversify its tax base despite the growth of
manufacturing and service jobs in the country over the last twenty
years.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Pemex relies heavily on government budget
allocations for much of its investment in maintenance, refineries,
and new drilling _ capital projects that for years have lagged
behind the United States, Venezuela and other oil-exporting
countries.
</P>
<P>
   This year, because of falling oil prices and weaker demand
around the world, Pemex has been forced to cut exports to about 1.3
million barrels per day and slash about $1 billion out of its $11.5
billion budget. At a press conference last Thursday, Adrian Lajous,
the company's director, announced that Pemex had lost $460 million
in the third quarter and that net profits were 36 percent lower
than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the administration of President Ernesto Zedillo
released its 1999 budget, in which it called for the 15 percent
gasoline price hike.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last 10 years, Venezuela, Argentina and Brazil have
changed their petroleum industry to a more open system and they've
benefited through lower prices,'' said George Baker, director of
Mexico Energy Intelligence, a Houston-based consulting group. ``If
Mexico had an open market there are plenty of companies who could
sell their gas for less'' than what they're paying now, he added.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the costs stemming from Pemex's inefficiency and
the country's refusal to open up its oil market, critics point to a
1995 decision by the Zedillo administration to sell more heavy
crude oil to the United States and import gasoline for domestic
use. Using current prices, Mexico sells each barrel to the United
States for about $11, while each barrel of imported gasoline is
sold back to Mexico for $60.
</P>
<P>
   For now, neither government officials nor Pemex directors are
willing to consider privatizing the monopoly, mostly because of its
financial importance to the budget and for fear of angering the
company's powerful, 114,000-member labor union with crucial
presidential elections less than two years away.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials do, however, pledge to make Pemex leaner and
more competitive by seeking more foreign investors and selling
non-core pieces of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, it began a $400 million project with Shell to
increase heavy crude oil processing at a plant in Texas. Also in
1995, the Mexican Congress opened up the national gas distribution
market to private competition. Last year, Pemex awarded a $1.6
billion contract to Korean and German firms to renovate a refinery
in the northern city of Monterrey. And two weeks ago, officials
said the company would sell off much its aging fleet of marine
tankers.
</P>
<P>
   But Pemex directors aknowledge they will have to raise more than
$7 billion in additional foreign capital to finance much-needed
programs over the next two years, especially to modernize its
refineries.
</P>
<P>
   And if Pemex is to preserve its standing with ordinary Mexicans,
it will also likely have to clean up its environmental act in areas
where it has been accused of ruining fields and polluting
neighborhoods where it has refineries and pipelines, such as the
states of Tabasco and Veracruz and in parts of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are those who believe that despite the pain of
higher prices and the costs associated with maintaining a
less-competitive oil company, Pemex's monopoly won't end until the
PRI monopoly on the presidency is broken, which could happen in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leading candidates, Vicente Fox, of the pro-business
National Action Party, has said that if he wins he'll dismantle
Pemex.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible candidate is Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the son of
Pemex's creator, who now belongs to the center-left Party of the
Democratic Revolution and is Mexico City's mayor. He hasn't said
what, if anything, he would do about Pemex.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a ironic, wouldn't it?'' said one American oil
company executive based in Mexico. ``If he were smart, he would see
that Pemex isn't helping the poor anymore. It's hurting them. His
father wouldn't stand for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
