<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-BISHOPS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC BISHOPS AFFIRM `NEW MILLENIUM' COMMITMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative NIRDI
RELIS in New York at (800) 972-3550 or (212) 499-3333, or fax her
at (212) 499-3382.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    WASHINGTON -- The National Conference of Catholic Bishops has
elected to its top posts a Spanish-speaking bishop from the
Southwest and an African-American bishop, both of whom have been
strongly committed to the cause of the poor and the marginalized.
 &HT;    Bishop Joseph Fiorenza of Galveston-Houston was elected
president for three years. He is the first NCCB president from the
South or Southwest.
 &HT;    As vice president, the conference elected Bishop Wilton Gregory,
the first African-American bishop to reach that position, making it
likely he will be elected president at the end of Fiorenza's term.
 &HT;    Both are deeply committed to fighting injustice and poverty and
have plans to get millions of middle-class Catholics involved in a
''Jubilee Pledge'' for the New Millennium, to help fulfill Jesus'
pledge ''to bring glad tidings to the poor ... to proclaim liberty
to captives and recovery of sight to the blind, to let the
oppressed go free.''
 &HT;    As the son of an immigrant barber from Sicily, Fiorenza, 67, has
''a heart for those who came to this country to make a better life
for their families,'' said Father Troy Gately, vice chancellor of
the new president's diocese. ''He has a rock-solid devotion to
those who are marginalized: the poor and immigrants.''
 &HT;    For example, as a young priest he joined Martin Luther King Jr.
in his 1965 Selma civil rights march. Shortly after becoming bishop
of Galveston-Houston in 1984, he launched a city-wide campaign for
the homeless. He got leaders of other denominations to join him in
creating a nonprofit housing corporation that has built many
housing units for the poor. He has fought for a higher minimum wage
and raised millions for the disadvantaged to attend Catholic
schools.
 &HT;    When Father Wilton Gregory was named an auxiliary bishop in
Chicago, he was only 35 years old and America's youngest Catholic
bishop. Father Bob Byrne, a friend for 20 years, says Gregory is
''very personable, extremely bright, with a fantastic memory of
anything he has ever read or seen, a person is as comfortable with
a cardinal as he was with my parents, who were farmers.''
 &HT;    As bishop of the largely rural diocese of Belleville in southern
Illinois since 1994, Gregory, now 50, created a largely lay
Diocesan Pastoral Council, and gave it substantial responsibility.
It created a Poverty Services Committee that has developed plans to
help the poor ''move from welfare to work.'' Volunteers are being
recruited and trained as mentors and tutors.
 &HT;    The Council identified ways that lay people could help pastor
and spearheaded a $12 million campaign to strengthen parish
councils and leadership development of youth.
 &HT;    In 1979 Catholic bishops published a paper on racism and vowed
to help eradicate discrimination in American society. ''Twenty
years later, hope in the possibility of achieving that great goal
has diminished, not only in the Church but also throughout
society,'' said a new NCCB report. ''Sadly, many people of color
see the Church as a white racist institution.''
 &HT;    The election of Bishop Gregory is one indication the Catholic
hierarchy is committed to change.
 &HT;    More important, Catholic bishops adopted a pastoral letter,
''Everyday Christianity: To Hunger and Thirst for Justice.'' It
states that ''Every believer is called to serve `the least of
these,' to `hunger and thirst for justice,' to be a `peacemaker.'
It outlines how to do so by encouraging every Catholic to sign a
''Jubilee Pledge for Charity, Justice and Peace, a Catholic
Commitment for the New Millennium.'' As disciples of Jesus,
individuals will pledge to:
 &HT;    --Pray regularly for greater justice and peace.
 &HT;    --Learn more about Catholic social teaching and its call to
protect human life, stand with the poor, and care for creation.
 &HT;    --Reach across boundaries of religion, race, ethnicity, gender
and disabling conditions.
 &HT;    --Live justly in family life, school, work, the marketplace and
the political arena.
 &HT;    --Serve those who are poor and vulnerable, sharing more time and
talent.
 &HT;    --Give more generously to those in need at home and abroad.
 &HT;    --Advocate for public policies that protect human life, promote
human dignity, preserve God's creation and build peace.
 &HT;    --Encourage others to work for greater charity, justice and
peace.
 &HT;    The Jubilee Pledge, which will be distributed in every parish,
is meant to motivate 61 million Catholics, who are mostly middle
class to prosperous, to consider how they are now serving the poor
and working for justice, and find specific ways to take new steps
to ''ACT on the pledge.''
 &HT;    In electing Bishops Fiorenza and Gregory, Catholic bishops could
not have chosen better men to lead this noble cause, a new drive to
help Catholics live the faith they profess.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Mike McManus
