<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-DEATH-$ADV22-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WOMAN'S DEATH HAUNTS SHERIFF IN TEXAS OIL COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 22)   (EDs: With MYSTERY-DEATH-SIDE)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROY BRAGG  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKELLYTOWN, Texas _ Three years ago, the everyday existence of
the conservative Texas Panhandle was peeled back to expose an
unlikely secret.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Born Howell's body was found slumped forward, face
first, against the base of a twisted oak tree in a Panhandle oil
patch ravine.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old mother of three boys was found fully clothed,
resting on her elbows and knees. She had not been robbed. There
were two gunshot wounds to her chest and a 9mm semi-automatic
pistol was lying on the ground by her side. There were no
footprints leading to or from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The Nov. 16, 1995, death of Cynthia Howell had the unmistakable
signs of a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   But to Loren Brand, an author, former rock musician and the
sheriff of Carson County, something didn't seem right.
</P>
<P>
   Two gunshot wounds, but no pool of blood. No footprints, not
even Howell's. Shell casings in the wrong places.
</P>
<P>
   As Brand, a veteran lawman who has held a badge in two states,
studied the evidence, it was obvious to him that Howell had been
slain. He may have found the motive hours after Howell's body was
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of making his routine checks to put the case to
rest, Brand stumbled upon a subplot: Cynthia Howell and her
husband, Danny Howell, it seemed, had a secret, one they shared
with other couples scattered throughout the quiet burgs and farming
communities of the Northwest Texas Bible Belt.
</P>
<P>
   They were swingers _ couples who swap sexual partners.
</P>
<P>
   A spouse typically is considered a major suspect when a mate is
slain. But a polygraph examination cleared Danny Howell, witnesses
can pinpoint his whereabouts the day of his wife's death, and
there's not a shred of evidence that links him to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Brand and Howell, 42, differ on what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Howell, who co-owned a nursery business in nearby Spearman with
his wife, is adamant that her death was a suicide, but said he felt
responsible for it nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   She took the ultimate way out, Howell said, because he didn't
leave her any choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something that got out of hand,'' he said. ``We were
playing with fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand said there were too many inconsistencies to call Cynthia
Howell's death a case of suicide. But he has no leads, no suspects
and no new ideas. The official ruling in the death is ``suspicious
and undetermined.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be easy to rule this as a suicide and drop it,'' Brand
said. ``But that wouldn't be right. I don't want to hurt Danny
Howell or his family. But I've got to find out what happened to
that woman. That's my job. And I'm going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre saga began at about 2 p.m. on Nov. 16, 1995, when a
rancher called the Carson County Sheriff's Office in nearby
Panhandle to report seeing an abandoned car, a 1989 rose and mauve
Olds 98, parked on his land.
</P>
<P>
   Rugged and ugly, the ranch typifies the terrain on this end of
the five-county Panhandle Oil Field. It's a nightmarish landscape
of scorched hills covered with a spotty patchwork of creosote and
noxious weeds. The hills are cut by a jagged network of dusty
ravines and crisscrossed by a serpentine string of dirt roads that
connect the weathered oil well pump jacks.
</P>
<P>
   Brand's deputies traced the car to Spearman, a town of 3,200
located 40 miles north near the Oklahoma border, and ultimately to
Danny Howell.
</P>
<P>
   Howell, who rushed to the Sheriff's Office as soon as he was
called, told deputies that the couple had argued earlier that day
and that his wife had left angry. He also said his wife was
diabetic and might be in some medical danger if she didn't get her
insulin shot.
</P>
<P>
   By 2:45 p.m., Brand's deputies and rescue crews had begun a land
and aerial search. It took nearly three hours for a helicopter crew
to find Howell's body.
</P>
<P>
   When Brand arrived at the scene, he noticed a few things
immediately. Women tend to dress up before they take their life,
Brand said. They rarely use guns, preferring to take a drug
overdose.
</P>
<P>
   And women who leave behind small children tend to leave notes
with very detailed instructions about how to care for their
children, the sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Howell left no note. She was dressed plainly _ jeans,
shirt, Windbreaker, sneakers _ and without makeup. When she was
found, she was still wearing her square-framed glasses.
</P>
<P>
   And she used a gun, which her husband had purchased years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   If Howell had turned the gun on herself, the shell casings would
have ejected to her left, Brand said. Instead, they were found to
her right.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the wounds. One bullet just wounded her,
entering her left breast and exiting through her back. The fatal
shot, fired through her chest, severed her pulmonary aorta,
according to the autopsy by Lubbock coroner Sparks Veasey.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of person shoots themselves in the chest, then has
the presence of mind to say `Oh, I didn't kill myself. I need to
shoot myself again?''' Brand said. ``She was either very dedicated
to the idea of killing herself or she had some help.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The autopsy showed some blood had collected in her chest, but
the ground underneath her was clean.
</P>
<P>
   Brand said investigators dug 7 inches down and tested the soil
but could find no trace of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the absence of footprints, Howell's shoes, socks and the
bottom of her jeans were clean _ no dust, grass burrs, or cactus
needles _ even though she was found nearly two miles from where her
car was parked. The terrain between the two points would have left
some trace on her shoes or socks, Brand said.
</P>
<P>
   Even more puzzling: There were no prints anywhere on the weapon,
the bullet or the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Howell wasn't wearing gloves, nor were there any gloves
found anywhere in the field.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest surprise came when Brand and deputies went to
the locked Oldsmobile and found Howell's purse.
</P>
<P>
   First, he found a brochure bearing typed text and two
photocopied pictures. The text was a personal ad, written
ostensibly by a New Mexico couple, both in their 30s or 40s, eager
to meet like-minded couples in the Eastern New Mexico-West Texas
area. One picture showed a smiling woman wearing an unbuttoned
shirt. The other photo was a full frontal nude shot of a man.
</P>
<P>
   Next Brand found a half-dozen unopened condom packages.
</P>
<P>
   Then came handwritten notes bearing the first names of couples
and phone numbers. Brand reached a man in Fort Worth who
reluctantly spoke to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very evasive, but he finally says they were involved in
a `swing' group,'' Brand said. ``As worldly as I am, I thought it
was a square-dance group or a clogging deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the guy told me it was a sexual activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand sat back in his chair and ran it through his mind: Danny
and Cynthia Howell. Small-town business owners. Parents. Happily
married 18 years. Swingers.
</P>
<P>
   But no answers on the death of Cynthia Howell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
