<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-DEATH-SIDE-$ADV22-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCARS REMAIN FROM A TRAGIC MARITAL DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 22)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROY BRAGG  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANHANDLE, Texas _ Police scanner traffic crackled in the
background as Danny Howell and his teen-aged son sat silently in
the Carson County sheriff's office.
</P>
<P>
   It was near dusk on a Nov. 16, 1995, and there had been no sign
of his wife, Cynthia Howell, for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Her abandoned car was found parked on a roadside in a isolated
oil field 16 miles away. Deputies and rescue workers had combed the
field all afternoon looking for clues.
</P>
<P>
   For two hours, a solemn Howell said nothing and knew nothing.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:48 p.m., there was a flurry of radio chatter. Howell
couldn't make out what they were saying, but it was obvious
something had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew,'' he said in a recent interview. ``By then, I already
knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, deputies pulled Howell to the side with
the news that his wife's body had been found at the bottom of a
ravine in a far corner of the oil field where the car was parked.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Howell, 36, died from two gunshot wounds to the chest.
Though her husband said the death was a suicide, the official
ruling is that the death was ``suspicious and undetermined.''
</P>
<P>
   Howell, now 42, broke down where he stood. His sister had to
help him of the sheriff's office and into her car.
</P>
<P>
   That night, at the family's home in Spearman, a distraught
Howell stood in the middle of the kitchen and wept. Suddenly, with
his family looking on, he pulled a carving knife out of a drawer
and plunged it into his own gut.
</P>
<P>
   He was flown to an Amarillo hospital. The knife didn't penetrate
very far and missed important arteries and organs. Howell was
released after two days to attend his wife's funeral at the Baptist
church.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after that day, the stomach gash has long since
healed, but another wound remains open.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Loren Brand says discrepancies in the evidence _ no
footprints at the scene, no blood on the ground, no fingerprints on
the gun, and the presence of two wounds _ make suicide an unlikely
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Howell chafed at the suggestion that his wife was
murdered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad enough that I lost my wife,'' he said. ``The sheriff
doesn't want to turn it loose. There's not enough blood. Or the gun
laid down wrong. It doesn't matter to me. I know what I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as the thought pains Danny Howell, he said his wife
probably killed herself after a weekend trip to a Dallas swinging
venue where couples swap sexual partners. That trip ended in a
vicious argument that morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie to you and tell you that I don't think
about it, because I still do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Howell was uncomfortable talking about the couple's sexual
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were country hicks going to try something different,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He would not discuss exactly what happened in Dallas that
started the fight between them, saying that she crossed an
emotional line at some point while they were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hurt me,'' he said. ``I saw her with another man. It
killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   They argued on the drive back to Spearman.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 16, the morning after the trip to Dallas where their
lives apparently unraveled, Danny Howell said he woke up mad.
</P>
<P>
   He went into the kitchen and there was a cup of coffee, as there
was every morning, by his chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted to make it up to me,'' he said of the gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his temper blinded him. He looked up and saw Cynthia Howell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said ... I never, ever will forgive you for what you did,'''
he said. ``She said, `You don't mean that, do you?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say nothing,'' he recalled in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   She got up and left the room, then the house.
</P>
<P>
   It was 9 a.m. Two hours later, she called Howell at the couple's
nursery business. He recounted this conversation with his wife:
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are you?'' Howell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too late for that,'' she said calmly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I guess it is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke with a sense of finality, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to cremate me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Howell said nothing. There was a pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny,'' she said. ``Take care of the boys. I'll miss you.''
</P>
<P>
   Howell said that was the last he ever heard from his wife.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
