<SLUG> BC-FILMS-GODS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GODS AND MONSTERS' HAS MUCH TO RECOMMEND IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are so many remarkable moments in the unforgettable ``Gods
and Monsters'' that it's difficult to know where to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Director and writer Bill Condon bases his film on a
fictionalized account (Christopher Bram's novel, ``The Father of
Frankenstein'') of the months before movie director James Whale was
found dead, floating in his swimming pool, in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Through flashbacks, Condon touches upon complex psychological
themes, painting stirring contrasts and parallels between the
personal demons Whale (Ian McKellen) could never exorcise in life _
and the monster he immortalized on celluloid.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hot Los Angeles summer and Whale has long retired from
making movies. Though he gave the world such notable classics as
``Hell's Angels,'' ``Waterloo Bridge,'' ``The Invisible Man,''
``The Man In The Iron Mask'' and ``Show Boat,'' he is only
remembered for his 1931 horror classic, ``Frankenstein,'' and its
sequel, ``Bride of Frankenstein'' (``The others were done by
hacks,'' sniffs Whale).
</P>
<P>
   Into his idle existence, for he lives alone with his German
housekeeper, Hanna (Lynn Redgrave), comes a young gardener, Clayton
Boone (Brendan Fraser), who befriends the old man and poses for him
as a sketch model.
</P>
<P>
   Boone doesn't know at first that Whale supposedly was drummed
out of Hollywood because of a sex scandal: he was openly gay. But
Whale later tells him he was a pariah because ``The Road Back,''
his quintessential film statement about war, was taken away from
him and recut by the studio and, when it failed at the box office,
Whale took the fall instead of the director who replaced him.
</P>
<P>
   A strange, compelling relationship develops between the erudite
bon vivant Englishman, and the young, hunky and heterosexual Boone,
who is barely schooled.
</P>
<P>
   They find a common ground in war. Whale was an officer in ``the
great war,'' losing his first love to it, and Boone enlisted in the
Marines to escape his abusive childhood. They're both running away
from their pasts and that initially bonds them. But Whale, haunted
by frail health and too much spare time, discovers the pain of his
early years (``it runs all over me,'' he complains) cannot be
ignored for long.
</P>
<P>
   Condon's extraordinary look at the last chapter in a forgotten
film artist's life is filled with great beauty and sadness. It's a
tinged, fading portrait of a man and his legacy, handed down to a
new friend _ because the old ones are all dead or have gone away.
</P>
<P>
   Condon shoots with great style and a wonderful eye for texture _
the camera sways and swoons over Whale, creating an eerie parallel
to scenes in his own films. Like Billy Wilder's great expose of
Hollywood, ``Sunset Boulevard,'' Condon's film captures the
difficult emotional void of how it feels to be forgotten after once
being on top of the world; Whale's house is an echo of empty
footsteps and shadows.
</P>
<P>
   McKellen, Redgrave and Fraser are all extraordinary. McKellen,
with his expressive face and fluttery hands, perfectly conveys the
agony that ultimately overtakes Whale. The movie belongs to him _
and it may be the part for which he's remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Though Whale could never escape the trauma brought by war, he
continually tried to expurgate the monsters lurking in his soul,
mind and heart by melding them into his art. In the end, they
destroyed him.
</P>
<P>
   Gods and Monsters. Directed and written by Bill Condon. Cast:
Ian McKellen, Brendan Fraser, Lynn Redgrave, Lolita Davidovitch,
David Dukes. Lions Gate Films. 105 minutes. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
