<SLUG> BC-FILM-CELEBRITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRANAGH IS IRRITATING AS ALLEN IMITATOR IN `CELEBRITY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What will Woody Allen's place in our cultural history be? He's
taught us about relationships (``Annie Hall''), morality and ethics
(``Crimes and Misdemeanors'') and murder (``Manhattan Murder
Mystery''). He's made us laugh over family and infidelity (``Hannah
and Her Sisters'') and cry at a mother's desperate suicide
(``Interiors'').
</P>
<P>
   The comedy ``Celebrity,'' as one characters tidily sums it up,
``says a lot about a society by examining who they choose to
celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Woody, the view isn't very becoming. We exalt super
models and delinquent actors; we follow them through rehab and
relationships. If a woman shoots her husband's underage lover, we
eat up the details. And when a hostage comes home, we give him a
medal and the key to the city (``But why?'' asks one old woman in
the film. ``Any idiot can get captured.'')
</P>
<P>
   Allen follows a couple, Lee (Kenneth Branagh) and Robin (Judy
Davis), as they acrimoniously split up, move apart and try to begin
anew. Lee is a ``celebrity'' journalist and he's neurotically
intent on ruining his own life. He searches continually for the
perfect experience and chance to find fame.
</P>
<P>
   He sleeps around with troubled and vacuous models and actresses
(Melanie Griffith, Charlize Theron, Gretchen Mol, Winona Ryder and,
weirdly, Leonardo DiCaprio, among them). He humiliates one very
decent woman (Famke Janssen) who tries to love and help him. He
abuses and uses everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, he's unable to write his ``great novel'' and he
can't stay faithful to anyone. He's a lost soul who won't grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Robin tries religious retreats and consults over plastic
surgery, thinking she'll find self acceptance. One day she meets a
TV producer, Tony Gardella (Joe Mantegna), who pursues her and
invites her to quit teaching and come onboard as an assistant with
his TV show. She obliges and finally overcomes her lifelong belief
that hadn't the right to be happy or in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrity'' takes place over the course of a year. And while
Allen has lots to say about the burden of fame and how everyone
pursues it _ even the most untalented _ he's picked an annoying
vessel to bear his message. Branagh does a ``Woody Allen''
impersonation through most of the film and, by the end, he's a
tiresome irritant.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness Davis is on hand to liven things up. Initially,
it's a little tough to watch her playing the same shrill shrew that
Woody always casts her as. But she's the one character who makes a
true journey toward self-knowledge. By the end, she lights up the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Allen has endured his own share of scandal and public
scrutiny. And while ``Celebrity'' is hit-and-miss as a movie and is
partly an acid bath purging of his own personal pain under the
public eye, he's also made some astute observances about our
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the end, as in his last film, ``Deconstructing
Harry,'' the character he's the roughest on and least sympathetic
to is the one who most resembles, well, Woody Allen himself.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity. Directed and written by Woody Allen. Cast: Kenneth
Branagh, Judy Davis, Winona Ryder, Melanie Griffith, Joe Mantegna,
Charlize Theron, Famke Janssen, Lenonardo DiCaprio, Gretchen Mol.
Miramax Films. 113 minutes. Rated R for language, sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1320EST &QL; 
