<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9118 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SEVENTH-SPI &LR;      11-19 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SEVENTH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH DIRECTOR KEEPS RECORD IN TACT WITH `SEVENTH HEAVEN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Benoit Jacquot is one of France's best kept secrets. He's made
10 films and worked with Marguerite Duras and Jacques Rivette
during the course of his career, but we've seen precious few of his
movies in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Single Girl'' graced screens last year and its hypnotic,
shot in real-time look at a day in the life of a young woman who is
unhappily pregnant was a rare find.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Jacquot's reputation is beginning to build. He has a
special gift for writing complex roles for women and is a keen
observer of modern urban life. ``Seventh Heaven,'' which was made
in 1997, is no exception on either count.
</P>
<P>
   Starring real-life couple Sandrine Kiberlain and Vincent Lindon,
the film explores the mystery, mystique _ and power _ of women and
the effect sudden change has upon a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Mathilde (Kiberlain) should he happy. Her husband, Nico
(Lindon), is a successful orthopedic surgeon and the pair live in
elegant simplicity in Paris with their precocious son. But Mathilde
has taken to stealing toys from shops, after which she swoons into
a dead faint.
</P>
<P>
   Nico prescribes western medicine but either it has no effect or
Mathilde absent-mindedly forgets to take it.
</P>
<P>
   One evening at a party, Mathilde spots a man staring intently at
her. His gaze signals a connection. ``I know all about you,'' he
implores and the next day, after another of her forays into
kleptomania, the man is again there. He takes her to lunch and
intensely grills her about the layout of her apartment, her
father's death 15 years ago, and whether she's ever had an orgasm
with her husband (she hasn't). He explains that he's a doctor of
hypnotism and feng shui, the eastern art of harmony with nature
through the balance of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Under his care, Mathilde begins to come out of her malaise. She
rearranges the flat and returns to work, making Nico suspicious.
Suddenly he seems less able to control his wife's doings and the
balance in the marriage is thrown off. Nico begins to fray while
Mathilde strengthens and revives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventh Heaven'' is a finely crafted and tuned work that
demands a detective's awareness to grasp its intricacies.
Kiberlain's face initially seems impassive but it's a study in pain
and confusion until she quietly becomes a radiant force. It's a
performance that is full of nuance, sly knowing and deft humor.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Jacquot films are like Flaubert novels. They're full
of subtlety and strong women characters _ and they engage the
imagination. His casting of Lindon and Kiberlain is ingenious
because the pair are so familiar with each other that their every
move feels like everyday life. The ordinary becomes extraordinary
and that's high praise considering the current state of movies,
where every plot development is predictable within the first 15
minutes of the opening credits.
</P>
<P>
   Seventh Heaven. Directed by Benoit Jacquot. Written by Jacquot,
Jerome Beaujour. Cast: Sandrine Kiberlain, Vincent Lindon.
Zeitgeist Films. Grand Illusion. 91 minutes. Unrated, with sexual
content. In French with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
