<HEADLINE>
`CUBE' IS HAMMY, TERRIBLY WRITTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was just a matter of time before someone had the idea of
making a movie based on Jean Paul Sartre's existential one-act
play, ``No Exit,'' the computer game ``Doom,'' and a Rubik cube.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's surprising that no one thought it up before. But
that could be because, at least with ``Cube,'' it's an idea that
has a very limited appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Six people, ordinary citizens who have regular jobs, wake to
find themselves in a prison. Upon further inspection, they learn
it's a maze of square rooms, each identical except in color and
lethal impact. Some rooms are killers, some are clean. And the six
must figure out why they have been placed within such a maze, and
more importantly, how to get out?
</P>
<P>
   A cop, a thief, a student of math, a doctor and an architect _
even an autistic youth _ are the players. Some will make it, some
won't. And death isn't pretty. It may be slice-and-dice by
invisible wires or acid blown in the face, eating out both brains
and eyes. Confinement will cause insanity, fury, fear and truth
among these embattled, exhausted contestants.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what the filmmakers would like you to believe.
``Cube'' is full of hammy acting, terrible writing and a
conveniently violent theme that might work for a 10-year-old boy
and his Nintendo or Playstation, but will infuriate and alienate
any viewer with a modicum of adult sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cube'' plays like a bad ``Twilight Zone'' episode and there
isn't a moment of redemption or real payoff. The filmmakers stretch
the story into an hour and a half of relentless sadism and futility
and the ending doesn't compensate for the agony that has come
before.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, there's no humanity at the core of this ugly lesson in
inhumanity. So what's the point? Sure, the essential components of
a compelling story are there, but as in the recent, equally distant
movie, ``Pi,'' cinema, in the hands of the ``new'' young filmmaking
generation, struggles to have a heart. It's just plain crueler and
colder and offers no escape from the negativism or stress of
everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Cube. Directed by Derek Rogers. Written by Andre Bijelic,
Vincenzo Natali, Graeme Manson. Cast: Nicole de Boer, Nicky
Guadagni, David Hewlett, Andrew Miller, Maurice Dean Wint. Trimark.
92 minutes. Rated R for violence, language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1321EST &QL; 
