<HEADLINE>
`ENEMY OF THE STATE' DOESN'T QUITE MEASURE UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first hour of ``Enemy of the State'' rates right up there
with the best of the ``paranoia'' thriller genre, including ``The
Parallax View,'' ``Three Days of the Condor,'' ``The Firm'' and the
recent ``Conspiracy Theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly all the components are in place: a single soul is
pitted against something (or someone) far greater and vast in
resources and malicious intent; he has no idea why or how he was
singled out, and he's ultimately aided by a mysterious stranger
whose shadowy presence is his only hope for solving the riddle _
and saving his life.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Will Smith plays Robert Clayton Dean, a young
hotshot lawyer who lives with his wife (Regina King from ``Jerry
Maguire'') and son in Washington, D.C. Dean is working on a
high-profile case involving the mob when he suddenly and
unintentionally becomes embroiled in an intrigue that endangers his
family, friends and everyone around him.
</P>
<P>
   While Christmas shopping, Dean collides with a college buddy who
is being chased. In desperation, the old pal discreetly slides a
computer disk that shows the murder of a congressman into the
lawyer's shopping bag. Two minutes later, the friend is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Dean is stunned by what's happened but thinks no more about it
until his house is ransacked and his credit cards and bank account
are no longer accessible. Soon he's framed for another murder and
he's pursued by people who can predict his every move and thought:
the National Security Agency (or as they're nicknamed, No Such
Agency).
</P>
<P>
   Only one man can help him now; a man he's never met named Brill
(Gene Hackman), who is an ex-intelligence operative living an
anonymous, underground existence. But Brill is fully clued into the
activities of the renegade group intent upon making Dean a
scapegoat for a political crime they've committed, and the fact
that as soon as they have the implicating disk, they'll kill Dean
as easily as one might swat a fly.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, early in its second hour, ``Enemy of the State''
turns to drivel. An intelligent, complicated setup twists into an
incredulous buddy movie and slow motion faceoff that's straight out
of director Tony Scott's violent 1992 cult movie, ``True Romance.''
The script erodes from a tense, taut cautionary tale about
intrusive high-tech surveillance of our private lives into
formulaic plotting that falls apart under scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a shame, because Will Smith makes a terrific everyman
caught in a web of deceit, corruption and ambition. Hackman doesn't
have a lot to do but, as always, he even does nothing well, and Jon
Voight seems to be making a lucrative second career out of playing
villains.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Scott has cast many ``new breed'' actors, including
Tom Sizemore and Barry Pepper from ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Jason
Lee, Jamie Kennedy, Scott Caan and Jake Busey in supporting roles.
</P>
<P>
   As with any of the director's films, the visuals and style are
cool and inventive and he conjures a creepy world where information
is power and human beings can change from flesh and blood into
electronic identities that are easy to manipulate _ or eradicate.
It's a scary concept that makes for great movie material. It's too
bad the script turns into tepid, unbelievable mush.
</P>
<P>
   Enemy of the State. Directed by Tony Scott. Written by David
Marconi. Cast: Will Smith, Gene Hackman, Jon Voight, Lisa Bonet,
Regina King. Touchstone Pictures. 130 minutes. Rated R for
violence, language, sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
