<HEADLINE>
OUSTING THE KING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now, even the most arrogant executive at Microsoft Corp.
realizes the Redmond, Wash., firm is in serious legal trouble. But
that's only the half of it.
</P>
<P>
   At first it was easy to scoff at the ongoing federal antitrust
suit. It began as an absurd attempt to stop Microsoft from mixing
Web browsing software into the Windows 95 operating system.
Luckily, a federal appeals court gutted the government's case by
declaring that the company can add whatever it wants to Windows, if
it benefits consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A chastened Justice Department broadened its inquiry, and while
it has yet to find a bloody glove, the feds have made an impressive
circumstantial case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the bitter Microsoft rivals on the witness stand are
releasing years of pent-up fury. But that doesn't mean they're
lying about Microsoft demands that they kill off promising products
or divvy up markets. Besides, their claims are often supported by
internal Microsoft documents that read like the collected works of
Vito Corleone.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's chief executive Bill Gates's Clintonian testimony,
so evasive that it provoked laughter. Get it straight, Bill. You're
master of the universe, not president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the case remains a he-said, she-said affair, with no
proof that Microsoft deserves anything more than a wrist slap.
</P>
<P>
   But on the left coast, Microsoft just got slapped upside the
head. A federal judge in California has ruled that Microsoft
attempted to strangle a promising new technology in its cradle.
</P>
<P>
   Java, you'll recall, is a software technology invented by Sun
Microsystems Inc. that allows many different kinds of computers _
Unix machines, Windows machines, Macintoshes _ to run the same
programs. Java hasn't yet lived up to Sun's press releases. For
instance, it tends to run very slowly.
</P>
<P>
   But major firms like IBM Corp. are spending millions to make
Java work better. If it all comes together, Microsoft's control of
the operating system market becomes irrelevant, and Bill Gates goes
from king of the world to just another rich guy with a big house. I
could live with that, but not Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives got busy looking for honest ways to compete
with Java. They failed utterly. So they tried the next best thing _
sabotage. In late 1995, Microsoft agreed to license Java from Sun
Microsystems, and include the software in Microsoft products like
its Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft also began making ``improvements'' in Java, which
would ensure that the software would work better _ or at least
differently _ when it was run on Windows machines. The idea was to
fragment the Java market by creating two different versions _
Microsoft's and Sun's. And since most people use Microsoft-based
computers, guess who would win that fight?
</P>
<P>
   But Sun sued Microsoft, saying the company had no right to alter
Java. Tuesday's court ruling, though not final, suggests that Sun
will probably win its case in the end. To prevent Microsoft from
destroying Java in the meantime, the judge has ordered Microsoft to
comply with Sun's Java standard.
</P>
<P>
   This surely hurts Microsoft's prestige, and also gives the
federal prosecutors a few extra rounds of ammo. But the Java case
also underscores a deeper woe.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind its press agentry: Microsoft has never been an
innovative company. Instead, Microsoft has excelled at skillfully
polishing and repackaging the best ideas of others. There's nothing
wrong with that when you're a tiny upstart going up against giants.
But when you dominate the industry, people expect more of you. And
Microsoft isn't delivering. Instead, it serves up overpriced
enhancements of its old products.
</P>
<P>
   Then consider the Java case, or the recently leaked memos in
which Microsoft mulls plans to sabotage the upstart Linux operating
system. Combined with the antitrust case, they paint a picture of a
company eternally on the defensive, more interested in destroying
competitors than in creating excellent products.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a picture of a firm that has no choice but to change.
Never mind how powerful Microsoft is. General Motors was far
stronger when Toyota came knocking. GM learned the hard way that
all the cash ever printed can't forever suppress rivals with better
products.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Microsoft wins all of its legal battles, the firm still
faces a hard choice. Either it learns to embrace innovation rather
than subvert it, or Redmond, Wash., will become the software
industry's version of Flint, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
