<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIOCIRTY TAKING TOLL ON SILENT MAJORIY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If you were at Husky Stadium last Saturday, you were
an earwitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dead as I've ever heard,'' said Bob Rondeau, KOMO radio's
longtime Husky play-by-play broadcaster. ``Some of it had to do
with the flow of the game, but there wasn't much noise from the
crowd at any time for a game against a second-ranked team.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor have crowds been different in the Kingdome, despite three
straight Seahawk sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't sense it's nearly as loud as it used to be,'' said
Steve Raible, KIRO radio's veteran color man and former Seahawk.
``You talk to former players who tell stories about it being so
loud that they couldn't hear themselves think. It was almost
painful at times on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that way anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   A pair of disappointing 5-5 teams is the easy explanation for
the deadness that prevails in the local football citadels. But is
that the full explanation?
</P>
<P>
   And is that enough of an explanation in a town that was regarded
as arguably the nation's best college/pro football town?
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers here have little idea how passionate fans once were
about football.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Seahawks retire the No. 12 jersey as a salute
to their 12th-man homefield advantage, the NFL adopted anti-noise
rules as a direct response to the Kingdome's audio muggings.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies always had a massive, loyal fan base that not only
failed to dissipate with arrival of the NFL in the 1970s, it
actually grew. A second deck was added to Husky Stadium's north
side and was filled easily as the team went to three straight Rose
Bowls in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Even in lean years, fans here cranked it up so steadily that the
stadiums were always listed at the top of the toughest-to-play
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   But now ... deadness. Even with full houses.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, this year's teams are mediocre. But they're not 2-8
either. Neither are they bereft of talented or exciting players.
</P>
<P>
   Something's happening here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans are a little different now,'' Raible said. ``I don't know
if there's excitement in the city about anything. We all are jaded
to a certain extent. We've had high expectations, as we should, but
I think we've been a little spoiled. We have every right to hope
for and demand a winner, but a couple of games for each team could
have gone the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the players ever responded like the fans do, they'd be in
real trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet a lack of realism is a standard feature of a fan's life.
That's part of the appeal _ even if things are turning to mud at
home or work, there's always the team to carry on one's
unachievable expectations.
</P>
<P>
   While slumps and losing seasons are an understood part of sports
cycles, what seems to have changed in recent times is fan
tolerance. When the primary talk of sports is salary caps,
free-agent contracts, NCAA violations and municipal extortions for
taxpayer-subsidized stadiums, a grimness and contempt sets in that
is corrosive.
</P>
<P>
   Sports become a chore, not a joy. And the emphasis on money
makes sports . . . well, like most of the rest of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was playing and making $25,000 a year, people could
relate to a football player,'' Raible said. ``Now, with these
salaries, they really can't. People figure that with
multimillion-dollar players, they must be the best ever. So when
Warren Moon doesn't complete every pass, or Darrin Smith doesn't
get a sack every time, or Ken Griffey Jr. doesn't hit a home run,
people are disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how many times players do charity work and community
events, a lot of fans just can't identify.''
</P>
<P>
   I have always dismissed the doomsday sports talk that emerges
after news of a new contract benchmark, or strike, or enormous TV
rights fee, ticket price hike or taxpayer ripoff. Evidence is
strong that fans always come back, no matter the fraud, indignity
or disgrace perpetrated upon them. The owners and bosses of sports
know that, and continue to abuse with impunity (see NBA).
</P>
<P>
   I am not ready to change that opinion. I am, however, becoming
increasingly less convinced.
</P>
<P>
   What's apparent is that if mediocrity is sustained _ the Huskies
have won one bowl game, a minor one, in five years and the Seahawks
have been out of the playoffs for 10 years _ the growing absence of
fan tolerance can make for a permanent case of disaffection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans will say, `I was there for so many years and they broke
my heart too many times,''' Raible said. ``Fans invest so much and
then get disappointed so often. They want to jump up and cheer so
badly, but they've had to sit right back down after the next
mistake. They're afraid to get excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Raible drew upon his Southern upbringing for the trenchant
adage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can beat a dog only so many times,'' he said, ``before it
doesn't come home to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Apathy in one sport in one town is not necessarily indicative of
a national trend. A couple more wins, and maybe the nation's best
football town revives.
</P>
<P>
   But the teams, and by association all sports leagues and
university jock factories, might want to think hard whether one or
two wins will do it as usual.
</P>
<P>
   For some dogs, the woods are looking better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
