<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILL'S CHOICE HAS PAID OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Northeastern football coach Barry Gallup remembers well
the skinny quarterback out of the small Massachusetts high school.
</P>
<P>
   Gallup got the word that the kid at Nashoba Regional was
something special on the football field. It was Veterans Day and
his Huskies practiced in the morning, and that afternoon, Gallup
took the whole staff out to Bolton to check out the kid.
</P>
<P>
   They fell in love with the tall talent with the strong arm who
was at the helm of the run-and-shoot offense, the same system the
Huskies employed. That night, Gallup called and offered a full
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   It was a short courtship.
</P>
<P>
   Within a couple of weeks, Hal Gill had made up his mind. He
chose hockey over football and was headed to Providence College.
Not a bad choice.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Gill, after four years at Providence, was the surprise
of Bruins camp and spent almost the entire year with the big team.
This year Gill is back in business on the blue line, again paired
with Ray Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   One of the tallest players in the National Hockey League at 6
feet 7 inches, the 240-pound Gill had a couple of goals and four
assists last year. He has a goal and two assists this year going
into Thursday's game against the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Any offense is just a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays defense; that's his main thing,'' said coach Pat
Burns. ``It's tough to find good defensemen who want to play
defense. Now they all want to go score goals and get points and
make all these millions and millions of dollars. They don't
understand that not everyone can be a Ray Bourque and not everyone
can be a Brian Leetch. Some guys have to play defense and play
within their limits, and he plays within his limits. He'll never be
a rushing defenseman. He doesn't have those skills. But he has a
great skill for playing defense, and that's a big asset that could
make him play a long, long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, Gill enjoys defense. Not that he dislikes
scoring a goal now and then, mind you. And not that he wouldn't
mind developing the offensive part of his game. But defense is his
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge for me,'' Gill said after practice Wednesday.
``I like being the eliminator, I guess. Eliminating the offense and
going out there and taking away guys' space and getting them
frustrated and taking them in the corner and pinning them. That's
my role and that's the way I like to play.''
</P>
<P>
   He's drawn praise from Burns in recent weeks for his work down
low with Bourque killing penalties. And he drew raves for the job
he did in helping shut down Jaromir Jagr in a 0-0 tie at Pittsburgh
two weekends ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, it goes unnoticed, what a defensive defenseman
does,'' Gill said. ``It's nice when you get recognized and people
say, `Nice job playing against Jagr.' It's exciting when people
notice what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   At quarterback, they're noticing all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a quarterback and everything clicks, you're on top
of the world,'' Gill said. ``When you roll out and throw a 10-yard
pass and then another 10-yard pass and everything kind of pops like
that, you're on top of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a dilemma. Football or hockey? Hockey or football?
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have been an outstanding college quarterback,''
Gallup said. ``Who knows after that? He was one of those sleepers
who was falling through the cracks. We thought we had a steal, a
great one.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill was torn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one of those pro-con lists going,'' he said. ``I did it
up one night and decided on hockey. I wanted to play the best level
I could and I thought my chances were better at hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   On to Hockey East. The Bruins. And Jagr. Taking on the Jagrs of
the NHL is his answer to a two-minute drill in football.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you shut someone down and at the end of the game, you can
look back on it and every play you see is successful and everything
you do is right and you feel like you can't make a mistake, you're
in the zone,'' Gill said. ``That's why you play. That's the best
feeling you can have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burns said forward Ken Belanger, acquired from the New York
Islanders in the trade for Ted Donato, was to make his debut for
the Bruins Thursday night. Belanger missed the Bruins' two games
last weekend after taking a puck to the face in practice. A nasty
cut to the nose required 18 stitches. Belanger was due to get the
stitches removed Wednesday and planned to play with no shield or
extra protecton. He was on a line with Ken Baumgartner and Peter
Ferraro in practice ... Burns said Tim Taylor (ankle) is not ready
to return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
