<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIAL-CIA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JAY' OF THE CIA MAY TAKE STAND IN TWISTY TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE MILETICH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ During the time when Morris Messinger Jr. is accused
of bilking hundreds of people out of millions of dollars, he also
was doing business with a surprising customer: the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   Messinger, who has a record of fraudulent dealings dating to the
late 1980s, went on trial in federal court in Seattle this week,
charged with cheating 1,300 investors out of $3.2 million with
wildly exaggerated promises to build exotic aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The case also has produced the startling disclosure that
Messinger struck a deal with the Central Intelligence Agency to pay
him $190,000 to design a pilotless aerial vehicle that crashed into
an airport hangar when a prototype was tested.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Messinger, 53, of Issaquah, Wash.is using his contract
with the spy agency as part of his defense. He maintains the CIA's
willingness to deal with him shows he was a legitimate businessman
trying to develop viable aerospace products.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, federal prosecutors have tentatively listed an
undercover CIA operative as a witness in the case, although
original plans to allow the agent to shield his face were set aside
in favor of having him testify under the simple pseudonym of
``Jay.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Westinghouse, who is prosecuting
the case, hasn't decided whether to call the agent to the stand.
But if he does, the agent will be summoned sometime next week,
Westinghouse said.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA's contract with Messinger is described in court
documents as an agreement to design but not actually build an
``Unmanned Aerial Vehicle'' capable of delivering a payload to a
specified location. Such craft are commonly referred to as UAV's or
drones.
</P>
<P>
   The records say the ``nature of the payload and the means by
which the UAV would be transported to the target area'' are
classified.
</P>
<P>
   The contract was signed Sept. 3, 1997, but came to an abrupt
halt eight days later when federal agents raided Messinger's
offices in Snohomish County and the CIA learned of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that the CIA was aware of the criminal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Messinger's attorney, James Vonasch, said Wednesday that his
client had completed the first stage of a three-part arrangement
with the CIA when the contract was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   But Vonasch said he couldn't comment further about the deal,
which isn't included in the multicount mail fraud and money
laundering indictment brought against Messinger in March.
</P>
<P>
   Although the $190,000 figure represents a fraction of the CIA's
budget, the transaction raises questions about what steps the
agency takes to examine the background and qualifications of its
prospective contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Harlow, a spokesman at CIA headquarters in Langley, Va.,
declined to answer any questions about the matter Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But records show the CIA wouldn't have had to look hard to find
out about Messinger's past troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Messinger first ran afoul of regulators in 1989, when Oregon
officials ordered him to stop selling unregistered securities in a
now-dormant corporation that supposedly was going to produce drone
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   A court judgment filed in Marion County, Ore., Feb. 5, 1991,
permanently enjoined Messinger from offering and selling securities
in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   It also ordered him to pay more than $50,000 to his investors,
but none of them received a dime, according to court documents
filed in the Seattle case.
</P>
<P>
   After a hiatus of two or three years in the electronics and
radio fields, prosecutors say, Messinger hatched what they describe
as an ``even bolder scheme to obtain money from investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Without filing registration papers, Messinger began selling
stocks in Washington in 1994, in a company called Omega Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   Listing himself as chairman of the company, Messinger registered
the company in Nevada but set up offices in Arlington, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Messinger, a former Navy pilot described by witnesses as a
charming and smooth-talking salesman, induced investors with
``wildly false claims'' about various purported products and
potential monetary returns, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   His plans included development of a pilotless aircraft, a jet
fighter and amphibious aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   In an initial stock offering, Messinger promised that the value
of the shares would grow from 10 cents to as much as $18.
</P>
<P>
   Most investors learned of the company through friends and
relatives and a church Messinger and his wife attended.
</P>
<P>
   Messinger made ``outlandish claims'' about his ability to
manufacture and sell amphibious aircraft and unmanned aerial
vehicles, including one named the Paradactyl, even though he lacked
the manpower, means and skills to carry out his plans, prosecutors
say.
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled investors sometimes got their money back, but only
at the expense of later investors, whose payments were quickly used
to pay about $500,000 to those seeking refunds, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those lucky enough to receive refunds, the lesson learned
from their victimization was much less painful than for the
remaining 1,100 investors who lost all they entrusted to
Messinger,'' prosecutors say in a brief outlining their case.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the brief says, investors lost all or significant
portions of their retirement savings, college tuition money for
their children and funds to cover necessary expenses.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, securities regulators in Washington served a
cease-and-desist order on Messinger in May 1996, but he kept on
selling stock, telling his employees there would only be a slap on
the wrist if he got caught, according to charging papers.
</P>
<P>
   His trial began Monday, with U.S. District Judge Barbara Jacobs
Rothstein presiding.
</P>
<P>
   Messinger, currently free on bond, faces more than five years in
prison if convicted, subject to complex federal sentencing
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony Wednesday, former Omega Marketing Director Jennifer
Fullwiler tearfully told jurors that she grew increasingly
uncomfortable with having to make excuses when people asked for
refunds.
</P>
<P>
   But right up to the moment she quit, she said, she took money
from two little old ladies ``because they were so excited'' about
investing in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Fullwiler also recalled a visit to Messinger's former home in
Edmonds, which she described as large, lavish and full of expensive
artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend that Messinger and his wife, Holly, used
more than $730,000, or one-quarter of the invested funds, for their
personal benefit between October 1994 and March of this year.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his sales pitch, prosecutors say, Messinger told
investors he planned to demonstrate the aircraft Paradactyl to a
host of government agencies, including the Army, Navy, Marines and
the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Those claims were misrepresentations, but Messinger did engage
in direct dealings with the CIA over a drone design, prosecutors
say.
</P>
<P>
   But court records shed no light on how Messinger came to the
attention of the spy agency.
</P>
<P>
   Westinghouse, the lead prosecutor, said the CIA operative who
might be called to testify was shown a video of the proposed drone
in flight.
</P>
<P>
   A witness in the case, Steve Fawcett, who built models for
Messinger, said the video shows a parachute-like device taking off
and briefly flying.
</P>
<P>
   The flight continued beyond what is on the video, he said, with
the drone sputtering and crashing into the roof of a hangar at the
Arlington airport.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials came running to the scene, taking down names,
Fawcett said.
</P>
<P>
   Westinghouse said Messinger's device simply didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   More information about his dealings with the CIA might be
learned when and if the undercover operative who dealt with him
takes the stand.
</P>
<P>
   Or the full story might remain forever buried in CIA files.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
