<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S HOW TRENDS ARE SHAPING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something old, something new.
</P>
<P>
   For my money, ski season has not yet started, and will not until
snow is respectably deep on piste and in the woods. Yet, by many
standards _ ski show, first tracks lain down on Killington, the
blizzard of faxed press releases from North country balyhooing the
new season _ it is here and under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it a better idea to market the later season, when
there's plenty of leftover snow but no skiers, rather than the
pre-Thanksgiving skiing in the boneyards?'' asks the faint voice of
reason.
</P>
<P>
   But when was such a sport as this any more reasonable than love
or youth itself?
</P>
<P>
   So as planet ski rotates into the season of 1998-99, here are
some of the trends, megatrends, minitrends, and negatrends of the
new season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _We are not by a long shot finished hearing about shaped skis.
The debate is over, of course, about whether parabolics
(interesting that this term has faded) are superior to classic
straight shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Shapes were not really a new concept back in the winter of '96,
but talk about an idea whose time suddenly came in a big hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Now the argument moves to whether shaped skis can be modified
for mogul bashing and straight speed skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the fact remains that for many skiers, much about shaped
skies is counterintuitive, making them feel for the first few runs
that their shoes are on the wrong feet.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're buying someone shaped skis for Christmas, be sure
to spend $50 for a shaped ski clinic and an hour's work with an
instructor who can spare new shapesters some of the entry
awkwardness.
</P>
<P>
   All this aside, the real question of shaped skis is whether the
quest for ultimate no-brainer, no-skill skiing is really good for
the sport. Does instant mastery via technology really feel that
good next to the reward for good lessons and long practice?
</P>
<P>
   Would a golfer feel good about dropping his handicap 10 strokes
because of a new club that magically directed the ball on an exact
trajectory to the green regardless of his swing?
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. I'll still take my shapes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _There is an argument or two to be made against helmets, but
after last season few are listening.
</P>
<P>
   With the much-publicized deaths of Michael Kennedy and Sonny
Bono, regardless of all the circumstances surrounding their skiing
accidents and regardless of the overall safety statistics, the
momentum toward helments is now relentless.
</P>
<P>
   But that means the competition to perfect headgear has heated
up, and helmets will only advance through refinement into lighter
weights, greater comfort, and warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Helmets seem an especially good idea for children, though
parents should choose and fit them without professional help.
</P>
<P>
   And the antihelmet argument? Well, when did skiing become some
rocketship ride or Derelict Derby stockcar crash race?
</P>
<P>
   Downhill racers have always worn crash helmets because they push
the very limits of survivability. If they did not do this, law
school would be a better option than ski racing.
</P>
<P>
   But recreational skiing is a far different matter. The sport is
not about pushing those mortal limits, any more than a drive in the
country is the same as racing 160 m.p.h. in the Goober 500.
</P>
<P>
   But ... oh, never mind. Helmets are coming. Let's just please
not have a law mandating them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _At one time the trek west for a year or two of ski bumming in
the Rockies was a rite of passage. OK, John Denver was de rigeur
then, and ``Rocky Mountain High'' was a siren song with many a
message.
</P>
<P>
   Aspen, Steamboat, Vail, Park City _ so new and exciting in those
days. But the simple-hearted life of ski bumming is long past now,
not the least of the reason being that resort town life is so
outrageously unaffordable that the option of taking a year or two
after college to work the ski patrol, or the lifts at a Western
resort, has become nearly out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   With rents pushing well over $500 a month for a single room,
kids in resort towns have to work so hard for sustenance that they
don't have the money, time, or energy to hit the slopes _ the very
reason they're out there.
</P>
<P>
   Solution: Given the current employment situation, even the lofty
Aspens and Vails must consider ... no, not busing kids to outback
shacks at the end of the day, but building ski dorms, as was done
in the East from North Conway to Sugarloaf a few decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _More than ever, the generations are moving in opposite
directions. Boomers are aging, enjoying the smooth cruising more
these days. Those football knees are finally kicking up _ not to
mention the bursitis in the shoulder. Bumps are over. Trees? Thanks
but no thanks.
</P>
<P>
   So, despite the trend toward vast glades, tree skiing, outback
bushwhacking, and bashing the zipper line though the moguls, the
largest block of skiers, the baby boomers, likes it fast, smooth,
and stylish.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely, generations going in two directions. The better ski
areas seem to be keeping up with both.
</P>
<P>
   (Tony Chamberlain is the Boston Globe's skiing columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
