<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG TOBACCO'S CHUMP CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Attorney General Scott Harshbarger takes the quick tobacco
money, Massachusetts will become just another spent butt, ground
into shards under the heel of Philip Morris and RJR Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   This may seem an exaggeration on the surface. Under the terms of
the settlement, Massachusetts would collect $7.6 billion over 25
years, or $1,245 per person. Massachusetts would collect nearly the
same money per capita as the two biggest winners in out-of-court
settlements against Big Tobacco, Minnesota ($6.1 billion, $1,326
per person) and Mississippi ($3.4 billion, $1,259).
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like big money, but under the microscope of public
health, it is chump change. The offer to the states of $206 billion
over 25 years is a crude bribe, made all the more incredible by the
fact that so many state attorneys general have bowed so meekly to
Big Tobacco's one-week, take-it-or-leave-it ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
   The $206 billion amounts to only 8 percent of the $2.5 trillion
that the federal government estimates we stand to lose over the
next 25 years to cigarettes in health care costs and lost work
productivity. In Massachusetts, we may get $7.6 billion from
cigarette makers over 25 years, but cigarettes, based on our
population, will have cost us $58.75 billion in that same time
span, 7.7 times more in health care and lost productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Big Tobacco, outside of some minor advertising restrictions that
it has been phasing out anyway, is essentially free to do business
as usual. Big outdoor billboards might disappear, but corner stores
will become even more plastered with eye-level window and checkout
counter advertising. Certain cartoonish icons, such as Joe Camel,
might be history, but magazines will continue to tell women
``You've come a long way, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Tobacco will also be able to continue brand-name sponsorship
at one event a year. But Philip Morris, RJR Nabisco, Brown and
Williamson, and Loews have many brand names to use to cultivate
goodwill. You will never know there was a settlement as they become
more crafty than ever to keep their name behind ``events'' that go
all around the country, such as stock car races, music festivals,
dance troupes, and art exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   They will also be able to continue to use their corporate name
to fund political groups, sports, the arts, and other cultural
events. Thus, for whatever noise public health officials raise
about the dangers of smoking, expect the voice of civic leaders
will remain as muted as today.
</P>
<P>
   If we knew that the public health message was getting through,
if we could accurately predict that the number of smokers in the
United States would decline dramatically to the point where our
health care costs would also fall, then there might be a reason to
take this money. The opposite is occurring. Despite the national
drive toward smoke-free workplaces, airplanes, and restaurants, the
percentage of young people who are smoking is on the increase.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published this week in the Journal of the American
Medical Association, smoking by college students is up 28 percent.
That mirrors findings that smoking by high school students is up 32
percent. Smoking has gone up regardless of color, gender, size of
college, or area of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Such findings are a reminder of Big Tobacco's reach. Low-income
children are assaulted at the corner store. Civic leaders become
slaves to funding. The media still tell youth that smoking is cool.
Harvard researchers found tobacco use in over half of the top
movies. The back of yesterday's Globe Living/Arts page featured a
full-page ad for Kool, with water dropping off a mint leaf toward
the lush greenery and waterfall on the cigarette box.
</P>
<P>
   It is extremely short-sighted for the attorneys general to sign
a deal that would prevent them from suing again 20 and 30 years
from now when today's rise in smoking becomes tomorrow's increase
in cancer. It is hard to believe that Harshbarger, who has fought
the tobacco wars longer than most AGs, would give up now when
Massachusetts has one of the strongest cases pending against Big
Tobacco. Minnesota did the nation an immense favor with its suit,
forcing Big Tobacco to cough up a motherlode of lies and deceit in
court before getting its settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that Big Tobacco can put a gun to the head of the
people via the attorneys general is sickening, especially since the
state is supposed to protect the average citizen who can never hope
to fight the legal artillery of the tobacco companies. When Big
Tobacco holds the gun and when Wall Street is already signaling
that this deal will be good for tobacco stocks, that can mean only
one thing. Unless Harshbarger stands up and says no to this deal,
the mass murder of thousands of people will continue, with the
state as an official party to the slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
