<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9141 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      11-19 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNAKES MAKE FAST WORK OF SLOW DRAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My tub drains very slowly _ five to 10 minutes. No other
drains in the house are slow. I've tried baking soda and vinegar,
and hot water, without success. I even took off the stopper lever
at the end of the tub and cleaned it thoroughly. I am stumped.
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN BARRETT, North Attleborough
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Slow drains are usually caused by a buildup of grease, oil,
hair, and other detritus that reduces the diameter of the drain.
The cure is to use a plumber's snake to break up the gunk so it
will flow away. The snake will also remove any other kind of
obstruction. The baking soda and vinegar might help some, but it is
a long, slow process. Better to use is straight bleach; put a cup
of it down the drain and let it sit in the trap for an hour or so,
then turn on the water to get the bleach farther down the drain. An
enzyme-based drain cleaner may be more effective than bleach.
</P>
<P>
   A plumber's snake, by the way, is a long, flexible rod of flat
wire with a hook on one end and a crank handle on the other; turn
the crank as you thread the snake down the drain so it will do
maximum good in breaking up and removing the detritus. You can put
the snake in the drain opening (remove the strainer cover first).
Or, it might be easier to remove the stopper mechanism and put the
snake in that opening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a caller asked what kind of a tenant she should rent an
apartment to _ a smoker or a cat owner _ the handyman suggested the
smoker because smoke is easier to remove from a house and deodorize
than cat urine that can get into just about anything and stay there
forever. Of course, that depends on the cat owner and who's in
charge: tenant or cat.
</P>
<P>
   Wrote Elizabeth Hoffman (an ex-smoker) of Putney, Vt.: ``I'd
just like to point out that a tenant who falls asleep holding a cat
is not a fire hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   You just made the handyman's day, Elizabeth Hoffman. Thanks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My interior woodwork is very wide and very handsome, a dark
mahogany-walnut look, shellacked or varnished. There are some
scratches and paint spots. How can I cover them or otherwise
improve the woodwork's good looks?
</P>
<P>
   NEIL SCANNELL, Auburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. For the paint spots, dab a little oil (any kind will do) on
each spot, wait 15 to 20 mintues, then rub with a coarse cloth or
even fine steel wool, but if you use the steel wool, go very easy
on the finish. The oil will soften the paint enough so it can be
wiped off. If the paint is latex, you can use Goof-Off, sold in
hardware stores, to remove the spots without affecting the original
finish.
</P>
<P>
   For the scratches, you can buy a sort of stain pen, loaded with
stain with a felt tip for staining the scratches. Minwax pioneered
these stain pens. Use a stain slightly darker than the finish; a
dark scratch is less obvious than a light one. This will disguise
the scratches; they cannot be removed without refinishing the
woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   If this does not work or does not appeal to you, you can instead
paint the woodwork with Polyshade, a Minwax varnish with the stain
built into it. Before you use the Polyshade, check to see if the
finish is shellac. Wipe a small section with rubbing or denatured
alcohol; if the finish softens, it is shellac and you may not be
able to use the Polyshade, because many clear finishes such as
polyurethane are not compatible with shellac.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My roof has a 12/12 pitch on one side, with a gutter 35 feet
long and at each end a downspout, one of which discharges on the
sidewalk. The city ordered me to remove that downspout. Can I
relocate it to the middle of the gutter and rework the gutter so it
drains from one end into that middle downspout? What is a good
pitch for a gutter?
</P>
<P>
   PAT PALAZZOLO, Revere, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You certainly can put a downspout in the middle, eliminating
the guilty one. And, it does not have to be in the exact center,
give or take a few feet. You really should do it anyway, because a
cardinal rule on gutters is that you need a downspout for each 30
feet of gutter. As for pitch, a standard pitch is 1/16-inch per
foot. That would pitch the gutter a little over 2 inches. But a
level gutter will drain, and you can make that pitch perhaps as
little as 1 1/2 inches. All this is necessary, I think, because
that 12/12 roof pitch is 45 degrees, very steep, and therefore will
cascade a lot of water quickly into the gutter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is urea formaldehyde insulation against the law? My son wants
to buy a house in Michigan and the owners disclosed that they think
U-F is in the house. What should he do?
</P>
<P>
   ANXIOUS CALLER
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It is not exactly against the law, but installation of U-F
is; and it is no longer installed. Houses that already have it are
not breaking the law, but some states require that it be removed
before the house is sold, even if it is not causing problems. The
reason for the controversy dates back nearly 20 years, when some
U-F was defectively installed, causing allergic reactions to people
who were sensitive to it. So, it was banned.
</P>
<P>
   Your first priority is to have the insulation checked; if it is
not U-F, there's no problem. If it is U-F, it should be removed and
safe insulation installed, but at great cost; if your son can
reduce the house price by the amount needed to remove the U-F and
put in new insulation, that might be a good idea. Short of that I
suggest he look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
