<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEIR WORDS ARE THEIR BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let begin with a disclaimer. My husband was perfectly happy
having two daughters. If Jack wanted a son, it was in the same way
that he hoped to see certain exotic locations in his lifetime.
Sure, it might be nice to sail down the Yangtze River before he
dies, but he's not losing sleep because the opportunity has never
arisen. He was always enthusiastically involved in our daughters'
upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   We both tried to help our daughters feel free to explore in
every direction, encouraging them to play sports, excel in school,
and speak up for themselves, but when Jack came home one afternoon
with a crystal radio kit and tried to entice them into doing
something he'd loved as a youngster, they weren't interested. Even
though he and his daughters shared common interests as the girls
grew older, especially a fascination with human psychology, our
daughters were indifferent to model airplanes, golf courses, and
building stone walls, Jack's boyhood hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   There was a small part of Jack _ let's call it the inner boy _
who had no one to play with, especially when our dog Buckwheat
turned out to be less than a perfect buddy. Tragically, Jack was
forced to give up his attempt to bond with the only other male in
our house after Bucky mistook a growling match as an invitation to
grab Jack by the throat. It looked as if my husband would never
hand down whatever wisdom older men pass on to the next generation
of males. Who ever dreamed that eventually our two daughters would
provide him with sons?
</P>
<P>
   In-law, of course.
</P>
<P>
   I've been watching Jack with Chris and Brian, trying to figure
out what men do together that a man and a woman cannot. I haven't
been able to observe Chris and Jack rising early on our weekends in
Vermont, the better to scour the woods for dry branches and stomp
them into kindling for the fire, because I sleep until summoned to
breakfast. I have, however, watched them each stretch out on a
hammock after their great labors of the morning. On both their
faces is the same expression God must have worn on the seventh day
when ``He saw everything that He had made and behold, it was very
good.''
</P>
<P>
   I do the dishes with water I haul from a stream 200 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   I've never even come close to that expression.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't until Brian decided to double the size of a
shed on his property that I actually got a chance to spy on the men
in my life. They huddled together over plans. They carefully
calculated lengths and estimated quantities. Then they set out
together in search of lumber, joist hangers, and galvanized nails.
Armed to the teeth with hammers and saws, they began to erect a
building.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the carpenters got hungry and needed
sustenance and the children got wild and needed supervision, Laura
and I did our share of the construction work. I was nailing
shingles on the front of the building while the men put on roll
roofing. As I lined up wooden rectangles, I eavesdropped on the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think this fits?'' ``Is that level?'' ``Hand that over,
would you?'' ``Lift your side a little.'' ``I think we've got it.''
``Is that OK?''
</P>
<P>
   I waited for something resembling conversation, some revelation
that would bring them together in sympathetic understanding. What I
heard was: ``How much overlap do we want?'' ``Put a little more tar
over there.'' ``Do we need longer nails?'' Can you imagine women at
a quilting bee spending their precious time together asking, ``How
many stitches should I use?'' ``Pass the scissors.'' ``Is there
enough contrast?''
</P>
<P>
   Though Brian tried to explain _ ``Men focus,'' is what he said _
as a woman, I needed help making sense of what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   I turned to Martin Buber's aptly titled ``Between Man and Man.''
In a section called ``Silence which is Communication,'' I read:
``Imagine two men sitting beside one another ... They do not speak
... In this moment neither is thinking of the other ... Yet (one
man) does something ... Unreservedly communication streams from
him, and the silence bears it to his neighbor ... (who) receives it
unreservedly ... No more knowing is needed. For where unreserve has
ruled, even wordlessly, between men, the word of dialogue has
happened sacramentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the light dawned. Show me someone who has the slightest
idea what Buber is talking about _ and I'll show you a man _
</P>
<P>
   Bonding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's website is at www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
