<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT FIRM STRUGGLES TO REVIVE LAGGING BOND UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Only baseball teams believe in silly things like the
``hometown discount.'' Money managers offer no hometown break on
fees, and expect none on performance. They know it is ``perform or
be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's exhibit: Putnam Investments, which takes a backseat in
this town of money managers to only you-know-who.
</P>
<P>
   This week the state's pension fund served notice that it will
find a new manager for a $1.3 billion fixed-income fund that Putnam
had overseen for more than a decade. The state said it would retain
Putnam as manager of two other equity portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident the pension fund is keeping Putnam as an
equity manager and dumping it as a bond manager. Put simply,
Putnam, once known best for its bond department, is now known as a
bond shop that isn't keeping pace.
</P>
<P>
   In a world of faceless money managers where the difference
between mediocrity and stellar performance is often measured in
hundredths of a percentage point, Putnam has managed to stand out
as a laggard on the fixed-income side. The $71 billion fixed-income
department has been turned upside down by reorganization _ some
people leaving on their own, others being shown the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are clearly not what we intend them to be,'' says
Stephen Oristaglio, a managing director who joined Putnam in July
from Swiss Bank Corp., where we was co-head of fixed income.
</P>
<P>
   For instance:
</P>
<P>
   _High yield (aka junk bonds), where Putnam is one of the biggest
players in country, is a disaster. Putnam High Yield Advantage and
Putnam High Yield, two of its biggest funds, are both near the
bottom of their category. The $3.8 billion High Yield, for example,
is down 8.37 percent this year compared with an average decline of
1.47 percent for its peer group, ranking it 216 of 232 such funds,
according to Lipper Analytical Services.
</P>
<P>
   _Its multisector funds, the kind of go-anywhere bond funds
Putnam now wants to emphasize over the more generic products, are
also struggling. Its $5.1 billion Putnam Diversified Income ranks
60th of 78 similiar funds this year, Lipper says.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam's fixed-income performance has been mediocre, at best,
for awhile _ something that Putnam boss Larry Lasser, not known for
his patience, was going to tolerate only so long.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Lasser extended the purview of Putnam's equity
chief, Tim Ferguson, to include global bond investing. In March
Putnam, saying it wanted to change the product mix, fired eight of
its 30 bond managers. A few months later Putnam hired Oristaglio.
</P>
<P>
   All the while William Curtin, head of the bond department, was
getting squeezed. In October, Putnam revamped the research
department, putting fixed-income research under Carol McMullen,
head of equity research. Curtin exited not long after that.
</P>
<P>
   Big institutional clients can live with short-term performance
problems, but they hate this kind of turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Henderson, director of the $22 billion Massachusetts
Pension Reserve Investment Management system, said Wednesday the
state had been unimpressed with Putnam's bond performance, but had
been willing to give the company a chance to fix the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said Putnam had initially billed Curtin, who joined
Putnam with a big reputation from Lehman Bros. two years ago, as
the centerpiece of its plan. When Curtin left, the pension board
decided it was time to leave, too, Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround just seemed too far away. ``We think it is going
to be awhile before they are up to speed with their competitors,''
Henderson says.
</P>
<P>
   Oristaglio, the Putnam executive, says the problems are fixable,
but are taking longer than expected. He said the trauma of the
third quarter, which crushed the high-yield market, did not make
things any easier. ``That explains why our performance has not
immediately improved,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Putnam took what Orsitaglio calls a ``silo
approach'' on the fixed-income side, with differing investment
styles and technologies. The goal is now to rationalize the system,
bringing consistency to both the equity and fixed-income sides of
the business.
</P>
<P>
   Oristaglio promises results starting next year. ``I don't expect
this will take another year,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It better not. Another year of revolving doors at Putnam and the
state pension fund will not be the only client hitting the exits,
says Jeff McConnell, a Morningstar analyst. ``I wouldn't be
surprised to see more of that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the state pension fund, the board has voted to
instruct its money managers to trade with firms other than Bear
Stearns &AMP; Co. when possible.
</P>
<P>
   The board is unhappy that Bear Stearns has been unwilling to
settle a dispute involving an investment gone bad in a bunch of
grade-B movies back in the mid-'80s. Last summer, a California jury
awarded the pension fund $6.5 million, but Bear Stearns has been
talking appeal, not settlement. Henderson, the pension fund
director, says the brokerage house makes as much as $1 million a
year making its trades.
</P>
<P>
   Says a Bear Stearns spokeswoman: ``We feel we will be vindicated
on appeal. We disagree with the jury's verdict, and we are sorry
they have decided to take this action.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
