<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9168 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORDON-BROTHERS-BOS &LR;      11-19 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORDON-BROTHERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON BROTHERS ACTS AS LIQUIDATOR, HEALER TO RETAILERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Ala., N.J.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Gordon Brothers Group may be the largest retailer that
nobody has ever heard of. Last year, it sold $1 billion worth of
merchandise, nearly twice as much as Filene's Basement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the Green Berets of retailing,'' Gordon Brothers chief
executive Michael Frieze likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   That's one way of putting it.
</P>
<P>
   For much of its history, a company founded 95 years ago by
Frieze's grandfather has been a liquidator.
</P>
<P>
   In that role, it's accustomed to dispatching a SWAT team of 200
retail specialists, often at a moment's notice, to organize
going-out-of-business sales for stores about to go belly up.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, the Green Berets have evolved into a
sort of MASH unit. As often as not, Gordon Brothers gives retailers
medical treatment rather than last rites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're classified as morticians,'' Frieze says. ``But quite
often we're the doctors'' who help keep the patient healthy.
</P>
<P>
   With Gordon Brothers earning both doctor's and mortician's fees,
sales have nearly tripled since 1993, says Gary M. Kulp, a Gordon
Brothers principal and managing director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over half our business is dealing with healthy retailers,''
Frieze says. ``Ten years ago, it was not even 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of this growth is driven by consolidation in the retail
industry as big-box superstore chains look to move into new
markets. When one chain buys another, it can turn to someone like
Gordon Brothers for help.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case of Just For Feet Inc., an Alabama company whose
Southeastern superstores sell sneakers and athletic gear.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Just For Feet bought Sneaker Stadium, a New
Jersey-based chain of 39 somewhat similar stores.
</P>
<P>
   Just For Feet wasn't interested in Sneaker Stadium's format or
inventory. For the Alabama company, the transaction was essentially
a real estate deal, a chance to establish a beachhead in the
Northeast and to acquire choice real estate sites.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for all Sneaker Stadium merchandise and fixtures to
be sold off. Once emptied of all goods, the stores will be shut
down for two months of remodeling. Then they will reopen as Just
For Feet stores.
</P>
<P>
   Just For Feet's purchase of Sneaker Stadium is typical of many
retail acquistions, Kulp says. In most cases, the buyer is
interested in only &UR;  &LR; 60 or 70 percent of the company purchased. The
rest, he says, is ``baggage.''
</P>
<P>
   After an acquisition, it's frequently Gordon Brothers that's
hired to quickly dispose of that baggage and get the acquiring
retailer the most value for it.
</P>
<P>
   Why wouldn't a retailer dispose of this baggage on its own? Why
not put up a sign that says, ``Everything 40 percent off''?
</P>
<P>
   Often retailers do, but Gordon Brothers claims a special
expertise in the narrow art of the clearance sale, which is
designed to transform a store filled with slow moving merchandise
into an empty building within eight to 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running a clearance sale, you can see sales volumes running at
1 1/2 to 4 times your normal levels,'' says Eric L. Tyra, Just For
Feet's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   For a retailer more interested in expanding into a new market
than in unloading sneakers in last year's color, a clearance sale
can be a sideshow and a distraction _ and a bit overwhelming
compared to what the retailer is accustomed to seeing.
</P>
<P>
   For the consumer, it's just a big sale. There's no indication of
Gordon Brothers' involvement.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to clearance sales, Frieze says, ``We consider
ourselves experts not because we're smarter than everybody else but
because we do it over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of doing it over and over again, Gordon Brothers has
an extensive data base for putting the right price on a
discontinued line of toaster ovens, say, or for figuring out how
much people will pay for rollerblades in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Discount an item by too much and a retailer will recover less
than the item's value. Offer too stingy a discount, and few
shoppers will want to buy anything.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Marshall, the Gordon Brothers specialist on shoe retail,
explains why a company is better off hiring Gordon Brothers than
getting rid of unwanted merchandise itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get them a buck and a quarter where they'd only get a
buck,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sneaker Stadium store in Natick, Gordon Brothers
personnel arrived on the scene Oct. 28 to help advise the staff on
the fine points of a clearance sale.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to have the store completely empty by Jan. 10 so a
remodeled Just For Feet can open in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   At Sneaker Stadium, shoes were grouped by brand _ a Nike section
here, a Reebok section over there _ and the format often required
customers to seek help from the store staff.
</P>
<P>
   Now the agenda has changed. The aim is to get as much product
out of the store room and onto the selling floor as possible and to
display it in a way so that shoppers can serve themselves.
</P>
<P>
   By Frieze's estimate, Sneaker Stadium in Natick will be one of
2,000 stores that Gordon Brothers closes this year.
</P>
<P>
   As the mission of Gordon Brothers evolves, so too does the
company. Two years ago, it sold its asset-based lending division to
BankBoston Corp. And last month, it acquired a real estate company
to help dispose of retail clients' unwanted leases.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a new mission, the stigma of the liquidator is not easy
to shake. Although Gordon Brothers claims that it has advised some
of the country's most successful retailers, Frieze says he is not
at liberty to name names.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even healthy retailers have unprofitable stores or a
division that doesn't meet sales targets. In many cases,
such &UR;  &LR; retailers hire Gordon Brothers to take care of their problems
with ``obsolescence,'' as Kulp delicately puts it.
</P>
<P>
   When the likes of a Wal-Mart or a Home Depot aggressively invade
a market, ``they bring in a ton of obsolescence,'' he says.
``That's where Gordon Brothers fits in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want to use us, or at least let anyone know
they're using us,'' Frieze acknowledges. ``The initial response?
`Oh, Gordon Brothers, the liquidator. People are going to think
we're in trouble.' Instead of being regarded like a professional
firm, like accountants or lawyers, people think we're dressed in
black.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
