<HEADLINE>
CSM PINS HOPES ON FACELIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How does a paper that eschews sensationalism, searches for
solutions, and struggles with a distribution system that precludes
reporting on breaking news, sell itself in this frantic media
environment? As the antidote to the all-Monica-all-the-time
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, The Christian Science Monitor -- whose circulation
has slipped to about 80,000 and which is projected to lose $18
million this fiscal year -- rolled out a $500,000 redesign and a $3
million marketing strategy. Among other things, readers will notice
a different logo; new ``streamlined'' looks for the five rotating
daily sections like Work &AMP; Money and Arts &AMP; Leisure; a reconfigured
editorial page; and a paper that will increase by eight pages a
week.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of all this is to change the Monitor's status -- in the
candid words of managing publisher Stephen T. Gray -- as ``the best
respected, least subscribed-to national newspaper.'' Noting that
the news industry is ``struggling...to hold off a tide of sleaze,''
editor David Cook said ``we're convinced that decency does not have
to be dull.`` One of the the Monitor's direct mail ads now features
the slogan: ``Expect more from your news source -- expect the
truth.'' And Gray went so far as to exhort the rest of the media
``to make principled journalism more universal and more relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in serious journalism has to root for the
Monitor. But in lieu of a media reformation, its fate may hinge on
efforts to end its reliance on the U.S. mails and to pursue plans
-- currently being tested in the Boston market -- to arrive at
subscribers' doorsteps first thing in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Iraqi people ever get to elect a leader, they could be
forgiven for choosing CNN boss Ted Turner. He, more than Saddam
Hussein, may have saved them from two punishing attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The latest instance was a November 14 CNN dispatch that proved
the catalyst for a last-second postponement of a major attack on
Iraq that was at least temporarily obviated by Hussein's agreement
to re-admit UN weapons inspectors. (Last February, CNN televised a
``town meeting'' ostensibly designed to prepare the country for a
military strike against Iraq. But the program turned into a public
relations debacle for the White House when vocal anti-war
protestors hijacked much of the event.)
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday's report, filed from Baghdad by CNN's Brent Sadler
at 7:39 on Saturday morning, stated that Iraq was prepared to
``respond positively'' to a UN call for the resumption of weapons
inspections. Until Tuesday's New York Times reported that CNN's
story generated a White House reassessment of an attack planned for
9 am, even CNN officials where unaware of their role in resolving
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge that the CNNs...of the world present is that
(they) can accelerate the course of events very rapidly,'' says
National Security Council spokesman P.J. Crowley, adding that
decision makers are adapting to this ``age of instantaneous
communications.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you pause when some reporting you did may have saved
(thousands of) lives,'' says CNN International Networks President
Eason Jordan, sounding dutifully somber.. ``And it all seems to
revolve around basically one word (``positively'') in a CNN
report...Just imagine that our report had come an hour later.''
</P>
<P>
   With the so-called ``CNN factor'' in geopolitics the subject of
much debate, Marvin Kalb, director of the Harvard's Shorenstein
Center, thinks the episode reflects well on the network and bodes
ill for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   CNN has ``everything to be proud about,'' he says. ``The unhappy
part of this is that a top official had to wait for CNN...to report
a development of this magnitude. This is nothing journalism has to
be concerned about. I think it's something the American people have
to be concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost two months after a jury awarded $163,000 to a former
Boston University Daily Free Press employee who said she'd been
fired because she was suffering from cancer, the two sides can't
agree on how close they are to the legal end game. Clearly stunned
by the verdict, the student-operated Free Press -- which has openly
fretted about its ability to continue publishing in light of the
judgment -- has changed lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The Free Press' new attorney, Shepard Davidson has filing a
motion to dismiss the case or to order a new trial and submitted a
notice of appeal. By his reckoning, all these options could remain
in limbo until a trial transcript is prepared, a process that can
take time. ``I don't foresee anything (final) happening unless we
can work something out with (the plaintiff),'' says Davidson.
``Appeals can take years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Homsey, attorney for the plaintiff Karen Miranda, says that
aside from the $163,000 judgment, tens of thousands of dollars in
interest payments and about $85,000 in legal fees could be added to
the award. Homsey also says he's anticipating a ruling on
Davidson's motions ``within a week or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, according to editor Gene Johnson, a chastened Free
Press is amending its bylaws and creating a human resources
position in order to shore up a lax business operation that is
blamed, at least in part, for the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the public believes people in glass houses shouldn't
practice journalism. Forty five percent of the respondents to a New
York magazine poll say journalists who pass judgement on the
president's infidelity should have their own sex lives scrutinized.
(That might not be as interesting as people suspect.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
