<SLUG> BC-HOME-GARDEN-TV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HGTV WHETS APPETITES WITH MENU OF HOME SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a rainy Saturday and Gary Riegel is puttering around his
apartment in a large Victorian house in Boston. His two televisions
are on _ one in the kitchen, the other in the den.
</P>
<P>
   He vacuums. He waters his plants. He talks to friends on the
phone. But he always keeps a close eye on his televisions, which
are both tuned to the same cable channel _ Home &AMP; Garden
Television, or HGTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not embarrassed about my love for this channel,'' says
Riegel, who works in marketing at the Boston Design Center. ``If I
had a third TV, I'd have it on in the living room. There's just so
much information being given on that channel. On weekends I'm glued
to it. And I know I'm not alone. When my neighbors and I get
together at 7 in the morning to walk our dogs, it's always, `did
you see this, did you see that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Home &AMP; Garden Television may only be five years old, but it can
claim to be one of the fastest-growing cable channels in the
nation. Why?
</P>
<P>
   It offers no-stress programming for viewers beleaguered by
information overload, assaulted by MTV-style imagery, and subjected
to ringside seating at Jerry Springer-created family contretemps.
And it's an insomniac's dream, filling one channel 24 hours a day
with 18 decorating and interior design programs, 11 building and
remodeling shows, 13 gardening and landscaping segments, four on
crafts and hobbies, and 17 other special-interest shows in the HGTV
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   And no one is shouting at you. No guns are fired. No bodies are
flying through the air. And there's nary a mention of Monica.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Mister Rogers Neighborhood for adults. And it now reaches
the homes of 44 million Americans, many of whom _ like Gary Riegel
_ have become addicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The variety of the shows, the hosts, and the half-hour
segments keep my constant attention,'' says Riegel.
</P>
<P>
   Adrienne Jackson, 39, of Newton, is an administrative assistant
for a data storage company in Boston. ``HGTV is such a treat
because there's nothing offensive on these shows,'' she says.
``It's a very user-friendly channel. The shows are really very
helpful and cater to every taste and pocketbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson says she watches the channel at least every other
weekday night and on weekends. Her sister, whom she lives with,
often joins her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shows give you the information and the tools to accomplish
what you might want to do in your home,'' says Jackson. ``There are
so many shows to choose from and not just Martha Stewart doing
Martha Stewart. The shows tell you what's out there, they educate
you, and give you the vocabulary and terminology so you don't feel
so stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Stay-at-home mothers with young children who want a passive way
to relax when their infants are napping or nursing also find HGTV
addictive. For these women, the content of the show doesn't much
matter _ they'll watch quilting and sewing shows even though they
can barely thread a needle.
</P>
<P>
   Others enjoy being voyeurs _ watching people spend gobs of money
on building and renovating their homes or lavishly decorating and
entertaining in their houses.
</P>
<P>
   Still others use it as background noise while doing housework,
reading, or talking on the phone. It's a quiet, uncomplicated
relationships with a ``friend'' that doesn't make demands on one's
emotional or intellectual inner life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is good and people are still spending money on
their homes _ the whole cocooning phenomenon just doesn't seem to
be abating,'' says Burton Jablin, senior vice president of
programming and production at HGTV. ``All our hosts are experts in
what they do, and this gives the shows a lot of credibility. Plus
we commission production companies in different parts of the
country to produce our shows and this gives a variety in style and
geographic location. We want to reflect all of America.''
</P>
<P>
   He says all the shows are consistent with the channel's mantra _
information, ideas, inspiration. With these three ``I's,'' anyone
can make the best of their homes _ regardless of income, says
Jablin.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sea of mediocrity on TV and news shows that assault
people's senses, HGTV has become a refuge,'' says Jablin. ``There's
very little on TV that you can watch with any member of the family.
People know HGTV is not offensive, that it provides a refuge, and
viewers have responded to this in droves.''
</P>
<P>
   The channel is also enhanced by a consumer response line that
viewers can call for information about programming or specific
questions about a program's content. There is also a Web site where
thousands of pages of information are posted. The channel is owned
by Knoxville-based E.W. Scripps and was the brainchild of Ken Lowe,
who created the channel in response to the $587 billion home and
garden market. According to published figures, HGTV was started
with $100 million and now has an asset value of between $900
million and $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Talbot of Westfield is resting at home these days with a
bad back, so she is catching up on her crocheting and watching more
HGTV than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``This channel is so down-to-earth and easy,'' says Talbot, 50,
who is a mother of five and grandmother of seven. ``(A project) may
not look easy at first but they explain everything step by step. I
started watching several years ago for the gardening shows, but
then I started watching the crafts shows, and now I watch
everything including ``Awesome Interiors.'' That show makes you
dream. But it also gives you ideas even if you can't afford what is
being shown in these very wealthy homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbot has one son, 16, still at home. He's taking carpentry in
school, so he'll flip through the channels and watch a woodworking
or building show.
</P>
<P>
   Christy May Powley of Westwood, Mass., owner of DM
Communications, likes everything on HGTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most TV is mindless but the Home &AMP; Garden channel, well, I can
apply it to my life,'' says Powley. ``There are such helpful hints
that I can apply to my daily life. When I'm watching the channel it
doesn't feel like a waste of time.''
</P>
<P>
   She watches HGTV at least three times a week. Sometimes she'll
be watching a movie and switch to HGTV during a commercial and
``get hooked.'' Her husband also enjoys the channel and flips there
to avoid watching the beer commercials during football games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can learn so much,'' says Powley. ``We have this sycamore
tree out front, and it was losing its leaves. We called a tree
service, and they didn't know what was wrong. We found the solution
to the problem on HGTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also like the stenciling and organization shows, and I'll
certainly watch the holiday shows'' which begin Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the shows are so much easier to take than Martha
(Stewart). They are more accessible. I don't feel like these people
are lecturing me or making me feel like a loser. Martha is so
serious. HGTV shows are, well, they seem to be saying, hey, let's
have some fun here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
