<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CARPETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIENTAL RUGS EMBODY A UNIVERSE OF ASIAN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1741, the Isaac Royall family of Medford, Mass. posed to have
their portrait painted by Robert Feke. Only one of their household
treasures is included in the painting _ their Oriental carpet. Such
a valuable textile was the pride of many an Early American clan;
there was no better way to proclaim prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was this attitude new to the New World. In European
paintings from Holland to Spain, Oriental carpets figure
prominently _ and not just on the floor. They're also table
coverings of choice. They're in so many paintings that there are
whole categories of carpets named for artists: Hence the terms
``Holbein Rug'' and ``Bellini Rug.'' And because carpets aren't
often well-documented, their appearance in paintings helps
historians to date them.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing popularity of Oriental carpets accounts for the
popularity of a recent course Museum of Fine Arts curator Julia
Bailey gave on the subject: It was sold out as soon as it was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   The Oriental carpet show ``Ambassadors from the East,'' which
Bailey has organized for the MFA, is equally well-liked: On one
recent morning, as soon as the museum opened, people started
streaming into the textile gallery where the show is on view.
Although the carpets are from the museum's own collection of about
125 rugs, their sensitivity to light means they're not often on
view.
</P>
<P>
   The very term ``Oriental carpet'' is misleading, Bailey says:
These textiles were made across a vast Rug Belt that stretched from
China to Spain. As for the terms ``rug'' and ``carpet,'' both are
acceptable, she says, although ``carpet'' is more accurate because
by definition it means a textile with pile, which gives color,
pattern, and texture to the finished piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be unlikely to find carpets like these on Boston floors
today _ but some certainly were there a century ago,'' Bailey says,
mentioning the Boston Brahmin who once chided her for wearing white
gloves to handle a valuable rug. To him, carpets were for floors
and feet, and for kids and dogs to roll around on.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a century ago when carpets began to be collected as
art objects rather than bought merely as furnishings. London's
Victoria and Albert Museum led the way, as part of its mission to
promote good industrial design. Astute Americans, including Denman
Waldo Ross, soon followed. A lecturer on design at Harvard, Ross
was willing to buy fragments of important rugs: He was using them
as teaching tools, not as decor, so a piece would suffice. He even
managed to snare a fragment from the identical twin of the most
famous rug in the world, the 16th-century Persian ``Ardabil
Carpet.'' Parts of one twin were sacrificed to repair the other;
leftover scraps appeared on the market, and Ross scooped one up.
It's in the MFA show, along with other fragments he gave to the
museum, plus a whole rug, the ``Polonaise Carpet,'' which he bought
for $7,500, the most he ever paid. It's now worth more than 10
times as much.
</P>
<P>
   Carpets offer clues to their past. One huge rug in the MFA show
has a line straight across its center, as if someone had used it to
practice tightrope-walking. Actually, says Bailey, the line
indicates it has spent considerable periods folded in storage.
Fading means the carpet has spent too much time in the light, and
uneven fading may mean that both synthetic and natural dyes were
used: They fade at different rates, throwing the color balance off.
A carpet in the shape of an arch probably surrounded a throne: The
flowers are arranged so the seated ruler would see them the right
way up.
</P>
<P>
   A 16th-century carpet from northern India has a one-way
pictorial design that ``begs to be put in a vertical position, the
way it's hung now,'' Bailey says, the better to see its rollicking
elephants, pink and cream striped lions, and beautiful maidens
sniffing flowers, all protected by a border of glowering monster
masks. This carpet's pristine condition suggests that it was never
used underfoot. It was also the first major example of the art form
that the MFA acquired, an 1893 gift from Boston's Ames family. It
was the illustrious architect H.H. Richardson, designer of
Frederick Ames's house, who chose the carpet; his recommendation
was enthusiastically endorsed by William Morris, leader of
England's Arts and Crafts movement.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the most opulent textile in this show is also the
smallest, a fragment of a 17th-century niche carpet with more than
1,750 knots per square inch producing the lushest of textures, and
an equally lush pattern of twining lilies against a ruby-red
ground. Bailey says a carpet connoisseur told her that in the event
of a fire, this would be the piece to rescue. But there are other
contenders, including a majestic 16th-century Persian silk carpet
alive with hunting scenes, another world-class example. And for
sheer mesmerizing beauty, there's a 16th-century Mamluk carpet from
Egypt with a symmetrical pattern of peridot, azure, and rosy red
glowing like stained glass.
</P>
<P>
   For ``ruggies'' in search of more information on the subject,
Bailey recommends two books: Jon Thompson's ``Oriental Carpets from
the Tents, Cottages and Workshops of Asia''; and Joyce Ware's ``The
Official Price Guide to Oriental Rugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The peregrinations of these peripatetic textiles have come full
circle, she adds. Many were made in the Middle East, bought by
Europeans, and then, when Europe's aristocrats fell on hard times,
acquired by affluent Americans. Now, says Bailey, they're being
bought by the wealthy in places like Kuwait and Qatar and loaded
onto planes bound for the region where they originated. They've
literally become ``flying carpets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
