<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9178 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-LEAF-BLOWERS-ART     11-19 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-LEAF-BLOWERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAF BLOWER TAKES OVER FOR THE RAKE IN SUBURBIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How many leaves must one man rake before he invests in a
machine? The answer, friends, is blowing in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Or into the woods in back of your house. Or into your driveway
or shrubbery, should you happen to be an unlucky suburbanite whose
neighbors care more about aesthetics than ethics when it comes to
leaf removal.
</P>
<P>
   Love 'em or leave 'em alone, praise their efficiency or curse
their nuisance potential, the power leaf blower has arrived _ and
noisily so _ to take its place beside the snow blower and ride-on
lawn mower as a tool of modern suburban living. Cruise through the
cul de sacs beyond Boston these days and you'll see more of these
appliances in use than Cuisinarts and minivans.
</P>
<P>
   In more upscale neighborhoods, yard workers wearing hooded
sweatshirts and backpack blowers scuttle across the landscape like
``Star Wars'' Stormtroopers on patrol. In zip codes where the house
lots tend to be smaller, and household incomes (if not leaf piles)
correspondingly less disposable, homeowners are more apt to strap
on air-spewing power packs and tackle the job themselves. Virtually
everywhere there are trees, though, the lowly rake has become
rather retro.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning in Wellesley, two residents named Rich and
Phil (both declined to give their last names, fearful perhaps that
a reporter was working undercover for the local Disposal Police)
were busily blowing up a storm of crinkly maple leaves in their
respective front yards. Rich was using a $50 electric blower,
although he said they ``stink'' compared to more powerful
gas-powered blowers, which are also costlier ($80 to $130) and more
polluting, not to mention cordless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought this one for my mother, but I borrowed it back
permanently, you might say,'' Rich confessed. ``It saves time,
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil, a retired engineer, stopped blowing leaves around his
10,000-square-foot lot long enough to show off his new toy, a
12-amp Toro combination leaf blower and vacuum unit. He happily
sucked up a small pile into the bag on his back, like a Hoover
salesman hoping to close a contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to rake, but it got too hard on my hands and knees,''
Phil said, laboring to be heard above the whine of the Toro. ``This
is better,'' he added. ``This is progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, though not everyone agrees. Since hitting the market in
the 1970s, leaf blowers have created a Luddite-like backlash in
scores of communities across the nation. Sales of blowers have
grown steadily over the past few years, from 75,000 units in 1985
to 464,000 in '87, 800,000 in '89 and more than a million units
today.
</P>
<P>
   In this area, where leaves abound and must be removed before
winter's first snow and ice freezes them to the ground for the
season, the contraptions cause relatively few complaints. But in
upscale communities, where pools and patios abound, it's a
different story.
</P>
<P>
   Carmel, Calif., was the first city to institute a ban on
blowers, in 1974. To date more than 300 municipalities have
followed suit, from Santa Monica to Greenwich, Conn. A California
public relations executive posted a treatise on ``leaf-blower
terrorism'' on the Internet, likening the machines to ghetto
blasters and off-road motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent improvements in noise reduction _ older-model gas
blowers roared at upwards of 110 decibels _ power blowers make
their presence felt wherever and however they are used. In at least
one case, the noise was a plus. During practice last year, New
England Patriots coach Pete Carroll revved up a pair of leaf
blowers to simulate crowd noise in Denver's Mile High Stadium. (The
Pats lost anyway, but that's another story.) Newton and Brookline,
Mass. are among the Massachusetts towns that ban the use of blowers
before 8 a.m. And in Newton, it's 9:30 a.m. on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Peter Scott of the Brookline Police Department says his
officers field few complaints about power leaf blowers, typically a
handful each season. ``Landscapers around here know the rules, and
those that don't know them learn in a hurry,'' says Scott. Usually
a first-time complaint draws a squad car and a warning. After that,
it's a $50 fine and a few choice words from the police.
</P>
<P>
   While it's against the law to blow leaves into the street, Scott
notes, Brookline, which bans overnight parking, sweeps its streets
with regularity, so delinquent leaf piles have little chance of
blowing back onto bordering lawns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are reasonable,'' Scott says. ``They want to get
along with their neighbors. Although my personal opinion is, they
should rake leaves. By hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Chet Herget, a professional landscaper in Westford, gets few
complaints about noise. ``Years ago,'' says Herget, ``owners put up
fences to keep out leaves from neighbors' yards. People are more
yard sensitive now. They keep up with their own cleanup because of
property values.''
</P>
<P>
   But yes, says Herget, squabbles arise from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some guy has been partying too late Saturday night, his
neighbor might go out early Sunday morning and try a little
payback.''
</P>
<P>
   For that job, Herget recommends a gas-powered blower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
