<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9180 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-19 1620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCEPTING A COLLEGE FRESHMAN'S NEW IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before your college freshman graces your doorstep next week,
only to deposit a kiss on your cheek and dirty clothes in the
laundry before disappearing with friends, consider this: Not only
is this particular Thanksgiving vacation the pits for parents, but
we should be thankful it is. That your child eschews your company
for friends is a sure sign she's making appropriate developmental
leaps.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the vacations in the four-year college period, a
freshman's Thanksgiving break is the most difficult, say family
therapists and college officials. Christmas break is not far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   The more prepared parents are for this, the better. ``Your child
is not the same person who left last August,'' says Karen Levin
Coburn, associate dean of students at Washington University in St.
Louis and coauthor of ``Letting Go: A Parents' Guide to
Understanding the College Years'' (Harper Collins, 3d edition).
</P>
<P>
   She tells parents to try not to get stuck on the obvious
changes, like a new hair color or facial piercings; that only
obscures more important psychological changes. ``Every student has
a new identity the parent isn't even part of,'' says Coburn.
</P>
<P>
   Even as you're experiencing shock at the way she looks (or talks
or eats or sleeps), she's going through a shock of her own. ``Each
child recreates himself at college and experiences massive change.
But strangely enough, she expects everything at home to stay the
same,'' says psychologist Linda Budd of the University of
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Any change _ siblings who are more grown up, rooms that have
been painted or rearranged, even a new bookshelf _ can be jolting.
``Life has gone on without them. They feel left out,'' says Budd.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest of all are the changes in relationships with friends.
Once they step in the door, anxiety starts to build: Will friends
be the same? Since the friends have had similar awakenings of their
own, the answer is: probably not.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are losses for a child,'' says Budd. ``They need to
grieve.'' She says irritability or anger we see at Thanksgiving, or
more likely during the longer Christmas vacation, is grief over
friendships that are lost or changes at home. Ironically, the more
adjusted and/or invested a student has become in college, the more
likely there is to be a disconnect with friends at home at the very
time he is trying to reconnect.
</P>
<P>
   ``A high school friend doesn't know what he's talking about when
he says, `I live on the 40,' or `We hang at the Rat,''' says
Coburn. ``It's dawning on him that he lives in two separate worlds
and he's wondering, `Which one do I really belong in?''' This can
be confusing, even scary.
</P>
<P>
   Budd learned the truth of that from her daughter when she picked
her up at college to bring her home for the first time. ``She got
in the car and asked, a little tearfully, `Is my home still my home
or is this my home?' I took a deep breath and told her, `Your home
will always be with us, but from now on you will have more than one
home.'''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Budd was wise not to answer her daughter in a dismissive
or defensive way _ ``Of course home is your home, what a silly
question!'' _ parents also shouldn't take it personally when a
child prefers to be with friends.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing a freshman knows he can count on to not have
changed is your love. ``When they run off with friends, they are
not rejecting you,'' says Budd. ``If anything, it's a tribute to
you, a sign they feel secure enough in your relationship to put
energy into other ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, parents who overreact can inadvertently make things
worse, says Michael J. Cunningham, director of New Student and
Parent Programs at Roger Williams University in Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   He says the natural consequence of the hurt is to withdraw
emotionally _ ``Fine, if that's what you want''; put up a fuss _
``How can you just walk out the door?''; or exert control _ ``You
have to be home by 1.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kind of lashing out,'' says Cunningham, ``a way to
bring the kid back into the fold.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't really children, and they aren't really adults,
but they feel to themselves like adults, so if you treat them as
children, arbitrarily setting rules, their response is to stay
away, be angry, and pull back,'' says Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   You were looking forward to a warm time together and what you've
got is conflict and hostility. Believe it or not, that isn't what
your child wants, either. ``They're as excited to come home as you
are to have them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is to focus on respect rather than rules and to have a
conversation about it before she comes home, over the phone this
weekend if necessary. Coburn suggests saying something like this:
``I know at college you come and go as you please, but at home,
we're still your parents. We need to figure out a way for you to
know that we respect you as a grown-up and for you to respect us as
parents, so we aren't worried all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Head off a conflict by asking, ``Will you be comfortable with
the same rules we've always had?'' Negotiate if you need to. In
other words, says Coburn, ``Let go of the idea that your child
needs your permission to do things, and negotiate out of
respectfulness for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham says that the more you own your emotions _ ``It's not
that I want to control what you do, it's that I feel better
knowing'' _ the less it will feel like you don't trust her and the
more she'll cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   There's another important distinction Cunninham urges parents to
make: ``What wasn't acceptable behavior before because a child was
too young or immature may be acceptable now, and you should say so.
But what wasn't acceptable before because it goes against family
values still isn't acceptable now.'' For instance, just because
your son's girlfriend sleeps in his room at college, doesn't mean
you have to allow it under your roof if it makes you uncomfortable.
But don't wait until he walks in with the girlfriend to talk about
it, cautions Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Talk in advance about household responsibilities, too. It may
feel OK to treat your returning student as a guest for a four-day
weekend, but it will wear thin over a four-week winter break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to give them a few days of sleeping late and
watching reruns, which all kids need, by the way,'' says Coburn.
Beyond that, however, they need structure. Talk about these issues
before the Christmas break: ``Do you want to volunteer or get a
job?'' Or, ``When you come in late, it wakes everybody. After the
holidays, your sisters and mom and I are back on schedules, waking
up early. How can we work this out?''
</P>
<P>
   Coburn promises that no other Thanksgiving vacation will be this
complicated. ``They get more competent at handling change and you
get better at them coming and going,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Johnson, the mother of three college graduates and one
current sophomore, is a veteran of comings and goings. She learned
to take in stride well-dressed daughters wearing ragged jeans and
kempt sons with hair down their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only time she can remember her husband being thrown
for a loop was during daughter Samantha's first vacation home. ``We
got into a very hot political debate at the table and he got me
alone in the kitchen and whispered in a panic, `I think she's
become a Communist!'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SUGGESTIONS FOR PARENTS &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Giving your child literal permission to see her friends _ ``I
understand how important it is to you to be with your friends, I
can wait until the next break for us to have real time together'' _
will remove pressure she feels to be all things to all people, not
to mention how grateful she'll feel.
</P>
<P>
   _Negotiate in advance what family obligations there will be.
</P>
<P>
   _Younger siblings can be very hurt by the lack of time a
freshman spends with them. Prepare them in advance: ``Christmas
will be a longer vacation; she'll have time to do things with you
then. At Thanksgiving, she may want to spend a lot of time with her
friends.'' Be alert to a sibling who feels left out by the
attention you lavish on the returning collegian.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't expect to engage your freshman intellectually over
Thanksgiving, but suggest it for Christmas break: ``I'm looking
forward to hearing more about that anthropology course.'' ``Maybe
there are some books you've read that I'd like.''
</P>
<P>
   _Don't spring major changes at home on him as a surprise or as a
way to cushion their impact, the dog dying, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   _At Thanksgiving, many freshman talk about transferring. Avoid
``I-told-you-so'' or dismissive comments. Ask instead: ``In what
ways does/doesn't it fit your expectations?'' If she comes home
unhappy, don't feel you have to rush in to solve problems; being a
good listener can be the best help you give.
</P>
<P>
   _Avoid reacting angrily to statements like, ``How can you go to
church? You're a hypocrite.'' It's part of her developmental growth
to question things she never did before. If she's open to it,
engage her in a discussion; otherwise, let it go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT: Recommended reading for a 4-to-9-year-olds: ``How
to Take Your Grandmother to the Museum,'' by Lois Wyse and her
granddaughter, Molly Rose Goldman (Workman).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
