<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE SPEAKER CREATES A STATE OF DESPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If it's true that the denouement for the New England
(nee Boston) Patriots has finally come, and that the 38-year
struggle to find a viable everlasting home in Greater Boston has
ended in defeat, then we have a problem on our hands which far
transcends the fate of this professional football team.
</P>
<P>
   The question is this: What kind of a political system do we have
if one locally elected official is allowed to become the unofficial
state dictator?
</P>
<P>
   We are now in the second decade of a peculiar political
circumstance. First it was State Senate President William Bulger
whose power mattered above all in this commonwealth. Now it is
Speaker of the House Thomas Finneran who controls our lives. Why
even bother to have a governor if some legislative czar is going to
wield all the power?
</P>
<P>
   So let's say it all comes to pass. Bob Kraft signs an
irrevocable deal to relocate his football team to a new complex in
Hartford, thus removing one of the primary professional sports
teams from both the largest metropolitan area and the entire
commonwealth. How could this happen?
</P>
<P>
   First, start with this comment from the current Senate
president: ``It never should have come to this,'' maintains Thomas
Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Senate president, Bob Kraft accepted a deal
approved by the Senate that was so antithetical to the new norm in
these matters that the senator is amazed the Patriots owner went
for it. In other words, they made Kraft a deal he could easily
refuse, and he surprised them by accepting it.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Finneran, Bob Kraft is trying to take advantage
of the unsuspecting taxpayers. They both can't be right.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham says it's a simple matter of finance. The difference
between the Senate deal, which would have the commonwealth buying
back land from Kraft after infrastructure improvements were made,
and the House deal, which would include no such proposal, is
$100,000 a year for the life of the deal ($2.3 million annually to
$2.2 million). If and when the Patriots go to Connecticut,
Massachusetts will lose $10 million a year in payroll taxes and
other income. If the good senator isn't fudging, I ask you, does
this make sense?
</P>
<P>
   Those aren't my numbers. Those are Senator Birmingham's.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is clear, at least to me. The Speaker is
offended by the drift of pro sports. Under the guise of fiscal
sanity, he is going to allow the Patriots to walk because, among
other things, ``Mike Piazza is getting $91 million to catch a
baseball.'' Quite aside from the fact that the Mets catcher is
being paid that sum to hit the baseball rather than catch it, what
does that have to do with the New England Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   In the Finneran world view, the answer is just about everything.
He is hardly sports-ignorant. He obviously yearns for the day when
5 bucks would get you into BU Field to see the Sweet Kentucky Babe
hook up with Gino for 6. Who wouldn't? Well, guess what, Mr.
Speaker. At the same time we were fortunate enough to have Parilli
to Cappelletti, a ticket to a movie at the (now-defunct) Gary
Theater cost a buck. The world has changed. Oh, and if you only
heard the sarcasm dripping from Mr. Speaker's voice, you'd
understand what the real problem is.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Finneran wants to teach the sports world a lesson. No
``whiny millionaire'' is going to push him around. If all the other
cities and states want to jump off a fiscal cliff, that doesn't
mean he has to. Most of all, he knows what's good for us, Tom
Finneran does. All by himself. And by extension, Tom Birmingham and
the 35 other state senators who made their deal for Kraft a 36-1
vote in their branch of the Legislature are either crazy or lying
to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Tom Finneran and you'd think it was no big deal if the
Patriots go skipping off to Connecticut. It's only sports, right?
It just so happens that sports are a part of our fabric, as are the
arts. Imagine the outrage if the Museum of Fine Arts or Symphony
Hall needed reasonable _ and I stress the word reasonable _
financial help from the commonwealth, without which one or both
would be forced to set up shop in Portland or Providence. There is
no difference here. A sports franchise is a major asset, defensible
on many levels, be they financial or psychic.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots are indeed gone, that may not be the end of the
story. Sooner or later, the Red Sox will find it necessary to deal
with our legislative leaders when they make the inevitable move
from Fenway Park. If he is still the unelected czar of
Massachusetts, will Tom Finneran decide that he won't be helping
them in any way because ``They paid Jose Offerman $26 million to
catch a baseball''?
</P>
<P>
   When arrogant, shortsighted politicians are in power, anything
can happen. Don't assume you'll always have the Boston Red Sox.
There once was an entity known as the Brooklyn Dodgers, and the
reason they left Brooklyn was a stadium issue. If Tom Finneran is
willing to kill one franchise, he'd have no qualms about killing
another. If you've seen one whiny millionaire, you've seen 'em all.
Right, Mr. Speaker?
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
