<SLUG> BC-SPACEY-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVIN SPACEY LEAPED AT CHANCE TO PLAY ANIMATED GRASSHOPPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHY CANO-MURILLO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Terrorizing young children, berating the elderly and
flaunting a scathing personality.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the behavior one would expect from an Oscar-winning
actor, especially in a Disney film.
</P>
<P>
   But please, rub your hind legs together for Kevin Spacey in ``A
Bug's Life,'' and his portrayal of Hopper, the baddest grasshopper
this side of the cinema.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had met John Lasseter (the director), and I loved ``Toy
Story,'' so we got to talking,'' he says while on the phone from
Dublin, Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   I dropped him a hint that I would love to star in an animated
film. Luckily, he picked up on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, my primary reason for doing ``A Bug's Life'' was
for kids. It didn't matter to me what part I got, just as long as
the story had morality and a good tale to tell, then it would be
worth it.``
</P>
<P>
   Lasseter didn't need a hint to offer Spacey the hairy-legged
role of Hopper. He knew Spacey and his growling voice would be
perfect as the scaly leader of a rowdy gang of grasshoppers,
bug-eyed insects who thrive on making life miserable for a colony
of hard-working and cheerful ants. Even with his character's
dangling antennae, Spacey made sure the words ``touchy-feely''
didn't exist in Hopper's personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the way my character is portrayed,'' he says. ``I hope
that kids stand up and scream and yell after seeing what Hopper
goes through. I want this to be something they remember for a long
time.``
</P>
<P>
   Along with co-stars Julia Louis-Dreyfus, Dave Foley and David
Hyde Pierce, Spacey spent almost two years perfecting his lines so
they would leap off the screen and into the thoughts of moviegoers.
Because computer animation is more complex than an underground ant
colony, his part, as well as those of the other characters, was
reworked multiple times over.
</P>
<P>
   The process begins with the actors watching line drawings of
their characters, then gradually adding dialogue and more
inflection. The actors are then videotaped, and with constant fine
tuning, the film is redrawn again and again to combine the actors
facial expressions, gestures and lip movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so awesome, but it's a very long process,'' he says. The
recording sessions last anywhere from 5-7 hours, then we would redo
them, sometimes 16 times. It's really quite miraculous once it's
all finished, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Backed up by his experience in heavy films such as ``L.A.
Confidential,'' ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evi'' and the
``Usual Suspects'' (for which he won an Academy Award), the
animation scene came as light as a fallen leaf for Spacey. Even
though recording the movie was grueling, his effort on the film was
not. Armed with lozenges and plenty of liquids, the only battle to
conquer in this case was straining those raspy vocal cords _ and
keeping a straight face while recording his parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the easiest job in the world; it was just like being
on a picnic,'' he quips. Especially with all that comical talent in
one room, everyone turned into kids. We had an endless amount of
goofy stuff happening. It was so hard to be serious a lot of
times.``
</P>
<P>
   Spacey is currently on location working on an Irish gangster
film, ``Ordinary Decent Criminal.'' Because of his distance, he
won't be able to see the completed version of`` A Bug's Life''
until Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   But he does know one thing: As much as he loved portraying the
monster mandible, he wants nothing to do with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing in common with Hopper,'' he says very
adamantly. ``I don't have wings, I don't have four hands _ although
sometimes I wish I did, and I don't have a wandering eye like
Hopper.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
