<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9187 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-PRAIRIE-BOS &LR;      11-19 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-PRAIRIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING THE PRAIRIE BACK HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In early September, circumstances placed me in Chicago, and when
I had some spare time, I placed myself amid the reconstructed
prairie at nearby Morton Arboretum.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the power of grasses, waving in the wind, stretching
endlessly (at least historically, and still in the mind's eye),
defining a region and, in part, even a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Morton's 100-acre Schulenberg Prairie is a mature, 35-year-old
planting whose stretch is not endless, only to the suburban houses
along one edge, a highway along another, and savannah and woods
bounding the interior arboretum sides.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it evoked in me strong feelings of how the landscape
appeared 150 years ago, of the lonesome and frightening awe it must
have drawn from early European arrivals as ``civilization'' began
the trickle that became a torrent that swept away almost all of the
prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Prairies are not all grasses, they just look that way. What I
saw was big and little bluestem and switch grasses mixed with
prairie and yellow gentians and purple prairie clovers. There were
sunflowers and butterfly weed and mints and asters. Black-eyed
Susans and coneflowers and coreopsis dotted the mix, and on the
list went.
</P>
<P>
   And while many of these plants would prefer Illinois to the
wetter life of the Boston suburbs, you can tell from the ones I've
named that if you were so inclined, it would be possible to
construct a reasonable facsimile of a prairie here.
</P>
<P>
   I am not so inclined, though I am growing a bunch of those
plants, including big bluestem (Andropogon gerardii), perhaps the
grass most associated with prairies, and sideoats grama (Bouteloua
curtipendula), another prairie grass.
</P>
<P>
   So-called ornamental grasses have attracted me for years. I
began by leaving some natives (never did identify them) in a yellow
cactus garden I planted. They looked nice, stiff vertical brushes
of green and brown, though I have been reducing their numbers, or
attempting to, for the last few years in an effort to bring order
to the chaos of this self-indulgent bed, where sedums and my fancy
have run amok.
</P>
<P>
   I edged the bed in blue fescue (Festuca ovina `glauca'), which
grows in clumps and sends up a bluish haze of fruiting heads. I
like this veiling effect. I grew these from seed, and they were as
easy as anything I have ever grown.
</P>
<P>
   My next venture into ornamentals had a practical side. I wanted
to block the northwest wind on the front corner of our property,
partly to protect other plantings by breaking wintry blasts, but
mainly because each fall the wind swept everybody else's leaves
onto my lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Bigelow Nurseries in Northborough had a nice selection of maiden
grass (Miscanthis sinensis `gracillimus'), which right now has
seven-foot-tall plumes, and ravenna grass (Erianthus ravennae),
10-footers.
</P>
<P>
   The towering, golden brown stalks block the leaves, break the
wind, and look incredible all winter, especially when there is
snow. In early spring, I whack them down and tie them in sheaves,
which I lean against a fence for decorative effect.
</P>
<P>
   There are drawbacks. Although they are clumping plants, they
still expand, and the roots are thick and woody. It takes a hatchet
and saw and sharp spade to divide them, and they do like to be
divided every few years. The ravenna grass is looking sparse this
year, and I am going to have to dig and hack and swear at it until
it bends to my will (or I am taken away).
</P>
<P>
   I have divided the miscanthis and stuck two chunks at one end of
the new roadside border. Substantial, they define that end of the
border, and the cyber goddess with whom I dwell tells me to plant
more (though I do not believe she plans to be home the day I next
divide these guys).
</P>
<P>
   The other end of this bed widens and is anchored by a red maple
where it juts into the lawn and a bed of day lilies by the road.
Now, day lilies are not grasses, but they do have a grasslike look
to them, and I decided to play off that and establish a large area
of similar foliage types. I hoped to exaggerate the depth of the
bed and draw the eye into it, veiling but not blocking the view out
from our front yard.
</P>
<P>
   I again turned to ornamental grasses, this time mail order from
Tripple Brook Farm in Southampton. Along the front edge I planted a
line of sweet vernal grass (Anthoxanthum odoratum), which bunches
and is fragrant when dried. Mine is about a foot high. That fronts
-sideoats grama, which sends up two- to three-foot-tall seed stalks
with the seeds all lined up along one side.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese pennisetum (Pennisetum alopecuroides) is next, graceful
fountains with feathery plumes. Finally, there is the big bluestem,
four-foot stands with bluish nodes on the stems and purplish flower
heads in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   I also grow some bamboos, which are members of the grass family,
but, for no good reason, I don't think of them that way.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other grasses (family Poaceae) and grasslike
plants. Sedges (family Cyperaceae) and rushes (family Juncaceae)
are often thought of as grasses, and you will find them lumped
together at nurseries, which increasingly carry them. (Just
remember, to tell the difference, sedges have edges, rushes are
round, and grasses are hollow with knees to the ground.)
</P>
<P>
   They perform many functions, tying gardens together, giving a
good late summer and fall show, blending well with other autumn
perennials. They can be specimens or groundcovers and anything in
between. In the 1980s, the great landscape architects James van
Sweden and Wolfgang Oehme carried their use to new heights, in
public gardens and corporate plantings.
</P>
<P>
   Grasses don't require a lot. Some like damp soil, and very few
will stand any real shade. Grasses, which do fine in poor soil,
provide nearly year-round interest in exchange for occasional
division and cutting down in late &UR;  &LR; winter or early spring (unless
you can talk your way into having an annual burn, like they do in
the reconstructed prairies of Illinois).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
