<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA AND LINDA -- DIRECT FROM THE LADIES' ROOM
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   The Monica Lewinsky-Linda Tripp tapes are significant not just
because of their connection to President Clinton but because they
reveal at last the answer to a question that has baffled men for
eons: What do women talk about when they go off together to the
ladies' room?
</P>
<P>
   This is it, guys. It's on the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Monica: ``I hate him. I hate him. I hate him.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda: ``Well, if you really hated him, you'd pack your bags and
scoot out.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course this kind of girl-talk isn't confined to ladies'
rooms. It can happen anywhere. The ladies' room, though, is a
classic arena. You know how it goes: You're in a restaurant, having
what you think is a perfectly good time when suddenly the women in
the group rise as one and go off to the ladies' room. You wait and
you wait. They don't come back. What are they doing in there? What
are they talking about? You start feeling paranoid, and you should,
because they're in the ladies' room talking about you, dissecting
the relationship, revealing all your secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Monica: ``I never even came close to sleeping with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda: ``Why? Because you were standing up?''
</P>
<P>
   They talk about you a lot of the time, anyway. Sometimes they
talk about more important matters.
</P>
<P>
   Monica: ``I got _ oh, oh _ and I bought a beautiful, beautiful
red very thin silk sweater top.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda: ``Ooh.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica: ``That's for my next visit. If I ever have one.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda: ``You in red. Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   This is fascinating stuff, no? In fairness, though, I have to
note that most ladies' room conversations aren't quite as riveting
as the tape talk because most don't have somebody like Linda Tripp
to draw out the other participants.
</P>
<P>
   Monica: ``I did see the cutest boy in the elevator yesterday.'
</P>
<P>
   Linda: ``Oh, where?''
</P>
<P>
   Monica: ``At Bloomingdale's. He was so cute.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there nothing Linda Tripp won't do for her country? Is no
sacrifice too great? Somebody should pin a medal on her. Or maybe
drive a stake through her heart.
</P>
<P>
   Her performance on these tapes is Oscar-worthy. The way she
feigns compassion for a clearly distraught Lewinsky. The convincing
way she flat-out lies (Monica: ``You know what's really weird? I
keep hearing these double clicks.'' Linda: ``That's my gum''). The
way she elicits information that otherwise might have passed
unnoted. Barbara Walters, eat your heart out.
</P>
<P>
   Monica: ``I just wish I could do something, I wish I could do
something that would make him go, `Gee, I was stupid,' you know?
`Boy, I was really dumb to let her go,' or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda: ``Mm-hmmm.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica: ``You know what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Linda: ``Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.''
</P>
<P>
   If they weren't talking about the president of the United
States, the conversation would be numbingly boring. Even taking
that into consideration, it's boring.
</P>
<P>
   Monica: ``I think he talked himself out of even being attracted
to me. I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda: ``Really?''
</P>
<P>
   Really. Some women will tell you they don't ever have
conversations like this in the ladies' room, or anyplace else for
that matter. Don't believe it. We revert to adolescence when the
talk turns to boys, clothes, makeup, shoes, hair. If somebody taped
our conversations and replayed them on MSNBC for the world to hear
we'd be as embarrassed as Monica must be today.
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1346EST &QL; 
