A9196 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      11-19 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD SUPER DUTY IS SUPER LATIVE  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Macho truck guys adore the mighty Ford F-250 Super
Duty. Its hulking appearance, its brawny V-10 engine, its broad
interior: This is a big rig among pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I set out in the Super Duty, I sneered at the common
run of pickups. To paraphrase Crocodile Dundee: ``You call that a
truck? That's not a truck. Now, (begin ital) this (end ital) is a
truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting things back into perspective for a moment, the Super
Duty is a truck for the job site. For personal use, it could be
used for carrying big loads, towing heavy objects or lugging a
camper.
</P>
<P>
   But the Super Duty is not exactly the kind of pickup you'd
choose for your hip urban vehicle, as you might an F-150
flare-side. No, this tough guy is big and heavy and drives like a
truck. A big, heavy truck.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, some people (mostly guys) will dig tooling around in this
big unit. On the freeway, you feel as if you're piloting a semi,
partly due to the interior's expansive glass, high ceiling and wide
shoulder room.
</P>
<P>
   This thing doesn't come cheap, either, though considering its
sturdiness, capabilities and high level of creature comforts, the
Super Duty probably is priced pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   The only really trucklike thing I did was take a load of
furniture and other stuff to St. Vincent's thrift store. That
wouldn't tax the F-250's abilities very much, though.
</P>
<P>
   The guys at the thrift-store loading dock were mighty impressed
with the rig.
</P>
<P>
   Take note that this is the least heavy-duty of the Super Duty
contingent, a rear-wheel-drive Super Cab model rated at 8,800
pounds gross vehicle weight (the truck plus its maximum payload).
In other words, you can carry about 3,000 pounds in this boy.
</P>
<P>
   Super Duty trucks also come in four-wheel-drive and include a
heavier-duty F-350 in various configurations and payload
capacities, including stake-body trucks and the like. The
granddaddy is the F-550, with a gross vehicle weight of 17,500
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The three-quarter-ton F-250, and its 1-ton stablemate, the
F-350, are new for '99. They ride on a different chassis than the
standard F-series trucks, and will help to continue Ford's reign as
bestselling pickup truck in America.
</P>
<P>
   If you see a resemblance between the Super Duty and the big
Dodge Ram, especially the semitruck styling of the front end,
that's no accident. The Ram was a revolutionary design, boosting
Dodge truck sales, a stylistic coup that redefined the muscular
image of pickups. Ford has followed suit, making the Super Duty
look as hunky as it is.
</P>
<P>
   The test truck also came with another fixation of the '90s: a
four-door stretch cab. This big cab potentially could seat six,
including three across the front bench seat, though the rear seat
has less comfort than most would desire for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   The longer four-door Crew Cab model has a full-size rear seat,
sort of like a huge sport-utility vehicle with a pickup bed.
</P>
<P>
   The front seats in the test truck, equipped with the high-end,
$2,500 Lariat trim package, are very comfortable, helping to take
the edge out of the rugged road manners. But leather seating in
what is essentially a tough work truck seems a bit much.
</P>
<P>
   Those who enjoy a high seating position, well, come and get it.
</P>
<P>
   Our tester came with the optional Triton V-10, a mill that makes
this huge vehicle jump off the line like a jack rabbit and roar up
to highway speed. Passing power is a bit lax, typical of a truck
engine with more grunt than cruising finesse.
</P>
<P>
   Why a V-10? Well, for one thing, there's lots of pulling power.
A V-10 delivers the torque with hardly any harshness or vibration.
The standard Super Duty engine is a beefy V-8, or one can go up to
the massive pulling power of a 7.3-liter diesel with 235 horsepower
and 500 pound-feet of torque. That's a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodge Ram also offers a V-10 engine, one that shares basic
architecture with the awesome powerhouse in the Dodge Viper
roadster. Hmmm. Maybe Ford could use its V-10 to power a superhot
sports car, too. A new generation Thunderbird, perhaps? Hint, hint.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a price to pay for all this size and heft and
power. And that's gas mileage. According to the computer reading in
the cab, we got only an average of 10 miles per gallon in mostly
city driving.
</P>
<P>
   Pumping up the price is the optional equipment, including the
$2,500 Lariat package, $970 for an automatic transmission, $310 for
limited-slip differential, a $190 paint job, $150 trailer hitch,
$150 chrome bumper and a whopping $500 for anti-lock brakes, which
should come as standard equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Handling is limited by size and bulk, and the ride is bouncy at
best. A good bump in the road will rattle your fillings. But for
what it is, the Super Duty is quite driveable, with good steering,
effective brakes and that awesome power.
</P>
<P>
   And compared with big, lumbering trucks of the past, the Super
Duty is downright sporty. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ford F-250 Super Duty &QL; 
Vehicle type: Six-passenger, four-door stretch-cab pickup,
rear-wheel drive. &QL; 
Base price: $23,305. &QL; 
Price as tested: $29,135. &QL; 
Engine: 6.8-liter V-10, 275 horsepower at 4,250 rpm, 410 pound-feet
of torque at 2,650 rpm. &QL; 
Gross vehicle weight: 8,800 pounds. &QL; 
Wheelbase: 141.8 inches. &QL; 
EPA fuel economy: 10 mpg overall (observed). &QL; 
Highs: Brawny power. Rugged good looks. Comfortable cab. &QL; 
Lows: Pricey options. Mediocre gas mileage. Rugged ride. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
