<HEADLINE>
GADGETS GALORE AT THE COMDEX COMPUTER SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ There was enough high-powered gear to outfit a NASA
launch facility at the Comdex computer trade show this week. But it
was the consumer equipment that was making headlines, especially
the flat-panel displays and hand-held computers that the major
vendors believe will produce a surge in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the eye-catchers for the home computer user
featured at the Las Vegas event:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Cyrix WebPAD: This a carry-around, three-pound tablet that
provides a direct connection to the World Wide Web. Input is by
stylus. The device measures 8 1/2 by 11 inches, the same as a piece
of office paper. It is due on store shelves next summer. Although
the price has yet to be determined, a Cyrix source says it will
cost under $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ daVinci: The Palm Pilot has taken the personal digital
assistant market by storm. But if you're going to be using your
organizer to track phone numbers and dates and jot the occasional
short note, do you really need to spend $400? Royal, the typewriter
people, are betting that the Pilot's price tag will make people
take a look at the daVinci palm-sized organizer.
</P>
<P>
   For $100, the daVinci offers almost all the functions of the
Pilot, though the on-board memory is a bit stingy (256 K vs. 4 megs
and up for the Pilots). But if you don't have thousands of friends
to keep track of, this hand-held organizer does the job. It
features a snazzy black case with a functional fold-back protective
lid. The optional folding keyboard ($30) is pretty cute, but the
tiny buttons are a bit tough to use. Available now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ GoType! Keyboard: Frustrated with the pen-based input system
of the Palm Pilot? Then consider the GoType! It's a smallish, but
very usable keyboard that the Pilot fits into. No power connection
is needed for it draws a trickle from the Pilot's batteries. About
$70. Shipments began last week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Sharp Mobilon Pro 5000: The Sharp Mobilon Pro 5000 looks like
a slightly smaller version of a standard laptop. But the LCD screen
is brilliant, the lithium ion battery is a real workhorse, and the
keyboard is very functional. The side flip-out modem connector is a
dream to use.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Xircom RealPort PC cards: If you're a regular laptop user, you
probably know the hassles of using a PC card-based modem: They
usually have some special connector or fragile pop-out phone jack.
All of which can very easily be lost or broken. Xircom has come up
with a modem card with the jacks built in.
</P>
<P>
   No fancy connectors. No flimsy pop-outs. The downside is that
the device takes up both PC card bays, but most people only use one
bay at a time anyway. Prices start at $199 retail for the plain
vanilla 56 K card.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ PC-Unite: Casio's PC-Unite watch has a lot of beef inside.
There's a scrolling display across the face. The watch holds
schedule, contacts, to-dos and all that crucial information. And it
links to a desktop by way of an optional infrared device, or with
the included cabling. It also includes synch software for the
Microsoft Outlook personal information software. $299, due out in
January.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ SynchMaster LCD Monitor: Comdex featured a sea of flat-panel
displays. Prices swung wildly and so did quality. Samsung's new 330
TFT seems to be the best of the low ends. It's only 13.3 inches on
the diagonal, but that's actual viewing size (its screen has as
much real estate as a 15-inch tube monitor). It has a maximum
resolution of 1024-by-75, and looks bright and sharp. Retailing for
$799, it is available now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Digital Voice Recorder: This Olympus hand-held voice recorder
stores thoughts on a memory chip (33 minutes maximum) and then
plays them back into a computer, where voice recognition software
converts the information into text. It also plays back in regular
audio through an on-board speaker. Nifty _ for $299. Out now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Clik: This is Iomega's portable addition to its Zip/Jaz
lineup. Weighing 4 ounces, it comes with its own miniature disks
and recharging stand and it hooks to digital cameras and computers.
Disks top out at 40 MB. The device costs $199 for the basic setup
and is available now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Memory Stick: Sony's Memory Sticks are chewing gum-sized
memory storage devices that can be shoved into a PC card and then
into a laptop. The sticks can store up to 8 MB of data. $99.95 for
the 4MB with the PC adapter thrown in. Available now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
