<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FELICIANO-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FELICIANO REMAINS TRUE TO HIS LATIN ROOTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in senor; an eacute, or accent
mark, needed over e in Jose) 
 
By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Decades before Chayanne steamed up the big screen, or
Selena shimmied her way into the hearts of the world, or Gloria
Estefan commanded U.S. audiences to shake their body and do the
conga, Jose Feliciano was successfully breaking down language
barriers to establish himself as an international superstar.
</P>
<P>
   His sound _ a soothing hybrid of jazz, folk, soul and Latin
rhythms _ earned the Puerto Rican singer a number of hits, most
notably a Grammy-winning cover of the Doors' ``Light My Fire'' and
the holiday chestnut ``Feliz Navidad.'' That song is still a
perennial favorite, most recently popping up on Celine Dion's new
collection of Christmas tunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never imagined that Feliz Navidad would be such a hit,''
Feliciano said over the phone from a tour stop in Florida. ``I
wrote it because at the time I was lonesome for my family in Puerto
Rico _ my brothers, my mother. I wanted to feel close to them, and
so I wrote Feliz Navidad.''
</P>
<P>
   Three decades, six Grammys and dozens of platinum albums later,
Feliciano, who was born blind, is still going strong. His latest
album, ``Senor Bolero,'' is a smoldering collection of romantic
tunes that harkens back to the singer's humble beginnings recording
boleros in South America.
</P>
<P>
   Feliciano will be showcasing both new and old material during
his concert Saturday night in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing with `Senor Bolero' was that I used to sing boleros
back in 1966, and then I left it for a while in 1971, and I started
singing ballads,'' Feliciano said. ``I wanted to come to the public
with the bolero, and of course, when I started, it was me, guitar
and percussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard this program on the radio about a year ago, and the
name of the program was `Senor Bolero,' and I thought to myself,
`Boy what a great title to come back with a bolero album.'''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Feliciano's return to his roots has proved successful.
The album's first single, `Me Has Echado Al Olvido,' is topping
radio airplay charts in New York, Miami and Puerto Rico, and it is
No. 17 with a bullet on Billboard's Hot Latin Tracks. Feliciano has
high hopes for his fans in Texas, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really hoping that the Mexican community in Houston also
gets behind it, because I like Texas. I like San Antonio, I like
Houston, I like El Paso. I'm really hoping for big things from
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The bolero is just one in the long list of sounds and styles
Feliciano has mastered. The 53-year-old guitarist and singer has
recorded songs in four languages; he wrote the music for Ray
Bradbury's play ``The Wonderful Ice Cream Suit''; and he composed
and performed the theme for the 1970s TV show ``Chico and the
Man.'' Feliciano said that diversity has kept him inspired over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's what's kept me up, kept me going for 31 years. I
think that when a performer isn't versatile, he then fades into
oblivion, and with me, I've always been a versatile performer,''
Feliciano said. ``I can play rock 'n' roll, I can play jazz, I can
play Spanish, I can play Tex-Mex if I want to. I mean, I can do
anything, and I owe that to God because to have those kind of
abilities is a rare thing. I don't say it to be conceited or
anything. I'm a very blessed person with having all these
abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Feliciano was one of the first Latin artists to win a Grammy. He
took two statues home in 1968, for best new artist and best male
vocalist. Since that time, Feliciano has taken note of the changing
face of Latin music and its current leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my career, there weren't artists like Gloria Estefan or
Jon Secada. There were none of those people during the time that I
was in music, and so I think that the doors have opened up more for
Latin music. Carlos Santana, who's my dear friend, has opened a lot
of doors. And then, of course, the Tex-Mex groups like Little Joe y
la Familia and, of course, Selena.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Feliciano's list of listenables is surprisingly
bubble-gum friendly, thanks to his 7-year-old son Jonathan Jose.
Feliciano has been married since 1971 and has two other children,
Melissa Anne and Michael Julian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like groups like Savage Garden. My little boy has made me
aware of 'N Sync. I do like the Backstreet Boys; I think they're
good. The Spice Girls you can keep,'' he said with a slight laugh.
``They're OK, but musically I just enjoy the real musician groups,
like Boyz II Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Balancing career and family is an admitted challenge for the
singer, whose end-of-the-year plate also includes attending the
White House tree-lighting ceremony in December and more touring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I love my family, when the kids grow up, they have
their own lives, and I still want to keep my career. My career is
very important,'' Feliciano said. ``They all tell me, `Oh Dad, you
have to go again. I miss you,' but that's natural. They know that I
love them and that I'm going out to work for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Feliciano's ultimate goal, though, is something he continues to
strive for even after achieving it so many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to show the American contingency that just because
you were Latin didn't mean that you couldn't happen in their
music,'' Feliciano said. ``I followed kind of like in the steps of
Ritchie Valens, in a sense, although I didn't change my name like
he did. (Valens changed his name from Valenzuela.) I stuck to my
guns when the record company wanted to change my name to Joe
Phillips. I said, `No. My name is Jose Feliciano, and that's what
it will be.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is that I've always been proud of the fact that I'm
Latin, and I'm proud of the fact that I'm a Latin who lives in a
great country like America. I enjoy both.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
