<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9247 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DIAZ-PROFILE-HNS     11-19 1530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DIAZ-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME VERY GOOD THINGS ARE HAPPENING TO CAMERON DIAZ 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The first thing Cameron Diaz does when she gets to the
table is drop her lipstick and dive unselfconsciously down between
the chair legs to fish it out.
</P>
<P>
   Nice icebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   She comes up giggling, but that turns out not to be of
particular note because she giggles after half the things she says.
</P>
<P>
   Why she has lipstick is not clear. She doesn't seem to be
wearing any _ or much else in the way of makeup. Not that most
people figure she needs a lot of makeup: big mouth, pale blue eyes,
strong facial features.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz also has no earrings, and there is a Band-aid wrapped
unceremoniously around the end of the ring finger of the right
hand, which she often runs through her short, dark blond hair,
pulling it back behind her ears.
</P>
<P>
   She's wearing a long-sleeved purple blouse over a black body
stocking top, with a purple stone necklace and dark gray slacks.
She looks casual, but somehow seems not completely relaxed. Her
body posture, often pulling her head down and shoulders in as
though hiding, battles with a natural effervescent quality. You
quickly realize she is gun-shy, or downright suspicious, of
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she easily holds her own. Asked a question about her
personal life, she feigns deafness.
</P>
<P>
   ``What? I'm sorry, what did you say?'' (Giggle.)
</P>
<P>
   Well, there goes any chance of inside information about what
happened in her now-defunct relationship with ``There's Something
About Mary'' co-star Matt Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, 26, was born in Long Beach, Calif., to parents of
Cuban-American (her dad) and European-American Indian (her mom)
heritage. Athletic, thin and 5-foot-9, she was a catalog model
before getting into movies in 1994's ``The Mask ''opposite Jim
Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   Until last summer, Diaz was recognized more for her looks and a
zillion magazine photos than for her acting talents.
</P>
<P>
   Then came ``There's Something About Mary,'' and she became known
as the woman in ``that'' movie. When we talked at the Toronto Film
Festival, the movie had already become a long-run surprise. Here it
is November, and it continues playing.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz still isn't known for her acting talent, but she is quite
well-known as Mary, the character who had that ... that ... well,
stuff in her hair. (Sorry, if you are one of the eight people in
North America who did not see the movie; you'll have to ask someone
else what we're talking about here.)
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters now that ``There's Something About Mary'' is
a blockbuster and that scene has acquired semi-legendary status.
But just for the record, Diaz did have reservations about acting
with that unmentionable gel in her hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually did talk to those guys (the movie's director-writer
team of brothers Bobby and Peter Farrelly) about it a couple of
times,'' Diaz said. She goes into a comically pretentious voice:
``Being the actor, my responsibility is to make sure the character
is valid throughout the entire thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in her normal voice: ``I felt that particular scene might
take away any sort of validity, make Mary look like an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I said: `You know, guys, you want Mary to be a
babe, right? She has to look good. I don't care who you are, any
girl who looks like that has to glance in the mirror once in a
while to check the lipstick.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think even Mary, who is the coolest girl, might take a
glance in a window reflection or something and realize her hair is
standing straight up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for movie history, the Farrellys did not agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were like, `What are you talking about? This is going to
be the funniest thing anybody's ever seen. Just do it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So you're, like, (a resigned voice) `OK, all right.'''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz shot the scene the way the Farrellys wanted, she did get
them to try something else first.
</P>
<P>
   ``They humored me and let me do it another way with the hair
just in a glob, kind of down,'' Diaz said. ``We looked at it and
said `No.' So we put it up, and it worked. They were right.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the impact of ``There's Something About Mary,'' it's
amazing that Diaz's next role and film are even further out there.
Diaz is just one of many characters in the ensemble cast of ``Very
Bad Things,'' which opens Wednesday, but her role is quite
outrageous, even in a film filled with outrageousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very Bad Things,'' written and directed at breakneck pace and
mind-numbing volume by Peter Berg (Dr. Kronk on TV's ``Chicago
Hope'') tells what happens when a Las Vegas bachelor party goes
abysmally wrong. Like, one of the guys at the party accidentally
kills the guest prostitute. And they decide to bury her in the
desert.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz plays Laura, the bride-to-be, whose obsessed wedding
planning is threatened when her groom might be arrested for a tiny
murder _ or two or three. Diaz's role is relatively small until
near the end of the film, when her determination to have her
wedding go just as she's dreamed leads her to do some things as
extreme as those that the bachelor-party bachelors have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure at one time Laura was a really great girl (giggle),
ya know, BW _ Before the Wedding,'' Diaz said. ``She probably had a
pretty strong moral base, but then the wedding came in and she lost
herself in it.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be fair to tell what Laura does in the scene, but it
is definitely severe and illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't ever see Laura as really cruel,'' Diaz said. ``She's
just a little delusional. She loses sight of what (marriage) is
really about. I don't think she was justified in her actions, but
certainly something had to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz may not be getting married in real life for a while, but
she has had plenty of practice in the movies. Just last year she
played a character whose movie wedding was disrupted by Julia
Roberts in ``My Best Friend's Wedding.'' Previously, she was a
bride in ``Feeling Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot about weddings over the last few years. I've
had a few different types, so (she turns on a melodramatic voice)
I'm just jaded now. It's over for me.''
</P>
<P>
   What has she learned from her movie weddings?
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I could never ever plan a wedding,'' she said. ``I
am just not that girl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very Bad Things'' may be the darkest comedy since ``Pulp
Fiction.'' As in ``There's Something About Mary,'' the humor is
often gross, but unlike Mary, there is a mean, sometimes gory edge
to it. If ``There's Something About Mary'' surprised some viewers,
``Very Bad Things'' is likely to shock them.
</P>
<P>
   She admits being disturbed when she found herself laughing at
something that could be considered horrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I laughed at a couple of things that I didn't laugh at the
first time I saw it,'' Diaz admitted. ``The first time I was kind
of like going, why are people laughing at that? People were really
bellowing at a couple of scenes that were disturbing to me. I was
like, what is going on?
</P>
<P>
   ``This time I found myself laughing at the absurdity of it.''
</P>
<P>
   From her first film role in ``The Mask,'' Diaz has been
associated with subversive humor. Or, as they say in the reviews,
``not for all tastes.'' Does that kind of humor reflect her own
style?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say, yeah,'' she said. ``I definitely think you can't
play those things if you don't understand or you don't get it. I'm
not doing Shakespeare. I haven't yet grasped the whole, you know _
whatchamacallit _ come on, help me out, uh, we're back in time ...
''
</P>
<P>
   Period piece?
</P>
<P>
   ``Period piece! My brain is not working. I haven't really done
anything like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies for me, it's always the movies I liked when I was a
kid. `Raiders of the Lost Ark' _ I saw that movie a million times.
That was an escape _ something you would love to be able to do.
It's like fantasy _ something you never would really get to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``My idea of films is being able to go into a theater and forget
about the reality of where you live and where you're at. All the
films I've done are slightly on the edge: They're borderline;
there's not a reality base to it. You play it straight, but the
situations are sort of absurd and fantastical.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Mary'' has ensured Diaz of getting more and
better script offers. Her next film will be ``The League,''
directed by Oliver Stone, in which she plays the general manager of
a football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really nice to have options,'' Diaz said, ``to have the
opportunity to work with Oliver and Al Pacino and James Woods and
Dennis Quaid (all in the film).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm terrified at that. I'm sure I'm going to apologize all the
way through and possibly be handing back cash they handed over to
me before I started. (But) I trust Oliver, and he says he thinks I
can do it,'' she said with another giggle.
</P>
<P>
   Since Diaz does such bad things in ``Very Bad Things,'' it's
easy to wonder if she's ever done any bad things she's ashamed of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chopped up a journalist once and put him in a suitcase and
dug a hole in the desert,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Time to go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
