<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ Coverage of Special Prosecutor Kenneth
Starr's appearance before Judiciary committee. (Carr/Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-WITNESSES _ WASHINGTON _ A look at the four new
witnesses subpoenaed by the House Judiciary Committee in its
impeachment inquiry _ who they are, what their connections to the
case are, what sort of previous testimony they've given in the
investigation, and why the committee wants to question them.
(Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-BARR _ WASHINGTON _ How does Bob Barr acquit himself?
(Carr/Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MOORE _ WASHINGTON _ Satirical documentary maker Michael
Moore roamed the Rayburn Building halls, wearing a baseball cap
with ``S'' for sex. He apparently sprayed Rep. Bob Barr with whip
cream and attacked his fitness to pass judgment on the president.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE _ WASHINGTON _ The scene as Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr testifies before the House Judiciary Committee on the
question of impeaching President Clinton. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-WHOUSE _ Reaction and scene at the White House.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TV _ Television coverage of the impeachment hearings.
(Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TEXANS _ WASHINGTON _ A sidebar on the two Texans on the
House Judiciary Committee and how they react to impeachment witness
Kenneth Starr. (Harlan, Cox News Service 500).
</P>
<P>
   (Scratched) IMPEACH-ANALYSIS _ WASHINGTON.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-EXCERPTS _ Text from Starr's statement and questioning.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ House Ways and Means Committee
holds a hearing Thursday to discuss a ``road map'' for Social
Security reform. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SMALLPOX _ WASHINGTON _ The world's last samples of the smallpox
virus are stored in Atlanta and Russia. With bioterror a rising
threat, experts debate at a meeting Thursday whether they should be
destroyed. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SAFE-TURKEY _ WASHINGTON _ The Center for Science in the Public
Interest holds a news conference to discuss, ``How Safe is Your
Thanksgiving Turkey?'' Topics include a review of the first year of
the new federal food safety program. (Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (d) food categories.
</P>
<P>
   AGRICULTURE-TEXAS _ WASHINGTON _ In the new Congress, both the
chairman and ranking Democrat on the House Agriculture Committee
will be Texans. Reps. Larry Combest and Charles Stenholm have a
history of working well together, and Texas agriculture interests
are hopeful that their cooperation could mean good policies for the
state. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Continuing spot coverage of the
Microsoft antitrust trial. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CLINTON _ TOKYO _ Taking his message of hope and change
far from home, President Clinton gave Japan an economic pep talk on
Thursday, urging the country to get behind a controversial set of
programs aimed at ending seven years of stagnation here that is
dragging down the world economy. With Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
struggling to implement $700 billion worth of initiatives meant to
shore up the country's debt-ridden banks and stimulate spending and
growth, Clinton avoided high-pressure rhetoric, publicly at least,
and instead encouraged the Japanese to embrace Obuchi's plans.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: UPDATES budget line, CHANGES slug from CLINTON-JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   MOVED in both the International and Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TOWN _ TOKYO _ President Clinton traveled 8,000 miles
away from Thursday's impeachment proceedings on Capitol Hill, but
it wasn't far enough to escape questions about his relationship
with Monica Lewinsky. Venturing back into what was once among his
favorite public settings, Clinton hosted a televised town hall
style forum here on Thursday, and an Osaka housewife threw him a
fastball. ''Regarding Miss Monica Lewinsky _ how did you apologize
to Mrs. Clinton and Chelsea,'' the mother of two wanted to know.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in both the International and Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-THANKS _ LONDON _ While the turkey will be British and
the football round, the city from which the Mayflower embarked for
the New World wants Americans to come and feel at home for
Thanksgiving. The port city of Plymouth is making plans for its
first American Thanksgiving Festival, complete such exotic-sounding
dishes as succotash and pumpkin pie to complement a dinner of
turkey with cranberry sauce. By some counts, as many as 250,000
Americans live in the United Kingdom, and many feel somewhat
dislocated during periods of traditional U.S. holidays such as
Independence Day, Halloween and Thanksgiving. And despite a full
embrace by many Britons of such American cultural icons as
McDonald's, shopping malls and Homer Simpson, there is only a vague
awareness that there is any significance to last Thursday of
November. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in both the International and Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GOV-BUSH-ED-PLAN _ NEW ORLEANS _ Gov. G.W. Bush goes national
with his education plan. The governor is scheduled to make
presentation at Republican Governors Association meeting. (Herman,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO _ Alabama Gov. Fob James and Alabama Attorney General
Bill Pryor went to war against each other this week over the
national tobacco agreement, with Pryor saying he intends to approve
the deal by Friday and James and his hired lawyers saying that is
too hasty. Checking on where the other states in the South stand.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAS-PROTEST _ Advance to Sunday protest in Columbus of the
U.S. Army's School of the Americas, which trains Latin American
Army officers. Several thousand demonstrators are expected to be
there, including actor Martin Sheen and dozens will likely be
arrested. Opponents call it a school for assassins. Supporters say
it boosts Democracy in the region. (Anderson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   OZARKA-SUIT _ Lawyers for East Texas landowners and a major
bottled-water company square off before the Texas Supreme Court on
Thursday to debate the rule of capture, a 94-year-old legal
principle allowing essentially unlimited pumping of groundwater. We
try to get a sense of the justices' thinking. (Haurwitz, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Attention Texas editors.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-SUPPORT-ENFORCEMENT _ The Texas Sunset Commission makes
recommendations on child support enforcement. (McCarthy, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Attention Texas editors.
</P>
<P>
   ANATOMY OF A CRASH
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Southeast Airlines Flight 529 was only a little
propeller-driven plane that fell in an obscure hayfield in west
Georgia: 10 people died, 19 survived. In terms of lives lost,
certainly it was not on scale with TWA Flight 800 and Swissair
Flight 111. More than 200 people died in each of those crashes. Yet
the ASA crash is writ large across many lives. Nearly two-thirds of
the people aboard survived _ a miracle gift _ and so this crash is
not
</P>
<P>
   only about death, but life.
</P>
<P>
   For nine months, award-winning Atlanta Journal-Constitution
reporter Gary M. Pomerantz trekked thousands of miles _ from
Georgia to Maine to Texas to Alaska _ to track down and interview
survivors of ASA Flight 529. He also canvassed investigative files
of the National Transportation Safety Board and testimony taken
during the ensuing litigation. Pomerantz vivdly describes the 9
minutes and 20 seconds of horror aboard that doomed aircraft as it
fell to earth, the fire that consumed the broken fuselage, as well
as how the tragedy has reshaped lives.
</P>
<P>
   This is the final part of the series. WITH PHOTOS and
ILLUSTRATIONS.
</P>
<P>
   DAY 6 _ Nov. 20
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-BLADEMAN _ TYLER, Texas _ The broken propeller stub showed
signs typical of fatigue cracking. It also yielded the most
important clue: serial number 861398. The paper chase now was on:
Maintenance records revealed blade 861398 had been repaired 11
months earlier after failing an ultrasonic inspection. Following
the paper trail, investigators discovered the repair _ a sanding
job _ had been made by a mechanic who signed himself in small,
tight handwriting: ``CSB.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Scott Bender, young, blond and earnest, is a
mechanic no more. He's 27, a Bible student now. Although the crash
is never far from his thoughts, he still knows few details of what
happened. But he knows that it was his blade that broke, and he's
often wondered: Was it my fault? (Pomerantz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
