<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFE-TURKEY20-COX     11-19 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFE-TURKEY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOOD SAFETY A TOP PRIORITY AT THANKSGIVING, GROUP WARNS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (d) food categories.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thanksgiving is no time to be lax about food
safety, a consumer group warned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent reports showing that contamination of poultry
with salmonella bacteria has decreased, the Center for Science in
the Public Interest urged all consumers to practice smart food
handling techniques when preparing meals this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it is imperative that the industry and the government
work to ensure safer turkeys, consumers remain the last line of
defense against food poisoning,'' said Caroline Smith DeWaal, food
safety director for the consumer advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Since the government started a new federal food safety system in
January, salmonella contamination in chicken has been reduced by
half _ from 20 to 10 percent, DeWaal said. Turkey and red meat also
showed improvement.
</P>
<P>
   However, DeWaal said there is no evidence to suggest that levels
of campylobacter bacteria in poultry have decreased. The No. 1
cause of bacterial food poisoning, campylobacter can cause serious
neurological disease which can lead to temporary paralysis similar
to polio.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996-97 survey taken before the new program began showed that
nine out of 10 turkeys contained the campylobacter bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   To help fight against food poisoning, the consumer group offered
the following advice for cooks:
</P>
<P>
   _ To prevent the spread of bacteria, keep your turkey
double-wrapped in plastic bags in your refrigerator or freezer
until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use a meat thermometer even if your turkey has a pop-up timer.
Turkey is done once the thermometer reads 180 degrees. Stuffing
much reach 165 degrees, especially if it is cooked inside the
turkey or contains raw eggs or oysters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use pasteurized egg products in recipes that call for raw or
partially cooked eggs. Also avoid unpasteurized juices or heat them
to a low boil.
</P>
<P>
   For more tips on safe cooking, call the U.S. Department of
Agriculture Meat and Poultry Hotline at 800-535-4555 or visit its
Internet site (http://www.fsis.usda.gov).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
