<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9328 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-HOUSE-$ADV26-CO     11-19 3371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-HOUSE-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A DAY IN THE LIFE OF THE WHITE HOUSE
 &HT;    For release Thursday, Nov. 26.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day in the life of the White House begins an hour
before midnight when Susanna McGuire rubs her coded photo ID across
the electronic scanner at a wrought-iron gate, punches in a
personal number, then enters under the gaze of a uniformed Secret
Service agent.
</P>
<P>
   An ambitious young press aide who will spend the night clipping
papers for President Clinton's morning news summary, McGuire is one
of hundreds of human cogs who make the White House a perpetual
motion machine _ running day after day, decade after decade,
president after president.
</P>
<P>
   Unique in the world, the building where the president lives and
works is among the most recognizable symbols of American democracy.
It is a home and a museum, a fortress and a bureaucracy, a
playground and a monument and a backdrop for TV newscasts. It is a
place permeated with the temptations of power, of course, but also
blessed with the virtues of community and continuity.
</P>
<P>
   During the depths of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, White House
correspondents sometimes described a paralysis in the building
looming dramatically behind them. Images of inactivity could not
have been more misleading, however, in portraying the legions of
employees who every day continued to shepherd through 6,000
tourists, open 10,000 letters, answer 1,600 phone calls, entertain
foreign dignitaries, cook meals, plan parties, prune shrubbery and
oversee operation of the federal government _ accomplishing the
mundane as well as the miraculous.
</P>
<P>
   Until he recently fell ill, for instance, 78-year-old John
Muffler continued to wind the 85 or so clocks in the White House
every Friday _ a routine he had followed for half a century. Now
semi-retired, the courtly electrician's tasks have ranged from
changing light bulbs for Harry Truman to programming a VCR for
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Head florist Nancy Clarke continues to keep fresh flowers in
practically every room _ ever mindful not to aggravate President's
Clinton's allergies with pollen and not to provide tourists with
tales of bugs crawling out of blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Overseeing a staff of four full-time designers in the basement
flower shop below the North Portico, Clarke has accommodated floral
tastes of first ladies since Nancy Reagan hired her in 1981.
Regardless of the time of year, for example, Mrs. Reagan wanted
peonies in arrangements. When the Reagans left, Clarke made a
needlepoint pillow for the departing first lady _ decorated with a
bright peony and the inscription ``Peonies Bloom in May.''
</P>
<P>
   Muffler and Clarke are among 1,500 people employed in the
Executive Office of the President _ posts that range from seven
speech writers to four physicians. About 400 work in the White
House, including about 90 on the executive residence staff.
</P>
<P>
   The full-time force is augmented by 1,010 volunteers who work at
least 16 hours a month _ mostly in the correspondence office. The
Clinton administration says these volunteers save taxpayers about
$1.2 million in wages per year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, about $8.5 million is budgeted for care, heating and
lighting of the historic residence and for official entertainment
expenses of the president.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential mansion, with its familiar columns and
porticos, was designed by James Hoban, an Irish-born architect
selected by George Washington. The cornerstone was laid on Oct. 13,
1792. Eight years later, John Adams moved in to became the first
president to live there.
</P>
<P>
   Built of Virginia sandstone, the central mansion has six floors,
including a basement and sub-basement, about 67,200 square feet of
floor space, 132 rooms including 34 bathrooms, three mezzanines,
147 windows, 412 doors, 12 chimneys, three elevators, two
dumbwaiters and seven staircases. Teddy Roosevelt dubbed this
building the ``White House'' in 1901. Before that, it was known as
the ``President's House'' and the ``Executive Mansion.''
</P>
<P>
   The first President Roosevelt also added the West Wing and its
famed Oval Office in 1909 to handle the increasing need for
presidential staff offices. The mansion and West Wing are connected
by the press area, built over what was a swimming pool from 1933 to
1969. The president walks from home to office through an open-sided
colonnade between the Rose Garden and windowless press rooms.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, Franklin Delano Roosevelt added the East Wing where the
first lady has her office. The Old Executive Office Building, a
massive gray structure that once housed all Cabinet offices next
door, is now part of the White House complex enclosed by a
protective and decorative wrought iron fence. Also inside the fence
are 19 acres of lawns, gardens and trees that make up the White
House grounds.
</P>
<P>
   It is a setting where there are no typical days.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   At 8 a.m., chief of staff John Podesta convenes the daily
meeting of senior presidential staffers in the Roosevelt Room of
the West Wing. The photocopied news summary begun by Susanna
McGuire already has been distributed to their desks. All are
stapled except the one bound for the Oval Office. A senior adviser
shuffles that summary to prioritize presidential reading.
</P>
<P>
   Small tables are fit together in the middle of the room to make
a large conference center. Top presidential advisers on domestic,
foreign and political issues fill the leather chairs around the
tables and the overstuffed armchairs and sofas along the walls. The
Roosevelt Room's namesake presidents look down from portraits _
Teddy on horseback and FDR signing legislation at a desk. The Nobel
Peace Prize won by Theodore Roosevelt sits on a mantelpiece over a
fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   A 49-year-old fitness buff who likes to jog shirtless, Podesta
is regarded as an unpretentious boss _ known for cooking elaborate
Italian meals and a passion for riding roller coasters. However,
the chief of staff can be demanding and has a dark side nicknamed
``Skippy'' by underlings. Nobody wants to provoke ``Skippy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the workaholic West Wing, where days routinely stretch from 7
a.m. to 9 p.m. or later, Podesta sets the standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we say here every Friday, only two more working days till
Monday,'' he has observed. Indeed, before the 8 a.m. session,
Podesta already has completed a smaller meeting in his nearby
office.
</P>
<P>
   The day's agenda is set at the senior staff meeting, which
usually lasts less than an hour. Afterward, attendees scatter to
preside over daily meetings of their various departments. Press
Secretary Joe Lockhart, for instance, holds a communications staff
meeting at 8:45 or so.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the president is usually in the Oval Office. Awakened
by a call from a steward, Clinton has breakfast _ often coffee and
fruit _ in an upstairs family kitchen decorated with cheerful
fruit-patterned wallpaper. The Clintons converted a butler's pantry
into this ``ordinary'' room shortly after they arrived in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Most mornings, a national security briefing is an early order of
presidential business. The data comes from the top-secret,
high-tech Situation Room located on the floor below the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   The West Wing has three levels, with staffers' offices on floors
both above and below with the Oval Office. The Situation Room is
staffed 24 hours a day by experts monitoring trouble spots around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, 52, is in
charge of the security briefing. A longtime friend, he met Clinton
when both worked on George McGovern's 1972 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The briefing takes place beneath the embossed presidential seal
on the white ceiling of the Oval Office. Behind Clinton's desk, a
table displays pictures of his wife and his daughter, Chelsea, and
his collection of political campaign buttons. On his desk are busts
of FDR and Harry Truman. On the floor nearby are an African drum
and a drum made by Native Americans to commemorate the North
American Free Trade Agreement _ showing the shared American Indian
heritage of Mexico, the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   A rocking chair sits in the adjoining private study. The
president's computer is there, too, connected to the Internet _
though aides won't say whether Clinton ever surfs through
cyberspace. There is no TV.
</P>
<P>
   From her adjoining office, Nancy Hernreich helps keep Clinton on
schedule. As director of Oval Office operations, Hernreich, 52, is
one of the ``meanies'' whom Monica Lewinsky complained was trying
to keep her away from the president. A longtime loyalist, she was
Clinton's scheduler in the Arkansas governor's office. Divorced and
a diligent runner, Hernreich dotes on her daughter, Ashley, a
student at Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   Hernreich is the gatekeeper _ regulating who gets in to see the
president and, to some extent, when they leave. However, it is up
to the president to decide when a meeting ends.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Caplan, assistant to the president and staff secretary,
manages the flow of presidential paperwork _ moving color-coded
binders on and off Clinton's desk. Green for action. Pink for
correspondence. Blue for information. Red for classified.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   By midmorning, White House kitchens are bustling. The holiday
season is approaching, and 120,000 cookies and pieces of cake will
be baked for a panoply of parties.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Walter Scheib, an imposing figure nearly 7 feet tall from
the top of his traditional toque to the toes of his shined shoes,
is responsible for all meals served in the White House. A graduate
of the Culinary Institute of America in Hyde Park, N.Y., Scheib was
chef at the Greenbrier Resort in West Virginia when hired by
Hillary Clinton in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady was looking for an American cuisine chef with a
light touch, and Scheib has worked hard at reducing the fat in the
White House fare without sacrificing flavor, texture or appearance.
Cooking oil is kept in spray bottles, for instance, and misted onto
pans rather than being poured or brushed.
</P>
<P>
   Now 43, Scheib grew up in the nearby suburb of Bethesda, Md.,
and remembers watching his mother cook the dishes Julia Child
demonstrated on TV. His wife, Jean, also is a chef, and the two
cooked together at the Boca Raton Resort and Club in Florida before
moving on to the Greenbrier.
</P>
<P>
   The first family pays for its own food _ which Scheib orders
from nearby wholesalers and from suppliers all around the nation.
He searches for the best ingredients _ buffalo milk mozzarella from
upstate New York, Michigan blueberries, Virginia ham _ and the
nation's food merchants eagerly solicit his business.
</P>
<P>
   Food bound for the White House is detoured to another facility
where it is checked by the Secret Service before being sent in
secure trucks to Scheib's pantries, refrigerators and freezers.
Scheib's staff includes two assistant chefs, a kitchen steward and
two assistant stewards. For state dinners and other major events,
this culinary force is augmented by chefs from local restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking separately in a tiny kitchen jammed between the state
floor and the family quarters is pastry chef Roland Mesnier and his
longtime assistant, Franette McCulloch.
</P>
<P>
   Mesnier was born in a French village in 1944 on the very day
American soldiers liberated the community from Nazi occupation. At
the age of 14, he left school and began an apprenticeship at a
village bakery. He created pastries in kitchens in Paris, London
and Bermuda and was cooking at the Greenbrier in 1980 when Rosalynn
Carter hired him for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Mesnier's themed desserts have become the sweet stuff of legend.
At a luncheon for Egyptian officials, he created a pistachio mousse
pyramid flanked by two edible palm trees and a marzipan camel. One
Christmas, he made gingerbread and chocolate reproductions of the
president's boyhood home in Hot Springs, Ark., and the suburban
house where Hillary Rodham grew up in Park Ridge, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   For Chelsea Clinton's 16th birthday, Mesnier decorated her cake
with a replica of her new driver's license, complete with color
photo, and a car with a license tag reading ``Sweet 16.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, after 18 years, it's hard to come up with ideas,''
said Mesnier. ``Two days before the birthday I was driving to work
listening to the radio and the announcer said, 'Chelsea will soon
be getting her driver's license.' Then, Boom! It hit me. Chocolate
car and license.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after noon, the last of this day's 6,000 or so tourists
_ more than a million visit the White House each year _ stops for a
final photo of the North Portico before leaving the compound and
stepping onto the sidewalk along Pennsylvania Avenue. The mansion's
ground floor and second story are part museum, open to visitors
from 10 a.m. to noon Tuesdays through Saturdays. The busiest times
are the summer months and December; the slowest are January and
February.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists enter on the east side and proceed through the library,
the Vermeil Room with its portraits of recent first ladies, the
China Room, the East Room where presidential press conferences are
held, the Green Room, the Blue Room where the White House Christmas
tree will be placed, the Red Room and the State Dining Room.
</P>
<P>
   Melinda Bates, 52, director of the Office of Tourism, is a
longtime friend of President Clinton. She took him to his first
Judy Collins concert in 1964. When Collins visited the White House
three decades later, Clinton returned the favor by introducing the
singer to Bates.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is a treasure trove of antiques, art and
oddities. Original Norman Rockwell drawings adorn the walls of an
out-of-the-way West Wing waiting area, for instance. In another
reception area, a handsome clock made of wood, inside and out,
keeps visitors aware of the time. Historic portraits are
everywhere. A photo on an end table shows Calvin Coolidge with the
original Boston Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   Curator Betty Monkman, who has worked at the White House for
three decades, is responsible for displaying and maintaining the
artifacts, furnishings and art.
</P>
<P>
   A job whose title belies its importance is the social secretary
_ responsible for every event inside the White House and on the
grounds. From state dinners to the annual Easter Egg Roll, Social
Secretary Capricia Marshall juggles VIPs and RSVPs and a myriad of
details of protocol and logistics.
</P>
<P>
   Three to 10 events take place every week at the White House.
More than 60,000 people are entertained annually at official
functions.
</P>
<P>
   A Cleveland native and law school graduate, Marshall joined the
Clinton presidential campaign in Ohio in 1991 and came to the White
House as a special assistant to the first lady after Clinton's
initial election. In 1997, at 33, she was appointed social
secretary. Marshall made an immediate impact in her new post by
posing in Vogue magazine wearing a backless Donna Karan gown.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   It's midafternoon, and President Clinton is standing in a sunny
Rose Garden promoting his proposals for health-care reform. Irv
Williams is concerned about reporters stomping on the grass.
</P>
<P>
   For more than four decades, chief horticulturist Williams has
tended the 19 acres of trees, grass and shrubbery that compose the
White House grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The groundskeepers work for the National Park Service. Williams
helped Jacqueline Kennedy redesign the First Lady's Garden, next to
the formal Rose Garden where speeches are staged and treaties
signed.
</P>
<P>
   Every first lady leaves her own special bloom in the garden _ a
peach-colored rose for Rosalynn Carter, a yellow rose for Betty
Ford, red for Nancy Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Every president plants a tree on the grounds before leaving. The
oldest surviving presidential trees are three magnolias given root
by Andrew Jackson. Clinton has planted several trees, including an
American elm, a willow oak and a linden.
</P>
<P>
   The gently rolling South Lawn, brightened by flower beds and
partly shielded by trees, is the first family's back yard.
</P>
<P>
   In the southwest corner are a tennis court and an outdoor pool.
A short chip shot from the Oval Office is a putting green laid out
by President Eisenhower in 1954. It was removed in 1971 by the
non-golfing Richard Nixon, who built a bowling alley in the White
House basement. The green was reinstalled in 1995 by Clinton, who
also added a padded jogging track around the South Lawn driveway
and subtracted the horseshoe pits dug by George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   While the president is speaking in the sunshine, Dan Burkhardt
is managing messages deep inside the Old Executive Office Building
_ a massive, foreboding gray building across West Executive Avenue
from the West Wing. The prime parking spaces for key staffers are
located between the ``OEOB'' and the West Wing.
</P>
<P>
   A political appointee from California, Burkhardt is director of
correspondence and presidential messages. The White House receives
about 10,000 letters a day at the 1600 Pennsylvania Ave. mailing
address.
</P>
<P>
   These are sorted by subject and assigned to volunteers for
replies. On any given weekday, 100 to 250 volunteers are handling
mail. The replies are checked by one of Burkhardt's 70 full-time
staffers _ who oversee everything from the processing of
presidential gifts to responding to the 2,000 or so e-mails the
president receives every day to handling incoming calls on 20 phone
lines.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the OEOB operation, an auxiliary White House mail
room is located at the U.S. Soldiers and Airmen's Home near Capitol
Hill where military retirees process letters addressed to
presidential pets _ currently Socks the cat and Buddy the dog.
</P>
<P>
   Many offices in the Old EOB are spacious, with high ceilings and
working fireplaces. They are not as eagerly sought as the cramped
quarters in the West Wing, however, for proximity to the president
is prized above all other perquisites in the White House complex.
</P>
<P>
   Aide Sidney Blumenthal's office, for instance, is a converted
barbershop _ but still coveted by many because it is downstairs
from the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   The Old EOB houses the staffs of many top advisers whose own
offices are in the West Wing. It also has a bank, a post office, a
cafeteria and a medical unit for staffers. In the main White House
is another medical unit for the first family. And on the bottom
floor of the West Wing, senior staffers can dine in or carry out
from the White House Mess, which is operated by Navy cooks.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Around 7 p.m., President Clinton walks down the colonnade,
headed to the top two floors of the White House that are the home
of the first family.
</P>
<P>
   He has likened this lifestyle to the way average Americans lived
in bygone decades _ residing above their stores or on their family
farms, with their jobs and homes practically melded. Here, though,
White House staffers zealously guard the upstairs private lives of
presidential families.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Walters, an aggressively discreet former Secret Service
agent with the unimposing title of chief usher, is the supervisor
of all who serve the first family in their home. With a staff of
about 90 to direct and the ultimate responsibility for everything
from state dinners to overflowing toilets, Walters has filled this
historically powerful post since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Eight chief ushers have served in the nearly 200-year history of
the White House. The improbably named Ike Hoover served the longest
_ 42 years beginning in 1891 _ and managed the care and comfort of
10 presidents and their families.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons are movie fans and regularly invite friends over
for films in the 51-seat movie theater off the East Wing portico.
Facing the screen are rows of four to six beige overstuffed
armchairs _ the rows rising on tiers toward the rear of the room.
When the Clintons show movies, tables stocked with popcorn, soft
drinks and other snacks are set up outside the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Many nights, though, Clinton takes memos upstairs to read late
into the night, aides say, working even as Susanna McGuire arrives
to start another day in the life of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
