<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9381 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENTERTAINMENT-BUDGET-     11-19 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-BUDGET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
SMITH-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ ``There's something about when you have
two kids: That's when you're really a parent,'' says 30-year-old
superstar Will Smith, who welcomed his second son in July. In
addition to stretching as a father, Smith has expanded his screen
image with his new movie, ``Enemy of the State.'' By Bob Strauss. 
. 
DIRECTOR-FILM (Los Angeles) _ It's not often that Joe and Jane Blow
get to meet the director of a film actually playing theaters and
talk about what goes on behind the veil. Find out Dec. 2 when Bill
Condon of ``Gods and Monsters'' attends a screening of his work in
Westlake Village. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
CELEBRITY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Woody Allen aims at a big, obvious
target _ America's obsession with fame _ and mostly makes broad,
obvious hits in his latest grouchy comedy, ``Celebrity.'' 2{ stars.
By Bob Strauss. 
. 
BUGS-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``A Bug's Life'' has a lot going for
it. The movie bursts with eye-popping colors, dazzling animation,
uproarious action and an array of funny, fast-talking insect
characters, yet it feels like something of a disappointment. 3
stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
DEVINE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Waking Ned Devine'' is a genuinely
likable and quirky British film about two lifelong buddies who
exhibit greed and generosity as they scheme to collect the national
lottery in place of the true winner who's dead. 3{ stars. By Bob
Strauss. 
. 
ENEMY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Enemy of the State'' moves fast and
has lots of bells and whistles, but the pleasant surprise is the
intelligence and star turns from Will Smith and Gene Hackman. 3{
stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
DANCING-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Redeemed by uniformly moving
performances, ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' nonetheless seems far less
stirring as a movie than it did on the stage. 3 stars. By Bob
Strauss. 
. 
RUGRATS-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Fans of the Nickelodeon television
series will enjoy this quick-paced, brightly colored big-screen
romp. 2{ stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
SAVIOR-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Savior,'' a straightforward telling
of one man's redemption in the face of the horrors of war, suffers
somewhat from blurry plot distinctions and an unwillingness to
probe more deeply into the psyche of its protagonist, played by
Dennis Quaid. 2{ stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
STORAGE-STAGE (Los Angeles) _ ``Cold Storage'' is a powerful piece
of writing about two patients who strike up an unlikely friendship
in the rooftop garden of a New York City hospital. By Reed
Johnson. 
. 
OVATION-AWARDS (Los Angeles) _ One of L.A.'s smaller theaters
scored big at the recent presentation of the 1998 Theatre LA
Ovation Awards. The Circle X Theatre Company's ``Great Men of
Science Nos. 21 &AMP; 22'' won three awards, including best play in the
small-theater category, at the annual peer-based competitive awards
ceremony Monday at the Shubert Theatre in Century City. By Reed
Johnson. 
. 
SHAWN-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ The times are a-changing for
singer-songwriter Shawn Mullins, who last year was voted best
acoustic artist at the Atlanta Music Awards. ``I've been touring
for nine years in a van with my dog, Roadie, and now we've got a
tour bus. Now, I can walk around or do pushups, sit, write or watch
TV.'' By Fred Shuster. 
. 
SHARPS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Colin Larkin, who has chronicled pop
music for 31 years, has penned the 8,000-page ``The Encyclopedia of
Popular Music, Third Edition,'' that covers performers, composers,
producers, record companies, events, venues, musical theater,
films, video and music magazines, and documents pop music's
position in culture. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ For his first album in four years, the
Grammy-winning Seal again collaborates with producer Trevor Horn
for a soulful and appealing collection of elegant electro-tinged
tunes. While there's nothing here as immediately grabbing as the
classy 1991 smash ``Crazy'' or the award-winning ``Kiss From a
Rose,'' there are warm nods to a variety of styles. By Fred
Shuster. 
. 
WOLVES-VIDEO (LoS Angeles) _ Oscar-winning pictures ``Dances With
Wolves'' and ``West Side Story'' make a good match with DVD
technology, with its superior sound and picture quality. These
titles are the latest additions to the growing DVD library. By Rob
Lowman. 
. 

