<HEADLINE>
SMITH, HACKMAN SHINE IN `ENEMY OF THE STATE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 { Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Coming as it does from director Tony Scott
(``Crimson Tide,'' ``The Last Boy Scout'') and producer Jerry
Bruckheimer (``Armageddon,'' ``Con Air,'' ``The Rock,'' etc.,
etc.), you know ``Enemy of the State'' is going to move fast and
have lots of bells and whistles clanging in your ear.
</P>
<P>
   The pleasant surprise here is that the movie also has a modicum
of intelligence, not to mention great star turns from Will Smith
and Gene Hackman and an array of wonderful performances from a
perfectly chosen supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences put off by Bruckheimer's recent deafening forays into
testosterone-fueled worlds will be pleasantly surprised by how much
he and cohort Scott (the two previously have made four
brain-rattling movies together, including ``Top Gun,'' ``Days of
Thunder'' and ``Beverly Hills Cop II'') have toned down their macho
posing to create an engaging and timely thrill ride into high-tech
surveillance and government paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enemy of the State'' opens with an arresting montage of shots
showing how surveillance cameras have thoroughly blanketed our
land. They (whoever they are) watch us while we drive our cars on
the freeways, take our money out of the bank and buy a six-pack at
the local convenience store. All of this vigilant scrutiny is
supposed to be for our good; however, as this movie so ably
demonstrates, Big Brother isn't always content to simply peek
through the window. Sometimes, he wants to bust down the door, too.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Robert Clayton Dean (Smith) learns this the hard way
when he accidentally comes into possession of a videotape that
shows National Security Agency administrator Thomas Reynolds (Jon
Voight) doing a very bad thing. Reynolds employs a band of NSA
renegade geeks (Jamie Kennedy, Jack Black and Barry Pepper among
them) to ruin Dean's life and discredit him before he can take the
tape to the proper authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Faster than you can say ``your credit card has been canceled,''
Dean endures a string of catastrophes that would make even Job's
head spin. He loses his job at the law firm and then his wife
(Regina King) after she sees incriminating photos taken of Dean
with his old girlfriend (and now professional confidante) Rachel
(Lisa Bonet).
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers print scandalous stories, and his clothes are
implanted with electronic tracking devices. Every sound he utters
is overheard, and every movement he makes is followed by government
spy satellites _ and Dean is not even sure why because he doesn't
know he has the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel eventually leads Dean to a surly former NSA agent, Brill
(Gene Hackman), who reluctantly helps the beleaguered lawyer fight
fire with fire. At this point, the film turns into a fairly
conventional thriller, but Scott's lightning-quick direction keeps
things moving briskly, and David Marconi's smart script saves the
best surprise for the crowd-pleasing finale.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, asked to carry a film for the first time, delivers a
stirring performance as the put-upon Everyman, effortlessly
radiating charisma and strength throughout the picture. Hackman,
who doesn't appear until the film's one-hour mark, makes a strong
impression, too. His bickering repartee with Smith recalls the best
moments of the Smith-Tommy Lee Jones teaming of ``Men in Black.''
</P>
<P>
   With its emphasis on government conspiracies and societal
paranoia, ``Enemy of the State'' summons memories of '70s suspense
thrillers such as ``Three Days of the Condor,'' ``The Parallax
View'' and, noting the Hackman presence, Francis Ford Coppola's
classic, ``The Conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   This movie isn't as concerned with making any grand, sweeping
statements about the nature of privacy, though. It's a popcorn
picture, pure and simple, albeit one with a kernel of intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a wonderful thing, given that ``Enemy of the State''
might just be the most flat-out entertaining movie of the year.
Filled to the brim with exciting action (Watch Will hang from a
building! See Will run through a tunnel in his underwear!) and
eye-catching supporting turns (Tom Sizemore, Gabriel Byrne and an
unbilled Jason Robards among them), this is a movie that aims to
please, and does so again and again and again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1531EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
