<HEADER>
A9404 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-POLLOCK-HNS &LR;      11-19 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-POLLOCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON POLLOCK: A GREAT ARTIST FOR OUR TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID BONETTI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1949, Life magazine published a story
provocatively titled, ``Jackson Pollock: Is he the greatest living
painter in the United States?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackson Pollock,'' at the Museum of Modern Art through Feb. 2,
updates that question, implicitly asking whether Pollock
(1912-1956) is the greatest American painter of the century.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which travels to London after it closes here,
has a lot riding on it. It is the first full-fledged Pollock
retrospective since 1967, and because of the relative rarity of his
work and its ever-rising prices, it is likely to be the last for
probably at least as long a period of time.
</P>
<P>
   To say it is the show of the year is to undervalue its
importance. It is impeccably organized by Kirk Varnedoe, whose
lucid catalog essay is rooted in a sketch of Pollock's life with
full discussion of his work and a history of its critical reception
and influences. Exercising its considerable power, MoMA was able to
borrow virtually everything it wanted, including paintings seldom
seen in public, so museum visitors can make informed judgments
about Pollock's status.
</P>
<P>
   Most viewers, however, will be satisfied merely to indulge in
the unprecedented beauty Pollock created in a few years circa 1950.
</P>
<P>
   To say the show is exciting is to understate its effect. There's
a scene in the movie ``12 Monkeys'' in which Bruce Willis is
reveling in his first encounters with the real world. As Fats
Domino's ``Blueberry Hill'' plays on a car radio, Willis screams,
``I love the music of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a space in the exhibition, where Pollock's three great
mural-scale ``drip'' masterpieces from 1950 hang together, where I
had to restrain myself from similarly screaming, ``I love the
painting of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   And as much as I do love 20th century painting, I have to admit
I don't get such an urge very often.
</P>
<P>
   But MoMA also took a risk by showing Pollock now. The question
that hovers over the exhibition about Pollock's greatness would
have been answered 25 years ago with a simple, ``Of course _ who
else?''
</P>
<P>
   Between then and now, there have been developments in the way
art is thought about and thus seen that have raised questions about
Pollock's achievement.
</P>
<P>
   A whole body of criticism sees Pollock's painting and that of
the entire abstract expressionist generation as having been used by
the State Department in Europe to advertise democratic freedom of
expression in contrast to Soviet repression. In addition, a crisis
surrounding painting in general was created by feminist critics who
dismiss painting as a male-identified medium and other theorists
who promoted concepts such as the ``death of the author'' _ not to
mention the rise and apparent triumph of camera-based arts.
</P>
<P>
   To many involved in the liveliest arts of the past
quarter-century, being the greatest American painter of the 20th
century is not quite the achievement earlier generations would have
understood it to be.
</P>
<P>
   But whether because good art, whatever its medium, always
eventually trumps theory or because we're now looking freshly at
painting again, Pollock's art here looks vital and thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all his paintings are equal. Like most members of
his artistic generation _ the misfits out of the Western plains,
homegrown dandies and striving immigrants from the Netherlands,
Germany, Russia and Armenia who propelled New York painting to the
forefront of world culture during World War II _ Pollock was
self-invented and went through a long and tormented apprenticeship.
</P>
<P>
   MoMA began buying his works when they were brand new, and
Pollock was being anointed the painter of his generation even
before he had figured out who he was. When Life asked its question,
Pollock hadn't yet made his masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are early works that grab your imagination and
won't let go. The tiny self-portrait he painted some time between
1931 and 1935, for instance, is haunting. Those deep, brooding eyes
that pull you in recur in later works, buried beneath whorls of
poured and dripped paint, and they hint at the unspoken anguish
that eventually led Pollock to a violent grave as well as to an
untopped, untoppable peak of personal creativity.
</P>
<P>
   And his late work is all too often tragically inept. Pollock
made relatively few pieces during the five-year bender he embarked
upon after Hans Namuth shot his famous film of the artist, a bender
that ended only with his death in a drunken automobile crash.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling that to repeat himself would be dishonest, Pollock
experimented by pouring black paint onto canvas, finding faces and
figures in the process _ a figurative recidivism he had previously
avoided. And in the few paintings, like ``Blue Poles,'' in which he
tried to create a lacy interweaving of poured and dribbled lines
characteristic of his classic drip paintings, he lost almost all
lightness and spontaneity, creating clogged compositions instead.
</P>
<P>
   In between, however, Pollock experienced an outpouring of
creative invention that is unequalled in American art. From 1946 to
the end of 1950, an astonishingly brief period, Pollock changed the
nature of painting and the status of American art.
</P>
<P>
   How he did it we'll never know, even with all the evidence
before our eyes. How he took several disparate influences _
including the regionalist painter Thomas Hart Benton and the
Mexican muralists who excited political artists during the 1930s
and '40s _ and put them together to create ``One: Number 31,
1950,'' ``Number 32, 1950'' and ``Autumn Rhythm: Number 30, 1950,''
the three great paintings that form the heart and soul of the
exhibition, will remain forever a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Such a feat reminds us that all creativity is essentially
unknowable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pollock invented a way of putting paint on a canvas surface that
served his purposes perfectly. He created vast veils of visual
activity, in which long, languorously applied lines were knitted
together with others violently thrown down and spattered.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Fields of energy caught in mid-action like a fly
caught in a fly trap. No one else captured so rightly the anxiety,
the fears, the hopes, the ecstasy of having survived the
mid-century chaos in which so many others perished. Today, they
look as if they had been just painted, but they also look like
relics of a far-off, never-to-be-lived-through-again time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (There is a $3 surcharge for the Pollock exhibition added to
normal Museum of Modern Art admission prices of $9.50 for adults;
$6.50 for students.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
