<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORAGE-STAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COLD STORAGE' OFFERS COMIC VITALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Expect more cool and edgy than warm and fuzzy
when you see a Ronald Ribman play.
</P>
<P>
   Take Ribman's 1976 ``Cold Storage,'' a comedy about death so
loftily cerebral that at times it seems to have been incubated on
Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   Not that ``Cold Storage'' lacks humanity. In the Odyssey
Theatre's feisty new production, humanity in all its anguished
eccentricity practically oozes from the pores of Joseph Parmigian
(Len Lesser) and Richard Landau (Jeff Seymour), two patients who
strike up an unlikely friendship in the rooftop garden of a New
York City hospital.
</P>
<P>
   To first appearances, the men hail from separate universes.
Parmigian, a cranky, conspiratorially minded Armenian, runs a fruit
and vegetable stand. Landau, Jewish and prosperous, is an
investment adviser in fine art.
</P>
<P>
   What begins as wary small talk builds (at a rather dreamy pace)
to more rancorous, metaphysically resonant repartee, prompting a
good deal of uneasy laughter both on stage and from the audience.
Kevin Hunt's purposefully spare scenic design makes the men's
encounter appear to be taking place at some featureless cosmic
waystation.
</P>
<P>
   Parmigian, though confined to his wheelchair, plays the
interrogator, querying Landau about the seriousness of his illness
and the happiness of his personal life, while making caustic
observations about the hospital's slipshod management.
</P>
<P>
   Lesser's funny devil's advocacy keeps us guessing: Is Parmigian
taunting Landau, or is he simply curious? Cheerfully fatalistic or
rudely insinuating?
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, is the outwardly self-assured Landau calmly deceiving
himself about that nasty black spot on his X-ray?
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold Storage'' ultimately dodges the dramatic conflict between
its two main characters, sliding off in Act 2 into Landau's long,
guilt-ridden anecdotal admission involving a memory of the
Holocaust. Though the specter of mass annihilation raises the
play's humanistic stakes, the dramatic resolution Ribman supplies
is less than convincing.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing an extra hat as director, the understated Seymour
doesn't always succeed in keeping Lesser's amusing banter from
accelerating into aggressive shtick. Some exchanges may remind you
of Archie Bunker and Meathead in one of their classic ``All in the
Family'' screaming matches.
</P>
<P>
   More distracting are Parmigian's long, simile-laden bouts of
circular philosophizing, along with cryptic allusions to dead male
poets. ``It's time to spread your filthy dream out in front of me
like a moth-eaten Moroccan carpet,'' he exhorts Landau in one
all-too-typical platitude.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Seymour, Lesser and Magda Rivera, who has a small part as a
nurse, have succeeded well in conveying Ribman's icily intelligent
humor. For all its intellectual noodling, ``Cold Storage'' is a
powerful piece of writing which insists that, against all odds, a
warm pulse still reverberates in this freezing, starlit void in
which  &UR;  &LR; we spin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1536EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9408 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIRECTOR-FILM-LADN     11-19 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTOR-FILM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GODS AND MONSTERS' DIRECTOR TO HOLD Q&AMP;A SESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For those of us on the outside looking into this
fish bowl called Hollywood, the movie mecca hasn't lost any of its
fascination from the days when gossip columnists Hedda Hopper and
Louella Parsons gave the inside dirt and heralded the next star.
Only today, thanks to the likes of Steven Spielberg and George
Lucas, directors command equal attention, too.
</P>
<P>
   Regent Westlake Theaters in Ventura County is hosting director
Bill Condon of ``Gods and Monsters'' at 8:15 tonight for a
screening and question-and-answer session afterward. Condon is
appearing as part of an occasional film forum that brings together
audiences and contemporary filmmakers for some all-too-rare
interaction between creators and consumers of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Condon was named best director at the recent Seattle Film
Festival International, and his ``Gods and Monsters'' is currently
playing in theaters. Its subject is famed director James Whale,
whose 1931 ``Frankenstein'' motion picture led to a series of
lesser imitations. ``Gods and Monsters'' stars Sir Ian McKellen,
Brendan Fraser (``George of the Jungle'') and Lynn Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the novel ``Father of Frankenstein,'' the film examines
the friendship between Whale and his handsome young gardener that
bears a strange resemblance to the one between Dr. Frankenstein and
his monster.
</P>
<P>
   Director Don Roos was a guest earlier this year at the forum
when his ``The Opposite of Sex'' screened at the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are $7. Call (818) 889-2388 or (805) 379-4100 for
information. The Regent Westlake Theaters are at 4711 Lakeview
Canyon Drive in Westlake Village.
</P>
<P>
   A WISE CHOICE: Robert Wise was a gifted film editor with a knack
for making great RKO films greater and B movies extraordinary, but
he wanted more. He wanted to direct.
</P>
<P>
   He got his chance in 1943, when the director of ``Curse of the
Cat People'' was replaced when the film fell behind schedule. Wise
took over the helm, ``Cat People'' was a success, and his
reputation grew from there.
</P>
<P>
   Wise, the Academy Award-winning director and producer of ``West
Side Story'' and the ``Sound of Music,'' is the guest of honor at
``An Evening With Robert Wise'' at 8 p.m. Dec. 2 at the Alex
Theatre in Glendale. Clips of his acclaimed films, which include
``The Set-Up,'' ``The Andromeda Strain,'' ``The Sand Pebbles'' and
``The Day the Earth Stood Still,'' will be shown, and Leonard
Maltin of ``Entertainment Tonight'' and the author of the popular
guide to film on video will interview Wise on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Wise was a then-27-year-old film editor who had worked his way
up from messenger boy at RKO when he was assigned to ``Citizen
Kane.'' His skill so impressed Orson Welles that the director told
the studio's bosses that he wanted Wise's talents on his next
project, ``The Magnificent Ambersons.'' Ironically, when the studio
ordered a recut without Welles, Wise directed the additional
footage.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets cost $10 and can purchased by calling (800) 233-3123.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
