<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLVES-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MORE REASONS TO THINK DVD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The DVD revolution is in full force. Prices on
players are dropping dramatically (some for under $300), and you'll
see a big sales push this holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Besides much better picture and sound quality than VHS, DVDs
offer convenience (they take up less room and you can jump from
scene to scene without rewinding) and extras that are attractive to
film buffs.
</P>
<P>
   And since you'll need something to watch after you succumb to
the sales pressure and buy that player, here are a few titles of
note that have hit stores recently.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with two Oscar-winning best pictures _ ``Dances With
Wolves'' (Image Entertainment; $24.99) and ``West Side Story''
(MGM, $24.98).
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Costner's directorial debut has a certain old-fashioned
sweeping grandeur about it. ``Dances'' tells the story of a Union
officer (Costner) who is sent to a remote frontier outpost after
the Civil War, where he befriends a Lakota Indian tribe. The film
won seven Academy Awards and is filled with wonderful performances,
including those of Graham Greene, Rodney A. Grant and Mary
McDonnell, as well as rich visuals that benefit from DVD quality.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD offers commentary on the filming of the movie from
Costner and his producing partner, Jim Wilson. If you haven't seen
``Dances,'' watch it first and then you can follow along with
Costner and Wilson, who sat down nine years later to watch the film
and talk about about what they were doing in each scene. It's
actually quite interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Side Story'' also benefits from being on DVD. The
landmark musical, an updated version of ``Romeo and Juliet,''
contains an unforgettable score by Leonard Bernstein and explosive
ballet- and jazz-infused choreography by Jerome Robbins. The
direction, by Robbins and Robert Wise, is sometime clunky but often
brilliant, capturing the rhythm of the music and the New York City
streets. The colors jump out at you on the DVD format while the
classic score sizzles. Best Supporting Actress winner Rita Moreno
is superb, and numbers like ``America'' or ``The Jet Song'' haven't
cooled down in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The 1962 political thriller ``The Manchurian Candidate'' (MGM,
$24.98) remains as provocative as ever. This DVD version includes a
short 1989 feature where the film's star, Frank Sinatra, sits down
with its director, John Frankenheimer, and screenwriter, George
Axelrod, to reminisce about the film. In it, Sinatra shows off his
pinky, which he broke while doing the ``first kung fu'' film fight.
The three also talk about how the audience didn't seem to notice
that Laurence Harvey was only one year younger in real life than
Angela Lansbury, who played his mother with such steely resolve.
The DVD also has a scene-by-scene commentary by Frankenheimer,
including his thoughts on the incestuous Lansbury-Harvey
relationship in the film.
</P>
<P>
   You won't confuse ``The Dirty Dozen'' (MGM, $24.98) with
``Saving Private Ryan.'' Unlike Spielberg's gritty World War II
film, ``Dozen'' is one of those old-fashioned flicks that examines
the dual themes of heroism and the tragedy of war. It's a familiar
enough story, with Maj. Reisman (Lee Marvin) leading an elite force
behind enemy lines to eliminate a stronghold of German officers the
night before the D-Day invasion. Instead of consisting of
top-flight fighters, however, the team is made up of 12 army
prisoners _ soldiers who have committed murder, rape or other
violent crimes. Each has been sentenced to death or lengthy terms
in prison, and volunteering for the mission is their only way out.
There are some marvelous performances _ playing a sociopath is
always fun for an actor _ including those of John Cassavetes, Telly
Savalas and Charles Bronson. The DVD includes an informative
10-minute behind-the-scenes ``making of'' special documentary and
the film's original trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Another war flick, ``A Bridge Too Far'' (MGM; $24.98) was
thought by many to be too long, but Richard Attenborough's
adaptation of Cornelius Ryan's book about a disastrous raid behind
German lines in Holland during World War II is worth watching. It
also looks at the absurdity of war while not overlooking the
sacrifices made by both civilians and soldiers. The ill-fated
mission was conceived by British Field Marshal Montgomery, who
air-dropped some 35,000 troops behind Nazi lines in order to
shorten the war. But the mission is riddled with bad decisions
(based on politics and vanities) and communications failures that
ultimately cost many men their lives. The all-star cast includes
Dirk Bogarde, James Caan, Sean Connery, Robert Redford, Gene
Hackman, Anthony Hopkins, Laurence Olivier and Liv Ullmann. The DVD
also has a behind-the-scenes ``making of'' documentary. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
