<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9412 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCS-MUSIC-LADN     11-19 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL A GOOD COLLABORATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
SEAL/``Human Being'' (Warner Bros.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   For his first album in four years, the Grammy-winning Seal again
collaborates with producer Trevor Horn for a soulful and appealing
collection of elegant electro-tinged tunes. While there's nothing
here as immediately grabbing as the classy 1991 smash ``Crazy'' or
the award-winning ``Kiss From a Rose,'' there are warm nods to a
variety of styles, from techno-dance (``Latest Craze'') and sad
ballads (``Lost My Faith'') to acoustic tunes (``When a Man Is
Wrong'') and grand statements (``Human Beings''). Pleasant enough.
2 { Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MARIAH CAREY/``1's'' (Columbia)
</P>
<P>
   This Christmas winner collects all of Carey's 13 chart-toppers,
from ``I Don't Wanna Cry'' to the amazing vocal performances of
``My All'' and ``Honey,'' plus four new cuts. It's a useful disc if
you're a Mariah fan and don't have all the albums or singles. Along
with the familiar romantic-ballad chart-busters, the track list
includes the megahit single version of ``Fantasy'' (featuring
rapper ODB) and a previously unreleased live version of ``Hero.''
The quartet of new cuts features ``When You Believe,'' a so-so duet
with Whitney Houston from DreamWorks' forthcoming ``The Prince of
Egypt,'' and ``Whenever You Call,'' a much better duet with Brian
McKnight. 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
JEWEL/``Spirit'' (Atlantic)
</P>
<P>
   A flower child who's apparently spent too much time in the
potting soil, Jewel is back with another wispy, wistful set of
lighter-than-air acoustic guitar-picked melodies and greeting-card
sentiments. It's 13 tracks of ``everything's gonna be OK,'' cut too
quickly as a follow-up to her 8 million-selling debut, ``Pieces of
You.'' The songs that stood out on that first disc, incidentally,
were co-written with veteran San Diego singer-composer Steve Poltz;
he's nowhere to be found on ``Spirit,'' and maybe Jewel should have
considered sharing the credit _ and some of the loot _ one more
time. Her band is solid, but the only tracks that have long-term
listening value here are ``Kiss the Flame,'' the first single
``Hands'' and ``Down So Long.'' The rest of these songs have as
much depth as a stick of gum. 2 { Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
JIMMY SCOTT/``Holding Back the Years'' (Artists Only!)
</P>
<P>
   A half-century after he broke into the business with the Lionel
Hampton Orchestra, emotive crooner Scott lends his eerie,
penetrating voice to pop fare by the likes of John Lennon
(``Jealous Guy''), Elton John (``Sorry Seems to be the Hardest
Word''), Bryan Ferry (``Slave to Love'') and Elvis Costello
(``Almost Blue''), transforming each into a torchy gem. Other
highlights of this recommended jazz vocal collection include a
passionate reading of ``The Crying Game,'' from the 1992 film of
the same title, a poignant ``Nothing Compares 2 U'' by Prince, and
a remake of Scott's own bluesy hit from 1955, ``Don't Cry Baby.'' 3
{ Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
OFFSPRING/``Americana'' (Columbia)
</P>
<P>
   Fans of hits like ``Come Out and Play (Keep 'Em Separated)'' by
Orange County bashers Offspring will find much to enjoy in the
follow-up to the band's best-selling ``Ixnay on the Hombre'' disc.
Produced by the always-reliable Dave Jerden, the punk quartet's
energetic fifth album slams through standout melodic thrashers like
``Have You Ever,'' ``The Kids Aren't Alright'' and the sardonic
look at high school, ``Pretty Fly (For a White Guy),'' while
landing only one bum note, a prank cover of ``Feelings.'' 2 {
Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FEAR OF POP/``Fear of Pop Vol. 1'' (550 Music)
</P>
<P>
   Ben Folds of Ben Folds Five wrote all the material and played
all the instruments here, but don't expect anything resembling the
compelling piano-led trio he fronts as his day job. Instead, the
experimental yet still tuneful ``Fear of Pop Vol. 1,'' which
features ``Star Trek's'' William Shatner on hammy spoken-word
vocals on one track, breaks little new ground and should probably
be avoided until the new Ben Folds Five album next year. 1 {
Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOUNDTRACK/``The Prince of Egypt'' (DreamWorks) &QL; 
VARIOUS/``The Prince of Egypt: Inspirational'' (DreamWorks) &QL; 
VARIOUS/``The Prince of Egypt: Nashville'' (DreamWorks)
</P>
<P>
   This was the worst music marketing idea of the decade,
especially during a flat year in the record industry. Three
completely useless soundtracks, all released on a single Tuesday,
will do little more than cause puzzled fans to scratch their heads
and purchase the Mariah Carey greatest-hits disc or the Springsteen
box instead. Tied to the animated story of ``Exodus'' due in
theaters next month, these discs represent blatantly hollow aims.
The soundtrack itself is simply empty orchestral drivel with some
Ofra Haza thrown in along with a tepid Mariah Carey-Whitney Houston
duet on the movie's theme, which resembles two tomcats being
throttled to within an inch of their lives; the gospel collection
tries to wedge every contemporary Christian star and gospel-pop
crooner from Take 6 to Kirk Franklin to Jars of Clay under one
mediocre roof; and the country disc featuring an overbearing
Wynonna, Vince Gill and Faith Hill is enough to drive real country
fans to jazz. 1 { Stars each. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HANK WILLIAMS/``The Complete Hank Williams'' (Mercury Nashville)
</P>
<P>
   His recording career lasted only six years, his time at the top
of his profession barely four, and he was just 29 when a life of
excess caught up with him. Nonetheless, honky-tonk crooner Williams
created one of the greatest bodies of work in American music. Songs
like ``Your Cheatin' Heart,'' ``Hey, Good Lookin''' and
``Jambalaya'' sold millions, crossing over from the country to the
pop charts and becoming the model for all authentic country music
that followed. This 10-CD box contains more than 225 tracks,
including 53 previously unissued, from Williams' earliest sessions
in 1946 to his last date in 1952, as well as rare radio
performances, demos, TV and concert recordings and 14
never-before-released tunes. While it's a little difficult to get
through all this in even a single weekend, this stuff will live on
forever. 4 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE ORB/``U.F. Off'' (Island)
</P>
<P>
   The Orb's ``hits'' album celebrates 10 years of strange blips,
beeps and layers of noise otherwise known as the electronic genre
ambient-house. Masterminded by the very odd Dr. Alex Paterson, the
synth-heavy Orb typically weaves multirhythms, mixes in classical
influences and wraps it up with mid-tempo electronic beats. It's
been dubbed ``lame ambient noodling,'' but as background music
while vacuuming, the Orb can't be beat. 2 { Stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1538EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
