<HEADER>
A9490 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-TEXANS20-COX     11-19 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-TEXANS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAMM, ARCHER DISAGREE ON SOCIAL SECURITY
 &HT;    With SOCIAL-SECURITY.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Texans who will play a major role in reforming
Social Security disagreed Thursday over how the program works.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said the Social Security trust fund
doesn't really exist, that it doesn't receive interest payments and
that its soundness rests on the moral obligation of the government
to pay benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, said the trust fund holds special
U.S. Treasury bonds that pay interest and are as sound as U.S.
savings bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm is chairman of the Senate Finance Committee's Social
Security subcommittee. Archer is chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, which has jurisdiction over Social Security in
that chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm made his comments at the start of a Ways and Means hearing
on Social Security reforms. Archer made his comments after Gramm
left the room.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm compared the Social Security trust fund to a child with a
paper route who gave his earnings to his mother for safekeeping. If
his mother put the money into a cookie jar solely for the child's
use, it was a trust fund, Gramm said. If she used it as part of the
family budget, it was not a trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way the federal government uses Social Security, he
said. The money goes into the unified budget, and there is no
benefit of compound interest.
</P>
<P>
   Archer disagreed. Social Security payroll taxes are used to
purchase special Treasury bonds which can be redeemed only to pay
benefits to Social Security recipients, he said. The bonds earn
interest at about 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The special bonds are as safe as a Series EE U.S. savings bond,
Archer said. Anyone who doesn't believe that should burn their
savings bonds, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Although they disagree on the way the system works, Gramm and
Archer have both suggested reforming the program to allow workers
to create their own investment accounts using a portion of their
payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
