<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9491 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-AWARDS-BOS &LR;      11-19 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-AWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDERMOTT'S QUIET STORY EDGES WOLFE'S BLOCKBUSTER AT AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID MEHEGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  NEW YORK _ For the second year in a row, the heavy favorite
among bettors on the National Book Awards Wednesday night proved to
be lame in the stretch, as Alice McDermott's ``Charming Billy''
edged out Tom Wolfe's ``A Man in Full'' in the fiction category.
</P>
<P>
   Like Don DeLillo's ``Underworld'' last year, which lost to
Charles Frazier's dark horse ``Cold Mountain,'' the buzz among
publishing insiders was that Wolfe's glitzy blockbuster was a
shoo-in. But McDermott's novel, a quieter story about a troubled
young man and his lost love back home in Ireland, took the coveted
$10,000 prize. Publisher Farrar Straus &AMP; Giroux was the night's big
winner, collecting three of the four prizes: fiction, nonfiction,
and children's.
</P>
<P>
   The winner in nonfiction was Edward Ball for ``Slaves in the
Family,'' about the author's search for his family's slaveholding
history _ and his African-American relatives _ in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The children's award went to Louis Sachar for ``Holes,'' the
story of a boy sent to a juvenile detention center for a crime he
did not commit. In poetry, the prize went to Gerald Stern for
``This Time: New and Selected Poems'' (Norton).
</P>
<P>
   Eyebrows were raised last month when the Wolfe novel was
announced as a finalist before the book was published, even before
book editors had seen prepublication galley. Wolfe is famous for
last-minute alterations, and the fiction judges received the
700-plus-page book in loose typeset pages in a box. Novelist Thomas
Mallon, chairman of the fiction committee said, however, there was
precedent for prepublication nominations.
</P>
<P>
   In her acceptance, McDermott, whose previous work has probed the
heart and pain of the Irish-American experience, said, ``I wouldn't
be true to my Irish roots if I thought this was entirely a good
thing. I can hear my grandmother saying, `Now don't go getting a
swelled head.'''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the awards, novelist John Updike received the
National Book Foundation Medal for Distinguished Contribution to
American Letters, which also carries a $10,000 prize. Runners-up in
all categories get $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The other finalists in fiction:
</P>
<P>
   _Allegra Goodman, of Cambridge, for her first novel, ``Kaater- &QC; 
skill Falls'' (Dial Press), about gentiles and Orthodox Jewish
residents of a village in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   _Gayl Jones, for ``The Healing'' (Beacon Press), the story of
faith healer Harlan Jane Eagleton. It is Jones's first novel in 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   _Robert Stone of Westport, Conn., for his novel ``Damascus
Gate'' (Houghton Mifflin), about an attempt to bomb the Temple
Mount in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   _Tom Wolfe, for ``A Man in Full'' (Farrar Straus &AMP; Giroux), the
best-selling novel of race, business, and the New South.
</P>
<P>
   In nonfiction, the other finalists were:
</P>
<P>
   _Harold Bloom for ``Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human''
(Riverhead/Penguin), a close reading of the plays that argues that
the bard created the idea of character as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   _Yaffa Eliach, for ``There Once Was a World: A 900-Year
Chronicle of the Shtetl of Eishyshok'' (Little, Brown), which tells
of a hamlet in Poland, from the Middle Ages to its destruction by
the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   _Beth Kephart for ``A Slant of Sun: One Child's Courage''
(Norton), an account of the raising of a child with a severe
developmental disorder.
</P>
<P>
   _Henry Mayer for ``All on Fire: William Lloyd Garrison and the
Abolition of American Slavery'' (St. Martin's), a biography of the
Boston editor and abolitionist.
</P>
<P>
   The other poetry finalists were:
</P>
<P>
   _B. Harry Fairchild for ``The Art of the Lathe'' (Alice James
Books), about small-town, working class life in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   _Alicia Suskin Ostriker for ``The Little Space: Poems Selected
and New, 1968-1998'' (University of Pittsburgh Press), poems on
childhood, family, motherhood and religion.
</P>
<P>
   _Linda Pastan for ``Carnival Evening: New and Selected Poems
1968-1998'' (Norton), about the passions and complexities hidden
under ordinary life.
</P>
<P>
   _Carl Phillips for ``From the Devotions'' (Graywolf), poems
about the interaction of desire with physical, moral, and spiritual
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   In children's literature the other finalists were:
</P>
<P>
   _Ann Cameron for ``The Secret Life of Amanda K. Woods (Farrar
Straus &AMP; Giroux), the story of a girl who carves out a new identity
for herself.
</P>
<P>
   _Jack Gantos for ``Joey Pigza Swallowed the Key'' (Farrar Straus
&AMP; Giroux), about a boy struggling with hyperactivity.
</P>
<P>
   _Anita Lobel for ``No Pretty Pictures: A Child of War''
(Greenwillow), a memoir of imprisonment and flight in Nazi-occupied
Poland.
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Peck for ``A Long Way From Chicago'' (Dial Books),
about small-town and big-city life during the Depression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
