 Order Out of Business Card Chaos  
 By STEPHEN C. MILLER 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Business cards are the bane of my existence. Everywhere I go I
collect them. I swear that I'll enter them into my database as soon
as I get back to the hotel. I'll do maybe one or two, but then
fatigue creeps in and sleep is more important. At the end of each
trip, I dump the stack of cards in a desk drawer with all the rest
of those that I've never typed into the computer. The desk draw is
full.
</P>
<P>
   The problem becomes especially acute during conventions and
trade shows. As you read this, I'll be at Comdex in Las Vegas,
where 200,000 of my best friends will all try to give me their
business cards. There is no room in my desk drawer.
</P>
<P>
   Something had to be done. The something is to take another look
at business card scanners. I had one several years ago, but I
quickly stopped using it because the Optical Character Recognition
(OCR) software just didn't work very well. The problem was that
companies and individuals try to make their cards distinctive. That
distinctiveness -- fancy fonts, intricate logos and sideways
printing -- caused real headaches for the scanning software.
</P>
<P>
   With the right software, you can use just about any
TWAIN-complaint scanner, but there are several companies that make
dedicated business card scanners. I tested Corex Technologies'
CardScan 300. The company was one of the first into the market and
is one of the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It took very little time to get up and running. It took exactly
22 minutes from the time I opened the box, including reading the
Quick Start Guide, until I scanned my first card into the system.
My only complaint about the process was that the A/C power brick is
as heavy as a real brick. I can't remember when I've seen a heavier
one. It weighs more than the scanner. I'm going to have to have a
really good reason to scan cards on the road before I lug that
thing around. Cards are going to get scanned when I get back home.
</P>
<P>
   That aside, the software has reached a point where it whips
through a variety of business cards without breathing hard. While
you have to feed the scanner one card at a time, it zips them
through fast enough that you can keep a steady flow going. The
software then processes them all at once -- what we old-timers call
batch mode.
</P>
<P>
   I fed through 156 cards and the software failed to read only 4
of them. Each one was really off the chart. One was gold leaf with
Old English script. Another had a black background with silver
letters. The third had a picture and the text wrapped around it.
The last one had all the text woven through the company's logo.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that all the cards were translated perfectly.
I had to edit about five percent of them. But even those edits were
minor. I had one from a professor whose titles ran on forever. The
software has a simple solution when it cannot figure out where to
