<SLUG> BC-TECH-PATRONS-CYBERTIMES-ARTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS(AT)LARGE 
 HIGH-TECH COMPANIES SLOW TO SUPPORT HIGH-TECH ART 
</HEADLINE>
  By MATTHEW MIRAPAUL 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to Bill Viola, David Ross was able to play Andrew S.
Grove like a fiddle. But high-tech companies' support for
multimedia creativity still sounds more like a string trio than a
symphony.
</P>
<P>
   During a retrospective of Viola's video art at the Whitney
Museum of American Art in New York last spring, Ross, then the
Whitney's director, led Grove, chairman of the mammoth chip maker
Intel Corp., on a tour of the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was blown away by it,'' Ross, now the director of the San
Francisco Museum of Modern Art, recalled in a recent telephone
interview. ``From that point on, the conversations with others at
Intel became a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Those conversations culminated in a late-September announcement
that Intel would commit $6 million to sponsor ``The American
Century: Art and Culture 1900-2000,'' a sprawling overview
scheduled to open at the Whitney in April before moving to SFMOMA
in May 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy was impressed'' by the Viola tour, said Dana Houghton,
Intel's director of corporate affairs. ``Andy had been pretty
lukewarm. He's chairman of the company, and if he's lukewarm, it's
pretty hard to spend 6 million bucks without him knowing about it.
I don't know if it was Viola's work or Ross's salesmanship --
probably a combination of both.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the grant is believed to be the largest ever given
to an art museum for a specific exhibit -- and the $6 million
figure does not include another $2 million to $4 million for what
Houghton described as ``digital extensions'' to the show, including
an education-oriented Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Most significant to those interested in digital art is Intel's
willingness to finance commissions if the museums decide they want
to complement the ``American Century'' exhibit with new work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got money to do those kinds of things,'' Houghton said.
``Those are not real high-budget programs. You could do quite a bit
for a couple hundred thousand bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if that amount seems small in context, it represents a
remarkable departure for the computer industry, which has been slow
in supporting the new-media arts initiatives that its own
technology has enabled.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the heart of Silicon Valley, known as a hothouse
for digital creativity, the San Jose Museum of Art has not
progressed as quickly as officials had expected in collecting funds
for a 900-square-foot multimedia center, bringing in just half of
its $1.3 million goal so far. Among the projects planned for the
space, scheduled to open in a year, are a computer-based
three-dimensional recreation of the avant-garde electronic-art show
in the Pepsi pavilion at the 1970 World's Fair in Osaka, Japan, as
well as an Internet database providing access to the work of Bay
Area new media artists.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after its Whitney pledge, Intel did make a donation of
$10,000 to the San Jose center. Josi Callan, the museum's director,
said she was pleased that the chip maker was finally supporting the
arts in a substantial way, but that it was a ``bit of a
disappointment that it wasn't closer to home.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that Silicon Valley denizens are not
always accustomed to encountering high-tech art, said Randall
Packer, the San Jose art museum's director of multimedia.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is also a contributor to the newly reopened Tech Museum of
Innovation in San Jose, which has a high-tech art gallery called
``Center of the Edge.'' During a recent visit, Packer heard an
attendant describe one virtual-reality piece, Michael Naimark's
``Be Now Here,'' as ``the ride.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who work in the industry here are not particularly
interested in art,'' Packer said. ``They're interested in
technology, and they love the idea that there's a museum where you
can go see the latest technology -- and have fun. But in terms of
the sociocultural context of technology, that's just not what turns
them on. That's why I'm so impressed with David's work with Andy
Grove. He somehow managed to spark his imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hero, president of Community Foundation Silicon Valley,
which promotes philanthropy in the region, confirmed that ``there
aren't any really big corporate givers to the arts out here.''
</P>
<P>
   But a major factor that hinders arts giving in the area, Hero
explained, is that most of the companies are young, staffed by
employees who are relatively new to the region and managed by
executives who do not yet grasp that a strong cultural base can
help attract and retain workers. ``They just don't feel that
community obligation yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hero recalled a conversation several years ago with Bill
Hewlett, co-founder of the Hewlett-Packard Company, who he said
told him, ``Don't be so frustrated. These companies are so new. We
weren't really known for our charitable giving until we were 20
years old, but that was in 1964.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: some high-tech companies have supported, and
continue to support, traditional arts programs. While they are not
as closely associated with the arts as Philip Morris, Sara Lee,
Texaco and Reader's Digest, technology companies like IBM and
Hewlett-Packard actively support museums, orchestras and other
cultural institutions. Microsoft Corp. even has an art acquisition
committee that arranges for works to be displayed throughout the
software giant's campus.
</P>
<P>
   The largest gesture on this front was the Oct. 27 announcement
that five Dell Computer Corp. executives and their wives would
donate $13 million toward the construction of a new $35 million
home for the Austin Museum of Art, which is near Dell's home base
of Round Rock, Tex. Elizabeth Ferrer, the museum's director, said
one of the building's exhibit spaces would be designated as the Art
and Technology Gallery, devoted exclusively to artists who
incorporate technology into their work.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the National Endowment for the Arts is still
coping with budget cutbacks, this kind of support from the
high-tech community is essential.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Jedlicka, president of the Business Committee for the
Arts in New York, said, ``High-tech companies are involved in the
arts; they just don't receive a lot of publicity for their
involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose art museum's Packer said: ``It's difficult to have
the opportunity to deal with highly educated people who are
interested in culture in Silicon Valley. Sometimes you wonder if
they really exist.''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   _ Tech Museum of Innovation: thetech.org/
</P>
<P>
   _ Austin Museum of Art: amoa.org/
</P>
