<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9595 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-WITNESSES20-C     11-19 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WITNESSES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROFILES OF POTENTIAL WITNESSES IN IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY
 &HT;    EDS: Hyde plans to have the formal vote to approve these
subpoenas at a meeting immediately after Starr's testimony ends.
Since the GOP has more votes, they should be approved.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., has said Republicans
on his House Judiciary Committee plan to subpoena at least four
witnesses other than Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, who
testified Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Each would be questioned privately by committee staff members.
Some might then be called to testify before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   DANIEL A. GECKER
</P>
<P>
   An attorney in Richmond, Va., he represented Kathleen Willey
during much of the time that she dealt with demands for her sworn
testimony in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit and in the
independent counsel's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Willey has charged, denied and then charged once again that
President Clinton made an unwelcome and uninvited pass at her in
1993, when she was a White House volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Willey's attorney-client privilege would keep Gecker from
talking about his dealings with her. But Republicans want to know
whether Gecker, 42, noticed signs that other people were trying to
influence Willey's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   NATHAN LANDOW
</P>
<P>
   He met Willey when she and his daughter were both White House
volunteers during Clinton's first term.
</P>
<P>
   He has confirmed to reporters that last fall he had her flown
from her home in Virginia to his retreat on Maryland's Eastern
Shore to discuss her misgivings, but has denied that he told Willey
to perjure herself or to avoid testifying.
</P>
<P>
   But when he was subpoenaed this year to testify before a grand
jury seeking to find out whether whatever he said was done on his
own or on behalf of the president, Landow invoked his Fifth
Amendment right not to testify. He may have feared opening the door
to questions concerning another federal probe, which concerns his
dealings with an Indian tribe that had hoped its campaign
contributions would help it obtain approval of a land deal by the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Landow, 65, is a developer whose nationwide business started
with projects in the District of Columbia and its suburbs. A former
Maryland Democratic Party chairman, Landow is best known as a
gregarious Democratic volunteer who specializes in convincing other
rich business people to give up to $1,000 apiece to presidential
campaigns. He raised substantial funds in 1976 for Jimmy Carter,
and a total of $600,000 for the 1992 and 1996 Clinton-Gore
campaigns, and even more for the losing campaigns of Walter Mondale
in 1984 and Al Gore in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   BRUCE R. LINDSEY
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer who graduated from Rhodes College and Georgetown Law
school, the 50-year-old Arkansan has known Clinton since 1968,
offering personal and professional advice and relaxing with
hundreds of games of hearts during all of Clinton's campaigns for
and terms as governor and president.
</P>
<P>
   A close and close-mouthed confidant, Lindsay has been involved
in many of Clinton's discussions and strategy sessions on how to
deal with career-threatening controversies over concerns ranging
from early Whitewater land deals to Monica Lewinsky's testimony and
the rejection of suspicious contributions to Clinton's first legal
defense fund.
</P>
<P>
   Because Lindsey is on the public payroll as deputy White House
counsel, Clinton was unable to convince the courts that
attorney-client privilege could be invoked to keep Lindsey from
testifying before one of Starr's grand juries. Though that
testimony turned out to be relatively innocuous, Starr has since
tried to convince the Judiciary Committee that when Clinton and
Lindsey discussed the handling of the Paula Jones lawsuit, the
president was improperly using a government attorney ``to assist
his personal legal defense.''
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT S. BENNETT
</P>
<P>
   As the private attorney defending Clinton against the sexual
harassment lawsuit brought by Paula Jones, Bennett succeeded in
delaying the case until after the 1996 election, then convinced a
judge to throw out the lawsuit. Jones appealed, but Bennett
negotiated a settlement before the appeals court ruled on the case.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the president was answering questions under oath
during that lawsuit, he falsely denied that he had a sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky. Starr has told the committee
that he believes that Lewinsky and Clinton conspired to lie in that
case. How Bennett, 58, could offer useful testimony without
violating his legal duty to protect Clinton's attorney-client
privilege is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
