<HEADLINE>
ON OR OFF STAGE, HOUSE HUNTING CAN BE TRICKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rl)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The battle over the Helen Hayes Theater ended this
week with the announcement that ``Band in Berlin,'' a new musical
about a singing troupe in Nazi Germany, would open there in late
February.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the theater's owner, Martin Markinson, to book
the musical was a heartbreaker for two off-Broadway hits vying for
a Broadway house: ``Wit,'' Margaret Edson's acclaimed drama, and
``This Is Our Youth,'' a dark comedy by Kenneth Lonergan.
</P>
<P>
   But by week's end there was a happy ending for at least one of
the shows. Negotiations were completed Thursday to bring ``Wit'' to
the Union Square Theater, a 499-seat house where ``Visiting Green''
closes on Sunday. ``Wit'' will finish its current run on Dec. 13 at
the 99-seat MCC Theater before reopening later that week in the
larger space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're totally thrilled,'' said Bernard Telsey, who will
produce the show along with Daryl Roth and the Long Wharf Theater.
``It's going to be the same intimate experience but for 500 people
a night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Our Youth,'' meanwhile, was also negotiating a
possible deal to move from its current home at Second Stage to the
Minetta Lane, where ``Primary English Class'' is folding after a
rude reception from critics.
</P>
<P>
   At the Helen Hayes, Markinson said he hoped ``Getting and
Spending,'' the current occupant, would last into 1999. But don't
count on it; weekly grosses are hovering around $70,000, an
estimated weekly loss of more than $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Band in Berlin,'' the move to Broadway comes as a pleasant
surprise. The show had originally been scheduled to open in
November at the Union Square but was bumped when the producer of
``Visiting Green'' unexpectedly extended that show. ``The Helen
Hayes was always my dream,'' said Robert V. Straus, a producer of
``Berlin.'' ``I didn't really want any other theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Something's Coming
</P>
<P>
   When Livent was chosen in August to renovate the Times Square
Theater on West 42d Street, it triumphed over higher bidders
because it planned a new theater for the space. But now that the
deal has collapsed, live performance may not be in the cards for
the 78-year-old landmark.
</P>
<P>
   Cora Cahan, the president of New 42d Street, which oversees the
space, said this week that of the half-dozen candidates for the
renovation, most made it clear they were not interested in building
a performance space. The theater poses several problems for
productions, ranging from its age to potential noise problems, to
its lack of an adequate lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really great for theater in its current state,'' Ms.
Cahan said.
</P>
<P>
   A real estate executive said current candidates included
Empire!, a Roman gladiator-theme restaurant; the Laugh Factory, a
comedy club, as well as the Manhattan Theater Club and the producer
Alexander H. Cohen, with a proposal for a vaudeville theater. Ms.
Cahan said she hoped for a decision by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Experience Optional
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect, most Broadway producers are a, well,
mature breed. And manly, too.
</P>
<P>
   Not Arielle Tepper. At 26, she is by far the youngest producer
on Broadway today, sharing top billing on Sandra Bernhard's ``I'm
Still Here . . . Damn It!''
</P>
<P>
   The show is Ms. Tepper's second on Broadway; her first was John
Leguizamo's ``Freak,'' which she produced with Gregory Mosher and
Bill Haber. Off-Broadway, Ms. Tepper is involved in ``Villa
Villa,'' at the Daryl Roth, and ``Trainspotting,'' at the Player's
Theater. Not bad for a woman whose first professional producing
experience was in March 1997, putting on an unknown musical in a
small theater in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a job after my freshman year in college in a production
office,'' Ms. Tepper said, speaking from a cellular phone from the
set of an independent film she's producing in Yonkers. ``Within 24
hours I knew this was what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tepper grew up in a wealthy family on the Upper East Side of
Manhattan and attended the Dalton School before studying lighting
design at Syracuse University.
</P>
<P>
   Like her idol, Cameron Mackintosh, she has experienced both
success and something less. While ``Freak'' was a hit, and ``I'm
Still Here'' is showing promise, ``Trainspotting'' has had a rough
time with the critics. Still, Ms. Tepper seems undeterred. ``If
I've figured one thing out,'' she said, ``it's the only way to
learn is to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   `Godot' Has Arrived
</P>
<P>
   Add ``Waiting for Godot'' and ``Stop Kiss'' to the growing list
of off-Broadway productions showing strong sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godot,'' which opened on Wednesday at the 180-seat Classic
Stage Company on East 13th Street, has sold out almost all its
six-week run, through Dec. 20. Barry Edelstein, the artistic
director of the theater, said that it had held back 500 seats, and
that those tickets would go sale today at $45, up from $35. With
apologies to Beckett, the obvious draw has been the cast: John
Turturro, Tony Shalhoub and Christopher Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to see actors they know are great,'' Edelstein
said. ``And in our theater, you're sitting five feet away.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of ``Stop Kiss'' is less easily explained. The play,
which began previews at the Public Theater on Tuesday, was about 85
percent sold out by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction has flummoxed the playwright, Diana Son, whose most
recent work had a brief off-off-Broadway run earlier this year.
``Stop Kiss'' concerns the repercussions on the lives of two women
after they kiss. ``I think people have heard it's a comedy about
New York, a drama about gay bashing and a love story, and it really
is all of those,'' said Ms. Son, 32. ``I guess people want to see
if we can pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   You Know His Name
</P>
<P>
   The next cast for ``Art'' _ George Wendt, Judd Hirsch and Joe
Morton _ will take over on Dec. 22. It will be the Broadway debut
for Wendt, the former ``Cheers'' star who just finished a
14-week-run of ``Art'' in London. ``The idea of opening London as
an American was a little scarier,'' he said. ``This is kind of a
lateral move in terms of scariness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
