<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, Nov. 20. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
JOBLESS-ARIZONA (Phoenix) - With the holidays approaching,
retailers at Arizona Mills last month went shopping for workers.
The Tempe, Ariz., mall held two job fairs in October, seeking to
fill 800 full and part-time positions. But many stores left with
their bags empty, as the recruitment effort generated just 500
referrals - and not all of those people were hired. Despite a
slowing national economy, a lingering crisis in Asia and some
well-publicized layoffs among local high-tech and mining companies,
Arizona's job market continues to boom. In fact, the Department of
Economic Security said Thursday that the state's jobless rate has
dropped to its lowest level since modern record-keeping began 28
years ago. By RUSS WILES. Story will move in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NURSING-SHORTAGE (Phoenix) - Every day in the Phoenix area, there's
a chance that a hospital unit could be shut down because of a lack
of nurses. Arizona is experiencing a shortage of up to 10,000
nurses, and even the most generous incentives aren't solving the
problem. Nurses, particularly those from out of state, are being
offered signing bonuses of up to $6,000, trips to Hawaii, college
tuition for their children and other incentives to work at Valley
hospitals. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will move in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BIBLE-ARIZONA (Undated) - Sixteen simple words adopted in 1791:
Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion,
or prohibiting the free exercise thereof. But why is it OK to pray
before a town council meeting but not proclaim Bible Week? Why can
the president proclaim National Day of Prayer and not get sued?
Religion is pervasive in government and civic life and the line of
church-state separation is fuzzy at best. We talk to experts on
both sides about what specifically is and isn't legal and how some
things - like National Day of Prayer - may violate the
Constitution. By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ENEMY-MOVIE (Undated) - Maybe Will Smith decided to star in a bad
spy thriller to find out if we really, really like him. You'd
better be among Smith's top fans because he's the only thing
``Enemy of the State'' has going for it. By BOB FENSTER. Story will
move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CELEBRITY-MOVIE (Undated) - Writer/director Woody Allen stays
behind the camera in ``Celebrity,`` a bitter comedy about a
magazine writer who pursues famous women but can find no
satisfaction. Allen's witty observations about human foibles are
dragged down by Kenneth Branagh's annoying over-anxiety and
off-putting comic delivery. By BOB FENSTER. Story will move in the
``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
JOURNEY-THEATER (Undated) - Anyone who has watched Arizona Theatre
Company grow from a Tucson community theater to the state's largest
stage operation must be bursting their buttons with pride. With
``Long Days Journey Into Night,'' the company has outgrown Arizona.
This production, a landmark revival of Eugene O'Neill's
masterpiece, is as fine a piece of theater as you would see in New
York and London. By KYLE LAWSON. Story will move in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SPACEY-MOVIE (Undated) - Terrorizing young children, berating the
elderly and flaunting a scathing personality. Not exactly the
behavior one would expect from an Oscar-winning actor, especially
in a Disney film. But please, rub your hind legs together for Kevin
Spacey in ``A Bug's Life,'' and his portrayal of Hopper, the
baddest grasshopper this side of the cinema.By KATHY CANO-MURILLO.
Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Undated) - Macho truck guys adore the mighty Ford
F-250 Super Duty. Its hulking appearance, its brawny V-10 engine,
its broad interior: This is a big rig among pickup trucks.The Super
Duty is a truck for the job site. For personal use, it could be
used for carrying big loads, towing heavy objects or lugging a
camper. But the Super Duty is not exactly the kind of pickup you'd
choose for your hip urban vehicle, as you might an F-150
flare-side. By BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
