<HEADER>
A9721 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLET-INNERCITY-COX     11-19 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLET-INNERCITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An urban 'Nutcracker'
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Give Nena Gilreath and Waverly Lucas a kid who lacks
focus, discipline or self-esteem, and they'll put him in a pair of
tights.
</P>
<P>
   Then they'll teach the youngster the meaning of hard work and
responsibility through a series of body-writhing, toe-pointing,
leg-leaping exercises.
</P>
<P>
   Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   As co-founders of Ballethnic, a classically trained dance troupe
that fuses modern, jazz and African dance movements with
traditional ballet, Gilreath and Lucas have been working their
magic on metro Atlanta kids for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The children will demonstrate their talent this weekend, when
the company stages its signature performance of ``Urban
Nutcracker'' at Georgia Tech's Robert Ferst Center. The ballet, set
on Auburn Avenue to depict the history of Atlanta's wealthy
African-American community, includes more than 70 youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons Gilreath and Lucas started Ballethnic in 1990
was to take classical ballet to inner-city youths. They especially
want to expose black males to the art form, to give them a positive
alternative to drugs, crime and other anti-social behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas tries to counteract myths that real guys don't wear tights
by rattling off a list of macho men who learned how to be more
agile in sports by dancing on their toes.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Swann. Herschel Walker. Willie Gault. Jean Claude van
Damme. Then there's Lucas himself, a basketball player and martial
artist who grew up in the 'hood and took his first ballet class at
age 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were not doing this, you can imagine what I, a young
black man on the streets of Detroit, would be doing,'' Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to start portraying dance in a different way for young
men. For me, dance is very masculine,'' added Lucas, who is also
the company's choreographer and artistic director and Gilreath's
husband of six years.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Perry, 14, has been a student at Ballethnic since he was
7. His classmates used to tease him when he took up ballet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it doesn't bother me,'' said Jamal, who performs a Russian
dance in the ``Urban Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to say I must can't play football, or I must can't
play baseball. But this year I played every game. The only time I
got off the field was at halftime. Now they're like, `Wow, ballet
must really help you.' Now they want to take dance too,'' he said.
``They just don't want to wear tights.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballethnic's founders think ballet is one of the best ways to
teach youngsters the self-discipline they need to succeed in school
and in life. That's why dance classes focus on exercises that
require students to sit still, listen and follow instructions.
</P>
<P>
   The company offers courses to children as young as 6. In
January, classes will begin for preschoolers.
</P>
<P>
   Gilreath and Lucas also want to show young people through their
own example how hard work and determination can help accomplish
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Gilreath, a petite woman with a dynamic voice, recalls how they
had to scramble for costumes for ``Urban Nutcracker's'' first
season. Every weekend, they rummaged through garage sales in search
of discarded prom dresses and formals. They had to stage the ballet
in November, a month earlier than the Christmas story is normally
performed, because all the theaters were booked. And the troupe
started with Act II, because Gilreath and Lucas didn't have the
resources to stage the first act.
</P>
<P>
   But the couple's dream of running Atlanta's first black ballet
company never died. These days, dance critics compare it to Dance
Theater of Harlem, the only other African-American classical ballet
company in the country. Lucas and Gilreath, both 34, danced with
the Harlem company and the Atlanta Ballet before going out on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Their resourceful spirit is one of the things that attracted the
support of Mozel Spriggs, former chairwoman of dance in Spelman
College's Division of Fine Arts, and big corporations such as
NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that they were the future of Atlanta,'' Spriggs said.
``Their energy, their determination, their ideas for combining
these art forms in a ballet company was, in a way, revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Ballethnic's approach to students.
</P>
<P>
   They want to work with the boys who might be a little clumsy or
rough around the edges. They welcome the girls whose bodies fill
out their tutus. And most of all they inspire kids whose faces are
browner, their hair kinkier, than the stereotypical ballerina's to
master the art form.
</P>
<P>
   Their students see them as family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Waverly really cares a lot about us,'' Jamal says.
``Sometimes, we come early to class, and he'll help us with our
homework.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing can definitely be a self-esteem builder,'' adds
Jennifer Thomas, 15, who has three parts in ``Urban Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never really talkative,'' she says. ``Now I'm a lot more
open. Dancing has brought out different things in my personality
and helped me become more of the person I am now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
