<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9722 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELIZABETH-COX     11-19 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIZABETH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Elizabeth' examines the Virgin Queen from a fresh, feminist
perspective
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elizabeth'' is such a good idea for a movie that it's sort of
amazing no one thought of it during, say, the past 25 years.
Basically, the film puts a slight feminist gloss on the ascension
of Queen Elizabeth I, known not only as the Virgin Queen but also
as one of the most powerful and effective rulers in British
history. She stayed on the throne for more than 40 years and, like
her descendant Queen Victoria, gave her name to an era.
</P>
<P>
   She's been portrayed onscreen before (most famously by Bette
Davis), usually as a strong-willed yet love-starved woman, torn
between her professional duties and her personal life.
``Elizabeth'' takes something of the same tack. So does most of
feminism, which makes the film seem both familiar and provocative.
Yet the connection is made with a relatively light hand. We're not
being preached at so much as being invited to see a celebrated
historical figure in a fresh way.
</P>
<P>
   The story starts in 1554 with Mary (Kathy Burke), Elizabeth's
half sister and a devout Catholic, still on the throne. But she is
childless and unwell. Thus the younger Elizabeth (Cate Blanchett),
Protestant daughter of Henry VIII and Anne Boleyn, poses a threat
by her very existence. Somehow surviving everything from palace
plots to imprisonment, Elizabeth becomes queen. How she's
transformed from the radiant, open-hearted girl we first meet into
the chilly icon of the Virgin Queen _ frizzy-haired and powder
white _ is the picture's focus.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchett, seen earlier this year as the sensibly eccentric
Lucinda in ``Oscar and Lucinda,'' makes a sensational Elizabeth.
She's a saucy and impetuous innocent in the early scenes, a guarded
and polished ruler by the end. Oscar winner Geoffrey Rush
(``Shine'') gives sturdy support as Sir Francis Walsingham, the
shadowy power behind the throne. We're never quite sure if he can
be trusted, or whether he's putting his own interests or
Elizabeth's first. Joseph Fiennes, who's almost as handsome as his
better-known sibling, Ralph (Blanchett's co-star in ``Oscar and
Lucinda''), is well cast in the comparatively thankless role of
Lord Robert Dudley, the man to whom Elizabeth gives her heart if
not her throne. There's even John Gielgud in a nanosecond cameo as
the decidedly anti-Elizabeth pope.
</P>
<P>
   Having the most fun, however, is the French contingent, Fanny
Ardant and Vincent Cassel. Ardant plays France's ambitious
``warrior queen,'' as formidable on the battlefield as she is in
the bedroom. Cassel is her whimsical nephew who, at her behest,
dutifully woos Elizabeth while still being true to his inner bad
boy.
</P>
<P>
   Indian filmmaker Shekhar Kapur isn't worried about the cliches
of historical drama: the portentous, history-in-the-making
dialogue, the elaborate royal entertainments, the whispered court
intrigues. Rather he embraces them, thus investing them with a
renewed vitality. True, there are a few lingering clinkers, but for
the most part, the movie's opulent production design (look for some
Oscar nominations), accomplished cast and raucous, event-filled
narrative win out.
</P>
<P>
   Should you tire of Elizabeth's romantic problems, remember that
sex and violence are what history is all about. There's plenty of
vicious religious fanaticism, manifested in scenes worthy of Ken
Russell's ``The Devils.'' And one sequence could be a replay of the
final purge in ``The Godfather,'' only the clothes are prettier and
the deaths more brutal.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is simple: ``Elizabeth'' is a really good
story. The story of a girl becoming a woman, of a woman becoming a
queen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Cate Blanchett and Geoffrey Rush. Directed by Shekhar
Kapur. Rated R for sex and violence. At Tara. 2 hours, 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The total woman, Elizabethan-style.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
