<HEADER>
A9725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-CELEBRITY-COX     11-19 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-CELEBRITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woody's fame game goes stale
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woody Allen seems to be in a strange place these days.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, there was ``Wild Man Blues.'' Supposedly a
documentary about his jazz band's European tour, it was actually
some thinly disguised, image-enhancing spin control vis-a-vis
himself and his new spouse, Soon-Yi.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ``Celebrity,'' which features Kenneth Branagh _ as in
``Hamlet'' and ``Henry V'' _ doing a jaw-dropping imitation of his
director, down to every stammer and twitch. For a while it's eerily
fascinating and even a bit funny. But then it turns tedious and,
well, more than a little weird as you remember that Allen is
standing on the other side of the camera, watching _ approving! _
this homage/impersonation of himself.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's Branagh's co-star, Judy Davis. A longtime,
usually brilliant Allen regular (``Husbands and Wives,''
``Deconstructing Harry''), she's doing Woody too. The neurotic
whining, the self-deprecating put-downs, even a Woody-esque worry
about contracting Lyme disease while strolling outside. Again,
you're initially intrigued, then you start to wonder, is this what
Woody wanted? Two people ``doing'' him?
</P>
<P>
   Within the movie's world, Branagh and Davis play former husband
and wife, Lee and Robin Simon. He's a travel writer and would-be
novelist with a screenplay he peddles on the side to his star
interviews. She's an English teacher, undone by the divorce and,
unlike her ex, just looking for a little peace of mind. Ironically,
during a should-I-or-shouldn't-I visit to a renowned plastic
surgeon, Robin meets a TV producer (Joe Mantegna) who not only
falls madly in love with her, but builds her into a major on-air
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrity'' is a terrific idea for a movie. As one character
says, ``You can learn a lot about a society by whom it chooses to
celebrate.'' But perhaps Allen himself has been famous for too
long. His film is less a thought-through investigation of an
omnipresent phenomenon than a scattershot series of sketches about
supermodels, hotel-trashing movie stars (Leonardo DiCaprio), the
art world, book signings at Elaine's, and so on. It's as if he had
pulled some old scenes from his to-look-at-later drawer and strung
them together into what might pass for a cohesive narrative. Some
of the pieces are hilarious: backstage at a TV show where the
rabbis, skinheads and ACLU lawyers are old pals from making the
talk-show rounds (``The skinheads ate the bagels already?'' grouses
a rabbi), or a fan accosting a TV weatherman with the backhanded
compliment, ``You're usually wrong, but you're always so
cheerful.''
</P>
<P>
   But too much of the movie is familiar to the point of being
stale. The star-spangled cast helps (along with DiCaprio, there are
appearances by Melanie Griffith, Winona Ryder, Charlize Theron,
Famke Janssen, Bebe Neuwirth and Isaac Mizrahi). But, then, a cameo
in a Woody Allen movie has itself become a certification of
celebrity, hasn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrity'' is aimed at those who can pick out Erica Jong in a
crowd scene or know Joey Buttafuoco (billed in the credits ``as
himself'') when they see him. If that's you, get in line. But Woody
has done better _ by his audience and himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrity''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kenneth Branagh and Judy Davis. Directed by Woody
Allen. Rated R for language and sexual situations. At metro
theaters. 1 hour, 54 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Fame is the name of the game, but the game is too
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
