<HEADER>
A9726 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-RUGRATS-COX     11-19 0325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-RUGRATS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keep telling yourself: `Rugrats' is for kids
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Rugrats Movie'' takes the Nickelodeon hit from the small
screen to the big. And it tackles a big subject: making room for
baby.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Tommy Pickles (voiced by E.G. Daily) has to do when
his folks come home from the hospital with Dylan ``Dil'' Pickles.
On top of dealing with the constant crying, Tommy can't help
noticing all the attention his parents are giving to this needy
newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   His pals Phil and Lil (Kath Soucie does both voices) and Chuckie
(Christine Cavanaugh) aren't crazy about the new kid, either. So
when they all get lost in the woods, Tommy fears that he has to
choose between playing with his friends and tending his nuisance
baby bro.
</P>
<P>
   Having never seen a ``Rugrats'' TV episode, I'll defer judgment
to the tiny children at the screening, who seemed to enjoy the
frenetic movie and the forgettable songs. They didn't seem to mind
the scary wolf, and they dug the poop jokes and the runaway circus
monkeys that pester the kids.
</P>
<P>
   The movie takes care of grown-ups every now and then, tossing
off a circumcision joke or pop-culture reference (``Is it true a
dingo ate your baby?'' asks a reporter when the Pickles parents
realize their children are missing).
</P>
<P>
   Even so, adults will probably feel antsier than the children,
having to listen to adult actors performing in baby voices and
mispronouncing words in gosh-darn-cute-kid fashion. But, hey, look
at it this way: It could be another Barney flick, or a Teletubbies
feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rugrats Movie''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring the voices of E.G. Daily and Christine Cavanaugh.
Directed by Norton Virgien and Igor Kovalyov. Rated G. At metro
theaters. 1 hour, 19 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A busy adventure for small children.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
