<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Nov. 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, powerful jet stream winds blowing 30,000 feet
over the northern Pacific Ocean were clocked at speeds near 200
miles an hour. This robust jet stream will set the stage for a
pattern of recurrent storminess over the Pacific Northwest over the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
   A barrage of wind and rain will last for much of Friday in
western Washington and western Oregon as strong, low-level winds
off the Pacific rapidly transport moisture inland. Ocean winds will
average 25-50 miles an hour at the coast, with higher gusts on
exposed beaches. Rainfalls of 2 inches or more are likely along
west-facing slopes of the Olympics, the Cascades and the Coastal
Ranges, where moist Pacific winds are forced to ascend the sloping
terrain. Rainfalls could exceed 5 inches or more in some areas by
Saturday morning. The risk of flooding will heighten, particularly
in the drainage system near the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, air cascading down the eastern slopes of the
Rockies will warm on descent, extricating the high northern Plains
from the deep chill of earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, broken areas of rain will spread from the Ohio Valley
early Friday toward the Middle Atlantic states as a low-pressure
system ripples northeast along a cold front. Much of southeast New
England will brighten once an arm of moisture swings east over the
Atlantic. A plume of high clouds streaming northeast from the
Middle Atlantic low will render the day mostly cloudy in New York
and Boston, with some rain arriving later Friday or Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Dueling Gulfs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many recipes for stormy weather in the East include moisture
from the Gulf of Mexico. The Gulf of Alaska also is a catalyst for
storminess. During the cold season, low-pressure systems coming off
the east coast of Asia are steered to the Gulf of Alaska, where
they often dissipate. But dying lows also plant seeds for new lows,
which then amplify, drawing energy from temperature contrasts
between the Arctic and milder air over the tepid waters of the
northern Pacific. This week, a huge, potent low over the Gulf of
Alaska will send a barrage of wind and rain into the Pacific
Northwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
