A9747 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE20-COX     11-19 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HISTORY AND HYPE AT CAPITOL HILL
 &HT;    Cox photos for this story will be placed in the National folder
on the Cox server.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Standing in the hallway outside the House Judiciary
Committee hearing, Doug Muzzio waited much of Thursday for his turn
to see a half hour of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up at 5 o'clock this morning and said, 'How can I be
here and not watch this?' I'd be crazy to miss it,'' said Muzzio, a
New York University professor here to do research at the Library of
Congress for a book on movie history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he WAS crazy,'' said his wife, Barbara, who
nonetheless came with her husband at about 7 a.m. to await their 30
minutes in the two seats set aside for the public in the packed
chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Rotating through, scores of visitors got a first-hand glimpse of
this long day of drama and droning on, as the only third
impeachment proceeding in the nation's history dragged toward its
uncertain conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr was presenting his
case against President Clinton to Congress, and seeing it on a
small screen was not good enough for these folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an historic process,'' said Isamu Dyson, a George
Washington University student who arrived at 5:45 a.m. to be the
first in line. ``I'm being a good citizen being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting in line, people pointed excitedly when committee members
passed by _ celebrities to the committed devotees of cable TV
channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an addict,'' admitted Muzzio, who teaches public policy
and wrote a book on the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite side of the Rayburn Building, other tourists
gathered to gawk at TV correspondents as reporters and technicians
worked in a makeshift studio set up in a lobby. Signs taped to
partitions identified the media territories: Fox, CBS, ABC, Lehrer
News Hour, Court TV, CBN. From chairs on the adjoining balcony,
carefully coiffed men and women told their stories with the Capitol
as a backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a parade of committee members stopped by the bank of
microphones and cameras set up at the end of the lobby to give
their spin on the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now this is good theater over here,'' said Rep. Lindsay
Graham, R-S.C., after a bystander yelled his opinion. ``But the
question is: Is Ken Starr unfair?''
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly the opinion of Michael Moore, the documentary
film-maker of ``Roger and Me,'' who was filming a segment for his
TV program ``The Awful Truth,'' which appears on Bravo. ``I'm
shooting stuff on Ken Starr's attempted coup d'etat.''
</P>
<P>
   But Starr was a hero to the protesters outside _ so-called
``freepers'' devoted to FreeRepublic.com, a conservative Internet
site. Wearing engineer's caps, they blew whistles and cheered the
start of ``the impeachment express.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Muzzios inched closer to the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to do the museums today,'' lamented Barbara
Muzzio.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thinks this is the line to see the van Gogh exhibit,''
laughed another of those awaiting entry.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
