<SLUG> BC-TV-MAYBE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SAINT MAYBE': RAISING ORPHANS TO ATONE FOR THEIR LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the sort of thing that happens when you're exhausted and
fed up and have been holding something back. It happens to Ian
Bedloe one night when his wacky sister-in-law, Lucy, asks him to
baby-sit for an hour, and then doesn't come back. This causes him
to miss a romantic dinner date with his girlfriend, Cicely.
</P>
<P>
   So by the time Ian's brother, Danny, turns up and drives him to
Cicely's house, Ian is steaming. He lets the accusations rip:
Hasn't Danny noticed that Lucy goes out a lot, supposedly with her
girlfriends, and comes back late, and that she seems to be buying a
lot of things she can't really afford? The clues make it all too
clear: She's being unfaithful.
</P>
<P>
   Danny, who has had suspicions, is now convinced. He lets Ian out
of the car and promptly drives into a tree, killing himself. Ian
will spend the rest of his life atoning.
</P>
<P>
   That scene sets the mood for ``Saint Maybe,'' a CBS movie based
on Anne Tyler's 1991 novel of the same name. Ms. Tyler, as her many
readers know, likes to take a cold, bleak look at human
relationships, particularly within families. Her characters reach
the warm, beaming-with-contentment stage _ if they do at all _ only
after painful self-examination under harsh light at the kitchen
table.
</P>
<P>
   As long as ``Saint Maybe'' keeps Ms. Tyler's tone, the film is
fascinating and moving. But apparently the writer, Robert W.
Lenski, or whoever gave him the assignment, just couldn't resist
turning it lazily heart-warming just in time for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Blythe Danner as Ian and Danny's mother helps,
because her glow always has a certain edge. Edward Herrmann is well
cast as the father. Mary-Louise Parker is one of the few actresses
who can get away with playing daffy, as she does here as Lucy. And
Thomas McCarthy makes Ian's transformation from college brat to
responsible surrogate father largely believable and sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Saint Maybe,'' the movie, refuses to do much questioning.
After the death of Danny (Jeffrey Nordling) and Lucy's subsequent
suicide, Ian wanders into a storefront church, where a minister
tells him the only way to be forgiven for his sin is to rear the
three children Lucy and Danny left behind.
</P>
<P>
   The only hint that this might be a strange, rather sudden turn
of events comes from Ms. Danner. Ian rushes home, tells his parents
about his plan and explains, ``It's the will of God.'' Ms. Danner
says, ``Who?''
</P>
<P>
   And the film seems to skip over what must be the most difficult
and most rewarding part of Ian's story: the two decades of rearing
the children. One minute, it seems, two children are in grade
school and one in the crib, and Ian is dropping out of college; the
next, the older daughter is a doctor in Los Angeles and Ian has a
receding hairline.
</P>
<P>
   There is one scene in between, in which the older daughter
declares herself an atheist and stays home from church. Apparently
that is meant to represent the day-to-day, never-ending challenges
of being a parent.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Ian was wrong about Lucy in some very
important ways, a fact that would haunt any thinking, feeling adult
for life. But in all fairness, he and the rest of the tortured
Bedloes certainly do deserve a merry Christmas scene by the tree,
and they get it.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SAINT MAYBE'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Sunday on CBS
</P>
<P>
   Written for television by Robert W. Lenski and based on the
novel by Anne Tyler. Michael Pressman, director; Suzy
Beugen-Bishop, supervising producer; Brent Shields, producer. Music
by Ernest Troost. Shelly Johnson, director of photography. From
Hallmark Hall of Fame Productions, Richard Welsh, executive
producer.
</P>
<P>
   With: Mary-Louise Parker (Lucy), Blythe Danner (Bee), Edward
Herrmann (Doug), Melina Kanakaredes (Rita), Thomas McCarthy (Ian)
and Jeffrey Nordling (Danny).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
