<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUGRATS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE RUGRATS MOVIE': A SIBLING TAKES A NEW RIVAL FOR A RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By ANITA GATES 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dil Pickles is not the first baby whose resentful older sibling
wanted to return him to the hospital, but he's probably the only
one who has such an interesting trip back.
</P>
<P>
   A talking wagon named Reptar takes him down the street, through
the playground, into the back of a Night Mattress truck and into
the forest, which is pretty scary and, as his big brother, Tommy,
says, ``biggerer than the park and the backyard put together.''
Luckily the whole ``Rugrats'' gang is with him.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Dil (full name: Dylan Preston Pickles) is the newborn hero
of ``The Rugrats Movie,'' a film that had to happen. No popular
children's television series goes unmerchandized these days, and
``Rugrats'' is Nickelodeon's most popular. The pleasant surprise is
that the film is a delight.
</P>
<P>
   The stars of ``Rugrats'' are five talking babies: Tommy Pickles,
his cousin Chuckie Finster (a redhead who, despite his extreme
youth, wears eyeglasses just like his father's), the twins Lil and
Phil Deville, and the oldest child, Angelica Pickles, whose raison
d'etre seems to be misguiding the other babies.
</P>
<P>
   At Tommy's mother's baby shower, for instance, Angelica informs
Tommy that when the new baby arrives he'll be completely forgotten;
in fact he'll be turned into a dog and forced to sleep outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy's mother, Didi, goes into labor at the baby shower, and
everybody heads for the Lipshitz Maternity Hospital. This is the
sort of place where an expectant mother might choose to deliver in
the Tibetan Terrace Room.
</P>
<P>
   It also has a constantly changing Due/Arrived/Delayed chart just
like the ones in airports. Tommy tries to like the baby, Dil, when
he arrives, but the first thing Dil does is to grab and twist
Tommy's nose.
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks later, Dil has pretty much taken over the household.
So when Tommy's pals suggest that they take him back to ``the baby
store,'' Tommy doesn't put up much of a fight. ``You can't do that;
my mom and dad want to keep him,'' he says halfheartedly, and
before you know it the five babies are on the road, with Angelica
and her treasured doll Cynthia not far behind.
</P>
<P>
   The group's adventures in the woods include encounters with
wolves, a supposed wizard and a troupe of out-of-control Russian
circus monkeys who escaped while their owners were discussing
whether the coffee was better in St. Petersburg or Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the monkeys kidnap Dil. It all seems pretty
threatening, but at a recent preview screening the young audience
was laughing rather than cowering in fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rugrats Movie'' does throw in some material for the
grown-ups. There is a mention of gender stereotyping, a passing
reference to Pearl Harbor and a scene with some pathetic reporters
who turn up at the Pickles house when the children disappear,
getting everybody's name wrong and asking, ``Is it true a dingo ate
your baby?''
</P>
<P>
   There is even, seriously, a scene that re-creates Abraham's
near-sacrifice of his son, Isaac, to God.
</P>
<P>
   Just to keep up with the Joneses (i.e, Disney and Dreamworks),
``Rugrats'' has hired some big names as guest voices. Tim Curry,
for instance is Rex Pester, the most obnoxious of the reporters,
and ``This World Is Something New to Me,'' one of the film's
several musical numbers, is sung by a chorus of newborns, whose
voices include those of Laurie Anderson, Beck, Jakob Dylan and
Patti Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography includes an unusual group effort at the end
that Busby Berkeley probably never thought of. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE RUGRATS MOVIE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Norton Virgien and Igor Kovalyov; written by David
N. Weiss and J. David Stem, based on ``Rugrats,'' created by Arlene
Klasky, Gabor Csupo and Paul Germain, and on the original
characters, created by Ms. Klasky, Csupo and Peter Chung; edited by
John Bryant; score by Mark Mothersbaugh, with the song ``This World
Is Something New to Me'' by Mothersbaugh and performed by Laurie
Anderson, Beck, B Real, Jakob Dylan, Phife, Gordon Gano, Iggy Pop,
Lenny Kravitz, Lisa Loeb, Lou Rawls, Patti Smith, Dawn Robinson,
Fred Schneider, Kate Pierson and Cindy Wilson; produced by Ms.
Klasky and Csupo; released by Paramount Pictures. Running time: 90
minutes. This film is rated G.
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of: E.G. Daily (Tommy Pickles), Christine
Cavanaugh (Chuckie Finster), Kath Soucie (Philip Deville/Lillian
Deville), Cheryl Chase (Angelica Pickles), Tara Charendoff (Dylan
Pickles) and Tim Curry (Rex Pester). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1754EST &QL; 
