<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9775 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELEBRITY-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      11-19 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBRITY-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRANAGH'S ADAPTATION OF WOODY ALLEN NOT AS YOU'D LIKE IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Woody Allen has used the stammering comic delivery to
tease, tense and release laughs for decades. Kenneth Branagh, on
the other, you know, on the other, well, the other hand, should go
back to stammering school.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Celebrity,'' Branagh takes the Allen role on camera (while
Woody stays behind the camera, writing and directing). Branagh
tries to use Woody's trademark stammering delivery to milk the
anxiety jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he becomes the movie's major source of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Branagh single, well, all by him, you know, single-handedly
ruins what would otherwise be one of Woody's middle pictures, not
as deep and funny as ``Manhattan,'' ``Bullets Over Broadway'' or
even ``Deconstructing Harry,'' but more interesting than ``Husbands
and Wives,'' ``Crimes and Misdemeanors`` or ``Shadows and Fog.''
</P>
<P>
   Branagh plays Lee, a struggling magazine writer who covers
celebrities, an opportunity he uses to pantingly pursue movie stars
(Melanie Griffith), supersexed supermodels (Charlize Theron) and
actresses (Winona Ryder) who are even more neurotic than he is.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is free to chase these women, while also chasing a dream of
becoming a serious novelist, because he has just dumped his wife of
16 years, Robin (Judy Davis).
</P>
<P>
   Robin finds that the way to put your life back together when it
has been shattered is to become as shallow as everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   While searching for ways to rid themselves of guilt and
self-contempt, or at least find someone to go home with, Lee and
Robin wallow around the periphery of the famous, trying to get a
piece of it for themselves. This gives Allen a chance for satirical
takes on movie stars, writers and the clamor of celebrity itself.
</P>
<P>
   Allen seems to be saying that being rich and famous isn't all
champagne and caviar. Sometimes it's champagne and caviar and
beautiful women throwing themselves at you.
</P>
<P>
   Allen has dealt with the hardships of celebrity before, notably
in ``Stardust Memories,'' in which he depicts his fans as a
Frankensteinian mob after his head.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Celebrity,'' Allen lays off the fans for the most part and
concentrates on the way fame separates people into two classes:
those who have it and those who aren't going to get even their 15
minutes' worth.
</P>
<P>
   The humor has Woody's typically bitter edge, with the occasional
release of his witty observations about human foibles.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has been in enough Allen movies to handle the angst humor
adroitly. But Branagh drags it down with his annoying overanxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Allen should have taken the lead role, but he probably had
reservations about picturing himself pursuing a so-young Ryder on
screen.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's most fun is wondering which star will turn up in a
cameo next. Leonardo DiCaprio tops the list as a pampered movie
star who has a celebrity arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrity,'' filmed in black and white to no particular
advantage, is rated R for profanity and sex. 2 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1756EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9790 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      11-19 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REAR WINDOW': REVIVING A SNOOPER SLEUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(bl) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's be blunt about the average viewer's response to the very
idea of Christopher Reeve in a remake of ``Rear Window'': it sounds
like a cruel joke.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve has accumulated an immense amount of good will for his
strength and tenacity after a riding accident left him paralyzed
from the neck down three years ago. Still, it's one thing to watch
James Stewart, in the 1954 original, play a man in a wheelchair
with a broken leg who spies on his neighbors and thinks he spots a
murderer. It's another to imagine Reeve taking over a role he would
seem to be living rather than acting. How can anyone overlook that
difference?
</P>
<P>
   The surprisingly sensible answer is that the difference is not
ignored but placed front and center. This film is less about
remaking Hitchcock than about reinventing Reeve as an actor, and he
pulls the trick off with a true performance and a remarkable
display of his old movie-star presence.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being a tacky embarrassment, this ``Rear Window'' is
tasteful, engaging and extremely clever as it revamps the original,
tailoring it for Reeve.
</P>
<P>
   The story includes embedded messages about the lives of the
disabled; Reeve's character lives in a high-tech apartment, in
which everything is voice-activated, including the camera and
monitor that allows him to amuse himself by snooping into the
apartments next door.
</P>
<P>
   This version is not nearly as snappy as Hitchcock's, even with
slight plot changes to add surprise. But it is a slick enough
cat-and-mouse game to serve the purpose of giving Reeve a star
turn.
</P>
<P>
   And, intentionally or not, his presence in the film bolsters its
theme of voyeurism. In the movie, his character watches the
neighbors; in everyday life, we watch Reeve interviewed by Barbara
Walters. We are all voyeurs to some degree, and at its core ``Rear
Window'' is about the guilty satisfactions of invading someone
else's intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Where Stewart's character was a photographer, the Reeve
character is an architect named Jason Kemp. The film begins with
his dream of the car crash that left him a quadriplegic, unable to
breathe for long without the help of a vent delivering air. While
still in the hospital, his breathing tube falls out and he clicks
out a message for help with his teeth. Even then, Jason never seems
a victim or an object of pity, as Reeve and the character swiftly
blend together.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take long to get used to the scratchiness in Reeve's
voice. He smoothly registers emotions with his face and eyes as
well as dialogue. And the use of judicious close-ups and editing
create a dynamic sense of Jason as the most active player in this
drama.
</P>
<P>
   The script has its share of preachy lines. Like Reeve, Jason is
blessed with financial freedom, though the script has him dutifully
note about his new technological equipment, ``Do you have any idea
how expensive it is to be disabled in this country?'' Only when
Jason arrives home does the story become recognizable as ``Rear
Window.''
</P>
<P>
   From his window, he spies on an up-to-the-minute array of
neighbors: a gay couple; a workaholic man always at his computer; a
heavy-drinking blonde with a passing resemblance to Sharon Stone,
who fights constantly with her husband, a sculptor. When she
vanishes after a violent argument, Jason is convinced the police
should search for her corpse.
</P>
<P>
   As in Hitchcock, point of view controls the suspense here. As
the murder plot comes to involve e-mail, cell phones and even
sabotage on Jason's air supply, we know only as much as he does.
Yet throughout, the quiet moments are equally involving, with his
face registering loneliness and longing as he observes the ordinary
lives of others.
</P>
<P>
   So much attention has been lavished on Reeve's role that the
others are not nearly as well drawn or cast. In the Grace Kelly
part, Daryl Hannah plays Claudia, this time an architect called in
to help Jason finish a project. She shares his voyeuristic
amusement and ultimately his belief that a murder has taken place.
</P>
<P>
   But when Jason's health-care aide, Antonio (Ruben
Santiago-Hudson), says of Claudia, ``She likes you, the way a woman
likes a man,'' he might as well be explaining to the surprised
audience as well as to Jason. The problem is not Reeve's
disabilities. Jason is attractive, he's charming, he's Christopher
Reeve, after all. But Ms. Hannah's cold-fish performance gives
little hint of the attraction built into the script, and resolved
with a too-easy storybook ending. Her stiffness is miles away from
Kelly's cool surface and simmering sexuality. And while Antonio is
pleasant enough, he's no substitute for Thelma Ritter's acerbic
nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Before his accident, Reeve was beginning to reinvent himself as
an actor who could go beyond ``Superman,'' notably as a congressman
in ``The Remains of the Day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rear Window'' is another reinvention of the actor, in a role
that carries a subtle message. Our initial fears that the film
would be a tasteless joke reflect just the sort of preconceptions
he is doing so much to dispel.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `REAR WINDOW'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Sunday on channel 7.
</P>
<P>
   Teleplay by Eric Overmyer and Larry Gross and based on the story
by Cornell Woolrich. Jeff Bleckner, director; Ken Kelsch, director
of photography; Stephen Hendrickson, production designer; Randall
Richards, art director; music by David Shire; Sharon Abend and
Robert V. Gaulin, producers; Jonathon Starch, co-producer. A
Hallmark Entertainment production. Christopher Reeve, Steven Haft,
Robert Halmi Jr. and David V. Picker, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   With: Christopher Reeve (Jason Kemp), Daryl Hannah (Claudia
Henderson), Robert Forster (Detective Moore), Ruben Santiago-Hudson
(Antonio), Anne Twomey (Leila), John Rothman (Porter), Kevin
O'Rourke (Mason), Richie Coster (Julian Thorpe), Allison Mackie
(Ilene Thorpe), Ali Marsh (Allison Flowers) and David Wohl (Dr.
Schneider).
</P>
</TEXT>
