<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBERTY-ISLAND-INDIAN     11-19 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERTY-ISLAND-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., N.J.)  
 MEMBER OF MOHEGAN TRIBE SUES U.S., CLAIMING LIBERTY ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years, Timothy J. Stoddard has tried to be
noticed in his campaign for American Indian rights. A member of the
Mohegan tribe, he and other American Indians sought to celebrate
tribal prayer and water ceremonies last year on Liberty Island,
home to the Statue of Liberty, but federal authorities prevented
the news media from filming the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Stoddard sought revenge of a legal sort. He filed
suit in U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York,
alleging that Liberty Island was originally owned by Mohegans and
other Northeastern tribes like the Manhattans and was never
properly sold to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of one of those tribes, Stoddard is laying claim to
Liberty Island, or at least seeking a ``third party,'' like the
International Court of Justice at The Hague, Netherlands, to decide
who really owns the land. If he wins, he will seek some of the
tourist revenue from the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Stoddard, 35, a computer network engineer from Slingerlands,
N.Y., a suburb of Albany, says he is three-eighths Mohegan on his
father's side. Bruce Clark, a lawyer, drafted the complaint, but
Stoddard said he would represent himself. Stoddard said in his
complaint that any land that has not been properly transferred, by
deed or treaty, remains Indian land. ``We want to be seen as a
sovereign nation whose land was usurped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Liebman, 57, a Columbia University professor of property
law, called Stoddard's suit ``the latest in a long series of
disputes as the United States continues to wrestle with claims that
go back to the original occupation of the continent.'' It is
similar to suits filed in China, India, Australia and Canada, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The view in all these cases is that the rights of native
peoples were never properly paid for,'' Liebman said.
</P>
<P>
   But American law, which has granted land to American Indians in
certain cases, is far more complicated than that, Liebman said. It
is true that the law says title to land must be properly
``extinguished,'' or resolved, but that can include war or a
declaration by Congress, he said. Also, Stoddard has to prove that
the Mohegans owned Liberty Island and that he is a Mohegan. ``Was
that group really there, and can he show continuous descent?''
Liebman said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest hurdle, Liebman said, is that courts have
consistently ruled that domestic land disputes are to be settled in
American courts, not international ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1814EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      11-19 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: RON HOWARD COMEDY; `BABE' SEQUEL; SCIENCE
NOSTALGIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back to Comedy
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ In one scene in Ron Howard's upcoming movie,
``edTV,'' a loutish character played by Woody Harrelson stands in
front of a television camera and delightedly discloses that his
sister is dating a man who plays the piano so badly that during a
gig at a bar his head was cracked open by someone throwing the tip
glass. How funny that the couple met in a bar, he blabbers, because
his sister is an alcoholic. Hah-hah!
</P>
<P>
   ``EdTV'' is about a family made famous when it agrees to have
its life broadcast 24 hours a day, and Ron Howard wants us to
understand that celebrity does strange things to people.
</P>
<P>
   It has been nine years since Howard, the director and producer,
created a comedy. His last comic effort was ``Parenthood,''
followed by dramas like ``Apollo 13'' and ``Ransom.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's back with ``edTV,'' which stars Matthew McConaughey,
Harrelson, Jenna Elfman and Martin Landau, all part of or friends
of the family, with the focus on one of the sons, Ed, who makes
himself a television fixture. Unlike the character in ``The Truman
Show,'' these slightly dysfunctional people invite the camera to
observe, until their lives spin out of control. The film, produced
by Howard's partner, Brian Grazer, is scheduled to open next spring
and carries a new, somewhat personal edge for Howard.
</P>
<P>
   The film is not just a comedy; it has a serious point to make
about how celebrity can twist people, an apt sentiment for a man
who says he suffered under his early celebrity as a child actor and
who has struggled to build himself a world of normalcy ever since.
Howard lives in Westchester County in New York, not Los Angeles,
and he said his four children go to public schools there.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said he had been looking for a way of getting back into
comedy; he called ``edTV'' ``thoroughly unpretentious
entertainment.'' Yet, he added, it offers an object lesson for a
country obsessed with the idea that celebrity solves rather than
creates problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I can relate to,'' Howard said. ``It's about
the notion of volunteering to become a celebrity and how you can
get caught up with it. But it was a way to deal with these issues
without copping to a poor-me attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, the normally controlled and somewhat
cerebral Howard suddenly spoke loudly, above the din of a
restaurant here, to imitate the way football players at the
University of Southern California, which he attended for a few
years, used to shout and call him ``Opie,'' the character he played
on television years ago. The memories clearly stung.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't exactly a happy kind of thing to face, but in this
movie I didn't want to do a story that was just bleak and awful,''
Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's not really about the media, although it does
use the power of television. It's about grabbing at the shortcut,
about what people think that will do, and what it really does.''
</P>
<P>
   Pig at a Snail's Pace
</P>
<P>
   Few films in recent years have charmed audiences with such
seeming effortlessness as ``Babe,'' a $30 million movie about a pig
that thinks it's a sheepdog. The seductive little hero won hearts,
awards and a huge box office gross with what seemed like the
simplest of techniques. What an easy film to follow up with a
sequel, one would think.
</P>
<P>
   One would have to think again. George Miller is the producer,
director and screenwriter of ``Babe: Pig in the City,'' and in an
interview this week he sounded zombielike after a string of what he
said had been 20-hour days, desperately scrambling to complete the
picture for its Nov. 25 release.
</P>
<P>
   More than double the amount of money was spent on the sequel as
on the original. It has many more lavish special effects, and it
has been anything but effortless, Miller said. The post-production
_ the process of editing, adding titles and combining the dialogue,
music and sound _ has been difficult, expensive and more
time-consuming than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a charity screening event had to be canceled at the last
minute because the movie was not ready, and there was even a
last-minute scramble to change some scenes so the film would get a
``G'' rating rather than ``PG.''
</P>
<P>
   The film was shot in Miller's home, Australia; it takes the
little pig on a journey of healing into the heart of the heartless
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an incredibly complicated movie because of all
the animals,'' Miller said. The production notes say that 799
animals were involved, from dogs and mice to, of course, pigs.
Miller explained that most had to be shot individually, and then
combined in the editing room to create the illusion that they were
talking to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the biggest problems involved the soundtrack. Early
last week, he said, the production team discovered that the sound
was grating on the ears, and that they would have to remix and
redub the entire thing. That is what forced the cancellation of the
advance screenings, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I realized how bad it was I thought the sound would
completely undo us,'' Miller said. He added that round-the-clock
efforts by a team of experts resolved the problems, but left
everyone exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a sensible way to make a movie,'' he said, adding
that he broke a front tooth several weeks ago and still has not had
time to get it repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Science Throwback
</P>
<P>
   Science has become one of the more frightening characters in
movies. Science fiction has become equated with malevolent forces;
at the least, science in film usually involves the creation of
technologies that have a funny way of falling into the wrong hands
and threatening civilized society, if not a neighborhood or two.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Johnston, who directed ``Jumanji'' and ``Honey, I Shrunk the
Kids,'' and created special effects for several Star Wars films,
introduces a radical vision of science in his upcoming movie,
``October Sky.'' The movie is a decided throwback, in that it is
based on the premise that science is about fulfilling dreams.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, which is based on a true story, the character Homer
Hickam, a boy living in the rough and tumble mining town of
Coalwood, W. Va., in 1957, looks up into the October sky one night
and sees a streak of light that changes his life. It is the Soviet
sputnik satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The vision is tantalizing and makes Homer and three of his
friends believe that, by building their own model rocket, they just
might escape the mines and find a new life built on their
imaginations and mastery of science. Homer is played by Jake
Gyllenhaal and his father by Chris Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read the first draft of the script, I thought to
myself, `This is probably not a film for L.A., or New York, or
parts of Chicago,''' Johnston said. ``It's not very hip. It borders
on corny at times. I did this as a conscious decision to be a
little old-fashioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Johnston, 48, said ``October Sky,'' which is scheduled
to run next spring, was an effort to ``overcome'' his background in
expensive, special effects-laden movies, about which he harbors
mixed feelings.
</P>
<P>
   He said that when he first saw the script, he had been working
on another expensive science fiction movie, but dropped it in an
instant to make ``October Sky,'' which is also about a boy's desire
to find a way of connecting with a distant father. The movie cost
$23 million, about a third the cost of ``Jumanji,'' which used some
of the most complex special effects ever created for film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped this would open up another avenue for me,'' said
Johnston, who said he took a big cut in his usual fee to direct the
film. ``I'd kind of been looking to do this for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
