<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9830 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-     11-19 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL ABOUT MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First it was Roger. Then Mo. Now Bob.
</P>
<P>
   Two are players. One is an owner. But their stories are the
same. In the end, their stories are all about money. The bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens left to make a financial score in Toronto and
blamed Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn is on the way out the door for more money and uses the
same exit strategy: Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kraft, who obviously has forgotten those nightmares he used
to have about the Boston Braves leaving town, has his New England
Patriots heading down the Mass. Pike to Hartford. He has the
perfect foil to blame for it: House Speaker Tom Finneran. If
politicians ever wonder why the public has so little regard for
them, all they have to do is listen to what Finneran has to say. To
label him the ``Speaker'' is to demean the term.
</P>
<P>
   I have the same beef with Kraft that I do with Clemens and
Vaughn. None is man enough to speak the truth on the way out the
door: ``I am doing this for money.''
</P>
<P>
   I watched Kraft's press conference in Hartford Thursday on
television and winced when he said he would have had to sell the
team if he had to continue to play in Foxboro Stadium under the
present conditions.
</P>
<P>
   That's a crock.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that Bob Kraft is taking his team to Hartford to
make more money than he could ever make in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   However, don't think for a moment that he wasn't doing well in
Foxborough. Here he had a home run with his investment. Hartford _
unless the deal falls apart, and I still give that a chance _ will
be a grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Said one NFL owner Thursday, ``He bought the team for $160
(million). When he opens in Hartford, it's worth $500 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft and his sons know how to make money. Within two years of
taking over the Patriots, they moved the franchise from near the
bottom of the NFL in gross revenues into the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Through their tough business acumen, they tripled local radio
and television rights to more than $6 million a year. And there's
no telling for sure how they did selling stadium advertising,
scoreboard rights, etc.
</P>
<P>
   When Kraft came into the league four years ago, the television
revenue from national networks averaged $38 million a year. In this
new deal, which has seven more years to run, it will average $70
million.
</P>
<P>
   Since he purchased the team, interest rates have dropped
dramatically, making it easier for him to make his payments.
</P>
<P>
   He will take in $17 million as his share from the expansion
Cleveland Browns. He will get just as much from the next expansion
team in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   No. Owning the Patriots has not been a hardship. We haven't even
mentioned that the government allowed him to write off more than 50
percent of his purchase fee, tax-free, over five years. That's at
least $15 million a year he doesn't pay taxes on. The government
also allows him to amortize the player contracts.
</P>
<P>
   No. Bob Kraft hasn't been mistreated in Foxborough. During his
ownership, the fans have responded by purchasing every available
seat for every game, a fact the team likes to announce proudly in
almost every publicity release. And local businesses have supported
him fully by giving him top dollar for radio, TV, and stadium
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft likes to say he cannot compete in Foxborough because of
all of the new stadiums being built in other cities for his
competitors. He creates the illusion that by having more money, you
have a better team.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Vikings have taken in less money than any other
team in the league. Look at their record.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Redskins, in their new stadium, take in the most
money. Look at their record.
</P>
<P>
   Every year Kraft has been in Foxborough, that stadium has
produced more revenue than Green Bay's Lambeau Field. Who has had
the better team over the past four years? Packers or Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   Each team in the league takes in roughly $58 million from
television this year, and the salary cap is in the area of $53
million.
</P>
<P>
   The salary cap is the same for every team in the league. So is
the TV money. The difference is in how much money they can generate
beyond the regular gate receipts. And this is where Karft's
fortunes will take a big upswing in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has 45 luxury boxes and no preferred seating in
Foxborough. In Hartford, he will have at least 100 luxury boxes and
better than 6,000 preferred seats. Kraft does not have to share the
money from the luxury boxes with the players. NFL players are
entitled to 64 percent of the revenues, excepting that taken in
from special seating.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the greatest difference will come between the
Foxborough and Hartford stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important difference lies in who is responsible.
Here Kraft would have to write the check to pay for the stadium. It
wouldn't have been his money, as his supporters like to say. The
money to pay for ``his'' Foxborough stadium would have come from
selling personal seat licenses for the most part.
</P>
<P>
   In Hartford, the state of Connecticut is on the hook. It writes
the check. There will be no personal seat licenses. Kraft keeps 90
percent of the revenues, if what we read and hear at this point is
to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft is doing what 99.9 percent of all businessmen in this
country would do. He is taking the better deal. Just like Roger.
Just like Mo.
</P>
<P>
   He could have stayed, just as they could have stayed. The issue
was for how much, and they went for more.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the state of Rhode Island thought it had a deal with
Kraft. At noon one Monday, the governor's press aides alerted the
local media that he would have a press conference at 6 p.m. to
announce an agreement in principle, or a letter of understanding,
whichever you want to call it, with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   When the time came, the embarrassed governor had to meet the
press to tell them there was no deal. The story is that Kraft tried
to up the ante at the last minute, and the state walked away.
</P>
<P>
   Until this is all signed and there is no way out in Connecticut,
do not consider it a deal.
</P>
<P>
   If they do make it, imagine how embarrassed the other owners
will be when the time arrives to vote on the move _ taking a team
out of the Boston area, where every seat has been sold for five
years, the team generated some of the highest revenues in the
league from its stadium, and it is still allowed to leave for one
reason, and one reason only.
</P>
<P>
   To make more money.
</P>
<P>
   (ill McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
