<HEADLINE>
AROUND FOXBOROUGH, SOBER REALIZATION SETS IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It was a dark, dank day, reflecting the mood
of those who walked around the tired-looking stadium with a blank
stare as if they'd just lost something precious.
</P>
<P>
   As the television blared in the makeshift press room that
doubles as a super suite on game days at Foxboro Stadium, a crowd
of media types hovered to watch a press conference from Hartford,
where Connecticut Governor John G. Rowland and Patriots owner
Robert Kraft were pictured arm in arm ready to enter into a 30-year
agreement for a 68,000-seat open-air stadium in downtown Hartford
that would house New England's NFL team starting in 2001, pending
legislative approval and a three-quarters vote of National Football
League owners.
</P>
<P>
   The mood there appeared joyous and celebratory, but here there
was a feeling that something familiar was ending. An era was over.
</P>
<P>
   Done.
</P>
<P>
   Dead.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the media people wondered whether their outlets would
give the Patriots the same coverage in Hartford that they'd
received in Foxborough, and most concluded that coverage in this
part of New England would be reduced dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots coach Pete Carroll seemed uneasy addressing the subject
of moving. After all, his team has enough problems, owning a 5-5
record and having lost four of its last five games; now comes this
major distraction. By 2001, Carroll would be in the final year of
his contract, but he couldn't feel comfortable about being around
that long if the team continues to slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to Bob last night, and he told me there might be an
announcement today concerning a move,'' said Carroll. ``He hoped it
wouldn't disrupt the team and the preparation for (Monday's game
against the Dolphins at Foxboro Stadium), but I think this was
motivated by the situation down there and a decision had to be made
at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   It all felt so strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived in the same house in Walpole for 28 years, and my
wife has already said we're not moving to Hartford,'' said a
security guard outside the gated area at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Of the more than 100 stadium employees, many hold positions that
augment incomes of spouses with full-time careers. For them, job
security is scheduled to last until 2001, when they, too, would bid
the stadium and the Patriots farewell.
</P>
<P>
   Those who would move with the team, such as director of football
operations Ken Deininger, would have to transplant their families
to the Hartford area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at this as a positive move,'' said Deininger.
``Kids tend to adapt quickest. They'll be adapting to new schools
and making new friends, but what I've told my kids is that there is
baseball and basketball and football and soccer and religion class
in Connecticut as well. As a family, you hope you can afford more
than what you have when you move. You don't want to move backwards,
so I hope to upgrade with the move.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots vice president of player development and community
affairs Don Lowery said he hasn't talked to many employees, but
``if this deal wasn't struck, the franchise would have been sold
and moved. I would think people are pretty happy that we kept it in
New England. We've had people who have been going through this for
10-12 years who are probably relieved about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Deininger will have to engineer the Patriots' move three years
from now. In the meantime, the Patriots also must decide about
their training facility for the short term. For several years, they
have trained at Bryant College in Smithfield, R.I., but the lease
ran out last summer. They can return to Bryant if they so choose,
and in the weeks ahead, that decision will be made while the
Patriots seek to design a new training facility in the Greater
Hartford area.
</P>
<P>
   The players appeared a little confused. Many may not be around
in 2001. Many don't live in New England year round, anyway, so
playing in Hartford would be no different from playing in
Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Tebucky Jones would be going home, having grown up in New
Britain, Conn., but he groused about having to provide more tickets
for family and friends. Ed Ellis, an offensive lineman of the
future who hails from Hartford, was pleased about the prospect of
relocating.
</P>
<P>
   But for most, the issue was peripheral.
</P>
<P>
   Punter Tom Tupa kidded, ``At the end of the year, if an owner
out there needs to have their team moved, call me.'' Tupa once
played with another team that moved _ the Cleveland Browns (now the
Baltimore Ravens).
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe, who knew the move was inevitable, chimed in,
``Anybody want to buy a house?'' Bledsoe and his wife, Maura, are
building a huge home in Medfield. ``There's still time to pick out
the carpet,'' he said. ``I guess we'll live in it for a couple of
years and then sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he'd never been to Hartford. Carroll said he might
have passed through there before. But for most, there was a bigger
issue _ Monday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had better not be a distraction,'' said Bledsoe. ``We have
to play so well to win Monday night that this can't be a
distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt ``mad.'' Not about the move, but about the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are pretty mad right now,'' said Bledsoe. ``To have the
kind of talent we have and be 5-5 ... it makes people angry.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was willing to predict what the crowd would be like
Monday night. Carroll alluded to the possibility that some fans
might express their displeasure with the move by taking it out on
the team. He asked for the fans' full support against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely emotional area of the country,'' he said.
``There might be something like that going on. There'll be some
reaction to it, but I hope people continue to support us.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Patriots don't want is for their home games to become
tantamount to road games, but Lowery said he expected support to
continue for the final two-plus years in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fans all over New England now,'' he said. ``Based on
what we see when we're winning, we'll get support. The television
ratings show that they are terrifically supportive of the Patriots,
and the attendance figures show they're terrifically supportive of
the Patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery said season ticket-holders would receive a letter in the
mail today or tomorrow telling them they would have preference in
retaining their seats.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that 30-33 percent of the Patriots' 17,000 season
ticket plans are from Rhode Island or Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   How about the new fans in Hartford? Will they be accommodated?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have 8,000 more seats with the additional
luxury boxes (100 instead of 42),'' said Lowery. ``We feel with a
68,000-seat stadium, that should handle the excess we may have from
Hartford-area people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery said Kraft spoke to Governor Paul Cellucci Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob called Governor Cellucci . . . and told him this was going
to happen,'' he said. ``The governor was remorseful but
understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots hope their fans will be in the same mood this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
