A9853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-SAFETY-NYT &LR;      11-19 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO SAFETY: PENALIZING ADULTS FOR UNBUCKLED KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: also sent in category `f') 
(bl) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Transportation Department plans to announce a
rule in a few days that will require standard hardware in cars and
child seats to make the two fit together better, with the aim of
lowering the annual death toll of about 600 children under age 5.
</P>
<P>
   But seats not secured to the car is the smaller part of the
problem, safety experts say; a bigger one is children not secured
to the seat. About 60 percent of the children killed in car crashes
were not buckled in, although there was often a child seat in the
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new standard will help people who are already doing the
right thing to do it better,'' said Chuck Hurley, a spokesman for
the National Safety Council. ``It won't deal with the central issue
of what's killing kids.''
</P>
<P>
   What will? And what, for that matter, will deal with the issue
of getting adults to buckle themselves in? Widespread use of
conventional seat belts could save 10,000 lives a year, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   Police think they know what will work, and will be trying to do
their part this weekend. Nearly 5,000 law-enforcement agencies
around the country will conduct a seat-belt enforcement blitz.
First tried by 1,000 police departments around Memorial Day 1997,
and expanded to about 4,000 for Memorial Day this year, the tactic
has proved so successful that safety strategists have decided to
make the crackdown a twice-a-year event, including Thanksgiving
this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
just before and after Memorial Day this year, taken on streets and
highways around the country, found an increase in compliance with
seat-belt laws, to 65.1 percent from 62.2, which works out to 6
million people. In passenger cars, the rate jumped to 68.7 percent
from 65.6, and in pickups, vans and sport utility vehicles, to 60
percent from 56.
</P>
<P>
   If all these vehicle occupants stay buckled for a year, experts
say, the annual death toll of 41,000 or so will fall by about 700.
But this will probably require continued fear of getting a ticket.
``You can pass laws, but people have to know that they exist and
that they're going to be enforced,'' said Dr. Ricardo Martinez,
head of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Since all cars built since the '60s have safety belts, the
problem is attitude, not hardware. That turns out to be true for
baby seats, too, according to a recent survey of parents who
received tickets for having unbelted children.
</P>
<P>
   In California, which has relatively strict enforcement of laws
requiring child-safety seats, judges often order offending parents
to take a remedial education course on the importance of
child-safety seats, and from January to July of this year, the
instructors polled 745 of them. Ninety-five percent said they had a
seat, although most said they had left it at home or in another
family car. Almost 30 percent had child seats in their cars at the
time they received tickets for not putting their children in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of people who take better care of their
groceries than they do of their kids when they drive on the
highways,'' Martinez said. ``We have to do a better job of getting
these kids properly restrained and protected during the violence of
a crash.''
</P>
<P>
   A study of accidents in California from 1987 to 1996 found that
558 children under age 4 died in that period, and that all but 97
would probably have lived if they had been properly buckled. Very
few died if they had been correctly buckled.
</P>
<P>
   Compliance is highest for newborns and infants, and declines
year by year until about age 25, according to surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, a former emergency-room physician, quoted an old
saying in medicine: ``Good judgment comes from experience, and
experience comes from bad judgment.'' The problem, he said, was
that waiting for people to gain experience by not using seat belts
or baby seats was not a useful strategy. As a result, federal and
state officials plan a long campaign of enforcing laws requiring
adults to wear seat belts and children to be secured in child
seats.
</P>
<P>
   While a change in parents' behavior is necessary, the easier
part _ changing the rule on how the auto makers and seat
manufacturers build their products _ will come before Christmas,
Martinez said. The likely choice for the agency is a requirement
for car makers to install small bars near the spot where the seat
bottom and seat back come together; baby seats would latch into the
bars the way that removable seats in the back of a minivan attach
to the floor. Or the bars might have a strap attached to them that
looks like the male end of a seatbelt, only smaller; a female end
would be required on the seats.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the solution, baby seats would come with two attachment
systems for a transition period of several years.
</P>
<P>
   As for adjusting attitude, that will take a continuing effort,
especially where children are concerned. ``This has to be addressed
forever and ever and ever,'' said Stephanie Tombrello, the head of
Safety Belt Safe, a 19-year-old nonprofit organization in
California, ``because there's a new parent born every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
