Kathleen Willey aspect of Starr's case, and point to the
committee's interest in whether the administration or its allies
attempted to intimidate a witness. By Neil A. Lewis. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CLINTON (Tokyo) _ At a ``town meeting'' on his visit to
Japan, President Clinton is asked whether his wife and daughter
forgive him. By James Bennet. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-VOICES (Houston) _ Waiting for a bus in Denver, walking
along the sidewalk in Coral Gables, sipping a glass of wine at a
sidewalk cafe in Houston, sitting at home sick in Brooklyn, the
sentiment was pretty much the same: Enough already. The spectacle
of Kenneth Starr delivering his testimony, alternately bolstered by
Republicans and hectored by Democrats, did not seem to do much to
change the minds of the testimony-weary members of this particular
out-of-focus group. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 7:30 p.m. ET &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLIFFORD (Washington) _ It was one of those accidents of
timing: two events, coinciding by chance, each of which throws the
other into relief. At 10 a.m. on Capitol Hill, Republicans and
Democrats began hearings into possibly impeachable offenses by the
president. At almost the same moment at Washington National
Cathedral, a memorial service began for Clark M. Clifford, friend
and adviser to presidents in a more genteel day. By R.W. Apple Jr.
(1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-WHITEWATER (Washington) _ A look at what has become of
Whitewater and other subjects of Starr's inquiry. By Don Van Natta.
(1000 words)
