<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLKE-ART-REVIEW-630&AMP;     11-19 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLKE-ART-REVIEW-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGMAR POLKE: WHEN PRINTER'S MISTAKE IS PAINTER'S OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With so much postwar abstraction in New York just now
_ Pollock, Rothko, de Kooning drawings _ it's a good time to
consider some of the genre's contemporary masters. One is the
German painter Sigmar Polke, who has a show of two dozen strange,
beautiful, sort of abstract new paintings at Michael Werner
Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Polke, 57, is an of-the-moment master, one for whom the very
notion of mastery _ the virtuosic touch, the thrill of
self-expression _ seems to hold little intrinsic interest. His
painting is a post-epiphany, post-ego art, a hybrid thing, impure,
mixing in a wide range of ideas and formal ploys like so many
chemical additives. They preserve a tradition, and they also turn
it into something else.
</P>
<P>
   The very title of his show, ``Sigmar Polke: New Paintings,
Printing Mistakes,'' gets the feeling of what he's about. It sounds
both celebratory and debunking, formal but also abject.
</P>
<P>
   For years Polke has been collecting examples of printing errors
found in newspapers: the off-register photograph, the passage of
smudged or bleached-out type, the strand of hair on the press plate
that shows up as a streak on the page.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the paintings at Werner are based on such errors
magnified many times so they became images in themselves, their
original contexts unrecognizable. Some of the forms are amorphous
and abstract; others take on new identities, as in the painting
``Structural Poetry,'' where a rupture in a field of benday dots
looks like a devouring cancer or a burrowing animal.
</P>
<P>
   In a few cases, Polke manufactures his own accidents. The
elongated figures in ``From `Learning to Learn Anew''' are the
result of his having dragged a picture through a photocopier. And
in ``Break Domination,'' he introduces a literal gremlin in the
form of a bizarre composite creature _ part human, part beast, part
plant _ lifted from the margins of a medieval manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   This leering little grotesque _ a mistake of nature, you might
say _ evokes the spirit of the myth-enthralled Joseph Beuys, who
was once Polke's teacher. But it is also a metaphor for the
mongrel, endlessly layered, decidedly unmythic medium that painting
has become in Polke's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Everything in his inventive art feels reality-based, and nothing
is simple. For years he has painted on printed fabrics, the kind
used for curtains and tablecloths, putting images on images. Many
of the works in the current show are done on stretched white
polyester that turns transparent when moistened, so that whatever
is painted on one side shows through as a distant ghost on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally he creates a further impression of depth by adding,
in front of or behind the transparent ground, a sheet of openwork
fabric netting with a diamond-shaped pattern resembling the wire
mesh embedded for security purposes in thick panes of glass.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiguities of surface and depth are especially pronounced in
paintings that have been coated with countless layers of synthetic
lacquers. In ``Salamander Stone,'' for example, the painted forms _
big black hand-rendered dots and a glistening, sluglike organic
``mistake'' _ seem to float like holographic images in an illusory
three-dimensional space.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is an optical trick wrought through a careful recipe.
Pollock and Rothko, using more traditional means, did somewhat the
same thing: the former with overlapping skeins of paint, the other
with fields of color that, if looked at in the right way, seem to
palpitate with transcendental potential.
</P>
<P>
   But Polke is asking something different from painting, maybe
something that only a television-generation artist could want, or
even envision: an art object that offers transporting
possibilities, but that also carries real-world information.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This may explain why the banal and the visionary enjoy a happy
marriage in Polke's work. His colors are prosaic. Some are pretty,
others gross; most, doused in lacquer or resin, are just neutral. A
few paintings are executed on a photo-refractive fabric that turns
ambient light into a prismatic sheen, a magically tawdry effect.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many of the images in the paintings, the
glorified glitches that have been hand painted, reworked, built up
and fussed over, have a surprising metaphoric weight.
</P>
<P>
   The brainlike bulge that swells from the surface of ``Elementary
Building Material'' seems to be packed with molecular forms and
hidden meanings; a tabletop still life of a bottle and glasses in
an untitled piece appears to atomize into a field of tiny rosebuds,
which are actually the pattern of an underlying fabric.
</P>
<P>
   A painting like this comes from a culture of fragments, of
ruins, of things coming apart, as the art of Pollock, Rothko and de
Kooning does not. Their paintings were part of a still-romantic
moment when abstraction was an intact, horizonless frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Polke's work _ not romantic (not even a little bit),
conceptually grounded in defect, heterogeneous, intellectually
probing _ is something else and very much of its time.
</P>
<P>
   It will be fascinating to see where he continues to take all
this. But there is no question about his secure, maverick place in
an exalted 20th-century lineage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sigmar Polke: New Paintings, Printing Mistakes'' remains at
Michael Werner Gallery, 21 E. 67th St., New York, through Jan. 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
