<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS: WEEK 12 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY 1 P.M.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (7-3) vs. Minnesota (9-1)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Minnesota won the first meeting, 37-24, back in October
in a Monday night game where Green Bay was flattened on the ground
by back Robert Smith and punished in the air by quarterback Randall
Cunningham's 442-yard passing game. This time look for Packers
receiver Antonio Freeman and Vikings receiver Cris Carter to steal
the show. Both make big plays on third-downs and both will duel in
another high-scoring affair where the defenses will be reeling.
Look for Green Bay to gain retribution. Look for Favre-to-Freeman
to break the game open. This is only the second time these teams
will meet this season. Breaking even here, Green Bay sets the stage
for a nasty third meeting, a final war between the teams during the
NFC playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Packers, 34-28.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY 1 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (5-5) vs. Washington (2-8)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Arizona toppled Washington, 29-27, earlier this month
with Joe Nedney converting a 47-yard field goal with 2 seconds
remaining. That victory helped keep the Cardinals alive in the
playoff chase. Washington was out of the hunt a long time ago but
showed life last week by whipping the sorry Eagles, 28-3. Arizona
limited Washington to 89 rushing yards the last time and if it can
duplicate that it will be on its way to victory. So much, too,
rides on Cardinals' quarterback Jake Plummer. In two starts vs.
Washington he has passed for 523 yards, five touchdowns and two
interceptions. He will keep it going.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Cardinals, 24-21.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (3-7) vs. Atlanta (8-2)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: The Bears and Falcons have not met since 1993. What a
welcome sight they will be for the Falcons. After gaining
tremendous confidence by beating the 49ers last week, Atlanta is
ready to roll. If already has its best start in club history. It
has won 13 of its last 16. It can win its eighth straight at home,
a club record. It has scored 284 points (third-most in the NFC) and
has the best rushing defense in the conference. Jamal Anderson (10
rushing touchdowns) is ripping defenses. Chris Chandler at
quarterback is steady and sometimes super. The defense keeps
flowing to the football. Need more reasons for an Atlanta victory?
</P>
<P>
   Score: Falcons, 30-10.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit (3-7) vs. Tampa Bay (4-6)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: The season has sunk for the Buccaneers, who had such
high hopes and grand plans but have seen inconsistency on offense
result in a crash. It is not over for the Bucs, but it is getting
close. They were hammered by Detroit, 27-6, earlier in the season.
But the Bucs will make one last run for the playoffs by winning
this one with defense and by showing a bit of offensive spark led
by back Warrick Dunn. Tampa Bay is 4-1 in its new Raymond James
Stadium and plays three of its next four games there. That helps
the Bucs cause in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Buccaneers, 21-13.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis (2-8) vs. Buffalo (6-4)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Peyton Manning has thrown a touchdown pass in seven
straight games. He has passed for 2,289 yards. He has taken every
Colts snap (642 plays). And he was sharp in the end in beating the
Jets on last Sunday. But Buffalo counters with quarterback Doug
Flutie, who is 13-6 as an NFL starter and in nine home games during
his career has never lost. Flutie looks at home. He is at home.
Great news for the Bills. Antowain Smith (3.7 average yards gained
per carry) can help Flutie and his team with a breakout game. Look
for Thurman Thomas, too, to shine (4,264 receiving yards). With 38
additional receiving yards he passes Jerry Butler for third most in
club history.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Bills, 28-17.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (8-2) vs. Pittsburgh (6-4)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Here go the Jaguars and Steelers again in another close
game with big hits and big plays and momentum swinging moments that
punctuate the game. That's what happens when these teams meet. The
last one ended in a Pittsburgh overtime victory. The last six
meetings have all been won by the home team. Pittsburgh has endured
a deflating Jekyll-Hyde year. They win a big game. They lose a big
game. They win on the road. They lose at home. Consistency has been
hard to maintain, but Pittsburgh gives it another shot with an
emotional defensive display and with hard Jerome Bettis running.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Steelers, 17-16.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (5-5) vs. Dallas (7-3)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Seattle is more talented than Dallas. Seattle is more
talented than several teams. Why the .500 record? Poor play. Poor
leadership. Poor production. This game may swing things Seattle's
way. Look for back Ricky Watters to break loose. Expect receiver
Joey Galloway to streak into the end zone. And watch for Michael
Sinclair (11 sacks) to apply pressure on Dallas quarterback Troy
Aikman. This victory could swing Seattle into gear for a strong
playoff push as the season concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Seahawks, 26-20.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia (2-8) vs. Giants (3-7)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Can either of these teams get the football into the end
zone? It could be brutal to watch. The Giants are more physical and
are at home, so that helps their cause. They should easily handle
the Eagles, especially if they pounce on them early, because
Philadelphia is a team full of doubt. Too, the Eagles are minus-12
in turnover differential. They will cough it up. The Giants will
scoop it. All day long.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Giants, 27-6.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY 4 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs (4-6) vs. San Diego (4-6)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: The bottom has fallen out for Kansas City, and it is
not pretty. Linebacker Derrick Thomas will not play due to
suspension for personal foul penalties vs. Denver. It is a game
where the Chiefs attempt to regain respect for being a class group
of players rather than thugs _ that is the way many fans, unfairly,
think of them now. On the field, the chief problem has been the
offense. It doesn't produce points. The receivers don't make deep
plays downfield. Kimble Anders is a fullback. He leads the Chiefs
in receptions. This is a problem. San Diego has had its share,
especially with rookie quarterback Ryan Leaf succumbing to
pressure. Kansas City needs this victory after five straight
losses. It gets it.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Chiefs, 19-13.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (1-9) vs. St. Louis (3-7)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Must we watch? Can we bear it? The Panthers and Rams
might just punt all day long. Or maybe they will fumble it all
afternoon. Or maybe they will drop it or kick it or just lose it.
Who knows. Does anyone care? Sure, their fans do. Steve Beuerlein
leads the league with a 63.7 completion percentage. He is a leader
among the Panthers. Unfortunately for them, there is not enough
talent or winners to lead.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Rams, 24-9.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore (3-7) vs. Cincinnati
</P>
<P>
   Comment: What a horrible year for both clubs. Both were expected
to be in their divisional chase. Both have become mired in bad
play. The Bengals win because they are playing this game at home.
They win it with Paul Justin in at quarterback, and he provides an
instant lift. It will be another tough game for Ted Marchibroda,
the Ravens' head coach, whose days in Baltimore are now numbered.
Watch Ravens' cornerback Rod Woodson. He has seven career
interceptions versus Cincinnati, the most he has gained against any
team.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Bengals, 23-17.
</P>
<P>
   Jets (6-4) vs. Tennessee (6-4)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Tennessee has won five of its last six, and in that
stretch quarterback Steve McNair has passed for 1,195 yards with
six touchdowns and three interceptions. Houston is a hot team.
McNair is a hot quarterback. The Jets are sorrowful after beating
Buffalo and then losing to Indianapolis. Opportunity wasted. The
Jets will blitz McNair and attempt to confuse him with a variety of
pass coverages. But look for McNair to find tight end Frank Wycheck
when it counts and for back Eddie George to keep the Jets' run
defense on edge. Two teams with intriguing schemes results in an
intriguing matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Oilers, 21-20.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders (7-3) vs. Denver (10-0)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Boy, the Raiders would love to upset Denver. They would
love to see Denver squirm. They would be thrilled to put an end to
this thought about Denver achieving a perfect 16-0 regular season.
It would be such a nice thing for Raiders head coach Jon Gruden. Al
Davis, the Raiders owner, would fly home without a plane. The team
would be jacked, ready for a strong push into the playoffs. Raiders
fans would laugh. Broncos fans would cry. The Raiders would be the
talk of the league. They would be only two games behind Denver in
the AFC West with five games to go. Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Broncos, 36-10.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans (5-5) vs. San Francisco (7-3)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: The 49ers are suffering an identity crisis after
dropping two big games in recent weeks, Green Bay first and then
Atlanta next. Who are we? Are we kings anymore? This is the 49ers'
psyche. Well, here comes a welcome face _ the Saints. They will
soothe the 49ers' egos. Quarterback Kerry Collins gives the Saints
a better chance versus the 49ers, but he will not be enough to end
San Francisco's spell over New Orleans. Steve Young will outplay
him and, for a change, the 49ers defense will soar.
</P>
<P>
   Score: 49ers, 30-14.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Miami (7-3) vs. New England (5-5)
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Welcome to lovely Hartford, Conn., for this showdown
between two ... uh, that's in 2001. Yes, the Patriots are moving to
Hartford, but this one will be played in Foxboro, Mass., at Foxboro
Stadium. The clock is ticking. Soon the Patriots will be gone. But
there is plenty of business to take care of first, including this
divisional battle with the Dolphins in front of the nation. The
Patriots fans will arrive and some, no doubt, will show their
displeasure with their team moving. But others will root and enjoy
as the Patriots get injured receiver Terry Glenn back and he
returns in a big way with big catches for long scores.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Patriots, 27-24.
</P>
</TEXT>
