<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOYOTA-DIVERSIFIES-AR     11-19 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYOTA-DIVERSIFIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME INVESTORS QUESTION TOYOTA'S EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ For years, investors have nagged Toyota Motor Corp. to
put its huge pile of cash _ some $20 billion at last count _ to
work.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the company has taken a hammer to its piggy bank,
those same investors are questioning the way some of the money is
being spent.
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, Toyota raised its stake in Chiyoda Fire and
Marine Insurance Co., increased its holdings in a brokerage firm,
Kokusai Securities, and bought control of a longtime affiliate,
Daihatsu Motor Co., a small-vehicle manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   It spent more than $450 million in the process, almost 10
percent of its estimated operating profits for the fiscal year that
ends in March, and it may spend more if it takes part in a bailout
of the troubled Sakura Bank, which it says is under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The company has justified past investments in software and
telecommunications as keys to its future as it develops alternative
engines, ``smart cars'' and the infrastructure to support them. And
indeed, roughly two-thirds of Toyota's investments are clearly
auto-related.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been some notable gaffes outside the automotive
business, in prefabricated housing and in a long-distance telephone
company. Toyota has given only the broadest description of the
plans for its latest investments, leaving some investors to
question the company's motives.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom is that Toyota hopes to create a
financial-services empire a la General Motors Acceptance Corp., the
arm of GM that extends well past financing car purchases, or
General Electric's profitable powerhouse, GE Capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear that Toyota is buying a stake in an insurance
company or a mobile-telephone operator, it sounds astounding,''
Iwao Okijima, executive vice president in charge of financial
matters, said in a recent interview. ``But please understand that
the majority of Toyota's investments are in car-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toyota is now expanding its auto-financing business all over
the world. Please regard it as part of our auto business from now
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company's plans for a financial-services business
seem to lack a road map. How does a securities firm like Kokusai,
in which Toyota has a 10 percent stake, fit in? What is the
potential in Chiyoda? What does a commercial bank have to do with
the auto business? How do they all fit together and complement the
auto business?
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy is difficult to understand at the moment,'' said
Takaki Nakanishi, an auto analyst with Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. in
Tokyo. ``It could be a great opportunity, but what we need is a
specific strategy, presented in terms of how much they will spend
and where they are headed with it.''
</P>
<P>
   This confusion over Toyota's strategy has led some investors to
wonder whether there is another, perhaps unconscious, agenda behind
the company's interest in the financial-services business: using
its shareholders' money to support troubled related companies and
in the process preserving a system out of keeping with trends in
the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Many Japanese companies are clustered in loose alliances around
a bank or trading company. These groupings, called keiretsu, form a
symbiotic relationship based on mutual shareholdings, debts and
other obligations.
</P>
<P>
   The system is slowly coming unraveled as the financial crisis
here forces Japanese banks and companies to unload their mutual
shareholdings and turn to the global capital markets for financing.
But Toyota, with its pristine balance sheet, appears to be bucking
the trend.
</P>
<P>
   The company is already part of the keiretsu centered on the
trading giant Mitsui &AMP; Co. _ as are Chiyoda, Daihatsu, Sakura and
Hino Motors Ltd., a beleaguered truck manufacturer in which Toyota
is considering raising its stake.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mitsui group is slowly loosening the ties that bind
it, Toyota is increasing its relationships with certain group
companies and earning its nickname, Toyota Bank. The way some
investors see it, Toyota is using their money to prop up its ailing
corporate cousins.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Toyota's purchase in September of a majority
interest in Daihatsu, the feisty but financially pressed
small-vehicle manufacturer in which Toyota has long had a stake,
made good sense. It ensured that Daihatsu stayed out of reach of
competitors and offered benefits from shared costs of development,
procurement and design.
</P>
<P>
   But some have questioned the motive behind its additional
investment in Chiyoda, because investors know that a struggling
life insurer that is also a Mitsui affiliate desperately needed to
sell its Chiyoda shares and could not find a buyer until Toyota
stepped up to the plate. Its purchase bailed out the life insurer
and bolstered Chiyoda, but its benefits to Toyota remain to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of the cross-shareholding business,'' said Jay
Woodworth, an independent auto analyst. ``Toyota is putting equity
into its longstanding relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Okijima said. On the contrary, it's all part of the
transformation away from the very conservative company outlined by
Hiroshi Okuda _ the first top executive in decades who was not a
member of the company's founding Toyoda family. One of the
strategic goals Okuda announced when he became president in 1995
was to have ``alternative'' businesses account for as much as 10
percent of Toyota's sales by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Under Toyota's definition, many businesses seemingly unrelated
to auto manufacturing are, in fact, keys to its future. Take
software development and telecommunications, which it began
investing in more than a decade ago. Its engineers foresee a day
when a Toyota Corolla running on a fuel cell will virtually drive
itself using an on-board computer navigation system, mobile-phone
technology and satellites to guide it.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, the company has started using its ties to
Chiyoda to create insurance products that are used as sales
incentives. Analysts are particularly keen on the first joint
Toyota-Chiyoda product, incentive insurance for buyers of Toyota
cars that incorporate a new safety-enhancing body.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, what may seem like disparate investments are
central to Toyota's vision of the future, right down to a
helicopter service it says will be used to produce maps for
on-board navigational systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that in the future, through these businesses, we'll
assure the long-term success of Toyota Motor,'' Okijima said.
``These investments are not very large, and they're all related to
the future of Toyota.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But others have more trouble seeing the relationships. ``Our
great hope is that the companies we invest in stick to their core
competencies,'' said John Alkire, managing director at Morgan
Stanley Asset and Investment Trust, which owns Toyota shares. ``I
cannot see how Chiyoda and some of these other things fit into
their core competency, which is making cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Redl, an automotive analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter in Tokyo and longtime critic of Toyota's investments, has
even said he believes Toyota's real reason for buying the
helicopter company, Aero Asahi, was to further its plans to go into
the aircraft-engine business.
</P>
<P>
   He suspects that rather than digital map-making Toyota really
wants Aero Asahi's political expertise to help it win necessary
approval from the government.
</P>
<P>
   In several annual reports Toyota has expressed an interest in
pursuing aircraft-engine manufacturing, and it has been investing
in air-related businesses since 1988. That aspiration dismays
analysts who still remember Nissan Motor Co.'s ill-fated foray into
that business.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, some of Toyota's ventures outside the auto industry
have been discouraging, although none so costly as Nissan's
misstep. Toyota's sideline business of manufacturing prefabricated
housing, embarked on as a way to demonstrate the versatility of the
vaunted Toyota Production System, has been mostly in the red.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a string of losses, Toyota ended up investing about
$1.4 billion in Teleway, a long-distance telephone company, for
more than 10 years. Teleway and KDD, another long-distance
provider, are now merging in a deal that will leave Toyota with a
passive 8.4 percent in the new company _ whose short-term prospects
have also dimmed as competition has increased.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are urging Toyota to pull the plug on Nippon IDO, a
mobile-telephone provider that they say is unlikely to ever win
significant market share. ``They have failed to take a leadership
position in telecommunications, which was one of their goals,''
Nakanishi of Merrill Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   Now investors are worried that Chiyoda and, especially, Sakura
could become similar money pits for Toyota. The company's track
record for managing financial matters within its traditional line
of business is less than stellar, according to analysts, raising
questions about its ability to manage a far-flung
financial-services empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Toyota is a top-rate manufacturer, wringing costs out of
its production system and making excellent cars, the way it has
managed financial matters like hedging against currency
fluctuations and return on its balance-sheet assets have been less
successful,'' Woodworth said. ``On balance, this has cost Toyota a
fair amount of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps recognizing its own limitations, Toyota may be backing
away from raising its stake in Sakura, currently at 2.3 percent.
The government is shoring up weak banks with public money, and now
analysts expect Toyota to invest between 30 billion and 60 billion
yen in Sakura, down from the 100 billion to 150 billion yen
previously discussed. Okijima stressed that no decision had been
made yet.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, it is unclear why Toyota, with a mountain of cash,
a pristine balance sheet and ready access to the capita markets,
needs a bank. Okijima supplied a rationale. ``It might be true that
Toyota Motor Corporation enjoys strong surplus capital,'' he said.
``But when you think about the whole Toyota group, in auto
financing, suppliers, imports and dealers, on a consolidated basis,
we need access to a bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting the issue of Sakura aside, Toyota's financial-services
plans, however fuzzy, have a certain logic, considering General
Motors' success with GMAC _ and many of GMAC's activities fall far
afield of car manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be an interesting strategy for the company to use its
funds more efficiently,'' said Peter Boardman, an analyst at
Warburg Dillon Read in Tokyo, citing the potential for Toyota to
sell asset-backed securities and other financial instruments
related to its business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, how do they go ahead and do that?'' he asked.
``I think you could make an argument that that concern is why the
share price has come off lately. A lot of shareholders are nervous
about whether they're managing their cash wisely or efficiently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
