<SLUG> BC-PRIMARY-ROTATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORRIED STATE OFFICIALS SEEK ROTATING PRIMARY SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fearful of a truncated primary schedule that could
determine a presidential candidate within a couple weeks rather
than months, a group of state election officials recommended
Thursday switching to a rotating regional primary system.
</P>
<P>
   Different sections of the country would take turns being among
the first to vote for a party's nominee for president. New
Hampshire and Iowa would be exempt from the rotation, continuing to
kick off the presidential campaign season every four years,
according to the plan proposed by the Committee on Presidential
Primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Secretary of State William F. Galvin, the chairman
of the committee, said he would bring the recommendation to a full
meeting of the National Association of Secretaries of State in
February. But it will take approval by every state's legislature to
turn the idea into reality, and that would be a massive undertaking
unlikely to happen before 2004, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still very concerned about 2000,'' Galvin said. ``The
current (schedule) represents a national potential for a
catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Galvin and his colleagues said a compressed primary schedule
could make it difficult for anyone other than a front-runner with
name recognition and money to win the Democratic or Republican
nomination. It could also have the opposite result of elevating a
relatively unknown candidate before voters know enough about that
person, testified William Mayer, a political science professor from
Northeastern University.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, states around the country have continued to push
up their primary dates in the hopes of having the sort of influence
and attention that Iowa and New Hampshire enjoy. Recently, a group
of eight Western states moved to hold a joint, regional primary on
March 11 of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we in the West feel we haven't had any say in the
selection of a president,'' said Olene Walker, the lieutenant
governor from Utah who endorsed the rotating primaries. ``We have
been totally non-players.''
</P>
<P>
   While the secretaries of state seemed eager to make changes,
officials at the Democratic National Committee and the Republican
National Committee are not. Further, candidates for president in
2000 are proceeding on the assumption that the primaries will be
bunched close together, requiring them to raise massive amounts of
cash in order to compete in numerous states simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Grossman, chairman of the DNC, said voters may feel
empowered and energized if they believe their votes matter when
they all go to the polls at about the same time in March of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, nor do I think anybody knows one way or the
other what impact this will have,'' Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Yu, a spokesman for the Republicans, said the RNC leaves
scheduling up to the individual states. ``We have a philosophy of
empowering the states and the state parties to decide how and when
their primaries take place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican convention in 1996 decided to award bonus
delegates to states that agree to hold their primaries later in the
calendar year. However, Mayer said, that arrangement had failed to
solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, candidates who have declared and even those who have
not are working to raise money. Senator Paul Wellstone, the
Democrat from Minnesota, has raised $500,000 since he created his
presidential exploratory committee last April. Steve Forbes, the
Republican publisher, has pulled together $10 million from
individual donors for his nonprofit group, Americans for Hope,
Growth and Opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's shown he's the number one Republican fund-raiser in the
country right now,'' said Paul Young, a Forbes adviser in New
Hampshire. ``Every dollar's a vote, and number two, it's going to
take a lot of money with these crowded primary fields.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas D. Rath, an adviser to Republican Lamar Alexander, said
candidates must be prepared to raise between $15 million and $19
million during 1999 in order to compete in the primaries that come
after New Hampshire. That works out to about $35,000 to $40,000
that needs to be raised every business day for the next 10 to 12
months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't, you'll be blown out of the water,'' Rath said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
