<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HEARING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR DEFENDS LEWINSKY PROBE AT IMPEACHMENT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN and MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr defended his
probe of President Clinton Thursday, telling the House Judiciary
Committee's impeachment hearing that he didn't pass judgment on
Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky but instead has focused
on the coverup of their affair.
</P>
<P>
   By itself, the Clinton-Lewinsky sexual relationship was not a
``high crime or misdemeanor'' defined in the Constitution as
impeachable offenses, Starr said. Instead, he said, his report
urging the House to impeach Clinton is based on issues of
obstruction of justice, lying under oath and witness tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's statement was an attempt to deflate a Democratic charge
that the Lewinsky probe was a morality-tinged probe of an illicit
sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   He also took aim at the Democratic contention that impeachment
was intended to be reserved for presidential misconduct in official
duties, not private behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Starr said a president who bribed a witness in a private lawsuit
would be subject to impeachment under the Constitution's
designation of bribery as an impeachable offense, he said. Also, a
president who committed murder or rape could be impeached, Starr
said. Linking impeachment to official duties is ``an incorrect
interpretation of the Constitution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of Clinton's efforts to conceal his 18-month
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky ``caused all
of us considerable dismay _ and continues to do so,'' Starr told
the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, ``I am proud of what we did,'' he added. ``We were
assigned a difficult job. We have done it to the very best of our
abilities. We have tried to be fair and thorough.''
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Chairman Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., tried to open
Thursday's proceedings on a non-partisan note. The hearing, he
said, ``is not a trial nor is it White House versus Ken Starr, or
Republican versus Democrat. Rather, the hearing today is another
step in our attempt to carry out our constitutional duty.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get very far. Rep. William Delahunt, D-Mass., made a
motion to allow Clinton's lawyer David Kendall two hours to
question Starr, instead of the 30 minutes allotted by Hyde.
Republicans defeated the motion 21-16 on a party-line vote.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde promised that Clinton would receive ``unlimited time'' if
he chooses to make a personal appearance before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Starr spent over eight hours at the witness table in the same
room where the Judiciary Committee held impeachment hearings
against President Nixon in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   He took two hours to read a 58-page statement in a professorial
voice, and then parryed the expected Democratic crticism of his
conduct of the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a federally-paid sex policeman spending millions
of dollars to trap an unfaithful spouse ... would have been
unthinkable prior to the Starr investigation,'' said the
committee's ranking Democrat, Rep. John Conyers of Michigan. ``Let
there be no mistake, it is not now acceptable in America to
investigate a person's private sexual activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington lawyer Theodore Olson, a close friend of Starr's,
described the independent counsel's testimony as vintage Starr,
noting that Starr didn't allow himself to be ``perturbed by the
tone of some of the questions which were hostile and
aggressive...He certainly demonstrated himself to be capable of not
letting people get under his skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's prepared statement contained few surprises, going over
much of the same ground covered in his Sept. 9 report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's intimate relationship with a subordinate
employee was transformed into an unlawful effort to thwart the
judicial process,'' Starr said. ``This was no longer an issue of
private conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said Clinton lied under oath about Lewinsky in his Jan.
17, 1998, deposition in the Jones civil lawsuit, and also lied that
same month to his Cabinet and at a televised public event.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, he added, also pressured his personal secretary, Betty
Currie, into agreeing with him that he and Lewinsky were never
alone, and that Currie could ``see and hear everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also lied in his Aug. 17, 1998, grand jury testimony by
claiming his Jan. 17 denial of a sexual relationship with Lewinsky
was legally accurate, Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr zeroed in on instances in which he claimed that Clinton
had stalled the legal process in the Lewinsky matter by refusing
for seven months to testify before the grand jury and trying to
prevent White House lawyer Bruce Lindsey and Secret Service
personnel from testifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president used the machinery of government and the power
of his office to conceal his relationship with Monica Lewinsky,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   On six occasions, from Dec. 17, 1997, when Clinton called
Lewinsky at 2 a.m. and told her she was on the witness list in the
Jones lawsuit to Aug. 17, 1998, when he admitted an ``improper
relationship'' with Lewinsky, ``the president had to make a
decision.'' Starr said. ``He could choose truth, or he could choose
deception. On all six occasions, the president chose deception _ a
pattern of calculated behavior over a span of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr disclosed that his office considered recommending that the
House undertake an impeachment investigation on the original
Whitewater allegations, but ultimately he declined to send it. The
issue concerned Clinton's testimony that he didn't know about a
fraudulent $300,000 loan and a second loan from Madison Guaranty
Savings &AMP; Loan which was owned by the president's former business
partners, James and Susan McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also told lawmakers he found no evidence of impeachable
offenses in his separate investigations of White House possession
of FBI files on Republicans _ an episode known as ``filegate'' _ or
in the firing of career White House travel office workers and their
replacement by employees close to Clinton _ ``travelgate.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr served in the Justice Department in the Reagan
administration and was appointed to the federal appeals court in
Washington by Reagan in 1983. During the Bush administration, he
was the U.S. solicitor general, the government's chief advocate
before the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   With such a Republican pedigree, Starr made a point of defending
the Lewinsky probe as one staffed by career federal prosecutors and
FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a bright line between law and politics, between
courts and polls,'' Starr said. ``It leaves the polls to the
politicians and spin doctors. We are officers of the court who live
in the world of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said he kept the attorney general's office informed of the
course of his investigations, even quoting Attorney General Janet
Reno that in high-profile cases ``you're damned if you do and
damned if you don't, so you'd better do what you think is right.''
</P>
<P>
   He also defended what Democrats have characterized as strong-arm
tactics by agents and prosecutors in confronting Lewinsky at a
hotel in suburban Washington in January 1998. Starr's staff
attempted to dissuade Lewinsky from calling her lawyer and her
mother.
</P>
<P>
   While such tactics ``may not be entirely comfortable for some
witnesses,'' Starr said, ``it was not our place to reinvent the
investigative wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   During a break, Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., called Starr's
argument about impeachment and official duties ``pretty
weak...Impeachment is meant to protect the Constitution, not punish
the wrongdoer.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Is a chief of executive, through a course of
conduct, rendered incapable of performing his duties? A lot of that
has to do with his stature with the electorate. The American people
have reached that conclusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
