<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HARVARD-PILGRIM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID MOUNTING LOSSES, HARVARD PILGRIM TRIMS EXECUTIVE JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the wake of unprecedented financial losses at
Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, the state's largest health maintenance
organization has eliminated the jobs of four high-level employees,
including Dr. Patrick Mattingly, widely perceived as the No. 2
executive at Harvard Pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement follows a report released Friday that outlined
the extent of Harvard's losses, which amounted to $22.2 million in
the first three quarters of 1998. Harvard expects &UR;  &LR;  to lose as much
as $30 million for the full year, including about $10 million in
one-time charges associated with the layoffs of 100 employees and a
bond refinancing that would save the HMO money in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   The losses prompted a recent decision to lay off 100 people as
part of an effort to trim the company's $3 billion annual budget.
At the time, Harvard said cutbacks would be made ``at all levels of
the organization,'' but health care observers were surprised that
the layoffs would claim executives at such lofty levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very significant positions,'' said Ellen Trager, a
health care consultant with Brown Rudnick Freed &AMP; Gesmer.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly's departure, in particular, was unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge surprise to me,'' said Stephen Caulfield,
chairman of the Chickering Group, a health insurance company in
Cambridge, who said he is a friend of Mattingly. ``I think he is a
real thought leader in this industry, and I think he's been
extraordinarily loyal and devoted to the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   In his job as senior vice president of planning and development,
Mattingly was part of an inner circle of decisionmakers at Harvard
Pilgrim. He played a key role in the company's strategic direction,
health policy and government relations. Mattingly was once in
contention for the top job at Harvard Pilgrim after the 1995 merger
of Harvard Community Health Plan and Pilgrim Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   Others on the list of layoffs include Dr. John Ludden, senior
vice president of medical affairs; Daniel D. Kaplan, senior vice
president of the Massachusetts region; and William Schlag, vice
president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Ludden, a psychiatrist, joined Harvard Community Health Care in
1972 as director of Harvard's Kenmore center. From 1983 to 1994, he
was Harvard's top physician, serving as corporate medical director.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan has been in charge of negotiating contracts with
Harvard's network of more than 15,000 physicians and 90 hospitals
in Massachusetts, while Schlag oversaw the marketing and
communications functions. Efforts to contact Mattingly, Ludden,
Kaplan and Schlag Thursday were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the people, it was the positions,'' said Allan
Greenberg, chief executive of Harvard Pilgrim. ``We found we could
spread the responsibilities of these positions or eliminate the
work to some extent.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg emphasized that Harvard Pilgrim's expected loss for
1998 of nearly $30 million , while unprecedented, is just one
percent of the company's $3 billion budget. ``We're talking about
small variances here,'' he said. ``As a nonprofit company, we've
never tried to budget extraordinary profits. As a result, you have
very small margins, and when you miss your numbers, you fall into
the red zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The operating loss largely resulted from higher-than-expected
medical expenses. Inpatient hospital expenses, for example, came in
over budget, Greenberg said. Harvard Pilgrim was also hit by a
larger-than-average share of seniors with higher medical expenses,
a fact that led Harvard on Monday to discontinue offering unlimited
drug benefits to seniors enrolled in its First Seniority Medicare
HMO, effective Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the layoffs, Harvard is expected to raise the
premiums it charges in 1999 in an effort to return to
profitability. While premiums for employers who are Harvard Pilgrim
customers went up an average of just 2 percent in 1998, they are
expected to rise between 6 percent and 8 percent next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
