<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-AID-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HURRICANE-RAVAGED HONDURAS, KC-BASED GROUP WORKS TO REBUILD
LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY SANCHEZ  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star   SAN PEDRO SULA, Honduras _ When
Blanca Estela Rodriguez looks over the village of Guacamaya, she
sees more than the physical damage from Hurricane Mitch. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She sees health and medical problems that will plague Hondurans
for months and years to come if she and her group of volunteers
don't intervene. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Men shovel floodwater from a roadway in one part of town.
Rodriguez, a veteran relief worker, knows the stagnant water is a
breeding ground for mosquitoes carrying deadly malaria. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patches of mud have dried and cracked into jigsaw puzzle pieces.
She knows the dirt soon will become airborne, a noxious dust that
can cause asthma and bronchitis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barefoot children, shoes lost in the hurricane, run through mud
nearby. She knows the muck holds tapeworms and other parasites
waiting to infect the children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The weight of her mission grows even heavier as she visits a
crushed medical clinic in Guacamaya, on the outskirts of San Pedro
Sula, Honduras' second largest city. All that remains is a roofless
shell of a building, half-buried in an avalanche of mud and dirt
from the Mico Quemado Mountains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The clinic is one of 13 medical and dental centers run by Kansas
City-based Children International, the relief agency Rodriguez
works for. These centers are the group's best hope of keeping
Hurricane Mitch from claiming more lives in Honduras. Already 7,000
have died, the country's worst tragedy in centuries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Rodriguez promises to get them running soon, so people can
get the medical care and supplies they need. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to accomplish it,'' she says while standing at
the demolished clinic. ``The people here still have a lot of faith
in us and we are the only really constant thing in their lives.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez says she'll leave it to others to rebuild the roads
and bridges. Her crusade is to make sure people have food,
medicine, homes. &QL; 
 &LR; brk:Saving children &QL; 
 &LR; tx:Rodriguez is Children International's project coordinator in
Honduras. The 14-year-old relief group is best known for recruiting
people in the United States and Canada to ``sponsor'' children in
nine poor countries. These donations have enabled the agency to set
up schools, medical check-ups, dental care and other benefits for
13,600 children in 70 towns in Honduras. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ordinary times, Children International's goal is to make
families self-sufficient. Rodriguez's team of 52 doctors, nurses,
dentists, teachers and social workers have trained more than 1,700
mothers in and around San Pedro Sula in hygiene, well-baby care and
organizational skills. A corps of volunteer mothers keeps the
agency's work alive in villages around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Rodriguez and her team of workers and volunteers have taken
on the daunting task of hurricane relief. The crisis has brought
out the best in people, Rodriguez said with pride. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As one mother fled her flooded home, she rescued an electric air
compressor that runs the drill in one of the program's dental
clinics. She hauled it with her to a homeless shelter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In many of the shelters for hurricane homeless, the volunteer
mothers assumed leadership. They began teaching the dangers of
contaminated water and noting who was missing family members or who
most needed medical care. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that we have taught the people is what is needed
most right now,'' Rodriguez said. &QL; 
 &LR; brk:`Just unbelievable' &QL; 
 &LR; tx:Children International, with headquarters in south Kansas City,
has kept close tabs on the Honduras relief effort. On one recent
day, CEO Jim Cook flew in from Kansas City so Rodriguez could show
him some of the hard hit spots in the San Pedro Sula area in
western Honduras. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First they drive to Guacamaya. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Rodriguez visited soon after the hurricane, she went by
raft. On this day, she and Cook drive in on a path plowed by
bulldozers. The original road ends midway over a collapsed bridge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At this Children International clinic, dirt surrounds the
building almost all the way to the roof. Cook easily steps onto the
roof supports to survey the landscape. Most of the homes nearby are
buried or completely washed away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a disaster,'' he says. ``It is just unbelievable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They meet Eva Cruz, who lives in a home behind the demolished
clinic. She is in her kitchen, boiling a meal of corn on a wood
fire. A hen and her chicks peck the concrete floor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, whose six children are sponsored by Children
International, has laid her baby's underwear to dry on what used to
be the clinic's roof. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the hurricane, the family fled to the mountains nearby.
They feared that their house, which sits between two streams, would
float away. It didn't, but the water caved in one wall and mud
flooded it waist-high. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For four days, many people from the area lived in the mountains,
taking shelter under a piece of corrugated tin. The only food was
the platanos (bananas) the children gathered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, a volunteer mother, said she would wait for the clinic to
rebuild. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We will stay here and wait to see what happens,'' she said.
``We have nowhere else to go.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At another town, Rodriguez leaves her high heels in the van and
puts on black, knee-high rubber boots. They are necessary to walk
the streets of Asentamientas Humanos, a village of about 4,000
people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Children International has a one-story building here with a
kindergarten, a dental clinic, a gynecology clinic and a meals
program. Mud and water flooded the building to its roof. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, volunteer mothers splashed pans of water on the
walls, scrubbing everything with bleach. Many were cleaning the
clinics before cleaning their own flooded homes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Rodriguez and Cook stop and talk with Lorenzo Dominguez
who is shoveling a canal to drain water away from his house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inside the three-room home, the family's refrigerator is wrapped
in twine and suspended from the ceiling beams six feet off the
ground. Dominguez hoisted it there before fleeing the floods. He
never dreamed the waters would rise above it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He lives in a shelter now with his wife and four children.
During the day, he returns to Asentamientas to work on the house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him we feel for him and the clinic will be up and running
to help soon,'' Cook tells the translator. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez's attitude is similar to many people Cook meets during
the tour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``With God's faith we will go ahead,'' he told the translator to
tell Cook. ``We don't have to cry for this.'' &QL; 
 &LR; brk:Garnering support &QL; 
 &LR; tx:Back in San Pedro Sula, Rodriguez spends much of her time in
meetings and on the phone. She fulfills the pivotal, though perhaps
not glamorous, role of recruiting volunteers, donations and support
from business and civic leaders in Honduras and around the world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a briefing with Cook, they discuss how Hurricane Mitch has
affected Children International in Honduras. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Has this deterred your plans to expand our services here?'' he
asks through a translator. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, Rodriguez answers. By Nov. 30, she will know the cost of
rebuilding the damaged clinics. Others are being cleared of mud,
scrubbed and fumigated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even with those obstacles, she plans to help 40,000 more
children in 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are needed now, more than ever,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cook tells her of letters sent this week to 200,000 current and
former sponsors, seeking contributions for Honduras. The agency has
never made a special plea, he says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In another meeting, Rodriguez successfully secures crucial
support from the city. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even before everyone is served coffee in the mayor's office, she
is smiling broadly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Roberto Larios Silva has promised to ease the passage of
Children International goods through customs. He has promised
storage space in the city warehouse. But most of all, he has
promised city land for a new development that will provide a
medical clinic and 4,000 homes for the 20,000 people who lost
everything to the hurricane. Construction should begin in a month
northwest of San Pedro Sula. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The village will be called Nueva Vida _ New Life. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
