<SLUG> BC-AT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU DARE NOT IGNORE TOM PETERS' ROAR 
</HEADLINE>
 WORK-COLUMN-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (begin italic)This is the beginning of the white-collar
revolution. But we AIN'T SEEN NOTHIN' YET. Just wait till the
white-collar ROBOTS come.(end italic) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Can you guess whose workplace seminar I attended this week? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (begin italic)It's a birdIt's a planeIt's the GIANT SUCKING
SOUND OF SLACK being extracted from the global economy!(end
italic) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hint: He's not searching for excellence any more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (begin italic)Think FREAKS! Think interesting. Think DENNIS
RODMAN. Think emotional, volatile, unpredictable. THAT'S THE PRICE
of imaginative.(end italic) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He came. He swore. He stomped the floor at Bartle Hall. He
hollered the gospel of innovation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (begin italic)Any change worth doing IRRITATES people. If
somebody's not mad at you, YOU'RE NOT ALIVE! Anything important
ANNOYS the current establishment.(end italic) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's Tom Peters _ Thomas J. Peters _ whom /{Business Week/}
called ``business's best friend and worst nightmare.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The self-described enemy of complacency, who repeatedly ranks as
the most-recognized name among business advisers and the world's
best-selling author of business books, shared his ``How to Survive
and Thrive'' advice with several hundred Kansas City business
folk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And then we all went back to work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem with attending a Tom Peters seminar. He takes
you soaring and swooping, sailing into the future with the fearless
focus of a hawk on a rodent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And then he drops you back into reality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, brain- and eardrum-popping showman. Hello, hierarchy.
Hello, policies and plasticized mission statements and annual
appraisal forms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (begin italic)Don't ever, ever, EVER, EVERRRRR say `exceeds
expectations' again. That is NASTY evaluation language. ARRRRGH!
Take an oath. Use `astonish.' How about `amaze'? EXCEEDS
EXPECTATIONS? (Expletive deleted!) WHO TALKS THAT WAY?(end italic) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peters is busy these days selling two big ideas. For
organizations: Innovators win. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (begin italic)I am an ENEMY of benchmarking. Benchmarking means
others are doing what you do. DON'T LOOK AT THE PICK OF THE LITTER!
Look at the gnats buzzing around. They're the ones who will bite
you.(end italic) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For individuals: You must sell the ``Brand of You.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (begin italic)You gotta have a story. YOU GOTTA STAND FOR
SOMETHING in the white-collar revolution. You gotta be able to
write a bumper sticker for yourself.(end italic) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you can't write an eight-word job description that describes
your specialty and your value to your organization, Peters smells
dead meat. If you couldn't construct a bang-up quarter-page ad for
yourself in an in-house Yellow Pages, you're downsizing fodder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peters urged us to analyze our work for WOW! projects. If we're
not doing things that will improve our resumes by the end of the
year, he has some advice: Question the assignment. Reinvent it.
Make it interesting. Take chances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (begin italic)``Do it right the first time.'' THAT'S SICK!
THAT'S MENTALLY ILL! We must strike out fear of failure. We must
REWARD failure. DO NOT aim for mediocre successes. You cannot
execute fast and flawlessly. DO NOT punish those kinds of
mistakes.(end italic) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peters roared to the seminar finish line with a
success-for-the-millennium observation from Mario Andretti: /{If
things seems under control, you're just not going fast enough./} &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
