A9900 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-B     11-19 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE HE GOES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There's still a lot of yardage between Foxborough and
Hartford. And given the way the offense is playing this year,
there's reason to believe the New England Patriots may not make it
to the Nutmeg State.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the latest wave of mostly sports media-driven hysteria,
a ``deal'' between Connecticut officials and Patriots owner Robert
Kraft is far from done.
</P>
<P>
   What was announced Thursday is a memorandum of understanding
that provides for an exclusive period of negotiation between Kraft
and the state of Connecticut. It spells out a set of legislative
and economic conditions that would bring the Patriots to a new
downtown Hartford stadium in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone still needs time to digest the fine print. But chances
are, even if Connecticut Governor John Rowland says there's no
wiggle room, there's plenty of weasel room for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   From Kraft's perspective, why sign anything in front of TV
cameras, anyway, if not to start drumming up yet another
save-the-Patriots outcry on Boston talk radio? He could have signed
the thing in private, and in 45 days, backed up the trucks to
Foxboro Stadium to drive Drew and the boys down to Nowheresville,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the odds seem strong that the Patriots will end up in
Hartford. On paper, a $350 million publicly financed stadium
project sounds like a very good business opportunity, quite
possibly too good to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   How much do we really care? Does Massachusetts without the Pats
really become Tupelo without Elvis as a legendary native son?
</P>
<P>
   A loud gaggle of media and business people will argue
passionately that we are on our way to turning into Dubuque without
the Patriots. The argument ignores the fact that the Patriots left
Boston more than 20 years ago and, far from being dead, the city is
more vibrant than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Polls consistently show a majority in this state does not care
enough about losing the team to spend public money to keep them
here. There's almost a Monica Lewinsky dynamic going on here. The
public yawns, while the media insist the common man or woman is
just too stupid to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe they do get it. Maybe they do understand the
Kraft-Patriots saga is all about money, ego, and leverage and has
little or nothing to do with them.
</P>
<P>
   And the matter of ego, by the way, applies to Kraft and his
nemesis, House Speaker Thomas Finneran. The speaker really should
stop arguing this as a matter of principle, when he is making it so
very personal with his comments about ``fat-ass millionaires.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kraft takes the Hartford deal, he is making a clear,
bottom-line business decision. The status quo _ being the leader of
a Foxborough-based Patriots Nation _ is unacceptable because he is
a businessman and he wants to make more money. He can do it two
ways: by selling the Patriots; or, if he wants to retain ownership,
he can make money by bringing in more revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the way to maximize revenue is to get someone else to
pay for a bigger stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran says he won't go higher than $57 million for
infrastructure, versus the $72 million offered by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Both numbers are very far away from the amount Hartford is
willing to put up.
</P>
<P>
   They are so far away it seems unlikely Kraft would turn down the
Hartford deal _ as long as he keeps emotion out of the equation and
doesn't start to imagine how it will feel to ride a golf cart onto
the 50 yard line and be closer to Waterbury, Conn., than to
Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Just like Kraft, we, too, should take the emotion out of the
equation. We can like football and think a professional football
franchise is nice to have. But we can still think of it as an
amenity, not a necessity. We can believe Boston is a terrific city
without the Patriots and that Hartford will be a better city, but
far from a terrific one, even with them.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand: if Kraft leaves, the Patriots are gone.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a psychic loss to some and an economic one to
others, at least until the land around Foxboro stadium produced
revenue from future development.
</P>
<P>
   It would mean nothing to most everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   (Joan Venocchi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
