<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-21STCENTURY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    6 top chairmen predict `good news, bad news' year for 1999
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Six Atlanta chief executives, peering beyond the
cloudy economic decline of next year, predicted tough and growing
competition in the next millenium, but expanding opportunities
because of advancing technology.
</P>
<P>
   The executives talked to an audience of Metro Atlanta Chamber of
Commerce members and others in an all-day symposium at the Downtown
Hyatt Regency Hotel, addressing the topic, Strategies in the Next
Millenium.
</P>
<P>
   The chairmen included F. Duane Ackerman of BellSouth Corp.; A.W.
``Bill'' Dahlberg, Southern Company; A.D. ``Pete'' Correll,
Georgia-Pacific Corporation; Frederick Schwab, Porsche Cars North
America; Charles Brewer, Mindspring Enterprises, and L. Phillip
Humann, SunTrust Banks.
</P>
<P>
   John Youngdahl, vice president and senior money market economist
for Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., set much of the tone with a prediction
that economic growth could slow next year to 1.5 percent, even more
bullish than the 2 percent growth rate projected by the Federal
Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a good news, bad news year,'' Youngdahl said. The
bad news is that consumer demand will be dampened, job growth will
weaken and a deeper sense of caution may rule consumer habits.
Also, because of political demands, there is little chance that
government spending or other steps will be available to stimulate a
new level of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   On the good news side, he said, inflation should stay moderate,
interest rates will remain low, and the equity markets should do
moderately well.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, Correll said his company, a world
powerhouse in lumber and building products, was deeply troubled by
the overseas malaise. Worsening economic conditions, especially in
Asia, have slashed currencies, thereby giving advantages to
exporters of pulp, board and other items that compete directly with
Georgia-Pacific's lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``As usual, the producers in Asia are likely to export their way
out of trouble and that spells trouble for us,'' Correll said.
``Pulp prices have dropped a third and other products even more.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the overseas threat was real for capital intensive
businesses like Georgia-Pacific, and the outlook is gloomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We face more uncertainty than we have faced in years,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the other players were generally more upbeat, but did
not see a landscape free of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman of BellSouth foresees continuing transformation of the
phone company into Internet business, wireless TV, and hopefully
long distance service.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the policy area, BellSouth should be allowed to deliver
long distance service,'' he said. Furthermore, he said, the company
plans bigger networks for digital distribution of data, using
packet switching for speed and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth wants authority to get into long distance to connect
to its local exchanges, as well as enable it to offer bigger long
distance networks, Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dahlberg, the affable chairman of Southern Company, said
the complicated fight to deregulate electric power would likely
succeed eventually. For that reason, he said, the company needs to
continue to be more aggressive in building buisiness elsewhere
across the nation and around the world to offset potential losses
through domestic competition.
</P>
<P>
   The company will continue to seek opportunities in the Northeast
and possibly in Texas, areas where power costs are relatively high,
to build power plants and compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always lose something in deregulation,'' he said, but
promised meanwhile to fight hard to preserve the Southeast customer
base.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Humann of SunTrust said the company would continue to
concentrate on its best customers, business and individual, and
persuade them to ``migrate'' to additonal services.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company would concentrate on developing its
talents and personal service. One element of the strategy, he said,
is to focus training and effort on 300 top corporate employees to
buttress the company's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``PC and Internet banking are the wave of the future,'' Humann
said. ``Though they are small now, they are growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
