<HEADER>
A9904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAYES-EARNINGS20-COX     11-19 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYES-EARNINGS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hayes lists loses at $19.1 million
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hayes Corp. reported a $19.1 million loss Thursday for
the third fiscal quarter ending Oct. 3 as the deeply troubled
suburban Atlanta-based modem-maker continued to suffer from a slide
in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, which filed for bankruptcy protection Oct. 9, reported
revenues of $24.5 million _ a 53 percent plunge from $51.8 million
in revenues during the same quarter a year ago. The loss for the
quarter amounted to 99 cents per share, compared to a $6.7 million
loss, or 87 cents-per-share, for the same quarter in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view this as more of a snapshot of where we have been as
opposed to a picture of where we are going,'' said Ron Howard,
Hayes chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The company work force has already been slashed to 450 from a
one-time high of about 1,200 and will almost certainly shrink even
more with the planned sale of its Norcross, Ga. manufacturing
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will change the head-count pretty substantially,'' Howard
said. ``Hayes is now a company that is well into restructuring. I
don't look at these numbers and say this is what Hayes can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Long-term company hopes are pinned to new devices for connecting
customers to high-speed lines. But large-scale introduction of
digital subsciber lines by phone companies and cable modems from
cable companies is a few years away. Meanwhile, analog modem sales
have been erratic at best _ and often abysmal. Howard said the
company's financial bleeding has drained the strength needed to
exploit the demand that still exists. Hayes has ``substantial''
orders for modems that have gone unfilled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is scrambling to arrange the financing needed to
take advantage of those opportunities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second sojourn in bankruptcy for Hayes, which in the
mid-1980s dominated the modem industry. The company emerged from
its first Chapter 11 in 1996, expecting growth, only to see sales
sag after several quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes merged with the much-smaller Access Beyond at the end of
last year. Since then, Hayes has reported sales of $101.7 million.
During the same three quarters of 1997, company revenues were
$146.7 million. The loss of $36.6 million for the first three
quarters of 1998 compares to a $14.5 million loss for the same
period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
