<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR PRESSES CASE; DEMOCRATS PRESS STARR
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) (EDS: Will be led with later testimony) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent counsel Kenneth Starr presented the
case against President Clinton in meticulous detail Thursday as
Democrats tried to turn the historic impeachment hearing into an
indictment of the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The counterattack began even before Starr uttered a word as the
leadoff witness before the House Judiciary Committee. Later, Starr
accused the president of lying under oath, obstruction of justice,
witness tampering and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused Starr of leading a politically motivated
witchhunt that became fixated on Clinton's sex life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, and many others, believe that Mr. Starr has crossed the
line into obsession,'' said Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, who
derided the independent counsel as a ``federally paid sex
policeman.''
</P>
<P>
   Conyers' opening statement set the tone for a politically
charged proceeding that provided plenty of partisan sniping but no
new revelations. By the end of the day, it was clear that no minds
had been changed on the 37-member panel that is expected to vote
strictly along party lines to recommend Clinton's removal from
office.
</P>
<P>
   Although the nationally televised hearing was only the third
time in the nation's history that a president had been subjected to
impeachment proceedings, the gravity of the occasion was often lost
in the bickering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the seating arrangement suits you. That's about all
that hasn't been complained of today,'' a sarcastic Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., the committee's chairman, told Democrats as the
session dragged into the late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who maintained his quiet demeanor in the face of
blistering criticism, portrayed himself as an impartial public
servant whose only goal was the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respectfully but firmly reject the notion that our office
was trying to inflame the public,'' he said. ``I am not a man of
polls, public relations or politics. ... I revere the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr also took issue with suggestions that he wanted to smear
Clinton by releasing graphic details of the president's sexual
liasons with Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our referral never suggests that the relationship between the
president and Ms. Lewinsky in and of itself could be a high crime
or misdemeanor,'' he said. ``The propriety of a relationship is not
the concern of our office.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to his X-rated Sept. 9 report to Congress, Starr's
58-page opening statement on Thursday avoided any mention of sexual
activity. The independent counsel kept the case against Clinton
tightly focused on the president's efforts to keep the affair
secret.
</P>
<P>
   Starr said Clinton lied under oath in Paula Jones' sexual
harassment case, lied to a federal grand jury, lied to White House
aides, lied to members of his Cabinet and lied to the American
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``On at least six difference occasions _ from December 17, 1997,
through August 17, 1998 _ the president had to make a decision,''
Starr said. ``He could choose truth or he could choose deception.
On all six occasions, the president chose deception.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton ``repeatedly used the machinery of government
and the powers of his office to conceal his relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   But Starr also acknowledged that he did not find compelling
evidence of wrongdoing by Clinton in several other matters,
including the failed Whitewater development that initially prompted
the four-year investigation.
</P>
<P>
   He cleared Clinton of any misconduct in the 1993 purge of the
White House travel office and the collection of FBI files on former
Bush administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found no evidence that information contained in the
files of former officials was used for an improper purpose,'' Starr
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Starr said Clinton and his White House aides
hindered virtually every step of his investigation. He suggested
that Clinton's supporters have paid Webster Hubbell, a Clinton
confidante and a former associate attorney general, about $550,000
to buy his silence _ an allegation that Hubbell has called untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats questioned Starr's motives and his tactics. They
accused him of putting undue pressure on Lewinsky to win her
cooperation, then ignoring her sworn statement that she was never
asked to lie or promised a job in return for silence.
</P>
<P>
   Starr said he did not quote Lewinsky in his report to Congress
because he thought her statement was misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, no one explicitly said, `You will lie,' using the L word.
Rather, it was we will continue with cover stories which are not
true,'' Starr explained. ``Ms. Lewinsky made it quite clear that
she knew how to lie. She was encouraging others to lie.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the tactics used against Lewinsky, which included
discouraging her from calling a lawyer and threatening to prosecute
her mother, are standard investigative techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did, in fact, use a traditional technique that law
enforcement always uses,'' he said. ``She was a felon in the middle
of committing another felony.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans rallied to Starr's defense
</P>
<P>
   ``You are the target of the bull's eye,'' said a sympathetic
Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C. ``If half of the unfair comments leveled
at you are true, you should probably be keelhauled.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats seemed to agree.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
