<HEADER>
A9907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT20-COX     11-19 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT MEMO SHOWS FEARED IMPACT OF HIGH PRICES
 &HT;    470&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial queues
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An internal document released Thursday at the
Microsoft antitrust trial reveals that top-level executives
discussed concerns that the company's high prices might threaten
its Windows software monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   A confidential memo to company chairman Bill Gates, written last
December, reviewed events that might ``derail'' Microsoft's pricing
strategy. It was written, at Gates's request, by Joachim Kempin,
vice president for sales to personal computer makers.
</P>
<P>
   The memo came to light as a government exhibit when economist
Frederick Warren-Boulton testified as the seventh witness to take
the stand. In a rare move, the Microsoft defense team insisted that
the entire Kempin memo, which was cited briefly in his 89 pages of
written testimony, be made public.
</P>
<P>
   Warren-Boulton contended that the memo shows Microsoft
calculating that the business climate would prevent other firms
from penetrating the market for operating systems. Microsoft asked
that the entire memo be made public in order to emphasize the point
that it considered its monopoly vulnerable to rapid technological
development.
</P>
<P>
   Firms such as Compaq Computer and Dell Computer, known in the
trade as original equipment manufacturers, or OEMs, license various
versions of the Windows operating system from Microsoft and install
them on machines that they then sell to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our high prices could get a single OEM (Compaq might pay us
$750 million next year) or a coalition to fund a competing effort
(say in India),'' Kempin wrote. ``While this possibility exists, I
consider it doubtful even if they could get a product out that they
can market it successfully, (and) leapfrog us,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A potential coalition of hardware vendors that would gang up on
Microsoft and use their combined financial power to clone Windows
was not the only peril on the horizon, according the memo to Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Other risks are posed by Sun Microsystems Inc., which is
promoting its Java programming language as a cross-platform
alternative to Windows-only applications, and by Intel Corp., which
has much the same hold over the central processing units (CPU's)
that run personal computers as Microsoft has on their operating
system, or OS.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they decide to own the OS as well as the CPU our business
... will get ugly,'' Kempin said, referring to Intel. ``If they
decide to sell the OS for $1 and the CPU for $200 they will get the
OEMs on their side,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Kempin saw the threat from Sun's Java, which has recently loomed
large in anti-trust circles, as a more distant one. ``For the next
2-3 years the barriers are huge for them and even IBM, after
studying the technology, is not convinced that it would satisfy
customers when implemented during that time frame,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In reviewing the company's pricing options, Kempin favored a new
tack: licensing Windows ``for a limited time (to) create (an)
annuity business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best thing long term but it might disrupt end user
operations and could require end user registration,'' the Microsoft
executive noted. The annual licensing plan, he told Gates, probably
could not be put into effect ``until Windows NT 6.0 comes out (in),
say, 2001,'' Kempin said. Microsoft is currently shipping NT 4.0
while testing NT 5.0 among 10,000 beta users.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a champion for this now if we want to do this,'' he
added, referring to the annuity pricing scheme. The memo's title
made it clear that Gates had requested Kempin's ``OEM pricing
thoughts,'' who also asked for ``feedback'' from Gates.
</P>
<P>
   The software giant contends it would be able to charge a lot
more for its Windows program if in fact it had a monopoly in
operating systems as the government alleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft does not charge more because this is a highly
competitive market, and a higher price would attract additional
market entrants,'' a recent company statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
