<HEADER>
A9910 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-19 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENDER BARRIERS HAVE FALLEN BUT NOT FAR ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is a measure of how far gender barriers have
fallen in politics that for the first time in history two women, a
Republican and a Democrat, ran credible races for top House
leadership posts.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of how far those barriers have yet to fall that
both were defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your perspective, you can look at this as the
equivalent of a political glass half-empty or a glass half-full.
</P>
<P>
   Women won six open House seats this month, bringing next year's
total for that body to a record 56 women, a net increase of two
from the current Congress. They held their own in the Senate at
nine seats, re-electing two incumbents and losing one but picking
up another female who was a challenger.
</P>
<P>
   But in the new Congress that is coming to power in January women
will make up only 9 percent of the Senate and 12.8 percent of the
House, even though they number 52 percent of the general
population.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 50 governors, there are only three women.
</P>
<P>
   Female candidates no longer generate the excitement of 1992, the
so-called Year of the Woman, when scores of them ran for office and
boosted their numbers in Congress overnight from 28 to 47. Since
then, the momentum and the novelty have passed.
</P>
<P>
   But recent predictions of an end to females' progress were
premature. Their political power, particularly in the state
legislatures, continues to grow, although at a snail's pace.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody blinked when Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., had the
audacity this week to challenge House Majority Leader Richard Armey
for his post, the most powerful and prestigious job in the House
except for the speakership itself. As Republican Conference vice
chairman, she had earned the right to try, although the effort was
a bit of a reach.
</P>
<P>
   Armey defeated Dunn and two other challengers, Steve Sargent of
Oklahoma and J. Dennis Hastert of Illinois. But Dunn is the most
visible GOP female in the House and lives to fight another day.
</P>
<P>
   She based her campaign in part on a contention that the GOP
leadership needs a woman's voice to soften the party's image and
present a more compassionate face to the world. `` I bring the
perspective of a working mother and a professional woman to the
leadership table,'' she argued.
</P>
<P>
   Most female politicians these days flaunt their motherhood,
although a quarter century ago it was considered a distraction and
a disadvantage for a public career.
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. Pat Schroeder, also a mother, arrived in Congress in
1973, a male veteran lawmaker told her that he preferred his women
cuddly and sweet-smelling. She replied she preferred her men the
same way.
</P>
<P>
   As the 1984 Democratic vice presidential candidate, Rep.
Geraldine Ferraro, still another mother, was asked if she baked
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays motherhood is seen as a good credential for proving a
caring nature and an appreciation for the problems of ordinary
families. But motherhood did not cut much ice for Dunn with the GOP
male majority, which outnumbers the party's women 207 to 16 and is
more conservative than Dunn is perceived to be.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic House leaders also had a chance to pick a woman for a
top post and passed when Martin Frost of Texas defeated Rosa
DeLauro of Connecticut to become chairman of the Democratic Caucus.
Embarrassed by the fact that this leaves the diversity-conscious
Democrats without a woman in a top leadership post, Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt hastily volunteered he would find some appointive
top job for DeLauro.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, only one woman is in a leadership post _ the
Democrats just re-elected Barbara Mikulski of Maryland as
conference secretary. The Republicans maintained their all-male
leadership. It was easier for them because there are only three GOP
female senators.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no matter how slow the progress, the large numbers of women
now in politics have demonstrated that they are here to stay, as
they are in other workplace situations. The more, the merrier.
</P>
<P>
   When women were around in only token numbers, it was easy to
ignore them or treat them like out-of-place freaks. But now that
women sit on the major committees and are even knocking on the
doors of the congressional leadership, issues they are interested
in and policies they espouse are making their way into law.
</P>
<P>
   This also encourages that old speculation: Is the country ready
for a female president? The answer is usually yes in principle. But
things get complicated when you look for a woman with competitive
political credentials at that ultimate level. The list is pitifully
small.
</P>
<P>
   No female has ever made a serious run at the presidency,
although Schroeder tried briefly in 1988, Rep. Shirley Chisholm
made a frivolous run in 1972 and Sen. Margaret Chase Smith was
nominated at the 1964 GOP convention in a public relations stunt.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, president of the American Red Cross, former
Cabinet officer twice and wife of Bob Dole, the 1996 GOP
presidential nominee, is often mentioned as a good candidate for
the Republicans. Despite frequent urgings from her husband, she
shows no sign of running.
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Clinton is the top draw for Democrats,
although she denies any such ambitions, and the president has said
he doesn't think she would ever run in 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Both Elizabeth Dole and Hillary Clinton are popular in the polls
and relish public life. But a female president is a tougher sell
than, say, a female House majority leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
