<HEADLINE>
TALK TO ME, BABY _ WITH A MICROPHONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Is it possible to use your telephone receiver
as a microphone, since it's connected to the modem? _ Just Curious
</P>
<P>
   Dear Just: Just drive by the nearest fire station and see if you
can borrow the Jaws of Life for a few minutes. Then maybe you can
pry your wallet open long enough to extract five lousy bucks for a
stinking microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't you ever picked up the phone while you were online? You
get knocked off immediately, right? That's because only one device
can be using the line at a time, unless you have some fancy digital
doodads. You can't just pick up the phone, murmur ``What are you
wearing, baby?'' into it and have it broadcast all over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The modem has nothing to do with transmitting your voice. All
that stuff is handled by your sound card, which records what you
mumble into the mike, then funnels it into your video- or
audio-conferencing software. From there, it gets turned into tiny
little bundles of data and passed on to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Your modem takes all those digital signals _ all those little
ones and zeroes _ and translates them into a horrid screeching
sound that can be sent over a regular phone line. Modems on the
other end reverse the process.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: On a CD-ROM drive, the tray slides out, and you
just place the CD on it. Once the CD is inside, what makes it spin?
On a CD player with a flip-up lid, the CD goes on a spindle, but on
the slide-out kind? No spindle, just a little hole. _ The Hole
Truth
</P>
<P>
   Dear Truth: It's been a closely guarded industry secret until
now, but there are thousands of tiny little invisible fairies who
live in your computer. It takes a specially trained army of about
70,000 of them to surround the CD, lift it ever so gently from the
tray, then run around in a circle as fast as they can until they
get so dizzy they throw up. That dust you see collecting in the CD
tray? Fairy puke.
</P>
<P>
   Look, there really is a spindle, and it's inside the drive with
the rest of the guts. When the tray retracts, the spindle grabs the
CD. No fairies are injured in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Bruce Williams has his picture in our paper.
Jane Bryant Quinn has her picture in our paper. Even The Motley
Fool has a picture in our paper. Why not you? _ A Real Fan
</P>
<P>
   Dear A: The statute of limitations hasn't run out in your state.
Anyway, that whole unfortunate incident at the liquor store was a
simple misunderstanding. It was all Bruce's idea.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: An objectionable picture has lodged itself on
my wallpaper as well as the wallpaper menu. How do I delete it so
my kids will not see it? _ Whoops
</P>
<P>
   Dear Whoops: Well, I guess that'll teach you to get twitchy with
your mouse hand. Most browsers let you capture Web images as
Windows wallpaper with a click or two. Of course, that means you
have to have been looking at the image in the first place. Nice
example for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Wallpaper images usually can be found in the Windows folder with
a .BMP extension. If it's not there, use Find (on the Start menu)
to locate it, then go delete it. Or better yet, send it to me for
safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   (Wondering if your wallpaper is naughty? Noted computerologist
Dr. Emilio Bombay will guard your morals, too. He can be reached at
drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com or via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Fax: 390-7257. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1848EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9918 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNEY-THEATER-AZR &LR;      11-19 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNEY-THEATER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA TROUPE'S `JOURNEY' UNSPARING, BRILLIANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KYLE LAWSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Tyrones are scary sons-of-bitches, all the more
frightening because they are real people masquerading as stage
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene O'Neill's celebrated family, his own, thinly veiled by
artifice, makes you laugh as it slashes through the chest cavity,
looking for your heart. Then the tears come, and after that the
pity.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for their human frailties, you might think these
people are monsters from some other, more terrifying dimension. Of
all theatrical families, they are the most magnificently
theatrical, the most splendidly horrible, the most compulsively
watchable.
</P>
<P>
   James, his wife Mary and their sons Jamie and Edmund are the
charismatic, doomed clan at the center of O'Neill's ``Long Day's
JourneyInto Night,'' a masterpiece of world theater that is being
revived by Arizona Theatre Company and director Marshall W. Mason
at the Herberger Theater Center in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix has never seen a production like this. New York and
London cannot best it. From the opening moments, when the Tyrones
stride boldly into their living room, the audience is aware it is
embarking on an experience that, if lucky, comes once in a
playgoer's lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   James Tyrone is an aging, miserly actor, living on his dwindling
investments and the faded memories of his glory days as a matinee
idol. Mary is a morphine addict, the victim of painkillers
prescribed by a quack doctor during the birth of her youngest son.
Jamie is an alcoholic whoremonger, a bitter, acerbic man who is
fiercely protective of his kid brother Edmund.
</P>
<P>
   It is a naked portrayal of O'Neill's own family, and Edmund is
the playwright's unsparing look at himself, a writer of potential
who idolizes his mother and brother, tries to respect his father
and fears that all rue the day he was born. As the play begins, he
is nervously awaiting a doctor's diagnosis on whether he has
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   God help them, for these people are beyond saving themselves.
They have plunged into the abyss before ever the lights come up
onstage. All that is left for the audience is to bear witness to
their agonizing descent into self-immolation and madness. &QL; 
 &QL; 
O'Neill at his best &QL; 
 &QL; 
But what a journey. O'Neill has few peers in his understanding of
the human tragedy and this is as good as he gets, a passionate,
darkly comic, lyrical ode to that razor's edge that bloodies most
of us before death puts an end to the mutilation.
</P>
<P>
   The Tyrones exist in an emotional netherworld between love and
hate, a place where the most sincere endearments are quickly
trampled by devastating truths. Every slight is a cut to the quick,
every outward sign of affection an occasion for cynical assessment,
but they can no more resist the ties that bind them than the tide
can stop its constant ebb and flow on the shores of the ocean that
fronts their summer home in New London, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Mason wastes no time in pitching audiences into the heart of the
maelstrom. He is not the first great director to take on the
Tyrones. Jose Quintero's 1956 production is still remembered for
its boldly dramatic vision. But Mason is not Quintero. His fame
rests on his body of work with Lanford Wilson, a playwright of more
intimate horizons.
</P>
<P>
   Mason's years of collaboration with Wilson have made him
something of an introvert when it comes to characterization. He is
less concerned with the outward show of the Tyrones' behavior, and
more involved with their inner struggle. Thus the family's pain is
both more evident and more subtle than it was in Quintero's
forthright approach.
</P>
<P>
   Mason choreographs his actors as if they were enemy warriors,
caught in an uneasy truce, suspecting that any minute the bloodbath
will renew itself. The Tyrones circle warily, reaching out to
tentatively pat a shoulder, to clutch at a robe, even to hold one
another awkwardly at moments of emotional overload _ but they never
(begin ital) touch. (end ital) Emotionally, they are opposing
magnets; their hearts push away as their arms open.
</P>
<P>
   It is a psychologically unnerving piece of staging, contributing
to an imagery of tension that pervades every aspect of the play.
Ming Cho Lee's massive, ghostly set broodingly evokes the past as
it imprisons the family in the present. Phil Monat's lighting
changes constantly, now highlighting, now casting the actors into
shadow, a visual metaphor for the Tyrones' distressing habit of
blurting out the truth, then fleeing from it.
</P>
<P>
   Always there is Peter Kater's haunting, melancholic music.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing can be trusted in this play, not love, not truth,
certainly not words. O'Neill uses them brilliantly, and at great
length _ the play runs 3 hours, 10 minutes, and, at that, Mason has
trimmed it considerably _ but always as a means to trap the unwary.
</P>
<P>
   The actors are finely tuned to this rhythm of deceit, stepping
on one another's lines as they battle to make their voices heard,
then falling into sudden silence as they realize they have
overstepped the bounds, even for this cacophonous family.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Reid's Mary may well be the definitive portrait of that
tragic, conflicted character. This is a woman who has seen the face
of God but who has forgotten what he looks like. Only devils peer
back at her now from her mirror, and she is frightened onto death. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tension-filled role &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reid judges her performance exactly, teetering on the edge of
sanity, a bomb surely primed to explode, but when? Yet that
explosion isn't what one anticipates. She goes not with a bang but
with a blood-curdling whimper. In more than 20 years of
theatergoing in Phoenix, this critic has seen nothing to match the
chilling impact of this moment.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Bennett's Jamie is another example of this actor's
chameleonic ability to transform himself. He can be, and has been,
everything from a teenager to an elderly geezer. This time, he is
many things at once. Like his father, Jamie is an actor, and
Bennett has the swagger, but a rot has set in, fueled by too much
booze, too many women and nightmares from which he can't seem to
awaken. Like different kinds of liquors blended in a single glass,
his feelings for his family swirl around and slosh over in messy
verbal confrontations that leave everyone soiled, himself most of
all.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, after seeing Jason Kuykendall's performances in
``All MySons'' and ``King Lear,'' Mason said he was convinced that
the 22-year-old actor could be another William Hurt. High pr aise,
for it was Mason who discovered Hurt and nurtured his career in its
early stages.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear from Kuykendall's sensitive, tortured Edmund that
Mason has lost none of his ability to unleash promising talent. Few
actors Kuykendall's age could achieve the necessary emotional power
_ much less hold their own _ in the shattering scene with Reid
where Edmund, goaded beyond endurance, finally confronts Mary with
the truth of her addiction. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Low-key Pressman &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If this ``Long Day's Journey Into Night'' has a flaw, it may be
Mason's decision to avoid any flamboyance in Lawrence Pressman's
portrayal of James Tyrone. There is no sense of the great actor
here; rather, Pressman reminds one of Charley Grapewin, the actor
who portrayed Judy Garland's kindly Uncle Henry in ``The Wizard of
Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   This low-key approach has the effect of reducing James' tirades
to whines. Too often, he comes across as crochety rather than
tyrannical. One can understand the family's disgust with its
patriarch's miserly habits; it's harder to grasp their reluctant
admiration for him. Still, Pressman is a remarkable actor. His
innate ability to find the humanity in any role he essays
transforms criticism of Mason's artistic misstep into nothing much
more than a quibble when set against the overwhelming impact of
this production.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, they like to say Mason is washed up. Otherwise, why
would such a legendary director waste his time teaching at Arizona
State University? Why he's here is another story. ``Long Day's
Journey Into Night'' is proof he is still master of his trade.
</P>
<P>
   The legend is not fading. Every performance at the Herberger
burnishes it more brightly. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
