<HEADER>
A9956 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS-AR     11-19 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PSAGOT, West Bank: our face.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What happened within the National Religious Party this week
provides a fascinating peek into the nexus of religion, ideology
and power in Israel. When the party's leaders decided to stay in
Netanyahu's coalition, they chose to keep their place at the table,
along with all the perquisites of office. But they also turned
their backs on their spiritual leaders, who had directed them to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can hope that this is the beginning of their political
autonomy and release from the system of being ruled by haughty
rabbis,'' Yirimiyahu Yovel, a philosophy professor at Hebrew
University, wrote in the newspaper Yediot Ahronot on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was pleased, though. It is likely to bring about a
split in a party that some believed was capable of transforming
itself into a genuine force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would we follow like sheep a prime minister who believes
in certain ideas and acts exactly the opposite and confuses
everyone?'' said Slomiansky, a dissenter within the National
Religious Party. ``Sometimes if you keep doing ideological
somersaults you end up on your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kleiner, the head of the Land of Israel front, said his
group, which opposes any territorial concessions, has been left
``an orphan'' by its ideological parent parties _ Likud and the
National Religious Party. ``The Likud and the NRP may have
capitulated, but there's still a constituency for our point of
view,'' he said. ``Maybe it's time for a new party, like when the
Republican Party was established in the United States. We can join
all the small forces on the right _ Tsomet, Moledet, Gesher _ with
Uzi Landau or Benny Begin from the disenchanted Likud.''
</P>
<P>
   In his settlement office, Wallerstein shrugged off the political
calculations. At this point, he said, it probably didn't matter
that much to the settlers whether Netanyahu or Ehud Barak, the
Labor Party leader, was in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we wouldn't have such good access to Barak, but Bibi'' _
Netanyahu's nickname _ ``had an open-door policy and look where it
got us,'' Wallerstein said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he authorized roadblocks, which briefly held up traffic
to and from Palestinian towns, after the agreement was signed so
that his people would have a way to express their frustration. ``It
gives them something to do even if it has no impact on the
government,'' Wallerstein said. ``If you don't give them a
psychological outlet, you cannot control them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallerstein, who is mayor of a group of settlements, said his
response to the Israeli withdrawal will be to expand each of the
settlements under his jurisdiction before the final status talks
that will decide the ultimate fate of the West Bank settlers. He
said he plans to double the number of settlers' houses in the area
from 3,500 to 7,000 by the end of next year. Already, he said,
1,000 new homes have been constructed, and they are selling for
$100,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Wallerstein said he had been doing some soul-searching and had
come to the conclusion that the settlers had alienated their
mainstream supporters, making it easier for Israeli society to
dismiss them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They describe me or my friends as fanatic, right-wing,
religious, with our prayer fringes hanging out, and a Kalashnikov
or Uzi on our shoulder,'' he said. ``And the majority of settlers
are secular and not armed. I think we project an image, like at our
funerals, that turns people away. That's why we lose someone in our
community to terrorism, it's, `Oh, just a settler, never mind.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help us to be a marked group,'' he said. ``I want
to be part of Israeli society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
