<HEADLINE>
MOVING A FRANCHISE? JUST ASK GEORGE YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Young knows about moving franchises. He saw it when the
Colts left Baltimore for Indianapolis. He saw it when the Raiders
relocated to Los Angeles from Oakland, and most recently when the
Cleveland Browns became the Baltimore Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a void, no question about that,'' said Young, the
National Football League's senior vice president of football
operations, who came to the league office after a long career in
the front offices of the Colts, Miami Dolphins, and New York
Giants. ``I felt there was a strong effect when the Colts left, and
I know it has had an effect with the Browns, having to deal with
the Cleveland people.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Patriots have announced they intend to leave Foxborough
for Hartford in 2001. It wouldn't be a dramatic switch, but Young
understands that the fan base is affected by even a local move.
</P>
<P>
   He saw the Giants move from Yankee Stadium in New York across
the Hudson River to the Meadowlands in New Jersey, and he saw the
Jets leave New York's Shea Stadium for the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what it does to the mood of a city or the way
people feel about where they live,'' he said. ``But it changes
things, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said the reaction is strongest after a team is gone. ``You
see how much a city does to get a team back after it leaves,'' he
said. ``You saw it in St. Louis and you saw it Oakland.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Patriots, Young says he knows only what he has read
thus far. ``If it indeed does happen, they'll still be the New
England Patriots,'' he said. ``And I know that Bob Kraft is very
sensitive to the Patriot fans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
