<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCONN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DEAL A BOOST FOR UCONN PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the focus of attention was in Foxborough and Hartford,
Thursday's announcement that the Patriots have reached a tentative
agreement to move into a proposed state-of-the-art stadium in the
Insurance City in 2001 was cause for jubilation in the athletic
offices at the University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Now the plans for UConn football to upgrade from Division 1-AA
to Division 1-A status can move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to wait for the stadium plan to be officially approved
by the state legislature,'' said athletic director Lew Perkins.
``Once that's done, we'll sit down and develop a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider that plan already formed. It's been in the works for
several years as the Huskies have dealt with the delicate issue of
moving from the Atlantic 10 to the Big East in football. They
already belong to the conference in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Like that of the Patriots, UConn's future has been directly
linked to a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for a domed facility in Hartford, which would house both
the basketball and football teams, as well as a proposal for a
stadium on campus, came and went.
</P>
<P>
   So did an automatic time frame in which the Big East would have
been obligated to accept the Huskies as a football member. That
deadline passed Dec. 31, 1997, and while there seems little doubt
that the Big East will accept the Huskies as its ninth member,
there is no guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to formally apply for membership,'' said Big East
senior associate commissioner Tom McElroy. ``Then the presidents of
the football conference will have to vote on it.''
</P>
<P>
   McElroy pointed out that the dynamics of the conference have
changed since last year. The Big East is negotiating with ESPN
about whether the network will exercise an option to continue
televising conference football games through 2000. The league also
has an arrangement with CBS to televise conference games that must
be renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're comfortable with what we're doing and confident that it
will work out as well,'' said Perkins, who must begin to make
scheduling changes in anticipation of the jump to Division 1-A.
</P>
<P>
   Although the stadium is expected to be ready for the Patriots in
the fall of 2001, it will be at least three and possibly four years
after that before UConn can expect to play a full Big East
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it once, when there was an official deadline, when they
had a guaranteed spot,'' said Big East commissioner Mike Tranghese.
``So a lot of it is in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Tranghese says the Big East wants specific details about stadium
accessibility. The conference has dealt with dual use of facilities
in the past. Temple and the Philadelphia Eagles have used Veterans
Stadium for home games, and the University of Miami and the
Dolphins shared the Orange Bowl for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for a new Three Rivers Stadium in Pittsburgh reportedly
include dual usage by the University of Pittsburgh and the
Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the conditions in the Hartford plan is the sharing of
facilities by the Patriots and UConn beyond stadium use. Included
in the agreement is a plan for Patriot personnel's technical
support and facilities to be made available to the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens,'' said Tranghese, ``it's not going to happen
right away. It's my understanding that it's at least a five-year
project.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn's immediate problem is that Big East schools will be
hesitant to schedule the Huskies until they reach Division 1-A
status, since 1-AA victories do not count toward the six-victory
minimum required for bowl eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the bottom line is that if our people want it to get done,
it will,'' said Tranghese. ``There isn't a detail that can't be
worked out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
