<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9975 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HEARINGS-BOS &LR;      11-19 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HEARINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TV, STARR NO STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Today, our witness is Kenneth W. Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   With those words, House Judiciary Committee chairman Henry Hyde
Thursday introduced to a national television audience the
independent counsel whose investigation of President Clinton has
convulsed the country, but who has been seen and heard little on
TV, the medium where lasting identities are forged in the heat of
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   There is an irresistible cultural momentum behind the
proposition that sooner or later, every player in a national
melodrama has to tell his or side of the story on television so the
citizenry can make up its mind. Monica Lewinsky agreed this week to
pour her heart out to Barbara Walters on ABC; Clinton's grand jury
testimony was televised in September; Thursday, it was time for a
Starr turn.
</P>
<P>
   Television can forgive anything but dullness. The Starr who
emerged on the TV screen during a full day of testimony and
question-answering was a rather mild, mostly imperturbable,
far-from-spellbinding figure who probably did little to change the
negative opinion that, polls show, much of the public has of him.
</P>
<P>
   While Starr bore little resemblance to the hot-eyed zealot White
House partisans have depicted him, he displayed little of the
savvily sympathetic TV presence that Clinton showed during his
televised grand-jury appearance, or the star-is-born panache Oliver
North demonstrated during the Iran-contra hearings.
</P>
<P>
   In an ironic similarity to Clinton, Starr tended toward
rambling, legalistic responses to uncomfortable questions about his
own tactics, frustrating the attempts of inquisitors to pin him
down. ``If you didn't do any of the leaking, why don't you just
tell us?'' demanded Representative Barney Frank, Democrat of
Massachusetts, after one circuitous response. Later, when Starr
gave the Clintonesque answer of ``It is not a date certain,'' Frank
shot back: ``I'll take a date ambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Starr's less-than-blockbuster performance on
television would not matter if the impeachment inquiry was strictly
a legal and constitutional matter. As Jeff Greenfield observed
Thursday on CNN, ``insufficient charisma is an odd way to think
about so serious an event.'' Starr is a judge, not a TV
personality. But the reality is that the White House sex scandal
has mushroomed into a combination of legal issues, political
calculations, and public-relations jockeying. Television is often
the key variable in such equations.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has been the prime mover behind the story that
has consumed the media all year, Starr's previous TV appearances
had largely been confined to brief sound bites. For obvious
reasons, he had not joined the TV talk-show parade discussing the
impeachment inquiry. ``We go to court, and not on the talk-show
circuit,'' he said pointedly, adding that he and his prosecutors
``leave the polls to the politicians and the spin doctors.'' Later,
however, his words would be turned against him by Democratic
Representative Zoe Lofgren, who noted, ``This very morning, you
appeared on `Good Morning America.' ''
</P>
<P>
   All day Thursday, the camera's unblinking eye was on him. Starr
the prosecutor became Starr the defendant, as Democrats accused him
of an ``obsession'' with prying into Clinton's private life and
acting as a ``federally paid sex policeman.'' Starr remained
unflappable. In his uninflected tone, he maintained: ``It's about
lying under oath, obstruction of justice, misuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   If this were a prime-time drama like ``The Practice'' or ``Law &AMP;
Order,'' Starr's testimony would have been a pivotal moment that
resolved all lingering questions in explosive fashion. But instead,
it more closely resembled an episode of ``The X-Files,'' another
murky, meandering and inconclusive chapter in a seemingly endless
saga.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Don Aucoin is TV critic for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1915EST &QL; 
