u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUPAIR-SUIT-BOS &LR;      11-19 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUPAIR-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD INFANT'S PARENTS ALLOWED TO SEEK DAMAGES FROM AU PAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The parents of the baby killed by British au pair
Louise Woodward will be allowed to seek punitive damages from
Woodward at a trial that is now scheduled for January.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge Thursday agreed with attorneys for Sunil and
Deborah Eappen that Woodward's 1997 conviction for involuntary
manslaughter entitles them to seek punitive damages, in addition to
compensatory damages, from Woodward in their wrongful death suit.
</P>
<P>
   Adopting the rationale advanced by the Eappens' lawyers, US
District Judge William G. Young agreed that the legal underpinnings
of a manslaughter conviction are equivalent to those alleged in the
civil suit, namely that Woodward engaged in ``willful, wanton, and
reckless conduct'' in shaking eight-month-old Matthew Eappen to
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such conduct is essential to that conviction,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Woodward had argued that the manslaughter conviction
did not encompass such conduct &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After Woodward was convicted of second-degree murder last
November, Middlesex Superior Court Judge Hiller Zobel reduced the
charge to involuntary manslaughter. His action was later upheld by
the state Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court rules that punitive damages are warranted,'''' said
Young. ``But to say they're warranted does not mean that they are
awarded.''
</P>
<P>
   It will now likely be up to a jury to decide how much money to
which the Eappens are entitled. Although Young could decide the
issue without a jury, the Eappens' lawyer, Fredric L. Ellis, has
said he wants a jury and if either side wants one, then a jury will
decide the issue, Young noted.
</P>
<P>
   The judge issued a default in the case in July after Woodward
did not respond to the wrongful death suit filed by the Eappens in
June.
</P>
<P>
   She finally responded to the suit earlier this month after it
was determined that insurance coverage for the agency that placed
her with the Eappens would pay for a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Young denied a request by Woodward's attorney, John P.
Ryan, that he be given four months to conduct discovery in the
case. Ellis objected, saying that the trial was originally
scheduled for last month. He also requested that if Ryan is allowed
to depose the Eappens then he be allowed to depose Woodward, who is
now studying law in London.
</P>
<P>
   Young also warned the attorneys that he doesn't want to see them
on television discussing the case. ``I see no basis for attorneys
appearing on television for any reason...This case is not to be
tried in the press,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1921EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9988 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COACH-ARREST-HNS &LR;      11-19 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COACH-ARREST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUBBOCK POLICE ADMIT `MISTAKEN IDENTITY' IN ARREST OF VIRGINIA
COACHES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Moved in ``a'' and ``s'' categories) 
(Attn: Hampton, Va.) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lubbock, Texas, authorities Thursday admitted the controversial
arrest of two black Virginia college basketball coaches for
attempted theft resulted from ``mistaken identity'' and said no
charges would be filed.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came just hours after officials at Hampton
University _ one of the nation's most prestigious black schools _
confirmed that they had hired former O.J. Simpson defense attorney
Johnnie Cochran to investigate the Monday arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Police action also was criticized Thursday by Houston U.S.
District Judge Vanessa Gilmore, a Hampton graduate and a member of
the university's board of trustees, who called the arrests
``unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lubbock Police Chief Ken Walker expressed regret over the
arrests but insisted they had not been racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe they are guilty,'' he said of the former
suspects. ``We will not refer the case to the district attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Hampton women's basketball coach Patricia Bibbs,
48, her husband, Ezell Bibbs Jr., 46, and assistant basketball
coach Vanetta Robinson Kelso, 36, after a Lubbock woman, Elenita
Hester, reported the women had tried to engage her in a ``pigeon
drop'' scam at a Wal-Mart parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Such schemes, which often target the elderly, generally require
the victim to provide the perpetrators with cash in exchange for a
share in a fictitious found treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Lubbock city spokesman Tony Privett said the decision not to
pursue charges of attempted felony theft was made after police
reviewed security video tapes made at the Wal-Mart Supercenter.
Additionally, he said, Hester, who had positively identified Kelso
as one of the suspects, advised police Wednesday night that she was
no longer certain the coach had been involved in the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Kelso, who is five months pregnant, began vomiting in the police
squad car after her arrest and was taken to a Lubbock hospital for
treatment before joining the Bibbs couple at police headquarters
for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches and Bibbs' husband were in Lubbock with members of
the Hampton, Va., university's women's basketball team for a
Tuesday game against 12th-ranked Texas Tech University. They told
authorities they had stopped at the store to buy supplies for the
team.
</P>
<P>
   The game was canceled after the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   After reports of the coaches' arrests were televised Monday
night, said Assistant District Attorney Clay Abbott, police
received a call from a second person who claimed to have been
victimized by a pigeon drop at another Wal-Mart earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   City spokesman Privett said interviews with that victim did not
incriminate the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Hampton University president William Harvey
criticized Lubbock police for failing to resolve the issue, either
by filing charges or dropping the case. He also complained that no
police reports had been filed.
</P>
<P>
   No one, he said, should be subjected to such ``degradation and
harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey said he had been in communication with Texas Tech
Chancellor John Montford about the case and that Montford had
expressed concern about the arrests. Montford was unavailable for
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Abbott said the second pigeon drop report complicated
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Police records show three officers' reports were filed within 13
hours of police receiving Hester's call.
</P>
<P>
   In the reports, Hester is quoted as saying she was accosted by
an African-American woman as she left the Wal-Mart shortly after 3
p.m. Monday. The woman showed her a purse and asked if she had lost
it.
</P>
<P>
   Hester responded she had not. A second black woman then joined
the group, and together they opened the purse to find an apparent
large sum of money and a note indicating that it had been illegally
obtained.
</P>
<P>
   As the black women suggested that the three of them split the
found money, Hester refused and drove home to summon police.
</P>
<P>
   Had the alleged pigeon drop been completed, police said, the
victim ultimately would have been encouraged to provide ``good
faith'' money until the found currency could be divided. The
thieves then would have vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott admitted that the case might have been difficult to
prosecute because Hester departed before she was asked for money.
</P>
<P>
   Privett said police are continuing to look for suspects in the
two crimes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COACH-ARREST-HNS &LR;      11-19 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COACH-ARREST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUBBOCK POLICE ADMIT `MISTAKEN IDENTITY' IN ARREST OF VIRGINIA
COACHES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Moved in ``a'' and ``s'' categories) 
(Attn: Hampton, Va.) 
 
