<P>
   The coaches and Bibbs' husband were in Lubbock with members of
the Hampton, Va., university's women's basketball team for a
Tuesday game against 12th-ranked Texas Tech University. They told
authorities they had stopped at the store to buy supplies for the
team.
</P>
<P>
   The game was canceled after the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   After reports of the coaches' arrests were televised Monday
night, said Assistant District Attorney Clay Abbott, police
received a call from a second person who claimed to have been
victimized by a pigeon drop at another Wal-Mart earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   City spokesman Privett said interviews with that victim did not
incriminate the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Hampton University president William Harvey
criticized Lubbock police for failing to resolve the issue, either
by filing charges or dropping the case. He also complained that no
police reports had been filed.
</P>
<P>
   No one, he said, should be subjected to such ``degradation and
harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey said he had been in communication with Texas Tech
Chancellor John Montford about the case and that Montford had
expressed concern about the arrests. Montford was unavailable for
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Abbott said the second pigeon drop report complicated
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Police records show three officers' reports were filed within 13
hours of police receiving Hester's call.
</P>
<P>
   In the reports, Hester is quoted as saying she was accosted by
an African-American woman as she left the Wal-Mart shortly after 3
p.m. Monday. The woman showed her a purse and asked if she had lost
it.
</P>
<P>
   Hester responded she had not. A second black woman then joined
the group, and together they opened the purse to find an apparent
large sum of money and a note indicating that it had been illegally
obtained.
</P>
<P>
   As the black women suggested that the three of them split the
found money, Hester refused and drove home to summon police.
</P>
<P>
   Had the alleged pigeon drop been completed, police said, the
victim ultimately would have been encouraged to provide ``good
faith'' money until the found currency could be divided. The
thieves then would have vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott admitted that the case might have been difficult to
prosecute because Hester departed before she was asked for money.
</P>
<P>
   Privett said police are continuing to look for suspects in the
two crimes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
