<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9992 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      11-19 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HAILS JAPAN'S EFFORTS TO SOLVE FISCAL CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Launching &UR;  &LR; a five-day Asian trip, President Clinton
brought a message of hope to Japan about its crucial role in
resolving the Asian financial crisis Thursday, while escaping the
glare of the impeachment hearings back home.
</P>
<P>
   In marked contrast to the tough talk that pundits had expected _
and that Vice President Al Gore delivered at an Asian summit on
Monday _ the president praised Japanese leaders for new efforts to
stimulate the economy and to bail out sick banks, and refrained
from lecturing them on their failings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton specifically lauded Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi for
making ``difficult decisions to overcome your own economic
challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The path back to growth and stability will require your
continued leadership, but we hope to work with you every step of
the way,'' the president said at a banquet in a baroque hall in
Akasaka Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has become a lightning rod for criticism from other Asian
nations in desperate need of a strong economy to lift them out of
recession. Tokyo bristles at the United States, which has berated
Japan publicly, saying it had not adequately addressed its economic
ills. The talks could have been doomed before they began had
Clinton set a harsher tone last night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's style highlights a good cop/bad cop approach to
relations with Asian nations that seems to have emerged within his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   At the Asian Pacific Economic Conference in Kuala Lumpur, Gore
played the hectoring enforcer, admonishing Asian leaders at a
dinner to end ``corruption and cronyism.'' And the US trade
representative, Charlene Barshefsky, accused Japan of trying to
bribe countries to scuttle a trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   But while his deputies talk tough about trade, human rights and
economic reform, aides say that Clinton uses his friendships with
leaders to apply discreet pressure. Even if the message is the
same, Clinton has a more palatable manner that disarmed even the
Chinese when he talked about human rights in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if these contrasting approaches produce
the desired results with Japan. Tokyo is under severe domestic
pressure to protect vested interests at the same time that it faces
a chorus of foreign voices demanding that it reshape its economic
system immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his focus on economic matters, Clinton could not flee
the scandal dogging him at home. In a televised ``town meeting,'' a
polite housewife from Osaka told Clinton she could not forgive her
husband if he had an affair. She asked the president how he
apologized to the First Lady and Chelsea _ and if they forgave him.
</P>
<P>
   Looking somber and pained, Clinton replied, ``Well, I did it in
a direct and straightforward manner and I believe they did, yes.
But that's really a question you could ask them better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   In this courteous society where one would never make a guest
uncomfortable, Clinton's questioner looked embarrassed and bowed
several times. The moderator cut away saying, ``Thank you very
much...Let's change the topic now.''
</P>
<P>
   The town meeting provided an opportunity for Clinton to take his
message of free trade directly to the Japanese public. Such a
format is unknown to Japanese, who are accustomed to stiff,
inaccessible politicians, and one that allows Clinton to exploit
his warmth and political gifts.
</P>
<P>
   As in a similar event in Beijing, where he fielded hostile
questions on human rights, Tibet and the future of Taiwan, Clinton
addressed issues sensitive to the Japanese such as trade
liberalization, the US military presence there, and the risks to
Japan of the closer relations between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
   One man who was worried about American pressure to open Japanese
markets asked Clinton if he owns Japanese products. Clinton replied
that he owns some televisions made in Japan, and that the United
States is fighting protectionist sentiment to keep its markets
open.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's trade surplus with the US grew 32 percent last month
compared to a year earlier, according to the Japanese Finance
Ministry. It will rise even more as Japan exports more automobiles
to the US to offset lost sales in recession-hit Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Questioners were curious about everything from how often Clinton
dines with his wife (whenever they are both in town, or about four
times a week) to his favorite food (chicken enchiladas).
</P>
<P>
   Clinton buoyed a depressed Japanese public last night with more
hope about recovery than their own leaders have given them lately.
Clinton defended Obuchi, saying he has not been in office long
enough yet to effect change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret you have the present economic challenges you have,
but we don't think you should be too pessimistic about the
future,'' Clinton said. ``In the last 50 years, no country has
demonstrated the capacity to change more than Japan...So don't be
discouraged, but do be determined. That would be the advice of a
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials said new tax cuts were being considered that
would significantly increase a $196 billion stimulus package
announced Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
