<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HAVE MIXED REACTION TO TEAM'S POTENTIAL MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ They came back to work Thursday, ready to
talk about whom they would be playing.
</P>
<P>
   No such luck for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The question of the day concerned where they would be playing.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Dolphins visit Foxboro Stadium Monday night for a
crucial AFC East game, but that has been dwarfed by the prospect of
the Patriots leaving Foxboro Stadium for Hartford in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the announcement that owner Bob Kraft has reached
a tentative deal to relocate New England's NFL team to the
Connecticut capital, the general reaction of the players was mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still the Patriots,'' said rookie fullback Chris Floyd.
``Our main goal is to win football games.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd said Kraft's 2001 Space Odyssey was not the primary topic
in the morning meetings. ``The main focus of attention is on
winning a game right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the veterans, who had more of a sense of history
concerning the courtship involved in new stadium proposals, had a
different perspective. ``I'm not sure it's going to make a big
difference to me,'' said offensive tackle Bruce Armstrong. ``I've
got two more years left on my contract. By 2001, who knows where
I'll be?''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong did concede there would be a sense of loss if the
Patriots leave Greater Boston. ``You wonder what it takes to get
things done,'' he said during a lunch break. ``Look around at the
rest of the league. Take Tampa, for example. They're tearing down a
stadium that's better than the one we have now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that no one really takes things seriously until it's
too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the entire situation is an abstract to the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't matter,'' said quarterback Drew Bledsoe.
``Look, this move will have very little effect on a high percentage
on this team. The turnover rate in this league is so high, a large
percentage of guys on this team won't make the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to happen for a few years. So the only real
effect on this team will be answering the questions about it. We'll
deal with that and try to win some games.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said the news did not come as a huge surprise. ``We all
knew at some point something was going to happen,'' he said. ``It
became very obvious it wasn't going to happen here. So here we
go.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is the Patriots will be lame ducks in Foxboro
Stadium for two years, beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   How will the fans react?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an interesting question,'' said Armstrong. ``I'm not
really sure. I think if we're playing well, they'll still support
us. If we aren't, they won't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
