<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HALLMARK EVENING OF FEAR AND FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hallmark has it covered on Sunday, almost like having a
Christmas card and a birthday card in the same envelope.
</P>
<P>
   Its ``Hall of Fame'' franchise checks in for the holiday season
with ``Saint Maybe,'' a warm and typically low-concept movie on
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark Entertainment, the company's separate movie production
wing, goes high-concept on ABC with Christopher Reeve starring in a
remake of Alfred Hitchcock's 1954 thriller ``Rear Window.''
</P>
<P>
   So Hallmark competes with itself. Someone got careless, a
Hallmark spokeswoman explained. It wasn't supposed to happen this
way.
</P>
<P>
   But the real upshot is that viewers are either well served by
two good TV movies or poorly served by the rarity of two decent
movies thrown against each other.
</P>
<P>
   At least they're different, and how.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rear Window'' is the bigger surprise because, (set
ital)goldurnit,(end ital) no one is supposed to improve on the
master. Sure enough, this TV version doesn't improve on the
Hitchcock original. But it doesn't disgrace itself, either.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jeff Bleckner, the new ``Rear Window'' benefits from
lush production values and from a razor script by Eric Overmyer and
Larry Gross.
</P>
<P>
   One or both of the scriptwriters has an especially deft touch
for dialogue. It's smart and sardonic, fitting perfectly with
Reeve's take on the main character, Jason Kemp, an architect who's
a quadriplegic, paralyzed below the neck, as the result of a car
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve plays him as a sophisticated man with a wicked sense of
humor. When a willowy young architect (Daryl Hannah) begins to fall
for him, he tells her, ``I'm damaged goods. Contents broken during
handling and shipping.'' The line is at once sorrowful and barbed.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's Daryl Hannah in, more or less, the role Grace Kelly,
no less, played in the old movie. A more elegant actress, even if
lesser known, would have been better. But it's only a quibble.
</P>
<P>
   The story has been updated. Released from the hospital, Reeve
takes up quarters in a sort of high-tech gulch where brick offices
are topped by lofts.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he becomes what he calls ``Citizen Voyeur,'' spying from
his wheelchair on the loft dwellers across the way.
</P>
<P>
   One is a quarrelsome sculptor (Ritchie Coster) who is cheating
on his alcoholic wife. When suddenly there is no wife, Reeve's
character suspects murder and decides to trip up the killer.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hitchcock movie, Jimmy Stewart played a photographer
mending from a broken leg. This movie has something inherently more
suspenseful going for it; Jason Kemp can defend himself with only
his wits. That difference works to the advantage of the TV movie
until the cat-and-mouse game ends and the killer penetrates Kemp's
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The climax is, alas, a letdown, but not enough to wreck an
exceptionally well-made television movie.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, third billing goes to Robert Forster (``Medium
Cool,'' ``Jackie Brown''), who plays a sympathetic police
detective.
</P>
<P>
   And, 10 points for all who know what actor played the murderer
in the Hitchcock movie. (set ital)Bzzzz.(end ital) Time's up.
Raymond Burr.
</P>
<P>
   I liked ``Rear Window'' well enough to hope, ever so slightly,
that ``Saint Maybe'' would be a dud and the choice would be easy.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Saint Maybe,'' based on the Anne Tyler novel, is another
``Hall of Fame'' example of a life-affirming, cockle-warming movie
you can watch with three hankies and at least half a brain.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a chance to enjoy two delicious actresses. It's fun to
watch Mary-Louise Parker seduce the camera and Blythe Danner merge
gracefully with the camera. Two approaches, two delights.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in North Carolina, the movie begins in the mid-1960s and
dwells upon Ian Bedloe (Thomas McCarthy), a teenager whose older
brother Danny (Jeffrey Nordling) marries a mysterious divorcee
(Parker) with two children. Soon _ too soon, Ian notices _ a third
is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   After a set of tragedies, for which Ian blames himself, the
children are orphaned. And that prompts Ian, at the age of 19, to
make a decision that will alter his life.
</P>
<P>
   The exquisite Danner plays Bee Bedloe, mother of Ian and Danny,
and Edward Herrmann is his solid self as Doug Bedloe, Bee's husband
and the boys' father.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Pressman from a script by Robert Lenski,
``Saint Maybe'' plays like an interesting blend of Anne Tyler and
Frank Capra.
</P>
<P>
   It's quirky, it's partly comedic, it meanders, and it's apt to
end at any time. Or maybe no time at all. Strangely enough, that's
just the type of movie that's been scoring rating points for
Hallmark and CBS.
</P>
<P>
   You won't feel the need to hose yourself off after watching
``Saint Maybe.'' Gosh, could that be why these movies succeed?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
