</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUPAIR-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD INFANT'S PARENTS ALLOWED TO SEEK DAMAGES FROM AU PAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The parents of the baby killed by British au pair
Louise Woodward will be allowed to seek punitive damages from
Woodward at a trial that is now scheduled for January.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge Thursday agreed with attorneys for Sunil and
Deborah Eappen that Woodward's 1997 conviction for involuntary
manslaughter entitles them to seek punitive damages, in addition to
compensatory damages, from Woodward in their wrongful death suit.
</P>
<P>
   Adopting the rationale advanced by the Eappens' lawyers, US
District Judge William G. Young agreed that the legal underpinnings
of a manslaughter conviction are equivalent to those alleged in the
civil suit, namely that Woodward engaged in ``willful, wanton, and
reckless conduct'' in shaking eight-month-old Matthew Eappen to
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such conduct is essential to that conviction,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Woodward had argued that the manslaughter conviction
did not encompass such conduct &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After Woodward was convicted of second-degree murder last
November, Middlesex Superior Court Judge Hiller Zobel reduced the
charge to involuntary manslaughter. His action was later upheld by
the state Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court rules that punitive damages are warranted,'''' said
Young. ``But to say they're warranted does not mean that they are
awarded.''
</P>
<P>
   It will now likely be up to a jury to decide how much money to
which the Eappens are entitled. Although Young could decide the
issue without a jury, the Eappens' lawyer, Fredric L. Ellis, has
said he wants a jury and if either side wants one, then a jury will
decide the issue, Young noted.
</P>
<P>
   The judge issued a default in the case in July after Woodward
did not respond to the wrongful death suit filed by the Eappens in
June.
</P>
<P>
   She finally responded to the suit earlier this month after it
was determined that insurance coverage for the agency that placed
her with the Eappens would pay for a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Young denied a request by Woodward's attorney, John P.
Ryan, that he be given four months to conduct discovery in the
case. Ellis objected, saying that the trial was originally
scheduled for last month. He also requested that if Ryan is allowed
to depose the Eappens then he be allowed to depose Woodward, who is
now studying law in London.
</P>
<P>
   Young also warned the attorneys that he doesn't want to see them
on television discussing the case. ``I see no basis for attorneys
appearing on television for any reason...This case is not to be
tried in the press,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
