<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0026 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      11-19 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONTEST AMONG TITANS, WITH NO SURE OUTCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a brisk November afternoon, the Week of the
Voices came to a close. Presidential consort Monica S. Lewinsky and
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr _ public figures and yet
figures of mystery _ finally have been heard.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Starr, demonized by his opponents as a zealot and
dismissed by the public as a voyeur, spoke for himself in the
solemn setting of a House impeachment hearing. In a tone that was
whispery, at a pace that was measured, in language that was
reasonable, he discussed the most incendiary charges against the
nation's chief executive _ diversion, deception, abuse of power,
misuse of government officials, lies and breach of trust _ in a
simple and powerful way.
</P>
<P>
   And after hours of lawyerly testimony and questioning by
lawmakers, he left the Congress with three sentences that define
the politics and public discussion of the last 10 months _ and the
conundrum the House faces as it races to complete the impeachment
process by year's end:
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's intimate relationship with a subordinate
employee was transformed. It was transformed into an unlawful
effort to thwart the judicial process. This was no longer an issue
of private conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   In a cramped hearing room, beneath 18-foot ceilings and under
the steady glare from an oversized portrait of Watergate hero Peter
J. Rodino, the ancient Constitutional process of impeachment
grinded into operation again Thursday for the first time in 24
years _ and as the gears creaked, it became increasingly clear that
this was a rare moment of awe and suspense in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Not because facts were unearthed. Not because a verdict seemed
near. Not because the strategies were new.
</P>
<P>
   But because in a city where almost every event is scripted,
every remark rehearsed and every outcome planned in advance, no one
involved in perhaps the somberest proceeding contemplated by the
Framers had even the slightest notion of how the Congress is going
to dispose of the yearlong drama of the president and the intern _
and of the Constitutional crisis their furtive friendship and
corridor trysts have prompted.
</P>
<P>
   This was a moment when lawmakers postured and preened, battled
and bickered _ and when it was impossible to suppress the thought
that the principals at the hearing, once so confident of their
roles and their resolve, were watching helplessly as the process
hurled out of their control.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this was no civics set-piece for the ages. For if the
frailty of the human will lies at the heart of the Lewinsky matter,
in 2138 Rayburn House Office Building the frailty of the human
condition was on full display.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most serious thing I've done here,'' said
Representative Bill Jenkins, the Tennessee Republican. ``It gets
beyond serious to somber.''
</P>
<P>
   On television, the proceedings may indeed have seemed grand and
grave. But in the chamber itself, the men and women gathered to
hear Starr and to rule on his findings seemed brittle in the face
of their burden. There was partisan predictability on both sides of
the dais; short speeches displaced sharp questions. And despite the
mountains of documents and evidence at their disposal _ and all of
ours _ almost no one had the stomache to fence about the facts.
</P>
<P>
   This was a day when the key actors seemed to grow smaller by the
hour, overshadowed by their historic mission. All save Starr _ who
may have grown a bit in public estimation with his show of
superhuman unflappability.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most unpopular figures in American life, Starr had
nowhere to go but up. For him, Thursday might have been the best
day of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   What was true of the actors, was also true of the stage they
were on. On television the chamber seemed cavernous, almost like a
coliseum built for the clash of warriors. Inside the wooden doors
the room seemed minute, almost like a small parish basement used
for community meetings where the familiar characters gather to
fight Wal-Mart from building at the interstate exit or to challenge
a saloonkeeper proposing to expand his parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   On television there appeared the tableau that seemed etched for
history: the solemn row of the president's men, the two banks of
lawmakers sitting behind their black nameplates, the kind of
slouches that in any other setting would be cited for bad posture
and bad manners, the elbow of the star witness held at a precise
90-degree angle. But in the hearing room there was no air of
majesty _ just a jumble of paper, a pasta pile of television cables
and a few rows of chairs that gave their occupants _ witnesses to
an interrogation of a witness _ the feel of being in the middle
seat of a transcontinental flight in coach.
</P>
<P>
   All day long the reluctant, the defiant and the ambivalent
battled, and though the day seemed more like a scene from Our Town
than a setting for Constitutional precedent, at the heart of the
proceedings were the perplexing questions of American civic life
that the Lewinsky affair brought to the surface: clashes about the
rights of privacy given to public people; questions about the
relationship between intimate acts and civic performance; disputes
about the responsibility of the most powerful to live by the rules
that apply to the merest; wrangles about whether the president
should set an example _ or be made an example of.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers and the independent counsel talked about the rules
of evidence and the meaning of precedent, but impeachment is a
political process and none of the evidence or precedents speak as
loudly election returns. This month the verdict of the election
returns was unmistakable, and now congressional leaders, working
offstage from the impeachment hearings, are struggling to find a
resolution short of impeaching a president who was elected twice by
the people and supported repeatedly by them in public-opinion
polls.
</P>
<P>
   That very effort exposed the partisan tensions that have never
been far from the surface of the Clinton scandal. The proceedings
opened, in fact, with partisan wrangling over just how they should
be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They decided to do exactly what they decided to do in the
first place,'' said Representative Steven R. Rothman, a Democrat
from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   There were no surprises in the evidence offered, in the
arguments put forward, in the questions asked. The only surprise
was the mien and mettle of Starr himself. He hewed to his prepared
text, but not to the expectations. His report was fiery, but he was
cool. His critics paint him as a man who gallups to conclusions,
but even they were astonished at how slowly he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   So slowly, in fact, that Representative Barney Frank, the
Massachusetts Democrat, calculated that he had time to duck out of
the morning proceedings for a quick work-out in the House Gym.
There he encountered former Representative Sonny Montgomery, a
Mississippi Democrat whose leisurely speaking style is the stuff of
legend. ``I asked him if he was Starr's voice coach,'' Frank said.
``I've never heard a guy from the North talk like a Southern guy
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   And so now the plot enters its final phase. The voters have
spoken. Monica Lewinsky has spoken. Kenneth Starr has spoken. The
nation and history await the verdict of the House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
