<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ADVISORY-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a revised and updated schedule of the New York Times'
package of stories on the impeachment hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Two stories have been eliminated: IMPEACH-WILLEY and
IMPEACH-GOV.
</P>
<P>
   The lede story will move by  &UR; 9:30 p.m. Eastern time &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ Kenneth Starr opened the third
presidential impeachment inquiry in the nation's history Thursday
by charging before a bitterly divided House Judiciary Committee
that President Clinton ``misused his authority and power'' to
impede civil and criminal cases against him. By Alison Mitchell.
(2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   These are the other stories in the package:
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 8 p.m. ET: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLIFFORD (Washington) _ It was one of those accidents of
timing: two events, coinciding by chance, each of which throws the
other into relief. At 10 a.m. on Capitol Hill, Republicans and
Democrats began hearings into possibly impeachable offenses by the
president. At almost the same moment at Washington National
Cathedral, a memorial service began for Clark M. Clifford, friend
and adviser to presidents in a more genteel day. By R.W. Apple Jr.
(1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: How Starr acquits
himself. By Jill Abramson. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CLINTON (Tokyo) _ At a ``town meeting'' on his visit to
Japan, President Clinton is asked whether his wife and daughter
forgive him. By James Bennet. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-VOICES (Houston) _ Waiting for a bus in Denver, walking
along the sidewalk in Coral Gables, sipping a glass of wine at a
sidewalk cafe in Houston, sitting at home sick in Brooklyn, the
sentiment was pretty much the same: Enough already. The spectacle
of Kenneth Starr delivering his testimony, alternately bolstered by
Republicans and hectored by Democrats, did not seem to do much to
change the minds of the testimony-weary members of this particular
out-of-focus group. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MEDIA (Washington) _ How the hearing plays on TV. By
Caryn James. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 8:30 p.m. ET &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-WHITEWATER (Washington) _ A look at what has become of
Whitewater and other subjects of Starr's inquiry. By Don Van Natta.
(1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ The scene on the Hill. By Francis
X. Clines. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCHUMER (Washington) _ As a member of the House
Judiciary Committee and as a senator-elect, Rep. Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y., finds himself in a potentially unique position in the
impeachment inquiry against President Clinton _ prosecutor on one
hand and juror on the other. By James Dao. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 9 p.m. ET &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MEMBERS (Washington) _ It took 60 seconds for civility
to vanish in a whirl of acrimony today as Republicans and Democrats
on the House Judiciary Committee faced President Clinton's accuser
for the first time. ``You are disrupting the continuity of this
meeting with these adversarial ...'' said Rep. Henry J. Hyde, the
committee's chairman, groping for the right word to cap his
sentence. ``We're disrupting a railroad, it seems like, Mr.
Chairman,'' said Rep. Melvin L. Watt, D-N.C. And so it went. By
Eric Schmitt and Lizette Alvarez. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON (Washington) _ Newly annointed as the next
speaker of the House, Robert Livingston has been talking to friends
on the Hill about a desire to have impeachment off the table before
he takes his seat at the head of it. By Katharine Q. Seelye. (700
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
