<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SURPLUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALLER STATE SURPLUS THAN EXPECTED MAY LIMIT BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's campaign promises of $2
billion in property tax cuts plus $1.6 billion in public school
initiatives got a whole lot more difficult to accomplish Thursday
after the Legislative Budget Board said lawmakers would have only
about $2 billion total to fund new programs in 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians have been fantasizing for months about having a
projected $6.3 billion in surplus funds and new money to spend next
session. That figure included a projected budget surplus of $3.7
billion plus additional revenues from a growing economy.
</P>
<P>
   Key state officials still expect to see a surplus when the
budget cycle ends Aug. 31, 1999, and LBB members said economic
growth in 2000-01 would generate $44.6 billion, or $5.3 billion
more than the current budget cycle, in undedicated taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But essentially, because of state constitutional spending caps,
lawmakers are likely to have more money than they can legally
spend.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Rob Junell, D-San Angelo and chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee, said that spending caps, plus projected
growth in required government spending, whittle the amount that
lawmakers will have for discretionary spending to $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This constitutional provision is there for a purpose,'' said
Junell, who also is a member of the budget board. ``This is one of
the few times _ the first time, I guess, since I've been in the
Legislature _ where we're in danger of busting the cap. I think it
shows this provision is doing what it's intended to do and that is,
even if you've got the money you can't go spend it all.''
</P>
<P>
   While the undedicated tax revenues, primarily from sales taxes,
represent about 65 percent of state revenue, most of the other
revenues are earmarked for specific state programs.
</P>
<P>
   Junell's comments came as the LBB began its biennial
budget-writing process by adopting Comptroller John Sharp's
projections that the Texas economy will grow by 13.4 percent in
2000-01.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a bouquet of roses out here, but there are some
thorns on the stems,'' said Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, who chairs the
LBB.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Constitution prohibits deficit spending and limits
increased spending to the same rate as the projected economic
growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   Including the projected surplus in the 2000-01 budget would
exceed the constitutional spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Junell said that $3.3 billion of the $5.3 billion in additional
undedicated tax revenues will be needed to pay for increased public
school enrollment, equalized school funding programs, operating
expenses for new prisons and tuition revenue bonds that will come
due in the next two-year budget cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bush's spokeswoman, Karen Hughes, said the governor
sees no difficulties with the Legislature being able to fund his
economic and education proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush's budget proposal is conservative, responsible and
balanced,'' Hughes said. ``It was designed to fit within the
constitutional spending limit and it does, unlike other
(politicians), who were making promises they could not fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Junell and state Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo and another LBB
member, said they would not rule out the possibility of tax relief,
but the spending cap will make it more difficult to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's lots of variables in here,'' Junell said. ``There's
lots of things you (could) restructure in here. The real issue is
... we're going to have to be clever in how we do (property tax
relief) or we're going to use up all the remaining dollars in doing
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proper question is can you do property tax relief and not
have it affect the constitutional spending limit,'' he added. ``The
answer is `yes,' but I don't know the details. We're going to have
to sit down and figure that out. We're going to have to be a little
more clever and creative than we were last session.''
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said one possibility is using tobacco lawsuit settlement
money to fund some programs, thereby freeing general revenue funds
for other uses. The settlement funds were the result of the state's
lawsuit against tobacco companies for reimbursement for health care
costs to treat smoking-related diseases. They are not subject to
the spending cap because they are not tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Junell, however, said he plans to file legislation to have most
of the tobacco funds placed in a permanent endowment, using the
interest off of the account to fund programs. Since the $17 billion
settlement is to be paid out over 25 years, Junell said it would
take a while for any endowment to produce a large amount of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic that we're still going to be able to accomplish
the initiative that the governor has laid out,'' Bivins said. ``As
you heard, the limitation that we have applies to about 65 percent
or 66 percent of the revenue stream that the state has. There are
other revenues that are not limited'' by the constitutional
spending limit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
