<HEADER>
A0040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     11-19 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES AND FILM SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of new or
noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in New York
City. (Star) denotes a highly recommended film or series. Ratings
and running times are in parentheses. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Playing:
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN HISTORY X,' starring Edward Norton and Edward Furlong.
Directed by Tony Kaye (R, 118 minutes). Flawed but gut-slugging,
renounced by its director yet still a showcase for his effective,
in-your-face style, this story of a neo-Nazi skinhead who develops
a heart of gold presses every possible hot button.
</P>
<P>
   And its toughest images stick even when its lurid
self-aggrandizing, presented in the ersatz poetic idiom of videos
and commercials, spins out of control. In a show of De Niro-like
fury and versatility, Norton plays a savage, racist killer who
learns the error of his ways through simple-minded but brutally
effective plot devices, and trying to protect his younger brother (
Furlong). Hotheaded and sensationalistic, but startlingly tough.
(Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) `BELOVED,' starring Oprah Winfrey, Danny Glover, Thandie
Newton and Kimberly Elise. Directed by Jonathan Demme (R, 172
minutes). A transfixing, deeply felt adaptation of Toni Morrison's
novel, with all the complexity (and occasional opacity) that
entails. Taking on the most enticing yet daunting job of literary
adaptation since ``The English Patient,'' Jonathan Demme succeeds
in bringing the novel's pulse to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Though it begins too slowly and literally, this daring effort
escalates into a gripping, imaginative film that mixes memories of
slavery with the occult and that isn't quite like any other. Its
linchpin, Ms. Winfrey, is more often a person acting than an
intuitive actress. But she plays her character, a onetime slave
literally haunted by her past, with enough presence to hold the
film together. The other major performances are extraordinary,
especially Ms. Newton's in the bizarre title role. (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) `THE CELEBRATION,' directed by Thomas Vinterberg (R, 100
minutes). Working under a set of self-imposed restrictions that are
meant to return filmmaking to a fundamental honesty, this Danish
director shows off dazzling ingenuity. The story of a family
reunion that becomes a psyche-bashing blowout is told with a
hand-held camera, without any special lighting or props or sound,
and the effect is invigorating rather than austere.
</P>
<P>
   Imaginative angles, nimble editing and agile camera work keep
the film spinning as a large Danish cast makes the festivities seem
utterly real. The central drama is Shakespeare for the tell-all
age, as a patriarch is haunted by past sins and vengeful children.
``It is quite a job being toastmaster tonight,'' says one
partygoer, putting it mildly. (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) `THE CRUISE,' starring Timothy (Speed) Levitch. Directed
and produced by Bennett Miller (not rated; 76 minutes). Levitch,
the loquacious subject of Miller's fascinating documentary, is a
Manhattan tour-bus guide who happens also to be a sidewalk
philosopher, improvisatory poet and walking encyclopedia of New
York City history. More than anything, he is a free spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Although he can be irritating at times, Levitch is a true
original, an erudite, intellectual version of a classic
motormouthed New York cabby. As he interweaves his personal story
between spiels about New York City landmarks, the city (beautifully
photographed in black and white) seems to come as alive as the man
describing it. (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) `DANCING AT LUGHNASA,' starring Meryl Streep, Brid
Brennan, Michael Gambon and Kathy Burke. Directed by Pat O'Connor
(PG, 94 minutes). Ms. Streep is grand, as are the other principals
here, in an actors' heyday of a film adapted from Brian Friel's
delicate play. And if O'Connor has lost some of the play's
intensity by opening it up so overwhelmingly, he's also gained a
good deal in the way of lovely Irish scenery and quaint rural
charm.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1936, the story presents a family of five unmarried
sisters on the brink of change and revolves around the return of
their gently eccentric brother from many years' missionary work in
Africa. Rather than major dramatic events, this beguilingly
atmospheric film observes the sea changes that alter these
characters' lives. (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ELIZABETH,' starring Cate Blanchett, Joseph Fiennes, Geoffrey
Rush and Christopher Eccleston. Directed by Shekhar Kapur (R, 124
minutes). In this lurid costume drama depicting Queen Elizabeth I
as a royal rookie, the impressive Ms. Blanchett plays the monarch
as if her principal responsibilities were being bejeweled,
selecting consorts and saying ``Leave us!'' with a wave of the
hand.
</P>
<P>
   For all its putative concern with Roman Catholic-Protestant
strife at the start of Elizabeth's reign, it's historical drama for
those whose idea of history is back issues of Vogue. Intent on
spectacle, complete with burning at the stake and one dance scene
reminiscent of ``Saturday Night Fever,'' it winds up imagining the
queen as a glamorously stressed-out modern woman, afflicted by a
super-intense case of having it all. (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) `GODS AND MONSTERS,' starring Ian McKellen and Brendan
Fraser. Directed by Bill Condon (not rated, 105 minutes). In a
performance that well deserves to be remembered at the end of the
year, McKellen becomes the deliciously urbane James Whale, playing
the gay ``Frankenstein'' director late in life. Shaken by the
aftereffects of a mild stroke, this Whale finds his past coming
back to greet him just as the present offers new fascination, in
the Adonis-like form of the gardener (Fraser, also fine) whom Whale
finds mowing his lawn.
</P>
<P>
   This beautifully acted, witty and heart-tugging film, from a
Christopher Bram book, imagines what Whale's final days may have
been like while shaping a splendid character study and a droll
portrait of closeted gay Hollywood. Lynn Redgrave provides ballast
and comic relief as Whale's perpetually scandalized housekeeper.
(Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) `HAPPINESS,' starring Jane Adams and Dylan Baker.
Directed by Todd Solondz (not rated; 135 minutes). In a much bigger
film than his ``Welcome to the Doll House,'' this audacious,
deadpan filmmaker explores loneliness in his murderously funny
fashion. Outrageous touches _ none more so than its title _ come
easily to ``Happiness,'' and so do the dark secrets that would
surely have brought it an NC-17 rating.
</P>
<P>
   No point in cataloguing this film's perverse details: what
emerges most clearly is a ruthless yet tender portrait of suburban
characters seeking romance, captured with enough acid precision to
make this a ``Bob and Carol and Ted and Alice'' for totally
dysfunctional times. Ms. Adams plays the dartboard in a
three-sister family with hilarious tremulousness. Baker's gutsy
portrayal of a bland-seeming pederast who is also a respected
doctor and a loving father is impossible to forget. (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) `LIFE IS BEAUTIFUL,' directed by and starring Roberto
Benigni (PG-13, 122 minutes). Italy's most antic funnyman dares to
find humor and tenderness in the midst of the Holocaust, and his
risk pays off. This Cannes prize winner is as stubbornly
entertaining as its central character, a Jewish waiter named Guido
who jokes his way through the nightmare for the sake of his loved
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Daring also to combine an opening hour of romance and pranks
with a more somber second act, Benigni avoids all traces of the
maudlin and effectively creates a situation in which comedy is
courage. In this unpretentious, enormously likable film, he shines
as a father whose fibs and hilarious buffoonery know no bounds, and
no fear. (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `LIVING OUT LOUD,' starring Holly Hunter, Danny DeVito and Queen
Latifah. Directed by Richard LaGravenese (R, 102 minutes). Making
his directorial debut, this sensitive screenwriter remains very
much a writer, constructing a talky, introspective character study
laced with flights of musical fantasy. Ms. Hunter stiffly but
passionately plays a newly divorced woman trying to reinvent her
life. DeVito is warmly credible as a lonely elevator man who cares
for her. Queen Latifah is the film's most attention-getting figure,
in the small but glamorous role of a torchy nightclub singer.
Would-be Chekhovian touches abound in this story of lonely people,
but they don't make it jell. (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `MEET JOE BLACK,' starring Brad Pitt, Anthony Hopkins and Claire
Forlani. Directed by Martin Brest (PG-13, 170 minutes). Hopkins
zestily plays a noble tycoon in this otherwise somnolent,
emotion-free, nearly three-hour (!) weepie. And Pitt appears
blankly as Death with blond highlights, serving as a kind of
personal afterlife trainer to the tycoon, whose number is up. Ms.
Forlani plays the big man's beautiful daughter in a story based on
``Death Takes a Holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   In a suffocatingly lavish film that cries out for a trip to the
cutting room, virtually every character is allowed to overstay his
or her welcome, with Pitt especially diminished by the
watching-paint-dry pace. The story drags on so slowly that there's
room for a subplot about party planning, and several scenes
establish how much Death loves peanut butter. (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `PLEASANTVILLE,' starring Tobey Maguire, Reese Witherspoon, Joan
Allen, William H. Macy and Jeff Daniels. Directed by Gary Ross
(PG-13, 116 minutes). This cleverly executed fantasy, with a
back-to-the-future trip into the small-town, squeaky-clean paradise
of a 1950s television show, tends toward the black and white,
visually and otherwise. The missionary zeal with which teen-agers
from the 90s try to awaken benighted 50s types from their slumber
is an attitude that wears thin.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime there are witty tricks integrating color
into black-and-white images, and nice little touches abound. The
cast is both poignant and amusing, with Ms. Allen especially
touching as a prefeminist housewife who's the prime recipient of
'90s hindsight. (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE SIEGE,' starring Denzel Washington, Annette Bening and
Bruce Willis. Directed by Edward Zwick (R, 109 minutes). This
thriller about Arab terrorists in New York City starts out in
crisply efficient style, then evolves into a speechifying
consideration of civil liberties and constitutional rights. The FBI
( Washington, bringing teasing charm to an officious role), the CIA
(Ms. Bening as one brusque Mata Hari) and the military ( Willis,
sneering evilly) all lock horns in a story that eventually sees New
York under martial law. (Inexplicably, the city's mayor doesn't
weigh in about this.)
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay is talky and carefully evenhanded. It's much less
forceful than the film's salacious images of terrorism and Arab
villains. (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) `VELVET GOLDMINE,' starring Ewan McGregor, Jonathan Rhys
Meyers, Christian Bale and Toni Collette. Directed by Todd Haynes
(R, 117 minutes). This dazzlingly surreal film reimagines the
glam-rock 70s as a brave new world of electrifying theatricality
and sexual possibility. And it offers a celestial ``Here's looking
at you, kid'' to the era's British pop flamboyance in general and
to David Bowie's chameleon heyday in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes (``Safe''), a deeply serious yet wildly experimental
stylist, draws on influences from Ken Russell to ``Citizen Kane''
to Fassbinder and winds up telling his neo-psychedelic story the
way operas do: blazing with exquisite yet abstract passions, and
with quite a lot to look at on the side. An interest in its subject
matter isn't a prerequisite for penetrating the nostalgic world of
``Velvet Goldmine,'' but it helps. (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WATERBOY,' starring Adam Sandler, Kathy Bates and Fairuza
Balk. Directed by Frank Coraci (PG-13, 91 minutes). The team behind
``The Wedding Singer'' looks like honorary Farrelly brothers with a
comedy that, like ``There's Something About Mary,'' is both
cheerfully outlandish and genuinely endearing. Sandler plays an
``amazing 31-year-old freshman'' who morphs from ``water
distribution engineer'' to sports hero, and he succeeds in doing to
football whatever he did to golf in ``Happy Gilmore.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot more innocence to his happy-idiot antics here than
there is in many a film made for children. Ms. Bates is a great
hoot as the waterboy's overprotective mama, perfectly in tune with
the film's sneaky sense of fun. (Janet Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   RENE CLAIR IN FRANCE. To celebrate the 100th anniversary of the
birth of the French filmmaker Rene Clair, the Museum of Modern Art
in New York City on Friday begins a retrospective series of 13 of
the 29 films he directed between 1923 and 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Their range extends from his earliest silent films, like the
Dadaist classic ``Entr'acte'' (1924), to his fantastical comedies,
his groundbreaking use of sound in ``Under the Roofs of Paris''
(1930) and post-World War II efforts like ``Man About Town,'' from
1947 (also known as ``Silence Is Golden''), and ``The Grand
Maneuver'' (1955), notable for its use of color.
</P>
<P>
   The series starts at 6 p.m. with a double bill of ``Entr'acte''
and ``Crazy Ray'' (1923), an early science-fiction comedy. At 8,
the feature is ``Man About Town,'' a homage to the early days of
moviemaking. Continuing through Dec. 13 at the museum, 11 West 53rd
Street, Manhattan, the series, with some films only in French, is
free with museum admission: $9.50 for adults, $6.50 for students
and people 65 or older; free for visitors under 16 accompanied by
an adult. Pay what you wish on Fridays from 4:30 to 8:30 p.m.
Information: (212) 708-9400. (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
