<HEADLINE>
TEXANS TO BRING `ALAMO DIARY' TO LONE STAR STATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde needed over n in Pena) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having beaten their competitors in a high-dollar battle to
acquire a controversial memoir detailing the capture of the Alamo,
a pair of native Texans announced through their agent Thursday that
they plan to bring the document back to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are delighted to have the papers and to be able to ensure
that they will be in Texas,'' said Wendy Evans, the New York City
art consultant who represented the buyers at the Wednesday auction
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The buyers _ their names a guarded secret _ paid $350,000 for
the memoir of Jose Enrique de la Pena, a junior officer in Santa
Anna's army during the battle of the Alamo in March 1836.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Texas dropped out of the bidding at $300,000.
The memoir and related documents _ about 700 pages in all _ had
been appraised at $200,000 to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   The memoir, an English translation of which has been published
by Texas A&AMP;M University Press as ``With Santa Anna in Texas: A
Personal Narrative of the Revolution,'' challenges commonly
accepted versions of Davy Crockett's death.
</P>
<P>
   De la Pena reported that Crockett did not die in battle, but,
rather, was among Alamo defenders who were captured and executed.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who said she was hired by the men, in large part, to
ensure their anonymity, said the buyers would publicly announce
their plans for the papers in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if they plan to give or loan them to a university or
library, she responded: ``I know, but I'm not allowed to say.''
</P>
<P>
   For about 20 years, the materials were part of the John Peace
Collection at the University of Texas at San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Peace, a UT regent and rare book collector, bought the documents
in Mexico 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They were put up for sale by Peace's widow, Ruby Peace, and
their son, John Peace III, a San Antonio rare book dealer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
