<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge, Steve Dollar and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Xscape Dfunct?
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Tamika Scott celebrated her 24th birthday Thursday,
word was seeping out that her R&AMP;B quartet, Xscape, has broken up.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta group's third recording, ``Traces of My Lipstick,''
has gone gold. And their current single, ``My Little Secret,'' is
in the top 10 of Billboard's R&AMP;B charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were thinking we might not be back together before we even
put out this album,'' said member Kandi Burruss. Burruss said the
group of five years _ which also included LaTocha Scott and Tameka
Cottle _ has wanted to work on individual projects for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Burruss and Cottle have produced a song for R&AMP;B trio TLC's
upcoming album and have put together a group called Kat. LaTocha
Scott is planning a solo R&AMP;B effort, while her sister Tamika, an
ordained minister at College Park's (Ga.) Christ Miracle Temple,
wants to pursue a gospel career.
</P>
<P>
   Musical billboard
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The city gets a couple of new billboards today,
hawking the virtues of...Yoel Levi?
</P>
<P>
   A grassroots group known as Atlanta for Levi has rented a
billboard above the Landmark Diner on Roswell Road and near
Piedmont Hospital on Peachtree Road to make its point.
</P>
<P>
   A.F.L. members don't want the departing Atlanta Symphony
Orchestra music director to pack his bags just yet. The group is
hoping the outdoor advertisements will encourage more folks to sign
its petition, which already includes more than 21,000 signatures.
</P>
<P>
   The signs state: ``21,286 Music Lovers Want Yoel Levi in
Atlanta. Call 404-223-LEVI. Add Your Name.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizer Gary Rowe told us: ``We feel that the process of
making important decisions about the city's orchestra should
include the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner turns 60
</P>
<P>
   Even though we swore we wouldn't show up and pop out of a cake,
the folks over at Turner Broadcasting Corporate Affairs stayed mum
on their employer's birthday plans Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The only solid word on Ted Turner's 60th birthday celebration:
He planned on a small, quiet gathering.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe we'll buy the ``small'' part...
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe Watch
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tom Wolfe leaves today, and we at Buzz central are
preparing for a bout of postpartum depression.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we've learned that Atlanta architect David McCowen
was the first to get a signed copy of ``A Man in Full'' during the
author's visit.
</P>
<P>
   McCowen, at Hartsfield International Wednesday on business, was
waiting when Wolfe arrived for his Atlanta visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't normally do this kind of thing,'' McCowen explained.
``But I wanted to tell him how much my wife and I had enjoyed it.''
The author cheerfully consented to signing McCowen's book (which
just happened to be stashed inside his briefcase).
</P>
<P>
   Result: McCowen, a book collector, went home with a personalized
signed copy.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe isn't the only person signing copies of the novel. Wolfe
pal Mary Rose Taylor was spotted Thursday autographing a copy of
Wolfe's ``A Man in Full'' for one fan and a dog-eared paperback
copy of ``The Electric Kool-Aid Acid Test'' for another.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was the Atlanta Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau
breakfast for Wolfe and 200 of his closest business acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe's Atlanta schedule today:
</P>
<P>
   11 a.m. _ Signing at Waterstones at Hartsfield International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   1 p.m. _ Boards plane for Miami.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: buzz(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   For more juicy gossip and keen commentary, see what Vixana has
to say on ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
