A0060 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYNC-Q&AMP;A-COX     11-19 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYNC-Q </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &AMP; A-COX &HT;    'N Sync a pop blend with loads of cutes
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents, here's your chance to get in sync with your teenage
daughters. Name the five guys from Orlando who specialize in Spice
Girls pop blended, as best they can, with soul-brother
choreography.
</P>
<P>
   No, not the Backstreet Boys. They're so a minute ago.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking Lance Bass, JC Chasez, Joey Fatone Jr., Chris
Kirkpatrick and Justin Timberlake of 'N Sync, the latest in the
pack of moneymaking pinups doing their best imitation of the 1980s
New Kids on the Block (``The Right Stuff''). The New Kids were
really a more mainstream-digestible imitation of the R&AMP;B group New
Edition. New Edition was admittedly crafted after Motown pioneers
the Jackson Five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which means the formula that's working for 'N Sync is really
nothing new, and kind of simple,'' says Maurice Starr, the Svengali
who put together New Edition and New Kids on the Block and is now
working with the gospel group Five Young Men. ``Appeal to the
hormones. Find an act that the young girls want on their wall, on
their radio, on their video channel, who they'll spend all of their
allowance to see, hear or have a T-shirt with their face on it.
It's really just that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. Tell that to such similarly fashioned ``boy groups'' as
Five, 98 Degrees and Boyzone. Acts that would love to have the 3
million-selling Top 10 debut (`` 'N Sync''), a Christmas album
(``Home for Christmas'') and biography that make 'N Sync pretty
hard to discount.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, let band member Fatone explain what it takes to be
'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm sure you've heard all kinds of descriptions of your
music. How do you describe your music?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hmmm. The 'N Sync sound is . . . the chords are very
intricate. There's a lot of harmonies throughout. And we're not
like many people out there. We can give jazz chords. People who
have an ear for music can really hear what we're doing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In Rolling Stone magazine, your manager said the Backstreet
Boys were like (R and B pioneers) the Temptations and you guys were
the Four Tops. Does that kind of comparison take you aback?
</P>
<P>
   A: Of course people are going to compare us with the Backstreet
Boys. We do basically the same kind of music. And we can't deny
that we both call the same place home. But obviously our individual
personalities make us different. And if people see our shows, we're
high-energy all the time. We basically don't stop moving.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Actually, I meant the comparison to the Four Tops. Kind of
lofty, don't you think, being a new group?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, definitely. Certainly. I mean, we are _ I guess this is
another description _ pop/R&AMP;B.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When was the last time you felt out of sync?
</P>
<P>
   A: This morning. Getting up is still rough. Don't let the group
name fool you. I don't always have it together.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
