A0062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER-COLUMN-COX     11-19 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeve sees hero role as a big step for TV
 &HT;    By Bob Longino and Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Viewers tuning in to watch Christopher Reeve in ABC's plywood
remake of Alfred Hitchcock's ``Rear Window'' (9 p.m. EST Sunday)
will witness a poignant, real-life moment for the disabled actor.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the film's more harrowing scenes, Reeve's ventilator
is made inoperable and he must speak briefly on his own. It is
something the actor has been unable to do since becoming paralyzed
after a 1995 riding accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally when I'm off the ventilator I can breathe but not
speak,'' Reeve says. ``The scene called for me to say a couple of
words. . . . I guess it's a Pavlovian response, but when the script
has me do something I try to rise to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   So, for the first time since his accident, he mustered the
energy to speak while being off his ventilator.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the most exciting moments that I've had,''
Reeve says. And then he recounts a recent birthday party in which
he successfully blew out the candle on a little cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not sound like much to you, but to be able on my own to
blow out a candle is another step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeve's performance in ``Rear Window,'' in which he plays a
character quite different from that of Jimmy Stewart in Hitchcock's
vastly superior original murder mystery, is a big leap forward _
the disabled actor's first return to a starring role (he directed
HBO's ``In the Gloaming.'')
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he spoke with the nation's TV writers by phone in a
mass conference call.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On handling the workload: ``I work an eight-hour day. It was a
26-day shoot and I was never healthier. Much to my surprise, I was
energized by the whole project rather than being exhausted by it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On getting the part: ``ABC bought the rights from two
gentlemen who had bought it from the Hitchcock estate. I believe it
was ABC's idea to use me. I didn't know whether I could do
something like this or not, but ABC went out on a limb.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On how the film differs from Hitchcock's original: ``The main
purpose was to take the basic premise and raise the stakes to show
how somebody in much more difficult circumstances could survive. .
. . (`Rear Window' is) not holy scripture. We're not doing anything
defamatory. . . . In a way Jimmy Stewart was already a voyeur _ he
was a photographer and used to looking at people through a lens.
With my character (a severely injured architect), he's really drawn
to the window out of loneliness. . . . Some people have said that
that's actually more compelling than pure voyeurism.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On what he's learned about acting since the accident: ``I had
to be very economical in what I was doing. And true to what is
happening. The story is a lesson in close-up acting. The approach
is the same _ to be as real and truthful as you can be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On whether portrayals of the disabled are changing:
``Unfortunately, severely disabled people have been cast as a
villain or shown as being very resentful. . . . What is unique
about this is to take someone and have them cast as the hero. I
think people will be surprised how much somebody in my condition
can do. . . . We've had equality for minorities and equality for
women _ and now we need equality for the disabled so they are
brought into the work force and the mainstream of society.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   'Winchell' falls short
</P>
<P>
   Ex-tree! Ex-tree! Read all about it! HBO movie falls back on
oldest cliche in the book, tossing newspapers off a truck and then
showing the front page spinning around!
</P>
<P>
   Back when Geraldo Rivera was just little Jerry Rivers, there was
Walter Winchell, the prototype of the journalist who starts buying
his own puffery. Winchell's career spanned vaudeville, newspapers,
radio and television, and at the peak of his popularity, his radio
addresses and newspaper column, which veered from political
punditry (he saw the menace of Hitler before many Americans) to
Broadway gossip, made him one of the most powerful men in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winchell'' (8 p.m. EST Saturday on HBO), a dramatization of
his life, is so much like the man it even has his fatal flaws: a
self-importance and an inability to see the absurdity and irony of
his descent into hackdom and being a finger-pointing stooge for
Sen. Joseph McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Tucci, one of our most underappreciated actors (his work
on ``Murder One'' was some of the best acting of the '90s), has
Winchell nailed, particularly that telegraph-key radio delivery.
But he's working with minimal help from the script, which lurches
from stock scene to cliche.
</P>
<P>
   Winchell, who died in obscurity but turned out to have a
profound (if debatable) impact on journalism, deserved a biopic
that picked apart what made him tick. HBO, which generally makes
interesting movies, was the outfit to do it. But this isn't it.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Leon takes center stage
</P>
<P>
   CNN turns a spotlight on the Alliance Theater's Kenny Leon on
Sunday's ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time'' (10 p.m. EST). Anchor-reporter
Joie Chen credits Leon with taking the Alliance to ``center stage
in the American theater,'' even though Atlanta is ``a city many
still consider a cultural backwater.''
</P>
<P>
   The segment starts off dramatically, with Leon bellowing, ``I am
the bastard son of Richard Nixon, and I will rule the world!'' in
the current play ``Lonely Planet.'' It also shows him rehearsing
``A Christmas Carol'' and joking about his one vice, golf.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
