<HEADER>
A0066 &Cx1f; tad-z
s w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-FARMER11-20-     11-19 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-FARMER11-20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SMALL COLOMBIAN FARMER REJECTS COCAINE CROP FOR BLACKBERRIES
 &HT;    910 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    For release Saturday, Nov. 21.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When drug traffickers approached Pedro Herrera
about using his small farm in southern Colombia to grow crops from
which cocaine and heroin could be produced, the offer was tempting.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-acre farm, more than 6,000 feet high in the Colombian
Andes, supported the families of Herrera, his three brothers and
their parents. Steep slopes made much of it inaccessible, and even
the fields where Herrera could plant corn, beans and coffee were
marginally productive, having been overfarmed and abandoned by a
previous owner.
</P>
<P>
   A damaging insect, the coffee borer, had reduced output from the
5 acres where he grew coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty and environmental degradation had caused other farmers
to join the Colombian guerilla movement, take up the ``money crop''
cultivation of coca and poppy for drug cartels or simply move to
the cities and look for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got an offer, and so did my brothers, to grow poppies,''
Herrera said. ``As the oldest brother, I called a family meeting.
We decided this would not be good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackberries were part of the reason Herrera and his brothers
were able to resist the temptation of drug money.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the family moved to the farm, Herrera came up with
the idea of growing blackberries and selling them in a nearby
village market. He got seeds from a neighbor who had some growing
in his yard.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the berries have become a flourishing local crop for
Herrera and his neighbors, and plans are under way to export them
to a grocery chain in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   International development agencies, intrigued by Herrera's
initiative, brought him to Washington recently to lecture World
Bank officials on the advantages of involving the poor people in
planning and managing the programs that are established to assist
them.
</P>
<P>
   The International Center for Tropical Agriculture, part of a
worldwide network of research centers supported by the World Bank
and foreign aid agencies in the United States and other countries,
has set up local ``committees'' of farmers like Pedro Herrera to
help direct their own assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments by small Colombian farmers with new corn varieties
have increased production more than 10-fold in some areas. Others
have worked out ways of planting sugar cane or rows of thick
barrier grasses to stop erosion, and others are planting
insect-repelling border plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bottom-up approach,'' said Jose I. Sanz, director of
the center's Hillside Agroecosystems Project. ``Our focus is in
working with the farmers in the improvement of the poorer
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed during his trip to Washington, Herrera said he and
his brothers purchased their farm, about 40 miles from the southern
Colombia city of Cali, 10 years ago with $7,000 of savings and a
$1,000 loan.
</P>
<P>
   A previous owner had plowed furrows up and down the hillsides,
rather than across the slopes, and a lot of topsoil had washed
away, Herrera said. With advice from Sanz and others, Herrera
learned to use no-till farming and composting to rebuild his soil.
</P>
<P>
   As he expanded his blackberry operation, he saved enough money
to buy a 1971 Dodge pickup truck, which he now uses to haul
blackberries for himself and his neighbors to a supermarket chain
in Cali. (During his trip to Washington, Herrera took time to visit
automobile salvage yards, in search of a used carburetor.)
</P>
<P>
   Besides blackberries, the farmers also began marketing a local
fruit, lulo, which is related to tomatoes but sought for its
tangy-sweet juice.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because the farmers cannot afford chemical fertilizers
and pesticides, their fruit qualifies as ``organically grown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we are sitting on a gold mine with people like Pedro
Herrera,'' Sanz said. ``Over 40 percent of the food in Colombia is
produced on these small farms. When the agencies that support us
ask what we are accomplishing, we can point to this model as an
example of something that works and can be replicated.''
</P>
<P>
   The key turned out to be involving hillside farmers in the
planning and management of their own assistance programs. Wary of
outsiders, the farmers had little interest in the ideas of
agricultural researchers hundreds of miles away in Bogota, and
often, those ideas had little relevance to a farmer's needs.
</P>
<P>
   In one example of the new approach, farmers were taught ways to
experiment with new corn varieties and to improve the way they
selected and cared for seed they saved for future crops. This
involved such simple principles as knowing kernels taken from the
middle of an ear of corn make the best seed and that the tops
should be broken out of unusually tall _ and wind-vulnerable _
cornstalks to keep them from pollinating other plants and passing
on undesirable traits.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, yields have increased so that a farmer can expect to
harvest over a ton of corn from a 1-pound packet of seed, compared
with a harvest of about 200 pounds in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera's farm now includes a few cattle, a small flock of
layers and another flock of broilers. He composts his own
fertilizer. He has set aside 6 acres of woodland for watershed
protection.
</P>
<P>
   He said that when he was a small boy, ``we were so poor, I had
to work just to earn money to buy wood so that my mother could cook
our meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very proud to be a farmer,'' he added, ``and I think the
best inheritance I can leave my children is good soil. I would like
for my children to continue giving life to my farm.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
