<HEADER>
A0074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      11-19 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amazon Joins The Film Fray
</P>
<P>
   The Web wars heated up considerably this week among several
leading purveyors of tapes and digital video disks on the Internet.
On Tuesday Amazon.com entered the field, adding videos to its
books, music and other products. The merging of different goods
into a unified shopping source is a trend in so-called E-commerce.
For example, the former Videoserve.com this week became a part of a
diversified operation called Buy.com, which carries merchandise in
five categories.
</P>
<P>
   Defending its specialized field, the movies-only site Reel.com
has opened a ``holiday store,'' with sales pitched to fast and
efficient gift selection.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the Web-site battle is waged with selection, price
and delivery times. Amazon.com opens with 60,000 titles. Prices are
up to 30 percent off suggested retail prices and delivery is
promised usually in one or two days. Buy.com advertises an
inventory of 85,000 videos of all kinds, deep discounts and
delivery within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Reel.com claims the most titles, 100,000, all of them movies.
Prices are discounted roughly 15 percent to 30 percent. Delivery
ranges from one to five days.
</P>
<P>
   All the sites promise to underprice everybody else. Sometimes
discounts exceed 30 percent, and prices change rapidly. Take a hot
new title like ``Armageddon,'' which has a retail price of $26.99.
Amazon.com's price is $15.86, down from $16.09 the day before.
Buy.com lists the film at $15.35, Reel.com at $15.99.
</P>
<P>
   The three sites also prominently advertise digital video disks,
which movie enthusiasts are buying in large numbers. About 2,000
films are on DVD. Another site, Netflix.com, is devoted solely to
DVDs.
</P>
<P>
   Since mail order involves shipping and handling, prices for the
biggest new films are usually lower at Wal-Mart and other mass
merchandisers. But requiring no shelf space, the Internet sites are
particularly useful for stocking enormous numbers of older films
that can't be readily found in video stores. ``That's where they've
really been able to make a dent,'' said John Gaffney, a columnist
for Video Business magazine. ``That's why the studios like them.
That's their strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Buy.com's listings include relatively few particulars about
films. By contrast, Amazon.com and Reel.com offer extensive
editorial services ranging from complete production details,
consumers' and critics' reviews, and myriad other features.
Amazon.com links users to the huge Internet Movie Database, which
the company bought in April, with reams of information on about
120,000 films. Reel.com emphasizes matching movies to personal
interests and helping people identify films they might not be aware
of.
</P>
<P>
   Web companies have been criticized by the rest of the industry
for occasionally offering certain big films for extreme cut-rate
prices to attract buyers to their sites. For example, Reel.com
offered ``Titanic,'' priced at $29.99 retail, for $9.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of pricing alarms standard dealers offering tapes for,
say, slightly below retail. ``The preponderance of the industry is
fighting for $19.99, trying to maintain value,'' Gaffney said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   `DR. DOLITTLE.' Because his father insisted he stop talking to
animals, the doctor (Eddie Murphy) treats only humans. But then he
accidentally injures a dog, which calls him a bonehead, and his
daughter's guinea pig sounds a lot like Chris Rock. In the delicate
position of conversing with animals while maintaining appearances
of normalcy, Dolittle necessarily gives the animals, portrayed by
Rock, Ossie Davis, Albert Brooks and others, the best lines. But
that's fine in Betty Thomas' film, which chalks up its appeal,
Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, in Murphy's ``ability to
play the straight man with hilarious aplomb.'' 1998. FoxNews Corp.
$19.98. 85 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   `CAN'T HARDLY WAIT.' Like most teen-age comedies, this one has
its hot couple (Peter Farinelli and Jennifer Love Hewitt), its nice
guy (Ethan Embry) who has always had a crush on the unattainable
girl and its down-to-earth friend (Lauren Ambrose) who coaches him
through the situation. Set during a wild high school graduation
party, Harry Elfont and Deborah Kaplan's film makes lively use of
stock characters from smug jock to nerdy valedictorian, tossing in
minor figures like the Girl Whose Party It Is (she screams a lot)
and the Reddi Whip Kid. If originality isn't its strong suit, this
movie recalls tenderhearted coming-of-age films from ``American
Graffiti'' onward, ``showing easygoing humor and the wisdom to
borrow well.'' (Janet Maslin) 1998. Columbia Tri-StarSony. $99.36.
101 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `TWENTYFOURSEVEN.' Alternately antic and maudlin, Shane Meadows'
ambitious first feature film is shot handsomely in black and white.
But the contrasts don't necessarily help a story about aimless
urban youth in the English Midlands and a saintly boxing coach
named Darcy (Bob Hoskins) who tries to give them purpose. After
extended scene-setting, the boys are put in the ring by Darcy, who
is something of a loner and a holy man. Railing against drugs and
violence, the coach allows some playful romps, which sometimes seem
out of step with the solemn look of a film that ``is as uneven as
it is inventive.'' (Janet Maslin) 1998. UniversalSeagram $89.98. 96
minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   `THE NEGOTIATOR.' When the police hostage negotiator Danny Roman
(Samuel L. Jackson) is accused of stealing from a disability fund,
he goes crazy like a fox and takes his own hostages in an effort to
clear himself. That leads to a standoff with Chris Sabian (Kevin
Spacey), the only negotiator who can deal with the negotiator.
Directed with brisk momentum by F. Gary Gray, the film suffers from
making its stars such bland nice guys. Flat dialogue doesn't help
either, nor does a script ``that doesn't leave much to the
imagination.'' (Janet Maslin) 1998. WarnerTime Warner. $107.37. 138
minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release or appeared on television:
</P>
<P>
   ``He Makes Me Feel Like Dancin'.'' In 1976, the New York City
Ballet dancer Jacques d'Amboise began exposing New York City
children to dance as one activity that could help keep them off the
streets. Here he takes 1,000 of them, and some New York City police
officers, in hand and trains them for a performance at Madison
Square Garden's Felt Forum. 1984. Fox Lorber. $19.98. 75 minutes.
Release date: Tuesday. Information: (800) 414-1690.
</P>
<P>
   ``Images of Life: Photographs that Changed the World.''
Memorable images from Life magazine chronicle half a century from
victorious Marines raising the American flag on Iwo Jima in World
War II to the student protests during the ill-fated democracy
movement in China's Tiananmen Square. 1996. CBS Video. $14.98. 60
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flesh'' (1968, 89 minutes), ``Trash'' (1970, 109 minutes),
``Women in Revolt'' (1971, 99 minutes), ``Heat'' (100 minutes,
1972). Three of these films by Paul Morrissey in collaboration with
Andy Warhol have been out of distribution for several years, and
the fourth, ``Women in Revolt,'' is on tape for the first time. For
the Warhol initiate, ``Heat,'' with Joe Dallesandro as a hunk whomoves in with an occasional game show contestant, portrayed by
Sylvia Miles, is a comparatively tame introduction. Seedy is the
word for ``Flesh,'' about a street hustler ( Dallesandro) and the
deviants he encounters. Not for the squeamish, ``Trash'' involves
an addict gone impotent and his lady protector (Holly Woodlawn). As
for ``Women in Revolt'' _ well, nymphomania, frigidity and incest
are central themes. . $19.98 each. None are rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
