<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0080 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-     11-19 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS OWNER SIGNS TENTATIVE AGREEMENT WITH CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Under another golden dome 99 miles from Beacon
Hill, an emotional Robert Kraft Thursday signed a tentative
agreement with state officials to move the New England Patriots
football team, its corporate offices and practice facilities to a
new $350 million publicly financed stadium here.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Connecticut Legislature has to approve the
Memorandum of Understanding in a special session before Dec. 31, a
confident Governor John Rowland called the deal a ``turning point
that will propel this state into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   In an austere judiciary room at the state Capitol, Patriots
owner Kraft, with tears in his eyes and pen in hand, signed the
agreement with Rowland. There was a crush of reporters in front of
the two men _ said to have a warm relationship _ and a pack of
giddy legislators and business leaders at their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Having lawmakers smiling behind him was a symbol that did not
escape Kraft, who has sought approval for several stadium deals on
Beacon Hill in Boston over the last few years, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   While there is a sliver of skepticism in the Legislature here
about the extravagant terms of the agreement and some concern that
the state is nearing its financing limit, support is generally
strong and bipartisan, a stark contrast to many other high-profile
redevelopment projects Rowland has attempted to spearhead that were
rejected by the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do it before the end of the year,'' said
Democratic Senate President Pro Tempore Kevin Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, a Republican keenly aware that he did not need another
public embarrassment, negotiated with the Patriots in secret for
several weeks, then quietly lobbied senators and representatives
one on one, winning their casual approval.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for both sides sewed up the deal at about 1:45 a.m.
Thursday. A little more than 12 hours later, the Hartford Courant
issued an extra edition. ``Touchdown!'' its headline screamed.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has placed in an escrow account $2 million he would
forfeit if he negotiates with any other state while the Connecticut
House and Senate debate the measure. But neither Rhode Island nor
Massachusetts voiced interest in making other offers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one more cautious than I am,'' Rowland said at the
announcement. ``But let's seize the moment. Let's make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Kraft: ``I signed an agreement. I'm going to live by it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Connecticut Legislature approves the terms by Dec. 31,
the 30-year lease deal is said to be binding.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kraft conceded that if lawmakers significantly alter
the understanding, the agreement would evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are material changes to the MOU we can't live with,
yes,'' Kraft said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Governor Paul Cellucci, who held a press
conference in New Orleans where he is attending the Republican
Governor's Association conference, said he was troubled his
homestate lawmakers could not compromise on bills that would have
kept the Patriots in their hometown of Foxborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have been able to work it out,'' Cellucci said.
``But I would not have recommended the deal Connecticut was willing
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford deal would require Kraft to pay $50 million to
build, own, and operate a hotel to accompany a planned convention
center. He would also spend another $20 million to build and own an
NFL entertainment theme complex and $5 million for a downtown
wellness center, which would include sports rehabilitation services
with team doctors and an athletic facility open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Connecticut would issue bonds to build a $265 million
68,000-seat open-air stadium with 6,000 premium club seats and
between 125 and 150 luxury boxes. The state would also pay for
another $90 million in infrastructure, parking and transportation
improvements around the site which would also support a proposed
convention center.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is part of a $1 billion downtown revitalization
project known as Adriaen's Landing, which sits along the
Connecticut River at the crossroads of interstates 89 and 91.
</P>
<P>
   The state would pay for any cost overruns associated with time
delays in stadium construction; the team would pay for overruns
associated with design changes, according to Kraft's son, Jonathan.
</P>
<P>
   The 17,000 current season ticket holders are guaranteed first
options to renew at the new facility in the same general location
as their existing seats at Foxboro Stadium, one of the oldest
facilities in the NFL. And instead of aluminum bleachers, every
seat would have a chairback in the Hartford stadium, Kraft said.
</P>
<P>
   The team would share the facility with the University of
Connecticut football team, upgrading its program to Division 1-A.
The Patriots would also provide coaching assistance to the Huskies,
under the terms of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland insists that the deal's 10 percent ticket tax on all
stadium events would primarily cover the debt service on the
football facility. The team also generates nearly $10 million a
year in Bay State taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft would keep all stadium revenue, including valuable
concessions and ticket proceeds, except for UConn or
state-sponsored events. He would receive naming rights, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said resolutely Thursday that he would not relocate
the San Jose Clash soccer team he just purchased, part of the
agreement calls for Kraft to study the feasibility of bringing
professional soccer to the proposed facility.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Revolution soccer team, which plays at Foxboro
Stadium, would remain there, Kraft said, along with concerts.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots and UConn would move to the stadium in late summer
of 2001. A year later, New England would relocate its practice
facilities to Connecticut. The team's summer training camp will
remain in Smithfield, R.I., at least for now, Kraft said.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft said he met with NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue in New
York Wednesday and was told the league would not try to block the
move, nor would another franchise be granted for the region.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Rowland said the young Republican governor
carefully planned his courting of Kraft. First, they say, Rowland
presented himself as the man in charge -- playing off of Kraft's
frustration with Cellucci, who was boxed in by House Speaker Thomas
M. Finneran, who almost single-handedly blocked stadium legislation
on Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Rowland made Kraft believe that he could be part of the
revitalization of Hartford, a city with a boarded up office tower
in Constitution Plaza, as part of a grand civic gesture.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of downtown Thursday, residents expressed a sense
of ennui, having seen the Hartford Whalers hockey team leave the
city and the Patriots flirt with moving there before.
</P>
<P>
   But those inside the Capitol were jubilant, especially Rowland,
who wants the project to be his legacy. Kraft said his wish was not
to sell the team, but to keep it in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland and Kraft hit it off, successfully using each other to
fulfill those goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kraft seems to be someone who wants love and respect. So here
was this funny, attractive governor who says, `Come on over to the
mansion. You can be one of the people to bring this city back. This
is my legacy, and you can be a big part of it,' '' said Christopher
Healy, a Hartford lobbyist and an operative in the Connecticut
Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny part about it is, we've always thought of
Massachusetts as a one-party state where the leaders sit around a
table and do a deal. And here we took a page right out of the
Beacon Hill playbook, and beat them at it,'' Healy said.
</P>
<P>
   When Rowland introduced Kraft at the press conference, the team
owner received hoots and rousing applause from many in the room.
Kraft was clearly taken aback by the reception. His eyes welled
with tears. He looked over at his son, Jonathan, who was also
struggling with his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly bittersweet,'' the elder Kraft said. ``Getting
the greeting here that we got. You really overwhelm me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan later added: ``It's nice to feel wanted. There are some
people who don't believe a football team _ even with a
privately-financed stadium _ is worth having...People put aside
small, parochial issues to get this done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
