<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ATTN: TEXAS EDITORS
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXANS ON JUDICIARY PANEL VARY ON WATERGATE COMPARISONS
 &HT;    500 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Both Texans on the House Judiciary Committee
offered comparisons to the 1974 impeachment proceedings against
President Nixon, but they took predictably divergent tacks Thursday
in their dealings with independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. Lamar Smith of San Antonio quoted Watergate
special counsel Leon Jaworski in giving Starr an opportunity to
bolster his charges that President Clinton abused his executive
privilege. Democratic Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of Houston cited the
unlimited time given Nixon's attorneys to rebut the impeachment
allegations and said Clinton's lawyers were ``bound and gag(ged)''
with their limit of 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With only five minutes allotted to each committee member for
questioning Starr, neither Texan, nor any other representative, was
able to make a rhetorical splash Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee tried twice, in the midst of Starr's testimony, to
stop his references to the Whitewater land deal and other matters
that he has probed during his 4 1/2 years as independent counsel.
None of those other matters, including the firing of the White
House travel office and the collection of FBI background files on
the staff of former President Bush, led to charges of impeachable
offenses by Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this testimony is inappropriate,'' Jackson Lee said as
Starr began to describe his investigations. ``I do not have before
me a referral from Mr. Starr or any of his deputies on the question
of Whitewater, Filegate or Travelgate. ...This testimony is not
germane, and it is a denial of due process.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee was overruled by committee Chairman Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., who reminded her that the impeachment inquiry authorized by
the House had a ``wide-open range.''
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Starr referred to the other investigations to
bolster his contention that Clinton and his lawyers engaged in a
pattern of obstruction, including frivolous claims of executive
privilege on behalf of White House employees.
</P>
<P>
   Smith seized on the alleged abuses of executive privilege,
asserting that Clinton and his lawyers ``knew that their claims of
executive privilege were not legal.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith went on to ask Starr about a passage in Jaworski's book,
``The Right and the Power,'' in which the Watergate prosecutor
described evidence that Nixon conspired with others to commit
perjury, including encouraging false testimony by his aides: ``For
the No. 1 law enforcement officer of the country, it was, in my
opinion, as demeaning an act as could be imagined,'' Jaworski
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Smith then asked Starr, ``Do you think that passage ... has
application to the case at hand?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do,'' Starr said, pausing to say the final judgment belongs
to the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that Mr. Jaworski, were he alive today, would say:
If lying to the American people is grounds for impeachment _ as he
thought it was, I believe _ he would say lying under oath is as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``But again,'' Starr said to the members of the Judiciary
Committee, ``it's your judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
