<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE ASSAILS IMPEACHMENT PROCEEDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House Thursday unleashed a stinging
critique of the House Judiciary Committee's impeachment hearings,
calling them ``bitterly partisan'' and ``profoundly unfair,'' and
the allegations unworthy of spurring a constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton's personal and White House lawyers
traveled to Capitol Hill to watch as he became only the third US
president in history to face impeachment hearings, Clinton was
asleep a continent and many times zones away in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   He slept through most of the daylong hearings, but caught a
snippet of it when he awoke, said Nanda Chitre, a White House
spokeswoman. ``He was watching CNN International and it was
obviously part of their news. He saw a clip on it. That's as much
of it as he saw,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The president, on the start of a five-day trip to Asia focusing
on the world economic crisis, left it to his lawyers to knock down
the case for impeachment laid out by independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr before the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers ridiculed Starr's two-hour opening statement,
describing it as a rehash of the 400-plus-page referral he sent to
Congress in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been more theatrics and partisan than substance or of
historical consequence,'' said White House lawyer and spokesman
James Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He offered no new evidence, no new information, and no new
explanations for his tactics,'' said White House special counsel
Gregory Craig.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process, unfortunately, remains bitterly partisan and, in
our view, profoundly unfair to the president,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's senior adviser Paul Begala said White House aides were
relying on the public to conclude, as they had, that the hearings
were unfair and the allegations surrounding the president's
relationship with former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky
unworthy of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Democrats controlled the Congress and a Republican
president was being investigated, the impeachment proceeding was
remarkable for its bipartisanship,'' Begala said. ``But these
hearings, these preceedings the Republicans have carried on have
been remarkably partisan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would point out that in the past, secret grand jury material
was not released to the press,'' he said. ``In the past, the
president's attorneys had a chance to review allegations and
documents and to cross-examine witnesses. None of that is the case
in these proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   But White House aides made much of the fact that Starr concluded
he found no evidence of wrongdoing by the president in his original
probe of the Whitewater land deal or the White House acquisition of
the FBI files of Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only new thing that he offered is, finally and belatedly,
he cleared the president and the first lady with respect to two of
his investigations,'' Craig said. ``This should have been done
many, many months ago, if not years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The start of the hearings marked another step toward the
impeachment of the president, a step that many White Houses aides
hoped would never happen, but always knew it would. ``I would not
characterize it as a day of dread. Frankly, it doesn't rise to that
level of concern,'' Kennedy said. ``It's a very serious matter, but
it's also been a very partisan matter.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been his modus operandi during the 11 months of the
unfolding Lewinsky scandal, Clinton was far away from Washington
Thursday. It is a familiar story. After testifying via videotape to
the Starr grand jury, leaving for vacation on Martha's Vineyard and
other than a brief return to Washington after the US bombed
Afghanistan and the Sudan staying away with travel to Russia and
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was in Florida for Democratic fundraising on Sept. 9,
the day Starr delivered his referral to Congress. When his
videotaped testimony to the Starr jury was released Sept. 21, he
was in New York addressing the United Nations. And Oct. 2, when the
House Judiciary Committee released a three-book volume of
supplemental material to the Starr report, Clinton was in Cleveland
and Philadelphia raising money for Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   And, just hours before the start of the impeachment hearings he
landed in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a long schedule of his events, and the
president is just doing his job, and that's what he American people
want him to do,'' Kennedy said, explaining Clinton's travels.
</P>
<P>
   Though Clinton slept through the beginning of the hearings, he
was briefed on it through his aides back in Washington, because
aides accompanying him in Tokyo had themselves slept through them.
</P>
<P>
   And even there, he could not get away from the trouble his
relationship with Lewinsky has caused. At a town hall style meeting
Thursday, a Japanese housewife said she would never be able to
forgive her husband for doing what Clinton did with Lewinsky. She
asked the president how did he apologize to Mrs. Clinton and
Chelsea and did they forgive him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I did it in a direct and straightforward manner, and I
believe they did, yes,'' Clinton responded. ``But that's really a
question you could ask them better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the pressures of his job at another point in the
meeting, Clinton offered: ``Of course, sometimes you want to get
away from it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
