<HEADLINE>
EVEN IN JAPAN, LEWINSKY ISSUE DOGS CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Not even in Japan could President Clinton escape a
Monica Lewinsky question.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-something Osaka housewife participating via video in a
nationally televised town hall meeting Thursday with Clinton asked
a question many a spouse on both sides of the world might raise.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of two greeted Clinton politely enough: ``So nice to
meet you, or talk to you. I have a question regarding Miss Monica
Lewinsky. How did you apologize to Mrs. Clinton and Chelsea?''
</P>
<P>
   And she also added her own thoughts: ``And I feel I would never
be able to forgive my husband for doing that, but did they really
forgive you, Mr. President?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared to listen carefully and answer slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I did it in a direct and straightforward manner, and I
believe they did, yes,'' Clinton said, as the studio audience at
the Tokyo Broadcasting Systems laughed aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's really a question you could ask them better than
me,'' he said referring to his wife and daughter. First lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton did not accompany the president on his
five-day tour of Japan, South Korea and Guam. She's in Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   The television host jumped in quickly, ``Let's change the topic
now. Now our bilateral relations is the most important of all ...
''
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky question was the most pointed of the 60-minute
session with Clinton. The first question from the host was whether
Clinton received good grades as a child.
</P>
<P>
   That softball was followed by a question of how involved Clinton
was in raising Chelsea, a request for tips about public speaking
and just how he motivates himself to work so hard.
</P>
<P>
   A businessman also wondered, ``Out of all the dishes that your
wife cooks, what do you like best, and how much do you eat with
your family a month? How many times do you eat with your family a
month?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he and the first lady always have dinner together
when they are both in town. (He did not correct the businessman's
perception that perhaps the first lady, and not the team of White
House chefs, prepares the meals.) Clinton said his favorite food
was chicken enchiladas ``although I like sushi, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
