<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSESS: STARR FAILS TO ELECTRIFY AUDIENCE AT HEARINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-CLIFFORD, IMPEACH-VOICES,
IMPEACH-MEDIA, IMPEACH-WHITEWATER, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-SCHUMER,
IMPEACH-MEMBERS, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON and JAPAN-CLINTON) 
(htv) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr's testimony Thursday had two purposes
_ to restore his once shiny professional reputation and to revive
an impeachment inquiry that has lost momentum. On his reputation,
he probably did himself some good. On impeachment there was little
sign he moved anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, the independent counsel had the opportunity to
redeem the prestige he once enjoyed as a persuasive solicitor
general with sterling legal credentials.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing Thursday, Starr went out of his way to speak in
lawyerly, measured tones. His dignified demeanor, which at times
bordered on the pedantic, recalled the days when he argued the
government's cases before the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   This Ken Starr was strikingly at odds with the caricature the
White House and its allies have drawn of an overzealous,
sex-obsessed prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Until the hearing, Starr had maintained a subdued silence.
``Second to Monica, he's been the unheard voice in all of this,''
said Bradford A. Berenson, a Washington lawyer who is acquainted
with Starr.
</P>
<P>
   According to Berenson and other friends, the prosecutor had been
looking forward to the hearing as a ``liberating'' moment, a chance
to introduce himself to the public and counter what he sees as an
unfair White House campaign to demonize him.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's personal chore of restoring his professional image was
difficult enough, but the goal committee Republicans set for him
was even harder to achieve. They had hoped that his testimony would
provide fresh grounds and new energy to drive the president from
office. In this mission, Starr seems to have failed. His testimony
offered no new evidence of impeachable offenses by Clinton and even
exonerated him on issues that some Republicans had hoped to pursue,
such as the dismissals of White House travel employees and the
allegations of misuse of the FBI files of government employees.
</P>
<P>
   His long-awaited testimony lacked the electric impact of star
witnesses at past congressional hearings. John Dean, Oliver North
and Clarence Thomas, have been able to shape the public mood with
their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike North, who arrived in uniform and talked in macho terms
about ``being the fall guy'' in the Iran-contra scandal, Starr
talked about Nexis searches and his ``primary factual
investigation.'' There were no dramatic phrases, such as Thomas'
memorable accusation during his Supreme Court confirmation hearing
that the Senate was conducting ``a high-tech lynching.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken doesn't talk in sound bites,'' explained Barbara Olson, a
friend and former prosecutor's.
</P>
<P>
   But according to lawyers familiar with his preparation for the
hearing Thursday, Starr had set two goals for his appearance. The
first was to lay out, as clearly and compellingly as possible, the
evidence and factual basis for his legal findings against the
president. The second was to blunt criticisms that his original
impeachment report on the Monica Lewinsky matter, which the
independent counsel sent to Congress on Sept. 9, was too graphic,
too focused on sex.
</P>
<P>
   Starr was at least partly successful. He spent two hours
offering a highly detailed account of the evidence his
investigation has uncovered, shifting the emphasis from sex to
lying. In the Paula Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit, Starr said his
evidence suggested that President Clinton had been deliberately
evasive both in his testimony in the lawsuit and before Starr's
grand jury last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also outlined evidence of stonewalling and evasion in
other branches of his investigation, including the Whitewater
matter and alleged efforts by the president's allies to win the
silence of the former Justice Department official Webster Hubbell
by helping him get lucrative retainers after he was forced to
resign from the Justice Department in disgrace. Last week, Starr
indicted Hubbell for a third time and chairman Henry Hyde has
indicated that his committee will delve further into the Hubbell
matter.
</P>
<P>
   But the evidence Starr recited did not do much to move his case
beyond perjury, and even some Republicans on the Judiciary panel
seemed unpersuaded that the president's unsuccessful citing of
executive privilege or attorney-client privilege amounted to an
abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
