<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0097 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-2NDTAK     11-19 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: of power. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As for introducing himself to the public on a more favorable
note, Starr had nowhere to go but up. He went into the hearing
Thursday with a dim, 18 percent public approval rating, according
to a national poll taken a few days ago by CBS News. In the face of
attacks from the White House and leading Democrats, Starr has
maintained a stoic silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken felt he had to make a deliberate choice, not to engage in
the public debate,'' said Terrence B. Adamson, a Democrat and
lawyer who has been close to Starr for almost 30 years. ``It might
not be the right political decision, but it was the right
professional one.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet at some points during the long day of testimony, Starr,
whose career has been rooted in the decorum of the law, found
himself the unlikely center of a political rumble.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat down to begin his testimony, he was greeted by
Democrats scrapping with Hyde over how much time Clinton's lawyer
should be granted to question the independent counsel. As Democrats
hurled loaded words such as ``railroad'' and ``gagged'' at Hyde,
Starr sat unblinking, looking slightly out of place.
</P>
<P>
   He remained outwardly unruffled as Democratic counsel Abbe
Lowell grilled him about his office's treatment of Ms. Lewinsky,
although sometimes he seemed evasive. He mostly sidestepped a
barrage of questions from Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., over alleged
leaks to the media from the independent counsel's office. Starr
defended the propriety of his office's conduct, remaining utterly
unemotional and offering few specifics, since there is a pending
investigation of leaks being conducted by a federal special master.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Starr called one of Frank's questions unfair.
``You're the expert on unfair questions,'' Frank retorted.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats used the hearing to question both the fairness of
Starr's investigation and of the Judiciary Committee's impeachment
investigation. Zoe Lofgren, D.-Calif., called the impeachment
proceedings ``embarrassing,'' and other Democrats, including
Lowell, pointedly compared the partisan rancor that has
characterized the investigation of Clinton with the Watergate
inquiry, which proceeded with bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the criticisms of Starr raised by Democrats, including
allegations of leaks, collusion with the lawyers for Mrs. Jones,
and rough treatment of Ms. Lewinsky, were not new.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his two-hour opening statement, the
prosecutor, who once considered a bid for the Republican Senate
nomination in Virginia, claimed that he is not suited for the
political high wire. ``I am not a man of polls, public relations or
politics _ which I suppose is obvious at this point,'' he said. ``I
am not experienced in political campaigns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
