<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHOPS-CATHOLICS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOP URGES POLITICAL SOLUTION TO END EMBARGO AGAINST IRAQ 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The outgoing president of the National Conference
of Catholic Bishops urged Thursday that the world find a way to end
the embargo of Iraq and pursue political, not military solutions to
ongoing tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the conference's 280 prelates, Bishop Anthony M.
Pilla of Cleveland said ``fresh efforts are needed to ease and end
the continuing, unmerited suffering of innocent Iraqi civilians
under U.N. sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's actions are the main cause of the current crisis, Pilla
said in a statement to be circulated to the State Department and
other government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has repeatedly attacked its neighbors and its own people,
has relentlessly pursued _ and used _ weapons of mass destruction,
has consistently defied legitimate U.N. resolutions, and has failed
to use available resources to feed the Iraqi people,'' he said.
Iraq should end internal repression, quit threatening Mideast peace
and accept the United Nations' efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest crisis _ ``played out with bombers in the air and
a last-minute response'' _ worries the bishops. While welcoming
Iraq's decision last weekend to accept U.N. inspections and the
United States' suspension of planned air attacks, the bishops
decried the ongoing conflict, reiterating their plea that the
embargo be ``reshaped, reduced and ended quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   They repeatedly have deplored the massive suffering and death of
average Iraqis while trying not to appear politically naive or to
downplay Iraq's role. The conference has issued at least 11 related
statements.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1991 Persian Gulf War, they have been among human
rights groups reporting that hundreds of thousands of Iraqis,
including children and the elderly, have died of disease and
malnutrition. Such suffering results from the blockade to punish
Iraq for not disarming, a move which has prevented food and medical
supplies from getting to ordinary citizens, the bishops have said.
</P>
<P>
   Their Iraq statement is this week's second clear signal the
bishops would retain an influential voice in public policy. Before
closing their fall session Thursday, the prelates decried racism
and passed a major statement asking that elected officials
experience ``a change of heart'' and stop supporting abortion,
euthanasia and physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Targeting elected Catholic leaders, the bishops' plea raises
their profile in the politically charged abortion debate, outlining
their role as moral leaders called to ``persuade, correct and
admonish'' politicians deviating from church teaching. The
statement directs priests, lay people and the bishops themselves to
speak out in voting and other political arenas.
</P>
<P>
   The conference's newly elected president, Bishop Joseph Fiorenza
of Houston, said both Iraq and the abortion debate have moral
dimensions. ``We feel that it's part of our responsibility as
teachers of the gospel to try to apply the values of the gospel to
these situations.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first speech as president, Fiorenza called for the
bishops, top policy-makers for 60 million American Catholics, to be
examples of ``a dynamic and evangelizing church, committed to the
poor, the immigrant and the oppressed and to the elimination of
racial prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks struck a conciliatory, authoritative note,
emphasizing racial justice, a theme of his 14 years leading more
than 1 million Catholics in the Diocese of Galveston-Houston.
Despite differences, the bishops should work as colleagues, always
loyal to the Vatican, he urged.
</P>
<P>
   As the year 2000 nears, reconciliation and outreach must be
primary goals to ``realize the new springtime of Christianity''
envisioned by Pope John Paul II, Fiorenza said. The pope wants
Catholics worldwide to approach the next millennium with repentance
and renewal, adhering to church teaching, but bridging cultural and
religious differences.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
