<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLIFFORD-NYT     11-19 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLIFFORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD WASHINGTON AND NEW, IN STARK RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-VOICES,
IMPEACH-MEDIA, IMPEACH-WHITEWATER, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-SCHUMER,
IMPEACH-MEMBERS, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON and JAPAN-CLINTON) 
 By R.W. APPLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was an accident of timing: two events,
coinciding by merest chance, each of which threw the other into
relief.
</P>
<P>
   A little past 10 o'clock Thursday morning on Capitol Hill, with
snarls of hostility worthy of a jungle clearing, Republicans and
Democrats began hearings into possibly impeachable offenses by
President Clinton _ only the third such proceedings in American
history. The hearings were conducted by the House Judiciary
Committee, but their tone was not always judicious. Members
referred to each other as gentlemen, but their language was not
always gentlemanly.
</P>
<P>
   At almost the same moment at the Washington National Cathedral,
a soprano named Ann Gordon stepped into view and began singing the
soaring hymn ``Amazing Grace.'' It was the opening moment of a
memorial service for Clark Clifford, lawyer and adviser to
presidents in a more genteel era in the capital, when a few wise
men like Clifford discreetly ran the show, though not always
wisely, and bipartisanship in the face of powerful enemies abroad
prevailed more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasts were unmistakable _ between the old, cozy
Washington and the new, noisy Washington, between a Washington
where foreign relations mattered most and one where public
relations preoccupies everyone, between a Washington where
compromise was an art form and one where gridlock is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   In the big hearing room in the Rayburn House Office Building,
named for the late House speaker, Sam Rayburn of Texas, a Clifford
friend of long standing, Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel,
was the protagonist of the impeachment drama. It was rendered
somewhat limp by this month's election results and by the release
on Wednesday evening of his prepared remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Starr cast himself as the moral avenger, the honorable outsider
called in to untangle a web of deceit spun by President Clinton and
his staff.
</P>
<P>
   It is a role that Clifford, for all his acting skills, which
were often praised by professionals, would never have assayed. He
was always Mr. Inside, in fact if not in title, who fixed things
before they became public, before people outside the inner circle
knew that there was anything to fix.
</P>
<P>
   When Clifford came to Washington from St. Louis 53 years ago,
World War II was in its final months. He worked first at the side
of his fellow Missourian, Harry Truman, helping to formulate the
Truman Doctrine, integrate the armed forces and plot the strategy
that led to Truman's memorable upset victory of 1948. He headed the
transition team for President John Kennedy in 1960 and 1961, the
first such group ever assembled. He served as secretary of defense
under President Lyndon Johnson and helped convince him that the
Vietnam War could not be won.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, who delivered one of the tributes to
Clifford, called him ``the single most powerful and effective
catalyst for change'' in the long national debate over Vietnam and
described his success in persuading Johnson to break off the
bombing campaign in North Vietnam as ``one of the great individual
performances in recent American history.''
</P>
<P>
   But all of that came before this city and the nation became
obsessed with round-the-clock radio and television talk shows,
before the culture of investigation flourished here and before
courtliness fled town.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford the lawyer prided himself on his powers of persuasion,
exercised in an office overlooking the White House, far from the
prying eye of the camera. It counted for little whether the person
who needed persuading was a Republican or a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Today cameras wait on the doorstep, and partisan lines are not
only drawn but chiseled. Starr lacks Clifford's persuasive powers.
His speaking style is prissy where Clifford's was magniloquent; his
voice is reedy and sing-song where Clifford's was a deep,
near-hypnotic near-whisper.
</P>
<P>
   That did not much matter, though, because by every indication,
every Republican and every Democrat on the committee had made up
his or her mind long before Starr began to testify. They were not
there to be persuaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington was a different place 50 years ago, smaller in size
but larger in imagination,'' said Sander Vanocur, the broadcaster,
who gave another of the tributes, ``a place where dreams could be
fashioned into reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The quality that defined Clark Clifford and made his fortune,
the carefully projected aura of prudent deliberation, has gone out
of style on Capitol Hill and in Washington. He pondered;
end-of-century Washington shouts.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, ambassador-designate to the United Nations
and co-author of Clifford's memoirs, spoke of another of the
lawyer's qualities _ ``the most absolute self-control and
self-assurance of anyone I have ever met.'' That preternatural calm
survived even his involvement in a banking scandal late in life.
Robert Bennett, Clifford's lawyer at that time, one of Clinton's
now, recalled recently that in more than 200 meetings to discuss
his defense, Clifford ``never spoke in anything but perfect
sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he lived so long _ he died on Oct. 10 at age 91 _
Clifford outlasted many famous friends and colleagues. That and the
lure of the televised Judiciary Committee hearings, which
fascinated the capital if not the nation at large, kept the crowd
relatively small for a memorial to so famous a man. And a few in
Washington stayed away, if truth be told, because they thought
Clifford had acted unethically if not illegally in the Bank of
Credit and Commerce International episode in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But there were plenty of old associates on hand. George Elsey,
who welcomed him to the White House staff in July 1945, was there,
as was Paul Nitze, the Cold War strategist and diplomat, whose
career also began in the Truman administration.
</P>
<P>
   From the Kennedy era, in addition to Edward Kennedy, came Frank
Mankiewicz, Robert Kennedy's spokesman; from the era of Lyndon
Johnson came Lloyd Hand, a member of the White House staff, and
Barry Zorthian, the American spokesman in Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said there could have been no New Frontier without
Clifford. Holbrooke said there would never be another like him.
</P>
<P>
   The cathedral's dean, the Very Rev. Nathan Baxter, began his
homily by remarking that he had been a private in Vietnam when
Clifford was working to change Johnson's mind. Vice President Al
Gore recalled in his, the fourth of the tributes, that he had met
Clifford for the first time at 12, when his father, the late Sen.
Albert Gore Sr., met regularly at the family apartment with
Clifford and others to plot strategy for John Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an age when America became the indispensable nation,'' the
vice president said, ``Clark Clifford became the indispensable
man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
