<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SMOKE-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TOBACCO INDUSTRY LOOKS LONGINGLY BUT IN VAIN AT CHINESE
MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (With CHINA-SMOKE)  
(smw) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As cigarette sales threaten to decline precipitously in the
United States, American tobacco companies are counting on China as
a land of extraordinary potential for growth, business analysts
say. But the American companies' plans are being thwarted by
China's government monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the opportunity for multinational companies is
staggering. ``China is the largest tobacco market in the world,''
said Martin Feldman, a tobacco analyst for Salomon Smith Barney,
who estimated that China accounts for 1.75 trillion of the 5
trillion cigarettes sold annually in the world. That's about a
third of global consumption.
</P>
<P>
   But the government tobacco monopoly, the China National Tobacco
Corp., ``is the most profitable corporation in the world,
accounting for 12 percent of the revenue of the Chinese
government,'' said David J. Adelman, a tobacco analyst for Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. ``It is a highly protected asset that is very
important to the Chinese government.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Adelman said, the tax rate on foreign cigarettes is
230 percent. No more than 40 billion cigarettes, or 2 percent of
those sold in China, come from outside China, according to
analysts' estimates. Of those, most are smuggled into the country,
largely through Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   According to Chinese government estimates, only 500 million
foreign cigarettes are legally sold in China; the most popular
brands are State Express 555, made by the British American Tobacco
Co., and the Marlboro brand of Philip Morris Cos.
</P>
<P>
   That corporation, the world's largest cigarette maker, has a won
permission to grow some tobacco and to produce Marlboros for local
sale. And the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., America's second-largest
producer, has a joint venture with the China National Tobacco Corp.
to produce 2.5 billion cigarettes, including its Winston, Camel and
Salem brands.
</P>
<P>
   But experts see little chance for American companies to expand
their operations soon. These companies ``are hoping for the day
when the government liberalizes the market, but that day could well
be more than five years away,'' Feldman said. ``The government has
shown every indication that it wants to keep industry profits to
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, American companies are spending a relatively small
amount, ``in the tens of millions,'' he said, to market their
products to an upscale Chinese clientele using posters, billboards
and music-event and sports sponsorships, including Marlboro's
support of soccer leagues.
</P>
<P>
   American companies are also putting neon advertising signs in
bars and nightclubs. ``Their strategy is to create awareness of the
foreign brands and create demand for them,'' Adelman said.
</P>
<P>
   These efforts are likely to be aggressively pursued, analysts
say, because American companies' need to enter the Chinese market
is growing, since sales in the United States have been declining
modestly. Feldman caused a something of a stir in the tobacco world
Thursday with a prediction that American sales will fall at least
10 percent in 1999 because of price increases brought about by the
anticipated settlement of more than 20 state lawsuits, at a cost to
the companies of $206 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
