<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-CLINTON-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JAPAN, CLINTON ANSWERS CITIZENS' QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ President Clinton arrived in Japan on Thursday to push
its leaders for a plan to fix their battered economy. But in a
town-hall-style discussion televised nationwide late Thursday
night, he found himself pressed to justify his own policies on
trade, land mines and Iraq _ and to explain how he apologized to
his wife and daughter for his affair with a former intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I would never be able to forgive my husband for doing
that,'' said his brightly smiling questioner, who identified
herself as a housewife and mother of two from Osaka.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's face compressed into a slight frown as the woman,
whose image towered over him on a giant video screen, asked the
question. But he began to smile, if tightly, as he replied that he
had apologized to his family ``in a direct and straightforward
manner,'' and his smile broadened as he added that he believed they
had forgiven him.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, still a giant presence via a live video hookup from
Osaka, smiled even more brightly and repeatedly bowed as the
president answered. ``Let's change the topic now,'' the moderator
suggested briskly.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides insisted that the president had expected such
a question and was not distressed by it. But coming just hours
before the House Judiciary Committee was to open its impeachment
inquiry, the extraordinary moment in video diplomacy suggested that
interest in his predicament remains more widespread than the White
House likes to argue.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, reporters who cover the White House and not residents
of the country the president is visiting raise such matters on
trips abroad, and the president's aides dismiss their inquiries as
irrelevant to the concerns of ``real people.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, noted that only
one of the 24 questions during the hourlong program dealt with the
scandal. ``You can twist this any way you want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the name Monica Lewinsky crashed like an unmoored klieg
light into the television studio, the president handled queries
about whether he got good grades at school (``mostly''), why he
could speak so easily before large audiences (``the microphone is
your friend'') and how he coped with pressure (``a balanced
life'').
</P>
<P>
   He adroitly navigated an inquiry about his favorite meal among
``the dishes that your wife cooks,'' by saying that he adored
chicken enchiladas, without specifying a chef. ``I like sushi
too,'' he added, sensitive as ever to his immediate constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Seated on a tall, swiveling stool, Clinton taped the forum
Thursday evening, for broadcast Thursday night. He was encircled by
an audience of about 90 people, identified as housewives,
professionals, university students, small-business owners and
others. A few dozen more people participated from Osaka.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said that the network, Tokyo Broadcasting
Systems, picked the audience and the questions, some of which were
read by the moderator from faxes and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who met with Japan's Emperor Akihito and Empress
Michiko on Thursday afternoon before a dinner in his honor at
night, hoped to use the forum to explain directly to the Japanese
people why he is urging their government to open its markets and
stimulate consumer demand, administration officials said. Seven of
the questions gave him a chance to do that.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton noted the rising U.S. trade deficit with Japan, he
seemed to suggest that some Japanese industries were engaging in
dumping, the illegal trade practice of selling goods in foreign
markets at prices below cost. He pointed out that U.S. imports of
Japanese hot-rolled steel had increased fivefold over the last
year. ``No one quite believes that that's just because of the
economic problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts at an economic conference in Malaysia last weekend to
further liberalize trade foundered on Japan's insistence on
protecting its fishing and timber industries. On Thursday night,
Clinton did not specifically address those negotiations. But he
said that United States had discovered that it had increased jobs
by deregulating its airline and telecommunications industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say I never consciously asked Japan or any other
country to do something that is good only for the United States,''
he said. ``My belief is that our country is strengthened if Japan
is very strong, because if Japan is very strong, that brings back
Asia.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One man, who identified himself as a farmer raising rice and
flowers, lectured Clinton on the dangers of free trade to the
Japanese family farm, arguing that it did not take into account
``culture and social values and human values.'' Such family
farming, he said, ``is losing, losing out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gently pointing out that family farms in North Dakota were
suffering because Asian countries could no longer afford their
wheat, Clinton argued that governments could find ways to help such
farmers. ``In my country,'' he said, ``we have tried to push for
more open markets and a policy to keep family farmers in
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton found himself in the unexpected position of defending
the government of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi against a questioner
who said the Japanese leadership ``is not as good as we would like
it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said that ``the big things that have been done
here are essentially moving in the right direction,'' citing
banking reforms and fiscal stimulus. Give it time, he said, in an
argument that Japanese officials have tried unsuccessfully on the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in brief closing remarks, Clinton urged the Japanese to
be optimistic, because ``these things run in waves over time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind, 10 years ago a lot of people said America's best
days were behind it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president was also asked why, given his stated opposition to
land mines, the United States had not signed an international
treaty banning them. Clinton said that the treaty unfairly banned
U.S. anti-tank mines while permitting those of other nations, and
that it would interfere with the defense of South Korea. Somewhat
indignantly, he said, ``Let me assure you all: I was the first
world leader to call for a ban on land mines.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how many Iraqis would have died if Clinton had proceeded
with the assault planned for last weekend, he said that ``large
numbers'' would have been killed. He said he was pleased that an
attack proved unnecessary. ``Peace is always better than war,'' he
said, ``if you can do it consistent with the long-term security and
freedom of the people. So I feel good about that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton is to speak to American business leaders and
meet with the prime minister before going to South Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
