<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-FINNERAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINNERAN STICKS TO HIS GUNS IN PATRIOTS STAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Boston sports world may have demonized him and the
sports talk show hosts are all but calling for his public hanging,
but House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran Thursday was not backing down.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting the media frenzy head-on, Finneran made no apologies to
his critics' charge that his uncompromsing stance on a Foxborough
stadium package for Patriot's owner Robert Kraft drove the football
franchise out of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Finneran laid the blame on Kraft and what he said is
the owner's decision to snub fan loyalty in his pursuit of greater
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought all along there would be some reciprocity of
loyality,'' Finneran told reporters just after Kraft appeared at
the Hartford press conference to sign an agreement with Connecticut
officials. ``In this case, it looks as if the Patriots decision is
to go with the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran did concede that he is concerned that Kraft's decision
hurts the state's reputation as business-friendly but he brushed
aside suggestions that the loss of the franchise would cost the
state serious prestige.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a legitimate concern,'' Finneran said of the immediate
economic impact. ``But I am more concerned about the psychological
impact on the economy. This runs contrary to everything we have
worked to do over the past 7 and 8 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The House leader also all but closed the door on going back to
the bargaining table. In fact, he said any effort to accommodate
Kraft now would be to succumb to blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you begin to do that quite clearly you have sent a signal
-- that the Massachusetts House at least can be highjacked and can
be bullied and will flinch in the face of economic bullying and
economic pressure,'' Finneran said.
</P>
<P>
   On television live-shots and interviews with reporters, Finneran
again hit on his themes that the players' salaries and the
``irrational economic'' decisions by franchise owners like Kraft
were at fault in this case, not his or his House colleagues'
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said the taxpayers are not going to be a no-cost bank
for any individual or any business, particularly a profitable
business,'' Finneran said. ``The taxpayers of Massachusetts don't
get help when the roof on their house has to be replaced or the
boiler or the furnace goes.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Finneran tried to paint himself as the defender of
sport fans who he said are facing huge hikes in ticket prices to
pay the mega-salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been priced out and they're dismayed at the salaries
that owners are paying and now someone has made the connection for
them,'' Finneran said.
</P>
<P>
   But still it was clear Finneran was standing alone Thursday amid
the rubble of the Patriot's franchise, while other Beacon Hill
leaders were not shy about laying the blame on him for costing
Boston the lose of a football franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always understood where he's coming from,'' said Senate
President Thomas F. Birmingham, who has worked closely for nearly
eight years with Finneran on thorny fiscal and policy issues. ``But
I honestly do not understand this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
