<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0110 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-VOICES-NYT &LR;      11-19 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-VOICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS PAY LITTLE ATTENTION TO STARR TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-CLIFFORD, IMPEACH-ASSESS,
IMPEACH-MEDIA, IMPEACH-WHITEWATER, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-SCHUMER,
IMPEACH-MEMBERS, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON and JAPAN-CLINTON) 
(JT) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Glenn Cartwright stood before the cash register with
his lips pursed, unable to decide between a Lightning Hopkins and a
Clifton Chenier C.D., but he was certain of one thing: When he got
home, he was not going to turn the House Judiciary Committee's
impeachment hearing back on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched it for a while this morning, but it was all the same
stuff we'd heard before,'' said Cartwright, a 27-year-old Houston
graduate student. ``It was like a remake of a movie you didn't like
in the first place. I'd rather watch an infomercial about a new
mop.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was because the hearing took place on a weekday, when
the children were in school and most of the country was going about
its hectic business. Perhaps it was because it was intruding into
the realm of afternoon talk shows and soap operas. But there were
further signs today that the long-running Monica Lewinsky
television series was continuing to lose its grip on the American
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just bored with the whole thing,'' said Deborah Shely, a
35-year-old legal secretary in Miami. ``I just think it should be
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Kirby, a banker, said that he had missed the opening of
the hearing because he had been on an airplane to Miami and that it
did not come up at all when he and several colleagues had lunch
together. ``I think the public has lost interest,'' Kirby said.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for a bus in Denver, walking along the sidewalk in Coral
Gables, stuck in traffic on a Los Angeles freeway, sipping a glass
of wine at a sidewalk cafe in Houston, sitting at home sick in
Brooklyn, people voiced sentiments that were pretty much the same:
Enough already.
</P>
<P>
   And the spectacle of Kenneth Starr's delivering his testimony,
alternately bolstered by Republicans on the committee and hectored
by Democrats, did not seem to do much to change the minds of the
testimony-weary members of this particular out-of-focus group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested,'' said Linda Holmquist, 58, of Hollywood.
``I have a life.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people who had already come to the conclusion that
President Clinton should be impeached said Starr's arguments had
only strengthened that opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked Ken Starr, I liked his demeanor,'' said Sean Elias, a
22-year-old business student at the University of Miami. ``He's
just trying to do his job. He doesn't have anything against the
president personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who had already put Starr in the role of the villain also
found their judgment reinforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's slimy,'' said Kerry Hardin, 39, of La Crescenta, Calif.
``He definitely has an agenda. He's out to get the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, however, said they had been pleasantly surprised by the
reasoned tone and apparent thoroughness of Starr's testimony. But
just as many said they had not even bothered to watch, having made
a conscious decision to tune the whole thing out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really take too much interest in the president's
personal life,'' said Vanessa Creech, a 27-year-old computer
technician in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   That apathy extended even to those convinced of presidential
wrongdoing. ``The fact that he lied is most bothersome to me,'' Ms.
Creech said.
</P>
<P>
   The judgment of Norm Chiles, a 62-year-old Denver office
manager, was even harsher. ``He's been a disgrace to the office of
president,'' Chiles said. ``I was watching the Veterans Day parade
last week, and I'm ashamed of him. Sure, the economy is going, but
him and Nixon are both a disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Campbell was trying to read the headlines through the
window in a downtown Denver newspaper box while on a break from her
job as a federal administrative assistant. ``I'm following the
hearings on the radio at my office, but I'm against them,'' she
said. ``I don't think he needs to be impeached. My 21-year-old
daughter agrees with me. She said, `Let it go, and let him finish
his term.' My fourth grader asks, `Why are they mean to the
president?' I mean, he did do something wrong, but don't leave it
hanging out there until the end of his term.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Catanzaro, 29, was at home sick in Brooklyn and had the
hearings turned on. ``It's my one day off,'' she said, ``and I
can't watch my soap operas because of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The network she chose, ABC, was broadcasting the hearing live
while running, underneath, a written synopsis of what had been said
earlier. It reminded her of watching a foreign film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The content of the inquiry is totally partisan,'' said Marie
Lovrod, a 38-year-old adjunct professor of women's studies at
Hunter College in New York, who was home sick, too. ``I wanted to
watch the opening, but then Starr started repeating himself. I'm
sick of hearing the same details over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise McKinney, a 26-year-old legal assistant on a coffee break
at a subterranean cafe in the network of tunnels beneath downtown
Houston, said she found the whole exercise a waste of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel he's just wasting our time trying to impeach this
man,'' she said of Starr. ``Clinton's not married to the whole
United States, so he doesn't have to answer to us for what he does.
He has to answer to his wife. So as long as he's running the
country, fine, I don't have anything against him. I do think what
he did was wrong, but I don't think it's grounds for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a few people continued to try to follow the plot, hoping
for an epiphany or at least some sense of clarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of want to see if this all begins to make sense, if it
validates all the time and attention given to this by the
independent prosecutor,'' said Steve Haggerty, 32, of Brooklyn.
``If they can prove abuse of power, then let them do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
