<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLAN-FREE-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KLAN CASE, RACE IS AN ISSUE ON EVERY LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two men could not be more different _ racially,
politically, philosophically. Yet Barry Elton Black, a white member
of the Ku Klux Klan, and David Baugh, the black lawyer who is
defending him in a Virginia court, are united these days in a
defense over what they see as the constitutional right of free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh, a Richmond lawyer who volunteered to take the case for
the American Civil Liberties Union after Black contacted the group,
is arguing that a Virginia law making it illegal to burn a cross
abridges Black's First Amendment right to express his views _ no
matter how racist those views may be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government can gag Mr. Black, they can gag the Jewish
Defense League or the Knights of Columbus,'' Baugh said in a
telephone interview. ``If you can gag one group, you can gag
another.''
</P>
<P>
   The case has drawn attention, not only because of the
constitutional questions it raises, but also because of the irony
of an African-American's defending a white supremacist who, if he
had his way, would oppress his lawyer because of his race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unusual case and has unusual aspects all the way
around,'' said Gregory Goad, the district attorney for Carroll
County, Va., who is prosecuting Black for burning a cross at a
demonstration in August.
</P>
<P>
   Although Baugh believes the case is about bedrock principle,
that does not mean he harbors no doubts. In the interview, he
fretted that the incongruity of a black lawyer's defending a
Klansman was drawing public and media attention away from the
case's First Amendment issues, and he wondered whether it would be
better for him to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even as he spoke of his concerns, Baugh seemed to talk
himself back into believing that his race allowed more of a
discussion of the legal issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reconvincing myself that this is a positive thing because
it gets people talking about the Constitution,'' he said. ``If a
white lawyer from a local jurisdiction were to take this case he
would be the subject of all sorts of questions about `Now we know
how old Charlie really feels about things.' With me, there are no
questions about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Black is charged with violating a state law passed in the 1930s
as part of a package of statutes to curb Klan activity. The statute
makes it illegal for anyone with the ``intent of intimidating''
another to burn a cross on another person's property or on a
highway or in a public place, which includes private property that
can be viewed by the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the public-place issue that we're defending here,'' said
Kent Willis, executive director of the Virginia ACLU ``We're not
defending the right to burn a cross on somebody else's property.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a preliminary hearing last Friday, Judge Edward Turner
III of the General District Court in Hillsville, Va., rejected a
defense motion that the state cross-burning law was
unconstitutional. Turner ruled that because the statute covered
conduct and not speech it did not violate the First Amendment. He
then found there was probable cause to refer Black's case to a
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Black, a leader of a branch of the Klan in Pennsylvania, was
arrested on Aug. 22 after a rally in rural Carroll County, about 60
miles southwest of Roanoke, near the North Carolina border. Though
the owner of the property had given the Klan permission to hold the
rally on his land, testimony at Friday's hearing indicated that the
burning cross was about 30 feet tall and was clearly visible from a
state highway.
</P>
<P>
   Local law-enforcement officers testified that the sight of the
burning cross caused a car with black occupants to flee the area
and some white local residents to seek protection from sheriff's
deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh, a director on the Virginia ACLU board, has a history of
taking cases involving First Amendment issues. He defended a
Vietnamese owner of a small video outlet in Prince William County,
Va., who was arrested for renting adult videos. He also defended a
county fair in Shenandoah County that included a tent featuring
nude dancing. Baugh won both cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``David is not only an adamant defender of free speech,'' Willis
said, ``he is an adamant practitioner of free speech. He has had
more than one contempt citation because of things he has said to
judges.''
</P>
<P>
   Baugh's efforts on behalf of a Klansman engaged in cross burning
have split opinion among some blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Salim Khalfani, acting executive director of the Virginia State
Conference of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, said: ``We think it's really an aberration for a
person of African descent to represent a Ku Klux Klan person, in
particular for burning a cross, which we don't consider a
free-speech issue. This is an act that has been used historically
to terrorize and intimidate African people. So I don't see it in
the light of the First Amendment. This is bigger than the First
Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Julian Bond, chairman of the board of the NAACP, said he
disagreed with Khalfani's contention. ``The First Amendment defense
this guy is mounting ought to be precious to all black Americans,''
he said in an interview. ``These are precisely the defenses that we
have used and will use to advance our cause.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little question that for blacks, Black presents an
odious figure to rally around.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials testified Friday that after he was
arrested, Black asked a police officer, ``When is the white man
going to stand up to the blacks and the Mexicans in this
neighborhood?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
