<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-43     11-19 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVINGSTON HOPES INQUIRY WILL END BEFORE DEC. 31 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-CLIFFORD, IMPEACH-ASSESS,
IMPEACH-VOICES, IMPEACH-MEDIA, IMPEACH-WHITEWATER, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-SCHUMER, IMPEACH-MEMBERS, and JAPAN-CLINTON) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bob Livingston, the presumptive speaker of the
House, said Thursday that he wants the impeachment inquiry into
President Clinton to be over by the end of the year _ before he
actually becomes speaker.
</P>
<P>
   But Livingston, who previously had been cautious and equivocal
in his comments on the impeachment proceedings and what he would
like to see happen, also said that it will be difficult to wrap
things up as long as Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr keeps
``shoveling'' information to Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Ken Starr still shoveling stuff over to him, it makes it
very difficult for any investigation to be complete if you haven't
gotten all the information,'' Livingston, a former federal
prosecutor himself, said in a brief interview. ``I want a fair and
full appraisal. That being said, if it could be done this year,
that'd be my preference. But I don't know that it could be done.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments, coming a day after he was officially nominated by
House Republicans as the next speaker and as Hyde conducted
impeachment hearings in an adjacent office building, offered the
first hint of his impatience with the process.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hyde said Thursday that he, too, hopes to end the
impeachment inquiry by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me repeat my New Year's resolution: It is my fervent hope
that we will be able to conclude this inquiry before the New Year
turns,'' Hyde said after gaveling Thursday's hearing to order. ``I
am hopeful that all members will bear that in mind as we conduct
this search for the truth with all deliberate speed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde has called additional witnesses. And with only three
full work weeks remaining in the legislative year, someone would
have to make a decision soon if Republicans want to end the process
by Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment is technically not Livingston's responsibility until
he steps into the speaker's chair on Jan. 6. And some of his
political allies say they hope it never becomes his responsibility,
so that Livingston can begin his tenure without being weighted down
by the issue, which some blame for the Republicans' poor showing in
this year's midterm elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we can be certain of is that Bob wants to get on
with his agenda,'' said Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., who is one of
Livingston's closest colleagues in the House.
</P>
<P>
   But Newt Gingrich, the current speaker, has left town on
vacation, and many in Washington are starting to turn to Livingston
for a sign on which way he wants to go and whether the curtain
might drop soon on this long-running drama.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt met with Livingston on
Monday to discuss reorganization of the House and briefly talked
about wrapping up the impeachment procedings, according to Laura
Nichols, a Gephardt aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some agreement that once we got passed these
leadership elections and these initial hearings today and tomorrow
that maybe we could have a further conversation,'' Ms. Nichols
said. ``It's important and significant that both leaders agree on
the timetable for getting this wrapped up by the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said: ``Different sets of people are
exploring a way out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston has acknowledged that the public does not see
Clinton's behavior as impeachable. But nor has he closed the door
on some sort of punishment. ``The president still has to answer to
the American people for the charges,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the House also want the process finished by the end of
the year, not because it has become an embarrassment but because
they worry that the chances of punishing the president are better
with the current Congress than with the next one. Republicans now
outnumber Democrats, 228-206. Next year their advantage will
shrink, with 223 Republicans and 211 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if the House votes out any articles of impeachment,
the Senate does not appear inclined to convict the president. And
already, several House Republicans have started to indicate that
they would vote against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   This complicates the picture for Livingston. But he insisted
Thursday that he had not flagged any signals to Hyde, denying in
particular a report that Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., had conveyed
a message from him to Hyde to kill the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of false reports going on,'' Livingston said.
``I sympathize with my friend Newt _ all of a sudden there are
reports of stuff that never happened. I have never talked to David
Dreier about meeting with Henry Hyde. I don't know anything about
that report.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Dreier, the incoming chairman of the Rules
Committee, said that the congressman wanted the House to end the
inquiry quickly but that he had not acted as a conduit or messenger
for Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston has generally refrained from moralizing about the
president, providing a sharp contrast to Gingrich, who at one point
said that Republicans should condemn the president's behavior in
every speech and poured millions of dollars into reviving the
matter in commercials just before the Nov. 3 elections.
</P>
<P>
   But a week ago, Livingston did convey some outrage about
Clinton. ``The president of the United States has a responsibility
to the American people to live by the laws, to obey the laws,'' he
said on the Imus radio program.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if it's proven that he did not, he's either going to have
to be dealt with or he should voluntarily recognize that he's got a
problem,'' he said. ``So far, I haven't heard any singular
recognition of his problem. So we'll just have to let the processes
move forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
