<SLUG> BC-BBN-MVP-SOSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SURPISE IN SOSA'S SELECTION AS MVP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, it can be said. Sammy Sosa is ``The Man.'' Mark McGwire
may be baseball's home run king. But the Chicago Cubs star is
officially the Most Valuable Player in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Few would argue with the choice made Thursday by all but two
members of the 32 voters from the Baseball Writers Association of
America. Sosa, who lost the home run derby to the St. Louis
slugger, was first or second on every ballot and amassed 438
points. McGwire, who shattered Rogere Maris's 37-year-old record
with 70 homers, was next with 272 points. Only Rick Hummel and Mike
Eisenbath of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch made McGwire No. 1 and
listed Sosa second.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's selection was a just reward for several reasons. With a
.318 average, 66 home runs, and 158 RBIs, he led the Cubs to a
wild-card playoff berth. The Cardinals failed to qualify. His bid
to overtake McGwire in September made the 1998 season one of the
most exciting in history. He also led the majors with 132 runs and
414 total bases, so he certainly earned the $250,000 bonus he gets
as MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Moises Alou was third with 215 points, followed by San
Diego's Greg Vaughn, who hit 50 homers and wound up with 185
points. Houston's Craig Biggio was fifth with 163 points.
</P>
<P>
   It was the eighth time a Cubs player won the MVP, the first
since Andre Dawson in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank God for giving me an opportunity to be in this
situation,'' said Sosa in a teleconference from Chicago. ``I hope
to be able to continue to do my job as well as be able to do good
for people. I believe in God, and when you do, good things can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who continually referred to McGwire as ``The Man'' as the
two approached Maris's mark of 61 homers, made a lot of things
happen on and off the field. He erupted onto the home run scene by
hitting a record 20 in June and ouhomered McGwire, 57-46, from May
23 to the end of the season. After being tied at 66, McGwire pulled
away on the final weekend. Sosa didn't care because his team had
made the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard for someone to hit 70 and not win the MVP,'' said
Sosa, a Dominican Republic native whose award came the day after
Puerto Rico's Juan Gonzalez was named the American League MVP.
``Mark's been a great player. But I took my team to the playoffs,
and that counts a lot. The decision that was made by the people
(writers) was great. But if they had voted for him, I'd happy, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody recognized the job I did in the field. The way that
I've been with the media helped. If we didn't get to the playoffs,
maybe I would have won it, maybe not. I don't know. All I can say
is I got it and I'm going to enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire expressed his happiness for Sosa in a statement from
Australia, where he is vacationing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a great job of carrying the Cubbies back to the
playoffs,'' McGwire said. ``I am proud of what this year meant for
the sport of baseball, reaffirming its position as America's
pasttime and passion. To put it in his words, today Sammy is `The
Man.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa probably did benefit from more positive media coverage,
which is not to say McGwire was ignored. Not by a long shot. But
each night, millions of fans watching the Cubs right fielder's
exploits would hear mention of the Sammy Sosa Foundation, and many
responded with cash donations to the charity. Sosa's ability to
lift his teammates and fill ballparks began to make him ``The Man''
in the eyes of many. Because of this, Sosa became an MVP candidate
even though McGwire was still getting the lion's share of the
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it the way it should have been taken,'' said Sosa. ``I
said all year long that if I have a good year, maybe I'll have the
MVP. And if I do it one time, then I have the ability to do it
again. I believe in myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I hit 66 home runs next year? I don't know. But I feel I
am capable of getting it because I have the ability and
opportunity. I'm a human being and I believe in God. When you do
that, you're never going to have any problems in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa had a hard time pinpointing the highlights of his season.
There were so many, ranging from his 20-homer month to a postseason
tour of Japan where, while earning the MVP title in the eight-game
series he found time to arrange for the shipment of 1,000 prefab
homes to the hurricane-ravaged Dominican. He is flying home today
to personally supervise the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in my country is tough,'' said Sosa. ``That's
why I'm going there so soon. They know about the MVP. They are
ready to celebrate. I won't do that much. I need time to see what
things look like for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Sosa means that for the first time in history,
both the NL and American League MVP awards go to Latin-born
players. Sosa is from Santo Domingo. Texas outfielder Juan
Gonzalez, named the American League winner Wednesday, was born in
Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor,'' said Sosa. ``Only one player in each league
can win the MVP, and a lot of people had great years, too. I'm just
glad what happened to me happened to Gonzalez. We played together
for Texas in the minors. It's a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a great year for Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never forget the 1998 season,'' he said. The month of
June. My three grand slams. I hadn't hit any before. Hitting No 62
was big for me. So was Sammy Sosa Day with my family here. I
promise to work hard next year. But I will continue to be the same
guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still respect Mark McGwire. If I had a vote, I would have
voted for McGwire. But I didn't, so thank you all for voting for
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
