<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAND-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RAGA: IN SEARCH OF FEMININITY': A HOVERING SELF, NOT MAN OR
WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An encounter between two bare-chested men is defined
by embraces in slow motion and the wordless commentary of five
other performers _ four women and another man: that is the ruling
image in ``Raga: In Search of Femininity,'' a 90-minute work by the
Indian choreographer Chandralekha.
</P>
<P>
   The piece, part of the Brooklyn Academy of Music's Next Wave
Festival, received a warm reception from the audience on Wednesday
night at the Majestic Theater (651 Fulton St., Fort Greene), where
it is being performed through Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, what you see is what you get, and what you get is
an awkward effort to put theory into unrealized practice. The
promotional verbiage around ``Raga'' suggests that it is about
``subconscious areas of male-femaleness in the body'' and ``an
exploration of the transformational area of femininity in the
bodies of men and women.'' There is more: femininity is ``the
actual act of becoming, the slippage from the state of fluidity and
harmony'' and associated with ``in between'' physical spaces.
</P>
<P>
   To be a victim of one's publicity is not the worst fate that can
befall an artist. That philosophical concepts lie behind
Chandralekha's work is not in doubt. But what one actually sees in
her ``Raga'' is physical action too simplified to carry the burden
of a viable esthetic.
</P>
<P>
   Originally schooled in Bharata Natyam, the best-known style of
classical dance in India, Chandralekha, 69, is not the first
choreographer there to use tradition as a springboard for a
creative approach. Pioneers like Ram Gopal and Uday Shanker opted
for hybrid theatrical spectacles, and hip young choreographers from
India today weave the idiom of classical dance into the texture of
Western post-modern ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Western modern-dance choreographers who usually
depart from previous codified dance vocabularies, Indian
choreographers, like modern flamenco choreographers, refer at least
occasionally to idioms identified with their national dance
traditions. In ``Raga,'' core movements of Bharata Natyam recur in
the choreography for the four women and for a young man who
suggests a youthful dancing god. Variations of yoga exercises,
especially visible in the beginning, are incorporated not for their
occasional contortionist shape but for their images of meditation.
Martial arts are visible in the formalized combat between the two
male leads at the end of their prolonged love encounter.
</P>
<P>
   A program note quotes from a 10th-century text of a poet, Devara
Dasimayya. Rather than defining men and women by physical
characteristics, he urges a deeper look: ``The self that hovers in
between is neither man nor woman.''
</P>
<P>
   But none of this is translated onstage, where the too-plain
choreography lacks the stylization of metaphoric resonance. The
problem is not what Chandralekha does with traditionally derived
movement but what she doesn't do with her own brand of movement.
</P>
<P>
   The young women who come rushing in periodically to stamp their
way through the piece function as a chorus, although they could
have been contemporary versions of the dancing angels in temple
sculpture. Their stance is rigid, robbed of variety. Nor does a
woman who plops down between two men on the floor suggest ``the
self that hovers in between.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement, not its symbolism, comes to the fore. Shaji John
and V.A. Sunny, the two men who execute the male duet, which
follows an introductory women's ensemble, do not seem to be
professional dancers like the others in the cast. But they are
admirably concentrated performers. They are often kept close to the
floor as they arch into sphinxlike poses, wrap around each other
with chaste caresses, entangle their interlocking limbs or bounce
along the stage in a push-up position. That one man hugs the knee
of another may suggest that every part of the body is worth
adoration from a lover, but when one man hugs the other's rump,
poetry no longer hovers in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The cast included Ramachandra Das, Janaki Meera Krishnamurthy,
Kalpana Krishnamurthy, R. Rajalakshmi and N. Yagnaprabha. T.H.
Subash Chandran led the percussion ensemble, which included N.
Ganesh Kumar and N. Ramakrishnan. The singer was G. Srikanth.
</P>
</TEXT>
