<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WELLES-REVIVALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS EVIL AS WELLES INTENDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orson Welles' last laugh must be heartier than ever,
now that ``Citizen Kane'' shines bright at the brand-new United
Artists Union Square 14 and ``A Touch of Evil'' continues its hit
run at the Film Forum. Anyone familiar with Welles' 1958 film noir
landmark knows that it could just as well have been called ``A
Truckload of Evil,'' and that its crazily sinister plot turns and
breathtaking camera work remain astonishingly fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Touch of Evil'' is, among so many things, the other film to
find Janet Leigh at a lonely motel under strangely menacing
management, and the one in which Welles gave one of his most droll,
swaggering performances as a corrupt police captain in an American
town on the Mexican border. As visually thrilling as it is
sin-soaked, this artfully reconstructed version of ``A Touch of
Evil'' remains one of the brightest lights on the cinematic
landscape this season.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the United Artists Union Square 14, at 13th Street
and Broadway, is $9; $5.50 for children 3 to 11 and the elderly.
Screening schedule and information: (212) 253-2225. Admission to
the Film Forum, 209 W. Houston St., South Village, is $8.50; $4.50
for members. Screening schedule and other information: (212)
727-8110.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
