<HEADLINE>
THE GIFT THAT REALLY GIVES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's installment of the holiday gift guide, just ``in time
for the holiday season,'' says its vendor, is Stun Um Self-Defense
Pepper Spray, reduced from $19.95 to $10 in the spirit of noel.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers of this festive product, R.A. Clark Co.,
specify the back-to-the-earth attributes that make it appropriate
for spraying by or at vegans and macrobiotics. Stun Um is ``made of
an all-natural cayenne pepper oil extract.''
</P>
<P>
   A fine companion gift would be  &UR; Claudia Hart &LR; 's new book, ``A
Child's  &UR; Machiavelli &LR; '' (Penguin Studio; $14.95), which is based on
``The Prince.'' ``You gotta be tough,'' warns this prettily
illustrated pink book. ``People won't really like you then, but
they're probably only your friends 'cos they think they can get
something off you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROYAL CHAT 'N' CHOW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In an otherwise extremely positive People magazine story about
 &UR; Prince Charles &LR; , royal watcher  &UR; Brian Hoey &LR;  described great dinner
parties thrown by the Prince of Wales:
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles is not a great intellectual, but he pretends to be. If
he's got guests for dinner, they are often told before they sit
down what the main topic of conversation will be that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might say, `Tonight we'll talk about deciduous trees,' and
they all start looking it up like mad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REGIONAL NOTES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ P.O.V., a magazine generally aimed at readers born after
 &UR; Richard Nixon &LR;  fell from grace, says that San Francisco is the 24th
booming-est town in the country. We rate high on people, nightlife,
culture, pride and coolness (highest in the country, except for New
York), but fall down in those ugly old skyscraper-cost-of-living
categories.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tom Wolfe &LR;  told W about the intricacies of writing accurate
dialogue in his new novel, ``A Man in Full,'' which is set in
Atlanta. ``Among men of the upper strata,'' he said, ``it is
considered very good form, and very macho, to assume down-home
accents. In a way, that would never happen in New York. Nobody
would slip into a Brooklyn street accent.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Cleveland is proud to proclaim itself the first city in the
country to have an online encyclopedia, an accomplishment worthy of
an excerpt:
</P>
<P>
   Before 1840, this important reference work reports, ``bands were
hardly more advanced than the fife-and-drum groups of Revolutionary
War times, according to  &UR; O.V. Schubert &LR; , author of a handwritten
and hand-illustrated book, `A Brief Sketch of Cleveland's Noted
Bands From 1840 to 1880.' Schubert was the son of  &UR; B.B. (Ben)
Schubert &LR; , who was born in Austria and was a cousin of  &UR; Franz
Schubert &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIG GAME HISTORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Allen Drury &LR; , the novelist and onetime journalist who died this
year, was such a loyal Stanford man that he abandoned
verisimilitude in his fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Drury's 1990 novel ``Toward What Bright Glory?'' tells the story
of the class of 1939 at a fictional place, ``The University,''
obviously modeled on Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   The author says the Big Game of 1939, between Berkeley and ``The
University,'' was won by ``The University,'' 7-6. In reality,
Berkeley won, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Fair-minded  &UR; Richard Reinhardt &LR; , a Stanford grad who became a
member of the faculty at UC Berkeley Graduate School of Journalism,
says Drury ``must have been a true Stanford fanatic.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost tattooed the Grinch on myself. I came so close. But I
won't do characters on my body.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Drew Barrymore draws the line somewhere, in Teen People
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what my calling is, but I want to be here for a
bigger reason. I strive to be like the greatest people who have
ever lived. Like Jesus. ... I'm in the middle of this movie thing
and loving it, but Malcolm X, Muhammad Ali, achieved a higher level
of personal greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Will Smith shares his aspirations _ including politics _ in
Rolling Stone.
</P>
