<HEADER>
A0133 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HEARING-1STLD     11-19 1474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HEARING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR DEFENDS LEWINSKY PROBE AT IMPEACHMENT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Complete writethru _ adds quotes, updates throughout)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN and MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr defended his
probe of President Clinton Thursday, telling lawmakers that he
never passed judgment on the president's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky but instead focused on Clinton's coverup of their affair _
conduct Starr said ``may constitute grounds for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   By itself, Starr told members of the House Judiciary Committee,
the Clinton-Lewinsky sexual relationship was not a ``high crime or
misdemeanor,'' what the Constitution defines as impeachable
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, his report saying that grounds exist to
impeach Clinton is based on issues of obstruction of justice, lying
under oath and witness tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Starr was attempting to deflate a Democratic charge that the
Lewinsky investigation was little more than a morality-tinged probe
of an illicit sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old independent counsel spent over 10 hours at the
witness table in the same room where the Judiciary Committee held
impeachment hearings against President Richard Nixon in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's marathon impeachment hearing was the only one
scheduled so far in a bitterly partisan process that has
Republicans trudging forward amid polls and election results
suggesting public disinterest in impeachment, and Democrats lobbing
grenades and trying to make Starr _ rather than Clinton _ the focus
of public debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is not above the law, Mr. Starr, and neither are
you,'' said Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., as the hearing moved into
its ninth hour.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic committee members attacked the independent counsel's
credibility and motives, rarely touching on the allegations of
Clinton's innocence or guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., accused Starr of bullying Lewinsky
into testifying against the president. He said lawyers from the
independent counsel's office had not allowed Lewinsky to call her
attorney when FBI agents first confronted and questioned the former
White House intern on Jan. 16 outside Washington. ``Why did your
office break the law?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Unruffled, Starr answered that the federal judge with
jurisdiction the case, Judge Norma H. Johnson, had cleared his
office of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., focused on Starr's announcement that
the president had been cleared in the so-called Filegate and
Travelgate investigations, saying that it ``disturbed him greatly''
that independent counsel had waited until after the Nov. 3 election
to release the information favorable to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the barrage of Democratic criticism, Starr remained
calm, often gently staring at attacking committee members or
quietly taking notes. On several occasions he told lawmakers that
he was merely the gatherer of facts, and that Congress alone judges
whether any of it constitutes grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Washington lawyer Theodore Olson, a close friend of the
independent counsel, described the testimony as vintage Starr. ``He
certainly demonstrated himself to be capable of not letting people
get under his skin,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Republicans split their time between defending
Starr and trying to refocus attention on the allegations of perjury
and obstruction of justice against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady of Florida voiced a common theme among the
Republican members when he said, ``I think what we are seeing here
is a desperate attempt to get away from the facts of the case
against the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he acknowledged the country's fatigue with Lewinsky
affair, Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., defended Starr and his
investigation against the country's desire to ``just drop this
whole impeachment thing, because everybody lies about sex and the
president ought to have the opportunity to lie about sex just like
everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that allowing the president to commit perjury would make
most sexual harassment and domestic violence cases ``less
meaningful'' and ``in many cases unenforceable.''
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., tried to open
Thursday's proceedings on a nonpartisan note. The hearing, he said,
``is not a trial nor is it White House versus Ken Starr, or
Republican versus Democrat. Rather, the hearing today is another
step in our attempt to carry out our constitutional duty.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get very far. Rep. William Delahunt, D-Mass., made a
motion to allow Clinton lawyer David Kendall two hours to question
Starr, instead of the 30 minutes allotted by Hyde. Republicans
defeated the motion 21-16 on a party-line vote.
</P>
<P>
   Before questioning Starr about his allegations against Clinton,
Kendall told the Judiciary Committee that ``nothing in this
overkill of investigation amounts to justification for impeachment
of the president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats on the committee seemed intent on making the most
of their first _ and possibly last _ opportunity to grill Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a federally-paid sex policeman spending millions
of dollars to trap an unfaithful spouse ... would have been
unthinkable prior to the Starr investigation,'' said the
committee's ranking Democrat, Rep. John Conyers of Michigan. ``Let
there be no mistake, it is not now acceptable in America to
investigate a person's private sexual activity.''
</P>
<P>
   In a professorial voice, Starr read his 58-page statement in
about two hours. He told lawmakers the investigation of Clinton's
efforts to conceal his 18-month affair with the former White House
intern ``caused all of us considerable dismay _ and continues to do
so,'' Starr told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, ``I am proud of what we did,'' he added. ``We were
assigned a difficult job. We have done it to the very best of our
abilities. We have tried to be fair and thorough.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's statement contained few surprises, going over much of
the same ground covered in his 450-page report to Congress Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's intimate relationship with a subordinate
employee was transformed into an unlawful effort to thwart the
judicial process,'' Starr said. ``This was no longer an issue of
private conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said Clinton lied under oath about Lewinsky in his Jan.
17, 1998, deposition in the Jones civil lawsuit, and also lied that
same month to his Cabinet and at a televised public event.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, he added, also pressured his personal secretary, Betty
Currie, into agreeing with him that he and Lewinsky were never
alone, and that Currie could ``see and hear everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also lied in his Aug. 17 grand jury testimony by
claiming his Jan. 17 denial of a sexual relationship with Lewinsky
was legally accurate, Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr zeroed in on instances in which he claimed that Clinton
had stalled the legal process in the Lewinsky matter by refusing
for seven months to testify before the grand jury and trying to
prevent White House lawyer Bruce Lindsey and Secret Service
personnel from testifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president used the machinery of government and the power
of his office to conceal his relationship with Monica Lewinsky,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr disclosed that his office considered recommending that the
House undertake an impeachment investigation on the original
Whitewater allegations, but ultimately he declined to send the
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the Whitewater case was Clinton's testimony that he
didn't know about a fraudulent $300,000 loan and a second loan from
Madison Guaranty Savings &AMP; Loan which was owned by the president's
former business partners, James and Susan McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also told lawmakers he found no evidence of impeachable
offenses in his separate investigations of White House possession
of FBI files on Republicans _ Filegate _ or in the firing of career
White House travel office workers and their replacement by
employees close to Clinton _ Travelgate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starr served in the Justice Department in the Reagan
administration and was appointed to the federal appeals court in
Washington by Reagan in 1983. During the Bush administration, he
was the U.S. solicitor general, the government's chief advocate
before the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   With such a Republican pedigree, Starr made a point of defending
the Lewinsky probe as one staffed by career federal prosecutors and
FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a bright line between law and politics, between
courts and polls,'' Starr said. ``It leaves the polls to the
politicians and spin doctors. We are officers of the court who live
in the world of the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
