<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIELBERG-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERLIN DEBATES SPIELBERG'S OFFER FOR HOLOCAUST VIDEO MEMORIAL  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ As the debate intensifies over how to recall Hitler's
destruction of European Jewry in the emerging new center of Berlin,
the Jewish Museum here has begun talks with Steven Spielberg over
the possibility of housing his vast video history of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, to open in 2000, said in a statement Thursday that
its director, former Treasury Secretary Michael Blumenthal, had
recently discussed the plan in Los Angeles with Michael Berenbaum,
president of Spielberg's Survivors of the Shoah Visual History
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In September, officials said, the assistant museum director, Tom
Freudenheim, discussed the possibility with Spielberg when he was
awarded Germany's highest honor, the Federal Cross of Merit.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are being conducted during the debate over what place
to give the remembrance of the Holocaust in the heart of this city
that is busy reinventing itself before the government moves here
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion has intensified in recent months, after sharp
criticism of a proposed Holocaust memorial by Michael Naumann, the
state culture minister in the new Social Democratic government.
Naumann, who recently moved back here from a senior publishing job
in New York, said in July that a favored plan that would build
4,000 pillars near the Brandenburg Gate amounted to a ``political
institution for wreath laying'' and was depressing.
</P>
<P>
   He has modified his remarks somewhat, suggesting last month that
Spielberg's history might form a central element of the memorial, a
distinct project from the Jewish Museum. The museum, already built,
was designed by Daniel Libeskind, the American architect.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Thursday about the discussions to send the
history, with its more than 40,000 interviews with Holocaust
survivors, to the museum suggested that the idea of making it part
of the separate memorial had receded.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this goes ahead,'' said a person familiar with the talks,
``then the question of the Holocaust memorial will be entirely open
once again. Naumann's suggestion was rather different.''
</P>
<P>
   Naumann could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week with the weekly magazine Stern
Spielberg said a Holocaust memorial should be built here. ``But
whether it is a Holocaust museum, an obelisk or a symbolic work of
art is something that Germany should decide alone. Germans should
make their own decision according to their own conscience, without
worrying what people abroad will think.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's government has said Parliament
will vote next year on the labyrinth of pillars designed by the
architect Peter Eisenman, of New York, the project previously
favored for the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   If, as seems quite likely, that plan is rejected, the whole
question of how, if at all, to recall the Holocaust will reopen, a
decade after the debate on it began. Many residents oppose a large
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
