<HEADER>
A0148 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACIAL-DIVERSITY-BOS &LR;      11-19 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACIAL-DIVERSITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COURT, DIVERSITY FACES STRICT LEGAL TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Should have analysis slug.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the end, Boston Latin's affirmative action
admissions policy was a lofty educational ideal that crashed into
the stricter structures of the law.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, educators, like the Boston School Committee,
have based their arguments for affirmative action on the idea that
racial diversity was good for minorities and for whites, that
students become better citizens when they learn in classrooms with
a rainbow of faces.
</P>
<P>
   But while this argument works in politics _ where Bill Clinton
vowed a cabinet ``that looks like America'' _ it no longer works in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Racial diversity might mean, as studies have shown, a more
tolerant citizenry, greater minority participation in charitable
activities, the ascension of blacks to the middle class. These
might be legitimate social goals. But in court, what matters is
whether they are ``compelling'' governmental interests.
</P>
<P>
   So far, defenders of affirmative action have answered this
question only in what the court ruled ``abstract'' _ what critics
would call nebulous _ terms. Even proponents admit they have long
simply taken it as an article of faith that diversity is a good
thing, up there with motherhood and apple pie.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Thursday's and other recent rulings, the
challenge for Boston, as for so many other schools and universities
where teaching diversity has become as much a goal as teaching
literacy, is now in proving the value of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask people who believe in affirmative action, `Why do
you believe?' I think most of them will say, `Because we'll be a
better society in the future if we have a well-educated population
that reflects the diversity of America,''' said Richard Fallon, a
professor at Harvard Law School. ``That's the argument that ought
to be the strongest argument, but when you get into court, it gets
filtered through these legal categories. The court doesn't allow
you to argue that we want to have a classroom that looks like the
city of Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   In the landmark 1978 Bakke case, the Supreme Court said
diversity in university admissions was a worthwhile goal, but said
admissions could not be based solely on race; it could be but one
factor in considering who to admit. As an ideal, that decision
upheld Harvard's admissions procedures, where the College selects
candidates for a class with a range of diversity _ geographic,
economic, artistic and athletic, as well as race.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, the US Court of Appeals in Texas ruled in the
Hopwood case against the University of Texas, saying that diversity
in education is not a compelling government interest.
</P>
<P>
   Upholding the Latin School policy in May, Massachusetts Judge
Joseph L. Tauro ruled diversity was ``an important factor
contributing to students' intellectual and moral development.''
</P>
<P>
   But a federal appeals court panel overruled that decision
Thursday. The judges left open the question of whether diversity
should be a compelling interest of government, but they were clear
in saying that the value of diversity must be shown concretely and
specifically. It is too abstract to say diversity ``nourishes the
intellect,'' or ``furthers mutual understanding and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An inquiring court cannot content itself with abstractions,''
the judges wrote. ``To persuade us that diversity may serve as a
justification ... the School Committee must do more than ask us
blindly to accept its judgment. It must give substance to the
word.''
</P>
<P>
   Even critics of affirmative action acknowledge there is a test
gap in scores between black and white students in Boston, as there
is gap in the SAT scores of blacks and whites nationally. But there
is little proof, if any, that a diverse classroom can bridge that
gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``To look at that gap and say it's the result of discrimination,
or the results of lowered expectations, it's a calumny,'' said
Stephan Thernstrom, professor of government at Harvard, and an
expert witness for the Wessman family. ``You really shouldn't say
that without some demonstrated effort to document it. They have a
lot of money, but they didn't spend one cent to investigate or
document it.''
</P>
<P>
   For years after the Bakke decision, supporters based their
support for affirmative action on little more than emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, there has been little hard evidence to confirm the
belief of educators in the value of diversity,'' admit two
proponents of affirmative action, former Harvard president Derek
Bok and former Princeton president William Bowen, in their
widely-cited recent book, ``The Shape of the River,'' which
examines racial preference programs.
</P>
<P>
   But when courts began dismantling such programs in the early
1990s, researchers began a flurry of study projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people in the legal world believe institutions will be on
more solid legal grounds if they can ... argue that all their
strategies on diversity are important to achieving educational
goals,'' said Debra Humphreys of the Ford Foundation's Campus
Diversity Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The Bok/Bowen book's data shows that a large proportion of
blacks who benefited from affirmative action in the 1970s went on
to become doctors, lawyers and community leaders in above-average
numbers. And their average salary was $71,000.
</P>
<P>
   But leaving it to the courts to decide whether these are
``compelling'' interests for government has some educators wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts are moving into a domain that previously educators
were considered to be the experts on,'' Humphreys said. ``It is
breaking with a precedent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
