A0149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAS-PROTEST20-CO     11-19 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-PROTEST20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Priest has high hopes for Benning protest
 &HT;    By Virginia Anderson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the 1,500 or so nights that the Rev. Roy Bourgeois
spent in prison, when the banging chatter of the inmates stopped
and the loneliness raced out of his mind to taunt him, one thought
sustained him: This will help close the School of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago, the protests didn't even attract enough people
to pack a potluck supper.
</P>
<P>
   But Bourgeois thinks Sunday's scheduled protest with an expected
4,000 demonstrators outside the gates of Fort Benning outside
Columbus is evidence his prayers to close the school may soon be
answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel this deep joy,'' Bourgeois said of this weekend's
expected crowd. ``Each year, it's really grown. It's reached a
point where people feel they must stand up for the poor of Latin
America.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army, which operates the training program for Latin American
soldiers, insists that the school will remain open, no matter how
many protesters show up and no matter how many go to prison.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations started with a dozen people following the
Nov. 16, 1989, murder of six Jesuit priests, their housekeeper and
her 15-year-old daughter in El Salvador. Nineteen graduates of the
School of the Americas were among those charged with the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   But defenders of the school say it helps keep peace in an
unstable region and that only a small number of the more than
50,000 graduates have been linked to atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's demonstrations could include actor Martin Sheen,
500 Jesuit priests, busloads of nuns and hundreds of college
students, retirees and homemakers. Demonstrators from as far away
as Washington state are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Some 50 Native Americans are traveling by bus from South Dakota,
even though they don't have money for a motel room and plan to
sleep on the floor of a restaurant that will close for the night to
accommodate them.
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeois, a 59-year-old decorated Vietnam veteran whose
experiences there steered him to become a missionary priest, has
said his protest movement would gain momentum with time.
Eventually, Congress will take away funding for the school and
force the Army to close it, he predicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always knew this, that you can send us to prison, but you
cannot silence the truth,'' Bourgeois said from his one-room
apartment across the street from the main gate of Fort Benning.
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeois and 14 others were released from federal prisons
across the country in September after serving time for crossing the
line at the base last Nov. 16.
</P>
<P>
   While 601 demonstrators were arrested that day, only those who
had been sent letters by the base banning them from the property
for their involvement in previous protests were sentenced to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law prohibits political speech on military bases, but
Bourgeois and the other protesters contend the law is applied
inconsistently. The protesters claim that favorable political
speech, such as when senators visit the base, is allowed and that
dissident speech should also be.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Robert Elliott has repeatedly disagreed with
the protesters. Last January, after sentencing them to prison, he
fined them $3,000 to reinforce his point.
</P>
<P>
   In response to this weekend's protest plans, the Army is holding
an open house for reporters, inviting them to meet faculty and to
monitor classes. Capt. Kevin McIver, school spokesman, said
representatives from 20 countries, including Canada, were at the
school last week for discussions on diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeois said he does not plan to cross the line at the base
Sunday because he has a hectic speaking schedule awaiting him this
winter and spring. He expects Sheen, currently filming a
documentary in Mexico and expected to arrive in Columbus on
Saturday, to cross the line with 1,000 or so other protesters.
Bourgeois said Sheen had received a letter from the base asking him
to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan Marianne Buckley and her husband, Ferd are among those
who may cross the line. They have begun to feel they must do more
than sit in church and pray, Marianne Buckley said. ``If we don't
do anything about it, then we're not living the Gospels,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
