A0151 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN20-COX     11-19 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    University of Dayton students expect to be arrested at protest
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The two ledgers on the blackboard are labeled
``A'' and ``OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The students get a laugh out of that, but the letters stand for
a decision that's anything but frivolous. The ``A'' list represents
the University of Dayton students who have decided to get arrested
at this weekend's massive protest against the School of the
Americas at Fort Benning in Columbus, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen students and three UD faculty are leaving this morning
to join what promises to be the largest demonstration ever against
the American-run school that trains Latin American soldiers and
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   At this meeting Tuesday night in campus ministry offices, more
than half the students _ the ``chain gang,'' as one wag called them
_ said they intend to risk almost certain arrest by crossing the
line into government property.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently no one alerted them they are the generation supposed
to be consumed by resumes and landing the big-bucks job after
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the least I can do for the people of Central America
who are scraping to get by,'' said student T.J. Meyer, who made a
service trip to Haiti in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The students will join an expected 6,000 protesters at a Sunday
vigil, with 1,000 _ including actor Martin Sheen _ expected to
cross the line into government property. (In past years, first-time
offenders have been arrested, but not charged or prosecuted.)
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 2,000 protesters attended the annual vigil sponsored
by the School of the Americas Watch, timed to commemorate the 1989
murder of six Jesuit priests in El Salvador. Many of the school's
graduates _ including 19 the soldiers incriminated in the killings
of the Jesuits _ have been linked to murders and other human rights
violations throughout Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The students, in other words, couldn't have picked a better
cause.
</P>
<P>
   If the 6,000 prediction seems inflated, consider the Dayton
contingent: Last year only four area residents went to Fort
Benning. This year that number has jumped to nearly 60, including
the UD contingent, 20 students from Antioch College, and nearly 20
other Daytonians.
</P>
<P>
   Why the groundswell? It could be the narrow defeat in September
_ by a margin of 212 to 201 _ of an amendment in Congress to cut
off funds to the School of the Americas. It could be the publicity
surrounding cases like that of Sister Marge Eilerman, a Fort
Loramie native currently serving a jail sentence for vandalism at
the school in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The UD students seem to be heeding no other drummer than their
own consciences. ``It's really a student movement,'' said senior
Rachel Hellman. ``The energy is here because the students want
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I need to go down there,'' said student Greg Luczak.
``But to get arrested could close a lot of doors in the future. I
might want to join the Peace Corps, and you can't do that with an
arrest record for civil disobedience.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the university courting the wrath of parents, or future
recriminations by the students themselves, by allowing its campus
ministry to sponsor the trip?
</P>
<P>
   UD president Brother Raymond Fitz said ``protesting is one
thing, getting arrested is another act. We wanted to make sure the
students saw through the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend a lot of time to get students socially aware, and
aware of what's going on around the globe,'' Fitz added. ``While
getting arrested might not be something I would have done, I have
respect for students who have thought through it. It's a
complicated issue, and they could have ignored it.''
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't. So much for the generation that doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
