<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    States expected to accept $206 billion tobacco deal
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By today's noon deadline, a majority of states are
expected to accept a $206 billion settlement from the nation's
biggest cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers nationwide already are debating how to spend the
money, and Georgia's Thurbert Baker is one of dozens of state
attorneys general who have scheduled news conferences to accept the
offer at the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, which stands to collect about $4.8 billion over the
next 25 years, was expected to be joined by South Carolina,
Louisiana and Virginia today in making endorsement of the deal
unanimous among Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   But in Alabama, a lame-duck Gov. Fob James has persisted in
battling one of his political appointees in an attempt to get a
better deal. Attorney General Bill Pryor, appointed by James in
1997, already has signed the documents that could deliver Alabama
$3.2 billion over the next 25 years. In the tobacco-heavy South,
James stood alone in his reluctance to accept the national
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Tennessee, and Kentucky claimed their share. North
Carolina and Arkansas joined earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the settlement, Georgia would receive annual
payments of $150 million to $200 million most years, through 2024.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in separate deals, Florida, Mississippi, Texas and
Minnesota negotiated settlements totaling $40 billion over 25
years. Negotiators hoped that at least three-fourths of the
remaining 46 states would endorse the latest agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the national settlement, the tobacco
companies would curtail advertising and fund an anti-smoking
campaign worth $1.5 billion. Tobacco-growing states pressed the
nation's largest tobacco companies _ Philip Morris, R.J. Reynolds,
Brown &AMP; Williamson and Lorillard _ to put a dollar figure on their
pledge to help farmers make up lost income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobacco farmers have a right to be heard, and they need to be
treated fairly,'' Tennessee Attorney General Knox Walkup said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the states' leaders, Alabama's Gov. James wanted
more time to wade through the extensive settlement document but a
circuit court judge denied his request for an extension Thursday.
Pryor warned James the national settlement would become reality
without him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
