<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BARR20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr calls for bribery charges against Clinton
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Georgia's Rep. Bob Barr used his latest five
minutes in the national limelight Thursday to try to saddle
President Clinton with an additional impeachable act: bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Barr was one of at least two Republicans on the House Judiciary
Committee who said Clinton's efforts to find Monica Lewinsky a job
amounted to a bribe for her silence or favorable testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``One could very legitimately make the case,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   But independent counsel Kenneth Starr, whose report did not
allege bribery, would not agree with Barr or Rep. Bill McCollum of
Florida, who put forth the same argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not want to join in a particular judgment beyond that
which we set forth in the referral,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, tell the Republicans: ``It's a fair issue.''
</P>
<P>
   McCollum, who first raised the bribery issue, contended the
facts were quite strong. ``It seems pretty darn clear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One probable explanation for the new interest in alleging
bribery is that the crime is one of only two the Constitution
specifically mentions as grounds for impeaching a president. The
other is treason.
</P>
<P>
   Making a bribery case against Clinton would end the debate about
whether his actions are sufficiently serious to warrant
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Barr waited more than 8 1/2 hours for his five minutes of
questioning Starr. Like all the Republicans on the panel, he was
extremely complimentary of the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend you for standing up to this nonsense,'' Barr said,
referring to often biting questions from committee Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Barr sought to strengthen Starr's conclusions by asking him to
assume a set of facts that would put many of the president's
accusers in a harshly negative light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's presume,'' Barr began, that Linda Tripp is a ``nasty
person,'' that literary agent Lucianne Goldberg is a
``maniuplator,'' that Lewinsky is ``an oversexed blabbermouth,''
that Paula Jones was interested in nothing but money and that there
really is a vast right-wing conspiracy, as first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton has alleged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would any of that change the conclusions contained in your
referral?'' Barr asked.
</P>
<P>
   Both grateful and ready for the friendly question, Starr
replied: ``It would not change it. The facts have a real power to
them. It was Justice Brandeis who said, 'Facts, facts, facts. Give
me facts.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
