<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MOORE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prankster Moore ambushes Barr for film on Starr
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), one of the impeachment
standard bearers, was fresh off his first television interview of
the morning Thursday when he ran into a camera lens he would have
sooner not seen.
</P>
<P>
   Producer/prankster Michael Moore, marauding Capitol Hill to
gather material for a satire on Independent Counsel Ken Starr,
ambushed Barr after an early morning interview on CBS' This Morning
to pepper him with questions about impeachment, marijuana and whip
cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting great stuff,'' exalted Moore after the
encounter. ``Some of our greatest stuff was with Bob Barr.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Moore, the Georgia Republican paused long enough to
explain why President Clinton's conduct was more than just sex and
why he opposed the District of Columbia voting on the use of
marijuana for medical purposes. Moore also said he asked Barr to
explain an incident in which Barr licked whipped cream off the
chest of a woman at a 1992 Cobb County fund-raiser for leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the whip cream incident has weighed heavily on his
mind,'' said Moore, wearing his trademark baseball cap. ``I asked
him why it was moral for him to sit in judgment of the president
when he has been married three times and licked whip cream off the
breast of a beauty contestant.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore hinted that he might have simulated the whip cream
incident for the benefit of the camera, but Barr spokesman Brad
Alexander said Moore played no tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Barr himself was mostly mum about the morning encounter, saying
in response to Moore's suggestion that the whip cream incident
weighed on Barr's conscience, ``Apparently, it was on his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who produced Roger &AMP; Me, his satirical account of General
Motors and GM plant closings in Flint, Mich., has been busy filming
a documentary on Starr for his cable show, ``The Awful Truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his recent antics include appearing outside Starr's
Washington house with a band of actors dressed as Colonial-era
Puritans.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he brought an overweight actor dressed as President
Thomas Jefferson who interrupted a GOP press conference shouting,
``Impeach me, impeach me. I had an affair and I've been lying about
it for 200 years.'' The man was promptly hauled off by police.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said he was surprised that Barr was willing to joust with
him, noting that most members of Congress would have blown him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, OK, (Clinton) lied, but he lied about sex,'' Moore
said to told Barr. ``I said, `Come on, we're guys! Guys lie about
sex. Some of us can only get sex if we lie.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barr's response, Moore said, was ``Yes, but he lied, he lied, he
lied.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very funny, I'll say that for him,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I should take that as a compliment,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
