<HEADER>
A0162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TV20-COX     11-19 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Starr testimony packs few dramatic punches
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cirque du Soleil can rest easy. Despite concerns _ or
perhaps in some quarters, secret hopes _ that Thursday's televised
impeachment hearings might have a whiff of greasepaint and the slap
of large floppy shoes, it was a pretty circumspect affair.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's Bruce Morton likened independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
demeanor to ``sort of like your high school Latin teacher,'' and
Greta Van Susteren said Starr's two hours of testimony was ``a
verbal Cliffs Notes (of his full report) for members of Congress.''
Two more reasons for believing real life is like high school, only
with less flamboyant clothes and higher stakes.
</P>
<P>
   And what a contrast to the last 10 months of media madness, what
CNN's Jeff Greenfield called ``this maelstrom of semi-informed and
uninformed windbaggery and totally partisan posturing on both
sides.'' He's obviously been sneaking over to CNBC to watch
``Geraldo Live,'' the World Wrestling Federation of
Clinton-Lewinsky coverage.
</P>
<P>
   There was a consensus among network analysts _ the partisan
posturers aside _ that nothing anyone said Thursday changed any
minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see anything happening that will cause any kind of
groundswell,'' said NBC's Lisa Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Taylor, a conservative PBS analyst who's been friendly to
Starr, noted Thursday that the prosecutor had a problem ``giving
direct, simple answers to direct, simple questions. My reaction is,
`Come on, get to the point.''' But ABC legal analyst Jeffrey
Toobin, who has been critical of Starr's investigation, praised the
independent counsel for his answers to pointed questioning from
House Judiciary Committee Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with television at full attention, dress grays,
shoes spit-shined. CNN, ABC, CBS and NBC, all anchored down and
ready for business. Fox, Court TV, PBS, C-SPAN and MSNBC. But
slowly they started peeling away.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Fox affiliate, WAGA, was the first defector, switching
to ``Judge Judy'' after Starr had barely begun. ``I have a truth
detector back here,'' Judge Judy admonished some miscreant before
her. Would that she had shared it with the country sometime during
the last 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   By the afternoon, the major networks had slouched back to their
soaps, leaving the grown-ups _ CNN, PBS, C-SPAN _ to soldier on,
even though there were long, long stretches that seemed like going
through the motions.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Greenfield nailed it. ``What the process has gained in
immediacy it seems to have lost in majesty,'' he said. ``We chew
over this debate day after day, night after night on 100 different
outlets. When we get to the formal proceedings, this hearing,
everyone knows their parts. We can almost recite along with
everybody what their lines are.''
</P>
<P>
   We _ all of us, the viewers, the voters, the politicians, the
spinmeisters, the talk show hosts _ had already chewed it all over
so thoroughly, for so long, that there was nothing left to chew.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
