<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 20
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-WATTS-PROFILE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Nov. 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Nov.
19, about J.C. Watts, one of the new House leaders, misstated the
year of his birth in some copies. He was born on Nov. 18, 1957, not
1956.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COURT-PERJURY-NYT (moved on Monday, Nov. 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Nov. 16,
about trends in the prosecution of perjury referred incorrectly to
a case against a Texas judge. The judge, not named in the article,
was indicted by a grand jury on a perjury charge in a case
involving political contributions, but the trial judge quashed the
indictment. The judge was not convicted. Prosecutors are seeking a
reinstatement of the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ELN-BANKING-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Nov. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Nov. 4,
about the expected selection of Senator Phil Gramm as the next
chairman of the Senate Banking Committee referred imprecisely to
derivatives regulation powers of the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission, which some lobbyists believe he would want to restrict.
The commission regulates derivatives traded on exchanges, like
futures contracts, but does not have sweeping authority over
derivatives.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NATIONAL-BOOK-AWARDS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Nov. 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Nov.
19, about the winners of the National Book Awards quoted
incorrectly from lines recited by Gerald Stern, the winner of the
poetry award, from his work ``The Bite.'' They should have read:
</P>
<P>
   now, like a hare, like a hare, like a hare,
</P>
<P>
   I watch the turtle lift one horrible leg
</P>
<P>
   over the last remaining stile and head
</P>
<P>
   for home, practically roaring with virtue.
</P>
<P>
   A corrected version of the article appears today on page B48.
</P>
</TEXT>
