<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-FAMILY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TEAM FULL OF FAMILY TIES OFF TO A PERFECT 11-0 RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 AFFAIR-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAULA CABALLERO 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EULESS, Texas _ If a family atmosphere is mandatory for team
success, then Trinity (Texas) High School's 11-0 football team has
more than met its prerequisite.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to having a team-wide chemistry every coach brags
about come playoff time, the Trojans also boast five sets of
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Brothers Julius and Kuna Maumalanga are starters and stars of
the team, and have their biggest fan on the sideline in first
cousin Tommy Fonua, a junior on the scout team.
</P>
<P>
   Senior cousins Joe and George Heimuli line up one behind the
other on defense. Junior identical twins Brian and Brandon Hall are
role players, aspiring full-time starters.
</P>
<P>
   Team trainer Mike ``Doc'' Pruitt is joined on the sidelines by
his son, junior Mitch Pruitt, a backup quarterback. Assistant coach
Chuck Caniford sends the running backs into battle and his cousin
Cori Menegay, a senior student trainer, patches them up afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Their ties are tight, and they say the result fuses the team
closer together. Whether that means more relatives in the stands to
cheer on the Trojans or personal inspiration to make the big play,
having family on the field makes the extra effort easy to give.
</P>
<P>
   ``We push each other harder, which helps us and it helps the
team,'' Brandon Hall said. ``Having a lot of family on the team is
good. We're not scared to get under each other's skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Each relationship is distinctive, bringing different motivations
and advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Doc Pruitt has been bringing Mitch to games since he was 3 or 4.
When Mitch was 6, he started as ball boy. Now, he's suited up on
the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people call him Doc, but I call him Dad,'' Mitch Pruitt
said. ``I like it because some kids don't get to see their dad
hardly at all, but I get to see my dad at work every day when I'm
at school.''
</P>
<P>
   George and Joe Heimuli grew up in San Bruno, Calif. They moved
to Texas for seventh grade when their parents were transferred, and
began playing tackle football.
</P>
<P>
   Now the two are starters on a successful defense, with George at
linebacker and Joe at defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pump each other up,'' George said. ``If I miss a tackle, he
gets my back. And if he misses a tackle, I get his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we're family, it gives us a little magic, a little
power.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maumalangas feel their brother connection gives them magic,
too _ and that magic is evident. Senior linebacker Julius leads the
defense with 110 tackles, including five for losses. Junior
flanker/defensive back Kuna has scored touchdowns receiving,
rushing and on defense.
</P>
<P>
   But the brothers will play their last game together sometime in
the next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to make this season good for him \RJulius\S because
it's his last year,'' Kuna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to enjoy it,'' Julius said. ``I'd like to enjoy it
by going to state together. And I hope we can continue to play
together past high school.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hall twins have one more year together. Maybe next year
their on-field performances will help separate the look-alikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in practice on second defense together and Brian got
yelled at and they took me out,'' Brandon Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then my brother misses his block and I got yelled at,'' Brian
said. ``It goes both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   As reserve players, the Halls savor their playing time,
particularly in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's most special when we're on the field together,''
Brian said. ``We're both usually in there on special teams. I don't
think about it as much if I'm in there by myself, but \RBrandon\S
will be the first to give me a head-butt when I get off the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Cori Menegay, in her third year as a trainer, and cousin Chuck
Caniford, in his first year as an assistant, say they're more like
brother and sister. The two grew up together in Trinity territory,
the two families' homes just blocks apart.
</P>
<P>
   And with both of them on the field, their families have become
even bigger Trojans fans than they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps get both of our families involved,'' Caniford said.
``We have 12 to 20 relatives in the stands on a given night. We
even had a game where grandparents came from Ohio to support us.''
</P>
<P>
   The families within the Trinity football family have helped keep
the team united, powerful and perfect. And no one acknowledges that
more than head coach Ed Hickman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working together, forgiving each other and supporting each
other,'' Hickman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is team? It is family.''
</P>
<P>
   (Paula Caballero writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact her at (817) 685-3863. Visit
the Star-Telegram's high school sports site on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
