A0188 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-STARR-BOS &LR;      11-19 1607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-STARR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR DEFENDS IMPEACHMENT EFFORT IN 10-HOUR GRILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With his conduct and credibility under siege,
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr Thursday coolly defended his
landmark case against President Clinton, as the first impeachment
inquiry in a generation unfolded under the nation's gaze.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, fully exposed to criticism for the first time in his
four-year investigation of the president, insisted during more than
10 hours of questioning by Clinton's lawyer, hostile Democrats and
friendly Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee, that he
violated no ethical, legal, or moral code in his controversial
probe of the president's sexual affair with the former White House
intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand by this referral,'' Starr told the committee, holding
up his 445-page report that contains allegations Clinton may have
committed 11 impeachable offenses. ``I stand by each word in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyer, David E. Kendall, echoed many of Starr's
critics in denouncing Starr's allegations as elaborate
exaggerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in this overkill of an investigation amounts to a
justification for the impeachment of the president of the United
States,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   The only major witness in the House impeachment drama, Starr
made no breakthrough disclosure that would have provided fresh
momentum for advocates of removing Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the former judge laid out a scathing review of the
Lewinsky scandal, renewing his charges that Clinton betrayed the
national trust and power of his office by engaging in a pattern of
perjury, witness tampering, and obstruction of justice in trying to
cover up his sexual trysts in the White House with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Under the hot lights of the same, packed hearing room where
impeachment proceedings led to President Nixon's resignation in
1974, Starr raised the possibility that Clinton could be prosecuted
for perjury after he leaves office, regardless of whether Congress
impeaches him.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also disclosed that he has found no evidence that would
warrant a criminal charge or impeachment allegation against Clinton
stemming from his office's separate inquiries into Arkansas real
estate transactions, the use of FBI files by White House political
operatives, and the firing of White House travel office workers.
</P>
<P>
   But the former judge spent most of his historic appearance
before the bitterly divided committee parrying verbal attacks from
Democrats on a vast range of topics, from the most minute details
of his prosecutorial techniques to the nature of his investigation
into the Lewinsky matter. Committee Republicans generally praised
Starr's record and his report and criticized Democrats for unfairly
maligning him and his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a federally paid sex policeman spending millions
of dollars to trap an unfaithful spouse would have been unthinkable
prior to the Starr investigation,'' said Representative John
Conyers Jr., of Michigan, the highest ranking Democrat on the
Judiciary Committee, jabbing his finger in the air at the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The president's supporters made virtually no attempt to defend
his admitted lies about the Lewinsky affair and his alleged coverup
of the relationship, and only rarely did they address the substance
of Starr's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   But they spared little effort in trying to skewer Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The fiercest attacks on Starr focused on allegations that his
office repeatedly leaked secret grand-jury evidence damaging to
Clinton and that Starr's staff violated Lewinsky's due process
rights when they detained her for more than 10 hours at a
Ritz-Carlton Hotel outside Washington in an effort to gain her
cooperation in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is not above the law, and neither are you,''
Representative Robert Wexler, a Florida Democrat, shouted at Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people do not approve, Mr. Starr,'' Wexler said.
``They know fairness when they see it. They know justice when they
feel it. They know hypocrisy when they smell it. ... In their gut,
they have figured this thing out.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat, accused
Starr of being an ``expert on unfair questions'' and adhering to
the policy that ``you don't have anything to say unless you have
something bad to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank also asked Starr why he waited until after the elections
to report the findings of his separate investigations when the
findings could have been released before the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, in a lilting voice and with a scholarly tone, remained
unruffled throughout the grilling, calmly describing himself as an
unbiased arbiter who is unschooled ``in politics, public relations,
and polls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We conducted ourselves properly and lawfully,'' Starr said of
his staff on various occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing unfolded amid increasing reluctance in Congress to
impeach Clinton and recent polls that show broad disapproval for
the way Starr and the House Judiciary Committee have handled the
case. Starr's appearance was seen as one of the last opportunities
for him to rehabilitate his image and reenergize the impeachment
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Starr has set forth a clear, documented, compelling case
against the president,'' Judiciary Chairman Henry J. Hyde said
after Starr's two-hour presentation of his prepared testimony,
which had been made public the night before. ``He has provided a
road map for us to see how and when the president chose deception
rather than truth at many important crossroads in the judicial
system's search for the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   But committee Democrats said Starr had said almost nothing he
had said before and had failed to score a public-relations victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's no Ollie North in terms of presentation,'' said
Representative William D. Delahunt, a Massachusetts Democrat, who
lashed out at Starr for engaging in ``unprofessional conduct'' in
the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt was referring to Oliver North, a key figure in the
Iran-Contra hearings, who won broad public support after his
performance in a congressional hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is one of the lowest ranking Democrats on the
37-member committee, Delahunt played a prominent role in
challenging Hyde's decision to limit Clinton's lawyer, David E.
Kendall, to 30 minutes to question Starr. Delahunt asked that
Kendall be given two hours, a motion that was defeated along party
lines, 21-16.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about one of the gravest constitutional events in our
national history,'' Delahunt told reporters after the vote. ``We're
not talking about the dredging of Boston Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat,
questioned Starr about numerous allegations of conflict of
interest, including his contacts with lawyers for Paula Corbin
Jones, whose sexual-harassment lawsuit against Clinton was
instrumental in the disclosure of the president's affair with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan told Starr he cited the conflicts because ``if your
credibility is tainted by bias or poor judgment on your part, this
committee and the American people must at the very least treat the
many inferences that you draw in your referral with extreme caution
and must question whether your referral is, indeed, the whole
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats repeatedly protested Hyde's decision to limit each
committee member's cross-examination of Starr to five minutes. And
Hyde, seated beneath a portrait of former Representative Peter
Rodino, the Democratic chairman of the Nixon impeachment hearings,
grew increasinly exasperated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're disrupting the continuity of these proceedings,'' Hyde
replied at one point to a protest from Representative Mel Watt, a
North Carolina Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disrupting a railroad,'' Watt retorted.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as the partisan rancor continued to roil, Hyde turned to
the committee Democrats and said: ``I hope the seating arrangement
suits you. That's about all that hasn't been complained about
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several committee Republicans were disappointed in
Starr's evaluation of the findings in all his investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Bob Barr of Georgia, one of the first lawmakers
to call for impeachment hearings, said he did not believe Starr
fully investigated the use of confidential FBI files by White House
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Starr determined that only two low-level operatives had access
to the files and did not misuse them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my understanding that there are a number of people that
have not yet been deposed or fully deposed in that case,'' Barr
said. ``I really would appreciate it if you would check on that and
so we don't completely close the door on that.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several Republicans seized on Starr's suggestion
that Clinton's alleged efforts to help Lewinsky find a job at a
time when she falsing denying her relationship with him to Jones's
lawyers may constitute an additional charge of bribery.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, the committee was scheduled to hold a
close-door meeting to consider Hyde's request for staff lawyers to
take private depositions from four other individuals, including
Bruce R. Lindsey, Clinton's deputy counsel and trusted personal
adviser, and Robert Bennett, Clinton's lawyer in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also wants depositions from two individuals familiar with
former White House volunteer Kathleen Willey: Democratic
fund-raiser Nathan Landow and Willey's lawyer, Daniel Gecker.
</P>
<P>
   Willey has accused Clinton of groping her near the Oval Office
in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
