<SLUG> BC-FILM-PAKULA-APPRECIATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALAN J. PAKULA: A SAVVY VISION OF THE PUBLIC WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICK LaSALLE  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Alan J. Pakula died Thursday in an incident as bizarre
as a scene from a movie _ but not one of his own.
</P>
<P>
   He was driving on the Long Island Expressway, 30 miles east of
Manhattan, when a metal bar smashed through the windshield of his
car and hit him in the head, causing him to crash into a fence. The
metal bar apparently had been struck by a vehicle ahead of him and
sent flying through the air.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-year-old director of ``All the President's Men'' leaves a
legacy of more than a dozen pictures, some great, some merely good,
but virtually all infused with his intelligence and worthy of sober
appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   While other directors might have specialized in probing emotions
and inner conflicts, Pakula concerned himself with the workings of
the exterior world, particularly social issues, the law and
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although his main artistic interest was the world of masculine
conflict, he could be a superb director of women, and his films
were far from emotionally tepid or pitched on one note.
</P>
<P>
   He guided Jane Fonda and Meryl Streep in their wrenching and
complex Oscar-winning performances in ``Klute'' (1971) and
``Sophie's Choice'' (1982), respectively. In those films and
others, powerful emotions were presented against a background of
social, legal or political events.
</P>
<P>
   In the thriller ``The Parallax View'' (1974), Warren Beatty
played a reporter investigating the assassination of a senator. Two
years later Pakula told the story of Watergate in the style of a
political thriller, in ``All the President's Men.''
</P>
<P>
   He guided Liza Minnelli to one of her best performances in ``The
Sterile Cuckoo'' (1969; his debut as a director). Bonnie Bedelia
shined in ``Presumed Innocent'' (1990). Pakula did not have as much
luck with Julia Roberts in ``The Pelican Brief'' (1993).
</P>
<P>
   Before turning to directing, at age 41, he was a producer of
such high-quality films as ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' (1962), ``Love
With the Proper Stranger'' (1963) and ``Inside Daisy Clover''
(1965).
</P>
<P>
   Pakula's last film, ``The Devil's Own'' (1997), was not one of
his best, but it was vintage Pakula, with political issues having
direct personal consequences. In that one, Harrison Ford portrayed
an Irish New York cop and Brad Pitt played an Irish terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
