<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-ARMS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS: IRAQ HAS NETWORK OF OUTSIDE HELP ON ARMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Iraq is using an outside network of front
companies and smugglers to supply centers around the country with
parts for illegal weapons systems, arms control experts said this
week. Iraq has also made efforts to produce some components abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The well-disguised centers inside Iraq are not considered likely
to be accessible to U.N. arms inspectors now back in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that evidence may be fragmentary, but that as Saddam
Hussein and those who watch him shift their focus to Iraq's ability
to rearm in the future it is apparent that Iraq has access to vital
components _ ready-made or built to specifications _ for weapons
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Khidhir Hamza, a former director of Iraq's program to devise a
nuclear weapon who defected in 1994, said in an interview on
Wednesday that in the nuclear area there was ``general planning for
removal outside Iraq of some sensitive work or possibly work that
requires some imports.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to do it outside and bring the thing back home,''
he said of Iraqi plans either to produce nuclear components abroad,
among them devices to trigger nuclear reactions in warheads, or to
import crucial parts to make arms in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Hamza, who arrived in the United States in 1995, said that at
the time he left Iraq a friend of his was importing electronic
parts for the military from a front company in Jordan that bought
the equipment in Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds of these companies in Jordan,'' he said.
``They have a whole system of runners in ordinary cars.'' He said
that Iraq repaired its radar after the Gulf War by smuggling in
parts.
</P>
<P>
   Hamza and others say that there are front companies as far
afield as Southeast Asia and overseas bank accounts from the
Persian Gulf region to Latin America to draw on to pay for
purchases. Smugglers pack valuable pieces in personal luggage.
Circuit boards in foam-padded bags cross the border from Jordan for
a small bribe, perhaps a bottle of whiskey, he said. Plastic bags
stuffed with goods are stored in the empty tanks of returning oil
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   And that is a monitored border.
</P>
<P>
   At the Center for Strategic and International Studies in
Washington, Anthony H. Cordesman, a co-director and an expert on
the Middle East, said that far more material was smuggled in on
trucks through Turkey, where a more porous border abuts the
semiautonomous Kurdish region of northern Iraq. Imports are
scattered around the country to a network of small centers working
to reconstitute arms. The centers are protected by Hussein's most
trusted security forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scattered throughout the country,'' Cordesman said. ``Not
only do you have small centers and duplicative efforts, but you
have groups that are now dedicated to using civilian covers to hide
and maneuver what they have left around.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has tried in the past to put private civilian property
off-limits to the U.N. Special Commission, known as UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly governments help when Saddam needs offshore research or
perhaps production centers, Iraqi exiles and some U.S. experts say,
although they disagree about the importance of projects in
countries like Yemen, the Sudan, Libya and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear experts were recently surprised to learn that the
director general of Iraq's nuclear research center, which Baghdad
insists is not developing arms, has been visiting India's leading
nuclear research laboratory. The previously unreported presence of
the Iraqi, Abdulkadir Abdulrahman Ahmed, was discovered when a
computer hacker got into the Indian center's files, Hamza said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that over the years Iraq had nurtured a ``deep and
multilayered cooperation'' with India that seemed to have cooled in
recent years. ``But it seems to be back now.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential for offshore work was highlighted when the United
States bombed a factory in the Sudan that U.S. intelligence had
concluded may have been making chemical warfare components for
Iraq. Although the evidence for that charge has been challenged,
the fact remains that there is broad cooperation between Iraq and
Sudan, some arms experts and diplomats in Baghdad say.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Duelfer, deputy executive chairman of UNSCOM, which is
charged with disarming Iraq and ensuring that the Iraqis cannot
rebuild prohibited weapons, said that vigilance by the commission
and the cooperation of countries dealing with Iraq, or through
which Iraqis may be shipping goods, was essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offshore work is more difficult to investigate,'' Duelfer
said. ``We have seen what happened in the past. Iraq set up front
companies in the 1980s and it is reasonable to suspect a
continuation. We have to monitor this very carefully.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Full cooperation, however, has not always been forthcoming,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists published an
article written jointly by an American and a Russian _ William C.
Potter, director of the Monterey Center for Nonproliferation
Studies, and Valdimir Orlov of the PIR Center for Policy Studies in
Moscow _ documenting how Iraq was able to buy gyroscopes for
missile-guidance systems from Russian stocks in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   At the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace in Washington,
Joseph Cirincione, director of the nonproliferation program, said
Iraq might also be shopping for scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``A senior Ukrainian told me just last month that he personally
knew of a couple of scientists from Ukraine who had given up hopes
of working there and had gone to Baghdad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts, however, caution restraint on seeing too much
danger from former Soviet-bloc scientists.
</P>
<P>
   David Albright, president of the independent Institute for
Science and International Security in Washington, said that while
the Iraqis would ``take whatever they can get, that they can get
away with, they don't want spies, and they will be hypersensitive
that outsiders would be spies.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright, a nuclear expert who has worked in Iraq for the
International Atomic Energy Agency, said the Iraqis were also able
to go it alone in critical areas.
</P>
<P>
   Spurgeon Keeny, a former government arms official who is now
president of the private Arms Control Association, also in
Washington, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would make the cautioning point that foreigners stand out in
a situation like that and would probably come to the attention of
Unscom or reporters in Iraq unless they were totally isolated,'' he
said. He added that outsiders would also not be as easy to control
as Iraqis, who live in a state of terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hired guns would be free to come and go,'' Keeny said.
``Saddam Hussein doesn't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that there was no specific evidence of significant
work being done abroad on behalf of Iraq, again at least in part
because the Iraqis would not trust scientists abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Hamza, the Iraqi nuclear expert, said that a few years ago an
Iraqi scientist sent to work on a project in Yemen, where there was
``large-scale cooperation,'' defected to Sweden, exposing the plan.
Libya has been less cooperative with Iraq, Hamza said, although
many Iraqis live and work there.
</P>
<P>
   The Sudan, he said, is suspect as a partner because of its
Islamic militancy. The Sudan has been cooperative in turning over
or expelling suspected terrorists in order to improve its relations
with the West, and may be regarded as unreliable. Money is no
barrier, Hamza said. He said the Iraqi government sent out
relatives of officials, merchants, even phony defectors to set up
bank accounts abroad, sometimes laundering money through small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   These couriers always knew that their families or colleagues
were virtual hostages in Iraq and would be harmed if they did not
carry out orders, Hamza said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
