<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PORN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE BLOCKS INTERNET SMUT LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge Thursday temporarily blocked a new federal law
intended to shield children from online pornography. Free-speech
advocates had asserted that enforcement of the measure, which was
to have gone into effect Friday, could violate the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Lowell A. Reed Jr. of U.S. District Court in
Philadelphia, issued a temporary restraining order blocking the law
for 10 days, until Dec. 4. Full hearings on the matter are
scheduled for Dec. 8 and 9. Reed is likely to extend the order
until the hearings are held, said Ann Beeson, a lawyer for the
American Civil Liberties Union, which is fighting the law.
</P>
<P>
   The law, the Child On-Line Protection Act, would make it a crime
for operators of commercial Web sites to make certain types of
graphic material available to those under 17.
</P>
<P>
   The suit challenging the act was filed on Oct. 22, hours after
it was signed into law by President Clinton. The case is being
brought by 17 online publishers, retailers and other organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
