<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 As Investment Bankers Turn, Layoffs Hit Volpe, Brown, Whelan  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Just in time for the holidays, another Bay Area investment bank is
lowering the ax _ and not, unfortunately, on the trunks of
Christmas firs.
</P>
<P>
   In what is fast becoming a trend from Wall Street to Montgomery
Street, San Francisco's Volpe Brown Whelan is laying off about 30
employees, or 17 percent of its workforce, confirms James Feuille,
the boutique firm's head of investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to size the firm to be lean, mean and
efficient,'' says Feuille. ``We wanted to be in a good position (in
the event of) a sustained down market.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's never a good time to deliver this kind of
news, but getting a pink slip a month before Christmas is worse
than finding coal in your stocking. And While Volpe is spreading
the layoffs from top to bottom (many coming on Friday the 13th, no
less), some of the trimming is still coming off the top of the
tree. Two Volpe managing directors (who are akin to being partners
at the limited liability corporation) were given their walking
papers, Feuille says.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the bottom line is that Volpe is slashing costs.
While the market has rebounded sharply, deal flow has slackened and
market uncertainty abounds. Volpe is a niche player with
aspirations of becoming a formidable regional bank. Or so it says.
But for now, it relies on small companies, which were slammed last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Volpe isn't alone. BancBoston Robertson Stephens, J.P.
Morgan, Merrill Lynch and many other firms have announced job cuts,
too. And there are more from whence they came. 1999 is expected to
be a tumultuous year for investment banks and brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   While massive layoffs aren't likely _ such as those that
succeeded the crash of 1987 _ firms will continue to notch their
belts while high-paid bankers, analysts and brokers scurry to find
more stable situations, says Don Putnam, president of Putnam,
Lovell, de Guardiola &AMP; Thornton, a San Francisco investment
boutique.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brokerage world is going to be an increased world of
chaos. Many people will find themselves in new jobs by the end of
1999,'' predicts Putnam.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, things change. It was just a few months ago that
Feuille was trumpeting his plans to help build Volpe into a
regional power.
</P>
<P>
   So what has come of those ambitious aspirations?
</P>
<P>
   Not a thing, says Feuille, who was head of technology banking
before leaving Robertson Stephens in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to think that we have an incredible opportunity
(to grow) in technology and health care,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some doubting Thomases in the investment banking world
wonder if Volpe isn't just dressing up the business with intentions
to sell. Could that be so?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not, there is still a huge opportunity for us (to
grow). If we sell the firm, we take that opportunity off of the
table,'' Feuille says.
</P>
<P>
   However, for the time being, Volpe will be taking food off some
of its former employees' tables.
</P>
<P>
   MBO FOR ROBBIE FUNDS: The principals of Robertson Stephens
Investment Management finally found a suitable buyer: themselves.
</P>
<P>
   After dancing with a number of prospective suitors, BankAmerica
announced it has reached a definitive deal to sell the Robbie fund
unit to a group of investors led by senior management of RSIM,
including RSIM chief executive Randy Hecht.
</P>
<P>
   No price was disclosed, but analysts pegged its value as high as
$100 million. Robbie investment management, which was founded in
1984, has about $4 billion under management, including $2 billion
in its mutual fund complex.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is how many of the group's high-profile fund
managers are pumping their own nickels into the proposed management
buyout, which is slated to close during the first quarter of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   While it is presumed that most, or all, of them are in the deal,
neither the buyer nor the seller is saying. Hecht was unavailable
for comment. A BofA spokesman would only say that there are
retention agreements with the portfolio managers in place, and the
new owners hope to forge new agreements with the money managers.
</P>
<P>
   Well, let's hope so. The primary asset being acquired is the
stock-picking talent. However, some of their picking hasn't been as
stellar as in the past.
</P>
<P>
   BofA put the Robbie fund group on the block in June after BofA
sold the fund group's sister investment banking unit to BankBoston.
BofA talked to numerous financial concerns before finally opting to
sell the unit to management.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, BofA was in serious talks to sell RSIM to
BankBoston_ the same buyer of the Robbie investment banking unit.
The two sides were close to reaching agreement, but the deal fell
apart largely because selected portfolio managers refused to work
for BankBoston, banking sources say.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners are changing the name of the company (yet again)
to RSIM, and the fund complex will be called RS Funds. It looks
like BankBoston will get sole control of the Robertson Stephens
moniker, after all. But the BofA spokesman was unable to confirm
that as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
