<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUIZ-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Now, Was That Attila or Lincoln?  &HT;       
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A growing number of books offer management advice supposedly based
on the lives of historic or mythical figures. But do these books
say anything unique or new?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick quiz. The following management tips came from
books touting leadership lessons from famous figures. Can you
figure out which tip came from which book?
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Be a skilled communicator.''
</P>
<P>
   (a) Lincoln. (b) Jesus. (c) Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Effective communication is the lubricant of effective
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   (a) ``Star Trek.'' (b) Founding fathers. (c) Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Of all the talents bestowed upon men, none is so precious
as the gift of oratory.''
</P>
<P>
   (a) Ulysses S. Grant. (b) Churchill. (c) Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Be your organization's best stump speaker, with droll ways
and dry jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   (a) Sun Tzu. (b) Lincoln. (c) Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Never allow your (subordinates) too many idle moments.
These give rise to the beginnings of discontent.''
</P>
<P>
   (a) Grant. (b) Churchill. (c) Attila.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Keep people out of trouble by keeping them busy.''
</P>
<P>
   (a) Founding fathers. (b) Lincoln. (c) Attila.
</P>
<P>
   7. `As a leader, it is vitally important that you keep in touch
with your boss on a regular, sacrosanct basis.'' (a) ``Star Trek.''
(b) Grant. (c) Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``If you aren't frequently communicating with the person you
are reporting to, you're asking for trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   (a) Founding fathers. (b) Lincoln. (c) Grant.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Seek casual contact with your subordinates. It is as
meaningful as a formal gathering, if not more so.''
</P>
<P>
   (a) Reagan. (b) Lincoln. (c) ``Star Trek.''
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Leaders must encourage creativity, freedom of action, and
innovation among their subordinates.''
</P>
<P>
   (a) Jesus. (b) Churchill. (c) Attila.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  Answers: 1c. 2a. 3b. 4b. 5c. 6a. 7c. 8c. 9b. 10c. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
