<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING RIVALS THIS SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regional rivalries are what make Saturday's
dawn-til-well-past-dusk college football menu in many ways more
delicious than New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 1 games might mean more, but these MEAN more. Which
means even with more than a dozen games available on over-the-air
and cable TV Saturday, there's room for even MORE.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:30 p.m., while No. 3 UCLA and USC face off in these parts
on ABC and top-ranked Tennessee meets Kentucky on CBS, No. 2 Kansas
State is playing Missouri and No. 4 Florida is taking on rival No.
5 Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Again, that's all at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully for those who happen to be out of their region of
interest but have addressable cable, ESPN GamePlan, that
pay-per-view service that some predicted would lead to all major
games taken off free TV, has stretched itself over the last few
years.
</P>
<P>
   For $11.95, viewers can embrace both K-State-Missouri and
Florida-Florida State during the USC-UCLA broadcast, in addition to
the North Carolina-Duke game at 9 a.m. and the Arkansas-Mississippi
State game (the winner of which faces Tennessee for the SEC title)
at 9:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   When the pay service started up eight years ago as an
experiment, Showtime Entertainment Television (SET) helped ABC find
a way to charge $8.95 to anyone who wanted one of the other games
that the network was already televising. That game depended on
whichever one the cable system decided to put on from the four
choices.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there have been as many as 10 games available for
pay-per-viewers on Saturdays, whether they bought the season
package or individual weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Two dramatic things have happened, according to ESPN's Skip
Desjardin, who's run the station's pay-per-view games the last four
years. Cable systems are devoting as many five additional channels
to pay-per-view, and small-dish sales with DirecTV, PrimeStar,
EchoStar and Dish Network are rising.
</P>
<P>
   And as digital cable becomes more common, there will be even
more pay channels on cable systems, opening the choices to far more
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Although cable itself has increased from about 50 percent of all
TV homes eight years ago to about 70 percent today, the addressable
cable (that which the viewer can call in and order pay-per-view)
has nearly doubled from 15 million to about 28 million. Add in the
dish systems and there are 38 million homes capable of ordering
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the story is that there are more games into more homes
and nothing has been taken away,'' said Desjardin. ``All we did was
add more choices. It's a no-lose situation for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   A system that not long ago seemed tenuous has paved the way for
more additional pay-per-view services. The NFL on DirecTV's
``Sunday Ticket'' has about 700,000 subscribers kicking in $159 a
season. ESPN's ``FullCourt'' expands college basketball coverage.
Recently, DirecTV struck a deal with CBS to air out-of-region games
during the NCAA basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It has also paved the way for the major-league baseball, NBA and
NHL national season pay packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved in this business it can be done technically and
there is an appetite for it with sports,'' said Desjardin.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that cable systems like Time-Warner in the West
Valley are even offering games beyond the ESPN ``GamePlan.'' When
the upstart Military Channel offered (for free) the Oct. 10
Navy-Air Force game, Time-Warner picked it up. The channel is
offering Saturday's SMU-Navy game to some cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   For advertisers who feared the pay games would siphon viewers
away, Desjardin said the numbers have not impacted viewership of
national games.
</P>
<P>
   About the only dent in this system is that not all cable
companies pick up the same games. You could live on one street and
be offered one or two games, while across the street, your neighbor
could have an entirely different selection of games, depending on
the cable system's capacity as well as who at the office is
determining what to funnel in. As a result, it's been up to cable
operators to get the word out on what games are available, and not
all do the same marketing job.
</P>
<P>
   On the upside, Desjardin said as pay cable expands, there might
be less confusion about kickoff times, which are now at the whim of
network programmers. More games can have a 12:30 p.m. kickoff, like
Saturday's bunch, without fear of overlap.
</P>
<P>
   Or that could be done on purpose to make viewers buy the games. &QL; 
THE RADIO SHUFFLE
</P>
<P>
   No official lineup changes have been announced at all-sports
KXTA-AM (1150), but program director Mike Thompson could be in the
position to do so as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Word on the Internet has been circulating about changes that
could affect every time slot except the syndicated Jim Rome and
Scott Ferrall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to conclude this is the time of the year when stuff
happens,'' Thompson said Thursday. ``Everyone's under evaluation.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson also said it wasn't fair to categorize the moves as a
change in philosophy from a ``sports talk'' format to ``guy talk,''
which several stations have tried after deciding that L.A. is not
as hard-core about its sports as other markets.
</P>
<P>
   The morning team of John Ireland and Steve Mason are all but
gone but by their choice. Ireland's workload at KCAL-Channel 9 will
increase with the departure of Tom Murray to Fox Sports News at the
first of the year, while Mason has other projects lined up. The
rumored replacement is a non-sports-driven show from Brian Whitman,
Rick Dees' sidekick on sister station KIIS-FM.
</P>
<P>
   A less active role for Vic Jacobs and the departure of long-time
L.A. sports-talk personality Joe McDonnell, who has been with the
station since June '97 in the afternoon-drive slot, has also been
tossed around.
</P>
<P>
   Will McDonnell have work at the station next week?
</P>
<P>
   ``After a week, probably; after a month, I don't know,''
McDonnell said after a meeting with Thompson on Thursday. ``All I
know is it's not fun seeing my name associated with being fired,
and I'm not the only one in that category.'' &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
__ Afternoon delight: Nationally, the ratings indicate ABC's
``Monday Night Football'' could reach an all-time low. But it won't
be on Los Angeles' account. Through last week's game, ``MNF'' has a
13.8 national rating, which would be an all-time low. But L.A.,
adjusting to the 5:20 p.m. kickoff, has been doing a 15.2 to date,
and the game is usually the highest-rated sports show of the week.
One reason for the overall drop might be the average victory margin
has been 17 points a game, with five games decided by 20 or more.
That doesn't include the Pittsburgh-Green Bay game, in which the
Steelers led 27-0 in the fourth quarter before it ended up 27-20. &QL; 
__ Point/counterpoint: Tonight at 7 p.m. on his KIEV-AM (870) show,
Irv Kaze brings on USC and UCLA alums to pump you up for Saturday's
game. The guests include Anthony Davis, Ron Mix, Craig Fertig, Mike
Garrett and !bold!Paul McDonald on one side and Tom Ramsey, Gaston
Green, David Norrie, Ken Norton Jr. and J.J. Stokes on the other.
Later, KTTV-Channel 11's Rich Garcia has a half-hour preview of the
game (10:30 p.m.), and on Saturday, KCOP-Channel 13's Newy Scruggs
has a half-hour wrapup (10:30 p.m.). &QL; 
__ Morning affirmation with Karl Malone Imitations from KROQ-FM's
Jimmy ``The Sports Guy'' Kimmel. They're simply Karl-rific. &QL; 
__ Your tax dollars at work: KLCS-Channel 58 has, for the first
time, the L.A. City volleyball championships tonight. The
Taft-Fremont match at 5:30 p.m., followed by Palisades-Narbonne at
8 p.m., will have Randy Rosenbloom in the mandatory play-by-play
chair with former UCLA star Liz Masakayan doing color and Geoff
Nathansen as the show's host. &QL; 
__ Big name, but does he back it up?: Fox Sports News landed NHL
Hall of Famer and recently deposed Tampa Bay GM Phil Esposito as
the studio analyst, starting early next month. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
__ Fox baseball guys Joe Buck and Tim McCarver have been relishing
the fact they can be heard in the background of the scandalous
Linda Tripp taped phone recordings of Monica Lewinsky that were
unnecessarily released to the drooling public Tuesday. Apparently,
Fox's Yankees-Indians Game 5 broadcast from Oct. 6 can be heard in
the background on Tripp's end of a conversation. ``That's
hilarious,'' McCarver told USA Today. ``If that's not a sign that
baseball's back, nothing is.'' And if that's not a sign that Tripp
purposely put something on TV that wouldn't distract her while she
tried to entrap a friend, nothing does. &QL; 
__ Unemployed sneaker salesman Shaquille O'Neal, another person
with too much time on his hands, bench-pressed Regis Philbin during
an episode of ``Live with Regis and Kathie Lee'' this week. Then,
when they played a game of one-on-one, Shaq lifted Regis up so he
could dunk. Philbin, who referred to Shaq ``a very hot rap
artist,'' was obviously heavily medicated. &QL; 
__ One of the most intense and emotional sports documentaries
you'll want to see is NFL Films' presentation of ``Anchors Aweigh
For Honor and Glory: The History of Navy Football.'' Most of the
country will see it on CBS affiliates Saturday afternoon. KCBS
Channel 2, however, had picked 01:30 Saturday night/Sunday morning
to sink it into its schedule. &QL; 
__ Goode news, bad news: Fox Sports News anchor/butcher Brad Goode
has left the building, returning to his to infotainment roots. No
more target shooting for us.
</P>
