<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Switching From Big to Small Firms  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I'm trying to find work as director of information
systems for a small to midsized company. I have a lot of experience
working at Fortune 500 firms, and I also have run a small
consulting business. Although I have contacts in most of the large
corporations in my area, I'm having trouble using my ``network'' to
find opportunities in small firms. Any ideas?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer:  &LR; You've got a two-part challenge here _ making contacts
in the small-business world and then convincing those contacts that
you'd be a good fit with their organization.
</P>
<P>
   Where to make contacts? Marcelle Bolding, a human resources
consultant in Oakland, suggests starting with local civic groups
that are gathering places for small-businesspeople, such as the
chamber of commerce or Rotary Club.
</P>
<P>
   Seek out local recruiting or staffing firms that cater to the
small-business market, and get your name into their Rolodexes. And
scan the media _ both the local business press and national
magazines like Inc. and Entrepreneur _ for names of up-and-coming
small companies in your area.
</P>
<P>
   Small companies may be justifiably skeptical about hiring
someone whose life has been spent on the relatively cushy campuses
of Fortune 500 companies.
</P>
<P>
   Small firms need people who can do a lot with limited funds.
They need people who are comfortable working without much
structure. And they need people who can wear multiple hats _ not
just running the computer network, for instance, but helping out
with marketing, sales or even answering the phones.
</P>
<P>
   Tailor your resume and interview responses to show that you can
do all this. Play up the entrepreneurial experience you got as a
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first questions they'll ask is, `You worked for all
these big companies: Why do you want to work for a small one? And
why would you be successful?''' said Linda Surrell, counseling
manager at the Career Action Center in Cupertino. ``You need to
have a good answer for that.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Q: I work for a company with fewer than 10 employees. My
employer has decided to close the office on certain days during the
holiday season, such as the day after Thanksgiving and the day
before Christmas. In order to be paid for those days, we've been
told we must use our vacation time. Is this legal?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Companies have the right to set whatever holiday schedules
they want, giving as much paid or unpaid time off as they feel
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies that shut down for Christmas Eve or the day after
Thanksgiving treat those days as paid holidays, according to Brain
Ashe, an employment lawyer with Seyfarth Shaw Fairweather &AMP;
Geraldson in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like yours, shut their doors during the holidays without
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, for instance, will shut down without pay for an
entire week between Christmas and New Year's as a way to trim
costs.
</P>
<P>
   That's completely legal.
</P>
<P>
   What  &LR; wouldn't  &LR; be legal would be telling employees that they
must take their accrued vacation at a particular time. ``Vacation
connotes that people can take the time off on their own
timetable,'' Ashe said.
</P>
<P>
   Your company's doing the correct thing _ giving you the option
of using vacation time but not forcing you to do so.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be generous, but it's completely legal.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Q: I'm a participant in an employee stock plan that requires
vesting over a period of several years. Is there any law requiring
the company to count my time off on maternity leave toward vesting?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: The Family &AMP; Medical Leave Act and similar state laws
require employers to continue your health insurance when you're on
leave with a new baby.
</P>
<P>
   But those laws don't require companies to maintain other
benefits for you or to count your leave time toward vesting in a
stock plan.
</P>
<P>
   There is one circumstance in which part of your maternity leave
might have to be counted for vesting _ if your company allows
employees to count time off for other medical conditions.
</P>
<P>
   California law says employers must treat pregnancy the same as
other medical disabilities. So if your firm counts time off for
heart surgery toward vesting, it should count your pregnancy
disability leave toward vesting, too.
</P>
<P>
   Note: The question you're asking has caught the attention of
people in Washington, too. Last month, President Clinton asked
Congress to pass a law allowing people to count FMLA time off
toward vesting in retirement plans. Want to make your opinion known
on the issue? Call or write your representative.
</P>
<P>
   Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways,
San Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or
send e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415)
764-2815. We can't respond to each query, but we will answer as
many in print as we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
