<SLUG> BC-CANDESCENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Candescent Builds Flat-Panel Plant in San Jose  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
In a high-stakes effort to win back the flat-panel computer display
market from Asian competitors, Candescent Technologies Corp. said
yesterday that it has begun construction of a $400 million
production plant in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, almost 95 percent of flat-panel displays are
manufactured in the Far East,'' said Harry Marshall, CEO of the San
Jose firm. ``This marks a serious manufacturing effort to bring a
market approaching $20 billion in annual sales back to the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Although the technology was developed here, Japan, Korea and
more recently Taiwan have taken over the market because of lower
production costs than in America. Candescent hopes to change the
economic equation by creating a totally automated production line
outfitted with robots and automated, guided vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Candescent's bright idea has been a long time coming _ and
expensive. Since 1991, it has raised $450 million to develop a new
class of flat-panel displays from several hundred investors
including venture capital firms, banks and insurance companies and
high-tech giants such as Hewlett-Packard and Compaq Computer. Two
weeks ago, Japan's Sony Corp. agreed to invest $50 million as part
of a joint development project.
</P>
<P>
   Candescent's proprietary ``Thin CRT'' product combines
conventional cathode ray tube (CRT) technology associated with TV
screens and conventional computer monitors, with advances in
semiconductor, disk drive and flat-panel manufacturing processes.
The product is expected to offer full-motion, true-color video
image quality, while using little power.
</P>
<P>
   The company's 340,000-square-foot plant at Hellyer Avenue and
Branham Lane in San Jose's Edenvale Redevelopment Project area
marks the first advanced fab facility built in Silicon Valley in
more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Construction is expected to be completed late next summer.
Sample production is slated by the beginning of 2000. At full
production, the facility is expected to have 500 employees and
produce up to 1.2 million 14.1-inch displays per year for portable
and desktop computers. Annual sales could approach $750 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company will begin shipping 5.3-inch displays from its $40
million development fab facility in San Jose in the first quarter
of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the largest venture-backed companies, and it
has the opportunity to win some of a multibillion-dollar market
back to America,'' said Jack Wilson, editorial director of
ComputerLetter.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson was worried about the Candescent's timing. ``There
could be a problem; the flat-panel market appears over-saturated.''
</P>
<P>
   Display industry analyst David Mentley of Stanford Resources
notes that Asian manufacturers overbuilt capacity for 12-inch
displays and that with threatened overcapacity of more than 2
million units, prices have plummeted to about $250 per unit from
$1,000 two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Candescent's Marshall doesn't deny that it looked like a
``meltdown'' six months ago as the Asian economic crisis took its
toll and companies shelved plans to invest in new plants. But he
believes that ``the market is slowly coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the excess of conventional flat-panel displays this
year, Marshall expects supply and demand will be in balance next
year and that there could be a shortage of 3 million or more units
in 2000, when Candescent starts production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
