<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENOAIR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Low-Fare Reno Air Acquired  &HT;       
 By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
American Airlines said yesterday it will buy discounter Reno Air
Inc. in a $124 million deal that will boost American's West Coast
presence, but kill Reno's low-cost pricing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Reno by American, the nation's No.2 airline,
will have the biggest impact on travelers flying in and out of San
Jose International Airport, where Reno is the No. 2 airline with 39
daily departures behind No.1 Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Reno burst into the discount air business six years ago and
constantly sought out routes where it thought it could make a
splash and a buck. But it abandoned routes almost as fast as it
created them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in and out of 39 city combinations in the last five
years,'' said Reno spokeswoman Joanne Smith. ``We were an airline
without much of a niche or a long-term strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Reno serves 14 cities in the West plus Oklahoma City
and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   If American maintains Reno's flights out of San Jose, as
expected, it will inherit the No. 2 position at that airport.
</P>
<P>
   Reno ranks a distant No. 31 at San Francisco International
Airport, with just three daily departures. It does not serve
Oakland International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reno Air has been very important to California travelers
because it's been a low-priced airline with pretty good service,''
said Ed Perkins, an Ashland, Ore., travel writer and former editor
of the Consumer Reports Travel Letter in San Francisco. ``As far as
I can see, this news is all bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reno airline said it had little choice but to find a merger
partner. It lost $12 million on revenues of $384 million last year.
Although it posted a profit of $7.3 million for the first nine
months of 1998 on sales of $294 million, it still was flying with
too many empty seats.
</P>
<P>
   Its planes generally fly with 65 percent of its seats full. That
compares with around 70 percent for American, and American's seats
are higher priced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected to be profitable for the year,'' said Reno Air's
Smith. ``But we had too small a market presence to do well in the
event of a downturn.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno and American have had a cooperative relationship for
several years. Reno has leased airport gates from American in San
Jose and it has extended American AAdvantage frequent flier miles
for all of its flights.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose Airport spokesman Jim Peterson said he does not expect
any Bay Area flight cancellations after American assumes control of
Reno in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``American has been building its presence, east to west, out of
San Jose by adding flights,'' said Peterson. ``Obviously they find
Reno appealing to help them reposition themselves up and down the
coast.''
</P>
<P>
   The purchase will mark the second time that American has
acquired a West Coast discounter. In 1986, it bought AirCal, one of
the first discounters born following deregulation of the airline
industry in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   American of Fort Worth, Texas, made it clear yesterday that it
will leverage its east-west prowess with more north-south
connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acquiring Reno will give our customers the benefits of a more
comprehensive travel network throughout the U.S. and around the
globe,'' said Don Carty, American's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   American has one of the industry's best ``yield management''
systems, which uses complex computer systems based on past
experience and demand forecasts to extract the maximum price for
each seat.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for an airline trying to maximize profit but a
mixed blessing for consumers, depending on how desperately they
need to fly.
</P>
<P>
   American is offering $7.75 for each share of Reno stock, a 5
percent premium to Reno's closing price yesterday. American also
will buy Reno's preferred stock at $27.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Reno shares rose 13 cents to $7.38 yesterday after doubling in
the past six weeks amid takeover speculation. Shares in AMR,
American's parent company, fell $1.63 to $63.13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
