<HEADLINE>
`PRINCE' TO GET ROYAL-SIZED RECEPTION ON WORLD'S SCREENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Size really does matter for biblical epics.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks SKG will open ``The Prince of Egypt'' on 8,000 to
10,000 screens in 40 countries and in two dozen languages between
Dec. 16 and 26 in what's believed to be the widest simultaneous
worldwide rollout ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a stupendous number,'' said film industry analyst Tim
Baskerville. ``It shows that the world has become a lot more
integrated in terms of marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest single market debut for the $80 million project, an
animated version of the story of Moses, will come Dec. 18 in the
United States with more than 2,500 theaters. Belgium, France,
Germany, Hong Kong, Hungary, the Netherlands and Singapore will
have already opened ``Prince'' by then.
</P>
<P>
   Major studio releases typically begin showing in foreign markets
a month or two after their U.S. opening to allow time for dubbing,
testing of marketing strategies and reusing prints from the
domestic run.
</P>
<P>
   But DreamWorks executives believe the holiday season is the
prime time for starting ``Prince of Egypt.'' ``It's the same
holiday around the world, so it makes sense to take advantage of
that on the international release pattern,'' said distribution head
James Tharp.
</P>
<P>
   Early buzz has been positive, particularly since performance by
``Antz,'' DreamWorks' first animated film, has beaten expectations.
Seven-week domestic grosses for ``Antz'' have passed $81 million
while its foreign take has topped $24 million.
</P>
<P>
   Baskerville noted that the gap between domestic and foreign
start dates has been narrowing due to growing worldwide interest in
entertainment. ``Tomorrow Never Dies'' and ``Titanic'' saw
particularly quick foreign rollouts last December.
</P>
<P>
   Four-year-old DreamWorks does not have a foreign distribution
arm. UIP, a Paramount-Universal-MGM joint venture, is handling
``Prince'' overseas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
