<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KENTUCKY-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL RESPECTS PAID AS KENTUCKY GRIEVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl) 
By JOE DRAPE and MICHAEL A. LINDENBERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The quarterback, Tim Couch, served as a pallbearer for his best
friend and former teammate, Christopher Scott Brock. The starting
center, Jason Watts, has been charged with second-degree
manslaughter and drunken driving in connection with Brock's death
and the death of another teammate, Arthur Steinmetz.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a heart-wrenching week for the University of
Kentucky Wildcats _ bus rides to funerals, football practices at
night, tearful sessions with ministers and bereavement counselors.
Breaking down film for their biggest game of the season _ against
the border rival and the nation's No. 1-ranked team, the Tennessee
Volunteers _ could wait. The grieving could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still disbelief and shock,'' Gabe Smith, a junior
wide receiver, said earlier this week. ``Especially when you have
seven wins and you think you are invincible. This brings you back
to earth and makes you realize what is important. There were two
lives lost. Bowl games aren't as important as that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a somber group of friends, the entire Kentucky team who
filed out of St. Pius X Catholic Church on Thursday in the small
northern Kentucky town of Edgewood. They were here to say farewell
to Steinmetz, 19, a defensive lineman who had transferred to
Kentucky, in Lexington, from Michigan State and was sitting out the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, many mourners who had attended Steinmetz's funeral
had traveled to Thousandsticks in Eastern Kentucky for the
21-year-old Brock's services. Brock, who was known as Scott,
attended Eastern Kentucky University, about 20 miles south of
Lexington, but grew up with Couch in Hyden, Ky., and was close to
many of the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   A festive week on campus in anticipation of playing the Vols
(9-0), in which Couch, a Heisman Trophy candidate, would be
showcased on national television, took a harrowing turn early
Sunday when a pickup truck driven by Watts veered off a rural
highway 60 miles south of Lexington, rolled over and threw Watts,
Brock and Steinmetz from the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, Kentucky (7-3) had beaten Vanderbilt, 55-17,
in the last game of the season at Commonwealth Stadium _ a
milestone for seniors like Watts, a three-year starter. They were
en route to a farm to hunt deer. Watts, 21, had a blood-alcohol
content of 0.15 percent _ the legal limit is 0.10 percent. _
according to the Pulaski County sheriff's office, which filed two
felony manslaughter charges and a drunken-driving charge against
Watts.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second time in 16 months that Watts had been charged
in an alcohol-related incident. Last year, he paid a fine after
shooting a teammate, Omar Smith, in the buttocks as they handled a
rifle outside the house they shared in Lexington. A police report
on the incident said that Watts' blood-alcohol content was 0.129
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Watts was initially charged with first-degree assault, but that
later was reduced to unlawful discharge of a weapon, a violation of
a city ordinance, in part because Smith refused to file a criminal
complaint or testify against Watts.
</P>
<P>
   News that Sunday's accident may have been alcohol related roiled
already raw emotions within the University of Kentucky community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a class postponed for about 45 minutes today to discuss
it,'' Brian Riddell, 21, a political science and psychology major
and the president of the Lambda Chi Alpha fraternity, said
Thursday. ``Reaction was sort of mixed. At first people were upset
and really found it to be tragic. When we found out alcohol was
involved, some of the sympathy and compassion has turned a little
bit to anger.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kentucky coach Hal Mumme does not know how his team will handle
the ordeal when it finally takes the field Thursday in Knoxville.
He said he had asked Mississippi State coach Jackie Sherrill for
advice. Last year, the Bulldogs' Keffer McGee drowned in an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Mumme has spent time at the hospital with Watts, who remains at
the University of Kentucky Medical Center after surgery for an arm
injury. Mumme and his staff have been available to their players.
The practices at night under the lights of Commonwealth Stadium are
perhaps more comforting than effective preparation for his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not going to be a lot of emotion,'' said Mumme, a
second-year coach at Kentucky. ``Let's face it, it is not going to
be easy to get emotional about football this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The week has been especially traumatic for Couch. His friendship
with Brock began as toddlers in day care whose walkers had to be
tied to separate ends of a sofa to keep them from fighting each
other. They went to school together, spent the night at each
other's house and played football together in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't quit thinking about all the stuff we've done,''
Couch said earlier this week. ``Every song that comes on the radio,
I remember just things me and him would think about ... so it's ...
you know ...'' Couch then broke down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   At a subdued practice Wednesday night, Couch took a single snap
so as not to aggravate a slight bruise to his upper arm. The early
part of the week he had spent with Brock's family. Now he sought
comfort in Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am looking at it as the biggest game in my life,'' said
Couch, who was highly recruited by Tennessee. ``I always circle the
Tennessee game every year on the calendar. I love playing against
Tennessee. It is a big rivalry and it means a lot to me and it
means a lot to the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Not too convincingly. Not this week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
