<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEADERSHIP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Leadership Lessons From the Legends  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
So you've devoured every book by Tom Peters, Peter Drucker and
Stephen Covey in your ceaseless quest to uncover the secrets of
business success.
</P>
<P>
   Who ya gonna call?
</P>
<P>
   How about Winston Churchill or Ulysses S. Grant?
</P>
<P>
   Or Abraham Lincoln, George Washington, Ronald Reagan, Jesus,
Aristotle, Sun Tzu, Captain Jean-Luc Picard or Attila the Hun?
</P>
<P>
   American publishers are spewing forth an unprecedented stream of
books claiming to offer management lessons from the lives of dead,
fictional and otherwise unlikely figures.
</P>
<P>
   This year's offerings alone have ranged from ``Cigars, Whiskey &AMP;
Winning: Leadership Lessons of Ulysses S. Grant'' to ``Reagan on
Leadership: Executive Lessons from the Great Communicator.''
</P>
<P>
   Such titles amount to only a tiny sliver of the 1,700 or so
books about business published each year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But they're a sliver that didn't even exist 10 years ago. And
the numbers are growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a trend,'' said Herb Addison, vice president
for business books &LR;   &LR; at Oxford University Press, which published
``Sun Tzu and the Art of Business'' in 1996 and is now hoping to do
a similar book based on the life of Confucius. ``We're all digging
up the past looking for possibilities to do books like this.''
</P>
<P>
   What accounts for this spate of leadership books based on dead
or mythical figures?
</P>
<P>
   People are hungry for information about how to get ahead in
today's rapidly changing business world. Publishers, in turn, are
hungry for sexy, new angles that can set their latest management
book apart from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   And some writers seem to be building entire careers churning out
these books.
</P>
<P>
   Wess Roberts, the fellow who brought us ``Leadership Secrets of
Attila the Hun'' is the same person responsible for ``Make It So:
Leadership Lessons from `Star Trek: The Next Generation.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And Donald Phillips _ a management consultant who is also mayor
of Fairview, Texas _ started with ``Lincoln on Leadership'' and
went on to write ``The Founding Fathers on Leadership'' and
``Martin Luther King Jr. on Leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of these books are carefully documented, with scores of
footnotes referring to historical sources. Others should really be
filed under fiction.
</P>
<P>
   But the actual advice in nearly all of them is pretty
conventional and virtually interchangeable.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Grant book reveals that the general's
management practices included ... (drum roll, please) ...
surrounding himself with good people, treating subordinates fairly
and trusting himself to make good decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan book, meanwhile, reveals that his success as a leader
was due to such less-than-shocking traits as being decisive,
communicating well and learning from mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes a good leader is pretty straightforward and
timeless,'' said David Vogel, a professor at the Haas School of
Business at the University of California at Berkeley. ``It's
unlikely, if not impossible, that any of these books contain
insights that aren't already known and available in other ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The granddaddy of this whole trend is the Attila book, first
published in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   It offers scores of pithy tips that make the fifth century
steppes of Asia sound amazingly like an enlightened 1998 boardroom:
</P>
<P>
   ``A wise chieftain never kills the Hun bearing bad news.'' Or,
``Wise chieftains grant both authority and responsibility to those
they have delegated assignments.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth? Almost nothing is really known about Attila's
personality or leadership style.
</P>
<P>
   There's certainly no historical evidence that Attila really
expected ``continual improvement'' from his followers, as the book
claims. Or that _ like some Silicon Valley team leader _ he
encouraged ``creativity, freedom of action and innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the Huns in general ruled an empire of widely
diverse people and exacted tribute from their allies as well as
their enemies,'' said Thomas Burns, an Emory University historian
who specializes in Attila's era.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as far as Attila, we know virtually nothing,'' Burns
continued. ``If a book is telling you these kinds of things about
Attila, someone is making it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there's more of a written record of Jesus' activities
as a leader. And in ``Jesus CEO: Using Ancient Wisdom for Visionary
Leadership,'' Laurie Beth Jones offers tips for managers based on
Jesus' life.
</P>
<P>
   Jones divides the book into more than 85 very brief lessons
about Jesus as an executive.
</P>
<P>
   They include: He Had a Plan. He Formed a Team. He Was a
Turnaround Specialist. He Kept in Constant Contact with His Boss.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' nuggets don't address the really hard questions, like how
Jesus-the-CEO would reconcile compassion for his workers with
shareholder demands for major layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And some readers might find her analogies a bit reductionist.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how she refers to Jesus' temptation by the devil:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the wilderness, Jesus was given several `business
opportunities' that did not relate to his mission. ... He resisted
them because they did not fit his mission statement.''
</P>
<P>
   And she describes Jesus' appearance at Galilee after his death
as a kind of team-building exercise:
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jesus returned from the dead, he prepared a fish barbecue
on the shore _ sort of a `team picnic,' '' Jones writes.
</P>
<P>
   Some books such as the ones on Lincoln and the founding fathers
can be interesting from a historical angle _ sort of a Cliff's
Notes version of American history for busy executives.
</P>
<P>
   But the history is pretty shallow. And the management advice is
simplistic and stereotyped. Some tidbits from the founding fathers
book:
</P>
<P>
   ``Be prepared for even the worst-case scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When people really care about a cause, they will not only act
on their own initiative, they'll move mountains to get the job
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Star Trek'' book, on the other hand, doesn't suffer from a
lack of historical depth.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it goes to the other extreme. Most of the book is made
up of lengthy retellings of ``Star Trek'' episodes _ so lengthy
that even this reader, an avid ``Next Generation'' fan, couldn't
bear it.
</P>
<P>
   The reward for boldly going through pages and pages of narrative
about Cardassian maneuvers and residual theta-band emissions? Bits
of wisdom such as: ``In space, officers can ill afford to allow
their crew to become distracted by misdirected competition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Churchill on Leadership: Executive Success in the Face of
Adversity,'' by Steven Hayward, is one of the few books to paint
its subject with any kind of detail and nuance.
</P>
<P>
   That may be because the author has a Ph.D. in history. It may
also be because Churchill himself left behind many explicit
writings and statements on leadership _ some of which are quite
incisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success is going from failure to failure without loss of
enthusiasm,'' Churchill is quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Other books such as the ones on Grant and Reagan gloss over
their subjects' significant failings as leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Grant was a great general but a disastrous president. Reagan
changed the political direction of this country but also oversaw
the Iran-Contra scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Grant and Reagan books devote only a few brief pages to
these debacles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Some observers say that leadership books about historic or
mythic figures are popular for precisely this reason: The subjects
are distant enough that readers can overlook their flaws in a way
that's impossible with real-life business leaders like Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a general cynical attitude (about work) and a
jaundiced view about modern leaders, so we look to people from
other places and times,'' said Jim Meindl, a management professor
at the State University of New York at Buffalo who is studying the
portrayal of CEOs in the media.
</P>
<P>
   But reducing the complex realities of leadership into neat
kernels of advice doesn't necessarily do anyone a service.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have something useful if a biography could capture these
people in all their complexity,'' said John Case, executive editor
of the Harvard Management Update. ``It's the complexity that's
missing from these books. The problem is the idea that you can take
this advice and boil it down to some interchangeable nuggets. It
loses what is unusual about these people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
