<SLUG> BC-UNION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Bank of Tokyo To Trim Stake In Union Bank  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
In a local reverberation of Japan's banking crisis, Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi plans to sell part of its stake in the parent
company of Union Bank of California through a $750 million public
stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   The secondary sale of stock will trim Bank of Tokyo's ownership
in Union's parent, UnionBanCal Corp., to between 62 and 70 percent
from the current 82 percent, depending on how many shares are sold,
said Union Chief Financial Officer David Matson. Union expects the
offering to take place before April.
</P>
<P>
   By selling a portion of its holdings, the Bank of Tokyo will be
able to do what it's long said it wanted _ avoid an outright sale
and keep a controlling stake in San Francisco's Union, which has
the third-largest market share among California banks.
</P>
<P>
   The sale will take place at the market price of UnionBanCal's
stock at the offering date. The shares of Union's parent company
rose $1.50 to $99 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of Tokyo, Japan's largest financial institution, has been
hit hard by East Asia's slumping economy and needs the sale's
proceeds to shore up its financial position, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Japanese banks, Bank of Tokyo is loaded down with bad
loans. For the fiscal year ended March 31, it lost more than $6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bank of Tokyo is one of the strongest banks in Japan, but that
doesn't mean they're insulated from what's going on in the
market,'' said Thomas Theurkauf, an analyst with the New York
brokerage Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Bank of Tokyo ``intends to maintain a majority ownership
interest in'' Union after the offering, the California bank said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, other Japanese banks are in headlong retreat from
Europe and North America, closing branches and selling
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Sumitomo Bank Ltd., for example, sold its entire interest in its
California unit, Sumitomo Bank of California, to Utah's Zions
Bancorporation earlier this year at a fire-sale price of $546
million.
</P>
<P>
   With $31.4 billion in assets and 244 offices throughout
California, Union is considered the crown jewel of
Japanese-controlled banking operations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Union's chief executive, Takahiro Moriguchi, is Japanese, but
most of the other top executives are U.S. banking veterans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the stock offering, UnionBanCal said it filed
plans with the Securities and Exchange Commission to issue
$750million in debt securities, which would finance a $500 million
buyback of its shares.
</P>
<P>
   Of that amount, UnionBanCal said it plans to repurchase $250
million in stock from Bank of Tokyo and up to $250 million in
shares held by other foreign institutional shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, UnionBanCal said it will carry out a 3-for-1 stock
split effective December 21. It also will boost its quarterly
dividend 36 percent to 19 cents a share after the stock split.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the stock split and the the sale of Bank of
Tokyo's position to the public should increase the number of shares
that are traded, making it easier for investors to buy and sell
UnionBanCal's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the combination of moves should make UnionBanCal
more attractive to investors. Still, some shareholders may abandon
the stock because they were hoping for a sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, this is a positive,'' said Van Kasper &AMP; Co. analyst
Joseph Morford. ``But there were some shareholders in the stock
based on takeover speculation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
