<SLUG> BC-LIVENT-BROADWAY-RESCUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOAN FROM LIVENT BOARD MEMBERS KEEPS CURTAIN UP FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
   (smw) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some of Livent Inc.'s board members came to the
Broadway theater company's rescue on Thursday, lending it $5
million, enough to keep the curtain up for 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which filed for bankruptcy protection on Wednesday,
is seeking loans of tens of millions of dollars more, which
executives say they need to pay salaries and other expenses while
the company reorganizes its financial matters.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nathan, a spokesman for Livent, said Thursday that he could
not comment on what moves the company may take to reduce costs as a
result of the bankruptcy filing.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Livent has canceled one of its productions of
``Ragtime,'' which is now performing in Minneapolis and was
scheduled to move to Seattle and to Boston in late January. The
company said it is trying to reschedule dates in Seattle and
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But a call to Ticketmaster Thursday found that agents were still
selling tickets to Boston performances in late January at prices of
as much as $75 a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan said he could not comment because of legal restrictions
relating to the bankruptcy filing.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Livent's other shows, including the musical ``Ragtime''
in New York, are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the company's two founders, Garth Drabinsky and
Myron Gottlieb, angrily disputed the accusations that Livent's new
managers have made against them. On Wednesday, the company's
management team, led by Michael Ovitz, the former president of Walt
Disney Co., had blamed Drabinsky and Gottlieb for the company's
financial failure, saying that the two men had engaged in a
widespread corporate fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky and Gottlieb said in a written statement that the
management's contention that they had improperly funneled
themselves more than $7.5 million of Livent's money was
``completely false.''
</P>
<P>
   They said that they would soon respond ``strongly and
factually'' to the accusations made by Ovitz and Livent's new
executives, who have filed a lawsuit against them that seeks $145
million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The company would not identify which directors had agreed to
lend the company a total of $5 million, saying that such
information was not significant. But the board includes many
wealthy individuals, including Ovitz; Thomas H. Lee of Boston, the
owner of a buyout firm; Conrad Black, a Canadian publishing
magnate; and A. Alfred Taubman, the owner of shopping malls and the
chairman of Sotheby's auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Without the loan, Livent would have been forced to dismiss its
employees and close its plays, Livent's lawyers told a judge at a
hearing Thursday in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Livent has retained investment bankers at S G Cowen to help it
find a buyer or a new partner, and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette to
advise it on how to reorganize its financial affairs if a buyer or
new backer cannot be found.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
