<SLUG> BC-ABC-LABOR-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR BOARD BACKS ABC ON ITS LOCKOUT OF STRIKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J.)   (af)  
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a major setback to ABC's off-camera television
workers, a federal official dismissed their union's unfair labor
practices complaint against the network Thursday, declaring the
company's 17-day-old lockout of about 2,200 workers legal.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by the National Labor Relations Board's regional
director for New York City came one day after ABC obtained a court
order in Los Angeles preventing union picketers from interfering
with the network's news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides planned to return to the bargaining table Friday
for the first time in more than six weeks, meeting with federal
mediators in Iselin, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very vindicated,'' said Julie Hoover, an ABC
spokeswoman. ``We are very pleased, because we always believed we
had behaved honorably and appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the union, the National Association of Broadcast
Employees and Technicians, said they would immediately appeal the
decision to the labor board's general counsel in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, they said, they looked forward to the negotiations
and were pleased with the success of their campaign to keep
politicians and celebrities _ most recently the boxer George
Foreman _ off the network's programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No union places all of its efforts or its hopes in a court or
in the labor board,'' said Tom Donahue, a spokesman for the union,
known as NABET. ``When you are engaged in this kind of dispute, you
are working multiple fronts. On every other front, we are
pressuring the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The lockout was ABC's response to a 24-hour strike on Nov. 2
that the union called to complain that the network had not provided
a detailed list of how much individual medical procedures would
cost under a new health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing the complaint, the labor board's regional
director, Daniel Silverman, wrote that ABC had done what it could
to get the information from its insurance companies and provide it
to the union promptly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were sufficiently forthcoming and timely,'' Silverman
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman's ruling that there was no unfair labor practice means
that ABC is legally allowed to lock out its workers for striking.
Both sides said Thursday that they were eager to end the lockout,
but the network continued to say that it would not let the workers
return until the union agreed to warn it before any similar
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say that giving the notice demanded by ABC _ 72
hours for in-studio programs and two weeks for on-the-road shows _
would weaken their ability to pressure the network.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Responding to Silverman's ruling, Robert Iger, president of ABC,
wrote in a memo to all network employees Thursday: ``While our
legal right to lock our NABET-represented employees out has been
affirmed, we take no pleasure in doing so. While the most recent
focus has been on the union's walkout and the company's lockout, I
want you to know that the company's ultimate objective continues to
be to achieve a new labor agreement with NABET.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Labor Alexis Herman, who had urged leaders on both
sides to return to the table, Thursday praised the resumption of
negotiations. The union members have been working without a
contract for 19 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that when the company and the union sit down
with the mediators and work through their differences, they will
find common ground and settle this dispute,'' Ms. Herman said in a
statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
