<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MIDSTREAM-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE THE RENOVATION, CONSIDER THE RETURNS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 22)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)  (af) 
 By JAMES SCHEMBARI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems that every house in my neighborhood is being renovated.
All summer, Dumpsters occupied one driveway after another, and an
angry hive of power saws started buzzing every morning, though
politely waiting until 8.
</P>
<P>
   This gave my wife a case of Dumpster envy. As a result, we have
redone our master bath, so that the door no longer bangs against
the toilet. And now, she has her sights on the cluttered family
room.
</P>
<P>
   Boomers are nesting, striving to create the perfect space in
which to raise their children. Kitchens are expanding, rooms are
being added, bathrooms are going upscale. Americans spent an
estimated $119 billion on home improvements last year, according to
the Census Bureau, up from $46 billion in 1980, and contractors say
the pace has picked up this year.
</P>
<P>
   Not all renovations make financial sense, however. While fixing
the bathroom was a no-brainer, my wife wants to add more toy
storage in the family room, somehow forgetting the inclination of
our children to ignore the latest in shelves for the convenience of
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to renovate is often an emotional one, and my wife
has a lot of company in wanting to make our home more inviting. But
from an economic standpoint, that can be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motivation of Americans to improve their homes is so
strong that they may make choices that are not good investments,''
said Paul Deffenbaugh, editor in chief of Remodeling magazine.
``Depending on circumstances, remodeling is usually not as good as
a 401(k).''
</P>
<P>
   That may sound coldblooded, but the truth is, we should treat
our houses as investments as well as homes if we want to afford
those condos in Florida when we retire. And contractors say more
people are realizing that.
</P>
<P>
   In the 80s, homeowners were throwing money at remodeling
projects with little concern for future value, said Joseph Matta of
Masterwork Kitchens in Goshen, N.Y. ``It was a frenzy,'' Matta
said. ``Now, boomers have bought more BMWs, kitchens, baths and
second homes than in the history of mankind. They are experienced
buyers. They want to see the return of their investment.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many of us have only the vaguest idea of what the
financial returns might be on all the hammering and sawing. Sure,
we have heard that improvements to bathrooms and kitchens, compared
with other parts of the house, probably add the most value, but we
have no clue how much. And what about the other rooms? Imagine
pouring money into stocks or mutual funds on such sketchy
information.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, Remodeling magazine studies the payoffs of various
renovation projects. The 1998 results, which have just been
published, can be a useful guide to where to put your money if you
want to maximize your home's value.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a new kitchen, on average, increases a home's
resale value a year later by 87 percent of the construction cost. A
minor kitchen renovation may be smarter, at 94 percent. The lowest
figure is for a home office, at 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that these numbers can change, so the return on
anything you do today may vary by the time you are ready to sell.
If the trend of working from home continues, for example, the
figure for home offices may climb.
</P>
<P>
   Brent and Terri Stuart of Goshen just finished a renovation that
included a new kitchen and full bath. They spent about $60,000 on
the two rooms _ $50,000 on the kitchen, $10,000 on the bathroom. By
the magazine's count, they can expect to recoup $52,400 of their
investment _ $43,500 from the kitchen and, at 89 percent, $8,900
from the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Anne and James Moss of Warwick, N.Y., just finished renovating
their house, a job that included spending about $50,000 on a
kitchen, family room, full bath and a deck.
</P>
<P>
   The return on the project was very important to the couple. They
consulted with experts on what work would increase the value of
their home the most. They learned, for example, that people in
their area were increasingly looking for a unified family room and
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   While just remodeling the kitchen would have cost the couple
about $28,000, for an additional $16,000 they were able to expand
the family room and then combine the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost to redo the kitchen was still going to leave the
house in a form that would not necessarily increase its
marketability by much,'' Ms. Moss said. ``But to do the total
renovation was in fact going to increase the value of the house
significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the magazine's numbers, the Mosses should get back about
$42,400 from their four main projects.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the returns from other types of projects, as calculated
from the magazine's survey: a two-story addition, 84 percent; an
attic bedroom, 83 percent; renovation of a master suite, 82
percent; siding replacement, 71 percent; a new deck, 70 percent,
and window replacement, 68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There is no getting away from how we feel about our homes and
how they reflect who we are. But there is also no getting away from
how important they are to our financial well-being. A bad housing
decision can do a lot of damage. That's why the return on any
renovation needs to be considered before the first nail goes in.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can go wild on the family room with your eyes wide
open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2146EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
