</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERGY-PILGRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUCLEAR PLANT SOLD IN FIRST MULTIPLE-BID AUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., La.)  (rl) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Entergy Corp., a major utility company in the South, emerged as
the winning buyer Thursday in the first multiple-bid auction for an
American nuclear power plant, a 26-year-old reactor on the
Massachusetts coast that sold for $80 million cash.
</P>
<P>
   The auction of the Pilgrim reactor, housed on a 1,600-acre site
on Cape Cod Bay, reflected the growing attraction of nuclear plants
among utilities after a prolonged period of diminished interest
because of their cost and concerns over safety. Most nuclear plants
are safe and have lower operating costs than other kinds of plants.
</P>
<P>
   Just four months ago, the Unit I reactor on Three Mile Island
was sold for $100 million in the first-ever sale of a nuclear plant
in the United States. But unlike the auction for Pilgrim, there was
only one bidder, the Amergen Energy Co., a joint venture of the
Peco Energy Co. and British Energy PLC.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Reed, president of Reed Consulting Group of Burlington,
Mass., said prior attempts at selling nuclear plants had been
``like having a party where no one shows up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you, a lot of people showed up,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten potential buyers expressed interest in buying Pilgrim, owned
by BEC Energy, the parent of the Boston Edison Co., a utility
serving the Boston area. It has been disposing of its generating
plants under a Massachusetts plan to open utilities to competition.
</P>
<P>
   Two utilities ended up submitting bids for the reactor, which
produces 670 megawatts of power. That is considered small among the
104 nuclear plants operating in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The auction demonstrated that a group of utilities that operate
large numbers of nuclear plants are now potential serious bidders
to buy up other nuclear plants as some states force their utilities
to spin off generation as they deregulate.
</P>
<P>
   Some utilities have encountered problems operating their nuclear
plants efficiently, forcing them to shut the plants down for long
periods and passing the high cost of buying power to customers.
</P>
<P>
   A few utilities have faced such severe problems with nuclear
plants that they have decided to shut the plants permanently, a
costly and lengthy process.
</P>
<P>
   But the vast majority of the nation's nuclear plants operate
efficiently and produce some of the cheapest electricity in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   This is one reason why they have become a major attraction to
some large utilities like Entergy, which already operates four
nuclear plants. Although its headquarters are in New Orleans, it
wants to become a low-cost supplier of electricity in other
regions, like New England.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said other utilities that own only one nuclear plant are
likely to sell them. He also predicted that a small number of huge
utilities, like Entergy, Peco, Duke Energy of Charlotte, N.C., and
Southern Co. of Atlanta would acquire most of nation's nuclear
plants. They will end up as major nationwide suppliers of nuclear
power.
</P>
<P>
   Don Hintz, the group president of Entergy Nuclear, a subsidiary
that runs Entergy's nuclear plants, said the acquisition of Pilgrim
was the first of a series.
</P>
<P>
   ``As other nuclear plants become available, we plan to acquire
some of them,'' he said. ``There is going to be a consolidation in
the nuclear industry, where a few companies will own and operate
all the nuclear plants in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the $80 million purchase price, $67 million will pay for the
plant's nuclear fuel. This means the amount paid for the generating
capacity works out to about $20 a kilowatt, compared with about
$500 a kilowatt that has recently been paid for coal-fired plants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981119.0506 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0238 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-WAKE20-COX     11-19 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-WAKE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech's Tarplin has become an oustanding defensive end
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About the time Jesse Tarplin was being recruited by
Notre Dame, Clemson, Florida and Auburn as a senior at Cross Keys
High in Decatur, Georgia Tech was in the middle of a 1-10 season
and Bill Lewis was on his way out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Tech had sent Tarplin letters earlier, but mail from The Flats
had long since stopped. By the time George O'Leary took over as
coach and called the Tarplin household, Tarplin was on his way to
the last of five official visits.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Leary caught his attention. So an unofficial visit was
arranged; Tarplin's parents paid for meals and drove their son to
campus. The night Tarplin returned from his last official
recruiting trip, he committed to Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to be a part of rebuilding Georgia Tech,'' his
mother, Shirley Tarplin, said. ``I'm like, `Yeah, but there are
other schools out there that have got winning teams,' I'm thinking
to myself. But I never said anything. He's so positive. If he said
it, you can look for it to be that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarplin, now a senior defensive end and the quiet leader of the
Georgia Tech defense, has made a believer out of his parents and
helped put the Yellow Jackets within reach of a share in the ACC
championship.
</P>
<P>
   He says the reasons he chose Tech were an opportunity to play
right away, the prestige of a Tech degree, the proximity to his
family.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Leary says Tarplin is the right kind of person to help
rebuild a football program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Jesse,'' the coach said, ``because when Jesse messes
up, he says, `Coach, I did that wrong; let's get it corrected,' and
he moves on. He doesn't go off and sulk. I respect Jesse for that.
When you meet his parents, you know why. They're all
eyeball-to-eyeball people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse and Shirley Tarplin have lived in the same house in
Decatur for 26 years. They have been to every one of their son's
games, from Little League baseball and Pop Warner football to high
school basketball and football to four years at Georgia Tech. For
his career-high 12-tackle performance against Clemson, Shirley
Tarplin was at Death Valley with her husband only two days after
she was in a serious car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Tarplin's father had taken a second job working security for
Crawford Long Hospital at night so he could pay to fly his wife,
his daughter and his granddaughter to Tech games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're supposed to be there for your family,'' Shirley Tarplin
said. ``That's what I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarplin learned responsibility from his parents. He remembers
one hard lesson in particular. As a fifth-grader, Tarplin took an
extra large pencil to school. When his teacher tried to take it
away, he resisted. Not only did he get a trip to the principal's
office, but his parents didn't let him go to Florida for a Pop
Warner championship game with his football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lesson learned,'' Tarplin said.
</P>
<P>
   Tarplin loves being close to his family, both in geography and
in life. He still goes home every Sunday for church and lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how they do it sometimes,'' Tarplin said. ``I've
always had great support from my family. It's one thing I'll
cherish always. A lot of people don't get that from their families,
and it's something you need, especially at the college level.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarplin, who began as a linebacker, missed the first six games
of his freshman year with a broken thumb. He was set back his
sophomore year after he rebroke the thumb, although he played in 10
games. By then, Tarplin had grown into the defensive end that
O'Leary had expected.
</P>
<P>
   In his no-nonsense manner, Tarplin has become one of the ACC's
most dominant defensive linemen. Tech is second in the ACC with 3.3
sacks per game. Tarplin leads the way with 10, double last season's
total.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of so many things,'' Tarplin said. ``I know
my position better, what I can and can't do. I've gotten stronger,
I've gotten quicker. I've got a great supporting cast from end to
end.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
