<SLUG> BC-FBN-BEARS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Season `a grind' for Bears
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They used to be da Bears, a team of national influence
and envy. Now, they are the Bad News Bears, a pathetic symbol of
ineptness. Chicago serves as a case study in how to execute the
painful fall from grace to disgrace. And how to stay there.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years removed from the Super Bowl championship, and the
resulting ``Super Bowl Shuffle'' video, the Bears find themselves
on the bottom. Such stars and personalities as coach Mike Ditka,
Walter Payton, Mike Singletary, Jim McMahon, ``Refrigerator''
Perry, Willie Gault et al. are long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, they have been replaced by forgettable
impostors. These Bears are devoid of star talent, and much of
what's there is injured. Meanwhile, the head of coach Dave
Wannstedt perpetually rests in a figurative guillotine. If the
season continues on its downward spiral, Wannstedt would have to be
a magician to avoid the falling ax.
</P>
<P>
   And the worst is that no one with the Bears (3-7) has a clue how
to reverse things.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at the Georgia Dome, Chicago faces Atlanta, a meeting of
teams headed in opposite directions. While the Falcons (8-2) are
flying high after an impressive victory over the San Francisco
49ers, the Bears are mired in their pitiable wallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me it's been the same thing year in and year out,
and it's frustrating,'' receiver Curtis Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   Their seemingly inevitable trek to another offseason of
rebuilding has frustrated and angered many players, fans and media
members. No. 1 draft choice Curtis Enis is out for the year with a
knee injury. Quarterback Erik Kramer is sidelined, too. Most
significantly, the Bears seem to lack the desire to reverse course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing, it's exhausting, it's disgusting,'' tackle
Jim Flanigan said.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago had won three of four going into its bye week and was
feeling good about itself. Now, Bears fans and the media are
questioning the team's commitment after a catastrophic 24-3 defeat
to the 3-7 Lions on national television Sunday night. They dropped
to 3-7, with no relief in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough mentally on all of us,'' cornerback Walt Harris
said. ``Once you start losing and continue to lose, it becomes a
grind on your mind. It affects you. You just try to hold on and
turn the season around in a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, he said ``years,'' although he meant ``games.'' Just
another indication of how losing has affected the players.
</P>
<P>
   In their Sunday loss to the Lions, the Bears were called for
nine penalties and managed just two plays over 20 yards. Also, they
allowed rookie quarterback Charlie Batch to ``look like Joe
Montana,'' defensive end Mark Thomas said. ``We made him look a lot
better than he is.''
</P>
<P>
   With Kramer out, unproven Steve Stenstrom is expected to start
at quarterback, if his bruised shoulder is OK. If not, rookie Moses
Moreno would get the call. Either way, it does not look good for
the once-proud Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a time when we have to stop looking back and look
forward,'' receiver Bobby Engram said. ``(But) I'm not going to lie
to you _ 3-7 is hard to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
