<HEADER>
A0240 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES20-C     11-19 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stenstrom probable Bears quarterback
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bears backup quarterback Steve Stenstrom practiced
Thursday for the first time this week, and will likely start
Sunday's game at Atlanta (8-2).
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (3-7) almost certainly will be without starting
quarterback Erik Kramer for the third game in a row. Doctors can't
find a tear, but he has symptoms that sound like he has a damaged
rotator cuff, and he also has shoulder tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dave Wannstedt said Kramer, who did not practice, will be
the No. 3 quarterback Sunday, and rookie Moses Moreno will be the
backup.
</P>
<P>
   Stenstrom, a fourth-year veteran from Stanford, came into the
season with a career passer rating of 61.1. The 6-foot-2,
206-pounder, who is in this position only because the Bears waived
Rick Mirer before the season, has completed 28-of-50 passes (56
percent) for 313 yards, one TD and one interception _ good for a
73.2 rating.
</P>
<P>
   Stenstrom's not gifted at any one thing, is considered slow to
read defenses, and is therefore susceptible to defensive schemes
that mix in a lot of coverages.
</P>
<P>
   He did not practice Wedneday with sore muscles in his
non-throwing shoulder and chest after last Sunday's 26-3 loss to
the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   Also for the Bears, starting tailback Edgar Bennett, who had
back spasms Wednesday, practiced Thursday and will start, Wannstedt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson returns
</P>
<P>
   Falcon RB Jamal Anderson practiced Thursday after being held out
Wednesday, and although he never really pushed himself or made any
hard cuts on his sprained left ankle, he said, ''I've got two more
days, and I think it will be 100 percent by Sunday.''... Tim Dwight
practiced for the second straight day after missing more than three
weeks with a strained medial collateral ligament in his knee. ''I
feel fine,'' said the rookie who is third in the NFC with a
26.5-yard kickoff return average. ''It catches once in a while, but
I think that helps it. I'm ready to go, but it's up to (coach Dan
Reeves).'' Reeves is probably going to be cautious. ''I think
because of the position he plays, we may want to give it more time.
We won't decide (any earlier than today),'' he said. ... Cornerback
Ronnie Bradford, who hasn't played defense since straining a medial
collateral knee ligament Oct. 25 against the Jets, will play
Sunday, likely in the nickel and dime defenses. If his replacement,
second-year cornerback Michael Booker, were playing this year as
poorly as he did when he replaced the injured Bradford for a few
games last season, coaches might rush Bradford back into the
lineup.... Safety Chris Bayne, who missed last Sunday's game with a
strained hamstring, is practicing.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the Falcons
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt is using the Falcons as an example. When he was going
over film with his team, he told players, ''They were 2-8 (last
year). If it happened for them, it can happen for us. We just have
to continue to work hard and stay together. That's what the Falcons
have done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bears have games remaining against Tampa Bay (4-6), at
Minnesota (9-1), at Green Bay (7-3), against Baltimore (3-7), and
against Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to problem injuries to Kramer, who was the Falcons
quarterback for the three strike games of 1987 and whom Reeves
tried to sign as a backup last season, Chicago has six players out
for the season on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   First-round draft choice Curtis Enis, a running back, tore the
anterior cruciate ligament in his knee. Also on injured reserve:
defensive tackle Ken Anderson, cornerback Tom Carter, safety John
Mangum, punter Todd Sauerbrun (who was leading the NFL with nearly
a 50-yard average), and fullback Tim Tindale.
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt, who is taking a lot of heat in Chicago after going
7-9 and 4-12 the last two seasons, is bummed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most discouraging thing over the last three years is not
having the opportunity to line up our best players and see if we're
good enough,'' he
</P>
<P>
   said. ''I felt we had an opportunity to make some headway this
season, but a couple of injuries have kind of slowed it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bright spot
</P>
<P>
   Chicago rookie free safety Tony Parrish, the team's second-round
draft choice out of Washington, has been one of the highlights. The
5-10, 206-pounder is third on the team with 74 tackles (trailing
middle linebacker Barry Minter, 91, and strong safety Marty Carter,
92), leads the team with four forced fumbles and has recovered two.
</P>
<P>
   Not-so-bright spot
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason both safeties have so many tackles. The Bears
are ranked No. 26 in the NFL against the run, giving up 134.4 yards
per game. Their pass defense is ranked No. 9, allowing just 186.6
yards per game. Part of that is because teams don't need to throw
much on Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, which has the NFL's No. 2 run defense, allowing just
76.5 yards per game, has the No. 30 pass defense, allowing 247.2
yards. But the Falcons have faced more passes (365) than any other
team, and given up the second-most completions (211) _ a 57.8
completion percentage. By contrast, the Bears have faced just 271
passes, allowing 173 completions (63.8 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Honor roll
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Ray Buchanan was named NFC Defensive Player of the
Week after tying middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle for team honors
with eight tackles, one pass defense, and a 34-yard interception
return to set up a TD.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
