<HEADER>
A0243 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-BMW-ART-2T     11-19 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-BMW-ART-2TAKES-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 22)
</HEADLINE>
  
 BMW 328i: THE BENCHMARK, NOW REBUILT  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One is always anxious when a dear friend has major surgery. Did
the doctors make the correct diagnosis? What if the scalpel slips?
After recuperation, will the patient have the same old zest, or
will the cure prove worse than any minor ailments it was supposed
to remedy?
</P>
<P>
   This year, those of us who've enjoyed the company of BMW's
vibrant 3-Series have spent some apprehensive time in the waiting
room while the car surgeons probed and sliced and sutured. Over
seven years, the last 3-Series established itself as the world's
pre-eminent sport sedan, a car of relatively modest price and
extraordinary poise.
</P>
<P>
   So what if it was a little cramped and austere? Were its
imperfections serious enough to warrant the risks of a redesign?
Would the new Bimmer emerge with plusher seats but a broken spirit?
</P>
<P>
   The bandages are off now, and two sedans, the first of the
next-generation 3-Series, are on sale. Enthusiasts' worries were
unfounded; the operation was a success.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 is more refined, and it mimics the bigger 5-Series in
its features, interior design and appearance. BMW has made
top-to-bottom changes including a new body and a couple of updated
engines, but it has left intact the car's character _ serious but
fun, solid but spritely. The 3-Series has grown up, and if it has
lost some adolescent spunk, it has gained a measure of maturity. It
feels different, but not degraded.
</P>
<P>
   With 30-some variations sold around the world, the redesign is
being phased in. The first to be remade were the sedans; they are
the only all-new '99 models. Coupes will be redone next year and
convertibles in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   BMW is eliminating four-cylinder engines in the American market,
and it has replaced the 318i with the new 323i, powered by a
2.5-liter six. Both that engine and the 328's 2.8-liter six now
have lighter aluminum blocks, and they have variable valve timing,
a bit of wizardry that improves power and economy.
</P>
<P>
   Both have slightly more horsepower and more torque at lower
speeds where it can be put to good use. A new five-speed automatic
transmission is also available.
</P>
<P>
   Some things have not changed. The engines are in-line designs,
valued for their smoothness and simplicity, not the V6s that most
companies _ including BMW's archrival, Mercedes-Benz _ have
switched to (the shorter V6s allow space to be used more
efficiently). And all 3-Series still have the rear-drive layout
that BMW treats practically as a religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to separate the steering from the wheels that
put the power on the street,'' Wieland Bruch, a BMW spokesman,
said.
</P>
<P>
   The sedan has grown, the wheelbase by an inch, the entire car by
1.5 inches. It is slightly wider, and the opposing wheels are
farther apart for better cornering. But when BMW boasts that
``there is absolutely no flab,'' it is not kidding.
</P>
<P>
   The styling is familiar, but freshened. The reverse cant of the
rear roofline, coupled with the forward-sloping outline of the rear
doors, give the sedan a thrusting look. The wheel arches are more
prominent, and the front wheels are about as far forward as they
can go. The round headlamps are even more prominent behind clear
covers, with cutouts calling attention to the shape.
</P>
<P>
   The test car, a fern-green 328i with the sport package _ it
includes a lowered suspension and 7-spoke, 17-inch wheels _ looked
aggressive but also tastefully restrained.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-Series' body structure, already strong, is even more
rigid. High-strength steel accounts for half of the body weight, up
from 4.5 percent, and the body is nearly twice as resistant to
twisting.
</P>
<P>
   The handling is still superb, thanks to the rigidity and the
perfect weight distribution, half over each axle. The wheels track
flawlessly with no drifting, and the car feels glued to pavement.
Steering effort is light _ perhaps a bit too light _ but the driver
gets plenty of feedback.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With the sport suspension and big tires, the ride was jumpy, and
there was more wind noise than one might expect. In terms of quiet,
this is no Lexus, and I'd rather have more engine hum and less wind
rush.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the rear seat is slightly more spacious, and it is
accommodating, in a cozy way, for a couple of adults. A few
features once conspicuous by their absence have been added: the
formerly fixed-in-place steering wheel now tilts and telescopes,
and there are controls on the wheel for the stereo, cruise control
and phone.
</P>
<P>
   The instrument panel, less oriented toward the driver, is more
like the 5-Series'. A single-CD player now fits in the audio panel,
which is more horizontal. The doors and dashboard have accents of
myrtle wood, aluminum-look plastic or an odd high-gloss plastic,
depending on equipment level.
</P>
<P>
   The test car's leather sport seats were up to BMW's high
standards: firm enough to stave off fatigue and bolstered to hold
one in place through aggressive cornering. Adjustable thigh
supports accommodate legs of various lengths.
</P>
<P>
   New safety features include head-protection bags that inflate
out of the roof. There are also side-impact bags in the front
doors; rear-seat bags are optional ($385).
</P>
<P>
   The best safety features, of course, are the ones that keep you
from having a crash. Take the excellent brakes, with ventilated
disks front and rear. A new system regulates the braking pressure
between front and rear wheels, and a cornering brake control helps
to keep the car stable if the brakes are applied during cornering _
a weight-shifting move that can send a rear-drive car into a spin.
</P>
<P>
   The 328i has a lot of thoughtful touches that aren't immediately
apparent. All four windows raise or lower at one touch, and the
rear windows retract completely. Each key remembers its user's
seat, climate-control and radio preferences.
</P>
<P>
   The windows and sunroof can be closed from outside, using the
key in the lock. The hood's safety release pops out when the inside
release is pulled, eliminating the need to fumble for it. Central
locking seals the doors, fuel door and trunk. There is a
rechargeable flashlight, first-aid supplies and a tool kit.
</P>
<P>
   Options include a parking distance control that measures the
distance to objects behind the car, a boon when parking.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints are hard to come by. The lock button is inconvenient
on the center console. Even with its latest dressing-up, the
purposeful interior may strike some people as too plain for the
price. Back-seat passengers are pretty much ignored, with no air
vents or cup holders. Last year's dual-zone temperature settings
are gone, a victim of cost-cutting. And the radio has lost a handy
button that called up weather broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the main criticism is one that carries over: The price.
The 3-Series is more of a sport sedan (like the Audi A4 or perhaps
the Saab 9-3) than an ``entry luxury'' car (like the Lexus ES 300
and a host of others), but that distinction is often lost on
comparison shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Given that a very nice and fully equipped car like the Acura
3.2TL runs just $28,000, the 328i, starting at $33,970, may not
seem like a great value. (The test car, lacking a sunroof or CD
player, had a sticker of $37,245; fully equipped, the 328i
approaches $43,000.) Even the A4 with a V6, which starts at less
than $29,000, includes items optional on the 328i _ a power
sunroof, wood trim, folding rear seat.
</P>
<P>
   The 323i offers a compromise. For $26,970, it offers most of its
sibling's performance and style at a considerable discount. But
here, too, some pretty basic items _ cruise control, center armrest
_ cost extra.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-Series' last redesign, for the '92 model year, was a great
leap; the latest revamping is evolutionary. Still, there is nothing
quite like the 3-Series, with its compact size; its balanced
rear-drive layout; its optimal weight distribution; its solid,
purposeful design. And that is as true now, after a thorough
revamping, as it was before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
