<SLUG> BC-BBN-MVP20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sosa officially `The Man'
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Deep into the summer and beyond, Sammy Sosa argued
with that not he but home run rival Mark McGwire was ''The Man'' as
the two slugged their way through the most epic home run race in
baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Baseball Writers's Association of America begged
to differ for the last time, voting Chicago's Sosa the National
League's most valuable player in a runaway over McGwire. Drawing 30
of 32 first-place votes, Sosa found that 66 homers and a
league-leading 158 RBI count for something.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never considered myself to be 'The Man','' Sosa said, ''but
I considered myself a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Moises Alou, the only other player named on all
ballots, finished third while San Diego slugger Greg Vaughn was
fourth. The Braves placed two players in the top 10, first baseman
Andres Galarraga placing sixth and third baseman Chipper Jones
finishing ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa became only the second player from the Dominican Republic
to win the MVP, joining George Bell who won the award for Toronto
in 1987. For the first time ever, the BBWAA voted two Latin
American-born players as MVPs, Sosa joining Texas' Juan Gonzalez, a
native Puerto Rican who began his career with Sosa in the Rangers'
Gulf Coast League affiliate in 1986. The NL had not had a Latin MVP
since Orlando Cepeda in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ''I put everything together _ played hard as a team player, as a
team leader,'' Sosa said. ''I took everything in my hands and did
everything correctly. Maybe I can do it again. I have a feeling
that I can come back and do everything I did in 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was voted second on 20 ballots and third on three
others. His two first-place votes both came from St. Louis-based
writers. The vote was surely swayed by how each players' team
fared, the Cardinals finishing 19 games behind NL Central Division
Houston while the Cubs made the playoffs for the first time since
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Their comraderie was just as remarkable as their competition,
even as the baseball press and the game itself received criticism
for overplaying McGwire while underplaying Sosa's accomplishments.
The Chicago right fielder shrugged it off then and, in a telling
comment Thursday, restated their funky friendship when asked if he
had talked with McGwire about the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Mentioning McGwire was vacationing in Australia, Sosa said, ''I
want to make a phone call but they don't accept collect calls over
there.''
</P>
<P>
   As special as his season was, Sosa's dedication to his country
excelled it, after the Dominican was ravaged by hurricane Georges.
Sosa was to be on a 6 a.m. flight today to return there to resume
relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of people suffering in my country,'' he said.
''I don't have a lot of time to celebrate right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
