<HEADER>
A0246 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COACHES20-COX     11-19 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COACHES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scott facing West, likely near sharing his fate
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This was Tuesday, the day before Tommy West's future
grew considerably dimmer, and shorter. The Clemson coach was asked
about the state of college football in the state of South Carolina.
With Clemson (2-8) and South Carolina (1-9) having taken such
simultaneous falls from grace, the Palmetto State is one contiguous
low country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really strange,'' said West. ``Never happened before.
Been a crazy year. You look at us, and them, and even the
(Carolina) Panthers, too. I know with us, anything that can go
wrong has. You think nothing else can. And then it does.''
</P>
<P>
   It went bad-wrong for West Wednesday, when he was fired with
three years left on his contract and one game left in his fifth
season: Saturday night's traditional Death Valley bloodletting with
archrival South Carolina, whose coach is nearly as embattled _ and
perhaps imperiled _ as West.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, The Game (6:30 p.m., ESPN2) has become secondary. More
pressing is whether Brad Scott will survive as South Carolina's
coach. If not, who'll succeed him? And more immediate, will West's
replacement hold the promise of the future (Tommy Bowden) or the
past (Danny Ford)?
</P>
<P>
   Those are Clemson's two leading candidates, and factions. Bowden
is this year's Gary Barnett, having taken Tulane to a 9-0 record
and No. 12 ranking. Clemson athletics director Bobby Robinson _ who
hired West in 1993, then fired him Wednesday _ reportedly spoke
last week with Cincinnati athletics director Bob Goin, an associate
AD at FSU from 1981 to 1991 when Bowden was an assistant coach to
his father, Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the elder Bowden dismissed the notion that
his son wouldn't want to coach in the ACC and compete against his
father. That heartened a large contingent of influential Clemson
alumni, IPTAY boosters and some trustees who favor hiring Bowden.
But with Tulane playing Houston Saturday and Louisiana Tech on
Thanksgiving, Bowden _ who has also been mentioned as a successor
to Scott _ likely won't make any decision until after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also considerable sentiment at Clemson for Ford,
who coached the Tigers from 1978 to 1989, went 96-29-4 and won the
school's only national championship. The football program also went
on probation twice, however, before Robinson fired Ford. Yet Ford _
fired by Arkansas after last season and now back living on his
Pendleton farm near Clemson _ has a strong Clemson constituency who
favor his return. Earlier this week, before West was fired,
innuendo even had Ford _ who was in Death Valley when Clemson lost
to Georgia Tech last week _ having reached an agreement two weeks
ago to succeed West.
</P>
<P>
   As for turning back the clock at Clemson, though, listen to
West, shortly after his firing: ``There was a lot of success here
in the '80s. I don't think it's wrong to want to have that success.
But the game has changed a lot since the '80s. The parity in this
game, it's here. I don't know if fans anywhere realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemson fans realized this: The Tigers are one loss away from
their worst finish since 1975. That such calamity occurred in
West's fifth season sealed his fate. Perhaps it will Scott's, too:
This is his fifth season at South Carolina. Going 2-9, even 1-10,
is acceptable in the first year or two. Not in the fifth, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't able to win the close games,'' said Scott, 23-32-1
with the Gamecocks (West is 30-28). ``We have a lot of youth and we
turned the ball over a lot more (25 times, to 13 for opponents)
than in previous seasons. But we were in our share of ballgames and
didn't win a single one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are rather damning for Scott. Yes, he did lead South
Carolina to a 7-5 record in 1994, including the only bowl win in
school history. Attendance soared in 1996-97. But after beating
Ball State in this year's opener, the Gamecocks have lost a
school-record nine straight. That included a home loss to I-AA
Marshall, later a disastrous 17-14 loss at Vanderbilt, which had
lost 22 straight SEC games.
</P>
<P>
   In Scott's five seasons, South Carolina is 13-26-1 in SEC play.
Against teams that finished seasons with winning records, the
Gamecocks are just 2-28-1 in that span.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Vanderbilt debacle, however, that has put Scott's job
in jeopardy. Yet after Saturday's finale, Scott expects to meet, as
usual, with athletics director Mike McGee early next week for their
annual end-of-season review of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's given me great support,'' said Scott, who understands
his predicament. ``He's an old football coach, been through similar
situations in the past. We'll sit down next week and evaluate our
football program after five years, and evaluate the future.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
