<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FSU backup Outzen doesn't back down
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ With a sprig of red hair that sticks up in
front, his nickname, of course, is Rooster. As in bantam. As in
fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Put Marcus Outzen in the ring, his friends say, and he isn't
going to back down. It doesn't matter how big the guy in the other
corner might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever shortcomings other people might think Marcus has,''
Florida State coach Bobby Bowden said, ``he has never lacked for
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good, because the sophomore quarterback will need all the
confidence and moxie he can muster Saturday when he faces the
biggest challenge of his football career: leading No. 5 Florida
State against No. 4 Florida (3:30 p.m., ABC) in a game that still
has implications for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Outzen, 6 feet 2, 220 pounds,was thrust into the role Nov. 7,
when starter Chris Weinke suffered a season-ending neck injury
against Virginia. Outzen came off the bench in the second half of
that game to lead a 45-14 victory. Last week against Wake Forest,
he got his first start and had some modest success, throwing for
164 yards in a 24-7 win.
</P>
<P>
   But all parties _ Outzen included _ agree that it was not the
kind of performance required for the Seminoles to beat the Gators
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing OK; he just needs experience,'' Bowden said. ``I'm
just glad we had a game before this one so he could get his feet
wet.''
</P>
<P>
   Outzen said his ability to move gives him an advantage Weinke
would not have had against Florida's quick defensive front.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can throw any route in this offense, just like Weinke, of
course,'' Outzen said. ``The only thing I add is the ability to run
and to make a big play out of a broken play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles probably won't score a lot of points against
Florida and can't afford to give any away. In that respect, Bowden
said, the young quarterback might need to be reined in a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I can't let him do is get in over his head,'' the
coach said. ``A big game like this usually comes down to turnovers,
and as coaches we have to be aware of that. ``
</P>
<P>
   But if Outzen were afraid of challenges, he wouldn't be at
Florida State. He had been a Florida State fan since age 10 when he
met Bowden at a booster gathering in Destin. Former Seminole
quarterback Casey Weldon was his hero. He never thought of going
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Outzen thought he would serve an apprenticeship behind Thad
Busby and then Dan Kendra. But in 1997, Weinke came back to college
after spending six years playing baseball. And in February, Florida
State signed Jared Jones, a Parade All-American.
</P>
<P>
   He thought about transferring after last season, but Bowden
talked him out of it. His advice: Be patient. You never know what
might happen.
</P>
<P>
   Busby graduated. Kendra suffered a knee injury in the spring and
was lost for the season. Weinke won the starting job but got hurt
against Virginia. Suddenly, in his third year, Outzen is the
starting quarterback against Florida in what is easily the biggest
game of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've done pretty (well) for the opportunities I've
had,'' Outzen said. ``I can't be too shocked and let this thing get
away from me. I believe that things happen for a reason. All I have
ever really wanted was a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, he will get that chance. The whole state of Florida
_ and a good chunk of the country _ will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
