<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite tough times, Dogs' defense decent
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ With apologies to songstress Joni Mitchell, Rich
Robich is a football player who has seen ``Both Sides Now'' _ in
more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman, the Georgia rush end was an Ole Miss Rebel
playing in a losing cause at Sanford Stadium. Now, as a Bulldog, he
has beaten the Rebels at Oxford and Saturday has a chance to do the
same in Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Robich and his defensive teammates have also seen both sides
of the game this year _ making brilliant goal-line stands (South
Carolina), tackling poorly (Kentucky and others) and getting
dumbfounded for a quarter (Florida.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to talk about any negatives about our
defense,'' Robich said. ``I honestly don't feel like we have a lot
of negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the Bulldog nation would be quick to dispute Robich. And
while head coach Jim Donnan agrees there have been some lapses, he
quickly points out a defense for his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you one thing about our defense,'' Donnan said.
``They have been good throughout the year at responding to the
sudden change _ when the offense turned the ball over (South
Carolina) or like the blocked kick (Auburn). And when you consider
(that) both offense and defense (have) been hurt by our lack of a
solid kicking game (both punting and kickoffs), they have played
with poor field position all year. ``
</P>
<P>
   Despite the field position, Georgia's defense has done a good
job of ``keeping the other team out of the end zone,'' Donnan said.
``We haven't given up big plays, except against Florida. We haven't
been as good on third down as I'd like, and we haven't created
turnovers. We have done a good job at stopping the run, even though
people are running more plays on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams have been getting more plays on the Bulldogs for two
reasons, he said: The Bulldogs haven't stopped teams on third down
as much as he expected, and the Georgia offense hasn't picked up
the first downs with the consistency he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Now come the Rebels, a team that has the confidence to gamble _
going for, and getting, a fourth-and-1 against LSU in a 37-31 OT
win _ and the players to make big plays. Quarterback Romaro Miller
and running backs Deuce McAllister (6-2, 215) and Joe Gunn (5-10,
196) have combined for more than 3,500 yards and 22 touchdowns this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have earned the right to be confident,'' Donnan said.
``They have exceeded their expectations. Miller is a versatile
athlete, and McAllister is a big back who can break tackles. And
Gunn is a good back, too. They concern me.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Joe Kines, who has received his share of
criticism this season, has coached from the field and from the
press box.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make football as complicated as you want to,'' Kines
said, ``but it still comes down to getting off the block and making
a tackle. It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also said, ``This team is very versatile and talented.
McAllister is an excellent back, a quality back and Miller is
talented. ... To me, the key, as it has been all year, is get off
the blocks and try to hem up (the running backs). We have to stop
their running game and pressure the quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Adrian Hollingshed, while conceding that the
defense has ``had some tough times this season,'' said because of
the Ole Miss attack, the game ``should be fun and a challenge. We
can't let (McAllister) get into the secondary. If he does, there
could be problems. We have to tackle well and stay low against
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a special game to me,'' the former Rebel, Robich,
said. ``To put on the red and black and play for the Georgia
Bulldogs. I have high expectations. I have had them all year. We
need to take care of these next two games and get to a good bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
