<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vikings have kept Packers on ice at Metrodome
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ He has never met the governor-elect of Minnesota,
but if Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren lived here, he, too, might
have voted for Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   The former professional-wrestler-turned-politician opposes the
use of public funds for a new stadium, a stance that could force
Vikings owner Red McCombs to relocate the franchise to San Antonio.
A loser in five of his previous six visits to the Metrodome,
Holmgren might not mind seeing the place turned into a flea market.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the exception of last year, that's been a house of
horrors for us,'' Holmgren said. ``Even when they didn't have the
kind of talent they've got now, the Vikings played us tough
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the top game of the week, the Vikings can all but relegate
the Packers' playoff aspirations to the wild-card variety.
Minnesota will clinch a postseason berth with a win over Green Bay
and with a loss by either Arizona or New Orleans. A Packers defeat
would leave the two-time defending NFC champions two games behind
in the NFC Central.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikes stunned the Packers earlier this season when
quarterback Randall Cunningham threw for 442 yards and four
touchdowns in a 37-24 victory. Although Cunningham is bothered by a
balky knee that required arthroscopic surgery just 11 days ago,
Minnesota's collection of big-play, skill position performers might
be unmatched.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the NFL bests for this weekend:
</P>
<P>
   _ Upset opportunity: The home team has won all six previous
Pittsburgh-Jacksonville meetings, but that streak will stop Sunday.
The Steelers don't have enough offense to hang with the Jaguars,
who will rely more on the passing game than on rookie tailback Fred
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual matchup: Give the Cardinals credit for identifying
wide receiver Frank Sanders as an essential player and keeping him
from free agency with a contract extension last year. Sanders is
among the NFL's hottest players, and his battle with Washington
cornerback Darrell Green will be worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fantasy play: In the last 15 quarters, the Chicago defense has
surrendered 13 drives of 50-plus yards, all for a minimum of seven
plays. Although the team has played hard for coach Dave Wannstedt,
it is no match for the Falcons. Jamal Anderson will pound at a
front seven that hasn't stopped the run much lately.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grudge match: It's time again for the twice-annual Mike
Shanahan-Al Davis blood feud. The Raiders owner fired Shanahan in
'89, and the Broncos coach will never forgive him. Against an
Oakland secondary missing cornerback Eric Allen, look for the
Broncos to pour it on.
</P>
<P>
   _ Division game: The Miami defense is quick and physical. New
England is fighting for its playoff life. There will be plenty of
bile and lots of train wrecks in Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
