<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-DUCKS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Season opens to warm reviews
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Weather so cold the air crackles; a steady rattling of
sleet on marsh grass; feet numb up to the knees. A duck hunter's
idea of perfection.
</P>
<P>
   But the way it looks now, conditions won't be anywhere close to
perfect when waterfowl hunting season opens in Georgia on Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The weather report calls for a low of 37 and a high of 56.
That's not bad for deer hunting, but there probably won't be a lot
of ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cold front they're having in the Midwest might drive some
of the big ducks down,'' said Atlantan Gary Merriman, proprietor of
the Fish Hawk in Buckhead. Before the migration is over, some 84
million ducks will have passed through Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Merriman, like most of Georgia's 16,000 waterfowl hunters, will
be hunting ``little'' ducks _ wood ducks _ opening day instead of
mallards or other big migratory fowl.
</P>
<P>
   The hunters will be on rivers and creeks, in blinds or maybe
floating along in canoes or on beaver ponds early in the morning,
waiting for a few woodies to skim in over the treetops.
</P>
<P>
   Or they'll be on one of the state's big reservoirs, such as
waterfowl-rich Lake Seminole, or maybe trying their luck at Lake
Lanier, where duck season is open for the first time in years.
</P>
<P>
   Waterfowl season runs through Jan. 19, and Canada goose season
through Jan. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lake Lanier and Lake Oconee have special regulations to
ensure the safety of other lake-users.
</P>
<P>
   On Lake Lanier, no hunting is allowed within 1,000 feet of a
dock, house, structure, bridge, road, boat ramp, marina or open
recreation area, and waterfowl hunting is allowed only in certain
closed campgrounds and certain closed portions of some day-use
recreation areas.
</P>
<P>
   On Lake Oconee, no hunting is allowed within 300 feet of any
dock, house, boat ramp or other facility.
</P>
<P>
   Although the state is between major flyways, hunting should be
as good as last year, when hunters bagged an average of 8.4 ducks,
according to the Wildlife Resources Division of the Georgia
Department of Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks
</P>
<P>
   _ Season: Saturday-Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limit: Six (12 in possession).
</P>
<P>
   _ Hours: Half an hour before sunrise to sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Geese
</P>
<P>
   _ Season: Saturday-Jan. 29.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limit: Two (four in possession).
</P>
<P>
   _ Hours: Half an hour before sunrise to sunset.
</P>
<P>
   _ License requirements for both: Georgia hunting license,
Federal Duck Stamp, Georgia Waterfowl License, Migratory Bird
Harvest Information Program Stamp, Migratory Bird Hunting and
Conservation Stamp.
</P>
<P>
   _ Info: 770-918-6414; Internet (www.DNR.State.Ga.US).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
