<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CAPITAL-GAINS-ART-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH FOR ILL-TIMED GAINS AS 1998 DRAWS TO A CLOSE  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 22)
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of top 10 funds potential cap gains is being sent
to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A warning to mutual fund investors who may already be struggling
through a tough year: You won't really know how bad it is until you
receive your funds' year-end capital gains distributions.
</P>
<P>
   Even though a fund may have racked up major losses this year, it
is required to distribute any realized capital gains, on which
investors will owe taxes. This year, the stars are aligned to make
those distributions whoppers for many funds.
</P>
<P>
   Why? In difficult market times, investors are wont to yank money
from a struggling fund, forcing it to sell appreciated stocks to
meet redemptions. Thanks to past years' bull-market returns, gains
on those shares may be particularly big.
</P>
<P>
   The question, of course, is which funds will be making big
distributions as the year winds down. Many funds, fearing a further
exodus, won't alert investors.
</P>
<P>
   But some have already reported: Templeton Growth recently made
an 11 percent capital gains distribution, though it lost nearly 16
percent for the 12 months through Sept. 30. And the MFS Managed
Sectors fund plans a 14 percent distribution despite its loss of 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   To compile a list of funds that are likely to make large
distributions, Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher,
looked at two factors: Does the fund have big potential capital
gains exposure, and has it seen the cash outflows that are likely
to prompt securities sales?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody has identified the precise formula for
determining the precise distribution,'' said John A. Rekenthaler,
Morningstar's research director. ``These are good candidates,
however.''
</P>
<P>
   Before buying a fund that is likely to make a big distribution,
it may be wise to ask when it intends to do so. If you already own
such a fund, one option is to sell the fund before the distribution
and then pop back in afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who want to lock in a tax loss, however, will have to
wait 31 days. The ``wash sales rule'' of the Internal Revenue
Service holds that if you buy back shares any sooner, you must
defer the deduction of your loss.
</P>
<P>
   A better approach may be to sell a fund before a distribution
and immediately buy a similar one that has already made its
payment. That way, if the market surges in the next month, you
won't miss out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
