<HEADLINE>
PLENTY OF COMEBACK HORSES BUT NO AWARD
</HEADLINE>
 -LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Racing hands out as many awards as the next
sport, but there's no Comeback Horse of the Year Award.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? There'd always be plenty of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   This season's competition would have ended when Da Hoss won the
Breeders' Cup Mile in only his second start since taking the same
race in 1996. Michael Dickinson's training job can be compared to
Charlie Whittingham's in preparing Cougar II to win the 1973 Santa
Anita Handicap after a four-month layoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was really amazing,'' trainer Craig Dollase said of
Dickinson's feat, ``just seeing how patient he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Other notable comebacks this year include Belle's Flag, winning
the California Cup Matron five months after getting hurt at
Hollywood; and Big Jag, making the Cal Cup Sprint one of four
straight wins following an 18-month break. None is likely to match
Da Hoss, but with the Breeders' Cup over and the rich Santa Anita
and Gulfstream Park winter meets ahead, lots of top horses are
making comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Dollase's 7-year-old Dramatic Gold, best known for
finishing third in the 1994 Breeders' Cup Classic, ran a tough
second in a $60,000 allowance race at Hollywood Park in his first
start since foot and back injuries in February.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, 3-year-old Artax, once thought to be California's best
Kentucky Derby hope, runs in an optional claiming race at
Hollywood, his first outing since suffering knee and shin injuries
while finishing 13th in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at (workouts), he's doing well,'' trainer Randy
Bradshaw said. ``But works and races are two different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Others from the 1998 Triple Crown trail who plan comebacks soon:
Event of the Year, shooting for the Dec. 26 Malibu at Santa Anita;
Hanuman Highway, Classic Cat, Orville N Wilbur's and Derby and
Preakness winner Real Quiet, who is in Kentucky with an uncertain
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Older horses on the way back include 1998 Santa Anita Handicap
winner Malek and 1996 Santa Anita Derby winner Cavonnier. The
latter had aimed for last month's Cal Cup Classic and then Sunday's
On Trust Handicap but will wait for Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend: Bob Baffert trains the top two in Saturday's
Prevue Stakes for 2-year-olds. Premier Property won the Sunny Slope
at Santa Anita and hasn't trailed in two starts; David Flores rides
for Indian Charlie owner Hal Earnhardt. American Spirit is coming
off a maiden win; Gary Stevens rides.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert won the Prevue the past two years with In Excessive Bull
and Commitisize.
</P>
<P>
   Big Jag is expected to head Sunday's On Trust Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   __ It's a festival: Not even those who tire of racing by this
time of year can ignore the Hollywood Park autumn meet. The reason
is the annual Thanksgiving-week Turf Festival that draws top grass
horses at a time when lawns across the nation are turning brown.
</P>
<P>
   More than $2 million in purses are at stake in the six-race
festival next Friday, Nov. 27; Saturday, Nov. 28, and Sunday, Nov.
29.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Day 1: The Hollywood Turf Express for sprinters and the Miesque
Stakes for 2-year-old fillies.
</P>
<P>
   Day 2: The Citation Handicap and the Generous Stakes for
2-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Day 3: The Matriarch for fillies and mares and the Hollywood
Derby for 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Neil Drysdale could dominate. He'll send likely
turf-females champion Fiji and Diamond on the Run against Auntie
Mame in the $700,000 Matriarch; Dr Fong against Ladies Din in the
$500,000 Derby; Hawksley Hill in the Citation; and Bodyguard in the
Turf Express.
</P>
<P>
   __ How's that again?: Frankie Dettori, who nearly rode Swain
into the Churchill Downs grandstand in the final furlong of the
Breeders' Cup Classic, has explained that he was trying to avoid
racing side by side with the tenacious Silver Charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the jockeys' room before the race, one of the riders told
me that you can't beat Silver Charm in a head-to-head, so I decided
to go four horses wide,'' Dettori said on English television in a
statement quoted by the Daily Racing Form. ``I did the best for me
and for Swain, but it did not work. That's life and it's all
forgotten now.''
</P>
<P>
   Swain finished third, a length behind winner Awesome Again and a
neck behind Silver Charm. Many think Swain would have won if he'd
run straight.
</P>
<P>
   Dettori apparently didn't defend his left-handed whipping, which
seemed to drive Swain to the outside. Instead he said Swain ``lost
a bit of concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that why horses have riders?
</P>
<P>
   __ Santos honored: Jose Santos was voted by his fellow jockeys
as the 50th winner of the George Woolf Memorial Award, which goes
to riders who bring credit to themselves and the sport.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation will be during the Santa Anita meet that starts
Dec. 26. The award is named for the rider who was killed in a 1946
accident at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being a finalist in the voting about 10 years ago,
and I was disappointed that I didn't get it,'' said Santos, a
37-year-old Chilean who rides mostly in New York. ``But it was
worth the wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Santos has ridden six Breeders' Cup races and led the nation's
jockeys in earnings each year from 1986 to '89. He rode in
California in 1991 but didn't catch on. &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL; 
__ Hollywood Park leaders: Jockeys (through Wednesday): Kent
Desormeaux, Garrett Gomez and Chris McCarron, 5 wins; Eddie
Delahoussaye and Alex Solis, 4. Trainers: Ron McAnally, 4; Randy
Bradshaw and Neil Drysdale, 3; several with 2.(UB)Handicapper
helper: After opening day Nov. 11, when late runners seemed to have
no chance on the Hollywood Park main track, the surface has
produced winners of all styles. Inside or outside post positions
have offered no obvious advantage. &QL; 
__ Upcoming stakes: At Hollywood Park: Saturday, $100,000 Hollywood
Prevue, 2-year-old fillies, 7 furlongs; Sunday, $100,000 On Trust
Handicap, 3-year-olds and up bred in California, 7{ furlongs;
Thursday, $70,000 Political Ambition, 3-year-olds and up, 1\ miles
on turf. At Aqueduct: Saturday, $150,000 Red Smith Handicap,
3-year-olds and up, 1] miles on turf; Thursday, $100,000 Fall
Highweight Handicap, 3-year-olds and up, 6 furlongs. At Churchill
Downs: Saturday, $150,000 Mrs. Revere, 3-year-old fillies, 1 1/16
miles on turf; Thursday, $250,000 Falls City Handicap, fillies and
mares 3 and up, 1[ miles. In Japan: Sunday, $1.3 million Mile
Championship, 3-year-olds and up, about 1 mile on turf. &QL; 
__ Mileposts: Golden Gate Fields in Albany, Calif., opened
Wednesday for a 45-day season. Racing starts at 12:45 most
afternoons. Highlight: the Jan. 16 Golden Gate Derby. . . . Jockey
Russell Baze led both halves of Bay Meadows' split meet this year,
giving him 20 titles in a row at the San Mateo track. Trainer Jerry
Hollendorfer led both halves, giving him 17 straight. . . . Rider
Roberto Gonzalez might miss five or six months with multiple
fractures after a fall Saturday at Bay Meadows. Jake Barton could
miss four to six weeks with a broken arm suffered in the same
accident. . . . Gary Stevens told the Daily Racing Form he might
ride in England starting in March. Stevens' wife, Nicola, is from
Doncaster, and he thinks the style of racing and higher weight
scale would be easier on his body. . . . Favorite Trick, the 1997
Horse of the Year at age 2, was retired to Walmac International
breeding farm in Lexington, Ky., after finishing eighth in the Nov.
7 Breeders' Cup Mile at Churchill Downs. . . . Also retired:
Breeders' Cup Distaff winner Escena. . . . Hall of Fame trainer
Charlie Whittingham, 85, continues to recuperate at home after
nearly two weeks in the hospital with pneumonia. . . . Moccasin
Stakes winner Perfect Six will run next in the Dec. 13 Hollywood
Starlet for 2-year-old fillies. . . . Breeders' Cup Sprint winner
returned to Craig Dollase's Hollywood Park barn Tuesday. . . . Kent
Desormeaux will ride Coronado's Quest in the Nov. 28 Cigar Mile at
Aqueduct, the 3-year-old colt's scheduled swan song. . . .
Desormeaux rode three of the first four stakes winners at this
Hollywood Park meet. Two were trained by Neil Drysdale. . . . Skip
Away's stud fee: $50,000 per live foal. He'll stand at Hopewell
Farm in Lexington. . . . The gelding Savinio has been retired at
age 8 after a 48-race career in which he won the 1996 Goodwood and
San Diego handicaps. . . . The mare Advancing Star was retired at 5
after finishing third in a minor stakes Friday at Hollywood Park. .
. . The post-Breeders' Cup National Thoroughbred Racing Association
media poll ranked Skip Away No. 1, followed by Awesome Again,
Silver Charm, Real Quiet, Sharp Cat, Victory Gallop, Buck's Boy,
Escena, Banshee Breeze and Fiji.
</P>
</TEXT>
