<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FED MINUTES SHOW CONCERN OVER PERCEPTION OF CUTS
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board decided to limit its rate cut on Sept.
29 to a quarter of a percentage point because it was worried that a
bigger reduction might exaggerate its concerns about the risks of
an economic slowdown, according to minutes of the deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   But just over two weeks later, the central bank cut interest
rates by another quarter of a point between meetings, despite
continued concern among some members of the committee that the move
would be interpreted as a signal that the central bank saw bad news
on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT ACCUSED OF LIFTING PRICES
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has kept the price of personal-computer software
significantly higher than would be expected if the company faced
real competition, an economic consultant testified at the software
giant's antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   LIVENT GETS $5 MILLION IN LOANS
</P>
<P>
   Some of Livent's wealthy board members came to the Broadway
theater company's rescue, lending it $5 million, enough to keep the
curtain up for 10 days. Meanwhile, the company's two founders,
Garth Drabinsky and Myron Gottlieb angrily disputed allegations
made by Livent's new managers that the two men had engaged in a
widespread corporate fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ASSET-MANAGEMENT UNIT SOLD
</P>
<P>
   Senior managers of Robertson Stephens Investment Management, the
asset-management arm of the old Robertson, Stephens &AMP; Co., teamed
up to buy the company from BankAmerica for an undisclosed price.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL DEMAND LIFTS STOCK MARKET
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose, led by demand for Intel and MCI Worldcom. The Dow
Jones industrial average rose 14.94 points, to 9,056.05. The S&AMP;P
500 rose 8.13 points, to 1,152.61, and the Nasdaq rose 22.24
points, or 1.2 percent, to 1,919.68. In the bond market, prices
rose as the yield on the 30-year Treasury fell to 5.23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   French authorities said the Paris stock exchange would join an
alliance between London and Frankfurt, Germany, that is seen as the
precursor of a pan-European market.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERGY TO BUY NUCLEAR REACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Entergy, a major utility company in the South, emerged as the
winning buyer in the first multiple-bid auction for a U.S. nuclear
power plant, a 26-year-old reactor in Massachusetts that sold for
$80 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   MET LIFE SETTLES FEDERAL CASE
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Life Insurance, the second-largest life insurer in
the United States, agreed to pay a $25 million civil penalty to
settle a federal investigation of its sales practices.
</P>
<P>
   STARTS OF HOUSING INCREASE 7.3 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Housing starts recorded their largest increase in 13 months
during October, and building permits rose to their highest level in
almost nine years, bolstered by low mortgage rates. The Commerce
Department said that housing starts rose 7.3 percent, to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.695 million units.
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSTS WARY OF VACANCIES
</P>
<P>
   A company that goes for some time without a chief financial
officer may be raising a red flag for investors. That is why some
analysts have been looking warily at Electronic Data Systems and
Nike.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST TRADE DISCUSSIONS
</P>
<P>
   Israel's chilly trade relationship with Jordan and the
Palestinian Authority warmed slightly this week as the three
neighbors held their first face-to-face discussions.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA THWARTS TOBACCO COMPANIES
</P>
<P>
   As cigarette sales threaten to decline precipitously in the
United States, American tobacco companies are counting on China as
a land of growth. But their plans are being thwarted by China's
government monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   China has begun efforts to comply with the coming U.S. ban on
imports containing untreated wood-packing material, a U.S.
agricultural official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
