<P>
   (NYT23) NEW DELHI -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- INDIA-ROYAL-SURVIVORS,
11-19 -- Prince Cyrus Riza, left, a turbaned royal servant, center,
and Princess Sakina, on a gray November day outside their ``dreary
lodge'' in New Delhi. Their mother once maintained the family in a
railroad station. Oudh was a wealthy swath of northern India in the
time of the maharajas. Its sovereigns traced their bloodlines to
ancient Persian kings. Their power seeped away under the rule of
the British, who finally seized the realm in 1856. Some of the
royal family never gave up their claim on the palaces. Nor did
their descendants. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) JERUSALEM -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- ISRAEL, 11-19 --Supporters
of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu hold posters bearing
his portrait during a rally recently in Jerusalem. The signing of
the Wye peace memorandum in Washington last month dropped like a
missle of doom into the right wing of Israel. It shattered
alliances, blurring the political identity of a movement built
around defending the Jewish homeland against territorial
compromise. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- IMPEACH-RDP-3, 11-19 --
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr looks at documents during his
testimony before the House Judiciary Committee in Washington on
Thursday. Starr opened the third presidential impeachment inquiry
in the nation's history by charging before a bitterly divided
committee that President Clinton ``misused his authority and
power'' to impede civil and criminal cases against him. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- IMPEACH-MEMBERS-3, 11-19
-- House Judiciary Committee Chairman Rep. Henry Hide, left, speaks
with ranking minority member Rep. John Conyers during testimony by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr in Washington, Thursday.Starr
opened the third presidential impeachment inquiry in the nation's
history by charging before a bitterly divided committee that
President Clinton ``misused his authority and power'' to impede
civil and criminal cases against him. In the foreground is Rep.
Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- IMPEACH-RDP-2, 11-19 --
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr testifies before the House
