cases against him. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BOSTON -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- HOME-LEAF-BLOWERS-BOS, 11-19
-- How many leaves must one man rake before he invests in a
machine? The answer, friends, is blowing in the wind. Cruise
through the cul de sacs beyond Boston these days and you'll see
more leaf blowers in use than Cuisinarts and minivans. Fred Watt,
blows clear some leaves in a Boston suburb recently. (Bill
Greene/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BOSTON -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- PROFILE-HILLARY-BOS, 11-19 --
He represents the last, if not lost, generation of world-class
explorers, 20th-century adventurers for whom the ends of the earth
were mere departure points for measuring what the human body -- and
human spirit -- is capable of enduring. With his 80th birthday
comfortably in sight, Sir Edmund Hillary, the first Westerner to
reach the summit of Mount Everest, is a living deity on two
continents and a towering presence wherever he roams. Hillary was
in Boston earlier this week. (Tom Herde/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) RASCINE, Wisc. -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- APPLES-MILWAUKEE-2,
11-19 -- The S.C. Johnson complex in Racine offers free
architectural tours. Sometimes, from some angles, Milwaukee and its
surrounding area can fool you. Is this Chicago? Both cities nurture
old-country traditions. Both have mastered the Midwestern knack of
keeping their feet on the ground. But Milwaukee, as its visitors
bureau proclaimed in an advertising campaign a few years back, is
Chicago several million people ago. (Steve Kagan/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MILWAUKEE, Wisc. -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- APPLES-MILWAUKEE,
11-19 -- The pseudo-Flemish City Hall in Milwaukee, built in1895,
was designed in emulation of the guild halls in Belgium. Sometimes,
from some angles, Milwaukee can fool you. Is this Chicago? Both
cities nurture old-country traditions. Both have mastered the
Midwestern knack of keeping their feet on the ground. But
Milwaukee, as its visitors bureau proclaimed in an advertising
campaign a few years back, is Chicago several million people ago.
(Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- THEATER-NOTES, 11-19 --
Arielle Tepper, 26, is by far the youngest producer on Broadway
today. At 26, she shares top billing on Sandra Bernhard's ``I'm
Still Here ... Damn It!'' Tepper's second production. Previously,
she co-produced John Leguizamo's ``Freak,'' along with Gregory
Mosher and Bill Haber. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- IMPEACH-MEDIA, 11-19
--Members of the media cover Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's
testimony before the House Judiciary Committee on Thursday in
Washignton. The committee opened its first day of impeachment
hearings listening to the testimony of the independent counsel who
is investigating President Clinton. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- IMPEACH-SCENE, 11-19 --
House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde jokes, ``Will someone
protect me from Rep. Maxine Waters please,'' walking past in the
foreground, as the House Judiciary Committee took one of their
first breaks during Thursday's hearing in Washington. Others are:
Republican counsel David Schippers, seated left, and ranking
minorty member Rep. John Coyners, seated right. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- IMPEACH-RDP-1, 11-19
--From left, White House Counsel Charles Ruff, President Clinton's
private lawyer David Kendall, and Special Counsel to the President
Lanny Bruer listening to testimony during impeachment hearings held
by the House Judiciary Committee in Washington on Thursday. The
House Judiciary Committee opened its impeachment inquiry Thursday
listening to Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, who was called
as the first witness. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW LEWISTON, Maine -- Nov. 19, 1998 --
CRASH-KENNEDY-3-COX, 11-19 -- Kevin Bubblier, a 37-year-old
shipyard worker, stills has nightmares about the night flight 529
crashed in hayfield in west Georgia. Bubblier was one of three men
who tried to save Jim Kennedy from the plane's burning wreckage.
``Just give me a second,'' he says when his retelling comes to
Kennedy in the fuselage. ``That's a touchy subject.'' (Rich
Addicks/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CENTREVILLE, Va. -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- CRASH-KENNEDY-2-COX,
11-19 -- David Schneider, a flight 529 crash survivor, had to jump
through flames to survive the crash. He still has ``survivor
guilt'' over leaving behind passenger Jim Kennedy. ``Maybe I should
have tried to carry him out.'' Schneider reflects. (Rich
Addicks/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PURCELLVILLE, Va. -- Nov. 19, 1998 --
CRASH-KENNEDY-1-COX, 11-19 -- Loudon County Deputy Sheriff Tod
Thompson survived ASA flight 7529 but his fellow officer on the
plane, Charles Barton did not. The pair were travelling to
Mississippi to pick up a fugitive. Thompson thinks about Barton
every day, especially at the sheriff's office. `` Going into the
building, seeing Charlie's old friends, the people he worked real
close with, just puts me uneasy,'' he says. (Rich Addicks/ Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CHICAGO -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- CRASH-2NDCHANCE-3-COX, 11-18
-- David McCorkell shares a moment with his ex-wife, Lila.
McCorkell, one of the 19 survivors of Flight 529, had been divorced
13 months and was en route to Mobile, Ala., when the plane crashed
in a hayfield in west Georgia. ``It's weird that this brought Dave
and I closer,'' Lila says of the crash which re-united the couple.
``Dave values family a lot more than before.'' (Rich Addicks/
Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ANCHORAGE -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- CRASH-2NDCHANCE-2-COX,
11-18 -- David McCorkell, a survivor of flight ASA Flight 529, says
that the experience has changed his life. He reflects on his
heroics by a glacier-fed stream outside of Anchorage. ``This is
nature to the Nth degree,'' McCorkell says. ``And I guess you feel
a little bit dinged up from what man has done anyway...'' (Rich
Addicks/ Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) GRIFFIN, Ga. -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- CRASH-2NDCHANCE-1-COX,
11-18 -- Matt Warmerdam, who was the first officer on ASA Flight
529, holds the cockpit window which passengers smashed with a
hatchet while trying to free him from the burning plane. With burns
over 42 percent of his body, Warmerdam spent 100 days in the burn
unit at Chattanooga's Erlanger Medical Center, then six weeks in
the cardiac unit. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CARROLLTON, Ga. -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- CRASH-THEFALL-2-COX,
11-16 -- The remains of the nose of Atlantic Southeast Airlines
Flight 529. The plane, a propeller-driven plane, fell in an obscure
hayfield in west Georgia: 10 people died, 19 survived. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- CRASH-THEFALL-1-COX, 11-16 --
Flight attendant Robin Fech demonstrates what she did during the
final seconds of the ASA Flight 529. Ms. Fech, the only flight
attendant on the plane, shouted to her passengers before impact,
``Hold on, y'all! This is going to be rough!'' (Rich
Addicks/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
