<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      11-19 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Delhi-Lahore Bus Link
</P>
<P>
   Bus service between New Delhi and Lahore, Pakistan, is expected
to begin next month after the two countries settle on fares and
schedules, Indian officials said. The rival nations have not been
linked by bus service for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe: Economic Talks Urged
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe called for broad-based talks
to resolve economic problems that have set off a wave of strikes
and escalating violence. Mugabe has been blamed by labor unions and
businessmen for a crisis that has seen inflation hit 35 percent and
the Zimbabwe dollar plummet by more than 60 percent in a year.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Cross-Border Trade Surge
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has edged out Japan to become the United States'
second-largest trading partner, after Canada. Cross-border trade
with Mexico in September amounted to $15.2 billion. U.S. trade with
Mexico, a partner in the North American Free Trade Agreement, grew
12 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Canada: Opposition to an Execution
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Ministry is trying to block the execution next month
of a Canadian convicted of murder in Texas. Canada, which has no
death penalty, will file a brief with the U.S. Supreme Court
contending that Texas breached international conventions by not
informing Joseph Stanley Faulder of his right to notify the
Canadian government after his arrest in 1975 for killing an elderly
Texas woman.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba: Case vs. Castro Is Denied
</P>
<P>
   A Spanish magistrate, Ismael Moreno, declined to accept a suit
filed on Nov. 5 by a Cuban exile group from Miami accusing
President Fidel Castro of Cuba of genocide and terrorism. The
ruling came from the same court that is pressing charges of
genocide against Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the former Chilean
dictator.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia: 30 Killed in Clash
</P>
<P>
   In Latin America's longest-running civil conflict, a clash
between left-wing guerrillas and right-wing death squads has left
at least 30 people dead in Uraba, an area of northwestern Colombia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
