</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PURCELLVILLE, Va. -- Nov. 19, 1998 --
CRASH-KENNEDY-1-COX, 11-19 -- Loudon County Deputy Sheriff Tod
Thompson survived ASA flight 7529 but his fellow officer on the
plane, Charles Barton did not. The pair were travelling to
Mississippi to pick up a fugitive. Thompson thinks about Barton
every day, especially at the sheriff's office. `` Going into the
building, seeing Charlie's old friends, the people he worked real
close with, just puts me uneasy,'' he says. (Rich Addicks/ Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CHICAGO -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- CRASH-2NDCHANCE-3-COX, 11-18
-- David McCorkell shares a moment with his ex-wife, Lila.
McCorkell, one of the 19 survivors of Flight 529, had been divorced
13 months and was en route to Mobile, Ala., when the plane crashed
in a hayfield in west Georgia. ``It's weird that this brought Dave
and I closer,'' Lila says of the crash which re-united the couple.
``Dave values family a lot more than before.'' (Rich Addicks/
Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ANCHORAGE -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- CRASH-2NDCHANCE-2-COX,
11-18 -- David McCorkell, a survivor of flight ASA Flight 529, says
that the experience has changed his life. He reflects on his
heroics by a glacier-fed stream outside of Anchorage. ``This is
nature to the Nth degree,'' McCorkell says. ``And I guess you feel
a little bit dinged up from what man has done anyway...'' (Rich
Addicks/ Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) GRIFFIN, Ga. -- Nov. 19, 1998 -- CRASH-2NDCHANCE-1-COX,
11-18 -- Matt Warmerdam, who was the first officer on ASA Flight
529, holds the cockpit window which passengers smashed with a
hatchet while trying to free him from the burning plane. With burns
over 42 percent of his body, Warmerdam spent 100 days in the burn
unit at Chattanooga's Erlanger Medical Center, then six weeks in
the cardiac unit. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CARROLLTON, Ga. -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- CRASH-THEFALL-2-COX,
11-16 -- The remains of the nose of Atlantic Southeast Airlines
Flight 529. The plane, a propeller-driven plane, fell in an obscure
hayfield in west Georgia: 10 people died, 19 survived. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- CRASH-THEFALL-1-COX, 11-16 --
Flight attendant Robin Fech demonstrates what she did during the
final seconds of the ASA Flight 529. Ms. Fech, the only flight
attendant on the plane, shouted to her passengers before impact,
``Hold on, y'all! This is going to be rough!'' (Rich
Addicks/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
