and Princess Sakina, on a gray November day outside their ``dreary
lodge'' in New Delhi. Their mother once maintained the family in a
railroad station. Oudh was a wealthy swath of northern India in the
time of the maharajas. Its sovereigns traced their bloodlines to
ancient Persian kings. Their power seeped away under the rule of
the British, who finally seized the realm in 1856. Some of the
royal family never gave up their claim on the palaces. Nor did
their descendants. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo)
