<SLUG> BC-CHILD-SUPPORT-ENFORCEMENT20-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Progress in Texas child support system minimal
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas legislators took a glimpse Thursday of the
beleaguered attorney general's child-support division that is
approaching a federal deadline for a whole new operating scheme
next year without preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with an Oct. 1 federal cutoff to set up a central system
to distribute child support, the attorney general's office has not
yet sought bids for a new way to handle the payment system, the
Sunset Advisory Commission heard. Currently, most child support
payments are handled at the county level.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office also has not completed its request
to the federal government to be allowed to keep the system that
works now.
</P>
<P>
   And lawmakers were told that the ill-fated $78 million computer
system bought for child-support collections will not be able to
handle all that the federal government will require by next year
without buying more hardware.
</P>
<P>
   After the beginning of the hearing Thursday morning, the
commission's child-support consultant, David M. Griffith &AMP;
Associates, painted a despairing picture of the Texas system.
Still, it recommended to the the commission that the division
continue to operate out of the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   The consultant was hired to assess how well the program was
working in the attorney general's office _ and whether it should be
moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is smoke and mirrors,'' said Rep. Toby
Goodman, R-Arlington. ``I heard different explanations here than in
front of my committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, chairman of the House Committee on Juvenile Justice and
Family Issues, conducted hearings on the division last summer.
Goodman, who is not on the sunset commission, was invited to help
conduct the inquiry by state Sen. Chris Harris, R-Arlington, a
member of the commission and himself a key legislative player in
child-support issues.
</P>
<P>
   After Goodman had elicited the fact that the attorney general's
office had not completed its federal waiver application, another
commission member, Rep. Patricia Gray, D-Galveston, interrupted
him. ``One of the things I'm a little disturbed about was, a little
more than two hours ago, I asked whether we had applied for a
waiver and was told yes,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a deposition where we are trying to determine the
definition of the word is. It's a simple question,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dan Morales is scheduled to appear today , when
the hearing continues. His first assistant attorney general, Jorge
Vega, appeared in his place Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman and Harris have been critics of Morales' child-support
program for years. The child-support division collects on about a
fifth of cases referred to it, although many of those referrals
involve children born to unwed mothers and the fathers have not
been legally identified.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
