<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0289 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOV-BUSH-ED-PLAN20-CO     11-19 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOV-BUSH-ED-PLAN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush still pondering 2000 presidential race
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ If George W. Bush dives into the 2000 race, he
will find a presidential derby vastly different from recent White
House contests.
</P>
<P>
   He also would find a personal challenge he has never encountered
_ candidates trying to outflank him on the right.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, as he spent another day never far from a TV camera
at the Republican Governors Association meeting, Bush acknowledged
2000 will be a different kind of presidential year for who ever
jumps in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has more of a feel of a national primary than ever
before,'' he said of the developing clustered primaries that could
favor candidates such as Bush with high name identification and
fund-raising ability.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of his father's bumpy rides through primaries, Bush
said he knows he would face a different game if he ran for
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be a premium placed on candidates' capacity
to raise money early,'' he said. ``I think a candidate is going to
have to have pretty broad appeal because there are western
primaries and eastern primaries all on the same day.''
</P>
<P>
   And while other potential GOP presidential contenders are
spending time and money to lure social conservatives who could be
key players in many states, Bush said he has no plans to do
anything special to curry their favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the way I'm going to play it if I choose to run,'' he
said. ``I'm going to be myself and let the chips fall where they
may.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Bush scared off all other potential GOP gubernatorial
candidates. This year, he faced only R.C. Crawford, an unfunded,
unknown political rookie from Round Rock.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of GOP opponents has kept Bush from having to compete
for the social conservative vote. Though he agrees with groups such
as the Christian Coalition on most issues, they have established a
largely arms-length connection to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks from the right already are being lobbed by Gary Bauer,
head of the Family Research Council, who also is considering his
own bid for president.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent appearance on the Fox News Channel, Bauer said the
success of the Bush uncandidacy is a ``mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush gets a lot of press, but we actually know very
little about what he believes on a whole host of issues _ his
policy towards China, abortion. His tax cuts in Texas ended up
being in many cases a tax increase,'' Bauer said. ``I'm assuming
that if George W. runs, he will run as a Bush Republican. And if I
run, I'm going to run as a Reagan Republican, and there is a
difference between the two.''
</P>
<P>
   The change in how the game will be played in 2000 is now going
on as states look to grab more importance. The campaign trail will
look more like a short series of clustered primaries than the
state-by-state procession the nation is used to.
</P>
<P>
   Though the final lineup has not been decided, it now looks as if
it will begin, as usual, with the Iowa caucuses followed by the New
Hampshire primary. Louisiana, as it did in 1996, may have an early
contest. South Carolina is planning a March 4 primary.
</P>
<P>
   But then the landscape changes dramatically, and in a way that
means the nominations could be decided before April Fools Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the candidate who can raise a lot of money in the
up-front will be benefited by the clustering,'' said Utah Gov. Mike
Leavitt, a driving force behind the developing western presidential
primary.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Bush, who has raised money from all 50 states for
his gubernatorial campaigns, and Steve Forbes, who finances his
campaigns by reaching into his own pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, said Leavitt, ``would likely fare quite well'' in a
western regional primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot in common between Texas and the interior
West,'' he said. ``It's a frontier kind of atmosphere. It's a
relatively independent group.''
</P>
<P>
   Other governors here also said Bush looks strong in their
states.
</P>
<P>
   Bush buddy David Beasley, ousted this month as governor of South
Carolina, spent this week talking like a man waiting to join a Bush
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to great friendship and working
relationships today and in the future,'' Beasley said. ``It's going
to be an exciting time. I support him 100 percent in all
endeavors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have very little doubt that the people of South Carolina
will support George Bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Iowa, a traditional bellwether, may be more challenging for
Bush, said Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad, who did not seek re-election
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Branstad is tight with ex-Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, a
former and probable future presidential candidate, and expects to
back Alexander in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Branstad noted, Alexander and other potential contenders
have been working Iowa for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iowa is a state that cannot be taken for granted, and I think
to do well there, you've got to spend a lot of time, you've got to
go to a lot of places,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Is it, somehow, already too late for a presidential candidate to
get involved in a caucus that is more than a year off?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is going to be tough,'' Branstad said. ``No, it is
not too late, but it is going to take a concerted effort because
there are other people that have been at least laying the
groundwork and spending some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it's wrong to think a presidential campaign not
already under way can't become a contender.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who will vacation out of the country with his family next
week, said his presidential decision is months away and still
highly dependent on input from wife Laura and 16-year-old daughters
Jenna and Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say don't do it,'' Bush said of his daughters. ``I think
they are against it. I know they are not against me, and I think
there is a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush, he said, is not opposing the race, ``nor is she
sitting there shoving me, `Please run,' urging me to jump out in
front of the next news magazine cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also wants it clear that the decision, though made with
family input, is his to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has got veto power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of days of high-powered national attention, Bush
said he is ``amazed'' by his front-runner status.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he knows something about physics and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand something,'' he said. ``What goes up, comes
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
