<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZARKA-SUIT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Justices grill both sides in ground-water case
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Justices of the Texas Supreme Court gave no
clear signal Thursday whether they want a ground-water law with
19th-century roots to survive into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The justices took one side and then the other as they quizzed
lawyers in a case challenging the rule of capture, a ground-water
doctrine adopted by the court in 1904 that is based on an 1843
common-law ruling in England.
</P>
<P>
   Several justices expressed keen interest in the legal, political
and practical implications of the rule of capture, which allows
essen- tially unlimited pumping of ground water even if wells,
springs and creeks dry up as a result. The case is one of the most
important environmental and property-rights issues to be considered
by the court in recent years. Nearly 150 spectators attended
Thursday's oral arguments, and security officers turned away other
people because of fire-code limits.
</P>
<P>
   The court is considering an appeal by two families in Henderson
County in East Texas who contend that the Ozarka Spring Water Co.
depleted their wells. Ozarka denies the allegation. Two lower
courts, citing the rule of capture, found in favor of Ozarka
without hearing any evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The families want the court to scrap the rule of capture for a
doctrine allowing ``reasonable use,'' or, failing that, to at least
allow lawsuits for negligent pumping.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Supreme Court is decidedly conservative, it is not
averse to new approaches on water law. In 1996, the nine-member
court unanimously upheld a law intended to restrict pumping from
the southern portion of the Edwards Aquifer, a water-bearing
limestone formation underlying the City of San Antonio and large
stretches of agricultural land in South Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the justices _ especially Priscilla Owen, Nathan
Hecht and Craig Enoch _ played devil's advocate with the lawyers in
an effort to test their arguments. Here is an edited version of
some of the discussion:
</P>
<P>
   Enoch: ``Haven't most states that abandoned the rule of capture
done so by legislation?''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Rea, a lawyer for the East Texas families: ``Yes, but last
year's overhaul of water law by the state Legislature stopped short
of addressing the rule, leaving individuals without protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Enoch: ``So you want the court to impose a regulatory scheme
that you can't win politically?''
</P>
<P>
   In another exchange, Christopher Hanslik, a lawyer for Ozarka,
argued that landowners could obtain relief by persuading voters to
create a local ground-water district. If that fails, they could ask
the Legislature to create a district.
</P>
<P>
   Owen: ``But what if landowners cannot get a ground-water
district created? What recourse do they have?''
</P>
<P>
   Hanslik: ``Drill a deeper well.''
</P>
<P>
   Another discussion centered on the advancements in science since
the 1904 ruling, which presumed that ground water was too
mysterious to regulate. In that case, the court ruled against W.A.
East, a North Texas landowner who sued the Houston &AMP; Texas Central
Railway for drilling a large well that dried up his smaller well.
</P>
<P>
   Enoch: ``What if the Legislature fails to manage ground water
comprehensively? Isn't the court obliged to say it adopted a rule
based on faulty science and change that rule?''
</P>
<P>
   Hecht: ``We decided East. Why can't we undecide East?''
</P>
<P>
   Hanslik: ``Senate Bill 1, the water law, is just beginning to be
implemented. Give it a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
