u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-1STLD-     11-19 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: of power.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As for presenting himself to the public in a more favorable
light, Starr had no where to go but up. He went into the hearing
Thursday with a dim, 18 percent public approval rating, according
to a national poll taken a few days ago by CBS News. In the face of
attacks from the White House and leading Democrats, Starr has
maintained a stoic silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken felt he had to make a deliberate choice, not to engage in
the public debate,'' said Terrence B. Adamson, a Democratic lawyer
who has been a friend of Starr for almost 30 years. ``It might not
be the right political decision, but it was the right professional
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet at times in the long day of testimony, Starr, whose career
has been rooted in the decorum of the law, found himself the
unlikely star performer in a political rumble.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat down to begin his testimony, he was greeted by
Democrats scrapping with Hyde over how much time President
Clinton's lawyer should be granted to question Starr. As Democrats
hurled loaded words such as ``gagged'' at Hyde, Starr sat
unblinking, looking slightly out of place.
</P>
<P>
   He remained unruffled as Democrats grilled him about his
office's dealings with Ms. Lewinsky, the news media and lawyers for
Ms. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats used the hearing to question the fairness of
Starr's inquiry and of the Judiciary Committee's impeachment
investigation. Zoe Lofgren, D.-Calif., called the impeachment
proceedings ``embarrassing,'' and other Democrats, including
Lowell, compared the partisan rancor that has characterized Hyde's
investigation with the Watergate inquiry, which proceeded with
bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the criticisms of Starr by Democrats, including
accusations of leaks, collusion with the lawyers for Ms. Jones, and
rough treatment of Ms. Lewinsky, were not new.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his two-hour opening statement, the
prosecutor, who once considered a bid for the Republican Senate
nomination in Virginia, said that was not suited for the political
high wire. ``I am not a man of politics, of public relations or
polls, which I suppose is patently obvious by now,'' he said. ``I
am not experienced in political campaigns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
