<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART NEEDED AN EXTRA FOOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ivan Stewart won his third SCORE Baja 1000 last weekend,
crossing the finish line after the trek from Santo Tomas to La Paz
five minutes ahead of runner-up and defending champ Larry Ragland.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart made the trek in 19 hours, eight minutes and 20 seconds
and averaged 55.91 mph over the rugged course despite having a
throttle-linkage problem partway through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could only go about 85 miles per hour and I had to use my
foot to pull up and push down the throttle,'' Stewart said.
Stewart's vehicle also suffered a pair of flat tires.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 228 vehicles, entered in 23 classes, started the race.
</P>
<P>
   Thousand Oaks' Steve Barlow won the ProTruck class, making the
trip in 23:26.34. Glendale's George Seeley Jr. was second in the
unlimited Baja Bug class.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Cox of of Lancaster, Denny Wolf of La Crescenta and Cain
Smead of Quartz Hill shared driving duties in winning the ATV
250cc-or-less class.
</P>
<P>
   Indy Racing League driver Mike Groff of Pasadena teamed up with
Marth Fiolka of Long Beach to take second in the SCORE Lite class.
</P>
<P>
   Other local finishers included Gary Pentis of Newbury Park,
eighth in Class 9, and Neil Manninen of Palmdale, third in the
motorcycle over-40 division.
</P>
<P>
   __ Last dance: Their regular season is over, but one last chunk
of change remains to be contested by NASCAR's Winston Cup drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the regulars will be in Motegi, Japan, on Sunday,
roaring around the 1.5-mile Twin Ring Motegi track. Among those
expected to race are this year's three NASCAR series champs: Jeff
Gordon of Winston Cup, Dale Earnhardt Jr. of the Busch Grand
National and Ron Hornaday Jr. of the Craftsman Truck.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the field will be Dale Earnhardt Sr., racing for the
first time against his son.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one cars will start the race, their starting positions to
be determined by qualifying runs on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Notably absent will be Dale Jarrett, who will be home
recuperating from recent gall bladder surgery. Driving the familiar
No. 88 will be Darrell Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   __ Turkey night moves north: The USAC midget and three-quarter
midget tours make their next-to-last stop of the year next
Wednesday and Thursday at Mesa Marin Speedway in Bakersfield.
</P>
<P>
   The tours will spotlight the 58th running of the annual
Thanksgiving Turkey Night races sponsored by Agajanian
Entertainment. Last year's Turkey Night races were held at Ventura
Speedway. The event began in 1934 at Gilmore Stadium in the Fairfax
district of L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Wednesday and Thursday races, the tours make one
final stop in Las Vegas on Nov. 28.
</P>
<P>
   __ Not again:Cruz Pedregon ended his 1998 NHRA funny car season
in fashion typical of the way he ran it at last weekend's Winston
Finals at Pomona. Once again, the Camarillo driver and his
Interstate Batteries Pontiac turned in the fastest qualifying time
_ the 12th time he has qualified first in 1998. And once again,
things fell apart soon after.
</P>
<P>
   At the starting line against Jerry Toliver in Sunday's first
round, Pedregon hit the gas when his lights went green _ then sat
motionless watching Toliver quickly become a distant blur.
Pedregon's throttle cable had snapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I stepped on the throttle, I thought the car was stuck,''
Pedregon said. ``That was one of the strangest feelings I have ever
experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedregon's season standing wasn't hurt by the problem. He went
in and came out of the season finale in third place while John
Force won his eighth season title of the past nine years.
</P>
<P>
   __ Nuts and bolts: Anheuser-Busch will continue to sponser
NASCAR's Busch Grand National Series through 2002 and has raised
its contribution to the season points' fund from $650,000 to $1.5
million. . . . CART racers Dario Franchitti, Jimmy Vasser, Max
Papis and Tony Kanaan will take on Formula One stars Jacques
Villeneuve, Ralf Schmacher and Miko Salo in the Elf Masters Karting
Championships near Paris, France next week. . . . Gloy-Rahal racing
has signed Ron Barfield to drive its NASCAR Craftsman Truck entry
next season. . . . Winston Cup driver Bill Elliott has released
crew chief Mike Beam from his contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
