<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOWARD MIGHT BE STEP SLOW, BUT BRUINS ARE WARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC coach Paul Hackett says R. Jay Soward will not
be 100 percent Saturday because of a sprained ankle _ and the
Bruins believe him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably like (Brian) Polak,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said
of his starting right tackle, also suffering from a sprained ankle.
``(Soward) will play, but you don't know how much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a trade-off, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Then Toledo laughed.
</P>
<P>
   While the Trojans haven't figured a way to stop UCLA quarterback
Cade McNown, the Bruins have failed to slow Soward. Two years ago,
he had six catches for 260 yards and three touchdowns. Last year,
he had eight catches for 181 yards, including an 80-yarder on the
opening play.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA won't alter its game plan to stop Soward, but the defensive
backs will be aware of his presence and position at all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a great matchup for any of our guys,'' said defensive
coordinator Nick Aliotti. ``He's very fast and very talented, and,
obviously, he's a concern. We'll just mix it up and try to do a
good job.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Back for more: UCLA cornerback Marques Anderson returned to
the starting lineup last week, just in time to face Soward in the
second chapter of their fledgling rivalry. Last year, after Soward
burned Jason Bell for the opening touchdown, Anderson held Soward
to 101 yards on seven catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to have my thinking cap on, as well as my blood
running high,'' Anderson said. ``Some receivers, you can relax on a
little bit. But not R. Jay. You never know when the big play is
coming or where it's coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was an opening-day starter, then lost his position
after a lethargic performance against Houston. Ryan Roques played
so well for six weeks that Anderson couldn't regain his spot. But
Roques struggled against Stanford and Oregon State, and Anderson
was reinserted for the Washington game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't disappointed because I knew it was for the better,''
Anderson said. ``I looked at myself and saw I wasn't doing the job
I was capable of. It was more of an eye-opener than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Sit back, relax: The mood at Spaulding Field this week,
although intense, lacked the sense of urgency that enveloped
practice before the Washington game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that game was over, there was a deep sigh of relief,''
Toledo said. ``We secured the Rose Bowl and the Pac-10. Now, let's
go cut it loose and have some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Smart guys: Five Bruins were named to the Pac-10 All-Academic
team: kicker Chris Sailer (3.33 grade-point average,
communications); receiver Danny Farmer (3.01, history); center
Shawn Stuart (3.61, sociology); guard Andy Meyers (3.37, political
science), and linebacker Ramogi Huma (3.15 sociology).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
