<HEADER>
A0329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-1STLD-W     11-19 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LAWYER PIERCES STARR'S CALM DEMEANOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) (Also see IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-CLIFFORD, IMPEACH-ASSESS,
IMPEACH-VOICES, IMPEACH-MEDIA, IMPEACH-WHITEWATER, IMPEACH-SCHUMER,
IMPEACH-MEMBERS, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, EDIT-IMPEACH and
JAPAN-CLINTON) 
(bl) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was not until the 11th hour of a long and
grueling day of testimony that Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's
measured, unflappably academic performance before the Judiciary
Committee began to wear thin.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, when he got into a knife-edged lawyers' duel with
David Kendall, President Clinton's attorney, Starr's testimony
resounded through the day with anticlimax after all the long months
of salacious news and sensational accusations that have left the
president facing impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel so long out of public sight except for
his morning taking-out-the-garbage photo opportunities finally
stepped forth to speak in defense of his case before a skittish
Congress and apprehensive nation.
</P>
<P>
   Far from offering another lengthy narrative on DNA results and
lurid Oval Office behavior, Starr chose to beam judiciousness and
managed to hide any rancor as he faced minority Democrats aching to
wrestle him into the dock in substitution of the president.
</P>
<P>
   But as he faced Kendall late in the evening, after a day of
calmly weathering the Democrats, Starr could not resist turning
back his attacks, even as he called him ``David'' and smiled. In an
instant, as Kendall asked about the independent counsel's hiring of
private investigators, Starr eyed his questioner and shot back:
``We have never hired Terry Lenzner, David.'' He referred to an
investigator who has looked into the background of anti-Clinton
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a long day's lawyerly calm seemed at risk for Starr,
who similarly could not resist pointing out that Kendall, even as
he complained that he was afforded only an hour to question Starr,
never dealt with the charges against the president but only
attacked Starr's methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dress, the DNA, the test results,'' he said, emphasizing
factual specifics in rebutting one of Kendall's inquiries about
news leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Except for that 11th hour, Starr did not rise openly to the bait
as the Democrats barbed their questions with everything from
mockery to irony. He responded in phrases of high professionalism
and supreme regard for the law, arguing that his proposed case
against the president was rooted not in political bias, but rather
in ``the sanctity, yes the sanctity, of the judicial process.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, this left Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., fairly
gagging in the hallway during a break. ``Pathetic! Pathetic!'' he
declared of Starr, asking how such proclaimed standards of sanctity
squared with Starr's continued private lawyering in the corporate
sector even as he pursued the president, or his renunciation of the
flood of news leaks that have buoyed the case against the president
for the past 10 months. ``He's much more political than I thought
he was,'' said Meehan as the Democrats warily took their first
up-close measure of the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   It is something of a Capitol Hill tradition that hearing
witnesses often gain the status of victim during a grueling
hearing. As the Democrats peppered Starr into the night with some
shouted salvos of ``Do you affirm or deny'' questions, the
independent counsel, as if mindful of that tradition, was far from
complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Starr wanted to indicate his special position,
according to committee staffers, by being allowed to stand and
speak before the Judiciary Committee at a lectern, as he did before
the Supreme Court when he was solicitor general. But Republican
majority members decided it best he make his case seated at a
table, like any other witness.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats took their opening shots at him frontally,
denouncing him as the nation's ``sex policeman.'' ``Mr. Starr has
crossed the line into obsession,'' declared a scowling Rep. John
Conyers of Michigan, the ranking Democrat, reviewing Starr's four
years of investigating a half dozen presidential portfolios, from
Whitewater to the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Neither harried nor hurried, Starr used every minute of his
two-hour opening statement to restate his case against Clinton in
slow emphatic tones. ``Few have ventured that the president told
the truth, the whole truth and nothing but the truth,'' he
declared, savoring the word ``truth'' and the court oath. This
became his rhetorical device at various times in accusing the
president of gravely violating that oath in the sex-and-mendacity
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats aimed to make their points before the watching
national audience. But, still, some seem frustrated in seeking a
promising handhold on Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't look like a terrible, horrible person,'' Rep.
Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., smilingly conceded during a break. ``He
looked like a lawyer reading a boring, monotonous speech.''
</P>
<P>
   After Starr disowned any personal talent or partisan experience
in the world of politics, Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., asked a
series of skeptical questions. ``Why did you withhold that before
the election,'' he asked, referring to the exoneration of the
president that Starr suddenly announced Thursday in several areas
of his investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, patiently, Starr denied all partisan machinations. When
Frank asked about leaks from the investigation, Starr, a former
judge, gently objected: ``That is an unfair question.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tell me it's an unfair question, why, I'll withdraw
it,'' Frank shot back in mock reverence at Starr's demeanor of
judiciousness.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the hearing, Kendall seemed nettled by Starr and
the feeling became mutual as Starr pointedly noted that Kendall was
spending his time talking about news leaks more than the behavior
of his client, the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like another crack at him,'' said Kendall even as his time
ran out and Starr resumed his judicious demeanor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
