</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR'S WORDS FAIL TO INSPIRE FIREWORKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Subs ninth graf to clarify what Barney Frank was doing) 
 
(Attn: Analysis logo needed) 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's highly
anticipated testimony before the House Judiciary Committee on
Thursday did not appear to alter the dynamics of an impeachment
inquiry that has divided lawmakers and failed to ignite much
outrage in an ambivalent public.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the daylong session, it was clear that Republicans
and Democrats on the panel agreed on little, from the format of the
hearing to the fairness of Starr's probe.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel, for the most part, calmly parried the
sometimes hostile questioning with lengthy and legalistic answers
that frequently frustrated Democrats eager to paint him as
overzealous prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But he also did not offer any explosive new information likely
to sway members wary of ousting a president on charges of lying
about sex.
</P>
<P>
   As Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., conceded, Starr was not a
``make-or-break witness.''
</P>
<P>
   The historic session was held in the same cavernous chamber
where the Watergate impeachment hearings on President Nixon took
place almost a quarter of a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a long wooden table, Starr dominated the morning with
his recitation of charges against the president. The bespectacled
prosecutor displayed little emotion as he slowly read 58 pages of
highly legalistic testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation, however, appeared better suited for the
courtrooms where the former judge usually works than the national
audience watching the hearings televised on all of the major
networks.
</P>
<P>
   While Starr labored to make his case, Rep. Barney Frank,
D-Mass., slipped out to chat with reporters and be filmed by
someone making a documentary on the gay perspective on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   However, another Democrat, Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of Texas paid
close attention to the details of the testimony, and interrupted
Starr at one point when he plunged into matters unrelated to the
Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee argued that Starr should not be able to discuss
Whitewater-related issues where the prosecutor had not found that
president committed impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston lawmaker, however, was quickly overruled by
Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who reminded everyone that
the GOP majority in the House had approved an open-ended probe.
</P>
<P>
   While the chairman has frequently stated that he wanted the
inquiry to rise above partisanship, the spirit of comity was
missing from the packed room in the Sam Rayburn House Office
building.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats went on the offensive immediately after the
meeting commenced.
</P>
<P>
   They attacked the Republican majority for allotting Starr far
more time to make his case than they gave the president's lawyers
to rebut it.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats later grilled Starr on a range of issues from why his
prosecutors initially discouraged Lewinsky from seeking legal
advice to charges he was leaking grand jury material to the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make no bones about it. I think some of the tactics that
have been used are unacceptable,'' Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif.,
sternly told Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The portly and generally affable Hyde at times appeared
frustrated with the Democrats' aggressive questioning and
objections.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not try to block them from having their say. And he
tried to inject some humor into the hearings to relieve the
tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will someone protect me from Maxine Waters,'' he joked during
one break.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were also quick to defend Starr, and said the
Democrats were ignoring charges that the president may have
committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, a Republican from San Antonio _ where Starr
was raised _ praised the independent counsel as a dedicated father
with a reputation for personal integrity. Smith said the prosecutor
had been ``unfairly savaged'' by his critics.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the day a weary-looking Starr hinted that the
five-year probe had taken its toll on him. He told Republican Rep.
Mary Bono of Palm Springs Calif., that he often thought about the
law school dean's job he turned down at Pepperdine University in
Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would prefer to be almost your constituent,'' he told Bono.
``I would like to be living my life.''
</P>
<P>
   While Starr's testimony may not have changed many minds on the
committee, his presence certainly captured the attention of the
national media, who filled several rows of seats in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing also drew a number of spectators including,
filmmaker Michael Moore, best known for his documentary ``Roger and
Me,'' which chronicled how General Motors downsized its carmaking
operation in Flint, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said he was filming a segment on impeachment for his new
cable television show, a piece that was clearly going to be
critical of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said he had previously staged a protest in front of
Starr's home, which included seven people dressed up as Puritans
meant to represent the Salem witch hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Other less famous spectators who came to watch the hearings said
the partisan squabbling was all too predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats are Democrats. The Republicans are Republicans.
It is too bad,'' said Beverly Keeler, visiting from Worcester,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Others who walked by the hearing room said they had no interest
in the historic inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would rather eat lunch than wait for this,'' said Cher
Kiel, a photographer from New Jersey, who was in Washington to see
the Vincent van Gogh exhibit. Commenting on the White House scandal
and the impeachment proceedings, she snapped, ``It bores me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
