</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRESSES JAPAN ON TRADE, DEREGULATION IN FINANCIAL REFORMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ President Clinton on Friday voiced confidence that Japan
will work its way out of its worst financial situation in 50 years,
but pressed the reluctant nation on trade and deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, counseling patience and fortitude as Japan enacts
financial reforms, also warned of the prospect of retaliation by
other nations if unfair trade practices continue.
</P>
<P>
   The president arrived in Japan on Thursday for a visit intended
to encourage the world's second-largest economy to embrace the
reforms that not only will help itself but also boost all of Asia,
now in an economic slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan and only Japan can lead Asia back to stability and
growth by meeting its own economic challenges,'' Clinton told
members of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce in Japan. ``We have every
confidence that Japan is fully capable of restoring growth for this
country and all of Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message to political and business leaders, as well as
to Japanese citizens who questioned him during a televised town
hall meeting Thursday, was the same: Hang tough.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi earlier this week unveiled a $196
billion stimulus package that would lower taxes, increase spending
on public projects and provide merchandise vouchers for the elderly
and young families.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also cited open trade and deregulation as keys to
restoring economic growth. He specifically warned Japan about
dumping hot-rolled steel into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put that against an inability to open more markets, to
have more investments, to have more deregulation, to have more
market access, it will create in our time a condition for a
retrenchment here in a way that will not be good for Asia or Japan
or for the United States over the long run,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing that can happen is if it appears that when
times are tough, borders are closing up, other markets are being
heavily penetrated in ways that can't be justified by economic
forces, and then you're going to have, I'm afraid, a round of
retaliatory protectionism. I'm quite worried about this now,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States became frustrated with Japan during the Asia
Pacific Economic Conference forum this week in Malaysia when the
nation balked at opening forestry and fishing sectors.
</P>
<P>
   During a Tokyo Broadcasting Systems telecast, Clinton urged the
Japanese, who have suffered through an economic downturn for eight
years, to remain patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strong Japan is good for you but also essential to the rest
of Asia emerging from its present difficulties. So, don't be
discouraged but do be determined, that would be the advice of a
friend,'' Clinton told the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi, the fifth prime minister in four years, later toasted
Clinton at a dinner, making no mention of the uneasiness that has
developed between the two nations because of the United States'
impatience with the pace of Japanese reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, Japan is in a period of great transition, which can be
described as the third opening of our country. This transition is a
challenge which entails a major institutional transformation which
is comparable with major restoration and rebuilding of our nation
after the Second World War,'' Obuchi said. ``We are resolved to
face and overcome this challenge with daring.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continued to press Japan to take stronger steps to
stimulate its economy as well as to overhaul its banking system to
bail out and close failed financial institutions. He also called on
the Japanese, among the world's most diligent savers, to spend more
freely.
</P>
<P>
   The TBS special round-table discussion with the president was
aired nationally. People selected for the studio audience were
allowed to ask questions that surprisingly focused on personal
issues, including whether Clinton has been forgiven by his wife and
daughter for his extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing weary after a 14-hour flight from Washington, the
president began his official visit Thursday afternoon with a
courtesy call on Emperor Akihito who extended a rare invitation to
the Imperial Residence. Only an official entourage is traveling
with Clinton. First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton is on an official
visit to Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's overseas departure had been delayed several days
because of the United States' confrontation with Iraq. Vice
President Al Gore attended the Asia Pacific Economic Conference
forum in Malaysia in place of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also is seeking to soothe Japan's feelings following his
trip in June to China. Clinton, at the request of China, did not
visit Japan as part of his trip to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   During the visit, Clinton and Obuchi plan to discuss threats
from North Korea, which is suspected of trying to develop nuclear
weapons. North Korea recently launched a rocket over Japan, a
provocative move to demonstrate its delivery capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will leave later Friday to visit South Korea and U.S.
forces stationed there. His trip ends Monday with a stopover in
Guam.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
