<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0502 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH20-COX     11-19 1728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Starr defends report, call for Clinton impeachment
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr and Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent counsel Kenneth Starr seemed more
defendant than prosecutor Thursday as the first witness at the
first presidential impeachment inquiry in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Making his case to 37 members of the House Judiciary Committee
and millions of television viewers, Starr calmly responded to
questions about his motives, his ethics and his actions before a
hearing that began with partisan bickering and ended with calls for
more witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Through the grueling 12-hour session, Starr_ seated in a
straight-back wooden chair, alone at the witness table _ vigorously
defended his view that President Clinton should be impeached, at
times cradling his sexually explicit 445-page report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand behind it because it is mine,'' he said. ``I stand
behind each word of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr relentlessly outlined what he said was a pattern of
presidential abuse designed to conceal Clinton's sexual
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``misused his authority and power as president and
contravened his duty to faithfully execute the laws,'' Starr said
in the same hearing room that served as the scene for impeachment
proceedings against President Nixon in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also said he believes the Constitution makes clear that
Clinton can be prosecuted once he leaves office for perjury or
other crimes he allegedly commits as president.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's personal lawyer who questioned Starr
near the end of the lengthy hearing, said nothing Starr has
presented is sufficient for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in this overkill of investigation amounts to a
justification for the impeachment of the president of the United
States,'' Kendall said, in a statement that preceded several sharp
exchanges between the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall prodded his adversary for more than a hour, drawing some
of Starr's edgier responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true. You know that's not true,'' Starr said when
Kendall asserted members of Starr's team ``held'' Lewinsky at a
Washington area hotel in January.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats attempted to make Starr the issue, portraying the
independent counsel as an overzealous prosecutor out to destroy the
president, and reluctant witnesses, at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a federally-paid sex policeman spending millions
of dollars to trap an unfaithful spouse, or to police civil
litigation, would have been unthinkable prior to the Starr
investigation,'' said Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, the panel's
senior Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Starr has spent $40 million over the last four
years, Conyers said the investigation has made it ``acceptable in
America to investigate a person's private sexual activity.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was little talk of sex Thursday from Starr, who said
the cover up, not the sexual affair, underlies his case. The rather
tame discourse Thursday differed dramatically from the wealth of
sexual material about Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky in the
report that Starr forwarded to Congress in September that outlined
11 possible grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides tussled repeatedly, with Democrats challenging the
Republicans and the independent counsel almost from the moment the
hearing began shortly after 10 a.m. Republicans, on the other hand,
concentrated on bolstering Starr's assertions and underscoring the
severity of Clinton's alleged misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The displays of bitter partisanship at times tried the patience
of the usually unflappable chairman, Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.).
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Starr remained calm in his first sustained
exposure to the American public. In his two-hour opening statement,
he six times intoned the phrase ``that was untrue'' as he
catalogued instances where he asserted Clinton lied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, Starr said deliberately that the president swore
to tell ``the truth, the whole truth and nothing but the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He frequently held his report to Congress aloft for the
committee members and television viewers to see.
</P>
<P>
   Starr came into the proceeding roundly disliked by the public,
according to opinion polls. But after nearly 10 hours in the
witness chair, Starr received a figurative bouquet from Rep. Mary
Bono (R-Calif.), the panel's junior member.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see that behind that image, there's a human,''
Bono said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr drew the biggest laugh of the day when he responded to a
question about a news release. ``Let me explain what press
statements are designed to do,'' he told a group that has had its
share of experience with press statements.
</P>
<P>
   Starr presented relatively little new material Thursday, turning
again and again to his report, which has been bound and sold in
bookstores, as well as blasted around the world via the Internet
since its release.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed the ``professionalism'' of his prosecutors, but
acknowledged the House could reject their work as not being
``substantial, credible evidence'' of impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   He found himself both defending Lewinsky's credibility and
questioning it, a point Democrats tried hard to elevate as a major
contradiction in the independent counsel's work.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Starr said he discounted her statement that no one
ever told her to lie and that she was never promised a job in
exchange for her cooperation with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Rep. Mel Watt (D-N.C.) raised two other instances in
which Lewinsky may have exaggerated or lied, but which Starr failed
to note in his report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``A substantial portion of your case, isn't it Mr. Starr, is
based on the credibility of Ms. Lewinsky?'' Watt asked. ``How are
you picking and choosing what you believe from Ms. Lewinsky?''
</P>
<P>
   Starr had a ready answer for why he included meticulously
detailed accounts of Lewinsky's encounters with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can answer with one word, corroboration,'' Starr said. ``She
could identify a phone call coming in from a member of Congress,''
even to the point of recalling the congressman's nickname.
</P>
<P>
   The White House sent at least a half-dozen aides to the plush
Judiciary Committee hearing room, which was packed with reporters
and television cameras. White House counsel Charles Ruff and
Kendall, Clinton's personal lawyer, were in the room for every
minute of the marathon hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the attention being paid the proceedings, some
members of Congress professed to be uninterested in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Two senior Republicans, House Majority Leader Richard Armey of
Texas and Rep. Jim Leach (R-Iowa), said they had no plans to watch
the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't got time to watch it. I've got work to do,'' Armey
said when encountered in a hallway in the Capitol complex.
</P>
<P>
   Armey's reaction reflected the ambivalence of House Republicans
who are trying to figure out how to handle the impeachment issue
without angering either their conservative base that favors going
forward or the general public, which overwhelmingly would like to
see the matter dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many voices telling us to halt this debate _ that
the people are weary of it all,'' Hyde said. ``There are other
voices suggesting we have a duty to debate the many questions
raised by the circumstances we find ourselves in _ questions of
high consequence for constitutional government.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde tried to get the committee off on a bipartisan footing.
``The hearing today is not a trial. It is not White House vs.
Starr,'' Hyde told the committee. ``Nor is it Republican vs.
Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   But it certainly seemed to be a pitched partisan battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are disrupting the continuity of this meeting,'' Hyde
snapped at Democrats, who mounted procedural challenges at the
outset.
</P>
<P>
   Watt, a sharp-tongued former civil rights lawyer, shot back,
``We're disrupting a railroad, it seems like, Mr. Chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   The main avenue of attack by the Democrats was to show that
Starr had abused his office by, among other things, trying to
negotiate a deal with Lewinsky in January without her attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is not above the law, Mr. Starr, and neither are
you,'' Rep. Robert Wexler (D-Fla.) said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.) pointed out that Starr waited until
after the November elections to announce Thursday that he did not
have evidence of criminal wrongdoing in his investigation of the
firing of White House Travel Office employees in 1993 and the
misuse of FBI files by White House aides.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Frank said, Starr sent the Lewinsky material to
Congress as the election season heated up.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were uniform in their praise of Starr, expressing
frustration and incredulity that his report has not generated an
outcry for Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Common sense and reality are conspicuously absent,'' Rep.
Howard Coble (R-N.C.) said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the committee would have to decide whether lying under
oath is an impeachable offense. ``Is it essentially different from
a garden variety lie, a mental reservation, a fib, an evasion, a
little white lie, hyperbole? In a court proceeding, do you assume
some trivial responsibility when you raise your right hand and
swear to God to tell the truth, the whole truth and nothing but the
truth?''
</P>
<P>
   Starr answered clearly that Clinton had lied repeatedly and
that, no matter the subject, the president's lies merit
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Zoe Lofgren (D-Calif.) disagreed with Starr, but expressed
one view that appeared to cross party lines. ``There is no doubt
that this is one of the most embarrassing chapters in the history
of the country,'' Lofgren said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the hearing ended, committee members met to vote subpoenas
for the deposition of several figures with some involvement in the
Clinton sex scandal: presidential adviser Bruce Lindsey; Robert
Bennett, the lawyer who represented Clinton in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment case; Daniel Gecker, who represented former White
house volunteer Kathleen Willey; and Nathan Landow, a Maryland
developer and Democratic donor who has been questioned about his
contacts with Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the addition of new witnesses, Hyde said he expected the
committee to conclude its work by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
