u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FPL-REGULATORS20-COX     11-19 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FPL-REGULATORS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hearings sought on FPL profit
 &HT;    By Susan Spencer-Wendell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The remote prospect of partial refunds
for Florida Power &AMP; Light customers stayed alive Thursday as state
regulators again recommended investigating whether the utility is
making too much money for itself and its investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Service Commission staff said it had been unable to
negotiate an agreement with FPL, and called on the commission to
open official hearings about FPL's profits, said PSC spokesman
Kevin Bloom.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member commission now must vote Dec. 1 on whether to
open hearings. If those hearings were to determine that FPL's
profits were too high, that could ultimately lead to consumer
refunds. Regulators have not estimated how much money, if any,
would be refunded.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how much money should FPL keep for itself and its
investors, and it revolves around two calculations _ the company's
return on equity and its equity ratio. Both figures have a bearing
on how much money the utility can charge its 3.6 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   FPL's parent company, FPL Group of Juno Beach, is making a 12.5
percent return on equity, which is in the PSC's permissible range
of 11 percent to 13 percent. But the PSC staff contends that rate
is now out of sync with other AA-rated utilities and too high when
balanced with the substantial declines in interest rates. FPL's
projected equity ratio _ the percentage of its value held by
stockholders _ is at 65.7 percent, which the PSC also says is too
high.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, FPL argued before the commission that comparing one
company to another based on equity ratio is not fair because the
comparison should be based on debt. And the power company has noted
in previous arguments before the commission that it had not raised
its rates since 1985, despite adding $10 billion in facilities
since then.
</P>
<P>
   All parties involved in the negotiations have agreed not to
comment on them, Bloom said.
</P>
<P>
   FPL spokesman Dale Thomas did say, though, that the company will
continue to try to negotiate an agreement before the commission's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
