<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0510 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUER-LAWSUIT20-COX     11-19 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUER-LAWSUIT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chuck Muer escapes blame for Charley's Crab boating deaths
 &HT;    By Val Ellicott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A brother and sister in Michigan waited
years to tell jurors that Palm Beach restaurateur Chuck Muer was
legally to blame for the boating tragedy that killed their parents
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But they may never get the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a judge in Michigan threw out the lawsuit filed by
the children of George and Lynne Drummey, saying the children
couldn't prove how close Muer's boat was to shore when it sank
during the so-called ``storm of the century'' in March 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Muer, his wife Betty and their longtime friends, the Drummeys of
Grosse Pointe Park, Mich., were sailing to Florida from the Bahamas
when the boat, Charley's Crab, went down in 20-foot seas. All four
were presumed killed, although no evidence was recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The distance between the boat and shore was crucial to the suit
against Muer's estate, said Jack Cote, the attorney for the estate.
</P>
<P>
   The Drummey children _ Kimberly Hunt, Patrick Drummey and Shawn
Drummey _ had demanded damages for the terror they said their
parents certainly experienced in the minutes before they died.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that those damages _ for
``pre-death conscious pain and suffering'' _ aren't available under
U.S. admiralty law when a boat sinks farther than 1 marine league,
or 3 miles, from shore. Based on that ruling, issued after the
Drummey children filed their suit, a federal judge dismissed the
suit about six months ago, Cote said. An appellate ruling later
sent the suit back to state court, where it had started in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 23, a circuit judge in Detroit dismissed the case, which
Susan Muer, one of Muer's daughters, described in 1995 as a search
for ``blood money.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Karbel, an attorney and personal representative of the
Drummey children, said two of the children _ Hunt and Patrick
Drummey _ plan to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel there was a terrible wrong committed by Chuck
Muer,'' Karbel said this week. ``He either knew or should have
known about the storm.''
</P>
<P>
   The third sibling, Shawn Drummey, is no longer interested in
actively pursuing the suit, Karbel said.
</P>
<P>
   Cote said Muer, 55, was an experienced sailor and never would
have set sail unless he believed weather conditions were favorable.
</P>
<P>
   Cote recalled that the hurricane-force winds of the ``no-name''
storm that sank Charley's Crab took almost everyone by surprise.
The storm also sank a 400-foot freighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position has always been that the Muers and their friends
would not knowingly have started out on a suicide mission,'' Cote
said.
</P>
<P>
   The boat was last seen in the Bahamas by a Coast Guard Falcon
jet the day before it disappeared. The last clue to its whereabouts
was a silent, 14-second cellular telephone call to 911 that
originated east of Lantana at 4:30 a.m. on March 13.
</P>
<P>
   Muer's company owns the Charley's Crab restaurant chain, Chuck
and Harold's restaurant in Palm Beach and other restaurants in
Michigan, Pennsylvania, Ohio and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Muer's survivors also had questioned a claim by Palm Beach
attorney Garrison Lickle, who billed Muer's estate about $48,000
for time spent helping to search for the missing boat as well as
legal services connected with settling the estate.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Muer children said they were shocked by the
bill and weren't aware Lickle was on the family's payroll. Lickle's
claim ultimately was settled for less than he had originally asked
for, one attorney said. Lickle said the payment went to his former
law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
