<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-19 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0499 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     11-19 1873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EMOTIONAL ROLLER COASTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When UCLA and USC meet on the football field, you
never can be sure who'll wind up blinking in the spotlight's glare
and who'll merely be blinking back tears.
</P>
<P>
   The stars are often humbled and the humble exalted. Some of the
most memorable games in the 67-year series have turned on a tight
end's first catch of the season, a walk-on kicker's nerves, a
receiver's inability to be heard over a crowd's roar.
</P>
<P>
   Selecting the best games in this intracity rivalry is like
settling on the best dish at a five-star restaurant. There are so
many choices, it really depends on one's tastes. Ours leaned toward
the meaningful and mesmerizing; thus, our decision to go with these
seven, one for every year of the Bruins' series winning streak:
1939, 1952, 1967, 1977, 1982, 1991 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The nitty-gritty of those games is common knowledge. The stories
have been handed down from generation to generation like a legacy,
so that someone who habitually forgets his wedding anniversary
(despite having been there) can turn around and rattle off minute
details of a game he never saw. The passion people bring to the
intracity game is what makes it awesome or onerous, depending on
which side of the final score you sit.
</P>
<P>
   For every Bob Robertson, there's a Don MacPherson.
</P>
<P>
   For every Al Carmichael, there's a Paul Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   For every O.J. Simpson, there's a Zenon Andrusyshyn.
</P>
<P>
   For every Frank Jordan, there's a Johnny Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   For every Karl Morgan, there's a Scott Tinsley.
</P>
<P>
   For every Arnold Ale, there's a Reggie Perry.
</P>
<P>
   For every Skip Hicks, there's an Adam Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   Time marches on, except for those for whom it stands eerily
still.
</P>
<P>
   __ First really big game
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-nine years have passed since MacPherson stood open, in the
right corner of the Coliseum end zone, waiting for fellow Bruin
Kenny Washington's throw. That so much more than the football was
up in the air only added to his anxiety and anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA football team historically hadn't had much success
against its cross-town rival, but in 1939 the Bruins had come into
their own.
</P>
<P>
   They entered the game undefeated and with three ties. USC also
was unbeaten with one tie, which meant that for the first time
there was more than city bragging rights on the line. To the
victors would go the Pacific Coast Conference title, a Rose Bowl
berth and national-championship consideration.
</P>
<P>
   A medium-sized city crammed into the Coliseum. The record crowd
of 103,303 grew so quiet in the first quarter you could almost hear
the football drop when it fell out of the hands of USC running back
Grenville Lansdell at the UCLA 2.
</P>
<P>
   So ended the Trojans' best scoring chance. The Bruins put
together their finest drive late in the game, marching from their
20 to USC's 3. After three successive running plays, UCLA faced a
fourth-and-goal at the 5.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback, Ned Mathews, huddled with his offense.
Substitution rules precluded players from running in plays in those
days, so Mathews was on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Straining his voice to be heard above the crowd, Mathews asked
his teammates for input on the play selection. A field-goal attempt
was out of the question, their confidence in their kicking game
having been eroded by four botched extra points the previous week
against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   MacPherson was sure he could break free, so Mathews called for
the ball to be snapped directly to Washington and for him to throw
to MacPherson. At the line of scrimmage, a USC linebacker cheated
up and MacPherson wanted to warn Washington that it was imperative
he get the pass off quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But the crowd's cheering was ringing in his ears and he didn't
want to tip off the defense. And so, to his everlasting regret, he
remained silent.
</P>
<P>
   Washington rolled right before throwing, which gave Robertson,
the defender, just enough time to throw himself in the ball's path
and bat it down before it reached MacPherson. So it was that the
game ended in a scoreless tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I dream about it, I catch that ball,'' MacPherson
said the other day. ``I wish now I had leaned in and told Kenny,
`Throw it quickly.' People talk about that play and they say things
like the pass to MacPherson wasn't complete. It sounds like I
dropped it. It's just tough to take.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Mathews harbors but one regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I wish I had done differently is called a
timeout,'' he said from his Harbor City home. ``That was my
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   __ USC comes up roses
</P>
<P>
   The next time the PCC title and a Rose Bowl berth were hanging
in the game's balance was in 1952. Both teams came into the contest
with 8-0 records. USC emerged unscathed, beating the Bruins 14-12
on two flukey scores.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans tallied their first points when Carmichael, while in
the grasp of tacklers, pitched the football to tailback Jim Sears,
who ran untouched 65 yards to put USC up 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of a safety and a 1-yard run by Bill Stits, the
Bruins pulled ahead, 12-7. They were poised to pad their lead in
the third quarter when they took the second-half kickoff and drove
to USC's 18.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's tailback, Cameron, then tried to throw. He was hit as he
released it and the ball landed, as if deposited by providence, in
the hands of USC's Elmer Willhoite. He carried the ball to the UCLA
8. Four plays later, Carmichael posed as a blocker, then slipped
into the flat, where Sears found him with a perfect pass.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron left the game soon thereafter with a sore shoulder.
Years later, the Bruins remained pained by the loss. Donn Moomaw, a
senior on that squad, would later say, ``If we played them seven
more times, we'd beat them six more times.''
</P>
<P>
   A journalist who covered the game wrote: ``The teams were so
evenly matched it was a shame one had to lose. Too bad they can't
both go to the Rose Bowl and each play a half.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Undone by the run
</P>
<P>
   The 1967 showdown was for the Pac-8 title, all the Roses and the
Heisman Trophy, too.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA was 7-0-1 and ranked No. 1. USC was coming off a loss at
Oregon State that had dropped it from No. 1 to No. 3. The Bruins'
Gary Beban passed for 301 yards and two touchdowns, only to be
upstaged by the Trojans' thundering O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, a junior, brought USC to within 14-7 with a 13-yard
touchdown run that left seven would-be Bruins tacklers grasping at
his wake. It was a singularly sensational effort _ surpassed only
by his 67-yard sprint early in the fourth quarter that put the
Trojans ahead 21-20.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the game ended after UCLA placekicker Zenon
Andrusyshyn had two field goals blocked in the final 10 minutes. So
it was that Andrusyshyn became a sad footnote to arguably one of
the greatest collegiate games played.
</P>
<P>
   His story bears repeating, for as sure as there is another game
in the series on Saturday, there will be a goat. Heaven help him if
he ends up feeling as caged as Andrusyshyn.
</P>
<P>
   Andrusyshyn was so disconsolate immediately after the game, he
couldn't bring himself to shower and dress alongside his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt I had let my teammates down and the university
down,'' he said from his home in Tampa. ``So I waited until
everybody had cleared out of the locker room before I went in.''
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason, he eschewed the team bus and bummed a ride
back to campus. As he was walking toward his dormitory, he saw a
group of students setting fire to something. Emotions over the
Vietnam War were running high on college campuses and it wasn't
unusual to see ritualistic burnings of draft cards.
</P>
<P>
   It was only as Andrusyshyn drew closer that he realized he was
being burned in effigy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt almost betrayed,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   His feelings remain pretty much unchanged today. The Bruins'
failed Rose Bowl bid in 1967 has become a permanent thorn in
Andrusyshyn's side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just last year there was a story published in a newspaper and
some of the comments my teammates made were a little critical of
me,'' said Andrusyshyn, who played 16 years in the NFL, CFL and
USFL before becoming an ordained minister. ``It hurt me that
they're still harboring (ill) feelings toward me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, after all, just a game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Clutch kick
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks the UCLA-USC clash is war needs to talk to
Jordan. In 1977 Jordan succeeded where Andrusyshyn could not,
booting a 38-yard field goal with 2 seconds left to put the Trojans
over the top 29-27.
</P>
<P>
   These days he works in the insurance business and organizes
historical tours of World War I battle sites on the side. He also
is finishing up a World War I docudrama he started writing long
before Steven Spielberg's World War II drama ``Saving Private
Ryan'' hit the cinemas.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan botched two extra points early in his first game against
UCLA. To this day there are Bruins who insist he never should have
had the chance to atone for those misses.
</P>
<P>
   Ask them their gripe and they'll tell you USC's last drive
appeared to have stalled at midfield when Lynn, a UCLA defensive
back, dived to deflect quarterback Rob Hertel's third-down pass
that was intended for flanker Kevin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   In a controversial call, Lynn was flagged for pass interference
and the Trojans were granted a first down on the UCLA 40. Six plays
later, Jordan redeemed himself with a kick that booted UCLA out of
the Rose Bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the football sailed through the uprights, Jordan was
smothered. He managed to walk away unhurt from the pile-on, but one
of the Trojans' assistant coaches, Mike Haluchak, wasn't so lucky.
He broke his nose.
</P>
<P>
   __ USC ends up sacked
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's nose guard, Morgan, was the star of the 1982 game,
sacking USC quarterback Scott Tinsley on a two-point conversion
with no time remaining to preserve the Bruins' 20-19 victory. Nine
years later, another sack, this one by Ale on Perry, would preserve
the 24-21 win that set the Bruins on their current series streak.
</P>
<P>
   How the streak reached six is the stuff of which syrupy
Hollywood movies are made. The Bruins rallied from a 17-point
fourth-quarter deficit to send the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with thousands of nonbelievers from the crowd of 80,644
stuck in traffic outside the Rose Bowl, Hicks broke a 25-yard
scoring run on the first play of the second overtime to give the
Bruins a 48-41 win.
</P>
<P>
   Left tackle Kris Farris couldn't blame the fans for getting a
head start on their evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have left too,'' the junior said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with the history of the series know to stick
around until the end. The Bruins have won the past seven meetings
between the two schools by an average of 5.7 points. This year's
undefeated UCLA squad has tested its fans' tickers time and again.
</P>
<P>
   All signs point to another fabulous finish Saturday afternoon
and wouldn't you know, there's one storyline tailormade for this
Tinseltown tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Abrams had a 40-yard field goal blocked that would have
won the game for the Trojans in regulation. In the name of Zenon
Andrusyshyn, may he get another chance to set his memories right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
