<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS ASSAIL STARR'S `OBSESSION' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent counsel Kenneth Starr told a partisan,
contentious House Judiciary Committee hearing Thursday that
President Clinton ``misused his authority and power'' to thwart
investigations into his White House affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   While Starr and committee Republicans targeted Clinton,
Democrats on the panel _ aided by the president's private attorney
_ took aim at Starr and his team of investigators, saying they
mishandled the Lewinsky probe and ``crossed the line into
obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing as the leadoff witness in only the third presidential
impeachment inquiry in U.S. history, Starr told committee members
that regardless of the outcome of their investigation Clinton could
be prosecuted for perjury after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the day Starr dryly defended his team of
investigators and the methods they used to investigate Clinton's
efforts to hide his affair with Lewinsky. Late in the evening,
Starr's temper grew short and his answers became more terse as he
went head-to-head on national television with Clinton's personal
lawyer, David Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is false, and you know that it is false,'' Starr snapped
at Kendall, who accused the prosecutor's deputies of misconduct in
their dealings with Lewinsky. ``I am confident that we have abided
by our obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the committee's Democrats, Kendall focused largely on
Starr's conduct and the tactics used by prosecutors and FBI agents
assigned to his office. At one point, Starr interrupted Kendall's
cross-examination and turned to committee Chairman Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., saying: ``It's time for some fairness with respect to all
of these charges that keep getting bandied about.''
</P>
<P>
   The first 2 1/2 hours of Starr's testimony involved his reading
a 58-page summary of his investigation and how in January it turned
from Clinton's business dealings in Arkansas to his affair with
Lewinsky, who _ when their trysts began _ was a White House intern
and later a government employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``On at least six different occasions ... the president had to
make a decision. He could choose truth, or he could choose
deception,'' the special prosecutor said. ``On all six occasions,
the president chose deception.''
</P>
<P>
   With each decision, Starr said, Clinton created the crisis
threatening his presidency. ``The president's intimate relationship
with a subordinate employee was transformed,'' Starr said. ``It was
transformed into an unlawful effort to thwart the judicial process.
This was no longer an issue of private conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, for the first time, Starr acknowledged that the five-year
investigation of Clinton, which began with his Arkansas business
dealings, have found no criminal wrongdoing by the president or
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton in the White House travel-office
firings or misuse of FBI files.
</P>
<P>
   Although his staff last year drafted an impeachment report
alleging that Clinton lied under oath during the Whitewater
investigation, Starr said he decided the evidence against the
president was not strong enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those matters will in fact not be coming to you,'' Starr said,
referring to the law requiring him to notify Congress when his
investigation turns up crimes involving the president.
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., asked why Starr had not told
the public before the fall elections that he had found no evidence
of impeachable offenses in the Whitewater, FBI files and travel
office cases, the prosecutor responded that the law did not require
him to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, you don't have anything to say unless you have
something bad to say,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's testimony was the first heard by the full committee
since the House voted for an open-ended impeachment investigation.
The inquiry was prompted by Starr's report to the House in early
September alleging 11 possible offenses that could warrant the
president's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Starr began testifying Thursday morning, he came
under a withering attack by the committee's ranking Democrat, Rep.
John Conyers of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Starr a ``federally paid sex policeman spending millions
of dollars to trap an unfaithful spouse,'' Conyers said the
independent counsel engaged in unacceptable tactics by forcing
Lewinsky's mother to testify, lawyers to testify against their
clients and Secret Service agents against the president they
protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``While an independent counsel can and should pursue a case with
vigor, I and many others believe that Mr. Starr has crossed the
line into obsession,'' Conyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Abbe Lowell, chief lawyer for the committee's Democrats, drew a
touch of sarcasm from Starr when raising questions about actions
taken by his deputies during their first contacts with Lewinsky and
Linda Tripp, the woman who secretly taped the intern's telephone
conversations
</P>
<P>
   On those tapes Lewinsky said she planned to lie about her
relationship with the president in a sworn deposition in the Paula
Jones sexual harassment case and urged Tripp to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Starr said his deputies' treatment of Lewinsky during their
first encounter _ which Democrats have charged was too harsh _
relied on standard law-enforcement techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a felon in the middle of committing another felony,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor also denied that his office had leaked secret
grand jury testimony to the media or hidden his contacts with
Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were far more gentle, and lauded Starr for his
unflappable responses to questions from the Democratic House
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend you for standing up to the nonsense ... that you
have had to put up with today,'' said Rep. Bob Barr, a Georgia
Republican who is among Clinton's most ardent critics.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., said the Democrats were off the
mark and accused them of firing ``drive-by questions'' at Starr.
``I think what we're seeing here is a desperate attempt to get away
from the facts of the case against the president,'' Canady said.
</P>
<P>
   When the committee hearing began, Rep. William Delahunt,
D-Mass., sought to expand the time allocated to the White House to
question Starr from 30 minutes to two hours, but committee
Republicans voted down the proposal. Republicans insisted on a
strict timetable, but as the day wore on Hyde used his discretion
to extend members extra time to question Starr. Kendall eventually
was given a full hour to grill the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde announced plans to vote after Starr's testimony on whether
to subpoena other witnesses. Republicans _ who have the votes to
set the committee agenda _ want to question Deputy White House
counsel Bruce Lindsey, the president's closest confidant, and
Robert S. Bennett, a private attorney who represented Clinton in
the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   When Starr began his 11 1/2 hours of testimony, Clinton was on
the other side of the world on a five-day visit to Asia. White
House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton did not watch any
of the live television coverage but saw one short clip from Starr's
testimony during a news broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
