<SLUG> BC-NY-UNION-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK UNION IS BEING INVESTIGATED FOR VOTE FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Manhattan district attorney is investigating
allegations that officials at District Council 37, the umbrella
group representing 120,000 New York City municipal employees,
committed extensive vote fraud in 1996 to win ratification of a
widely criticized contract that included a two-year wage freeze,
lawyers knowledgeable about the investigation said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawyers said a union leader had told prosecutors that
officials at a large local of clerical workers stuffed ballot boxes
with fraudulent ballots to ensure ratification of the five-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Arthur Schwartz, who represents several of the
council's 56 locals, said Joseph DeCanio, president of a local
representing highway workers, told prosecutors about the vote fraud
as part of a broad investigation into allegations of embezzlement,
kickbacks and other misdeeds at the council.
</P>
<P>
   Another lawyer knowledgeable about the investigation said
DeCanio has told the district attorney that the ballot-box stuffing
involved thousands of votes and was instrumental in putting the
contract over the top by a considerable margin.
</P>
<P>
   DeCanio, the lawyers said, has also told prosecutors that he saw
thousands of blank ballots in a union leader's office and has said
he believed those ballots were part of a scheme to tip the
ratification vote, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Ratification of the contract was important to the council's
executive director, Stanley Hill, because rejection would have
embarrassed him before his members and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani at a
time when the union leader was trying to solidify his relationship
with the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The contract also proved to be pivotal for Giuliani. He had
relied heavily on its two-year wage freeze to end the city's budget
deficit, and he has pointed to the contract with the largest
municipal union as the cornerstone of his peaceful relations with
labor.
</P>
<P>
   That contract set a pattern for contracts later accepted by
unions representing the city's other 180,000 workers, including
firefighters and sanitation workers. It also smoothed the way for
Giuliani's winning the endorsement of Hill and the council in last
year's mayoral election.
</P>
<P>
   DeCanio's statements to prosecutors echoed allegations of vote
fraud that James Butler and Charles Ensley, the leaders of two of
District Council 37's largest locals, made immediately after the
ratification 33 months ago. They said then that they were surprised
at how many votes for ratification came from the clerical union,
the same local that DeCanio has identified as the center of
suspected ballot-stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   But until DeCanio began talking with prosecutors earlier this
month, there were no specific allegations to back up the
suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   DeCanio declined to comment despite repeated requests for
interviews, and his lawyer, Debra Cohen, said she would neither
confirm nor deny that he had spoken to the district attorney's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan district attorney, Robert Morgenthau, has
subpoenaed records from all 56 locals in the council and is looking
into the disappearance of millions of dollars from union coffers.
The parent union, the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees, has already expelled the president of one
local after a union panel found that he had embezzled more than
$1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall officials declined to comment, saying the ratification
vote was an internal union matter.
</P>
<P>
   Labor experts said that even if the fraud allegations were
proved, the contract would remain in force, because the district
council's leadership had signed the contract and the city has
carried out its end of the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2334EST &QL; 
