<SLUG> BC-NY-MORGANSTANLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY PLANS ITS THIRD TOWER IN TIMES SQUARE AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. signed a deal
Thursday to build a million-square-foot office tower on Seventh
Avenue between 49th and 50th Streets, creating a pinstriped
corporate campus in what was once the unlikeliest of locations:
Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The planned 33-story glass skyscraper, tentatively named Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter Plaza, would be the giant financial service
company's third building at the northern end of the Times Square
area, where peep shows and T-shirt shops have given way to new
theaters, restaurants, hotels and MTV. The tower would rise on what
is now a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley signed an agreement Thursday afternoon with the
current landowner, the Rockefeller Group, after 11 months of
on-again, off-again negotiations. Under the terms of the deal, the
tower would be developed as a joint venture of Morgan Stanley and
the Rockefeller Group, a subsidiary of Mitsubishi Estate Co.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Kohn Pederson Fox, the new tower will be the latest
element of a building boom that has swept through Times Square. The
Planet Hollywood Hotel is under construction at the southwest
corner of Broadway and 48th Street, along with movie theaters,
theme restaurants and a Madame Tussaud's museum on 42nd Street.
Douglas Durst, the developer, is completing the first new office
tower in Manhattan since 1992, on Broadway between 42nd and 43rd
Streets.
</P>
<P>
   Two other towers may soon loom over Times Square as well.
Bertelsmann AG is inching closer to a deal to build a new home for
Random House at Broadway and 45th Street and the newly combined
Nasdaq and American Stock Exchange may build a headquarters and
trading floor at 42nd Street and the Avenue of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times Square has become a center for financial, legal and
entertainment companies,'' said Peter Riguardi, executive vice
president of Colliers ABR, a real-estate broker that represented
Morgan Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   The new Morgan Stanley tower will sit across the street from the
investment bank's building at 750 Seventh Ave. and only a block
north of the company's 43-story headquarters at 1585 Broadway,
between 47th and 48th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   The design for the building is nearing the end of the city's
land use review process, although Morgan Stanley may revise the
plans and begin the process again. The tower would include retail
stores at the base, an entrance to the subway, a plaza with a large
reflecting pool and the kind of large neon signs required in the
Times Square district. Morgan Stanley's headquarters is festooned
with a three-line stock ticker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
