<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JUDGES-PAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
21 PERCENT RAISE PROPOSED FOR N.Y. JUDGES
</HEADLINE>
   (smw) 
 By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York State's chief judge proposed a 21 percent raise for
state judges Thursday as part of an annual budget proposal that the
judge submits to the legislature and Gov. George Pataki for
approval.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether lawmakers and the governor will approve
the request or even when they might take it up for consideration.
The timing of the announcement by Chief Judge Judith Kaye suggested
that she would like legislators to consider pay increases for
judges if they decide to reconvene next month to vote raises for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   While lawmakers are usually reluctant to talk publicly about
raises, there is reason to suspect that they might return to Albany
in a few weeks to increase their pay. Assembly Speaker Sheldon
Silver, who has already endorsed raises for legislators and state
executives, would also support increases for judges, said Silver's
spokesman, Pat Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, the legislature cannot vote itself raises
during its two-year term. Because legislators may approve raises
only for a subsequent term, any increase for the next two years
must be voted before Jan. 1, when the next term begins. If the
window is missed, lawmakers cannot not get a raise until 2001 at
the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye noted that state judges had not received a raise since
1993. ``Over many years, the judges of this state have experienced
a significant decline in the real value of their salaries,'' she
said in a statement. A commission that examined the salaries of the
1,300 judges who are paid by the state, including City Court and
Housing Court judges, along with higher-level state judges,
recommended substantial raises earlier this year, Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has repeatedly opposed raises for legislators, and he
said last month that he would not support an increase now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
