u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-REACT-NY     11-19 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHILE BOSTON POINTS FINGERS, HARTFORD CLAPS IN GLEE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Conn.)  (lb) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In Boston, the saying goes, there are only three things
that count: sports, politics and revenge. And the announcement
Thursday that the New England Patriots will leave suburban Boston
to play in Hartford, Conn., combines all three, revealing that
underneath the sheen of its current economic boom, Boston is often
still a city of tribal neighborhoods and vendettas without strong
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is not our finest hour,'' said Chad Gifford, the
chairman and chief executive of BankBoston, who is also the head of
Boston's Chamber of Commerce and a close friend of the Patriots'
owner, Robert Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is a great city, from our history to our cultural
institutions to our geography by the water,'' Gifford said. ``But
there was a good opportunity here for the city, and sometimes we
are so proud, it verges on arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the Patriots to Hartford, 41 years after they played
the first game in the old American Football League here against the
Denver Broncos, is being blamed largely on one man, Thomas
Finneran, the speaker of the Massachusetts House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran seemed to make it a personal crusade to stop Kraft,
whom he at one point referred to as a ``whiny billionaire,'' from
getting state financing to help build a new stadium in Foxboro,
where the team now plays, even though Kraft had proposed putting up
$200 million of his own money to pay the bulk of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, on WEEI-AM, a sports talk radio station, Finneran
said he would not mind if his role in driving the Patriots out of
Massachusetts was ``chiseled on my gravestone.'' One caller to the
radio station said Finneran's actions were ``immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the view of many sports fans, real-estate developers and
other politicians, there was enough blame to go around, reflecting
on a widespread failure of civic and political leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. William Weld and the newly elected governor, Paul
Cellucci, had both promised to help Kraft get the government
financing to keep the team in Massachusetts. They failed. So did
Mayor Thomas Menino, who last year blocked a plan by Kraft to build
a privately financed stadium on unused land in South Boston near
the harbor after opposition from neighborhood groups.
</P>
<P>
   Menino said he was disappointed the Patriots were moving to
Hartford, but he did not sound deeply troubled. ``If it was the Red
Sox, I'd be concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have not played in Boston itself in years, Menino
said, whereas the Red Sox play 81 games a year at Fenway Park and
have a big impact on the city's restaurants and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are also trying to build a new ball park to replace
Fenway, the smallest and next-to-oldest baseball stadium in the
nation, but they too have so far been unable to come up with a plan
that will satisfy neighborhood groups.
</P>
<P>
   This is a serious problem for the Red Sox, for although Fenway
Park remains one of the best places to watch a baseball game, it is
simply too small and outdated to generate the revenues needed to
compete with teams like the Yankees or the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Football fans were despondent and did not accept Kraft's
contention that he was keeping the Patriots in New England, close
enough for them to still go to games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was going to be the Providence Patriots, I would view it
differently,'' said Steve Doran, a marketing consultant in Hingham
and a former season ticket holder. ``But I think of Hartford as
being a bedroom community for New York, Giants country. I don't
even think of Connecticut as being part of New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran did not return phone calls to his office Thursday. But
on WEEI radio he blamed Kraft's greed for the move. ``Why are the
owners of pro sports teams entitled to hundreds of millions of
dollars?'' he asked. ``Entertainment is not a public
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But the state Senate president, Thomas Birmingham, like Finneran
a Democrat, said he was ``befuddled'' by Finneran's position. Under
Birmingham, the Senate last spring approved a bill, by a 36-1 vote,
to provide $70 million in state money to improve roads and highway
ramps as part of Kraft's plan to build a new stadium in Foxboro
with $200 million of his own money.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran rejected that as too generous, and the bill failed in
the House, even though Birmingham said the proposal was the
``stingiest'' government support in the nation for the construction
of a new professional sports stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, Birmingham said, is that the Patriots
contribute $10 million a year in payroll taxes to Massachusetts,
and his bill would have involved an expenditure of $2.3 million a
year in government money. Now the state will lose $7.7 million a
year. ``How can this be justified in the name of fiscal
responsibility?'' he asked, jabbing at Finneran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
