<SLUG> BC-NJ-HMO-CONTRACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLED HMO BREAKS CONTRACT WITH PROVIDER, GOES UNDER STATE
SUPERVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Efforts to shore up the finances of New Jersey's
fourth-largest health maintenance organization took a bitter public
turn Thursday when the organization, HIP Health Plan of New Jersey,
broke its contract with the medical provider it hired 18 months
ago. That provider's parent company then filed for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The actions brought to an abrupt halt nearly two weeks of secret
negotiations among HIP, the medical provider it hired, Pinnacle
Health Enterprises, whose parent company is PHP Healthcare Corp.,
and state regulators. The talks were aimed at forestalling a
threatened state takeover of the plan, which serves 194,000 people.
Those negotiations began after officials of the state's Department
of Banking and Insurance and Department of Health and Senior
Services, which regulate HIP, moved in state court to take control
of the plan, saying that it was running deficits in excess of $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to breaking its contract with Pinnacle, HIP
voluntarily agreed to state supervision of its financial operations
as well as the network of Pinnacle-owned clinics that serve the
plan's members.
</P>
<P>
   Both HIP and Pinnacle said that Thursday's developments would
not affect the operations of the health centers serving HIP members
because HIP would continue to pay Pinnacle the fees for those
patients the company treated at its 18 clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Pinnacle charged Thursday, in comments made on the
condition of anonymity, that state officials never actively
participated in the weeks of negotiations, thereby dooming them.
The parent company, PHP, which is based in Reston, Va., stands to
lose the more than $140 million it had invested in the contract
with HIP. In a statement released Thursday, Pinnacle charged that
HIP had ``no legal basis'' for ending that contract.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, HIP of New Jersey accused Pinnacle of failing to
use money HIP provided from its premiums to satisfy tens of
millions of dollars in claims from health providers. Officials at
HIP also said that Pinnacle, which acquired HIP's nearly two dozen
clinics or health centers last year, had unilaterally laid off
employees in a manner that hurt the quality of medical services.
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Comfort, a spokeswoman for the state's Department of
Banking and Insurance, would not respond to the charge by Pinnacle
officials that the state failed to participate actively in the
negotiations over the last few weeks, noting that the state judge
in the case had prevented the parties from discussing the talks.
She added that the state would go to court on Friday to formalize
its supervision of HIP
</P>
<P>
   She noted that Pinnacle was required by contract to provide
medical services for up to 12 months after the end of the contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2338EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
