A0550 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-HARTFORD     11-19 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-HARTFORD-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `MAGIC DUST' FOR REDEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Conn.)  (lb) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Business owners answered their telephones with
bold greetings Thursday, boasting that they were in the home of the
Hartford Patriots. News dealers at Old State House Square hawked
souvenir issues of the local paper with headlines worthy of a war
or a presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Civic leaders predicted a downtown renaissance that would
include new museums, a community college and thousands of hotel
rooms and apartments. And sports fans signed onto the Internet to
order tickets for the National Football League season of 2001, when
the Boston-area franchise is expected to move 100 miles west.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a gray drizzle, Thursday's announcement brought a spring
to Hartford's dragging step, a straightening of its collective
shoulders. ``This is an enormous compliment to the city's
potential,'' said Evan Dobelle, the president of Trinity College
here and a dynamic force in the city's redevelopment efforts.
``It's a validation of all the work we've been trying to do. It is
immeasurably helpful, not even quantifiable. This will lift all
boats.''
</P>
<P>
   At ZuZu's coffee bar, near the Civic Center that not too long
ago lost its National Hockey League team, Dean Zappalorti predicted
that the Patriots would attract young professionals looking to
settle in a small, vibrant city. ``It's a great building block,''
said Zappalorti, who sells advertising for the Rangers'
minor-league club, which replaced the NHL Whalers.
</P>
<P>
   At Old Town Cafe in suburban Wethersfield, where ``Monday Night
Football'' draws standing-room-only crowds, Tom Tigno, a retired
firefighter, hoped for more restaurants, small businesses and
employment downtown. ``It's dead right now,'' he said. ``We need a
shot in the arm.''
</P>
<P>
   And at Timothy's Restaurant, where sprouts and nine-grain bread
are popular with the Trinity College crowd, Marsha Kelly, a retired
schoolteacher who lives downtown, looked forward to increased foot
traffic, energy and maybe even a movie theater or two. ``It's
unfortunate it takes a sports team to do it,'' she said. ``But
anything that brings people.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, Hartford's proud men and women worked in factories that
built bicycles, sewing machines, typewriters and rifles and relaxed
in parks built by Frederick Law Olmsted and museums endowed by J.P
Morgan. That glorious infrastructure remains in the compact
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years Connecticut's capital has been better known
for a collapsed manufacturing base, a downsized insurance industry
and a middle class that fled to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   A professional football team alone is no panacea for urban
decay, as other cities have learned, but Hartford sees the Patriots
as part of a broad redevelopment scheme. Plans were already in the
works for a convention center, hotel and riverfront esplanade at a
site known as Adriaen's Landing, just blocks from the gold-domed
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The project, according to Dobelle, a member of the redevelopment
task force, will include two new museums, a community college,
1,500 hotel rooms and 1,000 apartments. The arrival of the
Patriots, assuming NFL and legislative approval, would add other
elements _ the team's executive offices, perhaps a soccer franchise
and good fortune for the University of Connecticut football team,
which would move up a division in collegiate play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the magic dust,'' Dobelle said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Not that everyone here is a believer. Two government workers
lunching at Timothy's complained that Hartford needed new schools,
low-income housing and community services more than it needed
football. ``Tell me how it's going to help the poor,'' Joan Parker
demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Political cynicism ran deep at the Old Town Cafe, a blue-collar
hangout in a white-collar suburb. Jack Strasser, a food
distributor, worried that thousands of poor people would be
displaced from neighboring housing projects. And he wondered if
Gov. John Rowland, who roared to re-election, was motivated by
ambition for national political office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
