<HEADLINE>
CBS TO SHOW KEVORKIAN'S VIDEO OF MAN'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The CBS newsmagazine ``60 Minutes'' plans to broadcast on Sunday
a videotape provided to them by Dr. Jack Kevorkian showing the
doctor administering a fatal injection to a patient who then dies
on camera.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian, said Kevin Tedesco, a spokesman for ``60 Minutes,''
is ``trying to raise an issue, to get himself arrested and to make
his case a trial balloon.'' Kevorkian, whose license to practice
medicine has been revoked in his home state of Michigan and in
California, has in the past decade made himself synonymous with the
issue of physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 through 1996, Kevorkian was acquitted of charges
related to five separate deaths at which he assisted.
</P>
<P>
   The planned segment on the CBS television newsmagazine would be
the second national broadcast of an assisted suicide. In December
1994, the ABC-TV newsmagazine ``Primetime Live'' broadcast segments
of a Dutch television documentary, ``Death on Request,'' which
showed the assisted suicide of a 63-year-old man suffering from the
degenerative disease amyotrophic lateral sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after The New York Times published excerpts from the
transcript of ``Death on Request,'' a representative of ``60
Minutes'' called the editor who assembled the transcript, seeking
to get in touch with the Dutch documentary film makers. Those film
makers, however, already had an arrangement with ABC.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch broadcast was condemned by the Vatican as ``a
horrifying spectacle.''
</P>
<P>
   The CBS broadcast is scheduled to take place during the November
sweeps month, when networks are striving to achieve the maximum
viewership so that their affiliated stations can set the highest
possible charges for advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian could not be reached for comment Thursday night, nor
could Don Hewitt, the executive producer of ``60 Minutes,'' or Mike
Wallace, the correspondent who worked on the euthanasia segment.
</P>
<P>
   Tedesco said Kevorkian brought his video to the program last
week. The moment of death is shown on camera, Tedesco said, as is
the moment when the fatal injection is administered. Wallace also
interviews the family of the patient about their decisions
involving the death and the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it's in bad taste,'' Tedesco said. ``This
particular death is peaceful, calm and nonviolent.''
</P>
<P>
   Tedesco said the network plans to broadcast an advisory early in
the program warning that the segment may disturb some viewers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
