<SLUG> BC-NY-AG-SPITZER-275&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPITZER DECLARES VICTORY IN CONTESTED ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not waiting for confirmation from election officials
or a concession by his opponent, Eliot Spitzer, the Democratic
challenger in the race for state attorney general, declared himself
the winner of the tight contest Thursday and announced that he was
putting together a transition team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a long, tough race,'' Spitzer said at a press
conference in his law office in midtown Manhattan. ``And now that a
sufficient number of votes have been counted to establish beyond
any doubt that I have won, I think it is appropriate that I declare
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Elections said Thursday that Spitzer was
22,626 votes ahead of Republican incumbent Dennis Vacco in a race
in which more than 4 million votes were cast. Board officials
estimated that about 15,000 paper ballots remained to be counted
from the 250,000 that were cast. The bulk of those are from
Westchester County, where Spitzer won the voting machine tally by a
slight margin.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those totals, Vacco apparently considered his Democratic
opponent's declaration premature, coming as it did only a day after
lawyers for the incumbent filed a complaint in state Supreme Court
saying that there were widespread discrepancies in the vote
tallies, particularly in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco said in a statement, ``I do not intend to make any
additional statement with regard to the outcome of this election
until I am so advised by my lawyers and the court that a final
determination has been made.''
</P>
<P>
   Election officials have said they do not intend to certify a
winner in the race until all legal challenges have been settled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officials of both campaigns met Thursday to begin
inspecting the nearly 7,000 voting machines in New York City, under
a court ruling issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco's lawyers have complained that the number of votes
reported on election night did not correspond to the totals
released by the board a week later. As a result, Justice Thomas
Keegan of state Supreme Court in Manhattan ruled that the campaigns
could inspect the machines again and report their findings to the
court Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While Vacco was muted in his response, state Republican Party
chairman William Powers was vehement in denouncing Spitzer's
declaration. ``Spitzer can declare himself king if he wants to, but
that doesn't make him one,'' Powers said in a letter he sent
Thursday to his party's county chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's announcement, Powers said, ``is nothing more than a
cheap ploy to deflect attention away from the potentially
fraudulent vote count that occurred in New York City.'' The Board
of Elections tabulation represented ``a shell game,'' Powers said,
adding that ``Dennis Vacco is our attorney general and we have full
confidence he will remain so if we are successful in our lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Spitzer forthrightly took on the mantle of the
victor, standing at the press conference beside both his wife,
Silda, and Judith Hope, the chairwoman of the New York State
Democratic Committee. Spitzer announced that his law partner _
Lloyd Constantine, a former chief of the antitrust bureau of the
state attorney general's office _ would head his transition team.
</P>
<P>
   Of Vacco's legal challenge, Spitzer said, ``I do not dispute his
right to go to court and raise the issues he has raised.'' Still,
he said, it would now be appropriate for Vacco to ``designate
certain individuals in his office whom I can consult with so that
there can be an orderly transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer made it clear that he had already turned his attention
to the operation of the office, discussing a wide range of topics,
from his opposition to the recent agreement between the state and
the tobacco industry to the need to protect the state's water
supply. He also expressed his desire to have a cordial relationship
with Gov. George Pataki, a Republican who was re-elected to a
second term Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the state Board of Elections said they probably
would not complete the vote count until next week. State law
requires the board to declare a winner by Dec. 15, but officials
said that deadline could be delayed if legal challenges continue.
</P>
<P>
   If no certification is made by Jan. 1, Vacco would vacate the
office and an interim attorney general would be selected by the
combined houses of the Legislature, in which a majority of the 211
lawmakers are Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
