</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-CHASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE SETS AND A FLASHBACK: GRAF OUTLASTS SELES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the fifth match point of her epic quarterfinal
battle with her old foe, Monica Seles, Steffi Graf blew on her
serving fingers, not to cool them but to ensure a death grip on her
racket. She was preparing a serve that finally backed Seles into a
corner where she lost her last bit of leverage.
</P>
<P>
   Granted the chance to end the suspense with her signature shot,
one of those forehand missiles, Graf plastered it past Seles and
immediately raised both arms in the air to celebrate a 1-6, 6-4,
6-4 comeback at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just so glad to come back and win this match after she
came out and played so well in the first set; it was just amazing
for me to come back and win,'' Graf said. Graf is 9-4 against Seles
in a rivalry that's 10 years old and seems, if this match was any
touchstone, evergreen.
</P>
<P>
   Graf had her left foot wrapped after Seles held for a 3-2 edge
in the final set, but any discomfort she felt from it, or from
Seles' treatment of her in the first set, vanished once she broke
Seles for a 5-4 lead that set her up to serve for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, comebacks are becoming Graf's forte. She has won two
straight tournaments coming into this event after recovering in a
hurry from September wrist surgery: Given a chance to opt for an
early vacation or pound her body back into playing shape in time to
make a madcap dash into contention for the Chase Championships, an
invitation-only event for the world's top 16 players, Graf gambled
and made the dash.
</P>
<P>
   This latest victory extended her unbeaten streak to 12 matches
and sent her to the semifinals of the Championships, an event she's
dominated on five occasions, the last time in 1996 when she
outlasted Martina Hingis in five sets.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Thursday night's test against Seles, whose health
was in doubt because of a debilitating stomach bug, Graf had
defeated the top three players in the world: Lindsay Davenport,
Hingis, and this event's defending champion, Jana Novotna, in the
first round. No other player had ever defeated the top three in a
four-game span. Then again, the 12th-ranked Graf, now a very
veteran 29 but unmindful of it, is like no other player.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Seles, who performed so valiantly throughout the one hour
49 minute confrontation that her illness was invisible: In the
23-minute first set especially, Seles snapped away her shots, one
doublehanded slash after another, with such surgical power and
precision that Graf's forehand was ineffectual.
</P>
<P>
   Seles gobbled up the German's serve and treated it as fodder for
a battery of returns so vicious that Graf was forced to step
backward to try and corral them.
</P>
<P>
   While Graf did a slow burn on her side of the court, Seles kept
on attacking, and with a mean-spirited backhand return that shoved
Graf back into a corner and rendered her completely helpless when
Seles followed up with a backhand drop shot that landed and expired
on command.
</P>
<P>
   Graf gave herself a tongue-lashing as she sat in her changeover
chair, and in the second game of the second set she finally won a
game, her first since the third game of the opening set. After
breaking Seles to take a 2-1 lead, Graf marched back to her chair,
slammed down her racket as if incensed: She wasn't. She was simply
priming her competitive pump for the uphill climb she needed to
make to win the match.
</P>
<P>
   As theater, this was hardcore tennis: Graf and Seles come from
the old school, and their performance mode is gimmick-free. Their
shots flew across the net with harmful intent: The groundstrokes
burned like lasers, and their serves were designed to detonate on
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   If Graf and Seles were sending a message to each other, and to
the crowd of 13,023 they enthralled Thursday night, it was that
they remain a valid factor, and threat: This was vintage tennis
played by a couple of vintage champions with 30 Grand Slam singles
titles between them, champions determined not to give any further
ground to the teenage upstarts lately ruling the roost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to keep on going,'' said Graf. ``Everybody else
may be tired, but I'm feeling pretty excited just to be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
