<HEADLINE>
HE'S GOT INSIDE MOVE ON L.A. PRO FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A precocious 20-something has done what heavy
hitters like Michael Ovitz are only dreaming about _ bringing
professional football back to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Wasserman, just 24 years old and barely removed from his
college days at UCLA, stepped forward Thursday as the owner of
L.A.'s new Arena Football League franchise. The as-yet-unnamed
expansion team begins play at the new downtown Staples Center in
the spring of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman, the grandson of former MCA/Universal chairman and CEO
Lew Wasserman, is drawing on his family's entertainment experience
as well as its capital to make his first foray into sports
entertainment. The franchise fee was not disclosed but is no less
than $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am truly excited about this opportunity,'' Wasserman said at
a press conference to announce the team.
</P>
<P>
   As L.A. awaits the return of the NFL, Wasserman and AFL
commissioner David Baker both exuded confidence that the quirky,
50-yard Arena game will carve its own niche in the region's sports
market and, eventually, benefit from proximity to a new NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   With a spring-summer schedule, Arenaball doesn't compete with
outdoor pro football and, in fact, is close to reaching a
partnership with the NFL to promote the concept of year-round
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you love football, you're going to love Arena football,''
said Baker. ``It's in-your-face, rock-'n'-roll, hard-hitting,
helmet-popping, heart-stopping football.''
</P>
<P>
   Arenaball has already failed twice to catch on in this region _
the Cobras played in 1988 at the Sports Arena, and Baker's own
Anaheim team folded after playing in '96 and '97 at the Pond. But
Wasserman is undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal will be to create reasons for people to come to these
games,'' said Wasserman, a former Cleveland Browns ballboy. ``I
don't think we'd be here if we didn't think we could fill that
(20,000-seat) arena every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman and Baker figure the Arena franchise will benefit from
being cross-marketed with its fellow Staples tenants, the NBA's
Lakers and Clippers and the NHL's Kings. Staples management is
already creating mandatory combined ticket packages for luxury
suites and other high-end seating.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Soboroff, top assistant to Mayor Richard Riordan, and
Staples officials were also on hand to welcome Wasserman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that it's a great partnership,'' Baker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-19-98 2354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
